<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOPPINESS UNBECOMING TO YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (smw)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ No brooms emerged in the stands at the Metrodome
on Thursday night, even as the Minnesota Twins completed a two-game
sweep of the New York Yankees. Nobody had the gall to think a team
that almost never loses would drop back-to-back games to a
franchise locked in small-market oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   But it happened, and rather convincingly. Mike Buddie, normally
a middle reliever, started under emergency circumstances, and the
Twins knocked him around and won, 9-4, with the Yankees making a
season-high five errors.
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive losses and losses of this ilk are no small matter
for the Yankees (92-32). Consider this:
</P>
<P>
   _The Yankees were swept for the first time since they lost
back-to-back games at Anaheim to open the season.
</P>
<P>
   _The consecutive losses were the Yankees' first since July
19-20, against the Toronto Blue Jays and the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   _The Yankees did not lead during Thursday's game, the first time
that has happened since June 28, when they lost, 2-1, to the Mets
at Shea Stadium. The Yankees had held a lead at some point in each
of their previous 48 games, a total no other major league team had
ever reached.
</P>
<P>
   _Minnesota, in the midst of its sixth straight losing season,
became the first team to win four games against the Yankees this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Circumstances worked in favor of the Twins Thursday. Hideki
Irabu was supposed to start for New York, but could not because he
bruised his left instep in a game last weekend. Manager Joe Torre
intended to use Ramiro Mendoza, but Mendoza came down with what the
Yankees believe is a minor case of tendinitis in his right
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   So Torre turned to Buddie. In a perfect world _ the world in
which the Yankees have existed most of this season _ Buddie would
have pitched six solid innings and given the Yankees a chance to
win while saving the bullpen from extraordinary stress.
</P>
<P>
   He ultimately could do neither.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
He had good stuff, and yet as his pitch count mounted into a range
Buddie does not usually approach, 50 pitches and higher, the Twins
began hitting him hard.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Coomer banged a home run in the Minnesota second, giving the
Twins a 1-0 lead. Tino Martinez tied the score in the fourth with a
run-scoring single off Frank Rodriguez (3-2), but Rodriguez escaped
further trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins put Buddie away in the fourth and fifth innings,
scoring two runs in the fourth (helped by a catcher's interference
call the Yankees argued vehemently) and a four-run burst in the
fifth. When Marty Cordova singled home Brent Gates with one out in
the fifth, Torre had to call on Graeme Lloyd, who usually works to
one or two batters.
</P>
<P>
   As the Twins continued to score against Lloyd, the Yankees
abandoned the habits they have been admired for this year. Lloyd
turned to make a pickoff throw to second, and when he tried to stop
himself, the ball squirted out of his left hand and into right
field. A ground ball skipped under the glove of Martinez at first
base, another went past Scott Brosius at third.
</P>
<P>
   When Todd Walker banged a ball off the right-field wall in the
seventh, Paul O'Neill fumbled the ricochet and then haphazardly
tossed the ball toward the infield as Walker took third.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd had to pitch one and two-thirds innings and unless the
Yankees promote a pitcher from Class AAA, they will begin a
three-game series in Texas Friday night with just two rested
relievers, Mike Stanton and Mariano Rivera, and their middle relief
exhausted.  &QL; 
INSIDE PITCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bon Tewksbury was a mostly journeyman minor league pitcher
before making a big-league career for himself in St. Louis, where
Joe Torre was manager at the time and where Torre always offered
this philosophy for Tewksbury: There's nothing like being a winning
pitcher yesterday. Tewksbury, now with the Minnesota Twins, found
the statement so profound that he had it printed on T-shirts. And
earlier this year, when the Twins were leaving Cleveland just as
the Yankees arrived, Tewksbury left a note for Torre, now the
manager of a team challenging history. Tewksbury wrote, ``There's
nothing like being a winning manager yesterday _ and the day before
that, and the day before that, and the day before that, and the day
before that . . .''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
