<P>
   U.S. ATTACKS ON SUDAN AND AFGHANISTAN
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   (other foreign stories are listed further below)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-U.S. (Washington) _ Dozens of U.S. cruise missiles struck
targets in Afghanistan and Sudan on Thursday in what President
Clinton described as an act of self-defense against imminent
terrorist plots and of fearsome retribution for the bombings of
U.S. embassies in East Africa two weeks ago. By James Bennet. WITH
PHOTO (NYT29) and MAPS.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-BINLADEN (Washington) _ How Osama bin Laden, the youngest
son of a construction magnate from Yemen, became the world's most
feared sponsor of terrorism. The religious and ideological roots of
his rage lie in the 1980s, when he worked side by side with the CIA
backing the Afghan rebels. When that battle was over, he and his
fellow holy warriors went to work on the U.S. By Tim Weiner. WITH
MAP.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-CONGRESS (Washington) _ A cherished axiom of U.S.
diplomacy is that the opposition party supports the president when
missiles are flying. Thursday it worked, more or less. Most
congressional leaders, from Speaker Newt Gingrich to such reliable
Clinton critics as Sen. Jesse Helms, rallied around the
commander-in-chief. But in the surreal and cinematic atmosphere
that suffused Washington this week, a handful of voices on Capitol
Hill cried foul. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ASSESS (Undated) _ In the war against terrorism,
experience suggests that any operation, whether an assassination or
the sort of strike launched by the United States, has the quality
of damned-if-you-do-and-damned-if-you-don't. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SECURITY (Washington) _ The United States on Thursday
issued a new worldwide warning to Americans and diplomatic
personnel ``to exercise much greater caution than usual'' following
U.S. military strikes against suspected terrorist targets in
Afghanistan and Sudan. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MILITARY (Washington) _ The U.S. attacked targets in
Afghanistan and the Sudan with roughly 70 cruise missiles fired
from Navy ships in the Arabian and Red Seas timed to strike their
targets simultaneously, senior administration and military
officials said.The missiles struck at precisely 1:30 p.m. ET, after
dark settled over their targets, themselves more than 2,500 miles
apart, the officials said. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ Arrests in Albania show links to the
African embassy bombings: In a series of lightning raids with the
Albanian secret police this summer, American intelligence agents
appear to have thwarted a bomb plot against the American Embassy
here. They also seem to have broken up a ring of Egyptian Islamic
terrorists using this nation's anarchy to set up a base. By John
Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-EVIDENCE (Washington) _ President Clinton ordered strikes
on terrorist-linked facilities in Sudan and Afghanistan after
obtaining credible evidence that leading members of the
international terrorist network sponsored by Saudi exile Osama bin
Laden, who U.S. officials believe was behind the bombings of two
U.S. embassies in Africa, would be gathering Thursday at a
terrorist camp in Afghanistan to plan further attacks against the
U.S. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-BINLADEN (Washington) _ How Osama bin Laden, the youngest
son of a construction magnate from Yemen, became the world's most
feared sponsor of terrorism. The religious and ideological roots of
his rage lie in the 1980s, when he worked side by side with the CIA
backing the Afghan rebels. When that battle was over, he and his
fellow holy warriors _ having defeated the British in the 19th
century and the Soviets in the 20th _ went to work on the United
States. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SUDAN (Nairobi) _ U.S.-Sudanese tensions finally erupt
into open warfare. The air strike against a drug factory in Sudan
on Thursday marked the first act of open warfare in a
long-simmering cold war between the U.S. and the Islamic regime in
Khartoum. By James C. McKinley. WITH MAP.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MEDIA (Undated) _ After a week of what felt like nonstop
talk about sex, ties and audiotape involving President Clinton and
Monica Lewinsky, television screens were overtaken Thursday by news
of a different shock value. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT (Jerusalem) _ Israel was quick to
congratulate the U.S. night for its missile attacks on suspected
terrorist bases, but the early reaction from many other governments
in the Middle East was a notable silence. British Prime Minister
Tony Blair was alone among European leaders in expressing strong
support. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-WAG (New York) _ Is life imitating art? `Wag the Dog'
springs to many minds. Beginning with a reporter's question early
Thursday afternoon to Defense Secretary Cohen about the film ``Wag
the Dog,'' we cast a wide net in search of reaction. By Frank
Bruni. WITH PHOTO (NYT28)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-GAS (Undted) _ VX, the chemical nerve agent that the U.S.
alleges Sudan was preparing to make, is one of the deadliest nerve
agents known, especially when applied to the skin. A 10 mg drop on
the skin can kill an adult in 15 minutes. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-IMMIG (New York) _ In the metropolitan region, immigrants
from the Sudan and Afghanistan reacted to bombings by the U.S. on
their respective homelands with surprise, horror and skepticism. By
David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ In her second and probably final
appearance before a grand jury here, Monica Lewinsky offered more
specifics about her sexual relationship with President Clinton and
the gifts he gave her as prosecutors sought to draw distinctions
between her testimony and that of the president only three days
ago. By Don Van Natta Jr. and Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-GORE (Washington) _ The notes of a senior aide say
that at a November 1995 White House meeting where the distinction
between hard and soft money was apparently discussed, Vice
President Al Gore told the others present to ``count me in'' on
making fund-raising telephone calls that are now the subject of a
Justice Department review on whether to seek the appointment of an
independent prosecutor. By David Johnston. WITH PHOTO (NYT26)
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-GINGRICH (Washington) _ In 1996, Democratic attacks
on House Spea Newt Gingrich were not a rousing success in much of
the country. But in the left-leaning Northeast, they were
instrumental in defeating six Republican members of Congress. So it
is one of this year's political oddities that across the Northeast,
Republicans are unrepentantly embracing Gingrich, even as Democrats
prepare to bash them for it and opinion polls show that the speaker
remains about as popular up north as Sherman is down South. By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   UNABOMBER-REWARD (Washington) _ David Kaczynski and his wife
have been given a $1 million reward from the Justice Department for
turning in David's older brother, Theodore, as the Unabomber. By
Jmes Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   DENVER-BY-THE-SEA (Denver, Colo.) _ Denver, landlocked and 1,000
road miles from the nearest ocean, has always suffered from a mild,
municipal inferiority complex. Yes, it is the gateway to some of
the nation's most dramatic mountains, but where's the beach? This
year, the Mile High City is fighting back against geographic
determinism with indoor sand volleyball, Water Worlds and a giant
new Aquarium full of tropical fish. By James Brooke. WITH PHOTOS
(NYT22,23)
</P>
<P>
   MISS-KLAN-TRIAL (Hattiesburg, Miss.) _ Spectators here at the
trial of a former Klansman accused of ordering the murder of a
respected civil rights leader were surprised, to say the least,
when another former Klansman described the White Knights of the KKK
of Mississippi as a benevolent organization that existed to give
money to the rural poor and pass out fruit baskets at Christmas. By
Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-1918-FLU (Spitsbergen, Norway) _ Six young coal miners,
buried in permafrost since falling victim to the Spanish flu of
1918, are being carefully exhumed this week. Scientists plan to
take ``core samples'' from the bodies, in hope of building a
genetic profile of the mysterious virus that killed 20 million to
40 million people before vanishing. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   VIAGRA-WARNING (Undated) _ The American College of Cardiology
issues a report warning that Viagra poses a risk to patient groups
not described on the drug's label. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH (New York) _ The organizers of a planned
Million Youth March sued the city in federal court Thursday, saying
that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's refusal to grant them a permit to
hold the event in Harlem next month was both unconstitutional and
reflective of the mayor's discriminatory treatment of the city's
black residents. By Abby Goodnough. WITH PHOTO (NYT24).
</P>
