<P>
   CANADA-QUEBEC (Undated) _ The Supreme Court of Canada rules that
Quebec had no right to declare independence unilaterally under
Canadian or international law. Canada's top court said effectively
that Quebec must negotiate any independence with the federal
government of Canada. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ After a defiant outburst from
Baghdad, the Security Council voted unanimously to renew economic
sanctions against Iraq, and the U.S. representative to the U.N.
warned that the sanctions might never be lifted. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELLION (Kinshasa) _ A day after several African
governments pledged to help President Laurent Kabila repel an
attack on his government, a leader of the rebellion said he was
willing to negotiate a cease-fire in the 18-day war that is
increasingly becoming a political battleground for rival African
nations. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIG-SUNAMERICA (Undated) _ American International Group, a world
leader in corporate insurance, said it was buying Sun America Inc.,
one of the pioneers in selling investments for retirement, for $18
billion in stock. The deal, one of the largest in the insurance
industry, brings together two stellar stock market performers and a
pair of chief executives _ Maurice Greenberg of American
International Group and Eli Broad of Sun America _ who are among
the most respected and admired in the business. By Joseph B.
Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE-PROFITS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ As the stock market
struggles to get back on its feet, investors are focused on
corporate earnings, buoyed by reports that profits among the
biggest companies are still rising, albeit slowly. But a guage of
corporate profits produced by the government paints darker picture.
By Jonathan Fuerbringer. WITH GRAPHICS.
</P>
<P>
   LIVENT-ACCOUNTING (Undated) _ Behind the curtain at corporate
theater producer Livent Inc., the company's flamboyant impresario,
Garth Drabinsky, did not just produce Tony-award-winning Broadway
musicals. He also created a brilliant but mythical setting for his
business, a world where it now seems that some of his famously
lavish spending never hurt the company's bottom line. Parts of the
the company's financial books are now being examined by regulators.
Even theater executives with little knowledge of Livent's inner
workings wondered how long the company could spend such extravagant
sums and still make it. By Melody Petersen and Geraldine Fabrikant.
WITH PHOTO (NYT20,21) and GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   BARON-BEAR-STEARNS (Undated) _ Prosecutors have been granted a
court order that temporarily halts witness testimony in cases
surrounding the failure of the A.R. Baron brokerage firm, a signal
that a grand jury investigation into Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co.'s role in
the collapse is reaching a critical point. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   SURVEY-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The relationship between agencies
and advertisers is deteriorating, according to an annual survey,
after two years of results that had begun to narrow a yawning chasm
between the two sides. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   HONDA-EARNINGS (Tokyo) _ Honda is benefiting more than ever from
its global reach, which once earned it ridicule in Japan. It
reported that net income rose 26 percent in the latest quarter as
strong sales in the U.S. and the weak yen compensated for sinking
car sales in Japan. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The start of the Microsoft
antitrust trial is delayed until Sept. 23. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   NOVELL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Novell posts earnings. By Lawrence
M. Fisher.
