<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS PRESIDENT HINTS AGAIN AT LEAVING MEADOWLANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By VINCENT M. MALLOZZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Watching John Calipari and his coaching staff
conduct a basketball clinic at the Newark Boys and Girls Club on
Thursday, New Jersey Nets president Michael Rowe intimated that his
team might soon be doing business again in this city _ for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transportation to the Meadowlands Arena is tough, and the
arena itself has some hospitality and luxury seating problems,''
said Rowe, speaking softly beneath the sounds of screeching
sneakers. ``It was state of the art when it was built, but it's not
now.''
</P>
<P>
   With new ownership nearly in place and the Nets seeking to
expand their fan base in northern New Jersey with a more
commuter-friendly home, team officials are contemplating a move out
of the Meadowlands Sports Complex to a proposed site in Newark. The
Nets have played in the Meadowlands since the 1981-82 season.
</P>
<P>
   While the Nets' lease at Continental Arena expires in 2030,
there are windows to escape in 2000 and 2004, and Thursday, Rowe
sounded like a man talking from the exit ramp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the New Jersey Nets, we've assumed that somehow,
mysteriously, we were going to reach all 567 communities in the
State of New Jersey,'' Rowe said, ``and that they would
overwhelmingly support us, but we've spread ourselves too thin.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Mass transit is critical, we believe, to our future
growth. The Meadowlands does not have mass transit capabilities at
this particular point. The frequency of bus trips to the complex is
not great, and the rail is not great. Our existing ownership and
our prospective ownership believe that any new arena has to have
mass transit as a vital link to it _ and we think it's easier to
build an arena where there is mass transit than to encourage trains
to come to an empty parking lot right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Calipari, who said Thursday that he and his coaching staff were
planning for the start of a full season despite the current
National Basketball Association lockout, will follow the bouncing
ball wherever it goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on board wherever they want to play,'' Calipari said. ``I
want to coach this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowe said that the NBA could announce the Nets' newly formed
ownership team by Sept. 30 and that ``the clock was already
ticking'' on a ``12-month window'' in which the Nets would decide
whether to leave the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were the Paterson Nets or the Hackensack Nets or the
Newark Nets,'' Rowe said, ``it would be a lot easier for us to get
a lot more attention and to do a lot more good in a particular
community.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
