<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-HIV-VACCINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEER JOINS HIV-VACCINE PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Enduring the jab of a syringe was a small
sacrifice for Jeff Linden, considering he was about to become the
first Californian to receive a new HIV vaccine that could halt the
AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   So despite his dread of needles, Linden was inoculated Thursday
with the first preventive vaccine to reach the final stage of
testing before the Food and Drug Administration will consider
approving it for widespread use.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can do a little to help, that's important for me,'' said
Linden, a 33-year-old West Hollywood man. ``I'm hoping it will find
a cure and put an end to this epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine, AIDSVAX, is being tested on uninfected volunteers
across North America in a three-year clinical study that began in
June. Developed by South San Francisco-based VaxGen Inc., the
vaccine is the first of its kind to reach Phase III human clinical
trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a monumental trial, we're very, very excited to be
part of it,'' said Dr. Stephen J. Brown, director of clinical
research at AIDS ReSEARCH Alliance in West Hollywood where Linden
was inoculated.
</P>
<P>
   AIDSVAX is not a treatment for acquired immune deficiency
syndrome or infection with the human immunodeficiency virus, which
causes AIDS. The vaccine is a genetically engineered version of a
protein on the surface of the virus, not a live, weakened virus, so
it is not possible to contract HIV or AIDS, said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Like other vaccines, AIDSVAX is designed to train the human
body's immune system by creating antibodies to protect itself
against viral infection.
</P>
<P>
   AIDSVAX already has been given to more than 1,200 people in
earlier-stage trials.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS activists remain hopeful that the vaccine will work. But
some, including Michael Weinstein, president of the AIDS Healthcare
Foundation, are skeptical about the vaccine's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may learn something in administering an HIV trial and some
peripheral (information), but I think the study is very unlikely
going to result in a successful vaccine,'' said Weinstein, whose
Los Angeles organization is the largest HIV medical services
provider in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein believes that studies have shown a vaccine made from a
live, weakened virus will be more effective. However, that type of
vaccine always carries with it the risk of infecting the person it
is supposed to be protecting, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In studies of AIDSVAX, preliminary evidence using chimpanzees
has shown that the vaccine protected them against large doses of
HIV that should have infected them, said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping the protection seen in chimpanzees will translate
into human protection,'' said Brown, whose nonprofit alliance is
dedicated to finding and developing treatment for HIV and AIDS, and
a vaccine to prevent new infections.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are hoping to find at least 150 uninfected
volunteers in Los Angeles, primarily gay men and women with
HIV-positive partners. Those people are at risk of contracting the
virus, said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are expecting an overwhelming number of volunteers and
will not turn anyone away for reasons other than ineligibility,
such as not meeting the criteria of being at-risk for HIV, said
Nicole Lynch, a spokeswoman for the AIDS ReSEARCH Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 5,000 volunteers will take part from as many as 50
sites across North America, including Philadelphia, St. Louis,
Washington, D.C., Denver and others that have not been selected
yet.
</P>
<P>
   For more information or to volunteer for the study, call the
AIDS ReSEARCH Alliance at (310) 358-2430.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors will give the vaccine to two-thirds of the volunteers,
while the remaining third will receive a placebo, an injection that
doesn't contain the vaccine. Neither the doctors nor the volunteers
will know which injection they receive, said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of three years, the volunteers will receive seven
injections of the vaccine along with counseling on how to avoid HIV
infection and risky behavior. However, researchers expect a portion
of the volunteers will become infected with HIV in the hopes the
vaccine will protect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``By comparing the rate of infection of those with the vaccine
to the rate of infection of those with the placebo, we can tell to
what extent the vaccine reduced the risk of getting infected,''
said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Side effects include a slight fever, sore arms, fatigue and
muscle aches. For Linden, the side effects were his biggest worry,
but still it didn't deter him from volunteering, especially after
he watched his friends suffer as they dealt with the physical toll
of AIDS and HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about giving back to people,'' said Linden, who works in
advertising for a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The thought that his actions might one day be historic hadn't
crossed Linden's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overwhelming to think about,'' said Linden. ``It's being
so close to so many people who have the disease and seeing what
they go through. ... I just can do what I can do right now. And
that's all.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 0025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
