<HEADER>
A5128 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-INDIANS-T     08-21 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-INDIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PUT THE PINCH ON INDIANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates removed center
fielder Tom Goodwin for a pinch hitter during the bottom of the
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Indians manager Mike Hargrove forced the move by summoning
left-hander Tom Martin from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Oates countered with reserve outfielder Roberto Kelly from the
bench, and the right-handed batter deposited Martin's 3-2 pitch
into Greene's Hill for a game-clinching, three-run homer during the
Rangers' 8-2 victory last night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave us a little bit of breathing time for the first time
since Saturday,'' Oates said of the 407-foot blast that gave the
Rangers a 6-1 advantage. ``That was a good pass at the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The triumph gave the Rangers a sweep of their two-game series
with the Central Division's best and ensured that the American
League West-leading Angels will enter tonight's games with no more
than 11/2-game advantage in the division.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Todd Stottlemyre (3-1) earned the victory despite
his failure to complete the sixth inning for the third time in four
starts with the Rangers, but left-hander Eric Gunderson and
right-hander Danny Patterson gave the Rangers 32/3 scoreless
innings to preserve the triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing good baseball,'' said Patterson, who
recorded four strikeouts during 22/3 scoreless innings. ``I don't
know if we haven't been getting any breaks, but we've been playing
against some tough teams. To come home and take two from Cleveland
picks us up and gives us a little momentum going into our series
with the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin vs. Kelly _ a mismatch on paper _ played true to form.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly stepped into the batter's box hitting .349 with six home
runs and 17 runs batted in during 106 previous at-bats this season
against left-handers. Martin allowed right-handed hitters a .343
batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove summoned Martin after an infield single by shortstop
Royce Clayton advanced designated hitter Mike Simms to second with
one out. Oates removed the left-handed hitting Goodwin for a
right-handed batter, and Kelly responded with his first home run of
his career as a pinch hitter. His 12 home runs rank second only to
Simms' 14 among major-league players with 200 or fewer at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good hitter,'' said right fielder Juan Gonzalez, whose
second-inning, solo home run off right-hander Dave Burba (10-9)
gave the Rangers the early lead. ``This is one of the best benches
in the league. The guys there have great numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre departed with a 3-1 lead, but Gunderson inherited a
bases-loaded jam with only one out. The left-hander kept the damage
to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Indians designated hitter David Justice scored on the ground
ball off the bat of center fielder Kenny Lofton, but shortstop
Royce Clayton retired Omar Vizquel on the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime I come in, it's crucial _ especially 3-1 with the
bases loaded,'' Gunderson said. ``I was just looking to get a
ground ball hit into the infield.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunderson then retired second baseman Torey Lovullo on strikes
with a 3-2 changeup to terminate the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of nerves to throw a changeup there, and
Lovullo didn't have a chance against it,'' Oates said. ``That's a
nice pitch to have in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunderson retired left fielder Brian Giles for the first out of
the seventh inning before giving way to Patterson, who recorded his
second save.
</P>
</TEXT>
