<SLUG> BC-NY-NJ-RAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN FOR TRACK FROM STATEN ISLAND TO N.J. IS IMPERILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A half-finished freight rail link between Staten
Island and New Jersey was dealt a setback Thursday when an official
in Union County, N.J., moved to pull out of the joint project,
saying that changes in the plan meant that New York City now stood
to reap nearly all the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The move outraged the Giuliani administration, which with the
help of federal money has rebuilt tracks and a bridge across the
Arthur Kill that would give New York City freight direct access to
the world west of the Hudson for the first time in nearly a decade.
The New Jersey section of the project, a five-mile link to
Conrail's main north-south tracks, is still being designed. One New
York official said the project was now a ``bridge to nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Union County Manager Michael Lapolla recommended Thursday that
the county's Board of Freeholders withdraw from the project at the
next board meeting. He said that the project originally called for
the operator to provide local freight rail service for businesses
in New Jersey towns. Now, he said, Norfolk Southern/CSX, the
freight giant recently appointed to operate the rail link, planned
to use the New Jersey part of the track solely as a means to take
freight from Howland Hook Marine Terminal on Staten Island to
Conrail's Lehigh Valley line, on larger trains than were originally
contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, which is
coordinating the project, and environmental groups that have
supported it criticized Lapolla, saying he was overlooking an
important benefit of the project: It would get thousands of trucks
off Union County's congested roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the tremendous regional benefits for both New York
and New Jersey, it would be shortsighted if this project did not
move forward,'' said Christopher Ward, the Port Authority's chief
of planning and external affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state of New Jersey owns the track on the New
Jersey side and could complete the link without Union County's
approval, state transportation officials said they would not
interfere.
</P>
<P>
   New York City, New Jersey, the federal government and the Port
Authority have provided $30 million for the link.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Millard, president of the New York City Economic
Development Corp., the agency in charge of New York's part of the
project, said he hoped the Board of Freeholders would defy Lapolla
at its meeting on Aug. 27. But the nine freeholders tend to go
along with the county government, and Lapolla said he consulted
them before making his recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   The disputed project began in 1994. On the Staten Island side,
New York City has bought and rebuilt 15 miles of track on the north
shore of Staten Island and refurbished the 39-year-old Arthur Kill
Lift Bridge, which has a 500-foot-long span that can be raised 100
feet to let ships pass through. The bridge has not been used since
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Rail access, Ward said, is crucial to the future of the Howland
Hook Terminal, near the base of the bridge, which was reopened in
1996. Howland Hook handles about 65,000 freight containers a year,
less than 5 percent of the total volume of the Port of New York and
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey section of the project runs west though
Elizabeth, Linden, Roselle and Cranford before linking up with the
Conrail's Lehigh Valley line, one of the main freight lines in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   As originally conceived, Lapolla said _ and state and Port
Authority officials agree _ the operator of the line would have
been a small freight carrier that would offer freight service to
industries along the line and along another stretch of track west
of the Lehigh Valley line. This, Lapolla said, would have allowed
the county to market and redevelop several vacant industrial
parcels and ``brownfields.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point of us being involved in this was to redevelop
abandoned, underutilized properties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But after Norfolk Southern and CSX reached an agreement to take
over Conrail's operations earlier this year, the conglomerate,
which is the largest freight carrier east of the Mississippi,
expressed an interest in operating the line itself.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the agencies involved in the project _ including Union
County _ appointed Norfolk Southern/CSX to run the line. But at a
meeting last month, Lapolla said, Norfolk Southern/CSX officials
told him they did not intend to offer local service immediately and
instead planned to upgrade the track to run bigger, heavier trains
from Howland Hook on Staten Island. Norfolk Southern/CSX officials
would not comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lapolla blamed the Port Authority for failing to insure that the
county got the rail access it was offered. He called the situation
``another example of the county getting the short end of the
stick'' from the authority, which owns more than 2,000 acres there,
mostly at Port Elizabeth and Newark International Airport. For
years, Union County and Elizabeth have been trying to get the Port
Authority to increase the $1.7 million a year it pays in lieu of
property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   There are other possibilities for moving freight off Staten
Island by rail. The Port Authority has proposed building a
connection from the New Jersey side of the Arthur Kill Lift Bridge
to existing freight tracks on the Chemical Coast line, which runs
through a stretch of refineries along Union County's waterfront.
But that link is opposed by the Elizabeth Mayor J. Christian
Bollwage. And even if it is approved, it is about a year behind the
other link, Ward of the Port Authority said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
