<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NYTEAMS-PROSPECTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY THE PLAYERS THEMSELVES CAN STOP GIANTS AND JETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ A few days ago, New York Giants
defensive lineman Keith Hamilton, one of the key players on the
best young defense in pro football, did a dual no-no. First, he
missed a scheduled appointment with team trainers for treatment on
a leg injury. That amounted to a fine of more than $1,000. Then he
was late for a meeting. The coaches were not happy, so after
scolding Hamilton, he was fined again.
</P>
<P>
   In all, he paid thousands of dollars in fines within hours.
</P>
<P>
   This early in the season, nothing should be blown out of
proportion, especially with Hamilton, usually a solid football
citizen. Besides, it's not as if he cut a teammate with scissors
(oops, wrong team). But for a Giants team that played so well last
season but faces a much tougher challenge _ going from division
champion to advancing deep in the playoffs _ Hamilton's episode is
still a small danger sign.
</P>
<P>
   It leads to this question: Do the Giants players, especially key
ones like Hamilton, realize the sacrifices it will take to win the
division again, and then make a run at the conference title?
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the New York Jets. Last week against the
Baltimore Ravens, they looked like a team on the bottom, not a team
some have picked to win the American Conference East. After the
game, many players had cleared out and were on their way home
before the vocal cords of coach Bill Parcells stopped vibrating in
the locker room. One of the first players to leave was wide
receiver Wayne Chrebet, who looked terrible against Baltimore.
Parcells knew it, which is why this week during an intense practice
he chewed out Chrebet.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' coach seemed to be asking Chrebet and his teammates
the same question that hopefully Giants players have asked
themselves: Do you realize the high price it will take to build on
last year's solid season?
</P>
<P>
   Many expect either the Giants or the Jets to take a step back
from last season's success because each team will play a tougher
schedule. But that doesn't have to happen. The Giants and the Jets
have assembled enough talent to make the playoffs. The only thing
that will stop them is the players themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the San Francisco 49ers are successful every
year is because players such as Jerry Rice and Steve Young seldom
miss meetings or treatment sessions. The Denver quarterback John
Elway studies year round. Wide receiver Cris Carter takes part in
the Minnesota Vikings' off-season program every year _ and then
does his own intense workouts. His work ethic and professionalism
set the tone for the rest of the team.
</P>
<P>
   More than the usual episodes of sloppy play or arrogance can
lead to disaster and can prevent a team from making that gigantic
step from good to great, from division winner to conference
champion. Giants coach Jim Fassel is one of the best young coaches
in the game _ he may be the best _ and has already stressed to the
team a number of times that the players must almost be perfect to
better last season's 10-5-1 record. Parcells has done the same with
his team, which went from 1-15 in 1996 to 9-7 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is only so much a coach can do. He can prepare the
players, warn them, scream at them, fine them, whatever it takes to
get their attention. But in the end, much of what happens is on the
shoulders of the players themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There are some Giants who a coach can simply turn on and watch
them go. Linebacker Jessie Armstead, defensive lineman Michael
Strahan and fullback Charles Way are true pros. On the Jets,
offensive tackle Jumbo Elliott and linebacker Pepper Johnson are
two of the harder working players in the league.
</P>
<P>
   What both teams have to worry about is the players whose
attitudes act like an anchor, weighing the team down. Luckily for
the Giants, they have many more men on their roster like Sam
Garnes, a talented and hard working safety, than they do in Tito
Wooten. Wooten has been able to fool some who have bought into his
St. Tito act, but there is no question he is still the same old
cocky Wooten. He missed much of the off-season workout program. In
training camp, he has been mouthing off to some of the Giants
coaches, once in full view of a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Since Wooten has a history of violence against women, he was
told by the team to see a therapist, according to several of his
teammates. But he has missed some of those sessions, the players
said. These are the kinds of things that great players don't do.
And please don't blame Wooten's recent actions on management or the
coaches or anyone else; it is all on Wooten.
</P>
<P>
   Wooten is a game breaker, but talent alone doesn't win
championships. Mental discipline and work ethic do. Great teams
know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can win,'' Armstead said. ``But how much we win depends on
the players and how hard we work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
