<SLUG> BC-NY-FERRARO-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO TURNS TESTY WITH TV INTERVIEWER OVER REPEATED REQUESTS TO
DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A routine television interview with Geraldine Ferraro
turned into an on- and off-air scrap Thursday as her host
repeatedly pressed Ferraro about why she was declining invitations
to debate in the Senate Democratic primary race.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, flustered and angry, attacked her questioner, Marcia
Kramer of WCBS-TV, as unprofessional and sarcastically suggested
that she was on the payroll of one of Ferraro's rivals.
</P>
<P>
   With a control room full of technicians, producers and reporters
watching, Ferraro turned increasingly tense as Ms. Kramer pressed
the candidate on why she had declined several invitations to debate
her two major Democratic rivals, Mark Green and Charles Schumer.
The candidates have appeared in two public forums and are not
scheduled to do so again until the Sunday before the Sept. 15
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've debated the other two people,'' Ferraro said as the
taping of ``Sunday Edition'' began with Ms. Kramer explaining to
viewers that Ferraro had declined to appear unless it was apart
from Green and Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   The two women continued to talk over one another, with Ms.
Kramer challenging Ferraro to agree to a debate right on the spot.
The candidate finally turned to her host and said, ``Do you think
you're doing a disservice to your viewers by focusing on the
politics of debates, rather than where I stand on issues?''
</P>
<P>
   When the segment ended for an advertisement, Ferraro turned up
the tenor of her complaints to Ms. Kramer. ``What attack issue are
you taking next?'' she inquired archly, her off-air remarks blaring
over the speakers in the control room. ``I was curious which
campaign you are working for.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Kramer defended her question as legitimate, Ferraro shook
her head in disagreement. ``Unprofessional,'' she said.
``Unprofessional. Let's move on.''
</P>
<P>
   After the appearance, Ferraro's aides said that she had been
ambushed because she had been brought in on the pretense that it
would be a regular interview. Ferraro said that Ms. Kramer had done
the ``Green spin on this,'' adding, ``Marcia's annoyed because we
didn't agree to do a debate with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro considers herself the front-runner in the race and, as
such, she is following a standard course in trying to minimize
debates. The candidates have appeared together twice, and neither
debate was televised.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro has said that debates are time-consuming for her
campaign and more likely to produce damaging attacks among the
candidates than insights on what they stand for. Ferraro was
largely ignored by the other candidates in their last debate.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's encounter was unusual in that Ferraro, who has tried
to avoid making the kind of attacks on Green and Schumer that might
bring attention to their campaigns, exhibited no such restraint
when it came to WCBS-TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, the voters see through tabloid journalism and are
drawn to candidates who talk about the issues that appeal to them:
education, health care, the economy and the environment,'' said
Ferraro's spokesman, Stephen Gaskill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
