<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMBROWSKI, LASORDA SET TO TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Wayne Huizenga, outgoing owner of the Florida Marlins,
granted the Los Angeles Dodgers permission Thursday to interview
Florida general manager Dave Dombrowski.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers interim general manager Tom Lasorda is expected to speak
today with Dombrowski, who is in the final season of a multi-year
contract that is paying him $750,000 this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also received permission Thursday from Cincinnati
chief executive John Allen to speak with Reds G.M. Jim Bowden. But
the focus now is on Dombrowski, a favorite of the new owners at
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really isn't a lot I can say,'' Lasorda said. ``I am
waiting to hear from (Dodgers president) Bob Graziano. But I do
expect to start the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Dombrowski 40, refused to discuss the Dodgers opening, saying it
was inappropriate to discuss the future in the middle of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are hoping to have a new general manager in place by
the first week of October.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Dombrowski received an endorsement for the Dodgers'
job from an unlikely source.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield, who often battled with Dombrowski after joining
the Marlins in 1993, said he'd be a perfect choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those early years I was disappointed that the Marlins
weren't winning. It really got to me and I let him and everyone
know it,'' Sheffield said. ``I was young and immature. But then I
realized he wanted to win as much as I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him to be very honest and open to suggestions. I think
it would be great if he was the next G.M. of the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes returning: With right-hander Ismael Valdes scheduled to
return from the disabled list (strained left side) next Thursday,
someone was headed to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But strong performances by Brian Bohanon on Wednesday and Dave
Mlicki on Thursday have changed the Dodgers' plan. The Dodgers will
go with a six-man rotation for at least the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew something was going to happen but I tried to stay
focused on what I had to do,'' said Mlicki, who walked five Marlins
Thursday but limited them to three hits and one run in seven
innings. ``I haven't felt pressure. I figured if you pitch well
things will take care of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Remembering: Former Marlins on their return to Miami for the
first time since the May 15 Mike Piazza trade:
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we all had a lot of fun here,'' Bobby Bonilla said.
``But I think we're all moving on. Winning that series was great
for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Charles Johnson: ``I finally got to sleep in my own bed
last night. For the first month out there I lived in a hotel in
downtown Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Jim Eisenreich, who walked with the bases loaded in
the 10th inning Thursday to give the Dodgers a 2-1 victory:
``Mentally I'm doing OK. Physically I'm doing OK. Baseball-wise,
I'm doing terribly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
