<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-LIBERTY-DEFEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE UPS, LIBERTY ENDS ON DOWN NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Less than a week ago, the question was not
whether the New York Liberty was going to make the playoffs, but
how far the team would go.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty had won 10 of its last 11 games and had scored a
70-54 victory over the Houston Comets, the defending Women's
National Basketball Association champion, before a sellout crowd at
Madison Square Garden. Last Saturday's triumph over the Comets was
easily the high point of a season filled with ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, with a chance to finish first in the Eastern
Conference, the Liberty lost to the Cleveland Rockers, whose 70-64
victory at the garden clinched the top spot for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty's 82-68 road loss to the Detroit Shock on Wednesday
night, after New York blew a 14-point first-half lead, concluded a
turn of events that ended New York's season: no first place and not
even a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   A victory against the Shock, an expansion team the Liberty had
beaten twice this season, would have locked up a playoff berth. But
the stunning defeat, which left many Liberty players teary-eyed and
shaking their heads in disbelief, put their post-season destiny in
the hands of two underdog teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty needed to have either Charlotte or Phoenix lose
Wednesday. But it never got the help it required. As expected,
Washington, a team that had won just three games all season, was
beaten by Charlotte, and Sacramento was defeated by Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs begin Saturday with Charlotte playing host to
Houston and Phoenix at home against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have been ours,'' Rebecca Lobo, who scored 12
points, said after the Liberty's defeat on Wednesday. ``But we just
handed it over to Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   Kym Hampton said of the Liberty's 18-12 season: ``It was kind of
a roller coaster. It was very emotional because we worked so hard
to get things going after our rough start.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty was 8-9 before a victory at Phoenix on July 18 that
started a stretch in which they won 10 of 11 games before losing
their final two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked so hard to make the playoffs,'' said Sophia
Witherspoon, who scored a game-high 26 points on Wednesday. ``But
unfortunately, we did not fulfill our destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
