<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-JETS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEHORN SIDELINED FOR YEAR, SO GIANTS LOSE TWICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also FBN-JETS-FOLEY) 
(mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New York Jets rallied to defeat the
New York Giants, 27-23, Thursday night in their annual preseason
game at Giants Stadium. But for the Giants and their fans, the game
will not be remembered for how it ended but how it began: Jason
Sehorn sustaining a season-ending knee injury returning the opening
kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn, whose role as a return man was considered risky because
it jeopardized one of the team's most valuable players, tore his
anterior cruciate and medial collateral ligaments at the end of a
33-yard runback when he fumbled the football and went down in a
tangle of bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn was tackled by the Jets' Chris Hayes and Ray Mickens with
Sehorn's right leg bending at an awkward angle beneath his body. He
will have reconstructive surgery in the next seven to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first kickoff that Sehorn, one of the fleetest
Giants, had returned for the team. The team had decided to use
Sehorn to return kickoffs because he asked to do so and because
their kickoff return average last season was the worst in the
National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   After limping to the sideline, Sehorn was briefly examined on
the bench by team doctors and then taken off the field on a cart so
his knee could be X-rayed. While being examined on the sideline,
Sehorn momentarily buried his head in a towel as several players
came over to console him. Giants coach Jim Fassel also stopped by
to talk to Sehorn.
</P>
<P>
   The winning score for the Jets came on an 81-yard touchdown pass
from the reserve quarterback Vinny Testaverde to wide receiver
Dedric Ward midway through the third quarter. The touchdown pass
came one play after Giants running back Tiki Barber spoiled what
had been a fruitful drive with a fumble at the Jets' 19-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde's pass to Ward was precisely thrown, arching just
over the Giants defender, the rookie safety Shaun Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' final possession in the last minutes of the fourth
quarter stalled at the Jets' 43-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the starting quarterbacks for the Jets and Giants
performed well. The Jets' Glenn Foley completed 14 of 22 passes for
192 yards with one touchdown and one interception. The Giants'
Danny Kanell completed 16 of 25 passes for 156 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the first half that the teams looked sharpest, with
the first-string offenses trading scores and moving up and down the
field in what was the best display of offense for either team
during the 1998 preseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets scored first, taking advantage of Sehorn's fumble.
Foley completed three passes in what was a six-play drive. The last
of the completions was a 3-yard touchdown pass to Wayne Chrebet.
Place-kicker John Hall missed the extra point attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' offense, looking crisp and efficient, answered with
a 10-play touchdown drive. Kanell completed all four of his passes
and Gary Brown made an impressive debut as the starting halfback,
running for 11 yards and a first down on his first rushing attempt
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The drive concluded with a 1-yard touchdown run by Barber. With
Brad Daluiso's extra point, the Giants led, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants added to that lead 48 seconds into the second quarter
when Daluiso kicked a 33-yard field goal. The kick was set up by
three Kanell passes _ two to Ike Hilliard and one to David Patten.
Showing surprising command of a variety of passes, Kanell seemed
especially in sync with Hilliard, who missed two practices this
week because of back stiffness.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets responded to the Giants' field goal with a Curtis
Martin score _ a 14-yard touchdown dash off left tackle. The
pivotal play in the drive was a 23-yard pass play from Foley _ who
would complete his first eight passes _ to Chrebet, who was wide
open over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing the Jets 13-10, the Giants regained the lead with
another convincing possession. Giants safety Percy Ellsworth
intercepted a Foley pass in the early moments of the third quarter,
returning it 42 yards for a touchdown to give the Giants a 23-13
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Almost exactly three minutes later, Jets punt returner Leon
Johnson caught a 39-yard punt by the Giants' reserve punter, Will
Brice, and returned it 65 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
