<HEADLINE>
PITCHER HILL GETS CHILLY RECEPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Pitcher Ken Hill said it was the cold weather
in Stockton on Tuesday night that caused discomfort in his
surgically repaired elbow and consequently forced him to take
himself out of his rehab start for Single-A Lake Elsinore.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins, however, wasn't taking it so lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't take yourself out if it's not serious,'' Collins
said. ``Therefore, it's serious to me. It may not be serious to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels thought Hill would be able to start Sunday
against Toronto, but because of the setback, he's looking at
another rehab start either Sunday or Monday, provided his sideline
workout today goes without problems.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, though, said he hasn't decided where Hill will make
that rehab start.
</P>
<P>
   ``If cold weather was part of the problem the other day, I'll
send him where it's hot,'' Collins said. ``I'll send him to the
equator if I have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels believe Hill's elbow pain was caused by a developing
arthritic condition or tendinitis _ or a combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do my sideline (work today) and see how it goes,'' Hill
said. ``We'll go day by day, but I feel I can pitch.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell sore, but OK: The Angels would love Hill to come back
the way Jack McDowell did. After being out for 2{ months with a bad
elbow, McDowell, a Notre Dame High graduate, threw seven scoreless
innings Wednesday against the Tigers in a 2-0 Angels win.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, McDowell's arm was sore but otherwise fine. He is
tentatively slated to start the series-opener Monday in New York
against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, though, said he has learned he can't count on having
the same five in the starting rotation for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through way too much to think for the next 38 games
I can write down five names, he said. ``You want it to happen, but
it's not going to.
</P>
<P>
   Collins is already planning ahead to the five-game series
against the Yankees, trying to set his rotation. McDowell will go
Monday, Omar Olivares on Tuesday, Jeff Juden in the first game of
the doubleheader Wednesday and Chuck Finley on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Collins hasn't decided about the second game of the doubleheader
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got options, Collins said. ``We could go with (Steve)
Sparks on three days rest, we've got (Jason) Dickson, (Jarrod)
Washburn, (Allen) Watson and (Shigetoshi) Hasegawa.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely the Angels will go with a left-hander, either
Washburn or Watson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
