<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLOM VS. COOPER? IT'S A TOSSUP 
</HEADLINE>
 MVP-GILLOM-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper or Jennifer Gillom?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to who is the WNBA's Most Valuable Player comes
Monday. If the timing of the announcement is any indication, then
it favors a repeat for Cooper because the Houston Comets return
home that day for the second game of a playoff series with
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect for a hometown splash, perhaps in a combination press
conference with the Comets' Van Chancellor for going 2 for 2 as
Coach of the Year, the other award to be announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury plays its only semifinal home game Saturday and will
be in Cleveland when the MVP winner is revealed. Not the best of
signs for Gillom, who in informal discussions with media voters
will be No. 1 or 2 on most ballots.
</P>
<P>
   With 10 points given for a first-place vote and seven for second
(on down through fifth), the 34-year-old Mercury center needs to
top at least 23 of 45 ballots and finish no lower than second on
the rest to win the award. Or to have Lisa Leslie siphon some
first- or second-place votes from Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   What seems certain is that Cooper, the 35-year-old shooting
guard whose 22.7 points-per-game average led her to a second
straight scoring title, will not approach her 254-point MVP margin
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year there was not a lot of conversation (about MVP),''
said Clay Kallam, publisher of ``Full'' ``Court Press,'' a women's
basketball journal. ``Overall, it's a good thing for the league and
a lot of fun. And it's great for Jennifer Gillom, who is starting
to get some publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sort of the goal of the league, to give (veteran)
American players a chance to show how they were. Three years ago,
if you'd have said Cynthia Cooper and Jennifer Gillom to a casual
fan, they'd have said `who?' In that way, regardless of who wins,
it's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   The affable Gillom agrees to a point but has been public all
season about the MVP being her goal and shrugs when asked what more
she could do to accomplish it.
</P>
<P>
   A close second ``would be disappointing,'' she said, ``because
everybody wants me to win it, and I want to win for them and of
course for myself, too. I think it would be great for Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gillom does not play for the defending champions. Or do high
visibility commercials for General Motors, Nike, Champion and the
league. (``Hey, you play like girls,'' Cooper says in one
commercial to some guys, who upon recognizing her respond with a
thanks.)
</P>
<P>
   Gillom has a catchy nickname, Grandmama, but not much more going
for her nationally, something that even a strong runner-up finish
could help to correct, particularly because her contract with the
league must be renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would help me to realize that people are starting to
recognize me and recognize my play,'' said Gillom, who plans to
play a lucrative second season in Turkey during the WNBA
off-season. She makes a six-figure salary overseas, compared with
the WNBA-maximum $62,500.
</P>
<P>
   Playing year-round is one factor in her favor over Cooper, who
did not return overseas, Gillom said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you I've been fighting those (sore) knees all summer
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down in the post area, you do get double-teamed and
triple-teamed a lot, and it's a lot easier in the open court. Plus
she's (Cooper) surrounded by three awesome players (Sheryl Swoopes,
Tina Thompson, Kim Perrot). It's a lot easier that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kallam said Cooper is the best player on the best women's team
in the world, but she's been criticized for friction in the locker
room. That opinion is shared by others familiar with the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   And he thinks the ``relentlessly positive'' WNBA paints a better
picture of Mercury guards Michele Timms and Bridget Pettis than
their play this season warrants, detracting from an understanding
of the load Gillom has carried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really comes down to how you define MVP,'' Kallam said.
``Is it who's the best player, or who is the most valuable player
to that team?
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooper has more skills, she can do more things. Especially
early in the year, when Houston was still interested, Cooper has
the ability to take over the game. It's a little easier to take
Jennifer out of the game by focusing on not letting her get the
ball. It comes down to what you like better, ice cream or steak?
There's not much to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie, who led the United States to a gold medal at the World
Championships just before the season began, has statistics that
equal Cooper and Gillom but could not lift the Los Angeles Sparks
into the playoffs or even to a .500 record.
</P>
<P>
   What eliminates Leslie from the running is the Sparks' 12-18
record, compared with the Comets' 27-3 mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I would do is wait and see what happens in the
playoffs,'' Kallam said.
</P>
<P>
   Or in the case of Cleveland Coach Linda Hill-MacDonald, whose
team has been raked for 93 points by Gillom this season, including
a WNBA season high 36 on Aug. 10, not choose at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to be the one to have to make a choice between
Jennifer and Cynthia,'' she said. ``Both have made tremendous
contributions to their team, that's evident in the sheer numbers
they've been putting up and defensively what they're capable of
doing. I'm glad I'm not in on the voting on that one.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 0042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
