<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES CARTER, 99, INTERNATIONAL BANKER  
 PHIL LEEDS, 82, COMIC ACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Calif.)   (bl) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Carter, 99, International Banker
</P>
<P>
   James Prescott Carter, an international banker and economic
consultant who also bred Aberdeen Angus cattle, died Aug. 10 at his
home in Keene, Va. He was 99.
</P>
<P>
   Carter worked for more than three decades as an executive of the
predecessor of Citibank in Spain, Belgium and Latin America and
spent another eight years as a consultant in Latin America and
Africa before retiring in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   As the bank's manager in Cuba he became concerned about the rise
of the revolutionary forces of Fidel Castro long before Castro
seized power in 1959 and began nationalizing foreign businesses.
His advice to begin reducing investments in Cuba was credited with
sharply limiting the bank's losses.
</P>
<P>
   Carter had bought a 450-acre cattle farm in Virginia in the
1940s and when he stopped consulting in 1963 he began spending much
of his time there breeding prize-winning Aberdeen Angus. Among his
customers were several state agriculture departments. He sold the
farm in 1983 and had been living in Keene since.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who earned a bachelor's degree in chemical engineering
at the Virginia Military Institute and a master's degree in
economics at the University of Wisconsin, started his career in
Madrid in 1921 with what was then known as the National City Bank,
with headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is survived by five daughters, Katherine Parker of
Madison, Tenn.; Susan Miller of Richmond; Rachel Brown of York,
Pa.; Enriqueta Bond of Pittsboro, N.C., and Adelaide Ruffner of
Charlottesville, Va.; 11 grandchildren, and five
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Harriette Mortley Bovard, died in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Leeds, 82, Comic Actor
</P>
<P>
   Phil Leeds, a durable funnyman who began his pursuit of laughs
as a stand-up comic in the 1930s and went on to work in theater,
films and television, died Aug. 16 at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center
in Los Angeles. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Leeds' rumpled face _ ``I'm not pretty, but I'm warm and
feisty,'' he told an interviewer _ was a familiar one to television
viewers. Indeed, in May he appeared in the final episodes of four
television series on the same night: ``Ally McBeal,'' ``Ellen,''
``Everybody Loves Raymond'' and ``Murphy Brown.'' Over the years he
made guest appearances on dozens of shows, including ``All in the
Family,'' ``Maude,'' ``The Golden Girls,'' ``Barney Miller,''
``Roseanne'' and ``The Larry Sanders Show.''
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, Leeds was a member of the Army Special
Service Unit during World War II and entertained troops in the
Pacific. After the war he returned to New York and performed at the
Village Vanguard, the Blue Angel and other clubs. He eventually won
parts in several Broadway shows, including ``Make a Wish,''
``Can-Can,'' ``Romanoff and Juliet'' and ``Nobody Loves an
Albatross.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s he appeared with Jose Ferrer in a successful
production of Neil Simon's comedy ``The Sunshine Boys'' in San
Francisco. He also performed in the musical ``Two Gentlemen of
Verona'' at the Los Angeles Music Center in 1973. His film credits
included ``Rosemary's Baby,'' ``Beaches,'' ``Enemies, A Love
Story'' and ``Soapdish.''
</P>
<P>
   No immediate family members survive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
