<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-FOLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FOLEY TAKES OFF AND FLIGHT IS SMOOTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also FBN-GIANTS-JETS) 
(mk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ After a summer of inconsistency, Glenn
Foley on Thursday night finally produced the quick-strike effort
that coach Bill Parcells expected in naming him the New York Jets'
starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it without much of a running game. Although it was
only an exhibition game against the Giants, won by the Jets 27-23,
it was also merely the seventh start of Foley's rocky National
Football League career.
</P>
<P>
   He had completed only 11 of 28 passes in the first two
exhibition games, he had averaged under 4 yards an attempt, he had
been intercepted twice. But Thursday night Foley drilled his first
nine passes complete and was 13 for 18 in the opening half, good
for 162 yards. His 3-yard pass to Wayne Chrebet opened the scoring
in the 27-23 victory over the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Foley suffered a lapse to open the second half when his first
pass was intercepted by Percy Ellsworth and returned for a 42-yard
touchdown. Still, by the time Foley was replaced in the third
quarter by Vinny Testaverde, he had completed 14 of 22 passes for
192 yards. He suffered the one interception, threw the one
touchdown and was sacked twice.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Foley's favorite target was Keyshawn Johnson,
with whom he hopes to collaborate on big plays for many years to
come. He threw the ball in Johnson's direction seven times in the
opening half. Johnson snared five for 69 yards. For the game, Foley
and Johnson collaborated on six receptions for 99 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need the work,'' Foley, who has started only five
regular-season games, repeats daily after practice. ``I need as
much work as I can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday night, Parcells may not have been sure what he
had. A year ago in the exhibition season, Foley was coming off the
bench for Neil O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jets-Giants game last summer, Foley was the club's golden
boy. He came in to relieve O'Donnell and tossed a touchdown to
rookie Dedric Ward as the Jets won. A week later, against Tampa
Bay, he again replaced O'Donnell, brought the Jets into overtime,
and tossed a 48-yarder to Chrebet to position the Jets' winning
score.
</P>
<P>
   That capped a preseason in which he was 13 for 19 for 208 yards.
But he was also coming off the bench, and as far as Parcells is
concerned, that is not the same as having the pressure of starting.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Foley's spectacular summer last year even created some
speculation that he might start the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil O'Donnell is my quarterback,'' said Parcells when asked
Foley's chances to start.
</P>
<P>
   But now Foley is the starter, even though in Game 2 of the
preseason, against the Ravens, Testaverde got the nod.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the opening touchdown, Foley led the Jets on a
smart 69-yard scoring drive by completing three straight passes
that got the Jets to the Giants' 14. From there, Curtis Martin
swept left for 14 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was the only Jet to carry the ball in the opening half.
His eight carries produced 30 yards, although for the second
consecutive game he was stopped on a run needing a yard for the
first down.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was a game plan apparently designed to get the Jets'
passing attack moving. The Jets had not even averaged 5 yards an
attempt in splitting the first two preseason games. Parcells
believes that Martin will be ganged up on by opposition defenses if
they sense the Jets are reluctant to throw.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Jets established Thursday night is that they are
willing to wing it, and do it behind Foley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
