<SLUG> BC-NY-ARSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEUD BETWEEN TWO FOOT DOCTORS LED TO ARSON, AUTHORITIES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)  (js) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For 15 years they worked side by side in their Queens
podiatry practice. But in the past year, Dr. Irwin Sater, 65,
decided to put his three-and-a-half decades in podiatry behind him,
so he sold the practice to his junior partner and moved to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   That is when the feud began. As the junior partner, Dr. Steven
Mehl, 44, took over the practice, law enforcement officials said,
he discovered what he believed were financial irregularities, so he
made a series of angry phone calls to Florida threatening to stop
payments on the practice.
</P>
<P>
   The fight became so intense that on July 31, the authorities
said, Sater flew to New York from Florida and set fire to Mehl's
office. Thursday morning, Sater surrendered to fire marshals in
Queens. He was being held Thursday night while awaiting arraignment
on charges of arson in the fourth degree and burglary, said Maureen
Moore, a spokeswoman for the Queens district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He set the blaze in the basement, where the financial records
used to be kept, but they had been moved,'' one law enforcement
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Sater's arrest came after an intensive investigation by the fire
marshals, who deemed the July 31 fire suspicious from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Sater's lawyer, Samuel Gregory, denied the charges. ``Dr. Sater
is a wonderful man,'' Gregory said. ``He's probably done more good
than 99 percent of the population. As soon as he was notified that
he was a suspect in some wrongdoing he contacted me and came up
from Florida.''
</P>
</TEXT>
