</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ACCESS FEES AND THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in editorial on Fri., Aug. 21:
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court decision this week should benefit
Internet users and the fast-growing electronic information industry
by holding down connection costs. The decision upheld the authority
of the Federal Communications Commission to exempt Internet service
providers from interstate access charges paid to local phone
companies. The issue was raised in a lawsuit by telecommunications
companies challenging federal regulations intended to deregulate
the industry. The lengthy decision by the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals allows the agency to get on with that task without
dampening growth in the electronic information sector.
</P>
<P>
   The local phone companies have argued that Internet services
should have to pay the same access fees that long-distance carriers
pay for using the local phone lines. But the FCC contends that
Internet services are not equivalent to long-distance carriers and
do not use local systems in the same way. Imposing access fees
would very likely have caused online services to raise their rates,
and perhaps abandon the flat-fee structure that has attracted
millions of customers to online services.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC policy was created in 1983, recognizing that the nascent
electronic information industry needed breathing room to develop.
Last year the FCC decided that keeping the access fee exemption for
online services was still appropriate to avoid disrupting the
still-evolving industry. The agency also is not convinced that
Internet services impose uncompensated costs on the local phone
companies or that congestion on local phone lines warrants the
imposition of new charges. That judgment may change in the future _
but it is one for the agency to make without judicial interference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
