<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BASEBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SLUGGERS AWAKEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Ill., Mo.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Fri., Aug. 21:
</P>
<P>
   For a moment there it appeared that baseball's most hallowed
record _ Roger Maris' 61 home runs in a single season, set in 1961
_ might be safe for yet another year. Nobody was throwing hittable
pitches to Maris' two main threats, Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs
and Mark McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals, and both men seemed to
be tiring as the season entered its final months. Sosa hit 20 home
runs in June, only nine in July. By his own account, McGwire has
been little more than an ``ornament'' in the last seven weeks, with
45 strikeouts and only 10 homers since July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Then the two teams collided in Chicago on Wednesday, and
baseball's most intriguing two-man show was back in business. Sosa
seized the home run lead with his 48th homer in the fifth inning,
only to see McGwire take it back with his 48th and 49th. Still
rolling, McGwire hit his 50th and 51st against the New York Mets on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the interesting aspects of this assault on Maris' record
is what it says about the importance of power to baseball.
Spectacular fielding plays are fun to watch, and a no-hitter is a
rare thrill, but nothing quite captures the imagination like a home
run. In a recent tribute to Babe Ruth's magnificent 1927 season,
when he hit 60 home runs, Sports Illustrated suggested that Ruth
had singlehandedly changed the face of the game, elevating the home
run from ``its relatively modest role into baseball's most dramatic
event and a significant force in determining the outcome of a
game.'' The sluggers are also good for baseball's balance sheet.
The Cardinals are drawing capacity crowds despite a disappointing
season, and wherever they go, Sosa and McGwire attract thousands of
people who would otherwise have stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   They could not have picked a better year. Only one of major
league baseball's six regional divisions has produced a compelling
race. The only race of any national interest is the race between
Sosa and McGwire, who are chasing not only each other but the ghost
of Roger Maris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
