<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FIREMEN-BRAWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES DROPPED AGAINST MAN ACCUSED IN FIREFIGHTERS' CAFE BRAWL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prosecutors dropped assault and related charges
Thursday against a restaurant bouncer who was the only person
charged in a June brawl involving dozens of firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to drop the charges against the bouncer, Ethan
Kemp, means that no one has been held criminally liable in the
case, although several firefighters were disciplined by the Fire
Department. In dropping the charges against Kemp, prosecutors
concluded that he was trying to separate battling firefighters when
he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp's lawyer, Anthony Fusco Jr., said Thursday that the
30-year-old bouncer would be filing a multi-million dollar lawsuit
against the city accusing the police of wrongful arrest, malicious
prosecution and violating Kemp's civil rights during the June 3
fracas at the Bryant Park Grill in midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, who is black, said he believed race played a role in his
arrest. The majority of the firefighters involved in the fighting,
none of whom were arrested, are white. Marilyn Mode, a spokeswoman
for the Police Department, had no comment on Kemp's charge.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement investigators who spoke on condition of
anonymity said Thursday that they were still determining whether to
file criminal charges against firefighters. But their
investigation, they said, has been hindered because firefighters
have refused to offer much information about the brawl.
</P>
<P>
   A law enforcement official also said witnesses have described
more serious misconduct than outlined in a Fire Department
investigation released last month. On July 2, Fire Commissioner
Thomas Von Essen punished 11 firefighters by reducing their pay and
declared the department's investigation closed.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, department investigators said that accounts of an
evening of chaos at the restaurant _ involving fistfights, patrons
being harassed and firefighters urinating in bushes _ were
exaggerated. The firefighters had gone to the restaurant after
taking part in Medal Day ceremonies in which heroic firefighters
were honored at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Department spokesman Michael Regan said the department,
while not excusing the firefighters' behavior, concluded its
investigation last month. ``The department disciplined 11
firefighters for their role at the Bryant Park Grill,'' he said.
``This ends a sad chapter in the department's history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
