<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MET-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HARTMANN WINS MET OPEN FOR 4th TITLE OF YEAR  
(mk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCUST VALLEY, N.Y. _ Rick Hartmann, who arrived in the
metropolitan area six years ago after playing for 10 years on the
European tour, is starting to spread fear among golfers in the
area, the way Bruce Zabriski and Darrell Kestner have done for the
last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Hartmann captured the $100,000 Met Open by a shot Thursday with
a sizzling seven-under-par 63 on the difficult Creek Club course
here after starting the day five shots behind the leaders. His
bogeyless round included seven birdies and he finished the 54-hole
event with a total of 203 for his fourth victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's now the premier player in the area,'' Kestner, who shot
69 and finished second at 204, said about Hartmann, the head pro at
Atlantic Golf Club, who also won the Long Island Open, the Long
Island PGA and the head pro championship this season. ``This is his
time; he's the best player in the section,'' Kestner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big tournament to win on a great golf course like
this,'' said Hartmann, who earned $20,000 by winning the most
prestigious tournament in the area. ``It's particularly satisfying
because I beat Kestner and because I let it get away last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartmann and Kestner, the head pro at nearby Deepdale, who
earned $10,000, are inseparable friends. Hartmann stayed at
Kestner's house for the tournament. Hartmann said jokingly that he
was angry at Kestner Thursday morning because his host failed to
make coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``His name deserves to be on the trophy,'' said Kestner, who was
seeking his fourth title in the tournament. ``Shooting 63 here is
taking it to the limit. It's a remarkable round.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartmann started the day five shots behind Kestner and Greg
Rohlf of Wykagyl, who shot 71 and finished at 206, which tied him
for fourth with Jean-Paul Hebert (70) of Garden City Country Club.
Rohlf was the low amateur here and the winner of the Ike, the
stroke-play championship of the Metropolitan Golf Association.
</P>
<P>
   Rohlf had the lead after three consecutive birdies, but he
bogeyed three of the last eight holes, while Kestner's round
included two birdies and a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gilmore, the head pro at nearby Wheatley Hills Golf Club,
shot his second round of 69 and finished alone in third at 205.
Mike Burke Jr. of Mountain Ridge, last year's winner, shot 68
Thursday after two rounds of 72 and finished at 212, while
Zabriski, the teaching pro at Westchester and the winner two years
ago and also in 1993, shot 70 and finished at 213.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
