r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CASSTEVENS-ACADEM     08-21 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CASSTEVENS-ACADEMICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO EXCUSE FOR PLAYERS TO FAIL CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andy Katzenmoyer, the All-Everything linebacker for No. 1-ranked
Ohio State, may be ruled academically ineligible if he doesn't
bring up his grades in summer school.
</P>
<P>
   Buckeyes fans are wringing hands and gnashing teeth.
</P>
<P>
   As Andy burns the midnight oil, a campus newspaper headline sums
up the impact of this crisis: ``Eligibility May Affect Football
Rankings.''
</P>
<P>
   Grades will come out soon. The suspense is awful.
</P>
<P>
   Can Andy pass Music?
</P>
<P>
   Will he flunk AIDS Awareness?
</P>
<P>
   If he aces both courses, and fails Golf, is the season over?
</P>
<P>
   These are actual credit courses Katzenmoyer is taking. If the
NCAA scholar-athlete fails to bring up his average and isn't in
uniform for the Sept. 5 opener against West Virginia, well, it's
difficult to imagine the depth of disappointment and hurt those who
believe in him, trust him, and support him will feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a human being,'' Katzenmoyer said. ``I make mistakes. I
have flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy sounds almost presidential.
</P>
<P>
   The intent here isn't to call into question Ohio State's
curriculum. Every school offers a Heinz variety of electives.
</P>
<P>
   When he coached at Oklahoma City, Abe Lemons said he instructed
five of his basketball players to enroll in basket-weaving. Unknown
to the coach, one of the players was part Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kid broke the curve,'' Abe said. ``The other four flunked.''
</P>
<P>
   I once asked Charles Barkley what he majored in at Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music Appreciation,'' Barkley lied, flashing a grin. ``It was
great. I went to this class and they played music. After class I
told the teacher, `I ``appreciate'' that!' I got an A.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the worst occur, Katzenmoyer has no one to blame but
himself. Ohio State has a fleet of academic counselors. The school
provides support services for all its athletes.
</P>
<P>
   But Ohio State can't attend class for a player. It can't take
notes for him. It can't take his exam. NCAA athletes must make some
effort to expand their minds and show progress toward a degree
based on a five-year timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he holds his breath each summer while awaiting grade
reports, Arizona State Coach Bruce Snyder said, ``I think 112 (NCAA
Division I) head coaches do, collectively. Most of us have some
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU safety Mitchell Freedman attended Mesa Community College in
the spring and ASU during the summer and regained eligibility for
his senior season. Fright Night is with the team in camp. Three
others are conspicuously absent.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder doesn't know whether tailback Marlon Farlow, wide
receiver Ricky Boyer and linebacker Larry Johnson have met
classroom requirements this summer that will allow them to play.
All are seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Farlow earned the team's Most Improved award last season and is
penciled in as J.R. Redmond's backup. Boyer has game-breaking
speed. A starter last year, Johnson is one player the Sun Devils
don't want to lose. But they may be without all three. Snyder
doesn't sound optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the support available, if they don't succeed
academically, it's their choice,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a player needs a tutor, he's got a tutor. Some people are
more gifted than others. Not everybody is a Rhodes scholar.''
</P>
<P>
   But . . . ``If he's unsuccessful'' _ meaning he doesn't maintain
his eligibility _ ``he chose to sleep in.''
</P>
<P>
   The sad truth is, some don't value education or begin to
understand the importance of a college degree.
</P>
<P>
   When Snyder, a full scholarship in hand, visits a recruit and
his parents in their home, more times than not, he finds himself
competing with a blaring TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very important to your son,'' Snyder says. Without
asking, he turns the set off. ``Please, just give me 30 minutes of
your time.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
