u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWIM-E.GERMANY-DRUGS-     08-21 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIM-E.GERMANY-DRUGS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 GUILTY OF GIVING DRUGS TO EAST GERMAN ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Two doctors and a swimming trainer from the former East
Germany were convicted and fined here Thursday on charges of
systematically feeding growth-enhancing steroids to young athletes,
the first conviction in what is expected to be a long line of
trials over drugging athletes under the old Communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   Coming nearly nine years after the fall of the Berlin Wall, the
conviction gives new impetus to investigations of senior political
officials in East Germany who are suspected of having orchestrated
a national program to beef up promising athletes, many of them in
their early teens at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's decision came after all three former sports officials
admitted this week that they regularly gave steroids and other
hormones to female swimmers. Each of the three publicly apologized.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not alone. Numerous women have filed lawsuits
charging that their former coaches gave them male hormones without
telling them, and some argue that they still suffer from side
effects that include deeper voices, skin problems and infertility.
More than 90 formal criminal investigations are under way,
prosecutors here say, and another drug trial of six doctors and
trainers could reach a conclusion in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   All the activity stems in part from a treasure trove of recently
uncovered information from the former East German secret service,
the Stasi. As a result, a growing number of coaches and doctors are
breaking their silence and admitting their activities, though they
blame their superiors. The first public admission by a former East
German sports doctor came last month and was followed by Thursday's
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The three people convicted Thursday oversaw a Berlin swimming
club that groomed athletes for East Germany's national teams. They
were Ulrich Sunder, the club's head doctor; Dorit Rosler, a second
team doctor; and Peter Mattonet, the team's trainer. Because the
three confessed and expressed regret for giving out the hormones,
the judge limited their punishments to fines ranging from about
$3,900 to $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Two other trainers in the club admitted to handing out steroid
pills, but the charges were dropped after they agreed to pay
smaller fines.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the former swimmers was in court, because the trial
did not rely on testimony from any of the former athletes. The one
athlete present was Karen Konig, who had filed her own complaint
alongside the prosecutors' indictments. Konig, a rising star during
the 1980s, has complained that her trainers never told her about
the nature of the hormones they were providing and ignored side
effects like her deepened voice and intensified acne problems.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the trial, Rosler walked over to Konig with an
outstretched hand. ``I look forward to being able to look at each
other in the eye again,'' Rosler said. Konig hesitated before
awkwardly shaking Rosler's hand, but made it clear she did not want
to let the matter drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that this decision means we can move on to the next
level, those who had political responsibility,'' she said outside
the courtroom.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Christian Paschen, a lawyer representing Konig and three other
former athletes in another case, said the decision marked an
important advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time that sports officials have been
convicted of injuring athletes by systematically giving them
hormones, and it is important to note that all of the swimmers in
this case were minors,'' Paschen said. ``They knew what they were
doing, they knew about the possible side effects and they ignored
them when they became apparent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunder, the team's chief doctor, denied knowing much about the
side effects and said during the trial that his superiors had told
him that any damage would be temporary. But he too expressed regret
for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will have to live with my blame for the athletes,'' he told
DPA, the German press agency.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the verdicts, Judge Jurgen Warnatsch said the three
officials were part of a broader system. ``The doctors and trainers
were bound up in a state-run criminality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin's chief prosecutor, Christoph Schaefgen, told news
agencies that the conviction would help intensify investigations
into more senior government officials who organized the drug
program on a national basis. At the top of the list, Paschen said,
is the former head of East Germany's entire sports program, Manfred
Ewald.
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent targets are several high-ranking doctors who are
alleged to have conceptualized the entire hormone program by
defining the dosages, procedures and chemical combinations that
team doctors and trainers would put into practice.
</P>
<P>
   But there are potential difficulties. Under a law adopted after
German reunification, former East Germans cannot be prosecuted for
crimes under the old regime after Oct. 31, 2000. A second
difficulty is that prosecutors must convict people under the laws
that governed East Germany. Giving hormones to athletes was illegal
under the Communist regime, but the legal hurdles could prove more
difficult as prosecutors move up the chain of command.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
