<HEADER>
A5180 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONA_SPROTTE-A     08-21 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA_SPROTTE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATE LEAVES UA'S SPROTTE DETERMINED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A number along a road south of Globe, Ariz., is a milestone
etched in the memory of Arizona linebacker Scooter Sprotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marker 162.2,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was there, early in the morning on July 11, that Sprotte lost
his best friend, Justin Flores, when the truck they were riding in
slipped off the pavement and flipped.
</P>
<P>
   Flores was driving. Sprotte was a passenger. Fate sat between
them.
</P>
<P>
   Sprotte scrambled out of a hole that a Department of Public
Safety officer described as the size of a clipboard, according to
his father, Dr. Bill Sprotte.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Sprotte was left with scars along the front of his
legs and in the back of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered: `Why him and not me?' '' Sprotte said. ``I lost a
lot of sleep. There's the guilt aspect. You blame yourself. You
think: `Maybe if I had been driving it wouldn't have happened.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up a lot of nights thinking that I was seeing stuff.
But slowly, I'm getting back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Football intervened with the camaraderie, daily rigors and
mind-numbing regimen of repeated drills at Camp Cochise near
Douglas, where the Wildcats stage eight days of preseason
maneuvers. Exhaustion can be a pretty good antidote for emotional
demons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been by myself, I would have had some trouble,'' said
Sprotte, a psychology major whose older brother, Jimmy, is a
Tennessee Oilers rookie after starting at linebacker for UA last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight is a scrimmage (7:30) under game-like conditions at
Arizona Stadium. In two weeks, there's the opener at Hawaii. A
season and all its hopes are on the horizon. Career milestones
probably await the 5-foot-11, 219-pound Sprotte, a promising
redshirt junior and possible starter at inside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever he achieves, that marker on Arizona 77 near El
Capitan pass will always be a guide.
</P>
<P>
   Flores was Sprotte's boyhood friend, greatest fan, confidant,
teammate and classmate at Blue Ridge High School in Lakeside.
Flores had driven to Tucson from the Valley, where he had been
working since high school. He picked up Sprotte, and they planned
to drive the back roads through Globe and up to Lakeside for a
wedding. From there, they planned a trip to Lake Powell.
</P>
<P>
   But one life ended and another changed forever when Flores
apparently fell asleep and failed to negotiate a sweeping turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit this rock wall and just missed a guard rail, which
would have kept them on the road,'' said Sprotte's father, a
Lakeside dentist. ``Then, they went between the wall and the guard
rail and shot off the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprotte's father and mother, Barbara, grew concerned when their
son told them about his inability to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about counseling, but then it was time for camp,''
his father said. ``As it turns out, football has been a good thing
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during the just-completed camp that Sprotte talked as if
the mental scars had healed enough to become a potential source of
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Flores) knew me, my family and older brother,'' said
Sprotte, who played running back as a freshman and sophomore before
redshirting last season because of a move to defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking that he'll never have the chances I've got.
That's making me work harder than I ever have. It makes me want to
be even more of a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing has made me realize nothing can be taken for
granted. It's been one of life's curve balls.''
</P>
<P>
   As he talked, Sprotte pointed at the scars that crisscross his
shins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few,'' he said. ``They only make my legs uglier than
they were already. The mental scars . . . well, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something else. It makes you grow up, but I also would
hope it's something nobody else ever has to see. I remember every
bit of it, and I guess I always will.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
