r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONAST-ARCHULE     08-21 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONAST-ARCHULETA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LAND OF THE GIANTS, LINEBACKER STANDS TALL  
 ASU'S ARCHULETA FOLLOWS IN TILLMAN'S FOOTSTEPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP TONTOZONA _ Play linebacker at Arizona State? Adam
Archuleta wasn't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   That's when former assistant Lyle Setencich took the Chandler
High School senior into his office and popped in a videotape of Pat
Tillman at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think you can do this?'' Setencich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yeah,'' Archuleta said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's how it started for a standout defensive back at
Chandler High School that nobody wanted. Not a single letter from a
college. He only talked to the Sun Devils after calling ``them.''
OK, they said, but you have to walk on.
</P>
<P>
   Now look at him. Two years later, he is slated to start at
weakside linebacker. That could change if senior Larry Johnson
regains his academic eligibility, but for now, the sophomore will
start when ASU faces Washington on Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to compare him to (former standout) Pat Tillman,
because Pat's Pat and Archie's Archie,'' defensive coordinator Phil
Snow said. ``Archie brings some things Pat didn't and vice versa.
But he can run, he's aggressive and he's smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Tillman, Archuleta's 6-foot, 209-pound frame is often
questioned. By comparison, two of the top linebackers in the
country _ Ohio State's Andy Katzenmoyer and Florida's Jevon Kearse
_ are 6-4, 260 and 6-5, 255, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also worth noting that Texas A&AMP;M's Dat Nguyen,
considered by many the nation's second-best inside linebacker
behind Katzenmoyer, is 6-0, 216.
</P>
<P>
   Is Snyder worried?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' Snyder said. ``His speed makes up for all of
that. He's a tough nut and boy he can run.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Archuleta laughs at the improbability of his position.
He always played defensive back and reported to ASU weighing 185.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, after Sun Devils coaches finally agreed to meet with
the high school senior, he found it hard to believe they wanted him
to play linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't sold on the idea. The prospect of playing safety at a
junior college was equally appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 50-50 and (Setencich) had to convince me,'' Archuleta
said. ``Finally, I said, `OK, but only if I get invited to camp.'
If you walk-on and don't get invited, all you ever do is work out
with the scout team and I didn't want that. So they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Archuleta redshirted his first season,, but payed close
attention to Tillman. Even last year, when he played sparingly, he
took notes.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman, now with the Cardinals, was always available to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would always ask him questions to try and get better,''
Archuleta said. ``And he would often come up to me and tell me how
to play things during a game, even though he knew I wouldn't be
getting in. `Hey, this is what's going on and here's how we're
going to handle it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him be successful and that gives you a lot of
motivation. If he was a little guy and didn't play that well, that
would be a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   The adjustment to linebacker was a bit rough at first.
</P>
<P>
   Pass coverage came easily because of his experience at defensive
back. But run coverage, as well as those ``meetings'' with
offensive linemen, well, that was another story.
</P>
<P>
   He's always enjoyed the contact, although at linebacker it's a
little different.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, if I was playing safety and had some high-speed
collisions like Mitch (Freedman), that's fun,'' he said. ``But when
I have to mess with people like Grey (Ruegamer), it's a tugging
match. I don't like messing with linemen. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about strategy. I come to a line, I've got to juke, I've
got to do everything I can. If I don't do well. . . . Yesterday,
Victor (Leyva) got his hands on me and just tossed me. That's not
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU coaches often praise Archuleta, and Snyder has singled out
his play, even when he first arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But will that translate into a starting job? That could depend
on Johnson's return. Stephen Trejo has been starting at the
strongside and Joe Cesta and Archuleta at the middle and weakside,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson returns, he could displace either Trejo or Archuleta.
Trejo could also move to the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the back of my mind, I think if Larry comes in, they'd put
him in my spot,'' Archuleta said. ``It's not something that's
really discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I figure, if I play good, that'll take care of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
