<HEADER>
A5226 &Cx1f; tab-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO:BANK-SURVIVOR-     08-21 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO:BANK-SURVIVOR-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKING WITHOUT BORDERS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By JIM FREER 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In the 1980s, Mexico was a lonely country for bankers like Ralph
Heid and Claude ``Hank'' Miller. They searched the far corners of
Mexico, going outside the familiar financial hubs of Mexico City
and Monterrey, to find business for their Comerica bank bosses back
in Detroit. Along the trail, the pair seldom bumped into any other
U.S. bankers, let alone bankers from Europe or Asia.
 &HT;    ``Most banks concentrated on Mexico City and Monterrey, but we
felt there were some excellent companies in the regional
capitals,'' says Heid, who is a vice president for Latin America in
the bank's International Finance Department. ``We researched them,
stopping by a major city each time we came to Mexico.''
 &HT;    U.S.-based Comerica has since prospered, weathering many a
Mexican financial storm. Mexican clients top the bank's
international borrowing list, with US$414 million in loans
outstanding at year-end 1997. Overall, the bank had $2 billion in
outstanding loans to non-U.S.-based customers, which represents
little more than 7 percent of its $28 billion portfolio.
 &HT;    ``We have traditionally worked with the export sector in Latin
America and with subsidiaries of U.S. companies,'' says Heid. ``Our
experience relative to other banks was not painful. The companies
we served were mainly export-focused, and they continued to
generate dollars to service their debt.''
 &HT;    With clients in 14 Mexican cities and with offices in leading
U.S. exporting states, Comerica has taken advantage of the North
American Free Trade Agreement to become a bank without borders.
``We follow the natural trade flows between our market areas in the
United States and Latin America,'' says Heid, who has a staff of 25
lending officers who travel frequently to Latin America.
 &HT;    The bank's success in Mexico is a product of its strategy to
find promising companies outside the larger cities, in places like
Guadalajara, Aguascalientes, Puebla and Chihuahua. One clear
winning partnership was Internacional de Ceramica S.A. de C.V., a
leading ceramic tile manufacturer in Chihuahua.
 &HT;    The relationship began in 1989, blossoming with Comerica's
granting credit lines to the company. By 1992, Comerica was the
lead bank for working capital loans for the firm. At the same time,
the company began expanding sales on both sides of the border,
especially in Texas. Comerica then led the way as fast-growing
Interceramic sought funds to expand its main plant in Chihuahua and
built a plant outside Dallas, Texas. In 1993, the World Bank's
International Finance Corp. gave Interceramic a $38.5 million for
the Chihuahua project. The IFC sold part of the $17.5 million loan
portfolio to private banks, with Comerica being the largest
participant.
 &HT;    The following year, Comerica loaned Interceramic $8 million to
purchase machinery and equipment for its Texas plant. Despite the
damage caused by Mexico's peso crisis in 1994-95, Interceramic had
no difficulty making its loan payments.
 &HT;    Victor Almeida, Interceramic's chief executive officer, says
other U.S. banks might have deserted his company. He says Comerica
was very different from most U.S. banks that deal with Mexican
companies because it was willing to make money available to his
company by reviewing its export invoices.
 &HT;    ``Comerica is willing to listen and understand, and they have a
feel for (Mexico's ups and downs),'' he says.
 &HT;    These days, the ups seem to outnumber the downs for
Interceramic. Last year, the company earned $200 million in
revenues, with 56 percent coming from U.S. sales. The publicly
traded company employs 2,500 people in Mexico; 700 at its U.S.
subsidiary. It was founded in 1978 by Oscar Almeida, Victor's
father, who is the company chairman.
 &HT;    Heid and Miller say Interceramic is the kind of company a bank
can find in Mexico if it's willing to do some homework and look
beyond the country's bigger, more traditional markets.
 &HT;    To arrange loans to Mexican clients, Comerica uses offices in
the United States, its subsidiary in Mexico City and its
representative office in Monterrey. Miller is now managing director
of the Mexico City office. In Mexico, Comerica lends in dollars and
in pesos and performs cash management and other treasury services.
 &HT;    Lending to companies in other parts of Latin America is done
through U.S. headquarters in Droit, Michigan. A possible office is
being considered in Brazil, says Heid, who continues to keep up a
heavy travel schedule to Latin America. ``I go every two or three
weeks,'' he says.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
