u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COPS-SHOOT-BLINDMA     08-21 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COPS-SHOOT-BLINDMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SHOOT MAN, 65 AND LEGALLY BLIND, THEY SAY HAD MACHETE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A legally blind 65-year-old man who police said was
wielding a machete was shot early Thursday by officers searching
for guns and explosives at his son's Staten Island apartment,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department and the victim's family gave different
accounts Thursday night about the shooting of the father, Watson
Chin Young, who was shot once in the chest and was in serious but
stable condition at Staten Island University Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   According to Deputy Inspector Michael Collins, a police
department spokesman, officers had obtained a search warrant for
the upstairs apartment at 1865 Forest Ave., a two-story home that
has a barbershop owned by Chin Young, a downstairs apartment where
he lives and an upstairs apartment that is the residence of his
26-year-old son, Leighton Chin Young. The police, Inspector Collins
said, had got a tip that Watson Chin Young's son was storing guns
and explosives there.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the elder Chin Young opened his door, holding a
machete, after detectives and emergency service officers entered
the home's common foyer on the ground floor. He was shot, they
said, after refusing to drop the machete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preliminary investigation indicates that Watson Chin
brandished a 24-inch machete,'' Collins said. ``A fully uniformed
emergency service unit officer ordered him to drop the weapon
several times. When he did not, the officer fired one time,
striking him in the chest.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chin Young's daughter, Pauline Brown, said that her father
thought the police were burglars when they entered the foyer
shortly after 1 a.m. Mrs. Brown said she was on the phone with her
father when police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a loud bang and he said somebody was tearing off the
door,'' she said. ``He said, `One second,' and then I heard him
say, `Who's there?' Afterwards, there was another loud sound, then
the phone went dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Police later found an AK-47 rifle with 136 rounds of ammunition
and a .357-magnum handgun with 20 rounds in Leighton Chin Young's
apartment, although the bombs he was said to have been making never
materialized, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Watson Chin Young has been charged with attempted assault,
menacing and criminal possession of a weapon, police said. If it is
proven that he tried to assault a police officer, he could face up
to 15 years in prison. His son was arrested and charged with
criminal possession of a weapon when he arrived at the home after
the raid. If convicted, he faces up to four years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator who spoke on the condition of anonymity said
that the police raided the apartment after an informant ``who had
very good information in the past'' claimed that Leighton Chin
Young had been offering to sell homemade explosives on the street.
But neither Leighton Chin Young nor his father has a criminal
record, the investigator added.
</P>
<P>
   Family members said Watson Chin Young had been skittish since he
was robbed in the building's foyer about three years ago by masked
men who also tried to enter his apartment. They disputed the police
account of the shooting, saying that the police had been trying to
ram down his door when he confronted them.
</P>
</TEXT>
