<HEADLINE>
ANGELS RIP TIGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels have had to scratch and
claw for everything they've gotten this season, but Thursday night
they skated.
</P>
<P>
   A six-run third inning and five more in the fifth propelled the
Angels to a 13-2 rout of the Detroit Tigers before 27,548 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   With the win the Angels maintained their 1{-game lead over Texas
in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels played nearly flawless baseball in all facets of the
game, with solid pitching, defense and offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had 16 hits in all, but none left the ballpark. They
had 10 singles and six doubles as every starter but Orlando
Palmeiro had at least one hit.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad, Troy Glaus and Gary DiSarcina had three hits
apiece, Garret Anderson had two doubles and Randy Velarde reached
base four times (two singles, two walks).
</P>
<P>
   It made for an easy night for Angels starter Omar Olivares, who
gave up two runs and seven hits in eight innings to get the win.
Olivares (7-8) struck out seven, walked one and is 2-0 with a 2.38
ERA in his past three starts.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, though, Angels manager Terry Collins raved
about his defense, which ranks fourth in the league in fielding
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not clobbering the ball, scoring six runs per
game, defense wins games,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got Collins his six runs off Tigers starter Brian
Powell (2-4) in the third inning alone. It all started innocently
enough when Palmeiro led off with a strikeout. But the next six
Angels batters reached base.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde singled, went to third on a double by Erstad and scored
on a wild pitch. Jim Edmonds singled in a run, Anderson doubled
home another and Glaus doubled in two more.
</P>
<P>
   One batter later, DiSarcina singled home the sixth run of the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels batted around again in the fifth inning, DiSarcina
coming up with the big hit, a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Olivares started out the game by striking out the
side in the first and taking it from there. Tony Clark homered in
the fourth inning and Damion Easley's infield single in the eighth
drove home the Tigers' only other run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
