<HEADLINE>
BRONX MAN CHARGED IN FATAL STABBING IN GREENWICH VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A computer programmer who went to a Greenwich Village
hospital for treatment of gashes shortly after a man was stabbed to
death has been arrested in the Tuesday morning killing, police said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The programmer, Eric Carolina, 21, was picked up by detectives
at his home at 115 West 197th St. in the Kingsbridge section of the
Bronx on Wednesday night after investigators learned that he had
gone to St. Vincent's Hospital for treatment in the hours after the
victim, Fitzroy Green, 36, was killed in his Greenwich Village
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Carolina was arrested after discrepancies developed
in his account of meeting Green, whose body was found in his
apartment Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina has been charged with second-degree murder and criminal
possession of a weapon, police said. If convicted of the murder, he
could face up to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe Mr. Green had met Mr. Carolina in the early evening
and had invited him back to his apartment, where the murder took
place,'' Police Commissioner Howard Safir said. Noting that police
had recovered the knife believed to have been used in the slaying,
he said: ``It appears the suspect caused his own wounds during the
struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   An investigator who spoke on the condition of anonymity said the
killing appeared to have occurred after Carolina discovered that
Green, who sometimes dressed as a woman, was a man.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator said Carolina claimed he met Green on a
Greenwich Village street and, after going with Green to his
apartment at 714 Greenwich St., became enraged when he discovered
Green's true sex.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
