<HEADLINE>
BRONX WOMAN SHOT TO DEATH IN FRONT OF SONS, 4 AND 6  
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Bronx woman was killed in front of her two young
children Thursday after two gunmen forced their way into the
family's apartment demanding money and jewelry, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Almodovar, 31, was shot in the head at 443 E. 184th St.
in the Fordham section of the Bronx as her sons, ages 4 and 6,
watched, said Lt. Harry Scott of the 48th Precinct detective squad.
</P>
<P>
   The boys spent much of the evening in the precinct house, typing
and eating pizza and Tootsie Rolls until detectives located their
father, who does not live with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't seem to be too shaken up,'' Scott said of the
children. ``It will probably sink in tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys told police that two men pushed in the door around 1
p.m. , and forced Mrs. Ms. Almodovar into the back bedroom, then
shot her as the boys looked on, police said. The gunmen fled. As of
Thursday night, police had made no arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The motive may have been robbery, police said, but the apartment
had not been ransacked. Another possible motive may have been
revenge, police said. Ms. Almodovar's boyfriend, Julio Medina, is
awaiting trial on charges of murder in the death of Elvis Salcero
in May, in an argument over drugs, the authorities said. Ms.
Almodovar may have been killed in retaliation, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always with those kids,'' said a neighbor, Jeanette
Mojica. ``It's sad. She never let those boys out of her sight. She
never let anyone else take care of them. Now I don't know what's
going to happen to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
