<SLUG> BC-TERROR-REAX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE HAS OWN IDEAS ON U.S. STRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday's U.S. missile attack on suspected terrorist targets in
Afghanistan and Sudan was a violation of international law.
</P>
<P>
   No, wait, it was a righteous retaliation against murderers who
bombed U.S. Embassies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Or a political diversion tactic stolen from Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   That's the word on Valley streets, anyway, where the lone
certainty seems to be that there is no consensus among metropolitan
Phoenix folks about what happened, or why.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Navarro, 22, of Chandler, is a hawk when it comes to
dealing with terrorists: ``We just need to kick their butts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shouldn't be able to get away with killing innocent
people. The president needs to show them that the United States is
not going to put up with it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Navarro's view prevailed, there were plenty of dissenters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the United States has sunk to the terrorists'
level,'' said DeUndre Zackery, 26, of Phoenix. ``I felt it was
unwarranted to retaliate against two nations for attacks by
individuals. . . . The people in that chemical factory didn't have
anything to do with the bombings that killed U.S. citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Zackery argued that American justice requires proof of guilt
before punishment, yet the missile attacks amounted to a death
sentence without due process or a trial. And some of the victims
may have been innocent, he added, especially if the factory in
Sudan had stores of lethal chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Block, a 66-year-old Phoenix retiree, said there's a
difference between domestic crime and international terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acts of terrorism are tantamount to acts of war, and at some
point down the line it's got to require retaliation,'' he said.
``We're declaring war, big stuff. Apparently, the U.S. feels a
major attack deserves retaliation or major attacks will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath each argument, a secondary theme ran equally hot: Did
President Clinton manipulate the terrorism issue to divert public
attention from Monica Lewinsky, sex and perjury?
</P>
<P>
   As one woman put it, ``This is an opportunity for him to show
he's doing something besides sleeping with interns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that,'' Navarro responded. ``The president is
doing his job. He's doing what he has to do. Everybody should mind
their own business about President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Daggett, 39, Phoenix, said his first thought was about
``Wag the Dog,'' the movie about a scandal-ridden president whose
advisers fabricate a war to distract voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cynics will think that, but I certainly don't. . . . The
Africa bombings are still fresh in people's minds, and he (Clinton)
didn't make those up,'' Daggett said. ``I think it's a legitimate
political maneuver. . . . I'm assuming that the Pentagon knew what
they were doing and the retaliation was accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Smith, an Arizona State University professor who worked
at the White House during Watergate, said it's impossible to know
whether Clinton wagged the dog or acted on legitimate intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Smith recalled that President Nixon suddenly issued a military
alert at the height of Watergate, based on a supposed escalation of
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not unprecedented, I would say, for national security
matters to be intruded'' by political concerns, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Although most people interviewed Thursday discounted that
possibility, Valley Islamic leaders insisted it is the only
reasonable explanation for America's spasm of overseas violence.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference at the Islamic Community Center of
Phoenix, spokesman David Hadley said the crisis was contrived by a
desperate president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Operation Distraction,'' Hadley added. ``Anybody who
can't see it is in absolute denial.''
</P>
<P>
   Hadley and other Muslims condemned the embassy bombings in
Africa but said that America has fomented terrorism with a foreign
policy that discriminates against Arab and Muslim nations.
</P>
<P>
   As for Thursday's missile salvos, Hadley added, ``If anyone
believes this has done anything to send a message against
terrorism, they're dreaming. Clearly, it's a violation of
international law.''
</P>
<P>
   Ihsan Saadeddin, president of the American-Arab
Anti-Discrimination League, said he does not believe Clinton,
adding that the United States has offered no proof to justify a
military attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not going to take his word for it,'' Saadeddin
added. ``Show it to us. You cannot just claim something like this.
If you do, you've created more hatred, more enemies, over something
you have not proved.''
</P>
<P>
   Marwan Ahmad, a Palestinian immigrant and publisher of ``Arizona
Muslim'' ``Voice,'' predicted the Islamic world will almost
universally decry America's military action. He said the United
States' foreign policy smacks of hypocrisy when international law
is broken and of bullyism when a feeble country such as Sudan is
targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the base country was China, would those missiles have been
launched?'' Ahmad asked.
</P>
<P>
   But others said the message of Thursday's missiles was directed
not just at fanatical bombers but at the nations that protect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole terrorism thing is ridiculous,'' said Tim Pender,
38, a Chandler salesman. ``Maybe if we did this more often, you
wouldn't have these little countries giving refuge to
terrorists.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Dennis Wagner can be reached at 444-8874 or at
dennis.wagner &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
