<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5313 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      08-21 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS HANDCUFFS MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Roger Clemens needed minimal offensive support
Thursday night against a Mariner team skidding toward its first
meaningless September in four years. But the Toronto Blue Jays
provided their Rocket Man with a swift and decisive blastoff.
</P>
<P>
   A four-run first inning featuring Jose Cruz Jr.'s second home
run in as many games gave the Blue Jays and Clemens more than
enough of a head start to send the Mariners to a 7-0 loss before
26,642 fans at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto, which beat up Seattle pitching at SkyDome last week,
continued the onslaught at the Kingdome, adding 14 hits in Thursday
night's series finale to the 21 they amassed Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   As September gets closer, the M's are falling farther back in
the American League West. They have lost seven of their past nine
games and trail the division-leading Anaheim Angels by 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mariners insist they'll keep battling until the
season ends, the prospect of playing out the final month without
competing for a playoff spot holds little appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember what it's like because I did it for many years,''
designated hitter Edgar Martinez said. ``It's not fun. When you are
doing well the last month and fighting for a pennant, you can't
wait to get to the stadium. The days go by fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have anything to look forward to, it's not the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   Septembers in 1995, '96 and '97 were fun.
</P>
<P>
   This one looms without much hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Angels and Rangers haven't been playing well,'' Martinez
said, ``so if we can just hang in until we get hot...''
</P>
<P>
   The only hot hands Thursday night belonged to Clemens and the
Blue Jays' hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They jumped on us quick and Roger was on top of his game,''
Mariner manager Lou Piniella said. ``When you fall behind, it's
tough to come back against a good pitcher like Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran right-hander, who has one foot in the Hall of Fame
door, took a no-hitter into the fifth inning, losing the no-no bid
when David Segui chopped a grounder over Clemens' head and beat it
out for an infield single. Rob Ducey grounded a single to center in
the sixth and Joey Cora followed with another hit, giving Seattle
its only scoring threat of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens brushed the threat aside by retiring Alex Rodriguez
and Ken Griffey Jr., and retired 11 of the final 12 batters he
faced to win his 10th straight decision. It was his first shutout
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays apparently had a restful night after their 21-hit
assault in the series opener.
</P>
<P>
   Their rising team batting average started escalating immediately
when five hits produced four runs in the first inning against Bill
Swift, attempting to become the Mariners' first 11-game winner.
</P>
<P>
   After Carlos Delgado blooped a two-run single into shallow
right-center field, scoring Shannon Stewart and Jose Canseco, Cruz
extended his career-best hitting streak to 14 games with a home run
into the right-field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a fly ball,'' Swift said.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz's seventh homer of the season was Toronto's eighth in two
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Jays hit seven in Wednesday night's 16-2 victory, the most
homers Mariner pitchers ever had allowed in one game.
</P>
<P>
   Four runs would have been plenty for Clemens Thursday night, but
the Blue Jays kept tacking on runs, scoring again in the second
inning on Shawn Green's RBI single and twice more in the fourth on
RBI doubles by Green and Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are hitting everything we threw at them,'' Swift said.
``I made some good pitches that were hit.''
</P>
<P>
   In their past four games against Mariner pitching, Blue Jay
hitters have accumulated 59 hits and scored 41 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Swift lost for the first time in 11 starts this season with four
days' rest. He had been 7-0 with a 4.14 earned run average. The 12
hits allowed Thursday night were the most for the right-hander in
24 starts.
</P>
<P>
   There might have been extenuating circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a bad case of the hives two days ago,'' Piniella said.
``I don't know if that affected him, but it might have.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift (10-7) said he has been on anti-hive medication for the
past three days but didn't blame his performance on the ailment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That had nothing to do with it,'' he said. ``Roger threw a
great game and it didn't matter if it was one or seven runs.
Whenever you give him a four-run lead like that, it's going to be
tough to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco, the only Blue Jay starter without a hit in Wednesday
night's carnage, doubled twice, singled, stole a base and scored a
run in his first four at-bats Thursday night. He has 28 stolen
bases and 23 doubles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
