<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER STARTER BURTON ON THE BUBBLE WITH SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ James Burton isn't exactly in, but he's
definitely not out, either.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran cornerback is sitting on the bubble as NFL teams
approach their final preseason games and first roster cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks, like the 29 other teams in the league, must trim
their roster to 60 players by Tuesday and then make the final cuts
to 53 on Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Burton appears to safe for now. But whether he is still around
after that final cut will be determined by how well he and a couple
of other defensive backs play in Friday night's game against the
Arizona Cardinals in Tempe, and in next week's preseason finale
against the San Francisco 49ers at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to be here,'' Burton said. ``I'm playing nickel
back, cornerback, special teams. If they ask me to do it, and it
will help me make this team, I'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, 27, is unlike most of the players who are facing the
wrong side of the cutdowns. He has played in the league, even
started games.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth-round draft choice by the Kansas City Chiefs in 1994,
the former all-conference cornerback at Fresno State was released
on the final cut. But he was signed by the Chicago Bears and
started seven games the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   His last season in Chicago almost became his last season,
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to quit football,'' he said. ``I was really
depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton suffered a broken right leg in practice before the fifth
game of the season. He tried to return in November, but finished
the season on injured reserve. Not the type of season a player
wants to have when he is due to become an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a four-week injury that ended up being a four-month
injury because the Bears didn't handle it right,'' Burton said. ``A
lot of teams thought I was more hurt than I was. I didn't get any
calls at first. I didn't know what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton fired his agent because of it. Once he got a new agent,
he also got some interest. He selected the Seahawks over the
Buffalo Bills, because he wanted to stay on the West Coast, and the
49ers, because the situation was better in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If Burton is to stick with the Seahawks, he must beat out Reggie
Rusk for the fourth cornerback spot, or do enough on special teams
to convince the coaches he is worth keeping over rookie cornerback
Joey Eloms and safety Kerry Joseph as the ninth defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, Reggie is No. 4. But those guys will be moving
around. We're not sure about them,'' defensive backs coach Dave
Brown said. ``At this point, James is showing he still has the
ability to play in this league. But we probably won't know what
we'll do with him until the last cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Long odds? Not for someone who longs to remain in the league as
badly as Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having started in this league before, I know that feeling,''
he said. ``But I also know if you're second string, you're going to
stick by playing special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dennis Erickson will make next week's cuts in two groups
because he likes to meet with each player who is released. The
coaches will watch video of the game against the Cardinals on
Sunday, discuss the cuts later in the day and then meet again early
Monday to make the final decisions on who must stay and who should
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't depend on one game, it's the whole camp,'' Erickson
said. ``But there are some close battles there, so this game could
make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: QB Warren Moon on Thursday signed the two-year
contract he agreed to last week. ... DE Phillip Daniels is doing a
pretty good impersonation of the Bionic Man. He returned to
practice Thursday after suffering a hyperextended right ankle
Wednesday. Daniels bruised his right kneecap in Saturday's game in
Vancouver against the 49ers, but practiced Monday. ... Erickson was
not happy when the No. 1 offense broke the huddle and went to the
line only to have a defensive coach point out that there was no
tight end on the field. ``Why the hell is that happening? Pay
attention,'' Erickson yelled. ... Play du jour: WR Robert Wilson's
reaching grab of a John Friesz pass as he was falling. ... The
Seahawks' EndZone Store will release the team's 1998 merchandise
catalog Monday. To obtain one, call 206-682-2900.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
