<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5321 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI &LR;      08-21 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULISM HAS SECOND CHANCE WITH SEAHAWKS STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Before construction of the new baseball park commences
in Pittsburgh this winter, some fans there wanted a say in the name
of the park, something to reflect a little more on the team's
heritage and a little less on the tax write-off virtues for some
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   One idea that gained popularity invoked the name of the greatest
Pirate of them all, Roberto Clemente. As in, Humongoid Corporation
Park at Clemente Field.
</P>
<P>
   For a franchise with as much history and tradition as the
Pirates, the idea sounded halfway decent.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the name of the park?
</P>
<P>
   PNC Park. Period.
</P>
<P>
   A local bank two weeks ago bought the naming rights, for $30
million over 20 years. No Clemente. No Bill Mazeroski. Not even
Smoky Burgess Burger Barn.
</P>
<P>
   If there were ever a majestic sports figure worthy of
stadium-naming immortality it was Clemente, the four-time batting
champion and 18-year Pirate hero who died at age 38 flying in a
rescue mission to his earthquake-devastated homeland of Puerto
Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Grace, power, nobility _ Clemente was the best thing this side
of the New Testament. And since he died at the height of his
luminousness as a Pirate, there was no danger of a backfire.
(Imagine: On the day that Griffey Park is announced in Seattle,
Junior demands a trade to a contender.)
</P>
<P>
   As a sop to those wanting to honor the man, the council of
viziers in Pittsburgh changed the name of a bridge nearest the
ballpark to Clemente Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Coming next: the Dick Groat Goatfield.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, populist sentiment has no more sway in Pittsburgh
than in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You may recall that concept was in the spotlight in Seattle in
June, when Bob Wallace, a board member of the Public Facilities
District overseeing the half-billion-dollar monument to
millionaires, went ballistic over those who would challenge the
park's new name of Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely outrageous,'' Wallace fumed. ``The Mariners will be
apoplectic. ... To screw up $40 million in naming rights is
unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace had his way, and Safeco Field stuck. But not before
stirring some fans incensed at the arrogance displayed by the
Bellevue developer.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was, of course, futile, because the state granted
the Mariners stadium naming rights in its enabling legislation.
</P>
<P>
   It would have taken a visionary legislator or governor to have
included a provision for a symbolic naming touch that would have
fooled at least some into thinking that their $370 million in tax
money was buying them something.
</P>
<P>
   But a visionary politician in this state is harder to find than
consecutive outs from the Mariner bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   So the fact that some were surprised over the name game is
attributable to negligent citizenship. Nor is the dismay any fault
of the local insurance shop.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco spokesman Gordon Hamilton, who said the stadium-naming
issue hasn't returned to his attention in more than a month, said
nothing has changed since his fanciful turn of phrase when he
politely told protesters to drop dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a newspaper clip in which I was quoted as saying, `If
it's anything different, it's not the same,''' he said, chuckling.
``Some put that just below Yogi Berra, but I think it's quite
profound.''
</P>
<P>
   Profound or profane, Safeco's position about a compromise is
unyielding: They paid $40 million over 20 years for exclusivity in
the name. If something else were required in the name, they would
have bid less.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The more clever you get (with additional words), the more
people will use it,'' Hamilton said. ``It's not what we paid for.''
</P>
<P>
   My choice for an appellation appendage was not person-related.
In fact, the only Mariner name that had any validity was Dave
Niehaus. But the Nie-House nickname, however deserved, doesn't
exactly reflect nobly on the baseball heritage when the best thing
to be said about a franchise is that it had a good announcer (Cubs
excepted).
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion came from a recent tour of the unfinished yard,
and the nose hit enjoyed at a stop on the southwest-corner
promenade with views of the Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Saltair Park.
</P>
<P>
   It's sensory rather than intellectual (just like baseball's
appeal), apt for the Mariner name, neither exclusionary nor
discriminatory, costs nothing to provide and is unique to Seattle.
Even ``Saltair at Safeco'' has just a bit of rhythm to it.
</P>
<P>
   But unless someone offers $10 million or so to Safeco to back
down and share the marquee, it isn't gonna happen.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a second chance in town. As you may have
read, another ballpark is going up right next to Safeco Field. For
unfathomable reasons, it, too, will be open to the elements. In
fact, the salt air most of the time will be coming in hard, quickly
and horizontally aboard raindrops. It will be an even more vivid
sensory experience.
</P>
<P>
   So, populists, you are four years out from the opening of the
new football yard. Can't say you weren't alerted.
</P>
<P>
   Unless of course, Paul Allen says he needs the money from naming
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
