   &UR; WILL SOCIAL SECURITY BE AROUND WHEN I RETIRE? &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't buy President Clinton's State of the Union
pledge to save the system, Social Security is a fair bet to survive
in some form.
</P>
<P>
   The current system is pay-as-you-go: Taxes on today's workers
pay for the Treasury bonds whose interest payments fund today's
retirees. That's fine until retirees start to outnumber workers.
Then you're going to have some problems.
</P>
<P>
   How bad are these problems likely to be? The Social Security
Administration itself says the present system can't maintain the
current level of benefits past 2030.
</P>
<P>
   And according to one study, by the year 2045, workers could have
to pay between 17 percent and 22 percent of their wages _ about
three times what they pay now _ to fund the program.
</P>
<P>
   That said, consider the source of some of the most alarming
statements about Social Security. Is it out of pure altruism that
many in the mutual-fund business favor turning Social Security into
a kind of giant 401(k) program?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, much of the hand-wringing over Social Security ignores
political reality. Social Security is probably the most popular
social entitlement program in American history. How likely is it
that Washington will let its funding problems fester until it's too
late?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, just as with the budget deficit, the thrift crisis,
and any number of other incipient fiscal disasters, we will
probably muddle through somehow.
</P>
<P>
   Possible fixes to the present system are an incremental one, in
which the retirement age is raised in stages while benefits are
reduced and payroll taxes increased, and a semi-privatized system
in which some mandatory savings go into designated mutual funds and
others into a stripped-down Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   But in any case, Social Security is likely to make up a good
deal less of total retirement income than its current average level
of 30 percent. So keep funding your 401(k). &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAN I COUNT ON MEDICARE TO COVER ALL OF MY HEALTH-CARE
EXPENDITURES? &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forget Social Security _ Medicare is the entitlement program to
worry about.
</P>
<P>
   The ballooning number of elderly and the rapid increase in
health-care costs have turned the program into a time bomb.
According to the best available estimates, the Medicare trust fund
that pays for hospital and certain nursing and hospice care will
start running a deficit in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to avoid that outcome is to radically revamp the
system. It's too early to predict Medicare's fate, but a good guess
is that it will evolve into a kind of mega-HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Right now only about 13 percent of Medicare beneficiaries are
enrolled in managed-care plans, says Lisa Alecxih, vice president
of the Lewin Group, a health-care consulting firm in Fairfax, Va.
That percentage is almost sure to grow.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent budget bill, Congress attempted to spur growth in
managed-care-plan membership by adding coverage of the cost of
eyeglasses, prescription drugs, dental care, and hearing aids. The
trade-off: Most plans limit the doctors and the treatments they
will cover.
</P>
<P>
   That means most Americans will probably need some kind of
supplemental insurance _ but not medigap insurance, which ``is not
the bargain it used to be,'' says the Lewin Group's Lawrence Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees should consider long-term-care insurance, which will
cover not only a prolonged stay in a nursing home but also other
major expenses (such as some organ transplants) that Medicare
doesn't pick up. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Amy K. Barrett is a financial writer in New York
City.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
