</P>
<P>
   The division of ages into quarters of a hundred is bold and apt:
Recapture the under-65 set (the 50-plussers) and you reinvigorate
the concept of aging entirely. (Also ignore the fact that 0 to 25
isn't exactly a lifestyle category, though no less so than 25 to
50).
</P>
<P>
   The upshot of such thinking will be your 60-year-old college
students and consumers of retail goods. Pretty soon the middle
years will be the necessary evil, and retirement will come to seem
the be-all in addition to the end-all.
</P>
<P>
   There's no innate reason why it shouldn't. Among the Dagara of
West Africa, old age and childhood are held to be the important
times in life, the times when one does great work.
</P>
<P>
   Children and the ``elders,'' being chronologically closer to the
spirit world, hang out together and discuss the meaning of life,
while those in their middle years are seen as more or less taking
up space, providing little more than manual labor to feed the wise
children and elders.
</P>
<P>
   This might not be such a bad model for 21st-century America,
after all: Live like hell in the First Age, pay for it in the
Second, and do it right this time in the Third.
</P>
<P>
   And after age 75, by the year 2030, you might as well call
yourself an elder and go for broke _ the statistics are in your
favor. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Hillary Johnson wrote about the 008 Investment Club
(``I Don't Think We're in Beardstown Anymore'') for the February
issue of ``WORTH.'') &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
