<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5341 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-START-NOW!-RETIREMENT     08-21 1662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-START-NOW!-RETIREMENT-PKG-475&AMP;add-NYTSF-WORTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICE RETIREMENT: GET TO KNOW YOUR SPOUSE, YOURSELF  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Third of four-part package, `THE NEW RETIREMENT')   (This user-friendly ``separate buy'' personal-finance story is from
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A HELPFUL 425-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 475; FULL UNCUT VERSION
IS 1,525 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By RICHARD TODD  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bustling retirement industry has done its work so well that
people now in their 20s live in mild but persistent anxiety about
not being able to support themselves in old age, while those over
40 suffer full-scale panic.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is a good thing _ good for our long-flagging national
savings rate, anyway _ but it gives life a rather gloomy,
foreshortened air. Moreover, spending all your time making sure
that you can retire may distract you from an equally important
task: learning how to retire.
</P>
<P>
   I must tread lightly here. Freud was right. Your broker was
right. All the good things you have you owe to deferred
gratification. But I want to speak up for a contrary concept.
</P>
<P>
   Much is made of the present value of money, but there is
something to be said for the present value of pleasure. I am
speaking not of wanton hedonism but of useful pleasure. Investment
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the first rule of pre-retirement: To retire well you
should start to retire now.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take travel as our paradigm. Travel is the virtually
universal answer people give when asked what they want to do in
retirement. What they generally mean is that they're too busy for
that kind of indulgence now, but later _ freed _ they will roam the
world.
</P>
<P>
   I hold no special brief for travel, though I'm fond of doing it.
Travel makes you more interesting to yourself, not necessarily to
others. But if you're going to travel you should travel a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Deferred travel _ the ``trip of a lifetime'' embarked on at 65 _
strikes me as a dangerously melancholy idea. For one thing, you're
in better shape for it now.
</P>
<P>
   Air travel is one of the arduous pleasures. It generally becomes
less fun once you've reached the age when your right knee wants to
spend the whole journey remembering the Dartmouth game.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the dark side. One of the true joys of travel is
returning to places seen before: to visit a city whose great
monuments you already know so that you can concentrate on the
mundane or grumble enjoyably about the way things have changed. The
prerequisite for returning is going there the first time, and the
time to do that is now.
</P>
<P>
   There is a corollary pleasure. Extensive travel provides you
with something precious: a little list of places you would really
not mind never visiting again. There is something very satisfying
about spinning the globe and seeing whole countries you can live
without.
</P>
<P>
   With enough such places on your list, you might find yourself on
some fine retirement day in the full sun of an American summer
saying, ``Let's stay home this year.''
</P>
<P>
   As with travel, so with everything else in retirement. If you're
planning to do it later, start doing it now. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (425-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the margins, the good sense of the rule becomes obvious:
People sail across the ocean and climb mountains at 70, but people
who try to learn the requisite skills for those sports in
retirement tend to end up dead sooner than might otherwise be the
case.
</P>
<P>
   But the rule applies to less extreme behavior, too. ``A life of
leisure is hard work,'' said a friend of mine not long ago. He's
right. If you're planning to move to a new town in retirement, you
should be spending as much time as possible there now; otherwise
you'll be faced with showing up like a new kid on the first day of
summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   If you're planning to golf...well, I don't know about golf, but
in a sense I suppose what I'm saying here is essentially a golf
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   That is, it's all in the backswing, at least that part that
isn't in the follow-through. The moment when you actually hit the
ball _ the lugubrious day of the farewell dinner _ should pass by
virtually unnoticed. Because by the time you retire, you will have
retired already.
</P>
<P>
   Practical objections may be raised. It's hard to hold an
important job and also travel at will, live in two towns, sharpen
your wilderness skills, etc.
</P>
<P>
   True, true, and I am a poor guide here, except in a rather
comic-strip way. I left my last real office job when I was in my
early 40s in search of a more independent life _ and got all too
much of what I wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that you're retired...,'' said my youngest daughter one
day, exciting my displeasure. (``Who do you think is paying your
tuition?'' etc., etc.) In retrospect, she had a point. I bought a
lot of freedom, not to say self-indulgence, and I ``made some
sacrifices'' in money and security.
</P>
<P>
   My having left the work force 20 years early appears not to have
condemned me to staying in the work force 20 years after the
well-pensioned are teeing up.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to go all the way down my lonesome road to
ask some searching questions about whether adjustments might be
possible in your working life.
</P>
<P>
   Is another 20 years of 60-hour work weeks preparing you for
anything except being the exhausted overseer of a
generation-skipping trust?
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to think that health, wealth, and the effective
management of your coming leisure are all you have to worry about,
but of course that isn't the way it works. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF 425-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now we are about to sail into heavy weather. The subject is your
companion for the out-years.
</P>
<P>
   All societies contrive to let husbands and wives spend a great
deal of time apart. Our own society, with its usual hypocrisy, has
been brilliant at this.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guise of the equal-partnership marriage, everyone gets
to work impossibly long hours at the office and then enjoy tightly
structured quality time in child rearing. Without really trying to,
a husband and wife can confine their intimate hours to bed, just
like illicit lovers, except asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement puts an end to all that.
</P>
<P>
   Marriage in retirement is of course the stuff of bad jokes _
``for better or for worse but not for lunch,'' ho, ho, ho _ but as
the wise man said, a joke is the epitaph of an emotion.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible you may one day be sharing your house with a
relative stranger. Thus one of the best pre-retirement moves: Get
to know your spouse.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean some hideous encounter-group-tell-all sort of
session. After all, a gradually ripening acquaintance is the very
essence of a good marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, now might be a good time to arrange an occasional hour of
conversation about something impractical, involving neither money
nor children. And perhaps even a week alone together?
</P>
<P>
   The knowledge taken from such moments may buoy your confidence
in the relaxed joys awaiting you. Alternatively, you may be
horrified. If so, wouldn't it be better to know now?
</P>
<P>
   If it is easy to hide from your husband or wife in the midst of
a busy life, it is easier still to hide from yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to know yourself'' has always struck me to be a
hopelessly vague enterprise, so I've never tried it, but
discovering what matters to you in the present that might actually
matter more in the future _ that's a worthy and perhaps doable
task.
</P>
<P>
   The future. If you are in, say, your late 40s, you have begun to
realize that 65 ``isn't that old,'' although you can remember that
people of that age, seen from the vantage of 25, were geezers.
</P>
<P>
   Youth is intolerant and unimaginative. But youth is not always
stupid. You will look like a geezer to plenty of people. You will
have changed. By 65, everyone is a funny valentine.
</P>
<P>
   There is this one good thing that happens to the old. They
become more interested in doing things right. Some people are
blessed with this instinct from the start, but most of us must wait
for the simple realization that at last we don't have time to keep
doing things over.
</P>
<P>
   Doing things right can lead to great achievements, or it can
lead to endless fussing. You are going to be obsessed with
something: the trick is to discover the right obsession.
</P>
<P>
   As I look around at retired people I know, the happiest of them
are fussing, all right, but not over the aphids in their roses. One
is fussing about the free-book store he's founded, another about
the preservation of the town hall, another about how to identify
the right recipients for a few hundred thousand dollars he wants to
give away.
</P>
<P>
   If you have led a life of healthy self-interest, you may be
surprised in these upcoming years to see how readily the charitable
impulse flows in you _ don't worry, it's as natural as lust once
was _ and it's smart to be prepared for it.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I think of it, this is another good reason to have fun
now _ you may have better things to do later on. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Richard Todd's most recent story for WORTH was
``I'm Squared Up with the USA!'' in the March 1998 issue.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
