<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-HOGAN-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'DUNDEE' HOGAN TAKES A STARTLING NEW PATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia  Color slides and
black and white photos of Paul Hogan and Linda Kozlowski are
available. 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Who can forget Crocodile Dundee?
 &HT;    More than a decade ago the backwoods Australian arrived in
America in the form of the wry, irrepressible Paul Hogan and took
the box office by storm in two Dundee adventures.
 &HT;    He hosted the Oscars, adding a much needed touch of Aussie
irreverence to the whole overhyped proceedings and became the
definite flavor of the year.
 &HT;    While Dundee disappeared into the bush somewhere Down Under,
Hogan stuck around. He made a handful of movies _ none of which
came close to duplicating his Dundee popularity.
 &HT;    Today Hogan lives in Santa Barbara with his Dundee costar, now
his wife, Linda Kozlowski. She gave birth on Aug. 10 to their first
son, Chance. (Hogan, 58, has five children and eight grandchildren
from an earlier marriage.)
 &HT;    He also has an offbeat new movie in which he is virtually
unrecognizable from the weatherbeaten, wisecracking wild man of Oz.
``Floating Away,'' (airing Aug. 30 on Showtime) is a picaresque
comedy drama with Rosanna Arquette as a boozy mother trying to
regain custody of her baby. Along the way she meets Shane (Hogan),
a womanizing, reformed alcoholic, and a paraplegic.
 &HT;    If Hogan was trying to shatter his swaggering Dundee image, this
role would seem a good place to start. Yet Shane shareS two
important traits with Dundee, Hogan said: ``Shane has a crusty
humor and he's the biggest liar in the world.''
 &HT;    Indeed the movie's running gag is that every woman hears a
different story of how Shane happens to be in a wheelchair. He's an
ex-stuntman, he brags to one lass, and while working on a film with
Raquel Welch, she insisted he make love to her on horseback. He
tumbled and ... hence the wheelchair.
 &HT;    ``He's a first class b.s. artist,'' Hogan says proudly of his
character. ``Shane exploits his situation _ if he can get sympathy
or money from it, that's fine with him.''
 &HT;    Of course there's a serious reason for Shane's paralysis and the
part comes complete with an all-stops-out death scene, one any
actor would relish. But it's not exactly what one expects from one
of Australia's favorite import. ``People who expect me to do comedy
all the time or play some triumphant figure might be in for a
surprise with this one,'' Hogan said.
 &HT;    After Dundee hit pay dirt, Hollywood offered the craggy faced
Hogan the earth. He starred in ``Almost an Angel'' (1990) and a
western, ``Lightning Jack'' (1994) _ both box office
disappointments. In 1996 he popped up in the movie ``Flipper''
(based on the TV series) and that too sank at the box office.
 &HT;    ``That wasn't my film, '' he explains, ``I was an actor for hire
in that one. But I did rewrite my lines a little.''
 &HT;    But he regrets nothing about it. ``Linda and I and the dog went
to the Bahamas for 10 weeks and I was nicely paid and got to swim
with the dolphins. But it was incredibly boring just being an actor
and I decided I didn't want to do that for a living.''
 &HT;    He admits he never expected to be an A-list movie star. Dundee
was a shot in the dark that just happened to hit box office gold.
``You can't top that,'' Hogan said, ``so you don't try. I don't
expect to suddenly come up with a grand idea tomorrow and write the
script and produce a movie that's going to be more successful than
that.''
 &HT;    And since he didn't expect the success in the first place, he
hasn't been devastated by the fact that he hasn't managed to
duplicate it.
 &HT;    ``Look I realize they don't sit around in Hollywood saying,
'Now, let's see: 'Should we hire Harrison Ford or Paul Hogan for
this movie?''' he shrugs. ``And Linda doesn't get scripts because
they can't decide whether to hire her or Meryl Streep. I never
wanted to be a film star or an actor. These days what I get offered
is B-grade action scripts that none of the big stars will do. So I
don't do them either. I also get sent all the stuff that has the
word Australian in it _ whether it's a head nurse or a nun, they
send it up to me.''
 &HT;    Meanwhile, Hogan, who alone and unaided revitalized the Aussie
tourist industry with his ``shrimp on the barbie'' commercials for
his native land, says he's been making good money again as a
pitchman _ selling Suburu cars on TV in North America _ and he no
longer has to work as hard as he once did.
 &HT;    ``They pay me well, as well they might, because I've got
credibility,'' he says.
 &HT;    Though mainstream Hollywood is not exactly beating a path to his
door, he says he's perfectly content. Even more since the arrival
of Baby Hogan. ``Right now I've got nothing on my agenda _ just to
practice being a Dad again. It's been a long time _ and I've
forgotten a lot.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based
<TEXT>
reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</TEXT>
