</P>
<P>
   More than 130 of Picasso's works belonging to his housekeeper
and chauffeur, Jacqueline and Maurice Bresnu, will be on display
until Aug. 30 at the Kunsthaus, 13 Untere Weisgerberstrasse (43-1)
712-0495. These works in ``Picasso: The Secret Collection'' are not
masterpieces, but they have a certain charm and piquancy. They
include pencil and felt-pen drawings, watercolors and portraits, as
well as ceramics. Open daily 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. Admission for the
exhibit: $7.80; free on Monday.
 &UR; SIGHTSEEING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Naschmarkt has thrived for several centuries. Starting near
the Karlsplatz and running a few blocks south, immigrants from
Turkey, the Middle East and Asia run food stalls where you can buy
kebabs, spices and fresh fruits from around the world. Open Monday
to Friday 6 a.m. to 6:30 p.m., Saturday to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Applied Arts, locally known as MAK, at 5
Stubenring, features the best of the early 20th-century Wiener
Werkstatte. A stunning display of the changes in furniture design
is a reminder that Vienna is not just a place of heavy baroque.
Admission for permanent exhibits is $2.60, special exhibits, $7.80.
Open Tuesday to Sunday 10 a.m. to 6 p.m., Thursday to 9 p.m.;
(43-1) 712-8000, fax (43-1) 713-1026.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear a zither playing during Vienna in the
Footsteps of the Third Man, a tour by subway and on foot to
shooting locations of the movie based on Graham Greene's novel. A
highlight is a walk through the underground canal system. The tour
meets every Friday at 4 p.m. at the main exit of Stadtpark subway
station on the U4 line. Fee: $15.50.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian Gallery Belvedere, a Baroque castle at 27 Prince
Eugenstrasse, is where the Austrian constitution was signed in
1955. But the real attraction is the 19th- and 20th-century art,
with paintings by Gustav Klimt, Egon Schiele, Oskar Kokoschka and
Richard Gerstl. Admission: $5; (43-1) 795-570.
 &UR; WHERE TO STAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 40 comfortable rooms, Pension Domizil, 14 Schulerstrasse,
(43-1) 513-3199, fax (43-1) 512-3484, is one of the best values in
what can be a very expensive city. It is in the heart of the city,
two blocks from St. Stephen's Cathedral. The rooms are furnished in
a traditional, spare style. With breakfast, a double is $130.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Furst Metternich, 33 Esterhazygasse, (43-1) 588-700, fax
(43-1) 587-5268, is in a 19th-century building tucked away on a
side street in the Sixth District, near the popular shopping area
of the Mariahilferstrasse. The hotel has 55 rooms with contemporary
furnishings for $145, including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Budget: Pension Stadtpark, 7 Landstrasser Hauptstrasse, (43-1)
713-3123, fax (43-1) 713-3123, has 21 doubles at $82, including
breakfast. This traditional, family-run establishment with bright
rooms and high ceilings is near the Stadtpark.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury: The service is discreet and the copious wood paneling
shines like a mirror at the Hotel Sacher Vienna, 4
Philharmonikastrasse, (43-1) 51-456, fax (43-1) 51-456-810. Many of
the 108 rooms and suites are decorated in luxurious fabrics with
exquisite antique furniture. Doubles start at $365, including
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Radisson SAS, 16 Parkring, (43-1) 515-170, fax (43-1) 512-2216,
occupies what was a grand palace. The rooms are stylishly decorated
in a mixture of traditional and modern, some looking over the leafy
Stadtpark. The hotel has 245 rooms, including 49 suites. Standard
doubles: $335.
 &UR; WHERE TO EAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zum Schwarzen Kameel (The Black Camel), 5 Bognergasse, (43-1)
533-8125, which serves typical Viennese cuisine amid wood, tile and
brass from the early 1900s, opened in 1618 (Beethoven is said to
have been a customer). There is a 10-table restaurant and a
separate roomy bar and buffet area with delicious open-faced
sandwiches (spinach and red caviar), casseroles and cheeses, wines,
beer and coffee. Closing time is 7 p.m. so the main meal is lunch,
when the signature dish is boiled beef with creamed string beans
and two sauces: chive and apple horseradish. A meal for two is
about $120, including an Austrian wine.
</P>
<P>
   Locals have taken to Do &AMP; Co (pronounced Doe and Coe, after the
name of the owner, Dogotan Attila) in the Haas House, 12
Stephansplatz, (43-1) 535-3969. It is decorated with crisp white
table cloths and upholstered chairs, and has an outdoor terrace
facing St. Stephen's. The menu is international _ a Thai-inspired
crispy pork salad, for example, and there is a sushi bar. Main
courses center on fish (like a tower of roasted Atlantic tuna that
is a specialty), wienerschnitzel and beef. A meal for two, with an
Austrian cabernet sauvignon costs about $130.
</P>
<P>
   Collio Restaurant, in the Hotel Triest at 12 Wiedner
Hauptstrasse, (43-1) 589-18-133, takes some of its culinary
inspiration from Trieste, which used to serve the Austro-Hungarian
Empire. Designed by Terence Conran, the long room with blue chairs
and metal tabletops extends into the garden, where dinner is also
served until the fall. Lamb tenderloin with olive crust and thyme
sauce is one of the chef's specialties. A meal for two with wine
costs about $95.
</P>
<P>
   A wine bar and wine store are part of Zum Finsteren Stern (To
the Dark Star), which is on a small cobbled street at 3-5
Sterngasse, in the old Jewish quarter. Lunch, informal but
delicious, is prepared on a hot plate, and there is only one dish a
day, from whatever is fresh at the market. A mushroom risotto with
fresh parmesan or a pasta with basil cost $8.50. A plate of
cheeses, olives and sun-dried tomatoes was $6; wines by the glass
are $3.45; (43-1) 535-8152. Hours: 1 to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   (Jane Perlez is chief of the Vienna bureau of The Times.)
 &UR; ---- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1998 Jane Perlez &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
