A5666 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMUNIZATIONS-BEFORE-     08-21 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMUNIZATIONS-BEFORE-TRAVELING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER  
 IMMUNIZATIONS FOR OVERSEAS TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY
TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR
PAGES! SEE ABOVE FOR A SALESPERSON IN YOUR TERRITORY.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Getting your shots when preparing for an overseas trip is no
one's idea of fun _ but it's a necessity. Now travelers have a
streamlined way to find out what shots they need, thanks to a
computerized information service that reduces the usual time, cost
and hassle.
 &HT;    That service is Travax, which derives its information from the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta and other
data bases, refining it and updating it weekly for public use.
 &HT;    About 1,000 outlets subscribe to Travax, including companies
that underwrite major travel, travel clinics, student health
offices, health maintenance organizations and city, county and
state public health offices.
 &HT;    Dr. Bradley Connor, a gastroenterologist who is affiliated with
the International Society of Travel Medicine in New York and on the
board of Travax, became interested in travel medicine about a
decade ago when he noticed more and more travelers returning home
with diseases that could have been prevented.
 &HT;    It was a major quandary in those days, Connor explained, for
travelers to find reliable and noncontradictory health information
about their travel destinations. Travax now digests existing
information and distills it so that it's easy to understand and
use.
 &HT;    We made use of Travax through our county health department,
which subscribes to the service. We visited it in preparation for
travel to Greece and Thailand. Like many county health departments
across America, ours offers an immunization clinic for travelers
headed overseas.
 &HT;    We started out by listing the countries we would visit and
approximate dates. We were quoted a consultation fee of $25 for
two. Any necessary shots would cost extra.
 &HT;    A registered nurse supplied us with information for each
destination, ranging from general health precautions to
drug-violation penalties. For both countries we were provided with
information on risk and prevention for diseases such as hepatitis,
polio, rabies, typhoid, cholera, encephalitis and malaria.
 IMMUNIZATIONS WEAR OFF  
 &HT;    Since our hepatitis B immunizations were current, we
concentrated on hepatitis A, typhoid, malaria and polio. We were
surprised to learn that we, like many other mature travelers, had
neglected to get booster shots for polio, a disease that was so
rampant during our childhood years. As a result, some seniors
contract polio during their travels because their immunizations
have worn off.
 &HT;    Protection against malaria was a bit more complicated in terms
of the types of medicines, areas of the countries we would be
visiting and whether mosquitoes in those areas had built up
resistance to the medicines _ information we would not have been
able to sort out by ourselves. The nurse recommended that we see
our own doctor about the anti-malaria choices, since we were taking
other medications.
 &HT;    Less than half an hour later, we were on our way, our arms
stinging from the shots, and carrying handy yellow cards that fit
into our passports listing our vaccinations.
 &HT;    Our county office averages some 2,000 clients a year, according
to Steve Kutz, supervisor of our county's travel vaccinations
program.
 &HT;    In the wake of Connor's initial concern about travel diseases a
decade ago, there are now more than 1,500 members of the
International Society of Travel Medicine, including 500 clinics,
300 in the United States alone, specializing in travel medicine.
 &HT;    Some Travax subscribers cover large areas. For example, one
subscriber is the South Carolina Health Department, so the
information is available at any of South Carolina's 46 county
offices.
 LOCATING INFORMATION  
 &HT;    To help you or your doctor locate a reliable travel information
source near you, write the International Society of Travel Medicine
for a free list of travel medicine clinics. The address is P.O. Box
871089, Stone Mountain, Ga., 30087-0028.
 &HT;    Travax offers an Internet Web site at www.tripprep.com/, as does
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention at www.cdc.gov/. The
centers can also be called at their international travelers
hotline: (404) 332-4559.
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
 &HT;    _______ 
 &HT;     (The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 The Mature Traveler Newsletter  
