<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5678 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POTTERY-$ADV22     08-21 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POTTERY-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLACK POTTERY IS LUSTROUS AND LUCRATIVE FOR OAXACAN VILLAGERS
 &HT;    With MEXICO-ANIMALS-$ADV22, MEXICO-RUGS-$ADV22; photos placed in
the International and Travel folders on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    EDs: San Bartolo Coyotepec is one of three villages profiled in
a three-part look at the artisan tradition that thrives in Mexico's
Oaxaca state.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories
for use Saturday, Aug. 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BARTOLO COYOTEPEC, Mexico _ A special place in the hills
here has been yielding light gray clay for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   And the people of San Bartolo Coyotepec, a village in Mexico's
Oaxaca (Wah-HA-ka) state, still harvest it and shape it into bowls
and figurines -- much the same as their ancestors did.
</P>
<P>
   But since 1953, the Zapotec Indians here have given their
pottery a different spin. That's when a tiny, wizened local potter
named Dona Rosa discovered that she could give the subdued black
color of her oven-baked pots a lustrous shine -- simply by rubbing
unfinished pieces with a quartz stone before their final firing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People loved it. And today, thanks to Dona Rosa, people can
live from their art,'' says the now famous potter's son, Valente
Nieto Real, 70, whose family is among the top producers of Mexico's
popular ``black pottery.''
</P>
<P>
   The home of black pottery is San Bartolo Coyotepec, and it is
seven miles south of the colonial city of Oaxaca.
</P>
<P>
   The village is a well-known tourist destination, but it has
managed to retain its small-town character. The families who make
black pottery welcome visitors into their shops to browse and buy;
at Dona Rosa's workshop, her family also offers demonstrations
showing how they make their pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Small pieces of black pottery are often sold in Mexican art
galleries in the United States. But a visit to San Bartolo
Coyotepec, which is an easy drive down Oaxaca's Highway 175, offers
tourists from all over the world a chance to see and purchase
pieces hard to find abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parents showed us where the clay is, and their parents
showed them,'' said Nieto Real, as he eagerly demonstrated how he
shapes clay into large round pots, pitchers, candlesticks and other
shapes.
</P>
<P>
   The classic pieces of black pottery are orbs with fluted edges,
and they range from a few inches to nearly two feet tall. Many of
them are decorated with flowers or perforated with exquisite lacy
designs, so that you can place a candle in them that reflects beads
of light.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the pots, which range in price from less than a dollar
up to $40, are scored with elaborate designs that resemble South
Pacific tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   Dona Rosa's family ships pots to Mexico City for a modest price.
Shipping to the United States is very expensive, so if you really
want a pot be sure to leave room in your luggage for safe packing.
</P>
<P>
   The clay the villagers harvest -- and protect with municipal
taxes -- is placed in a tub of water and strained through a sieve
to rid it of debris, explained Nieto Real.
</P>
<P>
   He picked up a slab of clay and slapped it on a pre-Hispanic
potter's wheel: a clay plate that spins with another plate turned
upside down on top of it.
</P>
<P>
   Even the tools the potter's use are mostly pre-Hispanic, Nieto
Real said, grasping the clay, expertly turning it into a hollow
cylinder and inflating it by hand into an orb. Other than skilled
hands, the potters' tools include wooden sticks and clay discs
shaped like moons.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces must be dried for several days before they can be
decorated or before handles can be attached. The laborious process
includes rubbing the pots with quartz that comes from the same
hills as the clay, to give them their characteristic black shine.
</P>
<P>
   Shiny black pots are porous and cannot hold water, Nieto Real
said, so buyers should beware. But the traditional gray-black pots,
which some people still make here, had been used for centuries for
water or as vessels for mescal, the local hard liquor.
</P>
<P>
   Nieto Real is proud that figures of gods and goddesses made from
the same clay he uses have been unearthed from Monte Alban, the
majestic Zapotec Indian ruins near his village.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our culture,'' Nieto Real said, pointing at the clay.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GET THERE: Hire a taxi in downtown Oaxaca, take a city
bus or sign up for a tour at your hotel to go San Bartolo
Coyotepec, where signs point the way to Dona Rosa's shop on Benito
Juarez Street.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
