</P>
<P>
   Last week alone, the market lost nearly $3 billion and trading
virtually ceased to exist. As of August 18, the market's
capitalization was $18 billion, compared with $128 billion at the
end of 1997. (By comparison, capital in the U.S. market, the
world's largest, at the end of 1997 was $11.3 trillion).
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Trading System (RTS), which handles more than half
of all issues on Russia's stock market, began operating in the fall
of 1995 and currently trades in 87 companies. Russia's other major
stock markets, the Moscow Stock Exchange and the Moscow Interbank
Currency Exchange (MICEX) began trading shares in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The most actively traded stocks are Russia's electricity
monopoly Unified Energy System (UES), Russia's largest oil company,
Lukoil, and the main long-distance telecommunications provider,
Rostelecom.
</P>
<P>
   With prices low, will the market rebound soon?
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe a substantial upswing to profit levels seen in
1996 and 1997 will not come until after the scheduled Russian
presidential elections in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market isn't growing now because the situation is not
stable,'' said Nikolai Gusev, a trader at Regent European
Securities. ``Nobody knows what's going to happen tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
