<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-RUGS-$ADV22-CO     08-21 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-RUGS-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUGS WOVEN FROM NATURE AND TRADITION MAKE OAXACAN VILLAGE A
FAVORITE TRIP
 &HT;    With MEXICO-ANIMALS-$ADV22, MEXICO-POTTERY-$ADV22; photos placed
in the International and Travel folders on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    EDs: Teotitlan del Valle is one of three villages profiled in a
three-part look at the artisan tradition that thrives in Mexico's
Oaxaca state.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories
for use Saturday, Aug. 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEOTITLAN DEL VALLE, Mexico _ Margarita Sosa Vasquez plucked a
tiny lime off a tree in her patio, sliced it and squeezed its juice
into a cauldron of boiling orange water.
</P>
<P>
   It was a simple, sudden gesture. But it was part of a very
deliberate process that unfolds here every day: the preparation of
colored wool and the weaving of Zapotec Indian rugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lime helps keep the colors firm,'' said Sosa Vasquez, who,
like so many families in this Mexican village, opens up her home to
strangers who want to buy her rugs and observe them being made.
</P>
<P>
   Teotitlan del Valle, a Zapotec town surrounded by green hills
and fields of spike-tipped maguey plants, is 16 miles east of
Oaxaca (Wah-HA-ka) city, the capital of the state of the same name.
It's a well-known tourist destination and a magnet for folk art
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The rugs produced here, using techniques passed down for
generations, are similar to geometric-patterned Navajo rugs and
considered some of the finest in Mexican crafts. The town has
prospered with this trade, and some of the weavers have built
spacious homes and workshops that greet you as you roll into the
village.
</P>
<P>
   Books celebrate the weavers' skill, and many townsfolk have
printed business cards in English and Spanish to serve clientele
who return repeatedly or send friends to the village to browse
through racks and racks of rugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men used to weave before, but now everybody does it,'' said
Sosa Vasquez, who heads a large family of siblings and their
children, all who know how to dye the wool with natural substances
and operate the family's creaky old wooden looms.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked off an unpaved side street, the Sosa Vasquez home is
typical: chickens and children scamper in the patio and dogs snooze
lazily next to the looms and pots of scalding water where wool is
dyed. Inside the one-room home the family unfolds rugs of all sizes
and colors, offering prices that range from $25 to more than $200.
</P>
<P>
   Bargaining is expected.
</P>
<P>
   The patterns and colors are lovely, and so are stories behind
how each are made. To dye wool various shades of purple, pink and
red, the weavers scrape a pest off nopal cactus leaves called the
cochineal. The tiny pest, when crushed, creates a scarlet paste
that is added to boiling water.
</P>
<P>
   Blues and turquoises are derived from indigo leaves, greens from
alfalfa, orange from a local tree, and a rich brown comes from
crushed walnut shells.
</P>
<P>
   The wool is dyed, spun and then laboriously woven into mostly
geometric patterns on looms that are operated by foot pedals. Rugs
can take weeks or even months to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years old, and he's already weaving squares,'' Sosa
Vasquez said, helping her nephew, Luis Roberto Rivera Sosa, climb
onto a diminutive loom designed for children.
</P>
<P>
   The rugs' patterns traditionally include jagged stripes
symbolizing lightening bolts, diamonds and designs from ancient
Indian ruins here. The weavers also make rugs with flowers and fish
on them, and some have experimented with copies of Miro or Picasso
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers recommend you check a rug carefully to see that it is
tightly woven and doesn't shine too much. A sheen can be a sign
that synthetic fibers have been used instead of natural wool. In
addition to visiting family workshops, you can also browse and
bargain in a market in the town square.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very beautiful work, and very complicated and
time-consuming,'' said Sosa Vasquez, who clearly takes joy in her
art and her Zapotec tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``These rugs can last 100 years,'' she says with satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GET THERE: Hire a taxi, take a city bus or sign up for a
tour at your hotel in Oaxaca to take the 30-minute trip along
Highway 190 to Teotitlan del Valle. The Vasquez Sosa home is on a
cul-de-sac, Privada de Zaragoza.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
