<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5723 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN22-COX     08-21 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Escaping Russia in my sock feet
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IVANGOROD, Russia _ Better they should call this place Ivan Go
Rob.
</P>
<P>
   You pass through here by train from St. Petersburg on the way to
Estonia. It's the border stop. A hundred yards or so farther down
the track and you're free and clear.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   Before, I'd always exited the country at the Moscow
international airport. It takes awhile, and the customs and
passport officials are surly and sullen toward you, but what can
you expect? You're getting to leave and they're having to stay.
</P>
<P>
   This time, by train, I arrived at the border at 3:30 a.m. I was
sleeping in my compartment at the time, but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   I awoke to a pounding at the door and angry shouts from the
corridor. The border guards were at the door.
</P>
<P>
   What they dearly love is to burst into your compartment using
their own set of keys, flip on the lights and roust you out before
you're even halfway awake.
</P>
<P>
   I'd ruined their fun by having jammed the lock from the inside,
using a Swiss Army knife.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing personal against border guards. But there's a lot of
robbery on Russia trains. My friend and interpreter, Pavlik, who
was traveling with me, had been robbed of $1,200 on a similar trip
a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves were able to enter his compartment and go through his
bags without him ever waking up. He thinks they used sleeping gas.
Russians think that way.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I got the door open as quickly as I could, fumbling with
the lock and dropping my pocket knife in the process. I made a
mental note to retrieve it later.
</P>
<P>
   No less than four guards tried to push their way in. Everyone,
Pavlik included, was shouting in Russian. For all I knew they might
be reciting the Lord's Prayer or cursing each other's mother. It
all sounds the same to me.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't realize there was a problem until Pavlik told me they
wanted to see how much money I was carrying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Show me the money!'' as it were.
</P>
<P>
   I pulled my stash of good ol' American dollars from the bag I
kept under the bed and started counting out hundreds. Meanwhile,
the border guards were counting their blessings.
</P>
<P>
   Before even bothering to examine my customs papers, they told me
my papers weren't in order. Never mind that I had listed all the
currency, and even the travelers checks I brought into the country.
There was no official stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I thought about it, I remembered the airport customs
official, who was busy talking to a young woman, waving me through.
Now I could wave my money goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   All but $500, they said. That's the maximum you're allowed to
take with you when you leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlik intervened, claiming that he should be allowed $500 as
well. The border guard doing all the talking knew a fair split when
he heard it:
</P>
<P>
   I'd get $500, Pavlik would get $500 and they'd take the rest _
exactly $670.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't interested in the travelers checks or the
approximately $100 worth of French francs I had on me.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbacks were what these old Reds wanted.
</P>
<P>
   I protested loudly, and even tried to take their picture taking
my money. I was informed I could either put down the camera or
they'd put me in jail.
</P>
<P>
   My only other option, they said, was to leave the train and
appeal their decision in the proper court when it opened Monday
morning. This was early Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a seasoned world traveler. I've been to Mexico. I know how
to handle these situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much will it take to make this problem go away?'' I asked
the border guard. I stopped short of winking and nudging him
good-naturedly in the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you trying to bribe a government officer?'' he responded,
his eyes narrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Some people you just can't deal with.
</P>
<P>
   I paid up. They even gave me a receipt. All was on the up and
up, leastways as far as the cash.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until later, when I started looking for it, that I
realized one of them had stolen my Swiss Army knife as well.
</P>
<P>
   This was my seventh trip to Russia. Lucky seven.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, I'm never coming back.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.mom; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
