<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5771 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABLE-TELCOM22-COX     08-21 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABLE-TELCOM22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New president-CEO hopes to lift spirits, stock at Able Telcom
 &HT;    By John Murawski
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Able Telcom Holding Corp. has named its
fourth chief executive in as many years in an effort to stabilize
the company and jump-start its flagging stock.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Dupuis, a wireless telecommunications executive who lives
in Boca Raton, was picked as Able's top executive after a
five-month search by Korn/Ferry International, a Los Angeles-based
executive headhunting firm. He will start August 25 as Able
Telcom's president, director and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Able Telcom's previous CEO, Gerry Hall, stepped down from his
$200,000-a-year job in March to run the company's Traffic
Management Group, a division that installs computerized highway
toll systems. The previous two chief executives were fired. Neither
Dupuis nor Able Telcom would reveal Dupuis' salary.
</P>
<P>
   Dupuis, 44, said he was contacted by Korn/Ferry several months
ago. In January he had just finished a two-year stint as president
and CEO at the Boca Raton office of Radio Movil Digital Americas, a
wireless phone company with business in Argentina, Brazil and
Venezuela. RMD Americas was sold in January to International
Wireless Corp., a San Mateo, Calif. firm, and its 20-employee Boca
Raton office was shut down.
</P>
<P>
   For six years before that, Dupuis ran the international
operations for Bethesda, Md.-based Comsat Corp., a wireless phone
and satellite signal company.
</P>
<P>
   Dupuis said he was drawn to Able because he thought the company
had good prospects and he did not want to leave South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has its challenges but it also has great
opportunities,'' he said from his home. ``There's been a lot of
negative publicity lately about the company, most of which is
untrue. The company needs to get over that and needs to demonstrate
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Able stock (Nasdaq: ABTE) closed at $7.50 Thursday, up 31 cents
on the day but down from a high of $20.31 two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Able Telcom has 2,650 employees, mostly in this country,
including 12 at its West Palm Beach headquarters. The 11-year-old
company primarily lays fiber-optic cable and designs turnpike toll
systems in the southeastern United States and installs phone lines
in Brazil and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been bedeviled since June by Wall Street analyst
Manuel Asensio, a short-seller who bets that stock prices will
fall. The part-time Miami resident has been issuing ``sell''
recommendations on Able's stock and issuing reports saying that
Able is having problems paying for a telecommunications subsidiary
it bought from WorldCom in April. Able has denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Though not part of the job description when Able began its
search, part of the new CEO's task will be to thwart Asensio and
repair the damage he has wrought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stockholder appreciation _ that's the name of the game,'' said
Able's Frazier Gaines, who had served as interim president and CEO
and will resume as CEO of Able's International Division. ``(Dupuis)
has a history of moving into adverse situations and turning them
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Able named John Mario, former chief financial
officer of 1st United Bancorp in Palm Beach, as executive vice
president and Curtis Dale, GTE's senior manager of operations in
Caracas, Venezuela, as chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
