</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release on the weekend of Saturday,
August 22, 1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNERS-HOWPROSLIVE _ Brooks Garcia just can't get enough of
romance, both indoors and out. The East Atlanta bungalow he's
renovated harkens to the '30s, and his garden is spilling with
old-fashioned plants. It's a setting the garden designer relishes _
and a look he strived for in his work. With a list of tips from the
expert. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   HERBS _ Everything you ever wanted to know about herbs can be
found under one roof Aug. 28-29, when Callaway Gardens south of
Atlanta presents its gigantic Herb Days celebration. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   LEEMAY-COLUMN _ When it comes to gardens, every season something
happens that had not happened the year before, that might never
happen again: an unexpected bloom, a death... It's the little
garden surprises that makes it all worthwhile. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FACES-OF-FAITH _ These Faces of Faith are modest and humble. But
they touch lives in extraordinary ways. They are happiest when
serving their neighbors and surprised to discover those neighbors
think they are special. They came to our attention through readers
who suggested them for The Post's Faces of Faith feature. (Life
stories follow.) (Gushee, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (d Category)
</P>
<P>
   COASTAL-FOOD _ If you want tips on finding a great waterfront
restaurant, ask a boater. That's the premise behind the just
published ``Intracoastal Waterway Restaurant Guide &AMP; Recipe Book''
by Susan and Charles Eanes (Espichel Enterprises, $14.95). The
book, the authors say, is ``a culinary cruise'' along ``the liquid
Route 66.'' (Norris, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   CATSUIT _ AUSTIN _ My day in a catsuit, inspired by The Avengers
movie, first person by Carolyn Kelly. (Austin American-Statesman)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-SHORTS _ Into That Good Night. By Ron Rozelle. Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux. $22. 182 pages. This memoir about memory _ or
rather the loss of it _ at first seems as plain as its East Texas
landscape. There are snakes living under the rocks in East Texas,
and one wishes Rozelle had looked under a few more of them. (And
other brief reviews of books.) (Warmbold, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RATPACK _ The lifestyle is fun. The same can't be said about the
movie. While ``The Rat Pack'' gives us a fascinating _ and often
absorbing _ peek beyond the larger-than-life facades of Frank
Sinatra, Sammy Davis Jr., Martin, Peter Lawford and Joey Bishop, it
can't overcome the fact that the actors look and sound almost
nothing like the characters they play. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RATPACK-LIOTTA _ He got more press than Elvis. Wore the coolest
tailor-made suits. Bedded beautiful dames. Hung with mobsters and
helped elect a president. Oh, and Frank Sinatra could carry a tune,
too. HBO brings Ol' Blue Eyes and his booze-swigging, chain-smoking
cronies, Dean Martin (Joe Mantegna) and Sammy Davis Jr. (Don
Cheadle), back to life Saturday in ``The Rat Pack'' (9 p.m.).
(Thompson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
