A5774 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN22-COX     08-21 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Take time to splurge
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I missed it. Once again, I'm a day late and a dollar short.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know there is a National Splurge Day? Neither did I,
until it was past. It's a day promoting self-indulgence and the
abdicating of responsibilities. I always miss the good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   In prepartion for National Splurge Day, the Women's Network, a
websiite on the Internet, polled women and asked, ``If you could do
one thing to indulge yourself, what would it be?''
</P>
<P>
   The answers are worth noting for all of us who missed the big
day but have serious plans to catch up with individual observances:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)``Eat Ben &AMP; Jerry's Ice Cream straight from the
container.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)``Read a good book from cover to cover in flannel
pajamas.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)``Spend the day shopping till you drop.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)``Order sexy lingerie from Victoria's Secret.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)``See more than one movie that YOU choose in the same
day.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)``Take a bubble bath while listening to music and drinking
wine.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)``Eat as much chocolate as you would like _ preferably
Godiva.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)``Spend the day at a spa pampering yourself completely.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)``Take a day off from work for no reason at all and spend
time alone.''
</P>
<P>
   There also was an entry from a mother of young children: ``Lock
the bathroom door and stay there alone for more than five
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   I could like these women. I want to spend time with them. If I
could, I'd share some of my own favorite indulgences:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Go to an art museum and spend as much time as I like
pondering the brush strokes of Monet.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Get a massage while listening to taped rain forest sounds.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Eat as many friend potatoes and onions as I like, followed
by a heaping bowl of bread pudding _ preferably all made by my
mother.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Play with kittens and puppies.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Rock babies at the hospital nursery.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Pretend I am redecorating my house and go to furniture
stores and pick out all new furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Sit on a beach and watch the water.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Invite my best friends to a long, leisurely dinner at a
fine restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Go to a greenhouse and buy all the plants I like and then
spend the afternoon planting them.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Sing at the top of my lungs while taking a 20-minute
shower.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Swing gently in a hammock beneath a flowering mimosa tree.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Learn to play the guitar.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Sit in a Texas pasture in the springtime and do a
watercolor of wildflowers ... and be good at it.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Take a ballroom dancing class.
</P>
<P>
   What would you do? What ``gift of the present'' would you
present to yourself? Take 10 minutes and make a list. Put down the
outrageous things about which you only dream. Put down the things
that make you laugh just to think of them. Put down the secret
things you'd never share with another soul.
</P>
<P>
   Now choose one of them. Find some way to do this for yourself
this week.
</P>
<P>
   We all know the long list of things we must do each day: work,
cook meals, run errands, chauffeur the kids to their activities,
and on and on. There's one more thing, though, we must do for
ourselves daily: splurge.
</P>
<P>
   These splurges have different names, of course. Ann Bender, in
her book (IT)Everyday Sacred(RO), refers to the pauses she takes in
her day as ``little Sabbaths.'' She recalls advice from a friend
who told her, ``We all need a certain amount of fallow time ...
watching the grass grow, sitting on the hillside, staring out the
window daydreaming. When we don't have it, there is a deeper
intelligence that won't come forth.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't need to set aside a special day to be kind to
ourselves. We need to find time each day. It's not irresponsible.
It's absolutely vital.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
