</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: When bullets fly, support Clinton
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When I was halfway through writing a column
condemning President Clinton's treatment of his closest supporters,
my editor called an editorial board meeting to discuss the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bombings?'' I asked. ``Have they bombed us again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``Clinton ordered air strikes against
terrorists bases in Afghanistan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Awwright!'' I said. ``I'll vote for that.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take us long to agree that we would rally behind
Clinton's decision as long as there was credible evidence that we
were bombing the facilities of the people responsible for killing
257 people and injuring more than 5,500 in the Aug. 7 bomb attacks
at the U.S. embassies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   I returned to my office and discovered that I no longer wanted
to write a column condemning Clinton right after the man made a
critical national security decision that I strongly supported.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, I would have reached over the top of my
Smith-Corona typewriter and pulled the copy paper with the two
carbons out of carriage with a satisfying ``rrrrrrrttt.''
</P>
<P>
   With practiced precision I then would have grabbed up new copy
and carbon paper and snapped the new original with two carbons back
into the typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   Now I close the text file with the unfinished column and
instruct the computer to open a new text file. Some of the flair
has been lost over the years.
</P>
<P>
   After the cowardly terrorist attacks on our embassies in
Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, I wrote a column
attempting to explore why the United States is the target of deadly
terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   America, after all, supports democracy, individual freedoms and
religious tolerance and has never taken over one square-inch of
land from another nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point'' I concluded, ``understanding anti-Americanism
becomes unnecessary. When reasonable methods fail, the United
States should be prepared to meet force with superior force.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton appears to have done exactly what I had hoped he
would do, the timing of a column critical of him, albeit on another
subject, seemed inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   I supported the decision by President Reagan when he sent
ground-based F-111s and carrier aircraft into Libya to bomb the
headquarters of Col. Moammar Gadhafi and some of his
terrorist-support operations.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's decision was based on credible evidence that Gadhafi
ordered the April 5, 1986, bombing of a West Berlin discotheque
that killed a U.S. serviceman and two others.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi barely escaped with his life. Since then, the Libyan
dictator has adopted a more reasonable attitude about doing
anything to anger the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Early reports are that Osama bin Laden also escaped unharmed
from Thursday's bombing against terrorists targets in Afghanistan
and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden is a virulently anti-American Saudi millionaire who is
believed to be a major sponsor of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence also links him and his organization to the attacks on
America's embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gadhafi, bin Laden may get the message and find a new way
to spend his millions. If not, I still believe the United States
should remain prepared to meet force with superior force.
</P>
<P>
   Even if I had not agreed with Clinton's decision to order
military strikes against terrorist facilities inside two sovereign
nations, I believe in supporting the commander in chief once U.S.
troops are ordered into harm's way, if at all possible.
</P>
<P>
   When the bullets stop flying, however, I will finish that column
condemning Clinton's treatment of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
