anytime thereafter:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LANDMARK HEART STUDY TURNS 50 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words. Includes a 350-word sidebar other long-term
studies.) &QL; 
 &UR; By RICHARD A. MARINI &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Framingham Heart Study, based in New England, turns 50 in
September, with two generations now contributing invaluable data on
heart disease, diet and health. One conclusion is that lifestyle
changes are proving hard to make.
</P>
<P>
   Slugged BC-HEART-STUDY-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF, priority code w, category
code l) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOU MAY BE LESS FIT THAN YOU THINK &QL; 
 &UR; (1,200 words. Color slide of the new FitnessAge fitness-assessment
product is available. Will be mailed to LifeBeat subscribers on
Aug. 18. &QL; 
 &UR; By KEN McALPINE &QL; 
 &UR; From Spirit magazine &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're diligent about exercise, working out regularly
with great gusto, you may not be as fit as you think. A new
computer product for use in the home analyzes fitness after the
subject has taken a few simple tests.
</P>
<P>
   Slugged: BC-MEASURE-YOUR-FITNESS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF, priority
code w, category code l) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHICH PARENT-KID BATTLES ARE WORTH FIGHTING? &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By AVA L. SIEGLER &QL; 
 &UR; From Child magazine &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kids don't come into the world with good judgment, good manners
or even good sense. A large part of your job as a parent is finding
ways to get your kids to want to do what they should be doing. Here
is a guide to helping your kids, age by age.
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-FAMILY-BATTLES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF, priority code w,
category code l) &QL;
</P>
