<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5792 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTIN-CONVENTION22-C     08-21 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-CONVENTION22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin seeks developer to take plunge
 &HT;    on building mate to convention center
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Now that the City of Austin is planning to
double the size of its convention center, officials want to make
sure there will be enough hotel rooms to accommodate the added
conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the City of Austin is launching an extensive _ and
typically difficult _ search for a developer to build a convention
center hotel and parking garage. By adding more hotel rooms and
parking, the city hopes to bring in larger conventions and
stimulate economic activity in the area around the center.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Friday, August 22, the city will run ads in The Wall
Street Journal, the Austin American-Statesman and on the Urban Land
Institute's Internet site seeking developers to build and operate
an 800-room convention center hotel and 1,000-car parking garage
near the convention center, at Cesar Chavez and Red River streets.
Developers have until Oct. 6 to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing business because we're not able to get a large
enough block of rooms to satisfy meeting planners,'' said Ric
Luber, executive director of the Austin Convention and Visitors
Bureau, which oversees the convention center. ``We're going to need
to get larger pieces of business to fill up the expanded convention
center.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the experiences of other cities, it will take more than
just a good advertisement or two to lure a convention hotel builder
to Austin. Cities such as Houston, Denver and Tampa, Fla., have
spent years trying to attract downtown convention center hotels and
often have had to offer myriad incentives to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Austin city officials nonetheless hope to get a convention hotel
built and open by the time the convention center expansion is
completed in 2001. Convention center hotels _ usually 600 rooms or
more _ generally can accommodate larger, multiple-convention
groups. They typically have restaurants, meeting space and
ballrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Convention centers that have been built in conjunction with a
hotel have done well, while those that haven't have languished,
said John Keeling, senior vice president of PKF Consulting, a hotel
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The availability of large blocks of rooms is the most important
thing for a meeting planner, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the city has lost out on 240,000 room nights because of
the lack of a convention center hotel or because the convention
center wasn't large enough, Luber said. Of conventions that
bypassed Austin since the center opened in 1992, 17 percent said a
lack of hotel rooms or the absence of a convention-size hotel
influenced their decision, according to a 1997 analysis done for
the city by C.H. Johnson Consulting of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most important factor in their decision _ more
important than the quality of the convention center itself,''
Keeling said.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio didn't have a competitive convention market until a
1,000-room Marriott hotel opened near convention sites there, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Size matters,'' Keeling said. ``A lot of smaller hotels are
not the same thing as one big one.''
</P>
<P>
   But convention center hotels are expensive and risky ventures,
and most cities have had to offer generous incentives to attract
them, Keeling said. For many hotel chains, it's better to build a
dozen small hotels around the country than one large hotel, which
can cost upward of $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make it worth their while,'' Keeling said. ``A
city has to remove some of the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeling said the developers of almost every convention center
hotel built _ except those in Las Vegas, Atlantic City, N.J., and
Orlando, Fla. _ have received some kind of economic incentive from
the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   Luber said the city is willing to look at possible incentives,
including fee waivers. But at this stage, it wants to find out what
hotel companies are interested and what they're willing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's largest hotel is the 478-room Renaissance Austin Hotel
in Northwest Austin. The Hyatt Regency Austin, which has 448 rooms,
is the largest hotel in the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   The Radisson Hotel &AMP; Suites on Cesar Chavez is in the midst of
an expansion that will give it 413 rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Sites being discussed for a hotel include land to the east, west
and south of the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   City officials aren't the only ones trying to lure a convention
center hotel developer to town. One group of downtown property
owners has spent the past two years trying to interest hotel
developers in land they control on three corners of Cesar Chavez
and Red River streets _ land they believe would be ideal for a
large hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have land, and we are sitting there with our arms open,
waiting for somebody to embrace us,'' said Austin real estate
broker Robert Knight, one of the property owners.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
