A5793 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTIN-REALESTATE22-C     08-21 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-REALESTATE22-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Austin's office boom could be peaking
</P>
<P>
   By R. Michelle Breyer
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ In July 1993, the Prominent Pointe office building in
Northwest Austin sold for $10 million _ close to $67 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the 150,000-square-foot building changed hands
again, this time for $15 million, or $100 a foot. Last month, it
sold one more time, for $22 million, or a dizzying $150 a square
foot.
</P>
<P>
   While Prominent Pointe clearly carried a prominent pricetag, it
wasn't a record.
</P>
<P>
   That was set last December, when the Bridgepoint Square office
building sold for $78 million, or $177 per square foot _ a level
far surpassing any other real estate sale in the Austin area.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for that record to last, say some real estate
brokers. Other office buildings on the market, including the
245,000-square-foot Arboretum Plaza, may sell for more than $180 a
foot, some say.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the record price increases at the area's trophy office
buildings have been the city's strong economy, low interest rates
and an increasingly tight office market. Citywide, office occupancy
rates are about 95 percent, and rents have risen more than 50
percent over the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   But are the sky-high skyscraper sales an indication that prices
may be reaching their peak?
</P>
<P>
   Some brokers _ pointing to factors such as new office
construction, fewer buyers and less investment money _ say maybe
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we're not at the top of the cycle, we're very close
to the top,'' said Jeff Pace, vice president and market officer of
CarrAmerica Realty, a Washington, D.C.-based real estate investment
trust, or REIT, that owns land and office buildings in the Austin
area.
</P>
<P>
   The high sales prices alone may be turning away some potential
investors who once viewed the Austin area as one of the nation's
best values.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's general concern about a number of markets,'' said Ron
Witten, president of M/PF Research Inc., a Dallas-based real estate
research firm. ``And Atlanta, Dallas and Austin are among the most
frequently mentioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with high prices, worrying some real estate companies is
the fact that more than a million square feet of office space is
under construction in Austin. More space typically means lower
occupancy rates and lower prices, according to basic economics.
</P>
<P>
   Less demand may also be on the horizon. REITs, which have poured
money into hot markets such as Austin and driven up prices, have
been battered by the stock market this year with rent and occupancy
growth slowing in most parts of the real estate market. This will
make it more difficult for them to raise cash to acquire new
properties. REITs invest in all types of real estate, including
shopping malls, office buildings, even prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that there are fewer buyers out there,'' said Phil
Capron, president of Austin-based Synermark Commercial Real Estate.
``There are undoubtedly buyers who have gone to markets other than
Austin where they think they can get a better deal.''
</P>
<P>
   What buyers there are may be more selective, looking only at the
area's nicest buildings with the best locations, highest rents and
lowest vacancy rates. For many, the cost of building a
top-of-the-line property from scratch _ roughly $135 to $160 a
square foot _ may be preferable to buying an existing building.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the number of buyers in the market has declined,
don't expect a bust that will send prices down to levels last seen
in the real estate doldrums of a decade ago .
</P>
<P>
   That's because unlike the 1980s, when capital was available to
anyone who wanted it and many investors bought Austin properties
with the intention of gaining a tax write-off or selling them
quickly for a profit, more of today's investors are in the market
for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately a building is worth the cash flow it can
generate,'' Witten said. ``There is a market segment that wants to
pay and can pay those higher rents.''
</P>
<P>
   Capron concurs: ``There's always some investor taking a longer
view and willing to pay a premium to stake out a position in the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Austin's top properties _ those along Lake Austin or in
other prime locations _ investors are more than willing to pay the
higher prices, said Volney Campbell, vice president of the Austin
office of CB Richard Ellis Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask what's driving the price,'' Campbell said.
``Were people just getting giddy, or is demand and rent in place to
support those prices?
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as demand stays tight, we can sustain these prices,
especially for unique properties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
