A5794 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COASTAL-FOOD22-COX     08-21 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COASTAL-FOOD22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take a 'culinary cruise' of the best restaurants on the
intracoastal road
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want tips on finding a great waterfront restaurant, ask a
boater.
</P>
<P>
   That's the premise behind the just published ``Intracoastal
Waterway Restaurant Guide &AMP; Recipe Book'' by Susan and Charles
Eanes (Espichel Enterprises, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   The book, the authors say, is ``a culinary cruise'' along ``the
liquid Route 66.'' The Atlantic Intracoastal Waterway stretches
from Mile Marker 0 in Virginia to its end at the Gulf of Mexico in
the Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   While cruising the route, the authors dined at hundreds of
restaurants on and near the waterway, analyzing the food, service
and menu variety.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting guide includes descriptions of 110 restaurants in
five states, along with recipes and profiles of the chefs and
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants in Palm Beach, Martin and St. Lucie counties have
significant roles in Florida's listing _ a dozen are profiled, from
the new (Spoto's Oyster Bar, West Palm Beach) to the old (Conchy
Joe's in Jensen Beach).
</P>
<P>
   Many are boat-accessible, and all can be reached by car. Diners
looking to sample good seafood with a water view will do well with
the book, since fish is a natural bestseller at these restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced cooks, too, will find it useful for its recipes, which
often omit measurements. Many are complicated, but most can be done
by a home cook with experience.
</P>
<P>
   The book is available at bookstores, restaurants included in the
book, marinas and by calling (800) 330-9542.
</P>
<P>
   Here are recipes from the book.
</P>
<P>
   Bienville Grill chicken
</P>
<P>
   Big Easy
</P>
<P>
   4 6-ounce boneless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   Cajun seasoning
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces andouille sausage
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces crawfish tails
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped green onion
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream or thin bechamel sauce
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle chicken breasts with Cajun seasoning, lightly brush
with oil and grill until done.
</P>
<P>
   To make Big Easy sauce: Saute diced andouille sausage, crawfish
and green onions in butter. Add cream and reduce by 25 percent.
Salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Serve chicken on a mound of mashed potatoes and serve with Big
Easy sauce and a sauteed vegetable medley.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (
</P>
<P>
   Arena's peanut butter pie
</P>
<P>
   2 cups peanut butter cookie crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chocolate cookie crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 stick ( 1/2 cup) butter
</P>
<P>
   3 cups whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   24 ounces soft cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 cups peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Combine cookie crumbs and butter; press into two 9-inch pie
plates and freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Chill a bowl, and beat whipping cream until stiff.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate bowl, mix cream cheese and sugar; add peanut
butter and vanilla and beat till smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Fold whipped cream into peanut butter mixture and spoon into
prepared crusts.
</P>
<P>
   Top with chopped peanuts, and refrigerate until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Makes two 9-inch pies, or 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
