<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5796 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-CRUISETERMINAL22-     08-21 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CRUISETERMINAL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unveiling a $12 million 'crown jewel'
 &HT;    By Michael Utley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ The architectural firm Zeidler, Roberts &AMP;
Associates recently unveiled its design for a $12 million cruise
terminal that is expected to become the signature building for the
Port of Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The five-story complex _ which, fittingly enough, resembles a
ship _ is a key element in the port's three-year, $65 million
expansion. The 90,000-square-foot terminal also is widely expected
to be the cornerstone of a revitalization effort along the Riviera
Beach waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the crown jewel of the Port of Palm
Beach,'' Port Commissioner Bob Williams said at a news conference
Thursday. Construction of the terminal is scheduled to begin in
January and end by January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Lead architect Ebcq Zeidler described the building _ which
includes a passenger terminal, an office complex and a top-floor
restaurant _ as a combination of the contemporary and modern styles
of architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to create a building that responds to the emotional
needs of the tourist,'' said Zeidler, whose Toronto-based firm also
designed the Kravis Center for the Performing Arts in West Palm
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're waiting to take a cruise, you don't want to sit in
a wooden box,'' he said. ``You want to get the feeling that this is
a special event. . . . So what we've done here is combine the
emotional and the rational.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing a new venue for cruise passengers, the
building will house port offices and employees of the U.S. Customs
Service, the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service and the
U.S. Department of Agriculture. The port's two cruise lines will
have offices there, as well as any new lines.
</P>
<P>
   Port officials are aggressively courting more cruise ships to
sail out of the Riviera Beach facility, once the new terminal is
built.
</P>
<P>
   They are seeking small and mid-size luxury ships, such as those
run by Renaissance Cruise Lines and Silver Seas Cruise Lines, both
of Fort Lauderdale, that offer multi-day cruises.
</P>
<P>
   The ships now operating from the port mainly offer so-called
cruises to nowhere and casino gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The large cruise ships that sail out of the Port of Miami and
Port Everglades in Broward County are not being courted because
they would not fit into the smaller slips and shallow water at the
Port of Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Riviera Beach facility now handles about 200,000 passengers
a year. Port officials are hoping to double that by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   When the cruise terminal was first proposed about two years ago,
it caused some concern among local hotel operators who feared that
more cruise ships _ especially overnight operators _ would take
away from their business.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with port officials during the past few months,
many have changed their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never viewed it as much of a threat,'' said David Burke,
vice president for sales and marketing at the The Breakers hotelcq
in Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, it will probably add business'' by attracting
more tourists to the area, Burke said. ``I think it's terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
