A5798 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEAD-VOTERS22-COX     08-21 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-VOTERS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBP-VOTERS
 &HT;    Checks show felons, dead purged from voter rolls
 &HT;    By Ian Trontz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Secretary of State Sandra Mortham's
report that 18,000 registered Florida voters are dead may be
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, her assertion that 50,000 felons are illegally
registered to vote may also be inaccurate, according to elections
supervisors in Palm Beach, Martin and St. Lucie counties.
</P>
<P>
   Early checks have revealed that many of the dead voters cited by
Mortham on Tuesday had already been removed from voter rolls during
normal periodic purges, the supervisors said. And, they said, some
of the felons may have had their voting rights restored by a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Mortham's election division said they knew the
numbers would probably not be accurate because the legislature,
reacting to voting fraud in Miami, gave them less than two months
to prepare them. They also had never before compiled such a list.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really have blown the list way out of proportion,'' said
Palm Beach County Supervisor of Elections Theresa LePore. ``Madame
Secretary should not be making comments in press conferences
knowing that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   LePore, a Democrat, accused Mortham, a Republican, of trying to
protect her own re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can say that she's given the information to us two weeks
before the election, and if there's a problem, it's because we
didn't take care of it,'' LePore said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mortham's campaign manager said Mortham was just doing her
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislature passed a bill that told her to do it,'' Gene
McGee said. ``It's going to be news whether the number is 10, 3 or
even 1 voter.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Mortham, the death roll included 2,813 voters in
Palm Beach, 421 in Martin and 411 in St. Lucie counties. Felons
numbered 3,106 in Palm Beach, 316 in Martin and 781 in St. Lucie
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Only Martin County has finished checking its death list. All the
names had already been purged, or had never been registered, county
Elections Supervisor Peggy Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   On their voter registration forms, some of the purported felons
said they had never been convicted, she said. Others claimed that
they had their civil rights restored.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach and St. Lucie counties have checked less than half of
their names, but supervisors in both counties said their early
results echoed Martin County's.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their deadline, state elections officials said they
could not verify all the names, but will try to do so on future
lists.
</P>
<P>
   The only confirmed case of a dead person ``voting'' involved a
Miami man who died in 1993 and whose name appeared on an absentee
ballot last year.
</P>
<P>
   That and other allegations of ballot fraud led a judge to
nullify Miami's 1997 mayoral election, and led to a law requiring
Mortham's office to cleanse the voter rolls.
</P>
<P>
   County Elections offices in each county normally purge voter
rolls by comparing them with local court and health department
records.
</P>
<P>
   But those don't include people who are convicted or die in
another county.
</P>
<P>
   The law, which took effect July 1, required Mortham's office to
compare county voter rolls with statewide court and health records
by Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Many Floridians share identical names and birth dates, so if one
died or was convicted, the others could fall under suspicion, said
Sandy Brill, of the state elections office.
</P>
<P>
   On average, he said, criminals were found to carry four aliases.
</P>
<P>
   The one identification that would set everyone apart _ a Social
Security number _ isn't required on voter registration
applications.
</P>
<P>
   State officials also didn't have time to check which felons had
their rights restored by a judge.
</P>
<P>
   County Election supervisors say they won't erase anyone before
confirming they've lost their life or liberties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We phoned one person who was listed as dead,'' Robbins said.
``He answered the phone. We laughingly told him. Luckily, he was in
his 50s. It didn't bother him at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
