A5799 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONDA22-COX     08-21 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Honda sales climb in US, despite flagging home market
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Honda Motor Co., Japan's third-largest automaker, continued its
record earnings pace by reporting that first-quarter group profits
rose 25.7 percent as strong U.S. sales made up for sinking car
sales in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The company said group net income hit a record high $548 million
for the three-month period ended June 30, compared with last year's
first-quarter record of $427 million. Sales rose 12.4 percent to
$11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Honda, which employs 13,000 workers at four Ohio plants, relies
on the U.S. market more than any other Japanese automaker, analysts
said. The U.S. accounts for almost half of Honda's revenue and more
than two-thirds of worldwide operating income, compared to half for
Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's biggest carmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Honda vehicle sales in North America climbed 8.3 percent to
265,000 units. In Japan, Honda sold only 185,000 autos, down 11.9
percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have been surprised at double digits (for the
increase in net profit) but this rise is very impressive,'' said
Jeremy Tonkin, an auto analyst at Towa Securities Co. Americans
flocked to Honda's CR-V, a small sport-utility vehicle, and the
Civic compact and Accord mid-sized sedans, long known for their
reliability and high resale value. Honda's sales in the U.S. grew
more than 12 percent in April and May compared with the same months
last year, while sales in June rose 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Accord has been among the best-selling car in the United
States, along with the Toyota Motor Corp.'s Camry.
</P>
<P>
   Honda's Ohio plants include a Marysville factory that makes the
Acura and
</P>
<P>
   Honda Accord; an East Liberty plant, which makes the Honda
Civic, an engine plant in Anna and a Marysville motorcycle factory.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's car market, the world's second largest, has been
crippled by the country's worst recession since World War II, with
industry-wide sales falling for 16 straight months and production
decreasing for nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
