<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5801 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN22-COX     08-21 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stealing Ding Dongs can be considered a 'federal' case
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I went looking for my missing box of Ding Dongs when I came
across my
</P>
<P>
   youngest son, holding a foil wrapper in his hand and looking
suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you steal my Ding Dongs?'' I asked, narrowing my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to answer. I pressed my question with the threat of a
swat on
</P>
<P>
   the rear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely, positively did not steal that box of pastry --
Ding Dongs,''
</P>
<P>
   he said, jabbing his finger in the air. It was a pretty strong
statement and
</P>
<P>
   despite the physical evidence, I believed him.
</P>
<P>
   He was indignant that I would have asked the question, however:
``Now, it's
</P>
<P>
   time for me to get on with taking out the trash, the job you
sent me outside
</P>
<P>
   to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Not being one to give up easily on an investigation, I pressed
on. It
</P>
<P>
   wasn't long before I found my youngest daughter with chocolate
stains on her
</P>
<P>
   dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aha!'' I said, ``So it was you who stole my Ding Dongs!''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, `` she answered, ``I'm just saving this dress from the one
time you
</P>
<P>
   actually gave me a Ding Dong instead of eating them all
yourself. Since it
</P>
<P>
   will probably never happen again, I've decided that this dress
will not be
</P>
<P>
   washed.''
</P>
<P>
   She went away in the same huffy mood as my son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm going to need a complete makeover,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I next ran into my oldest daughter who was holding a cassette
tape in her
</P>
<P>
   hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it is,'' she said. ``Twenty-three hours of your two
youngest children
</P>
<P>
   recorded doing nothing but eating Ding Dongs.''
</P>
<P>
   I plugged in the tape to hear the loud sound of chewing and
giggling. It
</P>
<P>
   was disgusting, but apparently it was all the evidence I needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you get this tape?'' I asked my oldest daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple,'' she said, ``I just made my sister think I was her
friend. What
</P>
<P>
   difference does that make?''
</P>
<P>
   On the way to apprehend the two criminals, I ran into my oldest
son and
</P>
<P>
   began questioning him. Just at that time, my youngest son
reappeared from
</P>
<P>
   taking out the trash and began talking in a highly agitated
manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait! You can't talk to him! He's my personal advisor,'' he
complained. ``I
</P>
<P>
   told him secrets never expecting them to be revealed. It isn't
fair. I want
</P>
<P>
   this matter taken directly to the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, would be my wife.
</P>
<P>
   Though she frowns on my two-a-day Ding Dong diet she did, as
expected, rule in my favor. Unfortunately, after all of that, my
oldest son said he knew
</P>
<P>
   nothing. This left me to the still-unresolved question of
whether he had
</P>
<P>
   been given any Ding Dong payola in exchange for his silence.
</P>
<P>
   I recalled my youngest daughter for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the tape,'' I said, ``and I know you were involved, but
I'm after the
</P>
<P>
   big fish. He's been suspected in Ding Dong theft before, you
know. If you
</P>
<P>
   'fess up now I'll give you complete immunity. Heck, I may even
let you have
</P>
<P>
   a Ding Dong or two in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me meet with my advisor,'' she said, walking over to her
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes she was back, ready to tell the whole story. It
was a
</P>
<P>
   twisted plot to deprive me of my Ding Dongs.
</P>
<P>
   I called my son and he reluctantly came forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' he said, ``I admit I had an improper relationship with
your Ding
</P>
<P>
   Dongs. In the legal sense I was truthful, I did not steal your
Ding Dongs, I
</P>
<P>
   merely borrowed them. I regret that I have misled many people,
including
</P>
<P>
   even my Mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   I was about to feel better about the whole situation -- at least
he was
</P>
<P>
   finally coming clean -- but he had to continue talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I furthermore believe that no punishment is called for in this
case,'' he
</P>
<P>
   said. ``Too many innocent people have been hurt by this. It is
time to move
</P>
<P>
   on. I have homework to do. It never would have happened, anyway,
if there
</P>
<P>
   hadn't been an unprecedented investigation as to the whereabouts
of missing
</P>
<P>
   Ding Dongs. I demand to be left alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Now where in the world would he get the idea to say something
like that?
</P>
<P>
   (Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall News
Messenger)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
