</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCOY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reyes delivers excellent start for Reds
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH, Pa._ Jack McKeon thumbed through a statistical sheet
before a recent game in Three Rivers Stadium and his finger stopped
on the line with the numbers for pitcher Dennis Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see Reyes have a good September to vault him into
next year, give him a little confidence boost going into spring
training next year,'' the Cincinnati Reds manager said.
</P>
<P>
   September?
</P>
<P>
   How about August?
</P>
<P>
   On a recent night, the 21-year-old Reyes cranked up his fourth
straight excellent August start for the Reds. And although neither
he nor the Reds gained anything in the win column, his performance
does earn this one-word comment: ``Terrific.'' And he has two more
starts this month.
</P>
<P>
   (In only six innings against the Pittsburgh Pirates, Reyes
struck out a career-high 12 _ most for a Cincinnati rookie since
Gary Nolan struck out 15 in 1964 _ but the Reds fell, 6-5, in front
of 13,137.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh catcher Jason Kendal doubled off Danny Graves to open
the ninth inning, boldly stole third and trotted home with the
winning run when Manny Martinez lined the game-ender to the
left-center wall.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes pitched five scoreless innings before a leadoff walk in
the sixth and four straight hits buried him under three runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds took Reyes off the hook in the seventh with three runs,
but the Pirates scored two in the bottom of the seventh when
shortstop Barry Larkin double-clutched a throw home, then threw to
first as the go-ahead run crossed the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates added another run in the inning on an infield hit by
Freddy Garcia, the sixth infield hit of the night (out of 11 hits)
for the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati got run-scoring singles from Dmitri Young and Jeffrey
Hammonds in the top of the ninth to tie, 5-5, but pinch-hitter
Eduardo Perez grounded out with two teammates on base.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes has pitched well enough in his four starts to be 4-0 since
the Reds traded closer Jeff Shaw for him and Paul Konerko, but he
is only 2-0 with a 2.13 earned run average, giving up six runs and
16 hits in 25 innings, while striking out 31 and walking 17.
</P>
<P>
   Using an assortment of breaking pitches that floated in at 79,
83 and 85 miles an hour with a few 91 mph fastballs, Reyes struck
out the side in the fourth, thus tying his career high with nine
strikeouts just four innings into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds were doing no better during the first six innings
against Jon Lieber, who held them to a first-inning two-out double
by Barry Larkin and a two-out double by Sean Casey in the third.
Neither runner advanced beyond second.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh broke through in the sixth, with an error by Reyes
helping. Kevin Young walked and Jose Guillen beat an infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the Pirates had four hits and only one reached
the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Martinez took care of that after Reyes tried to pick Young
off second base and threw into the outfield, moving the runners to
second and third. Martinez drilled a two-run ground-rule double on
one hop over the right field wall, then scored on Garcia's
solid-shot single up the middle to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds tied it with three in the seventh on a rally started by
Eddie Taubensee's double and Bret Boone's single. Lieber injured
his left side (muscle strain) and left with a 3-and-1 count on
Chris Stynes. Mike Williams took over and induced a fielder's
choice grounder out of Stynes.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Nieves batted for Reyes against left-hander Ricardo
Rincon and doubled to the left field corner, scoring Stynes. Reggie
Sanders reached on third baseman Garcia's error, putting two on
with one out. After Sean Casey lined to left, Rincon walked Larkin
and Young on eight pitches to force in the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   But Hammonds left the bases loaded by grounding into a force
play and the Pirates took care of business in the bottom of the
ninth
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
