<SLUG> BC-RATPACK-LIOTTA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Rat Pack's back, baby
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He got more press than Elvis. Wore the coolest tailor-made
suits. Bedded beautiful dames. Hung with mobsters and helped elect
a president.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and Frank Sinatra could carry a tune, too.
</P>
<P>
   HBO brings Ol' Blue Eyes and his booze-swigging, chain-smoking
cronies, Dean Martin (Joe Mantegna) and Sammy Davis Jr. (Don
Cheadle), back to life Saturday in ``The Rat Pack'' (9 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Ray Liotta (``Goodfellas,'' ``Unlawful Entry,'' ``Operation
Dumbo Drop'') stars as The Chairman of the Board. The intense actor
revealed what it was like playing a larger-than-life guy who slept
with Ava Gardner, sailed with John F. Kennedy and had a gold-plated
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Question: How much did Sinatra seep into your life? Did you go
to Vegas? Call women ``broads?'' Start drinking a lot?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: I'd play around at home with my wife and sometimes say
things. For a couple of months, there was complete total immersion
into his life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did you say?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'd say, ``Come here, you little broad!''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did she like that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, she knows me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Rate the Rat Pack. Who was the coolest?
</P>
<P>
   A: Depends on what your perspective of cool is. In a sense, Dean
Martin was the coolest, in terms of his temperament and demeanor.
It was much more even-keel. Frank was much more emotional and ready
to go off at the drop of a hat. Some people think of being edgy and
wound tight as cool. But Dean Martin was the coolest. I think Sammy
tried really hard at the coolness, but he was almost a caricature
with his lingo, ``Hey, babe'' and the hipness he tried to
personify.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your favorite Rat Pack lingo?
</P>
<P>
   A: Calling Kennedy ``Chickie, baby.'' Saying this is
``Endsville'' when you're finished with something.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few years ago, you turned down CBS' offer to play Sinatra.
Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wasn't sure I wanted to get involved in a miniseries. It
was a four-hour deal that spanned his life, and I just didn't feel
I was ready to take on Sinatra. When this came along, this script
was much more concise and tighter, and I turned down that. I
thought Sinatra was a lot to bite off, but when I sat down and
talked to the director (Rob Cohen) and saw how he wanted to do it,
I decided not to worry about how it was going to be received and
just go out there and act, have fun and let it rip.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was the role as intimidating as you thought it would be?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, I wasn't sure how they were going to do the music and
then if we were going to mimic Sinatra as he was singing. Then how
do you mimic him as a human being? Once I knew they were going to
use a sound-alike, it took the pressure off. He's a really hard guy
to get down. I mean, I'm from Jersey, I can understand the
edginess, but I didn't know that much about him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were you a Sinatra fan?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not really. You hear the negative things. The Mafia ties. The
tussles with reporters, but his was a generation before mine. It
was more like my parents' generation, and you don't really want to
listen to your parents' music.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Once you got into his skin, what surprised you the most?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably his troubles with women. At one point, they say he
faked his suicide with Ava Gardner. One time they said he took
pills. Whether it was true or not, here was somebody who seemingly
had everything and lost it and got it back again, but he never, as
many of us do, worked it out with his women.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you sing?
</P>
<P>
   A: When I first started out in theater, the first year and a
half, all I did was musicals. I can carry a tune. I used to play
guitar. But when it comes to Sinatra, that's a whole other
dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you try to look like Sinatra?
</P>
<P>
   A: To a degree. We caught him at a period where he was in his
40s, so he wasn't as skinny as he once was. We did fix my hair to
make it look like I was wearing a toupee. I shaved my hairline way
back because he had a very high forehead. We got the clothes and
used the people who made his suits, things were much tighter and
form-fitting, so it gave you a certain kind of posture.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the deal with the fake horse's head you received
from Tina Sinatra?
</P>
<P>
   A: I didn't know where she was coming from with it. There are a
lot of projects that are going to be coming out about his life, and
I'm sure she just wants to be a part of them. She saw and heard
that we were being extremely diligent about what happened, this
wasn't a sensational look.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Operation Dumbo Drop.'' What were you thinking?
</P>
<P>
   A: I just finished ``Unlawful Entry,'' and there was another
edgy part that I played, so a lot of people were only seeing me as
this tough guy, so I said, ``I need a Disney movie.'' And then I
heard about this `Dumbo Drop' and said, `There you go, I need a
movie about me and an elephant.'
</P>
<P>
   When I first started acting, I did musicals, Shakespeare,
Tennessee Williams, you do a little bit of every-thing . . . that's
the same reason why I did ``No Escape.'' Whether they were the best
career moves, probably not. But why not do that? How many gangsters
can you play? How many rough, edgy guys can you play?
</P>
<P>
   The biggest boo-boo I made was probably ``Turbulence.'' That was
a too-edgy guy. But I was sick of losing out to certain people I
felt weren't qualified to play the parts that they were playing.
For what it was, ``Dumbo Drop'' was a well-made movie that had
something to say that was heartwarming. I don't regret doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If Sinatra were alive today, what would he say about your
performance?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hopefully, we got to the heart of his emotional core. He was
somebody that gave his all and wore his heart on his sleeve, and
I'd like to think we captured his essence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
