<SLUG> BC-RATPACK22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let's be frank: 'Pack' stars don't look the part
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine living like Tinsel-town-sized icons for three months.
Millions of fans adore you. Vegas and Hollywood are your
playgrounds. You drive expensive cars and have different babes
hanging on your arm every night.
</P>
<P>
   Then . . . like that, it's gone. Over. Endsville, baby!
</P>
<P>
   That kind of ring-a-ding life is hard to give up, says Joe
Mantegna, who plays Dean Martin in HBO's ``The Rat Pack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wrapped something like two in the morning and we all looked
at each other and I think we collectively said, `Gee, wouldn't it
be nice to go to Vegas and do a few more weeks of this and maybe
take this on the road for six months?' It was a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can't be said about the movie. While ``The Rat Pack''
gives us a fascinating _ and often absorbing _ peek beyond the
larger-than-life facades of Frank Sinatra, Sammy Davis Jr., Martin,
Peter Lawford and Joey Bishop, it can't overcome the fact that the
actors look and sound almost nothing like the characters they play.
</P>
<P>
   Only Mantegna bears some resemblance to his bubbly, yet distant,
Rat Pack character who was fond of calling Vegas his ``room.''
Despite giving a fine, almost ``Goodfellas''-like turn (especially
while beating up reporters and pushing around a wimpy Lawford), Ray
Liotta is woefully miscast as Sinatra. For starters, he lacks
Sinatra's charisma and looks as much like Ol' Blue Eyes as Pee Wee
Herman. We won't even mention that Liotta's almost whiny voice is
about five octaves higher than Sinatra's.
</P>
<P>
   As a tortured Sammy Davis Jr., it's Don Cheadle who actually
turns in the movie's best performance. But, once again, you never
believe you're watching the real Rat Packers.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the point, sort of. Instead of looking for
impersonators, the producers chose the best actors for the parts.
``This film is not about impersonation,'' says Kario Salem (``Don
King: Only in America''), the movie's screenwriter. ``It's not
about the mannerisms and the sort of cartoon version of who we
think these people are. It's about their insides-out. No one tried
to impersonate these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Cheadle was hesitant to admit that he nailed his character.
``I can't say that,'' he says. ``Sammy was a one-of-a-kind and we
probably won't see the likes of him again. He was a septuple
threat. Anything he grabbed, he could do.''
</P>
<P>
   What the often dark ``Rat Pack'' does is take us backstage,
showing us how these hip, cool cats lived when the music stopped.
It focuses mostly on Sinatra's friendship with the Kennedys and how
that friendship soured after John F. Kennedy became president and
abandoned the singer because of his alleged mob ties.
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Rat Pack'' is basically Sinatra's story (his
legendary fights with Ava Gardner, how he almost got whacked by the
mob and his skirt-chasing ways), it's Davis' story that is most
compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was often at odds with the black community, who viewed him
as an ``Uncle Tom'' and first-class sellout. He was despised by
white audiences after he married a white Swedish actress, May
Britt. He was often the brunt of mean-spirited and racist Rat Pack
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He slid back and forth between caricature and character,
sometimes invisibly,'' says Cheadle. ``It was hard to tell where
that line was.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds director Rob Cohen: ``I think the expectation of this film
is going to be singing, dancing and (messing around) in the Sands
Hotel. There's a lot of that in the film, but, on the other hand,
it isn't a fluff ball either. There was a lot going on, politically
and socially.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the actors say they had no trouble researching their
roles since there are reams of information on the Rat Packers.
Cheadle had the toughest time, though, considering he had to learn
to tap dance (from Broadway whiz Savion Glover), twirl a Colt
six-shooter, play the trumpet and bang a drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost after every take, I would have to pull (director) Rob
aside and say, `Is this too far? Am I in the pocket?' '' he
recalls. ``Because every footage I've seen of Sammy, there was
always an awareness that he was on camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Liotta says he read 14 books, went to Sinatra's Palm Springs,
Calif., retreat and watched more than 20 of his movies. But his
biggest insight into Sinatra came after watching a Walter Cronkite
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank was at Joey Bishop's with friends and the camera was on
them and there they were interacting without the whole
celebrity/icon kind of image,'' he says. ``And they were just goofy
and fun. That was the biggest thing for me, to play human beings
who happened to be icons.''
</P>
<P>
   But after learning more about Sinatra, Liotta admits he didn't
like him very much. ``If I ever met him, I'm not sure if he was
somebody I'd pal around with,'' he says. ``I don't like celebrities
who get too big for their britches.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
