<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High construction bids for Ohio stadium mean more bids
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Construction bids for the proposed baseball
stadium in downtown Dayton came in high, forcing project planners
to consider more cost cutting and another round of bids.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that have bid on the job said the stadium needs to be
shrunk or the $16 million estimated cost needs to go up.
</P>
<P>
   Only two companies submitted bids this time and the lowest was
about $1 million over estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The city asked for bids for the stadium, and for estimates of
savings if masonry was reduced, a proposed front plaza not built
and the number of seats reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Dugan and Meyers Construction of Cincinnati bid $17.8 million
for the full project and $17.1 million with the reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Danis Building Construction bid $19.6 million for the full
stadium and $18.9 million for the scaled back project.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton wants to build a 10,000-seat stadium to be home for a
Class A minor league baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the bid opening, city officials met with the
project architect and other staff to go through the bids and
discuss what to do now.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from both companies said they bid as low as they
could. Both also said they could meet the requirement that 10
percent of the work go to minority-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Tuss, Dayton's director of community development, said it's
possible the region's busy construction industry may have led to
the high bids. ``We're in a very hot construction market right
now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The city cannot accept bids above the $16 million estimated cost
that's set in a city ordinance for the project, Tuss said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's options include redesigning the project and putting
it out for bid a third time.
</P>
<P>
   Five companies bid on the project in June, with the lowest
coming in $2.6 million over budget. At that time, the city had the
project on a very tight construction schedule, which contributed to
the high costs.
</P>
<P>
   The city extended the timetable for the second round, but Vince
Corrado, president of Shook Construction, said, ``Unless they go to
a complete overhaul of the design, they are going to have to raise
the estimate.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his company put bids together for both bid openings, but
did not submit them because they were above the project estimated
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Kylander, principal estimator for Messer Construction in
Cincinnati, which bid in June, said the design changes made after
the first bids were not enough to bring the costs down several
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually you have to take something out of the building,''
Kylander said. ``You need to reduce the size of the project.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
