<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACES-OF-FAITH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Worshiping God by quietly helping others
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These Faces of Faith are modest and humble. But they touch lives
in extraordinary ways.
</P>
<P>
   Some work with the poor. Others teach their faith to new
members, visit the sick or care meticulously for their place of
worship.
</P>
<P>
   All of them go about their tasks with a smile, a willing heart
and little fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   They are happiest when serving their neighbors and surprised to
discover those neighbors think they are special. They came to our
attention through readers who suggested them for The Post's Faces
of Faith feature.
</P>
<P>
   MARGARET GARR
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I participate is to give other people the
realization that they can do it, too,'' said Margaret Garr, a
great-grandmother whose day is seldom long enough to embrace all
the people she would serve.
</P>
<P>
   So, she has to choose.
</P>
<P>
   Garr stopped her volunteer work at St. Mary's Hospital after
nine years so she could teach inmates three days a week at the Palm
Beach County Jail in West Palm Beach. She helps them pass the high
school equivalency exam.
</P>
<P>
   The North Palm Beach resident still tutors kids one day a week
at Hope Rural School in Indiantown. She has done that for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   The retired math teacher is also a Eucharistic minister who
serves communion during Mass at St. Paul of the Cross Roman
Catholic Church in North Palm Beach. And she takes the sacrament to
the sick.
</P>
<P>
   Garr reads Scripture at services, helps teach a course for the
Christian initiation of adults, takes a weekly turn in the church
gift shop and serves on her church's St. Vincent de Paul committee
that helps the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a woman who has been blessed with many talents,'' said
her pastor, the Rev. Arthur Venezia. ``More importantly, she has
been willing to share those with the church and the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Garr came to Florida from Kentucky when her husband died 13
years ago. She suggested three reasons for her active life in
service to others.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband were deeply moved by a verse in the Gospel
of Matthew (25:40) that reports Jesus saying, ``Whatsoever you did
unto the least of these, you did unto me.''
</P>
<P>
   She is a happier woman if she is busy, she said, and God has
given her health and energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell myself that if I use those things for his honor and
glory, I'll keep them a while,'' Garr said. ``So far, so good.''
</P>
<P>
   The will to serve must be in the genes. Garr has one son who is
a priest in Peru and another who works for World Hunger Year, a New
York agency concerned with world poverty. Her daughter is the
director of a social service agency in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The children bought her a computer so she could stay in touch
with them by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   She uses it to fire off epistles to Washington politicians. Garr
also is a member of Pax Christi, a national Roman Catholic
organization that works for peace and justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (the computer) helps a lot to zap letters to the
president and senators about some of our causes,'' Garr said.
</P>
<P>
   PHIL DAVIS
</P>
<P>
   Phil Davis manages computer systems to earn a living and serves
Christ to offer others a life.
</P>
<P>
   He is on the streets of Riviera Beach most Saturdays to proclaim
his faith. He greets people, gives them literature and invites
everyone he sees to join him in worshiping _ and serving _ God.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is really committed,'' said the Rev. Tony Drayton, pastor
of St. James Missionary Baptist Church in Riviera Beach. ``All the
outreach ministries of the church are coordinated through him. He
really believes in the great charge of evangelism.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man from West Palm Beach is a computer consultant who
has a hand in almost everything that happens at his church.
</P>
<P>
   As one of five church deacons, he is responsible for the
pastoral care of more than 40 church families.
</P>
<P>
   He stays in touch with them, works to include them in church
activities and carries their concerns and needs to the pastor. He
calls on them at home and, when needed, visits them in the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a love for Christ,'' Davis said. ``It's not
an easy journey. You always have to address the needs of others
first. The self has to come out of the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is married and helps his wife, Natasha, raise their two
children, Deon, 8, and Phylicia, 4. His family comes first, he
says, but that doesn't prevent him from serving the church.
</P>
<P>
   In his spare time, he teaches a Sunday school class, is part of
the church's AIDS ministry, is a member of the praise team and
teaches a computer class to the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not do these things with an air of superfluity but
rather with a genuine, Godly motivation,'' wrote Rendell Brown when
he nominated Davis for recognition. Brown is a church member and a
West Palm Beach attorney. ``He is always ready with a smile, a hug
and an angelic presence. Deacon Davis is a daily delight for us
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has a simple _ if difficult _ explanation for keeping his
life in balance while giving his time and energy to serve his
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put others first, the self will take care of
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   MEYER COHEN
</P>
<P>
   It's the little things that count. And Meyer Cohen spends most
of the hours of most days doing them.
</P>
<P>
   He opens his synagogue every morning. Closes it at night. He
arranges rooms for daily services and the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   When the rabbi is away, he organizes the prayers. He visits the
sick and takes people to the store. And he is one condo president
admired by people. His philosophy is simplicity itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody can't come, I bring them to shul or shopping,''
Cohen said. ``I think it's the right thing to do. My religion tells
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is an 81-year-old widower who lives in Century Village,
runs his condo, serves his synagogue and cares for all sorts and
conditions of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of who they are, he just wants to help people,''
said Norma Kuras of West Palm Beach. ``I really respect him as a
human being who doesn't look at whether you're Jewish or not. If
you need help and he can help, he's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is the first vice president of Aitz Chaim Congregation, an
Orthodox synagogue in West Palm Beach. Much of his life revolves
around the building and its people.
</P>
<P>
   He arrives before 7 a.m. each day to open the building and set
up for morning prayers. He is there for evening prayer at 6. Except
for the Sabbath and holidays when the faithful cannot drive, Cohen
drives members to and from services and activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been affiliated with the synagogue since its inception,''
said Palm Beach County State Attorney Barry Krischer, who is a
member of the synagogue. ``He's very active. He never hesitates to
fill in. He's a wonderful man.''
</P>
<P>
   He looks after his neighbors in his condominium association so
well they gave him a plaque to recognize his kindness.
</P>
<P>
   Looking after his neighbors is Cohen's principal occupation.
Many Century Village residents have no family in the area, Kuras
said. Cohen has become their family.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to visit someone who is ill, Meyer is there, or just
left or is on his way over,'' Kuras said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen gives himself endlessly to his friends and neighbors, but
he doesn't take himself seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a human being, I think it's the right thing to do,'' Cohen
said, hinting that he is just collecting good deeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always short of mitzvahs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   FRED MCKOY
</P>
<P>
   Fred McKoy is equally at home in all churches.
</P>
<P>
   He serves meals to the poor at St. George's Episcopal Church in
Riviera Beach. He helps patients at Noreen Mckeen Roman Catholic
home in West Palm Beach. And he is an indispensable presence at his
own First Presbyterian Church in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one God,'' McKoy said. ``The name of the church
is secondary as long as you're willing to do God's work.''
</P>
<P>
   McKoy, 75, came to Florida 11 years ago after retiring from an
insurance company job in New Jersey. He got involved at the church
at once.
</P>
<P>
   Twice chosen to be a deacon, McKoy has also served a term on the
church's governing body. But it's the ``hands on'' service to
church groups and individuals that brings out the best in this
humble man.
</P>
<P>
   He began cleaning the church when the sexton was sick, and he's
still doing it. He prepares meals for women's groups, sets up for
flea markets and helps with the ministry to senior adults.
</P>
<P>
   When a church member who uses a wheelchair needs help, McKoy is
quick to respond, said Eileen Zern from West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there is something different when Fred helps,'' wrote
Zern, who suggested McKoy be recognized for his ministry. ``There
is always a quiet smile. There is always an encouraging word.
There's always an aura of caring and concern in which Fred shows
his faith.''
</P>
<P>
   He arrives at St. George's soup kitchen by 10 a.m. for the noon
meal on Tuesdays. There's soup to cook, trays to prepare, people to
serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always cheerful,'' said Miriam Bigbee, helps out at the
soup kitchen. ``He's never out of sorts. He's willing to do
anything at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
