 Friday, Aug. 21, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLL (San Francisco) _ Responses to a San Francisco
Examiner survey of President Clinton's public apology this week
showed a clear majority, nearly 55 percent, felt he had not
redeemed himself with his speech. By ANASTASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   DAY-CARE (Malta, N.Y.) _ Parents of kids at a local day care
center will soon be able to check on their children without leaving
the home or office. The YMCA Day Care Center is one of the first in
the region to position video cameras that, for a fee, can be
accessed via live Internet feeds in the corners of eight rooms at
the center. By BRENDAN LYONS.
</P>
<P>
   SAMARITAN-FIGHTS (San Antonio) _ A couple of would-be carjackers
picked the wrong target the other day. Bill Sanchez said he stopped
to help two young men who flagged him down as they peered under the
hood of a dirty white Camaro. But instead of receiving thanks for
his trouble, Sanchez, 49, found himself staring at the glint of a
knife blade pointed at his chest. So he fought back and won. By
KATE HUNGER.
</P>
<P>
   PCB-HUDSON (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Environmental Protection Agency
will decide by the end of the year whether to order an early action
to stanch the flow of PCBs from hot spots in the Hudson River. By
PAUL ZIELBAUER.
</P>
<P>
   SF-SECURITY-FIRM (San Francisco) _ The security firm Mayor Brown
has courted to take over patrol and guard duties in the city's
public housing owes the federal government more than $300,000 for
unpaid taxes, records show. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   LOTTO-WINNERS (San Antonio) _ They each chipped in $2, and now
17 City Public Service employees are going to reap a tidy sum after
purchasing one of two winning tickets in Wednesday's $33 million
Lotto Texas jackpot. The CPS 17 will split the jackpot with an
unidentified winner from Houston, lottery officials said. By
CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Monster 3D video cards have grown
from a curiosity among hard-core gamers to a must-have addition for
anyone who regularly plays PC games. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader wants to know how to find
out how fast a computer runs and how to check the megahertz. A Q&AMP;A.
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Interviewing someone for a job? Don't
call his former supervisor. Peer evaluations often provide better
information than a supervisor. Peers provide a lot of valuable
information and often have a good handle on what makes a candidate
``tick,'' said Bill Bufkins, director of human resources for
Johnson Engineering Corp. in Webster, Texas. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FRIENDS-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Your Friends and Neighbors''
is about six people, three couples, one marriage and an infinite
number of messy relationships. The movie, a ``Bob &AMP; Carol &AMP; Ted &AMP;
Alice'' for the cynical 1990s, is, as Pauline Kael said about ``A
Clockwork Orange,'' appallingly funny. By JEFF MILLAR.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DANCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ There are very few nice surprises
in this movie-reviewing business, which makes ``Dance with Me'' all
the more unusual. It's a gentle, good-tempered, wholesome-hearted
movie. By JEFF MILLAR.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-RATPACK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Call up all your hepcat pals and
tell them to skip ``The Rat Pack,'' HBO's new movie airing Saturday
night at 9. It's hard to believe anyone can screw up a film with
such lively subject matter as the complex relationships between
Frank Sinatra, his entertainer pals, John F. Kennedy and a host of
mobsters. But ``Rat Pack'' is relentlessly bad. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BESTMAN-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Best Man,'' a new comic
romance from Italy, tells the story of Francesca, the beautiful
young daughter of a good but gone-into-debt family. It's the
morning of her arranged marriage to the older, colder Edgardo, and
Francesca begs the saints to come down and save her. By STEPHEN
WHITTY.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DANCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Dance with Me'' is about a young
Cuban named Rafael Infante (Chayanne) who comes to Texas to find a
dance studio operator named John Burnett (Kris Kristofferson). John
gives Rafael a job as a janitor, unaware that he is Rafael's
father. By BARBARA SHULGASSER.
</P>
<P>
   ART-FACES (San Francisco) _ ``The Face of Art,'' at the Ansel
Adams Center here through Oct. 18, might be the sleeper of the
season. The show includes more than 100 photographic images of
primarily American artists made from 1850 to 1950, and they
document the radical changes that occurred during that time in
fashion, lifestyle and art itself at the same time that they show
how artists, both well-known and unknown, looked. By DAVID BONETTI.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BEST-LOOKOUTS (San Francisco) _ California's best lookouts are
much that way give you more than a dramatic view. You also get a
sensation that goes with it, and that is why the experience can
stay with you _ sometimes for years. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
