<HEADER>
A5881 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DANCE-REVIEW-HNS     08-21 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DANCE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOLESOME-HEARTED `DANCE' HAS A SOUL FULL OF SALSA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEFF MILLAR 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are very few nice surprises in this movie-reviewing
business, which makes ``Dance with Me'' all the more unusual.
</P>
<P>
   It's a gentle, good-tempered, wholesome-hearted movie. It's not
much more that a snow cone; but 15 minutes into it, by golly, you
might discover you want a snow cone. This one is cool and sweet.
That's as much as you can ask of a snow cone.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the film's draw comes from the actor in the
protagonist's role. He bills himself by the mono-name Chayanne.
</P>
<P>
   I'd never heard of Chayanne before now, but he's already a big
blip on radar screens I do not routinely monitor. He's a Puerto
Rican singer who's been working since he was 10 and is platinum in
Spanish-speaking markets from his music videos, concerts and
appearances in soaps.
</P>
<P>
   There apparently was a lot of pent-up demand for Chayanne to
take off his shirt, for the taking-off produced sounds of
appreciation in the higher frequencies from the screening audience.
</P>
<P>
   He's a rather good actor, but what Chayanne has principally
going for him is neither trainable nor obtainable by experience:
The camera simply loves him, the way it loves Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Chayanne plays Rafael, first seen in Santiago, preparing to
leave for the States, sad to be leaving Cuba. His visa sponsor is
John Burnett (Kris Kristofferson), who owns a rather tatty dance
studio in Houston and will provide Raffa a job as a handyman.
</P>
<P>
   Raffa's principal reason for coming is to meet John, who does
not know he is Raffa's father, the result of John's cruise-ship
affair with Raffa's mom, who has recently died.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arrival in Houston, Raffa becomes quickly smitten by Ruby
(Vanessa L. Williams), a dance instructor. She has come close to
winning the national Latin dance competition. She fears this year's
event in Las Vegas will be her last chance. But the partner with
whom she's working can't cut it; and she can't stand the partner
with whom she could win, who is also the father of her small son.
</P>
<P>
   Can Raffa dance? ``Of course I can dance, I am Cuban,'' he says.
Not dance in the ``and-one-two-three'' Bob Fosse choreography
sense. He doesn't much admire that. But put him on the floor in a
Latin club and the music will inform him what to do. Does Ruby
respond to that? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   You can pretty well take the narrative from there, can't you?
And that's one of the deposits in this film's growing bank account
of good will: You know just about everything that's going to happen
and when it's going to happen. But because that's what you want to
happen, it seems counterproductive to complain about it.
</P>
<P>
   Director Randa Haines, whose previous credits include ``Children
of a Lesser God'' and ``Wrestling Ernest Hemingway,'' very
skillfully, very slyly seduces us into liking this wisp of a movie,
mostly by not selling it to us. She's a less-is-more director, and
it pays off in gentle laughs and an unforced warmth that comes from
respect for the culture of music and dance.
</P>
<P>
   She is also careful not to overdirect the dancing sequences.
There are some silky camera moves, but they are silky because they
do not call attention to themselves. She wants to put you not on a
camera boom but on the floor with the dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Matthews wrote the screenplay and shares the choreography
credit with Liz Curtis. OK, so the characters are a bit from stock.
But we like them.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography, though, is an unchallenged delight. Raffa and
Ruby go to a salsa club where movement becomes a pandemic. We
expect the chairs to start dancing. Something like a salsa line
dance breaks out, and eventually everybody is dancing with
everybody. Wall-to-wall charming.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got junior-high-school competitive salsarians who want
to check out the pros' moves, you can trust the PG rating. ``For
mild language and sensuality,'' says the MPAA. I suppose by
sensuality they mean the scene were Raffa and Ruby kiss (just
kiss).
</P>
<P>
   And the mild language is mild. At almost every branching where
the producers had the choice between X and Y, they chose the word
that one usually hears only in the versions prepared for showing on
airplanes. It's all rather sweet.
</P>
<P>
   If there is to be a reward due these producers for sweetness,
may it not be only in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
