<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTOLOGY-COLLECT-ART-     08-21 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTOLOGY-COLLECT-ART-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTOLOGISTS HOPE TO WIN BIG WITH SCRATCH-OFF COLLECTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT photo service) 
(Attn.: La., Fla.) 
(For release Sunday, Aug. 23) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Every time the state of Texas inaugurates a new
scratch-off lottery game, Dr. Alfred Ricks goes out and buys 200 or
300 tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But he's never scratched the paint off one of them to see if
he's won a prize.
</P>
<P>
   Not one.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother tells me that I've probably passed up a
million-dollar winner on one of my tickets,'' said the 48-year-old
physician from West Columbia, a city of 5,100 about 45 miles south
of downtown Houston. ``But I'm still not tempted to scratch it off.
I tell everybody I know that every ticket I buy is a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricks is a lotologist, one of a growing number of people who
collect, study and admire lottery tickets _ not for the prizes they
promise, but for their art and value as collectors' items. Though
most of his tickets have yet to grow beyond their $1 face value,
his mint condition Lone Star Millions, from Texas' first lottery
ticket series, are valued at $225 each. He estimates his
collection's total value at $30,000 to $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   As the games proliferate worldwide, collectors' groups claim
membership in the hundreds. They host conventions where people buy
and swap tickets. And, of course, there are Internet sites devoted
to the hobby (www.lotology.com is one example).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Ricks, lotologist Valerie Castrianni of Houston collects
only lottery tickets that have been scratched off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't go to sleep at night not knowing if there was a big
prize on one of my lottery tickets,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Castrianni, 27, deals in all sorts of collectibles, and admits
that tickets that have been scratched off are valued at a fraction
of the pristine ones. But their throwaway quality is part of the
attraction for her, she said. Unlike valuable sports cards or rare
stamps, most of her lottery tickets are free.
</P>
<P>
   A network of friends collects boxes of discarded tickets for her
from convenience stores and other lottery outlets. Not all of those
tickets are really losers, she has found.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always go through them to check for any winning numbers,''
Castrianni said. ``Sometimes people don't know how to play the game
or just don't notice that they've really won.'' She's won up to $20
on discarded tickets that way.
</P>
<P>
   Castrianni saves the tickets that are in the nicest condition.
She often sends sets of Texas tickets to collectors in other states
to exchange for tickets from their states.
</P>
<P>
   She also specializes in selling the voided sample tickets sent
to dealers to be used for sales displays.
</P>
<P>
   Lotologist Vladimir Parungao, 55, also of Houston, is a forensic
pathologist by day. He has a technique that combines those of Ricks
and Castrianni. He buys at least two of every new kind of Texas
scratch-off lottery ticket. He scratches some to check for winners;
others he saves in mint condition.
</P>
<P>
   Parungao's collection got started in 1992 when his son gave him
some tickets and a collector's album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the artwork on them,'' he said. He also enjoys the
challenge of collecting some of the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not like collecting postage stamps, which are on sale
at post offices everywhere in the country,'' he said. ``Some of
these are issued in small states just for a very short time.'' In
Pennsylvania, he recalled, certain lottery tickets have been issued
only in a few select towns and cities.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting things is a relaxing hobby that he has enjoyed since
his childhood in the Philippines, Parungao said. His first
collection, which he still treasures, was of different kinds of
cigarette papers. Then he collected Johnny Mathis records _
hundreds of them _ enough to listen to for two days without
repeating one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play golf and my kids are grown,'' he said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Ricks, Castrianni and Parungao each boast complete sets, or
samples from each of the 130 or so different ticket series issued
in Texas. They have their favorites from other states as well.
</P>
<P>
   Castrianni said she likes many of Louisiana's colorful tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mardi Gras tickets are really colorful,'' she said. ``And
the wording on many of their tickets are really funny _ wonderful
puns.'' At Christmas they often feature a Cajun Santa bellowing,
``Heaux, heaux, heaux'' instead of ``Ho, ho ho.'' One ticket
featured a picture of a New Orleans streetcar with the title,
``Streetcar named Retire.'' A fine arts series included a
``Pica$o'' and a ``Money Lisa.''
</P>
<P>
   Castrianni said she was amazed to find that so many other people
around the country are also collecting lottery tickets. One
national organization claims about 700 members, another about 150.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the millions that collect stamps or coins, lotology
``hasn't even scratched the surface yet,'' said collector Glen
Faulhaber of Clearwater, Fla., using a favorite lotology pun.
</P>
<P>
   Lotteries have long been used to raise money in the United
States, he said. Many of the country's earliest governmental
projects were funded by lotteries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The modern scratch-off lottery began in 1975-76 in states like
Michigan and Illinois, he said. Today, 32 states and the District
of Columbia issue tickets. One state, Alaska, issued tickets for a
couple of years and then stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Although his collection of 40,000 to 50,000 tickets features
8,000 different types, not even Faulhaber claims to have an example
of every kind of scratch-off ticket issued in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just been too many,'' he said. Although most tickets
originally retail for $1, some states have issued tickets costing
up to $25, making it hard for collectors to buy very many, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most collectors concentrate on collections of tickets issued by
their own state, as well as collections of tickets that have a
theme. Faulhaber said he is especially fond of a set of 20
different tickets issued by Maine that had antique autos. Alaska
issued sets that featured that state's birds and different kinds of
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a ticket theme is used by more than one state. Seven
states have issued tickets with ``Star Trek'' themes and five have
issued sets featuring Harley-Davidson motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   Texas sells more than $2 billion in scratch-off lottery tickets
a year, said Texas Lottery Commission spokeswoman Gail Phillips. On
average, she said, two new series are introduced every month.
</P>
<P>
   Ideas for lottery tickets come from many sources, she said. The
San Antonio company that prints them suggests some themes; others
are based on tickets issued by other states. Texas has had contests
seeking designs submitted by private individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The individual games are usually kept open for about a year or
so before being retired and declared closed, Phillips said. After
that, no more prizes are given out for that ticket. Although many
minor prizes are never cashed in, Phillips said few big-ticket
prizes have ever gone unclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Phillips said, collectors have been such a minority of
the millions who buy Texas tickets that the commission hasn't
really thought about them.
</P>
<P>
   Ricks said that when he started selling his collectible tickets
over the Internet, he got a call from the state lottery commission
warning him that it is illegal to sell lottery tickets unless he's
a licensed lottery dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell your lawyers to go to hell,'' he said he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said the commission has since decided that it is not
illegal for collectors to sell tickets from games that have been
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Ricks offers a special deal for people who want to start their
Texas lotology collection in a big way _ a complete set of mint
examples of all 130 Texas tickets for $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he hasn't sold a set, but Ricks said he has 100 such
sets squirreled away in safe-deposit boxes.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that some day those unscratched tickets will be big
winners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
