<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO NEEDS `WAG THE DOG' WHEN THERE'S CLINTON LIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The guy will do anything to get out of the
house. That's the kind of cheap shot everyone was taking, along
with ``Wag the Dog'' comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   I saw the movie, and what the world saw Thursday wasn't a
sequel.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton sent a ``message'' to terrorists and to us.
</P>
<P>
   These million-dollar bomb-o-grams look great in the old Pentagon
films we saw Thursday on CNN, and thus the American people got a
message of national and presidential strength.
</P>
<P>
   However, launching a cruise missile at a terrorist training camp
is like shooting a .45 at a swarm of bees. You may kill a few bees,
but the rest are going to get mad. Terrorists are not good at
learning from messages, and tend to respond with car bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Keep telling yourself, ``This isn't a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the beginning of the Vietnam War, American presidents
have been ``sending messages.'' Lyndon Johnson and Robert MacNamara
conceived of escalated bombing as a series of messages to bring the
North Vietnamese to their knees.
</P>
<P>
   However, the North Vietnamese thought of bombs as bombs, not as
telegrams, so escalation progressively hardened their resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Since Vietnam, the rules of engagement have become even more
disengaged. Not only do we send messages to enemies, we must follow
the first rule of American intervention: No American should die or
be captured.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the cruise missile is the perfect weapon from a political
point of view. Even if the missile recipients don't get the
intended message, the American people do. They are led to believe
that the president is fighting international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in this case, Ken Starr suffers collateral damage.
Monica Lewinsky disappears from the front page.
</P>
<P>
   I don't believe the real targets of those missiles were the
polls and Ken Starr's office. There is a real world, after all, and
it's a dangerous place, as recent events in Kenya and Tanzania
demonstrate. There is a man named Osama bin Laden who has declared
war on the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That's him in those photographs, not an actor in fake beard and
camouflage fatigues. He may seem like a villain out of a Tom Clancy
novel, but even Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, assures us he's real,
noting that he first brought bin Laden to the attention of the
government in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Besides congratulating himself, Hatch congratulated the
president on his military action, while sounding a lot like a
candidate to replace Clinton as commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans would like to see terrorists in the cross-hairs
of a cruise missile's video camera for the second or two before
they're vaporized.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, we're more likely to see the aftermath of bombs
delivered by old-fashioned motor vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean we shouldn't fight terrorists. It means we
shouldn't fool ourselves into thinking we can stop them with our
technology. Least of all, the president shouldn't fool himself.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may be a slippery politician and an admitted liar, but
he's too smart to try to distract the people with a cooked-up war
the very month that ``Wag the Dog'' hit the video stores.
</P>
<P>
   I rented the movie, and it has a lot of laughs and fine
performances by Dustin Hoffman and Robert De Niro. However, it's
inferior to the production we watched on CNN and MSNBC on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, ``Wag the Dog'' is a broad comedy, but how can anyone
believe that dozens of technicians can film a fake war without a
single leak to the press? How can anyone believe Americans have a
long enough attention span to let Albanian terrorists distract them
from a presidential sex scandal for 11 days?
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-CNN-MSNBC team are masters compared to the makers of
``Wag the Dog.'' The cruise missile war was over in 45 minutes.
Military leaders and talking heads wrapped it up beautifully
between shots of the president's jet taking off from Martha's
Vineyard and landing at Andrews Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   While the jet was taxiing, MSNBC's Brian Williams smoothly
described how its fuselage is polished daily with household spray
cleaner and paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   This was drama well above the level of ``Wag the Dog,'' almost
at the level of ``Dr. Strangelove'' _ without the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the afternoon, the news channels were back to
Monica, talking about ``unusual sexual practices.'' You know the
world has changed when military interventions last 45 minutes, and
sex lasts seven months.
</P>
<P>
   No, Clinton wasn't trying to distract us from his scandal. He
would have made the intervention last a lot longer, and stayed out
of that summer house for as long as possible. This is the real
world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
