<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of Mon., Aug. 24 and
anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FARMERS TAKE AIM AT TROUBLESOME INSECTS &LR;  _ Farmers may soon be
firing containers full of wasps around their fields to help control
the pests that devastate their crops. The U.S. Department of
Agriculture, in Shafter, Calif., is developing two devices which
will be faster, cheaper alternatives to spreading the insects by
hand. By Jonathan Beard. 400 words. (slugged:
BC-FARMERS-VS.-INSECTS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SALE: SOUVENIRS OF A CLOSE ENCOUNTER &LR;  _ Pieces of the radio
dish which shot to fame in 1977 for picking up the most tantalizing
evidence to date of extraterrestrial intelligence are up for sale.
Small pieces of the Big Ear dish were rescued before it was
demolished to make way for a golf course. By Marcus Chown. 300
words. (slugged:
BC-SOUVENIRS-OF-A-CLOSE-ENCOUNTER-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FERTILITY INDEX &LR;  _ The symmetry of your two hands and the
length of your fingers could be a predictor of reproductive
ability. Researchers at the University of Liverpool in England
measured the hands of men and women attending a fertility clinic
and found a link between hand shape and fertility. By Alison
Motluk. 400 words. (slugged:
BC-FERTILITY-INDEX-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
