<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL WAYS TO GET UP TO SPEED ON JUST HOW FAST YOUR COMPUTER IS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How can you find out how fast your computer is running?
What's the megahertz? I've lost everything that might have the
original specifications on it.
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several ways to do this.
</P>
<P>
   You might find the information you want in the system's BIOS
settings. How you enter the BIOS depends on the kind of computer
you have, but usually it involves hitting a specific key just
before your PC starts loading the operating system. For example, on
systems that use an American Megatrends BIOS, you'd hit the delete
key.
</P>
<P>
   On newer systems, you'll see the speed of the processor as one
of the settings.
</P>
<P>
   (Be very careful when entering this setup feature. If you make
any changes that don't match your computer's configuration, you
might run into serious trouble _ including rendering your PC
inoperable.)
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, you might be able to tell the speed by the model
number. For example, Gateway numbers its PCs in a way that includes
the clock speed of the main chip. A G6-400 is a Pentium II
processor running at 400 megahertz. Check the Web site of your PC's
manufacturer for clues.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, try downloading SiSoft Sandra, an excellent shareware
utility that tells you all kinds of information about your PC,
including the processor's speed. Get it at
www.sisoftware.demon.co.uk/sandra/.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently visited a Web site that had colored text on a
colored background. Unfortunately, the text's color was white, so
when I went to print it out, the paper was blank! What can I do to
get a hard copy of the text?
</P>
<P>
   A: By default, neither Netscape Navigator nor Internet Explorer
will print the background of a Web page.
</P>
<P>
   If you are using Netscape Navigator, you can tell the browser to
use only the colors you specify to view a Web page. This way, you
can choose the standard black type on white background, which will
make your printer happy.
</P>
<P>
   In Navigator 4.05, which comes with the latest version of
Communicator, click on Edit, then Preferences, then Appearance. Go
to the Colors menu and click the box titled ``Always use my colors,
overriding document.'' Remember to change it back when you are
done.
</P>
<P>
   In Microsoft Internet Explorer 4.01, you can print the exact
colors on the Web page. Though this will use up lots of ink, it
will print the page exactly as you see it, including the
background. Click on View, Internet Options, then the Advanced tab.
Scroll to the bottom of the list of choices and click ``Print
background colors and images.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the simplest thing to do may be to copy the text and
paste it into your word processor, then print from there. Drag your
cursor through the text you want to print, which will highlight it.
Then, right-click and choose copy. Launch your word processor and
paste into a blank document. Start printing!
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have Internet Explorer 4.01, and I'm interested in sending
secure e-mail. How do I do that?
</P>
<P>
   A: You'll need to get a digital ID, a way to electronically
``sign'' and encrypt messages you send.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also need to make sure that your recipients have a copy
of your digital ID, so they can read the messages you send.
</P>
<P>
   In Outlook Express, which is the e-mail software accompanying
Internet Explorer 4.01, go to the Tools menu and choose Accounts.
Click on your e-mail account, then click the Properties button.
Choose the Security tab.
</P>
<P>
   From here, you can sign up for a digital ID. A button called
More Info will tell you more about the process of acquiring and
using a digital ID.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
