<HEADLINE>
HBO BUNGLES STORY OF SINATRA &AMP; CO. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ring-a-ding-ding, baby _ call up all your hepcat
pals and tell them to skip ``The Rat Pack,'' HBO's new movie airing
Saturday night (see local listings).
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe anyone can screw up a film with such lively
subject matter as the complex relationships between Frank Sinatra,
his entertainer pals, John F. Kennedy and a host of mobsters. But
``Rat Pack'' is relentlessly bad, so bad, that you start reading
the press material early on, wondering if you missed the part that
says this is supposed to be a comedy. As a comedy, it's great _ the
portrayals are so over-the-top they just have to be intentional,
except that they aren't.
</P>
<P>
   There's enough blame to go around, but why not nail Kario Salem
first? The screenwriter, who turned in a fine effort with previous
HBO work, ``Don King: Only in America,'' is so heavy-handed with
the dialogue that there is zero room for nuance in the acting
realm. Everyone, by virtue of the lines they are forced to say,
becomes an instant caricature. Reading that Salem's next script
will be for an Oliver Stone movie on Martin Luther King sheds some
light _ Oliver Stone is a sledge hammer director, so maybe Salem
was just getting warmed up for Ollie.
</P>
<P>
   The story, such as it is, focuses on the late '50s and early
'60s when Sinatra and his Rat Pack buddies _ Dean Martin, Sammy
Davis Jr., Peter Lawford and Joey Bishop _ ruled the Hollywood
roost. Being a skirt-chasing booze hound is back in fashion, so the
timing of the movie was perfect. These days, people like to smoke
and drink and chase broads and get crazy. Actually, people have
always been like that, only now it's cool again.
</P>
<P>
   So Frank, played by Ray Liotta, sets the pace, with Martin (Joe
Mantegna), close behind. The others _ Davis (Don Cheadle), Lawford
(Angus Macfadyen) and Bishop (Bobby Slayton) _ are essentially
hangers-on, although Davis at least had some talent. The casting is
debatable at best, and with Mantegna as Martin, downright horrible.
Mantegna looks like Dino's father _ which is unforgivable since
Dino was the absolute King of Cool of his time. Frank tried most of
his life to be as cool as Dean _ Dean just was cool.
</P>
<P>
   On a positive note, casting Slayton as Bishop is perfect, since
it takes one mediocre comedian to truly understand the inner
mediocrity of another. And it's tough to tell if Cheadle is playing
Davis for laughs, since Davis was always just downright bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   The plot, which is pretty much historically accurate, revolves
around Sinatra's fascination with the Kennedy mystique and the
power of the office of the presidency and JFK's equal intrigue in
the world of Hollywood. Through Lawford, Kennedy's brother-in-law,
introductions are made and wheels are set in motion that ultimately
involve alleged Mafia assistance in rigging elections in Kennedy's
favor, Kennedy's subsequent ``betrayal'' of the mob through his
appointment of his crusading brother Bobby as attorney general, and
all the hell Sinatra has to go through when he is ultimately
rejected by both the mob and the Kennedys, those ingrates.
</P>
<P>
   It's great material for a movie, just not this movie. The
language is crude and vulgar, which isn't so bad, but even
Kennedy's assignations with Marilyn Monroe and Mafia moll Judith
Campbell were probably arranged with a tad more grace than imagined
here. One hopes, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rat Pack'' is great for all it's period authenticities,
from the clothing to the cars to the unfiltered Camels
Sinatra/Liotta shamelessly inhales. The singing is handled largely
by studio pros, although Cheadle and Mantegna croon a bit, badly.
If you want a few laughs, go ahead and tune in.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a little Rat Pack reality, give it a miss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
