<HEADLINE>
VOODOO2 CHIP CASTS GOOD SPELL ON GAMES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Diamond Multimedia first introduced its Monster 3D video
card in late 1996, it didn't immediately catch on. Most users
couldn't see why they'd need a second graphics card in their
computer _ certainly not for $200!
</P>
<P>
   That changed by late last year, when it was nearly impossible to
find a Monster 3D card on store shelves. What began as a curiosity
among hard-core gamers grew to become a must-have addition for
anyone who regularly plays PC games.
</P>
<P>
   The Monster's magic comes from a set of chips made by 3Dfx
Interactive called Voodoo. Not only does the Voodoo chip set
dramatically accelerate 3-D game play, but it also can enhance the
appearance of a game. With the Voodoo, 3-D really looks ... well,
like 3-D.
</P>
<P>
   When 3Dfx announced it would create a second generation of the
chip, the Voodoo2, other graphics card companies decided they
wanted to cash in. Today, more than a dozen vendors are selling
Voodoo2 cards _ including Diamond. I reviewed the Monster 3D II
earlier this year (see
www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/98/03/27/compute.html).
</P>
<P>
   There also are more reasons to get one of these cards than ever
before. Game software developers increasingly are including support
for the 3Dfx chips in their titles. Whether you're into
first-person shooters and action games or prefer more placid
pursuits, such as flight simulators and adventure titles, a card
that uses a Voodoo2 chip set can make computer gaming a more
realistic experience.
</P>
<P>
   All Voodoo2 boards use a pass-through connector, a cable that
links your regular, 2-D graphics card to the Voodoo2. You then plug
your monitor into the Voodoo2, and the signal from the 2-D card is
supposed to pass cleanly through to the monitor.
</P>
<P>
   One caveat _ you'll need a fairly powerful machine to enjoy a
Voodoo2-based card. I'd recommend at least a 166-megahertz Pentium
system with 32 megabytes of memory. If your system is less powerful
than this, you might want to consider an original Voodoo-based
card, which can be found dirt-cheap. I've seen the original Monster
3D advertised for as little as $50, after a rebate.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at a pair of Voodoo2-based graphics cards that
plug into a Windows-based system's PCI slot. One's aimed at the
hard-core game market; the other at everyone else who wants killer
graphics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pure 3D II, $289, Canopus Corp.: Most of the Voodoo2-based
graphics cards use a similar design recommended by 3Dfx's
engineers. Canopus, which marketed a popular original Voodoo card
called the Pure 3D, has opted to tinker with that design to add
features and performance.
</P>
<P>
   But those benefits may not be enough for the average game-player
to justify the price, which is more than what you'd pay for most
other Voodoo2 boards.
</P>
<P>
   The Pure 3D II comes with 12 megabytes of video memory, as do
many of the other Voodoo2 cards. But that's about where the
similarities end.
</P>
<P>
   The Pure 3D II has a connection for a standard TV, allowing you
to connect your PC to a big-screen television for a truly immersive
experience. The image is not going to be as good as on a
high-definition computer monitor, but it is as good as, or even a
little better than, what you'd find on a game console.
</P>
<P>
   The board also comes with a built-in fan. Voodoo2 chips are
notorious for running hot. And hard-core gamers are notorious for
overclocking their systems and graphics cards _ meaning they fiddle
with settings so they run at faster-than-rated speeds. The Pure 3D
II's internal clock can be pushed up to 100 megahertz via a control
panel.
</P>
<P>
   The Pure 3D II uses a slightly different kind of cable to
connect to your standard video card, and the result is that, with
some 2-D cards, text in Windows applications appears to have a
slight shadow. This irritated me at first, but I don't even notice
it any more. Nevertheless, it's a defect not seen in other Voodoo2
cards that I wish Canopus would fix.
</P>
<P>
   The Pure 3D II comes with software that lets you change
brightness levels in games with a single keystroke, and a
taskbar-style launcher to give you quick access to your favorite
games.
</P>
<P>
   It comes bundled with only one game, but it's a nice one _ the
Quake II Mission Pack: The Reckoning from Activision. You'll need a
registered version of Quake II to play it, however.
</P>
<P>
   _ 3D Blaster Voodoo2, $250, Creative Labs: Creative Labs was the
first out of the gate with a Voodoo2 card, and it was a 12-megabyte
version at that. While the company now has an 8-megabyte version
for about $50 less, this is the one to get if you don't need all
the features in the Canopus card.
</P>
<P>
   The Blaster is about as plain-vanilla a Voodoo2 card as you can
get. In fact, it lacks some software features found in most
competing boards. For example, there's no easy way to goose the
Blaster's clock speed _ although there are shareware programs
available on the Web that will do this for you.
</P>
<P>
   The Blaster uses the more traditional pass-through cable, and
the result is a crisp, clean look for your regular Windows
programs. However, there's no TV-out connection, so you're stuck
with playing on a regular computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The 3D Blaster Voodoo2 comes with three games: Microprose's
Ultim(at)te Race Pro, Rage Software's Incoming and Psygnosis'
G-Police.
</P>
<P>
   How do these two cards compare in performance? I ran both on a
200-megahertz Pentium MMX system with 64 megabytes of RAM with a
variety of games. The Canopus card was slightly faster, but not by
much. I'd say most gamers probably could not tell the difference.
That makes the Creative Labs card a better buy if you can live
without the Canopus card's bells and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
