<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR PERSONAL AQ MAY DETERMINE WHETHER YOU PREVAIL OR FAIL IN A
CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing like a crisis to winnow the winners from the
whiners.
</P>
<P>
   Some people hit with a setback become paralyzed and give in to
helplessness, while others seize the situation and turn it into an
opportunity for success.
</P>
<P>
   Why do some people prevail where others despair? The difference
lies in their ``adversity quotients,'' said Paul Stoltz, chief
executive officer of Peak Learning Inc., an Arizona-based training
and consulting firm that specializes in adversity training for
companies.
</P>
<P>
   An adversity quotient is a measure of how well someone handles
bad news, said Stoltz, who coined the term and has written the book
``Adversity Quotient _ Turning Obstacles Into Opportunities''
(Wiley, $24.95, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   The good news is you can change your pattern of reactions to
adversity _ up your AQ, as it were.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes more than positive thinking to get people through a
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not always the people with the most positive, upbeat
outlook who do the best,'' Stoltz said. ``Sometimes it's the people
you would not have guessed who turn out to have the quiet spine of
steel.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoltz is not a big believer in what he calls ``happy-think
training,'' despite the fact that motivational pep talks have
turned into a $60 billion-a-year industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's reached cultish proportions because adversity is so
pronounced and people feel so much more exposed, in their jobs and
elsewhere,'' he said. ``They're looking for solace.''
</P>
<P>
   But the motivational industry is like the coffee business, he
said. It's selling a product that makes people feel good for a
while, but then it wears off and they need another shot.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who knows how to rebound, no matter how difficult the
circumstances, is more likely to be able to sustain a positive
attitude, he said. That's good for people, and it's good for
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of response to life's hurdles is typically ingrained
early on, Stoltz said. If a child has a parent who panics, acts out
in anger, shirks responsibility or assumes helplessness, that child
often grows up to respond to adversity in a similar fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But those patterns can change, he said. ``They can rewire their
brains.''
</P>
<P>
   There are four components to handling adversity well.
</P>
<P>
   The first is control. People who deal well with adversity are
able to gain some sense of control, even in situations that appear
overwhelming, he said. People who do less well perceive that
matters are completely out of their hands.
</P>
<P>
   A second component is ``ownership'' of the problem. People who
hold themselves accountable for dealing with situations, even if
they didn't cause them, tend to do better in adversity than do
people who assume helplessness.
</P>
<P>
   A third component is ``reach,'' or how far a person lets fallout
from the adverse situation spill into other areas of his life.
People who don't do well in negative situations tend to
``catastrophize'' the problem, magnifying it and letting it gain
control over their lives, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, there's endurance. People with high adversity quotients
can maintain their hope and optimism by seeing past even the most
seemingly insurmountable difficulties, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Public Schools Superintendent John Stanford, who is
battling an aggressive and rare form of cancer, is a textbook
example of someone with a high adversity quotient. He would score
well in all four categories _ taking some control of his situation,
owning it by making his own decisions, refusing to let it leak into
other areas of his life, and remaining hopeful by being able to
envision a positive future.
</P>
<P>
   There are several steps people can take to move their adversity
quotients from the low end to the high end, Stoltz said.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to examine how you respond to a crisis, he
said. Then ask yourself what is realistically about to happen, and
what piece of it you can be accountable for dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   Next, don't give into suppositions and worst-case scenarios.
Instead, take a ``funnel approach'' for figuring out what to do.
Make a list of all possible moves you could make, and then commit
to at least one constructive step you can take immediately, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That automatically strengthens your sense of control,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, this process of listening, analyzing and taking
action becomes automatic in a crisis situation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adversity is an unfortunate fact of
</P>
<P>
   life. Few people escape it in one form or another.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't be afraid of bad times, Stoltz said. ``Without
adversity, what would we ever learn about ourselves and each
other?''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Smith is a reporter and columnist for the P-I Her e-mail
address is carolsmith(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
