A5961 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLL-HNS &LR;      08-21 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN POLL, PEOPLE SAY CLINTON DIDN'T REDEEM HIMSELF IN SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Responses to a San Francisco Examiner survey of
President Clinton's public apology this week showed a clear
majority, nearly 55 percent, said he had not redeemed himself with
his speech.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the day after Clinton appeared on national TV and
admitted to an inappropriate relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky, the Examiner asked readers to respond to
the following question: ``Did President Clinton redeem himself with
his speech to the nation about his role in the Monica Lewinsky
scandal?''
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 people responded in the informal, three-day
telephone survey. The majority of the votes had been cast before
the U.W. attack Thursday on terrorist sites in Afghanistan and
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Several letters, faxes and e-mails forwarded to the Examiner
expressed outrage and called for Clinton's immediate resignation.
Others ranged in their emotional intensity from despair to
compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Many called for Clinton's resignation, but more than one
suggested that ``he who is without sin cast the first stone.'' And
many pleaded for an end to the national obsession with Clinton's
intimate indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   Of 6,031 responses, 3,314 said that no, Clinton had not redeemed
himself, and 2,717 said yes he had.
</P>
<P>
   No votes tallied Tuesday and Wednesday outnumbered yes votes by
a margin of about 900, but on Thursday the gap had closed
considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what some readers had to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Clinton) tries to continue in office, he will make a
laughing stock out of the presidency of the United States of
America, because he will go down in contemporary world history as
the only leader who has tried to continue in office after having
openly violated the 11th commandment (getting caught.)'' _ John
Buencamino.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the eyes are windows to the soul, Mr. Clinton's eyes were
blank Monday evening as he tried to persuade us the fault was (with
independent counsel) Judge (Kenneth) Starr. A simple, heartfelt
apology would have done the job _ but he could not pull it off with
his superior attitude and cockiness.'' _ A.R. Gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only honorable thing Bill Clinton could do to save his
reputation for history/herstory is to gallantly resign from the
presidency. His speech was a finger-shake at everyone but himself.
... Bill Clinton has lost most of his credibility since he first
took office, but now his credibility is non-existent.'' Anita
Kristi, a self-described liberal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any of my children apologized the way President Clinton did
... I would send him back to his room.''_ Christina Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not care to see the personal life of my
commander-in-chief exposed daily. However, his poor judgment is the
cause. Any Marine who displayed the lack of judgment, compassion
and integrity that our president has displayed, would not be a
Marine for long.'' _ Sean P. Dalton, a former Marine first
lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say this is a personal matter ... but if they stop to
think how stupid his behavior has been, how can they trust him to
make smart decisions. He has shown such poor judgment in his
personal behavior. For a so-called Rhodes scholar, he sure appears
to lack a cognitive brain.'' _ Eugenia Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish ... he had told the truth in January when this whole
messy business came out, but I also wish ... the whole right-wing
would stop (its) hypocritical yammering and allow him to get back
to the real reason he was voted into office in 1992.'' _ Cynthia
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding is that nearly all, if not all, American
presidents have indulged in extra-marital affairs. But since in
prior times no one would think of questioning (their) private life
_ they didn't need to `lie.''' _ Bill Gompert.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he made a mistake, so what? So far nobody is perfect in the
world. I just hope Ken Starr is a saint.'' _ John Willkom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly more dangerous to keep an untrustworthy
president in office than to remove him. The nation will go on. In
spite of what Clinton die-hards and the hyperactive press would
have you believe, impeachment is no big deal in a government
designed as wisely as ours is. Presidents come and go every four to
eight years anyway.'' _ Charles E. Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has apologized and has been humiliated in every sense
of the word. Why drag his corpse around any further? He is at our
mercy. Just let him do his job and rebuild his shattered
marriage.'' _ Jean Pesce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
