<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5967 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DANCE-REVIEW-HNS     08-21 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DANCE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIT DOWN AND `DANCE WITH ME'  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like ``Ballroom Dancing,'' ``Flashdance,'' ``Dirty Dancing'' and
``Saturday Night Fever,'' ``Dance with Me'' is a feel-good movie
with great music, two beautiful lead actors and a good deal of
joyous choreography and booty-shaking.
</P>
<P>
   But also as in the other movies, the plot is shakier than the
dancing. ``Dance with Me'' is about a young Cuban named Rafael
Infante (Chayanne) who goes to Texas to find a dance studio
operator named John Burnett (Kris Kristofferson). John gives Rafael
a job as a janitor, unaware that he is Rafael's father. That little
tension buzzes through the movie as writer Daryl Matthews (a former
professional dancer and choreographer) defers Rafael's spilling the
beans for, I suppose, dramatic purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Rafael holds back some other vital information
you'd think he might want to reveal the moment he walked into the
studio: that he can dance better than Charo.
</P>
<P>
   You'd especially think he'd want this information out there
since he is immediately smitten with Ruby (Vanessa L. Williams), an
instructor who used to compete in Latin ballroom dancing
competitions but quit when she broke up with her egomaniacal
partner, who is also the father of her young son. Whew.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, once Rafael and Ruby start dancing together, both the
screen and their passions heat up. It would be tough to find two
more attractive people than Williams and Chayanne and director
Randa Haines makes us long for the pair to commingle, which they
obligingly do after the requisite hesitations.
</P>
<P>
   Kristofferson looks like he's never danced a step in his life,
but it doesn't much matter and Joan Plowright as a plucky dance
student adds a little comic whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   Chayanne, who is a Puerto Rican singing idol and television
star, is especially fun to watch because unlike the other dancers
in this movie, he moves with a grace and fluidity that seem
organic. While Ruby's professional partner, Julian (Rick
Valenzuela), dances spasmodically as if he means to throw his limbs
out of their sockets, Chayanne's body is easy and loose when he
moves to the Latin rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography by Liz Curtis is exhilarating and not only as
spirited as you'd expect Latin movements to be, but also full of
humor and happiness. Just what you want for a couple of hours of
mindless fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
