<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5978 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV2     08-21 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV23-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVER SCORCHED COUNTER TOP WITH CONTACT PAPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 23, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My Formica counter top was badly scorched when a hot pan was
put on it. How can I cover it, fix it, or restore it? Can I cover
it with Contact paper?
</P>
<P>
   AGNES MIRISOLA, Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If it's a light scorch, you might be able to clean it with
baking soda and water, or light scouring with a scouring compound.
If it's a heavy scorch, the plastic is gone forever. But you can
cover it; your idea of using Contact paper is a good one. The paper
won't last very long, but it will be good enough until you replace
the plastic. The nice thing about the new Contact (new in the last
10 years or so) is that it is easily pulled off when the time
comes. The old Contact was impossible to remove.
</P>
<P>
   Another temporary fix is to put a cutting board over the scorch.
No one will know but the cook and the dishwasher.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The roll roofing on my bump-out roof has degraded, with one
or two small holes, but they are not leaking. Can I put on a second
layer?
</P>
<P>
   J.B., Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, and I suggest doing it before it springs a leak. Cut new
roll roofing to the size of the roof, lift the flashing where the
roof meets the wall, and tuck the roofing under the flashing and
line it up with the old, to check the proper fit. Then take off the
new and slather roofing cement on the old roof, along the edges and
in the middle. Put the new roof on; with luck, it will last 15 or
more years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. There is a cleanout plug in the four-inch iron pipe in my
basement that leads to the septic tank. It's a hexagonal plug
screwed into a brass fitting. I mashed the plug trying to take it
off. Any way to take it out now so I can clean out the drain?
</P>
<P>
   VICTOR BANEVICIUS, Westborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There might be, doing it as mechanics do to back out a bolt
that has lost its head or has a messed up screw slot. Spray some
pentrating oil into the threads of the plug. Place a sharp cold
chisel on one side of the plug and tap lightly, counterclockwise.
Chances are the plug moves counterclockwise and tapping might get
it started. The chisel will dig into the soft brass and will stay
in place, usually, when you tap. If no go, you may have to drill it
out, but make sure you can find, or have a substitute the right
size. Does the drain really need cleaning? I suppose it may if the
flow is sluggish, but I'd also have the tank pumped out, which may
allow the drain to clear itself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a sump hole in my basement that acts as a drain for
the condensing water from my air conditioning system. It is 3
inches wide and 18 inches deep, and in heavy rains the hole fills
and water backs up to flood the floor. How can I prevent that?
</P>
<P>
   JUDY AND DAVID SCHURGIN, Malden, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The flooding is caused by the level of water underground
(ground water or water table, take your pick for a name), which
rose during heavy rains, filled the hole from below, and flooded
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, I think, is that the sump hole (that's a
redundancy; a sump is a hole) is way too small for the amount of
water it gets. Make the sump bigger: 18 inches square and 24 inches
deep. Add crushed stone to a depth of 6 inches. This bigger hole
may handle the ground water plus the condensate from the A/C. If
not, install a pump, which will pump the water automatically away
from the house before it floods the floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My garage roof is a flat concrete slab, 70 years old, and it
has been leaking badly and damaging the cars under. A contractor
sealed the holes, then applied a clear sealer. It did not help.
Another man put in two inches of concrete which also did not work.
Still another man took off the concrete and sealed the roof, also
without success. Now what can I do?
</P>
<P>
   LEE BURNS, Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. After spending a small fortune for all thsoe unsuccessful
patches, consider moving the cars out for a while until the roof is
fixed, once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   And this might be the once-and-for-all fix: If the roof is
relatively intact, I suggest hiring a roofer to put on a rubber
roof. But be warned that you cannot walk on this rubber roof, even
if it is on concrete. In fact, I know of no roof that can be walked
on (with added stress of furniture, etc.) that is waterproof. If
you want to use the roof as a patio, you have to build a deck above
it; a few inches above it will do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The set-tubs in my basement have small leaks, at the bottom
of the sinks where they drain out. How can I fix them myself?
</P>
<P>
   ELLIE CRONIN, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Since the leaks are at the drains, dismantle the drains and
drain covers and install plumber's putty in the openings before
putting them back. And don't put them back too tightly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
