</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BLADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVENTUALLY, `BLADE' LOSES ITS EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
BLADE 
Directed by: Stephen Norrington 
Screenplay by: David S. Goyer 
Starring: Wesley Snipes, Stephen Dorff, Kris Kristofferson, N'Bushe
Wright, Donal Logue, Udo Kier, Traci Lords, Arly Jover 
Running time: 120 minutes 
Rated: R (strong, pervasive vampire violence and gore, language and
brief sexuality) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those vampires! They never say die, except to the likes of us,
so you can see why Wesley Snipes couldn't say no to the idea of
climbing into black neoprene armor, loading up on heavy-duty
weaponry, and blasting away in _ and as _ ``Blade.'' The gimmick is
that he's as strong as the vampires because there's a bit of
vampire in him, untimely ripped from his mother's womb after a
vampire tore her throat open. But the vampire Macduff is mostly
human, despite a need to ingest the odd vial of blood when thirsty.
And he's bent on revenge.
</P>
<P>
   In the film's dark gothic world, inherited from the comic book
on which it's based, the powerful vampires have organized and are
on the verge of taking over the earth after buying time by bribing
human power brokers. But why, the ringleader asks, go on making
deals with your food? Played by Stephen Dorff in black duds and a
pond scum look, he suggests Kiefer Sutherland's rancid kid brother,
a downtown entrepreneur in whose after-hours club the sprinkler
systems rain blood as the vampires sprout fangs and perforate their
victims to a techno beat.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Snipes as Blade, blasting and slicing and dicing away,
alone except for Kris Kristofferson's grizzled weapons-maker and
N'Bushe Wright's hematologist, who does her best between action
scenes to do something about Blade's blood problem. It's lively
enough as Snipes easily establishes himself as the American action
hero who comes closest to the incredible acrobatics of the Hong
Kong breed of supermen. There isn't an art that he isn't prepared
to be martial about as he wades into the vampire nation, swinging
away.
</P>
<P>
   But the more strenuous and elaborate the effects become, the
less scary and kicky the film becomes until we're unable to escape
the glum truth that what we're watching has turned into high-energy
claptrap. In fact, ``Blade'' stops seeming a film, and suggests
instead a large-screen video game, no longer remotely linked to any
pretense of being connected to something human. The ending more
than hints at a sequel, but long before it does, ``Blade'' does
what most sequels do as Snipes turns into his own action figure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5983 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-     08-21 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRINK UP, KNUCKLEHEAD! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long after Gillette Co. debuted its Mach3 three-bladed
razor, another Boston product was launched in late July with much
less marketing fanfare _ Three Stooges Beer.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, plans called for the beer launch to be supported by
an advertising campaign from Boston ad agency Holland Mark Martin
Edmund, but now ads may not run before October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see how well the beer does by word of mouth,'' said
Dewey Parsons, who, along with Mike Herbert, cofounded Panther
Brewing Co. of Westwood to market Three Stooges Beer.
</P>
<P>
   Ads will run ``when the beer starts to wane a tad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For boys who grew up with Larry, Moe, and Curly, the idea of
buying a six-pack of Three Stooges Beer is almost irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   For aesthetic reasons and display purposes alone, every fan is
sure to covet a Stooge longneck beer bottle. And who wouldn't want
to swagger into some saloon with two sidekicks and demand the
tattooed publican, ``Three Stooges, chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, plans are in the works for tap handles that would
emit such signature Stooge noises as ``Nyuk, nyuk, and nyuk'' and
``Woo, woo, woo,'' when a Stooge draft is poured.
</P>
<P>
   All this is very nice _ and a major news flash for the Stooge
aficionado _ but when it comes to the beer, will anyone actually
want to drink more than one?
</P>
<P>
   According to the brewing industry, the biggest consumers of beer
are men in their 20s. At first glance, it would seem that this key
demographic is far too young to have many fond memories of the
Stooges, a comedy team that tossed its first custard pie in 1923
and whose later film work, with its witty eyepokes and slapstick
repartee, perfectly captured a 10-year-old's beau ideal of what
male adulthood ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, 43, acknowledges that market research is not the forte
of Panther Brewing. (The company's name is inspired by a Stooge
episode that may represent a defining moment in the trio's comic
oeuvre.)
</P>
<P>
   What market research the first-time brewers did convinced them
that Stooges beer would be pretty much ``a guy thing,'' Parsons
said. ``Only 6 percent of women like the Stooges. The rest of them
think men who watch the Stooges are complete idiots.'' He paused.
``My wife is in that 94 percentile.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Herbert believed there was a strong overlap between beer
lovers and Stooge fans. And for years, he secretly harbored his
dream of a Stooges beer before broaching it to his pal.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons was reluctant at first. A food broker, he was thinking
of getting out that business and buying a car wash, but when
Herbert vehemently pleaded his case in a predawn phone call,
Parsons bid adieux to a prospective career in suds and turtle wax
and said hello to Three Stooges beer.
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business was obtaining the costly Stooges
licensing rights, which are controlled by Bela Lugosi Jr., son of
the famous horror-movie star, Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks so much like his dad, it's like meeting with
Dracula,'' he said. ``You want to wear garlic to feel safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Once it had licensing rights, the Panther team chose a recipe
that could be made under contract at a Pennsylvania brewery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted something mainstream, not a microbrewed beer,'' said
Parsons, who claims Panther has shipped about ``30 truck loads'' of
the product to liquor stores since late July.
</P>
<P>
   If the beer catches on, there are plans to make a Curly Light
and maybe a Shemp special reserve, Parsons said. (After the duress
of superstardom forced the original Curly to take a much deserved
early retirement, several substitutes, including his real-life
brother Shemp, were brought in to replace him.)
</P>
<P>
   A pale ale to honor Curly Joe DeRita, another Stooge
replacement, seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans hear Joe DeRita and they say, `Forget about it,' '' says
Parsons, adding, ``We're trying to create a brand here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, Jordan's Furniture of Avon, Mass. has run ads that
parody ads made for other companies. No one had ever objected until
a recent complaint by Gap Inc., a Jordan's spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it responded to a Gap request, Jordan's stopped running
an ad that showed khaki-clad hoofers dancing around a couch to the
tune of ``Don't Sit Under the Apple Tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's acknowledged that the ad was about to go off the air
anyway. Scheduled for a six-week flight, the ad began airing Fourth
of July weekend, said Jordan's spokeswoman. Would Jordan's have
scrapped the ad if the Gap had yapped earlier?
</P>
<P>
   Replied the spokeswoman, ``That's very hard to say. I would say,
yes. We don't create parodies to stir up hard feelings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5984 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-21 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS BOSTON STILL BILL CLINTON'S CASH MACHINE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cynics call Boston ``Clinton's ATM.'' No matter what kind of hot
water the president douses himself in, donkey-loyal Hub Dems can be
relied on to show up at a $1,000-a-plate fund-raiser to cheer on
the president and pour a cool mil or two into Democratic coffers.
I've been a guest at two of these events, which inevitably take
place at the Park Plaza and quickly devolve into an unseemly
Bootlickers' Ball, as the Clintons' delightful friends from the
real estate and nursing home industries vie for face time with the
First Couple.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I attended, Hillary was there, and her husband
addressed the plutocrats via video feed from the White House. Fancy
that.
</P>
<P>
   How very unsurprising then, that the president and vice
president are scheduled to return to the Park Plaza Sept. 17 for
yet another shake of the Boston money tree. The occasion: the
biannual ``Unity Dinner,'' when the Democratic primary candidates
kiss and make up (Down Tom! Down Lois!) and vow to sally forth
against the Republican threat etc. etc. One might expect the ardor
of the Lincoln Bedroom crowd to have dimmed in recent weeks, so I
wasn't surprised when a friend of mine who's been invited said
``there's a big push on'' to fill up the tables.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Meet Paul Adao, literazzi
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My friend Joyce Maynard's decision to sell the story of her
nine-month affair 25 years ago with reclusive New Hampshire writer
J.D. Salinger has resuscitated more than just her own career. It
has also breathed new life into the bank account of stalkerazzi
photographer Paul Adao.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Adao and a partner snapped the first photographs
taken of Salinger since 1955. They camped out for six days in
Salinger's hometown of Cornish, N.H. and eventually took a picture
that ended up on the front page of the New York Post. It shows an
enraged Salinger approaching Adao's stakeout. ``I was inside the
car and he came over and started hitting me,'' Adao said, sounding
aggrieved.
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to him, the shot made literary history. Novelist Don
DeLillo has cited the picture as an inspiration for his 1991 novel,
``Mao II.'' ``When they took his picture he came at them,'' DeLillo
told The New York Times. ``His face is an emblem of shock and rage.
It's a frightening photograph.'' Adao himself is not exactly
bookish. He once told an interviewer that ``Catcher in the Rye''
``is supposed to be a great book. ... I found it kind of boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Adao returned to the Salinger beat. After a
trip to Cornish, he sold a full-page Salinger shot to Vanity Fair,
and Newsweek bought a second image. When I reached him by telephone
in Hyannis, (why do I think he was headed for the Vineyard?) Adao
turned press-shy. ``You're irritating me,'' he complained, cutting
short our brief chat.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being a footnote to literary history, Adao's name
endures in the annals of law. Earlier this summer, he ``won'' a $1
settlement _ the lowest amount permitted by law _ from actor Woody
Harrelson. Three years previously, Adao alleged, Harrelson
assaulted him and a colleague while they were taking pictures of
the actors' young children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
We can top that
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a recent column, I conceded to Dan Kaercher, the editor of
Midwest Living magazine, that New England has nothing so cool as
the life-size, refrigerated butter cow displayed at the Iowa State
Fair. But several readers wrote in to correct me. ``Two years ago
at The Eastern States Exposition (Big E) in West Springfield, there
was a butter cow (full size),'' according to Scott Poitras, ``and
last year there &UR;  &LR; was a butter goat and turkey, along with a few
other butter animals.'' This year's Big E runs for three weeks
starting Sept. 18; Poitras says ``the butter carving will be of a
team of Clydesdale Draft Horses pulling a milk wagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, we learn that Len Libby Candies of Scarborough,
Maine, has a 1,700-pound, life-size, chocolate moose on display in
its store. Designed by candymaker Fernand Hemond with the help of a
sculptor from the Maine College of Art, ``Lenny'' is standing in a
pond of white chocolate. How very Midwestern.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
