<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S ONLY OPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can there be any moral authority left in President Clinton? It
is nearly impossible to take him seriously after he admitted lying
about his sexual relations with a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Take problems confronting our youth. Last year, Clinton said,
``We still have some pretty big problems in our society. None
stands in our way of achieving our goals for America more than the
epidemic of teen pregnancy.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd pay to see this guy tell teenagers now about abstinence. Or
safe sex. Is anyone placing bets that Clinton used condoms with
Lewinsky? On second thought, Kenneth Starr might consider that
tampering with the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   It is time to cease with the rationalizations. It is time to
stop enabling this man before he disables the Democratic Party and
gives the right wing a clear path to the presidency in 2000.The
nation can no longer ignore Clinton, just because we are not at war
and most Americans have a car in the garage, a chicken in the pot,
and a cellular phone in the ear. Nor can it fall for the assertion
by Clinton defenders that his lying pales next to Richard Nixon's
attempt to corrupt democracy itself.
</P>
<P>
   We have reached the point where Pinocchio, by any angle, has a
long nose. My wife told me Clinton's sex drive probably would not
matter as much if all his targets were consenting, mature women,
independent of his office. Then it really would be between Bill and
Hillary. Clinton could claim that he was behaving no more badly
than John F. Kennedy with Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's second brain led him down a path no one should
accept. In his speech to the nation Monday night, he said, in an
amazingly unapologetic way, ``Even presidents have private lives.
It is time to stop the pursuit of personal destruction and the
prying into private lives and get on with our national life.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing private about Clinton and Lewinsky. Both held
jobs paid for by the taxpayer. He was elected and she was hired to
serve the public, not each other, on the public's time and dime.
</P>
<P>
   Far more important, Clinton should not be allowed to walk away
from this matter with his arrogant declaration that ``our country
has been distracted by this matter for too long.'' His acts are a
fireable offense at many universities and workplaces.Clinton is
twice Lewinsky's age and held infinite power over her, so much
power that Lewinsky's intentions in the affair are irrelevant
compared to her vulnerability. It was incumbent on the president to
say to himself, don't ask, don't touch.
</P>
<P>
   He went ahead with a woman barely older than his college
daughter. Lying to his own daughter was the icing on his hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Clinton who puritanically drove, by his count,
three million women off welfare. He demanded a morality from single
moms that he was not willing to strive for himself, despite a life
where he never has to cook a meal or clean a toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Clinton said welfare reform ``ended the old welfare
system when we said to those on welfare, responsibility is not an
option. It must be a way of life.'' Clinton's way of life, his
endless rhythm of dalliance, denial, and forced divulgence have
cost him incalculable energy that should have gone to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco settlement, like health care reform in Clinton's
first term, has died. Clinton's race dialogue has virtually
disappeared. The economy may be booming for some, but too many
public schools are wastelands, health care and Medicare remain
dangersously unresolved and too many Americans are forced to play
musical jobs as corporations send jobs overseas.
</P>
<P>
   All of those issues require a president who can rally enough
popular support to make Congress sweat. But the only perspiration
is coming from the Democrats, steaming from betrayal. Any chance to
push an agenda for Americans who have the least, slim to begin with
against the now snickering Republican majorities in Congress, are
now gone.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason why we should have to live with such a
weakened leader. There is not a parent who would not demand the
head of a college president who hits on their daughter. There is
not a feminist organization that would stand still if the next
Supreme Court nominee had this track record. There is not a
newsroom that would not be thrown into turmoil if a 50ish managing
editor went down the hall to have sex with a summer intern.
</P>
<P>
   There should be no America that tolerates a president who lets
his ``private life'' defile the public trust. In talking about teen
pregnancy, Clinton has said it is wrong unless ``you are ready to
take on the responsibilities of parenthood.'' He said, ``It's
something you pay for the rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   It is now clear that Clinton never intended to hold himself
responsible for practicing what he preached, whether as a lying
parent or lying president obsessed with sex on public time and with
his employees. For that, it is time for him to pay with his
presidency. When Bill Clinton returns to Washington from Martha's
Vineyard, it should be for only one reason.He should return to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
