<SLUG> BC-JET-SET-GOLF-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICEY ISLAND COURSE LURES THE JET-SET ELITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. _ At the new Nantucket Golf Club, there are no
tee times.
</P>
<P>
   Members and their guests, some of the richest and most powerful
people in the nation, just show up and tee off whenever they want,
as Microsoft's Bill Gates, General Electric's Jack Welch, and
Republic Industries' Wayne Huizenga did the other day.
</P>
<P>
   As befitting a club where privacy is valued as much as a hole in
one, officials declined comment on the trio's power golf outing.
But the club's determination to keep a low profile hasn't stopped
island tongues from wagging about the spectacular new course
designed by Rees Jones that has helped transform golf into a
jet-set activity.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of the club's 303 members don't even have a
home on the island where they can hang their hat. They just fly in
on their private jets, play golf, and fly out again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's causing quite a bit of additional traffic,'' said Fred
Jaeger, manager of the Nantucket Airport, one of the busiest in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Green, whose Edwards, Colo., company oversaw the
development of the Nantucket Golf Club and who is its the titular
president, of the club, said a second private golf course was
desperately needed on the island because the wait to get into the
Sankaty Head Golf Club was 40 years. There are also two nine-hole
public courses on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who does not own a home on Nantucket, refused to discuss
how much it cost to build the course or how much it costs to become
a member. ``It's a lot of money,'' is all he would say.
</P>
<P>
   According to records on file with the Registry of Deeds, the
250-acre property was purchased in 1995 for $8.25 million, which
may have been a bargain given today's hot real estate market.
Island sources estimate another $15 million was spent designing and
building the par-72, treeless course, erecting the elegant but
hardly ostentatious clubhouse and adjacent cottages for members and
guests, and complying with environmental agreements needed to gain
clearance for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The club, which will be open only six months this year, may be
one of the most expensive in the country to join. Sources say the
cost of membership has risen from $200,000 for early initiates to
$300,000 for the last to join. On top of the membership fee, most
of which sources say is reimbursable if the member quits, annual
dues run about $6,500.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Sankaty Head Golf Club charges $15,000 for a
full family membership and $1,500 in annual dues. About 50 of
Sankaty Head's members also belong to the Nantucket Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's known out there as being one of the most expensive golf
courses around,'' said Thomas Bresette, the Nantucket Golf Club's
clubhouse manager. ``But that hasn't stopped people from joining.''
</P>
<P>
   The membership list is closely guarded, but it includes Dirk
Ziff, No. 127 on the Forbes list of the 400 richest Americans; John
Loose of Corning Inc.; Arie Kopelman of Chanel Inc., and most
likely Welch and Huizenga, both of whom have houses on the island.
What members get for all their money is a purist's golf experience.
There are no tennis courts and no swimming pool. Other than a nice
restaurant and grill, there's nothing to distract from the golf.
</P>
<P>
   Carts are not allowed on the course unless a member is unable to
walk. Everybody takes caddies, who get paid $40 for each bag they
carry. Most of the caddies are island residents, trained by eight
professional caddies imported from the South and put up at a 42-bed
employee lodge at the club.
</P>
<P>
   The clubhouse is set well back from Milestone Road, on the
southern side of the island. There's no sign for the club along the
road, in keeping with its low profile. Visitors drive up a road
until they come to a guard who keeps unwanted visitors out.
</P>
<P>
   The course itself is links-style, meaning it rolls with the
existing landscape. And it is as quiet as the nearby moors and
almost as desolate. All golfers hear is the wind whistling through
the tall brown grass that forms the rough along the lush green
fairways. Kevin Walker, the club's golf pro, said the 7,081-yard
course is never boring because it is constantly changing with the
wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, it's a tournament-caliber golf course, but I don't
think that's on the agenda,'' Walker said. ``If you don't need to
do it, why would you?''
</P>
<P>
   Golfers aren't the only ones raving about the course, which
opened in April. Even though its construction meant bulldozing one
of the most pristine areas of the island, home to several
endangered plants and animals, environmentalists generally praise
the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really does a fabulous job of fitting into that
landscape,'' said James Lentowski, executive secretary of the
Nantucket Conservation Foundation. ``On a continuum of choices,
this certainly is a choice closer to the most desirable rather than
the least desirable.''
</P>
<P>
   The club's willingness to spend money to solve environmental
problems also didn't hurt. In an agreement negotiated with the
Massachusetts Fish and Wildlife Department, the club agreed to
locate and transplant two species of rare plants _ the bushy
rockrose and the St. Andrew's cross _ and to try to propagate them
at a nursery on site. Charlie Passios, the golf course manager,
said the propagation efforts are going well so far.
</P>
<P>
   The club also agreed to spend about $800,000 to fund a 50-year
effort to restore sandplain grasslands and coastal heathlands on
1,110 acres of land owned by the Nantucket Conservation Foundation
and the Massachusetts Audubon Society. The effort, already begun
with clear-cutting of scrub oak in the middle moors section of the
island, is expected to help bring back the rare northern harrier, a
bird of prey often known as the marsh hawk.
</P>
<P>
   Bresette said all the buzz about the club is well deserved.
``When you get all the rumors about the prices here, people want to
come out and see what it's all about,'' he said. ``But what's
amazing is that it lives up to their expectations. There's not too
many places that do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
