</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RAT-PACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIAR FACES TAINT `RAT PACK' TALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE RAT PACK 
Starring: Ray Liotta, Don Cheadle, Joe Mantegna, Angus Macfadyen,
Dan O'Herlihy 
Directed by: Rob Cohen 
On: HBO 
Time: Saturday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVMA 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how expertly the makeup people round his forehead, Ray
Liotta is Ray Liotta, and not Frank Sinatra. When he arches his
ferocious eyebrows and throws a fit because Jack Kennedy has
rejected him, or when he gets in a passionate spat with a drunken
Ava Gardner, or when he trades ethnic jabs with fellow Rat Packers
Sammy Davis Jr. and Dean Martin, he is strangely, stubbornly,
ultimately, and forever, Ray Liotta.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the barriers it's hard to get over while watching
``The Rat Pack,'' a new HBO movie premiering tomorrow night at 9.
It's consistently a strain to make the leap of imagination that is
all-important when watching a traditional biopic, to let the
present subside into the legendary past _ in this case the boozy
Las Vegas nightclub scene of the late 1950s and early 1960s.
Basically, the ``Rat Pack'' actors adopt a few obvious trademarks
of their famous characters _ Don Cheadle adds the word ``baby'' to
the end of every sentence to simulate Sammy Davis Jr., Joe Mantegna
has Dean Martin's cocktail manner down pat, Dan O'Herlihy spews
that very-easy-to-sound-ridiculous Kennedy accent _ leaving none of
them quite convincingly transformed. Nor do they aim for cartoon
versions, except, perhaps, Barbara Niven's Marilyn Monroe and
Zeljko Ivanek's Bobby Kennedy, whose accent gradually evolves into
some kind of strange Southern scat.
</P>
<P>
   Director Rob Cohen and writer Kario Salem, the screenwriter of
HBO's superior ``Don King: Only in America,'' focus their Rat Pack
story on the years when Sinatra courted the friendship of
presidential hopeful John F. Kennedy. Sinatra procures women for
Kennedy, who is rumored to fancy more than one at a time, and he
also procures votes for the young candidate from Massachusetts,
with a little help from mobster friends like Sam ``Momo'' Giancana.
After the election, much to Sinatra's dismay, Kennedy distances
himself from the Chairman of the Board precisely because of those
mob connections. Meanwhile, Davis falls in love with Swedish
actress May Britt, and the public protests that greet their
engagement cause him to postpone his wedding until after the 1960
election.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, the script plays like a jukebox of the
biggest hits of Rat Pack gossip. There's the scene with Marilyn
Monroe drooling over Kennedy while Joe DiMaggio gets uptight; the
scene of Sinatra and Gardner screaming at each other with love-hate
intensity; the saga of Peter Lawford's role as secret messenger;
Kennedy putting down J. Edgar Hoover of the FBI, asking ``Isn't he
getting his estrogen?'' While it's obvious why Sinatra's family
refused to give its blessing to ``The Rat Pack,'' with its bold
portrayal of the connections between the entertainer and the mafia,
still the movie is not really a tabloid treatment. It is clearly
fictionalized and heavily romanticized, pandering to our desire to
witness the condensed story of history without pretending to be
factual. If you blindly believed this movie, after all, you'd have
to think that entertainment meant nothing to Sinatra next to his
political power plays.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of ``The Rat Pack'' is its lush period look, a
vivid nightscape of clubs and stages and restaurants and drinking
parties. One effective montage moves smoothly in and out of rooms
at the Sands Hotel, as Davis, Sinatra, Kennedy, and Lawford have
sex with women in character-revealing ways (Lawford, for instance,
watching himself in the mirror). Another imaginative sequence has
Davis fantasizing about performing ``I've Got You Under My Skin''
before an angry mob of cross-burners. It's one of the only scenes
that pushes a little beyond our cliched understanding of these men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
