<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5997 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BABY-DANCE-BOS &LR;      08-21 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BABY-DANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABY' EMOTIONS ARE PITCH PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
BABY DANCE 
Starring: Laura Dern, Stockard Channing, Richard Lineback, Peter
Riegert 
Written and directed by: Jane Anderson 
On: Showtime 
Time: Sunday night at 9 
Rated: TV14 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may come to pass that Laura Dern will be one of the great
actresses. In movies like ``Rambling Rose,'' ``Wild at Heart,'' and
``Citizen Ruth,'' she has given performances that are utterly
seamless in their emotional reality. Like, say, Gena Rowlands in
``A Woman Under the Influence,'' she has acted with her heart and
her instinct, exposing deep levels of vulnerability without lapsing
into sloppiness or attention-getting. She has been especially good
playing intellectually limited women without leaving the impression
of condescension, or calculation.
</P>
<P>
   And she is the main reason _ though not the only reason _ to
watch ``The Baby Dance,'' a beautifully made cable movie that
premieres on Showtime Sunday night at 9. From the moment you see
Dern's Wanda LeFauve at a Bingo game with her mother, with her long
blond hair in a crummy perm, you already feel the authenticity
about her and the movie itself. Wanda is a poor mother of four who
decides to sell her forthcoming baby, to give it a better chance in
the world with a wealthy, childless couple. She loves her children
profoundly, but she and her husband, Al, live in a tiny,
stifflingly hot trailer in Shreeveport, La., while their kids have
to stay at her mother's slightly more spacious house. ``I gotta get
my tubes tied,'' she moans to her mother.
</P>
<P>
   The dance of the title is between the LA couple who are eagerly
planning to buy the baby, Rachel and Richard Luckman, and Wanda and
Al. It's a beautifully choreographed series of forward moves, and
retreats, and sidesteps, as the couples need something from each
other, but feel mutual discomfort about their different
backgrounds. And because the script and the performances are so
fully persuasive, the dance is also between the viewer and the
movie, as our sympathies move from one character to another and
back again in a slow, complicated rhythm. In some scenes, it seems
as though Wanda and Al are doing a good thing by delivering their
baby from their trailer-park hell, which even has a barking dog at
its gate; in others, Rachel and Richard are like vultures as they
drop checks for $500, waiting impatiently to take home another
couple's infant.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing black and white about ``The Baby Dance,''
particularly at the very end, which I will not disclose. Wanda and
Al are clearly in love, but in one scene Al smacks Wanda and you
know it has happened many times before. ``He doesn't hit hard,''
says Wanda, justifying it to Rachel. ``It's all for show.'' One of
the virtues of the movie is that after this horrible moment it does
not become about Al's abuse, and indeed Richard Lineback's
performance as Al makes him a fully dimensional guy, an overgrown
child who feels both helpless and wily. In one series of scenes, Al
starts drinking, and you see the anxiety register on Wanda's face.
She knows liquor brings out his aggressive side. But the movie
avoids reducing itself to the alcoholism theme, as well, and the
drinking problem becomes just part of the tapestry of Al and
Wanda's life together. At certain moments _ particularly a lovely
scene in which his daughter silences a restaurant with her
beautiful singing _ Al looks like the model of a proud family man.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel is played by Stockard Channing as a realist who, after
nine miscarriages, is still brave enough to hope. She watches Wanda
with envy, and possessiveness, and she can't help but flinch when
she spies Wanda sneaking a smoke, or drinking coffee. She tries to
restrain herself from demanding that Wanda take better care, but
she fails and Wanda lets some of her suppressed anger leak out:
``Don't worry, I won't mess up your baby,'' she snaps. The scenes
between just Dern and Channing are pitch perfect, with the sort of
focus and physical acting usually found in the theater. In fact,
``The Baby Dance'' began as a play that ran both in Los Angeles and
off-Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Director Jane Anderson, who wrote the play and the screenplay,
has given the Showtime production the sort of texture and detail
you'd expect from a big-screen movie. Rachel faces a whirlpool of
kids and dogs as she visits the trailer-park, where Wanda serves
her a cold-cut platter with white bread and American cheese.
Wanda's mother is a hairstylist who sports a very bad wig and works
on customers in her kitchen sink. The sign in front of her house
reads: ``Elegance by Doreen.'' These kinds of incidental touches _
showing Richard rearranging the cheap motel room where he and
Rachel wait for Wanda to give birth, or Al listening to his
father's only recording _ nicely embellish the solid drama that the
actors and the script have created. The premise of ``The Baby
Dance'' makes it sound like one of those network made-for-TV issue
movies that's just this side of ``The Jerry Springer Show.'' But
without a lot of self-congratulation, it reaches the sort of
emotional depths that most network movies avoid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
