</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOLIC-SUCCESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LESSON OF A HARD-DRINKING SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: FILED in ``k'' and ``f'' categories)  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Ingvar Kamprad, the founder and owner of the innovative
Ikea assemble-it-yourself furniture chain in 30 countries, started
from nothing to become one of the world's wealthiest men.
</P>
<P>
   But the 72-year-old Swedish-born billionaire has just added a
chapter to the literature of rags-to-riches by admitting in a new
biography that during the years he built his commercial empire, he
was usually in an alcoholic daze.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 30 years, he drank so heavily that he had to enter
a sanitarium to be ``dried out'' every four months or so, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His condition apparently did nothing to hinder Ikea's growth,
one of the great retail success stories of our time. Yet Kamprad
was wholly in charge, all decisions emanating from him. His
associates either failed to detect his woozy state or kept quiet.
The bankers whom he borrowed money from in the early days also seem
to have been in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if he had been an employee instead of the boss, he
would soon have been out of a job. However, not only was he the
head of the company, he wholly owned it, as he does to this day,
with no shareholders looking over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   This strikes me as a fabulous tale that raises some intriguing
questions.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, would he have made an even greater success if he
had been sober? This is hardly likely, given that it is difficult
to see how Ikea could be bigger or more profitable than it has
turned out to be.
</P>
<P>
   But on the reverse side, the Kamprad confession poses the
question of whether it really matters much who is running the shop
if the idea behind it hits the right note with the buying public.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people, I've wondered for years whether big executives
who are paid six- or seven-figure salaries plus huge stock options
and bonuses for what are often vaguely defined responsibilities are
really worth the money.
</P>
<P>
   A debate over this question has gone on for a long time in
America where executive remuneration is on average the world's
highest. Now the same discussion has shifted across the Atlantic.
Chief executives in Europe receive two or three times as much as
they did a decade ago, a trend accentuated by the privatization of
many previously state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet critics point out that company results frequently don't
justify the big increases. Many enterprises are doing no better
than they did under modestly paid chief executives. Some are doing
distinctly worse. But the pay hikes keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of being accused of excessive cynicism, I would
suggest that some of these handsomely paid but under-achieving
executives might do worse than try the Kamprad method, which seems
to have consisted of taking several stiff drinks before, during and
after a day's hard work. Admittedly, not everyone could manage, but
those who could might prove to be winners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WONDERLAND-BOS &LR;      08-21 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WONDERLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WONDERLAND' HAS TASTY TWIST OF WRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
NEXT STOP WONDERLAND 
Directed by: Brad Anderson 
Screenplay by: Anderson, Lyn Vaus 
Starring: Hope Davis, Alan Gelfant, Victor Argo, Jon Benjamin, Cara
Buono, Phil Hoffman, Roger Rees, Sam Seder, Robert Stanton, Holland
Taylor, Callie Thorne, Jose Zuniga, Paul Wagner, Robert Klein 
Running time: 91 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most romantic comedies turn too sugary too soon. There's a
bracing against-the-grain quality to Brad Anderson's ``Next Stop
Wonderland'' that sets it apart from most of the formulas to which
the genre usually succumbs. Maybe it's just the way the film so
easily aligns with the bred-in-the-bone Boston conviction that
nothing should come easily. Struggle is an integral part of the
Boston ethos and it's embodied with wry ease by Hope Davis's glum
nurse, Erin, and Alan Gelfant's plumber, Alan, who wants to become
a marine biologist.
</P>
<P>
   They don't meet until the final reel, and you can understand why
it might take a while. Apart from the fact that each is sloshing
around in joylessness, Alan is lumbered with a father pressuring
him to take over the family plumbing business. All Alan asks is to
be hired by the Aquarium as a biologist while trying not to be
depressed by the fact that the Aquarium values him more for his
plumbing skills than his pescatorial ones. He's also kept busy
dodging demands for pay back by the loan shark to whom his gambling
addict father is indebted. And he's also dodging a nymphet chasing
him through night school.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is an actress poised on the brink of a big career
breakthrough, and while this film doesn't quite supply it, it
nevertheless gives her the chance to create an original character,
and a likable one, if you can get past Erin's initially off-putting
rejection of anything that comes at her. She's usually right to be
sharp-tongued, starting when her mother takes it upon herself to
insert a personals ad on Erin's behalf that brings Erin the
attentions of a string of full-of-themselves jerks. Not that she
suffers them gladly, or in silence. She's witty enough and just
malicious enough to shoot them down amusingly.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Davis's Erin is a delightfully unplacating character,
uninterested in charm or self-marketing. Erin's is a genuinely
melancholy temperament, she convinces us, reinforced by the
departure of her longtime political activist live-in lover and the
death of her surgeon father. A character of palpable presence whose
absence is felt, the father is a gifted and sensitive man who
dedicated a volume of his poems to his adoring daughter. Davis
convinces us she's very much her father's daughter, not easy, but
worth sticking with.
</P>
<P>
   She's got heart, but doesn't make it readily accessible,
especially since she dropped out of Harvard after a promising med
school start and snatches solace by easing the pain of others as a
nurse. What she and Gelfant have in common is a stubborn integrity.
They don't mind being thought of as unruly, and are true to
themselves as they tool around Boston _ she caught in an undertow
of sadness, he trying to conceal his desperation to blast free of
his working-class baggage and move to the South End, where Erin
lives in dispirited ennui. The film uses other Boston-area locales,
most notably the Burren in Somerville. Part of the fun lies in
spotting local notables, ranging from Jeremy Geidt to Jimmy Tingle,
in cameos.
</P>
<P>
   There are rough edges, loose ends, bits of narrative drift, and
an ending that seems tacked-on, not of a piece with what went
before. But the gritty and deliberately roughhewn ``Next Stop
Wonderland'' achieves an anti-slickness that's refreshing and
believable. If I hadn't read the program notes afterward, I would
never have learned that Anderson intended to make a film that took
its cue from the wistful and melancholy Brazilian music called
saudade. Certainly this accounts for the evocative soundtrack on
grounds deeper than the fact that one of Erin's false romantic
starts is with a Brazilian musicolgist. ``Next Stop Wonderland''
entertains with rueful humor and an undertow of bluesy yearning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-DANCE-BOS &LR;      08-21 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALSA, WINNING STARS PUT MUSIC IN `DANCE WITH ME' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
DANCE WITH ME 
Directed by: Randa Haines 
Screenplay by: Daryl Matthews 
Starring: Vanessa Williams, Chayanne, Kris Kristofferson, Jane
Krakowski, Beth Grant, Harry Groener, William Marquez, Scott
Paetty, Joan Plowright, Rick Valenzuela 
Running time: 126 minutes 
Rated: PG (mild language and sensuality) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dance With Me'' is a tangy screenful of salsa that makes a
strong bid to mainstream its Latin dance movements into the kind of
popularity enjoyed by ``Flashdance'' and ``Strictly Ballroom.''
Like those earlier films, it doesn't let a clunky script detract
from the winning charm of the leads, Vanessa Williams and Puerto
Rican pop star Chayanne. She's sultry, and he's sexy in a boyishly
engaging way that should do a lot for his crossover potential as
the film overrides its lumps by convincing us that it really goes
for dance.
</P>
<P>
   There's more soap opera and less dance than you hope for, at
least in the early stages, as ``Dance With Me'' laboriously sets up
its romance. It begins inauspiciously as Chayanne's character,
Rafael Infante, arriving in Houston from his native Havana
following the death of his mother, is given a job by the man who
used to be a dance instructor on a cruise ship where his mother
sang. What Kris Kristofferson's tired proprietor of a downmarket
dance studio doesn't know, and what Rafael is shy about telling
him, is that he is Rafael's father.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael and Ruby, the instructor played by Williams, are mutually
attracted. But she's reluctant to be deflected from her goal of
reentering professional competition after a six-year timeout to
mother the son she had by her ex-partner; he, meanwhile, is ready
to jump-start both their careers, unaware that he's a father. Her
mixed feelings remain mixed after Rafael takes her to a salsa club
and shows her what a sinuous sizzler he can be on the dance floor.
Ruby looks down her nose at salsa, which she considers too
down-home amateurish.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ruby is about to enter a professional competition, and
Rafael isn't professional, he teams up with a promising amateur,
Jane Krakowski's lyrical ballet-oriented newcomer. This means each
of the predestined lovers enters the competition in different
divisions, with different partners, which whets the curiosity as to
how they're going to be brought together. There's not a lot of
suspense in terms of who winds up with whom, or even whether Rafael
can bond with Kristofferson's crusty and outwardly warm but
essentially standoffish father.
</P>
<P>
   The script by Daryl Matthews doesn't exactly move like the wind.
But the dancing, once it finally gets going, does. Williams
convinves us that although she's dancing with one man, she'd rather
be dancing with another. Chayanne wins us over with his
graciousness _ and with Rafael's gratitude at encountering
something resembling the communal spirit he left behind in Cuba
when he's ushered into the family celebration of a Cuban auto
repairman he visits.
</P>
<P>
   The film is most at home on the dance floor, though. While it
serves up a juicy array of Latin steps, it also includes swing
dancing and even gets away with a disco sequence. It avoids the
usual pall of Hollywood cliches when it comes to portraying Latin
cultures. Chayanne adds humor in a beguiling genuflection to Gene
Kelly's ``Singin' in the Rain'' puddle solo when he dances through
a grassy stretch of geysering lawn sprinklers. Even in the dance
movie genre, where scripts invariably are schematic and
predictable, Matthews's is singularly maladroit. But ``Dance With
Me'' loves dance and loves its leads, and Randa Haines's fluid
camera embraces them with winning advocacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6007 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-DEAD-MAN-BOS &LR;      08-21 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DEAD-MAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLLEGE COMEDY THAT'S DEAD ON ARRIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
DEAD MAN ON CAMPUS 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Written by: Michael Traeger, Mike White  &QL; 
Directed by: Alan Cohn &QL; 
Starring: Tom Everett Scott, Mark-Paul Gosselaar, Poppy
Montogomery, Lochlyn Munro, Randy Pearlstein, Corey Page &QL; 
Running time: 96 minutes &QL; 
Rated: R (adult language, crude sexual humor, drug use) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are three essential myths of college life:
</P>
<P>
   Cafeteria food is indistinguishable from your mom's home
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Diet pills are an acceptable study aid during finals week.
</P>
<P>
   You will automatically receive a 4.0 if your roommate commits
suicide during the academic year.
</P>
<P>
   The latter of this misinformation troika has caused countless
students to gaze eerily upon their roommates with images of
Seconals and straight A's dancing in the their heads. It is also
the premise of ``Dead Man on Campus,'' a lame college comedy about
two flunking buddies who decide to drive a chronically unstable
roommate to off himself. There are freshman biology lectures with
more laughs than this one.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Everett Scott, an actor who becomes less likable with each
film role (he last appeared in the abysmal, ``American Werewolf in
Paris''), is Josh, a pre-med student from Indiana. His success at
fictional Daleman College seems guaranteed until he meets his
suitemate, Cooper (an occasionally charming Mark-Paul Gosselaar
from that endless ``Saved by the Bell'' series.) The son of a
wealthy toilet manufacturer, Cooper is one of those kids who has
always ridden Daddy's money and influence to get what he wants _
and what he wants to do most is party. Babes, booze, and bongs are
the sum of Cooper's college experience. Eventually, Josh gets
sucked into Cooper's world, and soon finds himself failing
everything, and in danger of losing his scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Then the two discover an obscure rule in their school's charter
which will award straight A's to the grief-stricken survivor of a
suicidal roommate. So, instead of hitting the books to bring up
those lousy grades, Josh and Cooper start hanging around the
school's mental health center to nab some stooge likely to commit
suicide, especially if they can help push him over the edge.
</P>
<P>
   There's Cliff (played with a take-no-prisoners verve by Lochlyn
Munro), a dangerously psychotic frat boy, who may not kill himself,
but is likely to wipe out everyone around him; there's Buckley
(Randy Pearlstein), a hyper-paranoid conspiracy theorist convinced
that Bill Gates is trying to take over the world (What's so wacko
about that?); and lest we forget, Matt (Corey Page), a bitter,
bile-spewing Brit who has clearly listened to way too much Joy
Division.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, they fill their room with instruments of
self-destruction: knives, a noose, pills, pills, and more pills.
</P>
<P>
   Are you laughing yet?
</P>
<P>
   In the right hands, this film could have been as sharp as
``Heathers,'' Michael Lehmann's jet-black comedy about high school
cliques and pecking orders. If wicked humor could be found in
murdering obnoxious classmates, then certainly there should have
been something funny, in an equally sinister premise. But Michael
Traeger's script isn't that smart or ambitious, and the film flunks
miserably.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, this little moldy slab of cheese comes courtesy of
MTV Productions, the same folks responsible for the roach-infested
(literally and figuratively speaking) ``Joe's Apartment,'' a very
bad movie very few people saw.
</P>
<P>
   A similar fate should await ``Dead Man on Campus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
