<HEADER>
A6013 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-REGENERATION-BO     08-21 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-REGENERATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY, HIGH-MINDEDNESS DON'T HEAL `REGENERATION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
REGENERATION 
Directed by: Gillies MacKinnon 
Screenplay by: Allan Scott (novel: Pat Barker) 
Starring: Jonathan Pryce, James Wilby, Jonny Lee Miller, Stuart
Bunce, Tanya Allen, David Hayman, Dougray Scott, John Neville 
Running time: 113 minutes 
Rated: Unrated 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Regeneration'' is a high-minded and luxuriantly brooding but
ultimately inert study of the clash between idealism and expediency
in an upper-class World War I rehab facility. Craiglockhart
Hospital, a requisitioned Scottish castle, is bathed in an underlit
decorousness as the film rides an actual historical circumstance _
the meeting there of poets Siegfried Sassoon and Wilfred Owen in
1917. The upper-class Sassoon, played with just the right edge
toff-like entitlement by James Wilby, is a problem patient. He was
stashed away, we soon learn, in an effort by the government to
discredit his impassioned anti-war writings.
</P>
<P>
   The implication is that the poet's attack upon the shift of the
war from defense to aggression is the product of shell shock. The
catch is that if he is judged sane he could be tried for treason.
To his credit, Wilby convinces us of Sassoon's essential
worldliness and romantic heedlessness. Go ahead and persecute me,
he says in effect to his nominal superiors. Either way, I'm your
problem. Wilby's air of familiarity with the ways of power is just
palpable enough, moreover, to convince us that he just might be
attempting a daring power gamble.
</P>
<P>
   He's aided by two things _ a respected army psychiatrist is
sympathetic to him, and a young unpublished poet finds in him a
friend and mentor. Owen, the poet from Shropshire whose poetry was
published posthumously after his death in the war and later set to
music by Benjamin Britten in his ``War Requiem,'' is played with
frayed-nerve hesitations by Stuart Bunce. Poet and writer Robert
Graves, played by Dougray Scott, is also seen, but only fleetingly.
Perhaps to avoid the implication that this was a celebrity war, the
film allots equal screen time to Jonny Lee Miller's earnest
working-class bloke, traumatized into muteness.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the ethical dilemmas embodied by his patients
come close to unhinging Jonathan Pryce's high-minded psychiatrist,
William Rivers. After he visits a sadistic colleague who in effect
tortures the wounded into declaring that they're ready to return to
combat, he becomes shell shocked, too, although nowhere near a shot
fired in anger. The battlefield sequences only punctuate what
should be but isn't often enough the tension between the walking
wounded and the officers who, ironically, become their enemy no
less than the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   As the English officer class and politicians seem intent on
confirming the merit of Sassoon's arguments, Sassoon, meanwhile,
befriends Owen. He encourages the latter's writing, advising him to
turn from ideals of beauty to the horrifying realities of war they
both experienced and for which Sasoon had been decorated. Without
ever betraying any sense of awareness that Sassoon was one of those
charmed souls who could walk through fire and remain unscathed (he
in fact lived until 1967), Wilby justifies the poet's arrogant air
by underpinning it with believable moral passion.
</P>
<P>
   Miller brings sensitivity to a character who seems a cardboard
cutout, despite a sympathetic romance with a local munitions worker
played by Tanya Allen. Pryce is always interesting to watch, even
if his character _ Rivers, too, really lived _ seems needlessly
muted. But then the whole film seems rather more muted than you
expect, given its weight and resonance. The film's title, by the
way, refers to one medical researcher's goal of regenerating nerve
tissue. But the film remains a beautifully crafted, lugubrious
reminder that literacy, intelligence, and compassion aren't enough
to galvanize a film.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
