<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MESSINA-BOS &LR;      08-21 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MESSINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMEGROWN COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Move over Shania, LeAnn, and Faith. There's a new woman topping
the country charts _ and she just happens to be a Yankee. She is Jo
Dee Messina, who is not yet known only by her first name, though
that day may come since she's had two No.1 hits this year.
</P>
<P>
   Messina's double-sided single _ with the playfully assertive
``I'm Alright'' and comic kiss-off song ``Bye Bye'' _ has been a
phenomenon resulting in both tunes cresting the charts in recent
months. Each time, Messina, who grew up in the Boston suburb of
Holliston, has been left in a happy daze.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like when you ring the bell at the circus,'' says
Messina, 27. ``When I first heard I had a No.1, I flipped out and
started screaming. The rest of my band was on the bus and when I
ran on the bus to tell them, they thought someone had been in an
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   No accident here. Rather, Messina's latest radio hits _ coupled
with two Top 10 hits in 1996 with ``Heads Carolina, Tails
California'' and ``You're Not in Kansas Anymore'' _ follow a life
of hard work dating to the days she played defunct clubs such as
the Blue Star in Saugus, Saco's in Watertown, and the Adelphia in
Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   She was only in high school then (she left right after
graduation for Nashville) and the apex of her year was watching the
Country Music Association awards to ``check out the latest
hairstyles'' and see who won the Horizon award for rising star.
</P>
<P>
   So guess what? Messina is now nominated for that same Horizon
award, going up against Trace Adkins, Lee Ann Womack, the Dixie
Chicks, and Michael Peterson. She's also up for top music video for
``Bye Bye.'' The CMA awards will be broadcast nationally on Sept.
23 from Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew this was what I wanted to do,'' Messina says of
her country dream. ``But I didn't picture all of this. Hey, you
might want to be a movie star, but you don't picture yourself
standing on a set with Steven Spielberg, do you?''
</P>
<P>
   When Messina first came to Nashville, she went to endless talent
contests and jam sessions, but struggled and watched her savings
sink so low that the electricity in her apartment was shut off.
Still, she ``sang every chance I could get.''
</P>
<P>
   Her big break came when she was at a party and went up to a Curb
Records executive and dared to say, ``What you all need over there
is a redhead.'' The exec thought about it, then called her for a
demo tape. The rest is a Yankee-goes-to-Nashville fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe I said that to him,'' says Messina. ``The
minute I said it, I thought it was goofy. But I guess it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   She also fatefully befriended Tim McGraw, who is now a huge
Nashville star (and husband to Faith Hill). ``We were both poor and
scurrying around to get a record deal,'' notes Messina. ``I said,
`When you make it big, don't forget me.''' He didn't and has since
produced both of her albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim is awesome. He's so creative _ and he knows what it's like
to be on both sides of the music. He knows the business, but he
also knows when to tell you that a song tempo is weird or something
like that, and you should change it. He's been great.''
</P>
<P>
   Messina has learned well herself. For ``I'm Alright,'' a
hard-driving, middle-class anthem (key verse: ``I'm stuck in the
middle where money gets tight, but I guess I'm doing all right''),
Messina decided at the last minute that she wanted a dobro on the
track. ``So they called in a dobro player and it's on there,'' she
says proudly.
</P>
<P>
   As the daughter of a onetime football coach at Holliston High
School, Messina grew up as a tomboy and youngest of four children.
``I know how to throw a football,'' she says. She also saturated
herself in the music of her main influences _ Tammy Wynette, Reba
McEntire, Patsy Cline, Loretta Lynn, and Janie Fricke.
</P>
<P>
   After initial success in Nashville two years ago with ``Heads
Carolina, Tails California'' and ``You're Not in Kansas Anymore,''
Messina went a long time without a follow-up hit _ and that proved
to be one of the best lessons of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``When `Carolina' had hit, I had a jillion friends and my phone
was ringing off the hook,'' she says. ``But then in '97, my record
wasn't out and we weren't hot. And my phone wasn't ringing off the
hook. I'd call up and hear someone say, `Well, we're going to
so-and-so's No.1 party. See you later.' So I changed my phone
number and only my real friends call me now.''
</P>
<P>
   Messina writes only a few of her songs (and none of her hits so
far), but she has good taste in choosing material. Her two recent
No.1 hits are both written by rising songwriting star Phil Vassar,
a personal favorite. ``We've got three of his songs on hold for the
next album,'' she says. ``And we start working on the record in
September. We want to have it ready before long, so we can keep up
the momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, her latest album, driven by the two hits, is still
cooking. The next single is likely to be ``Stand Beside Me,''
featuring an assertive message about a woman who breaks up with her
man, takes two jobs so she can make it on her own, and then when he
wants to come back, tells him no.
</P>
<P>
   The sentimental choice for next single, however, is ``Even God
Must Get the Blues,'' a ballad that touched the crowd when Messina
performed it at Great Woods during the WKLB-FM (99.5) Boston
Country Festival earlier this summer. It's a topical song about the
bad news found in daily newspapers, including a story about a
battered woman. ``The devil's been busy,'' she sings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an in-your-face song. I started doing it on stage after
the Oklahoma City bombings,'' she adds. ``We've talked about it as
a single, but I think it frightens the folks at the record label. I
don't think it will be a single any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, you can expect Messina to keep plugging away,
because that's her nature, again going back to her Holliston tomboy
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Are you going to sit back and relax now that
you've had some success?' No way. You fight to get into the game _
and you fight to stay in the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1342EDT &QL; 
