<HEADER>
A6016 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-FACES-HNS &LR;      08-21 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-FACES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AT ARTISTS THROUGH THE EYES OF ARTISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID BONETTI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Because they depict members of the species about
which we hold infinite curiosity, portraits have always been an
alluring genre among the arts of representation, and portraits of
artists, the people who make the images, have exerted an especially
strong pull on those who follow the arts. There is something
fascinating about artists' portraits, whether made by the artists
themselves or by someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Face of Art,'' at the Ansel Adams Center in San Francisco
through Oct. 18, might be the sleeper of the season. The show
includes more than 100 photographic images of primarily American
artists made from 1850 to 1950, and they document the radical
changes that occurred during that time in fashion, lifestyle and
art itself at the same time that they show how artists, both
well-known and unknown, looked.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs come from the collection of Susan Herzig and
Paul Hertzmann, private photography dealers who collect artists'
portraits for themselves. They state that their interest in
artists' portraits dates from their sale, in the early 1980s, of a
portrait of Ash Can School painter Robert Henri by pictorialist
photographer Gertrude Kasebier. Having let an extraordinary print
go, they vowed to hold onto every artist portrait that subsequently
came their way. To date, they have collected nearly 900 such
images.
</P>
<P>
   The show is nicely installed and organized. Most of the work is
made in a variety of standard processes such as daguerreotype or
albumen or silver prints, but a number of carte de visites _
calling cards bearing photographic images _ and stereo views give
the exhibition variety.
</P>
<P>
   The stereo views, once you've learned how to use the glasses
that give the images a sense of three-dimensionality, are a kick.
The picture of Thomas Moran, who specialized in painting the Grand
Canyon, sitting on the Canyon's edge in startling 3-D, for
instance, is an exhibition highlight.
</P>
<P>
   The show is neatly divided between photographs made in the 19th
and 20th centuries, and it allows you to trace the development of
the medium from that of a relatively unself-conscious tool to
capture likenesses to a vehicle of self-expression.
</P>
<P>
   Herzig and Hertzmann write that they are particularly drawn
toward images of artists in their studios surrounded by their
paraphernalia and of images of painters who traveled West during
the age of exploration. They also went out of their way to collect
portraits of women artists.
</P>
<P>
   The prints of artists in their studios form a lively leitmotif
that runs through the exhibition. In the first grouping of artists
at work or pretending to be at work, there are images of Hudson
River School painter John Frederick Kensett in a painting-filled
interior, brush in hand; of academic sculptor Daniel Chester French
shot from above (by Jessie Tarbox Beals) in his sculpture-filled
studio; and of academic painter Elizabeth Nourse in her
objet-d'art-filled studio painting two children in Dutch costume.
</P>
<P>
   Especially noteworthy among them is the portrait by Ansel Adams
of Gottardo Piazzoni in his studio in front of the murals he was
creating for San Francisco's old Main Library. Adams portrayed
Piazzoni smocked and with head turned down in reflection, the very
image of the romantic artist. It is a shame that the Asian Art
Museum, in its legitimate desire for a better building to house its
collections, plans to destroy those murals, which are widely judged
to be Piazzoni's masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Also interesting are portraits of cowboy artists _ or cowboy
wannabes _ among them Gutzon Borglum, the sculptor of the
presidential portraits on Mount Rushmore, and Charles Marion
Russell, the sculptor of cowboys in action. The image of Maynard
Dixon by his then-wife Dorothea Lange is particularly striking.
Shot in shadow, Dixon presents a dark, undifferentiated form
against the Western landscape, the easel and brushes in his hands
and his cowboy hat providing him with a distinctive profile.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most memorable images, however, are standard head
shots. The exhibition's title wall includes some seven artistic mug
shots ranging from a circa 1845 daguerreotype by Boston
portraitists Southworth &AMP; Hawes of painter George Peter Alexander
Healy to more recent pictures of mid-century artists Thomas Hart
Benton, David Alfaro Siqueiros, Paul Manship, Pavel Tchelitchew and
Yasuo Kuniyoshi, some of them endowed with the glamour of Hollywood
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Modernist aesthetics mirroring the work of the artists depicted
is evident in a portrait of Yves Tanguy by George Platt Lynes in
which a double-exposure shows the artists' head emerging from a
surrealist landscape of one of his own paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Two other works memorably capture in portraits of Paul Cadmus,
George Tooker and Jared French the campy light surrealism of their
work. In an amusing photo by Cadmus, Tooker, French and pal Monroe
Wheeler strike stilted homoerotic poses on the beach with a large
piece of driftwood. In a group portrait by Lynes, Cadmus, Tooker
and French are each captured at work, each in his own room,
receding in perspective as radical as the Italian Renaissance
painting that inspired them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
