<HEADER>
A6030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV23     08-21 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV23-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL CONTRIBUTION HIKES NOW MEAN BIG GAINS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 23, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am employed at a company which has recently expanded the
menu of investment options available in its 401(k) program. It now
offers these options: MainStay Institutional Multi-Asset, MainStay
Growth Equity Index, MainStay Indexed Bond, Janus Fund, Fidelity
Low-Priced Stock, Invesco Industrial Income, PBHG Emerging Growth,
PIMCo Mid-Cap Growth, T. Rowe Price International Equity, and
Warburg Pincus International Equity. My wife is a former employee
of the same company and has left her $19,000 401(k) balance there.
I have a balance of $32,000, to which I add $10,000 a year and plan
to increase this at a rate of 5 percent annually. We both now have
our investments evenly divided between Janus and Fidelity
Low-Priced Stock funds, both of which have served us well. With the
broader menu, we would like to diversify more to spread the risk,
although we have a fairly high tolerance for risk. Ideally, I would
like to retire at age 60, which means I have 27 years to go.
</P>
<P>
   P.N., Gloucester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I agree that more diversification would serve you well,
although you don't need to make drastic changes. I would continue
to hold Janus fund as your core position, retaining the full 50
percent commitment to that fund. Since Invesco Industrial Income
and MainStay Growth funds have largely the same makeup and mission
but a records that aren't as strong as Janus Fund's, I would cross
them off. I would also cross off the two MainStay fixed-income
funds, because you don't need any bonds at all at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Low-Priced Stock has a superior record to PBHG Emerging
Growth, so no need to make a move in that direction. But PimCo
Mid-Cap Growth fund has a fine record, and I'd add it to the list.
Of the two international stock funds, I'd give the nod to T. Rowe
Price International Stock, based on its superior record. As for
allocations, I suggest you simply divide the second half of the
portfolio evenly among Fidelity Low-Priced Stock, PIMCo Mid-Cap
Growth, and T. Rowe Price International Stock.
</P>
<P>
   Where should all of this get you? After a long calculation,
adjusted for a 5 percent increase in contributions for each of the
27 years, the answer came out at $2,622,122. To give you an idea
how important those small-but-regular increases in your
contributions will become, the initial calculation, which presumed
all 324 contributions at the current rate, came out at $1,935,043.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 52-year-old woman, and I have had a $40,000 rollover
IRA in a savings account for two years now. I am currently
attending school, but will be working full time in a year. I know I
am in a situation in which the word ``retirement'' will not be
used. So the money won't be needed for about 15 years. How do you
suggest I put this money to work for me? What do you think of
purchasing large-cap stocks? From what I've been reading, mutual
funds are not making as much money as the stock market. Also, how
do I access the IRA to purchase stocks, if that's your suggestion?
How would I set up a brokerage account? Would I fund a discount
broker or can I purchase them myself?
</P>
<P>
   P.T., Santa Ana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Whether you decide to go with a personal stock portfolio or
whether I can persuade you that mutual funds are the better route,
you'll need some entity _ either a brokerage firm or an agent
assigned by a mutual fund company _ to serve as the custodian for
the money _ thus retaining its status as an IRA. If you tried to
simply withdraw the money yourself, it would become a premature
withdrawal in the eyes of the IRS, and you would not only face
taxes on the amount in question, but early withdrawal penalties as
well. To make this transfer while retaining the account as an IRA,
make your choice of the target investment, tell them what you want
to do, and they will supply you with an application that includes a
form by which you authorize the new custodian to obtain the money
from your bank. Still with me? It's just red tape, but it's
important that it be done right.
</P>
<P>
   So the main question becomes where to put the money. I'm against
your idea of a portfolio of individual large-cap stocks, for two
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One is that if you were to select six or eight stocks, you would
have very little diversification. Even if most of them did well,
unfavorable results with one or two of the issues could wreck the
overall portfolio average.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it's the large-cap stocks that have been behind the
much-heralded stock market gains of the last few years, and to my
way of thinking they should be about played out at this point.
</P>
<P>
   If I were designing a long-term portfolio for a person in your
situation, I would use four different funds at the outset, and
eventually weed them down to three.
</P>
<P>
   I'll cite Vanguard funds in this selection, although many fund
families could be used to build a similar portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   I would select the three stock funds that will become the
critical parts of the portfolio. Target half the money for a
value-oriented large-cap fund, such as Vanguard Index Value. Start
by plunking down $1,000 _ the minimum allowed to open an IRA
account at Vanguard _ there. I would then move down the scale to
Vanguard Mid-Cap Index, again making the $1,000 minimum initial
investment, but targeting it for a position that will eventually
represent only 25 percent of the portfolio. The same goes for the
final element, Vanguard Small-Cap Index.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $37,000 would go into one of Vanguard's money
market funds, of which the largest is Vanguard Prime Money Market.
You could then ask Vanguard to move $850 a month into your three
target funds. If you achieved 5 percent average returns from the
money fund, this would spread your investment over 48 months _
providing you with a degree of protection against a short-term drop
in the market.
</P>
<P>
   It would require a bit of juggling at the outset to get your
allocations on schedule. The first month, you would move the entire
$850 into Vanguard Index Value.
</P>
<P>
   The second money, $500 would go to Index Value and $175 each to
the Mid-Cap and Small-Cap funds. Then you would have achieved the
target allocations, so for all subsequent months, the moves would
involve $425 going to Index Value and $212.50 each to the remaining
funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
