<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Aug. 22:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; U.S. ATTACK ON TERRORIST SITES &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a three-page package of stories
covering the aftermath of attacks Thursday against suspected
terrorist sites in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-DAMAGE (Washington) _ Damage assessment of the attacks.
The Taliban says 21 killed in raid on the center in Afghanistan; 10
injured in Khartoum. Pakistan says an errant missile landed in its
territory, killing six. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-EVIDENCE (Washington) _ The administration has long
considered Osama bin Laden to be a top terrorist. A look at what
evidence they had in the past, and what they learned in recent
weeks that allowed the administration to finally agree to an
attack. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-PAKISTAN (Islamabad) _ Pakistan says a U.S. missile
apparently intended for Afghanistan missed, hitting Pakistani
territory and killing civilians. Other developments. By Raymond
Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SUDAN (Khartoum) _ Developments in Sudan and damage at
the attack sites. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ American and Albania agents fan out
with lists of people to arrest but there are concerns that many
have fled from a country whose security is porous. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-DIPLO (Washington) _ Senior American officials say their
failure to make progress in the Middle East badly complicates their
ability to be credible in the Arab world, even when they attack
terrorists that also frighten the established rulers of the region.
By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-RECAP (Washington) _ A recap of the process leading up to
the decision to attack: Clinton had cut short a political trip to
California to attend a military strategy meeting. For the next
eight days, he and the White House were consumed with planning on
two tracks for two events: his grand jury testimony and the
attacks. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ISLAM (Undated) _ President's Clinton's speech was an
unprecedented recognition of the Islamic faith, but also a
carefully nuanced attempt not to whip up hostilities between the
United States and believers. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   And these roundups of international reaction:
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT (Jerusalem) _ Reaction from the Mideast. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT (Berlin) _ Reaction from Europe. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-RUSSIA-REACT (Moscow) _ Reaction from Russia. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
