<P>
   BOMBING-NEW-WAR (Undated) Thursday's military strikes against
targets in Afghanistan and Sudan were the first battle in a new
form of war the Pentagon has been gearing up for since 1994 _ one
against terrorists or rogue states capable of launching attacks
against U.S. targets. Joint Chiefs Chairman Gen. Henry Shelton made
a point of noting that the U.S. operation was very different than
the Gulf War: ``We are in a different ball game today,'' Shelton
said. ``We're going against a terrorist organization, and that
calls from some different techniques.'' The military option used
Thursday is part of a multi-billion-dollar Pentagon initiative
against terrorism that was began in late 1993 and formally was made
part of defense planning and budgets the next year. It was a
reponse to the heightened threat of nuclear, biological or chemical
attacks against American targets.
</P>
<P>
   By Ed Offley. (story has moved in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH (Undated) There is nothing like a crisis
to winnow the winners from the whiners. Some people hit with a
setback become paralyzed and give in to helplessness, while others
seize the situation and turn it into an opportunity for success.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
