 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, Aug. 22,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, Aug.
22, 1998. We will update this budget at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   USSTRIKES-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ Eleven days before he is set to meet
with President Clinton in Moscow, Russian President Boris Yeltsin
on Friday sharply condemned the U.S. air strikes against suspected
terrorist targets in Afghanistan and Sudan, calling them
``indecent.'' Yeltsin said: ``My attitude is negative, just as to
any act of terrorism. The basis for (armed) intervention is
impotence to solve this question through talks.'' U.S. Ambassador
James Collins held talks at the Kremlin and the foreign ministry in
an effort to explain the U.S. actions and soothe Russian concerns.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: ETA: Noon.
</P>
<P>
   USSTRIKES-QUESTIONS _ WASHINGTON _ Although the U.S. government
provided no air cover for the more than 50 Tomahawk cruise missiles
fired at terrorist operations in Sudan and Afghanistan, officials
provided plenty of ``on-air cover'' for the operation itself.
Following President Clinton's Oval Office address, readily
accessible administration officials blanketed the airwaves with
briefings and interviews. Air cover that continued Friday morning.
But curiously, they're offering few specifics on the so-called
``compelling evidence'' that led to the air strikes, thus leaving
numerous questions remaining about the most significant operation
aimed against terrrorism in U.S. history. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   USSTRIKES-HOME _ WASHINGTON _ The morning after the U.S. forces
launched missiles to send a strong message to terrorists around the
world, Americans awoke to ``terrorist warnings'' at home.
Travelers, tourists and commuters were immediately bombarded Friday
with warnings of heightened security at airports, mass transit
systems, federal buildings and even national monuments. ``Watch
for, and report suspicious packages and/or people,'' Washington,
D.C. area METRO riders were told. All that seemed to be missing
were the air raid sirens. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This story can be localized with inserts from Cox papers.
</P>
<P>
   USSTRIKES-DETER _ WASHINGTON _ How effective were the military
strikes in terms of deterring future terrorist attacks? (Carr, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TUTU _ ATLANTA _ Interview with the Rev. Desmond Tutu, who
arrived this week at Emory University in Atlanta to teach this
year. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN EDs: With its brilliant hand-woven rugs, shimmering black
pottery and fantastic carved animals, Oaxaca state is indisputably
one of Mexico's favorite travel destinations. Three villages
minutes from Oaxaca city specialize in these widely-recognized
crafts, which have found their way into museums, galleries and
homes around the world. Cox Newspapers Mexico correspondent Susan
Ferriss visited the three towns, and talked to Zapotec Indian
artisans about their crafts and how their businesses have helped
curb poverty. Following are the budget lines for three short
stories:
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-RUGS _ TEOTITLAN DEL VALLE, Mexico _ Some have business
cards printed in English. Others have clients who fly in to buy in
bulk. Zapotec Indians in Teotitlan del Valle, Oaxaca, make
hand-dyed and hand-woven rugs that are considered some of Mexico's
finest in arts and crafts. With chickens and children running about
her patio, Margarita Sosa Vasquez proudly demonstrates how her
family produces these rugs _ which are a bargain when bought in the
village but can fetch hundreds more in the United States. To dye
wool for the rugs, Margarita shows how a blight is scraped from
cactus leaves to produce various shades of red. Greens are squeezed
from alfalfa, browns from nutshells and blues from indigo. The
patterns Margarita weaves are ancient, depicting lightening bolts,
mescal plants, diamonds and other shapes. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ANIMALS _ ARROZOLA, Mexico _ Carved from pieces of the
copal tree and painted in riotous colors, the animals of Arrazola,
Oaxaca, enrich Mexican culture -- and have enriched the Zapotec
Indian families that produce the creatures that tourists flock here
to buy. Claudio and Teresa Ojeda, who are particularly successful,
fashion animals that are larger than most in town, sometimes
measuring up to three feet wide or tall. The pieces are in demand
as far away as Hong Kong. And no wonder: they are mind-bending
fusions of shapes and colors that defy the imagination.
Fire-breathing dragons sport tails that turn into spitting
serpents. A giant lobster sprouts a lizard on its back. A ram with
curved horns ripples with sensual, almost human muscles. The Ojedas
say their designs are spontaneous. But they also attribute them to
visions they've seen after eating hallucinogenic mushrooms, an
ancient tradition among some Oaxacan Indians. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POTTERY _ SAN BARTOLO COYOTEPEC, Mexico _ For thousands
of years, Zapotec Indians in this Oaxacan community have harvested
a dull gray clay from a special place in the hills and fashioned it
into pots and sculptures that turn black once they are fired. In
the 1950s, a tiny Zapotec potter named Dona Rosa discovered that if
she rubbed her black pots with a crystal stone and fired them again
the pieces would take on a lustrous shine that people seemed to
love. Today Dona Rosa's son carries on his mother's art in the
village of San Bartolo Coyotepec, not far from the city of Oaxaca.
Using ancient methods _ and the same clay as their ancestors _
potters here spin vessels huge and small and sculpt candlesticks,
mermaids and other creatures. The pots are often pierced with
delicate patterns that cast flickering shadows when candles are
placed inside. And some of the larger vessels are scored with
intricate webbed patterns that resemble South Pacific tattoos.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photos for all three stories to be placed in the
International and Travel folders on the Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Package moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel
categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   The following story, which moved Thursday, is being resent for
those who may have bumped it due to space limitations caused by
Thursday's U.S. bombings.
</P>
<P>
   MONICABEACH _ WASHINGTON _ Among those Americans who aren't so
anxious for independent counsel Kenneth Starr to wind up his
investigation of President Clinton are the residents of Monica
Beach _ the photographers and TV technicians who have camped
outside the E. Everett Prettyman U.S. Courthouse since January.
``As a citizen, I guess I am glad to see it ending. But jobwise _
no,'' said a network cameraman. ``This has been a gravy train.''
For networks employees, the overtime pay has been great. And for
freelance photographers, the endless stream of witnesses has meant
lots of business. (Dart, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH-FINANCE _ Gingrich speaks at the annual Seattle-area
GOP picnic Sat., Aug 22. Nothing unusual here, except that the host
is Thomas Stewart, CEO of Services Group of America, and he and
another company exec pleaded guilty this year to laundering
campaign cash. He paid nearly $5 million in fines. His home
detention ended in May. He's also the Washington GOP's largest
contributor. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TRYPTOPHAN _ WASHINGTON _ A popular food supplement,
L-tryptophan, sickened hundreds of people in the United States and
caused 30 deaths in the late 1980s, when a contaminated form was
sold. The supplement was temporarly withdrawn from the market. Now,
the pills appear again to have been contaminated, scientists say.
Researchers at the Mayo Clinic, in a paper to be published Sept. 1,
in the journal Nature Medicine, say they tested L-tryptophan now
being sold in health food stores and found some lots contaminated,
possibly in the same manner as before. L-tryptophan is marketed as
``nature's sleeping pill,'' taken for insomnia, obesity and
headaches. Although no cases of the condition that led to deaths in
the 1980s have been reported, the FDA has been notified of the
potential contamination. Some scientists call the situation an
``epidemic waiting to happen.'' This paper is embargoed for
publication only after Aug. 31. If the embargo is not lifted by
Nature Medicine, we plan to break it because of public safety
implications. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT. in both the (w) Washington and (l)
Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-MUSEUM _ FAIRFAX, Va. _ From a musket that came over on the
Mayflower to an M-16 from the Vietnam War, from Annie Oakley's
rifle to the pearl-handled pistol Teddy Roosevelt kept by his White
House bed, from a buffalo hunter's Sharps carbine to a Baby
Boomer's Daisy ``Red Ryder'' BB gun, the new museum recalls a
nation's history through its guns. The National Rifle Association's
$3.1 million National Firearms Museum provides an array of dramatic
displays illustrating the notion that guns are as all-American as
baseball or Old Glory _ a controversial concept in an era when
schoolchildren shoot classmates and politicians bemoan the
availability of assault weapons. (Dart, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS (in the national folder on the Cox server).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving in (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   CITADEL_ CHARLESTON, S.C._The new freshman class of The Citadel
arrives on campus this weekend, with more women than ever. We check
in on changing attitudes, talking with some of the new arrivals and
some of the veterans who have been through all the protests and
media attention. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
