<HEADLINE>
MORE AMERICANS SHOULD HAVE ASKED THIS IN THE FIRST PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Gallup pollsters and their media partners, CNN and USA
Today, have been busy explaining a discrepancy in their instant
analysis of public reaction to President Clinton's post-grand-jury
speech Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gallup's initial polling after the speech suggested that the
percentage of respondents holding a favorable view of Clinton had
plummeted from 60 percent to 40 percent. The precipitous drop was
amazing, especially when compared with Clinton's 62 percent job
approval rating in the same poll.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that a change in the wording of a poll question
produced a misleading result. The pollsters normally ask folks if
they have a favorable or unfavorable opinion of the president; this
time, they asked those polled if they had a favorable or
unfavorable opinion of Clinton ``as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see what happened here. Lots of Americans believe
that Clinton is OK in his role as chief executive of the country.
But Bill Clinton ``as a person?''
</P>
<P>
   That's another story.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Associated Press, the editor in chief of the
CNN/USA Today/Gallup Poll explained that the decrease in Clinton's
favorable rating was probably half what the wrongly worded poll
suggested _ meaning that 50 percent of poll respondents viewed
Clinton favorably after the speech, compared with 60 percent before
he publicly confessed to participating in a relationship that was
``not appropriate'' with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In quickly clarifying the discrepancy, the pollsters were trying
to be fair to Clinton. The misleading 20 percent drop in his
favorability rating was widely reported in the media _ this column
included _ and was generally interpreted to suggest that Clinton
had suffered a severe loss of good will as a result of his speech.
</P>
<P>
   But the mixup raises an interesting question: Why doesn't every
poll try to find out how the American people view their president
``as a person''?
</P>
<P>
   As Gallup's mistakenly worded question emphasized, there is a
distinct difference between Americans' assessment of Clinton the
man and Clinton the president. Why isn't any president's standing
as a person considered crucial to measuring his standing as
president?
</P>
<P>
   The American people made it clear during Clinton's second
campaign for president that they were willing to separate their
view of his job performance from any misgivings they might have
about his character. Numerous polls showed that a majority of
voters believed that Clinton was deficient in the areas of honesty
and trustworthiness, but he still racked up a decisive victory over
Republican opponent Bob Dole, whose ratings for honesty and
integrity were far superior.
</P>
<P>
   Does all this mean what it seems to mean _ that Americans don't
care what sort of rogue their president might be as long as the
economy is strong and most people have a job?
</P>
<P>
   If so, then perhaps we are witnessing the ultimate triumph of
cynicism over citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   We'll find out soon enough. In the coming days and weeks, we
will surely learn more and more about the depths of Clinton's
failings as a person.
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming more difficult by the minute to believe the
president's claim that his answers under oath to questions about
Lewinsky in a January deposition were ``legally accurate.'' And
it's increasingly difficult to believe that Clinton made no effort
to influence the testimony of Lewinsky or others who were dragged
into the sordid sex-and-lies scandal that has besieged the White
House for seven months.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the president has committed no ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' that would demand his removal from office, can we
continue to accept the leadership of a president who has admitted
to deliberately deceiving the American people, the judicial system,
his family, his devoted friends, his loyal advisers?
</P>
<P>
   This is a president who has confessed to a ``critical lapse in
judgment'' in his personal conduct. Can we now trust his judgment
in ordering military action against our nation's enemies?
</P>
<P>
   How do we know that Clinton is telling the truth when he says
that Thursday's attacks on terrorist facilities were a legitimate
and necessary use of America's military might?
</P>
<P>
   The attacks almost certainly were legitimate _ maybe even
urgently overdue. But if the man who ordered them is a known liar,
how can we be sure?
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Gallup's mistaken question about Americans' view of
the president ``as a person'' wasn't a mistake at all. It's a
question that far more Americans should have asked and answered
before extending Clinton's contract as commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
