<SLUG> BC-DAY-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARE CENTERS GIVING PARENTS A CHANCE TO SPY ON BABY VIA INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRENDAN LYONS  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALTA, N.Y. _ Clients of a day care center here will soon be
able to check on their children without leaving the home or office.
</P>
<P>
   The YMCA Day Care Center is among the growing number of centers
in the United States to provide video pictures of activity rooms
live over the Internet, allowing anxious parents some control after
they drop their children off for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the parents a chance to see their kid when they're at
work for 10 hours a day,'' said Kelly A. Decker, the director of
the center in this small town north of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   But critics fear the technology could be exploited by pedophiles
who could download images of the children. Some also fear it could
lull parents into a false sense of security because incidents can
still occur off-camera, such as in a bathroom. The audio-free
images also wouldn't disclose verbal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, as a parent, would never dream of allowing an image of my
child to be on the Internet,'' said Robert Ellis Smith, publisher
and editor of Privacy Journal, a monthly newsletter based in
Providence, R.I. ``I think parents are not as naive to think no
wrongdoing is not going to take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian R. Loomis, vice president of the Binghamton, N.Y.-based
Open House WorldWide, the company providing the service for the
Malta facility, insists the system is secure.
</P>
<P>
   Loomis explained that a private server line, similar to a phone
line, links the Malta day care center to the company's facility in
Binghamton. Parents of children can access the World Wide Web site
of live video feeds for $9.95 per week.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, grandparents or others who are pre-approved to use the
site are able to see images taken by the video monitor only in the
room where children are playing. At the Malta day care center, for
example, there are eight different rooms for children.
</P>
<P>
   The video feed actually takes a freeze-frame shot of a room
every 20 seconds, and is not a continual image like a normal video
camera.
</P>
<P>
   Parents access the Web site with a pass code, and then enter
another pass code to link onto the video feed that depicts their
child's day care room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people who can see the children in the center are
subscribing parents from that center,'' Loomis said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Web sites operated by Open House and similar
companies do not identify the name or location of the day care
center.
</P>
<P>
   If a hacker were able to break a code and access a video feed,
the person stealing the live images wouldn't know where the center
was located, said Frank Wagner, vice president of Watch Me!, a
Dallas company that offers a similar program at 22 day care centers
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Malta center has sent a letter to parents about the video
feeds and so far, no one has objected, Decker said. While parents
don't have to sign up for the service, they can't prevent their
child from being filmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one parent is really, really adamant about not having their
children (on video), then at that point maybe it's time that they
look for another center,'' Loomis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
