(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
SQUARE-DANCE (Los Angeles) _ While other clubs and organizations
are hanging on by a thread, losing members right and left, the
Trail Dusters square dance club is celebrating its 40th anniversary
Aug. 29 with more than 500 Valley members, and still taking in new
ones. By Carol Bidwell. 
. 
KROFFT-PUPPETS (Los Angeles) _ To anyone who grew up in the '70s,
the Krofft brothers' puppets were as inescapable a part of Saturday
morning TV as sugary breakfast cereals. H.R. Pufnstuf, Lidsville
and Sigmund &AMP; the Sea Monsters were among their creations of
puppetmasters Sid and Marty. At a one-of-a-kind auction Sunday at
the Beverly Hilton Hotel, they'll be auctioning off some of their
signature works. By Reed Johnson. 
. 
RATPAC-TV (Los Angeles) _ The year is 1960, and John F. Kennedy is
the president. His interaction with Frank Sinatra and the Mafia and
the floozies who go along with both are at the center of the
misleadingly titled HBO movie ``The Rat Pack.'' It would have been
more fitting to call the movie ``Frank &AMP; Jack.'' By Keith Marder. 
. 
BABY-TV (Los Angeles) _  Fox, the network that promises to be
daring and distinctive, kicks off its new season with ``Holding the
Baby,'' a formulaic sitcom that breaks less ground than a plastic
shovel. By Keith Marder. 
. 
SEVENTIES-TV (Los Angeles) _  You get to hear ``Love Will Keep Us
Together'' and ``Hooked on a Feeling,'' the lamps are filled with
lava, and the lips on the Farrah Fawcett poster move and sing a
song. ``That '70s Show'' is a special-effects-laden romp back in
time that does its best to re-create a more loudly dressed _ if not
innocent _ time. By Keith Marder. 
. 
