<HEADER>
A6147 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     08-21 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNGER THRIVES ON A SHORTAGE OF COMPASSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A stranger is traveling through town late one night when his car
crashes in a drenching rain.
</P>
<P>
   After a long string of motorists passes him by and he is near
death, he pens a note saying he would rather die than live in a
world so void of compassion.
</P>
<P>
   I read this story, or some version of it, nearly 20 years ago as
a student at the University of Southern Mississippi. The
particulars, of course, have faded with the passage of time. But
I've never forgotten the utter horror in it, or its message about
the human condition.
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of both the other day as I read a letter from
Dorothy Schilling, responding to a column I wrote recently about
the Tarrant Area Food Bank's plans to open a Kids Cafe and provide
a badly needed meal to children who might otherwise go to bed
hungry.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 45,000 children go hungry in Tarrant County, Texas,
on any given day; more than 12 million live in communities
nationwide. And now Schilling was asking me to talk about the
responsibility of their families to feed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in 1921,'' she wrote. ``My poor mother and father
thought it was their job to feed their family. Was this wrong? ...
If you have answers, please do answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is that there's nothing wrong with a mother and
father taking responsibility for their family. Nor is it wrong, as
Schilling suggests, to expect others to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   I feel that way every time I see an able-bodied man or woman on
the street with a sign that reads, ``Will work for food.'' I want
to scream, because the longer he stands there in the middle of the
road, off somebody's payroll, the more taxes I will have to pay and
the longer I will have to struggle to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   But in a world where little children go to bed hungry, where
some even dine from Dumpsters, I find it hard to talk about family
responsibility. No sooner have I gotten the words off my lips then
I am reminded that there, but for the grace of God, go I.
</P>
<P>
   When I'm able to confront my own human frailties, the answer
becomes much more complicated, because then I'm willing to think
with something other than my head.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't grow up during the Depression, but I lived in a family
that knew hard times, knew hunger like a best friend. We also knew
what being responsible meant, and that it went far beyond taking
care of ``us and ours.'' Responsibility meant loving your neighbor
as yourself, giving them water when they thirsted, providing food,
shelter and clothing when they had none.
</P>
<P>
   And now, because that family taught me the importance of sharing
(even though more often than not, we were on the receiving end), I
am constantly amazed at how God blesses me to do much with the
little that I have.
</P>
<P>
   Responsibility? Jesus said that when we do unto the least of
these, we've done it unto him.
</P>
<P>
   You only have to look at my daughters to know they've never
missed a meal. Recently, as Asha led us in prayer before leaving
home one morning, she thanked God for food, ``because you know we
Staples women love to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   As often as we can, we donate nonperishable food items to those
who are less fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   And yet every night in Tarrant County, in this country and the
world, children goes to bed hungry. I can't speak for Schilling,
but I'd rather die than live in a world that didn't care enough to
take responsibility for that.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can e-mail her at: gbs(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
