<HEADER>
A6149 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEVENTIES-TV-LADN     08-21 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEVENTIES-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FOX-Y TAKE ON THE '70S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; You get to hear ``Love Will Keep Us Together''
and ``Hooked on a Feeling,'' the lamps are filled with lava, and
the lips on the Farrah Fawcett poster move and sing a song. What
more can you ask for?
</P>
<P>
   ``That '70s Show'' is a special-effects-laden romp back in time
that does its best to re-create a more loudly dressed _ if not
innocent _ time.
</P>
<P>
   The team that created ``3rd Rock From the Sun'' is back with
another trippy show, chock-full of fantasy sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Point Place, Wis., the Foremans, Pinciottis and Hydes
don't live far from Milwaukee, where the Cunninghams, Webers and
Malphs lived 20 years earlier in fictional neighborhoods born on
TV. It is the first _ and most blatant _ attempt to take us back
two decades, a mini theme of the new television season.
</P>
<P>
   The date: May 17, 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The location: Eric Foreman's basement.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-age men get permanents, kids steal beer, grown-ups wear
gold Italian horns around their necks, teen-agers make fun of ``The
Brady Bunch,'' and all of the carpets are shag.
</P>
<P>
   The kids _ including Taft High School student Wilmer Valderrama,
who plays a foreign exchange student _ and parents in this show
often mock each other in ways that are difficult to describe, but
worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   The look of the show is all '70s, from kitchen appliances to
fashions to hairstyles.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some controversy over some content in the pilot,
such as the 16- and 17-year-olds drinking and apparently smoking
pot. In one scene, the kids have an inane, obviously stoned
conversation in a smoke-hazed room. Eric then goes up to speak with
his family while the walls in the background move in a psychedelic
manner.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is some high school students drink beer and smoke
marijuana. Depiction of such behavior on the show, while not
glorifying the use, adds to the show's honesty, as does its
portrayal of young love, which the program dissects like a frog in
a biology lab.
</P>
<P>
   There are many fabulous pop-culture references, such as the kids
taking the Vista Cruiser wagon to a Todd Rundgren concert, people
dancing the hustle, KISS posters, a game of Yahtzee and teen-age
boys wishing they lived in Hooterville.
</P>
<P>
   Some will like to relive the memories ``The '70s Show'' evokes.
Those too young may be happy they never lived there.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6150 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-TV-LADN     08-21 0268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABY' A FAR CRY FROM CLEVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Fox, the network that promises to be daring and
distinctive, kicks off its new season with ``Holding the Baby,'' a
formulaic sitcom that breaks less ground than a plastic shovel.
</P>
<P>
   The baby should fire his agent for getting him into this mess.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called comedy is about a guy who works, but his marriage
didn't; his brother who works too little; his boss who wants him to
work more; a nanny who doesn't want to work; and a kid who causes a
lot of people a lot of work.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of weeks, when Fox drops ``Holding the Baby,'' a lot
of people should be looking for work.
</P>
<P>
   The acting in this show is often forced, the premise is
contrived and the characters are not believable.
</P>
<P>
   The baby, however, is cute. And, the oldest cast member, Ron
Leibman, who plays boss Stan Peterson, steals every scene he's in.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Stiles (Eddie McClintock) plays a struggling actor/drunk
who is somewhat of a babe magnet for no apparent reason. Kelly
O'Malley (Jennifer Westfeldt) plays a chatty, opinionated grad
student who berates someone she wants to work for because he bought
a carpet made by Third World sweatshop workers.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the show is Gordon Stiles (Jon Patrick Walker),
whose wife leaves him after meeting a man at a women's retreat. She
has moved to Tibet and Gordon is left .... holding the baby.
</P>
<P>
   The show is all too predictable. Not even a mother could love
``Holding the Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
