A6152 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAX-FASHION-LADN     08-21 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAX-FASHION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING L.A. DESIGN TO THE MAX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Los Angeles fashion designer Max Azria soon will
be the new owner of the famous French couture house of Herve Leger.
</P>
<P>
   Azria, a past California Designer of the Year whose BCBG line of
contemporary mens' and womens' fashions is expected to reach $200
million by the end of the year, told the Daily News this week that
the transaction will be complete in September. He would not
disclose the selling price, but earlier this month he announced
that he had reached an agreement with GH Mumm &AMP; Cie, a subsidiary
of the Seagram Co. LTD, to buy its 95 percent stake of Leger.
</P>
<P>
   The French company, whose clients include supermodel Cindy
Crawford, has been losing money, but Azria will work to turn it
around and double its volume. Currently, it is $10 million, with 40
percent of its business from sales in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the local fashion industry has been buzzing with
speculations that Azria would be moving his operation to Paris.
According to Azria, ``I have liked this designer for many years,
and I had the opportunity to buy it, so I did. This is a dream come
true for me. I cannot ask for better in life than to have my own
business and also own the house of Herve Leger. But I will be the
director, not the designer, and I have no plans to leave Los
Angeles. Ever. I will die here.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the designer says the relationship will create what he
calls a ``global synergy'' which will benefit both companies. Not
only does Azria expect it to increase sales for Leger, but he
expects that its French connection will help BCBG open boutiques in
Paris, Milan and London in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   BCBG clothing and shoes already are sold in numerous department
stores, including Macy's and Neiman Marcus, as well as in 13 BCBG
boutiques throughout Southern California. None of his businesses
are in the San Fernando Valley, but Azria says he is looking at the
community of Calabasas as a future location.
</P>
<P>
   Azria also owns Parallel, To the Max and Maxime clothing lines.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6154 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RATPACK-TV-LADN     08-21 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATPACK-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGERS IN THE NIGHTCLUB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; The president is a handsome philanderer who is a
little too close to Hollywood and takes a lot of policy advice from
a family member.
</P>
<P>
   The story is true and extremely familiar. Only in this scenario,
Linda Tripp and Kenneth Starr are nowhere in sight. Monica Lewinsky
and Gennifer Flowers are replaced by Marilyn Monroe and Judith
Campbell; Ted Danson is replaced by Frank Sinatra; and Hillary
Rodham Clinton is replaced by Bobby and Joe Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 1960, and John F. Kennedy is the president in
question.
</P>
<P>
   His interaction with Sinatra and the Mafia and the floozies who
go along with both are at the center of the misleadingly titled HBO
movie ``The Rat Pack.'' It would have been more fitting to call the
movie ``Frank &AMP; Jack.''
</P>
<P>
   The name Rat Pack conjures up images of ring-a-ding,
koo-koo-crazy times when a bunch of guys drank together, smoked
together and womanized together in between delighting America with
song and dance, sprinkled with racist barbs.
</P>
<P>
   There is some of that in ``The Rat Pack,'' an altogether
watchable film, but not enough to warrant the name.
</P>
<P>
   Mantegna's Martin delivers the best line in this regard when he
tells Bishop, ``The whole world is drunk, and we're just the
cocktail of the moment, pally. One of these days, everybody's gonna
wake up with a heckuva hangover, down two aspirin with a glass of
tomato juice and wonder what the hell all the fuss was about.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, we get no idea what enabled this uncommon bond and
brought these five entirely different entertainers together. There
was Sinatra (Ray Liotta), the volatile Alpha member; always-cool
Dean Martin (Joe Mantegna); omni-talented Sammy Davis Jr. (Don
Cheadle); Brit twit actor Peter Lawford (Angus Macfadyen); and the
reigning King of Zing, Joey Bishop (Bobby Slayton).
</P>
<P>
   The group dynamic is glossed over, as is the reason that these
men worked so well together on stage and in films.
</P>
<P>
   You are asked to suspend disbelief for a couple of hours. The
actors, for the most part, don't look or sound like the men they
play, nor are they trying to. And the beginning scene is a little
hokey, with an aging Sinatra standing in the wings, waiting to go
on stage, Jack Daniel's in one hand, cigarette in the other,
repeating twice, ``I miss my guys.''
</P>
<P>
   But the transformation to the Frank of the late '50s and early
'60s is slick, and screenwriter Kario Salem and director Rob Cohen
team to tell the story they set out to, even if it wasn't the one
they have advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra is infatuated with the idea of being a pally of the
president. His ex-friend Lawford becomes a friend again after he
marries Kennedy's sister, Patricia, and is able to be the
matchmaker between politician and crooner.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the ``Brother-in-Lawford'' character gets a bit too much
screen time in comparison to his place in Rat Pack history.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedys use Sinatra's mob ties to help rig the election. As
it turns out, these same ties _ and Sinatra's stubborn loyalty _
lead to his demise with the first family.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Liotta plays Sinatra's roller coaster of emotions
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an 18-karat manic depressive,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Cheadle, who had to learn how to play drums, twirl guns and tap
dance to play ``Mr. Wonderful,'' is impressive, and Mantegna does a
good job as the suave Martin, despite his lack of matinee-idol
looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank &AMP; Jack'' is worth a watch, even if it is called ``The
Rat Pack.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
