<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT SHOW ABOUT THE '70S IS ALL RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, the title.
</P>
<P>
   Producers Bonnie and Terry Turner tossed around dozens of names
for their '70s-based sitcom, beginning Sunday night on Fox, and
nothing stuck. Not ``Reelin' in the Years,'' not ``Feelin'
Alright,'' not ``The Kids Are All Right.'' Frustrated and a little
fried, the producing partners took the name that was right under
their noses.
</P>
<P>
   Test audiences could never remember the show's title and would
finally mutter in frustration, ``You know, that '70s show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody kept calling it that for so long that we started to
say to ourselves, you know, `I'm going to be over at the '70s
show,''' says Terry Turner, whose writing credits include such
offbeat projects as ``Wayne's World'' and ``The Brady Bunch
Movie.'' ``Finally, we just gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That '70s Show'' (7:30 p.m. Sunday) is getting an aggressive
push by Fox, largely because the network is convinced that it will
be a hit. That's a bold forecast, even for a network that had one
of only two new hit shows from last season, the Emmy-nominated
dramedy ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   A snappy, funny and lively treatment of '70s living stuffed into
a sitcom format, ``That '70's Show'' comes from the creative brains
of the producers whose other high-concept comedy with an odd name
(''3rd Rock From the Sun'') and premise (aliens set up camp on
Earth) was a pleasantly surprising success for NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is so giddy about ``That '70s Show'' that it wedged it
between ``The Simpsons'' and ``The X-Files,'' and dispatched its
first two episodes to the press, figuring that early buzz would
generate a following before the annual onslaught of new entries.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1976, the series follows Eric Foreman (Topher Grace) as
he navigates the treacherous waters of the teen years. Lanky but
baby-faced, smart but unsure, Eric leads a small band of buddies
who lean on him for approval and who find his parents' spacious
basement the perfect chill-out zone.
</P>
<P>
   His pals are a tight-knit group of misfits who could probably be
friends only with one another; all are unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   Mila Kunis is Jackie, a spoiled loudmouth; Ashton Kutcher is
Kelso, Jackie's boyfriend, Eric's best bud and something of a
gullible nut case; Danny Masterson is Hyde, the resident conspiracy
theorist (Hyde on ``Petticoat Junction'': ``Does it bother anybody
else that these women live in Hooterville?''); Wilmer Valderrama is
Fex, the naive foreign-exchange student; and Laura Prepon is Donna,
Eric's childhood friend and, judging from the first two episodes,
involved in a touchy-feely story line with Eric.
</P>
<P>
   Adding extraordinarily to the mix are Eric's parents, Kitty and
Red, played by Debra Jo Rupp and Kurtwood Smith, who does such
subtle work here it appears he's not even acting. His voice _ a
deep monotone usually reserved for big-screen bad guys _ slides
from elation to frustration with only the slightest tonal change.
He's hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '70's Show'' is filled with disco music and pop-culture
references, but for the Turners, the plastic garishness of '70s
fashions and decor is more than a matter of camp nostalgia. It
speaks to the ironic innocence of what may be the last moment in
this country when people simply did what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of Sunday night's episode, in which the teens
sit around getting stoned. It's actually quite a funny scene,
particularly when Eric is talking to his parents while the walls
behind them dip and dance.
</P>
<P>
   The producers agonized over whether to keep it, finally deciding
to let the chips fall where they may. ``I think we would be
criticized if we ignored it and criticized if we did it,'' Bonnie
Turner says. ``It happened. Kids did it, adults did it. We feel
we've written _ hopefully what we've done _ is portrayed the '70s
in a very honest form.''
</P>
<P>
   Also new Sunday night:
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Stiles (Jon Patrick Walker) is in trouble. And from the
looks of it, so is his sitcom. ``Holding the Baby'' (6:30 p.m.) is
a standard-issue comedy about a workaholic learning how to parent
an infant after his wife skips town.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly O'Malley (Jennifer Westfeldt) is the cutie-pie graduate
student who ends up as the kid's part-time nanny. There's also
Jimmy, (Eddie McClintock) Gordon's freeloading brother, who's
perpetually between acting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Press materials stress that the three may not have much
experience in handling a baby, but ``working together, they may
just add up to be one great parent.'' I'd settle for one decent
sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH CHECKING OUT THIS WEEK:
</P>
<P>
   Although often overshadowed by other groups that emerged in the
'60s, the Beach Boys have remained a part of American pop culture.
``Endless Harmony: The Beach Boys and Their Music'' (8 p.m. Sunday
night, VH1) documents the group's music, including recent and
vintage interview footage in which Brian Wilson, Mike Love, Bruce
Johnston and Carl and Dennis Wilson talk about the inspiration
behind their songs and how they were created.
</P>
<P>
   ``Endless'' was researched for a year and features footage from
collectors as well as from Dennis Wilson. ``Seventy percent of
these clips haven't been seen before,'' producer Stephanie Bennett
says. ``It's great stuff.'' It is.
</P>
<P>
   ELSEWHERE:
</P>
<P>
   Roma Downey (''Touched by an Angel'') hosts ``Before Your Eyes:
Don't Take My Daddy'' (9 p.m. Monday, CBS) a documentary about
three American women, all with young children, who are dealing with
the threat that their husbands, natives of Northern Ireland, may be
deported because of allegations that they have ties to the Irish
Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids of Survival: The Life and Art of Tim Rollins &AMP; K.O.S,'' a
``Reel Life'' documentary on Cinemax, follows one man's crusade to
help at-risk kids through art. Set in the south Bronx, ``Kids of
Survival'' (5:30 p.m. Tuesday on Cinemax) is one of the success
stories we don't hear enough of, and it shows the difficulties of
running unconventional programs. With few large-scale corporations
willing to pitch in, the workshop is entirely funded by the sale of
the group's art. It's not always easy, as ``Kids of Survival''
reveals.
</P>
<P>
   The daytime soaper ``Sunset Beach'' gets a prime-time showing
Friday on NBC with a story line said to be ``easily accessible'' to
those who aren't regular viewers. Hmmm. Better be, since it airs at
7 p.m. The daily series, still trying to find a footing in the
ratings, revisits a previous ``Sunset Beach'' tragedy that did
fairly well _ about a tidal wave smashing into a cruise ship. When
all else fails, drum up a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
