<SLUG> BC-SAMARITAN-FIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD SAMARITAN FENDS OFF KNIFE ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE HUNGER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A couple of would-be carjackers picked the wrong
target Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sanchez, 49, said he stopped to help two young men who
flagged him down as they peered under the hood of a dirty white
Camaro on a San Antonio street.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of receiving thanks for his trouble, Sanchez, found
himself staring at the glint of a knife blade pointed at his chest.
One of the men cursed at Sanchez and demanded his silver, 1997 Ford
F-150 pickup, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to hand him the keys, but he lunged at me,'' he
said. ``He was going to take me, so I took him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez said he grabbed the man's arm and pushed it toward the
ground. The action deflected the knife away from his chest, but
into his leg.
</P>
<P>
   With the weapon still in the assailant's hand, Sanchez said, he
turned the knife and thrust it deep into the abdomen of the
attacker. After seeing his companion get stabbed, the second man
started the Camaro and began to speed away.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the wounded man jumped through the front
passenger window of the Camaro with the knife still lodged in his
abdomen, Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle left Sanchez with four stitches above his right
knee and a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of grew up on the streets,'' said Sanchez, a compact
man with a cheerful demeanor and streaks of gray in his dark hair.
``I didn't grow up with a silver spoon in my mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. John Leal of the San Antonio police said officers notified
emergency rooms citywide to be on the lookout for he wounded man.
Leal said the suspects were in their early 20s.
</P>
</TEXT>
