<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6211 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRIDGE-TEACHER-art-$A     08-21 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-TEACHER-art-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A SURE BET: THE BRIDGE CLUB HAS BECOME COOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 23)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If it seems odd that there's a framed article about
Isaac Mizrahi at the entrance to the Manhattan Bridge Club, a musty
place bustling with Upper West Side retirees, then you've got a
thing or two to learn about style-conscious New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   No, the place doesn't turn into a lounge at night. And the chef
who makes lunch ($2, prix fixe) and dinner isn't famous. But
Mizrahi, along with the socialites Nina Griscom and Sandy Hill and
the fashion photographer Wayne Maser, have beaten a path to the
Manhattan Bridge Club in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   They, and many other unlikely converts to bridge, have sought
out Jeff Bayone, the charismatic, straight-shooting owner of the
club. Tall, slightly stooped, with strawberry blond hair and an
endearingly droopy moustache, Bayone is the master of this
universe. On a sunny Tuesday afternoon, the dowdy club was jammed
with mostly older Manhattanites fond of telling visitors that
they've been playing bridge since the war. (They meant World War I,
not II, and not all of them were joking.)
</P>
<P>
   A mentor to seniors with plenty of time to build their master
points, Bayone, along with a fellow teacher, Tom Ng, has also
attracted a new crowd recently. It looks as if bridge is enjoying
something of a hip resurgence, along with pedal pushers and
mid-century Richard Neutra houses. The newcomers play at night,
drawn in no small part by the retro ambiance of the game they once
watched parents or grandparents play, with cigarettes and highballs
in hand.
</P>
<P>
   On Mondays, when Bayone teaches beginner classes, chances are
good that there will be a 30-ish editor from Conde Nast learning to
bid at the same table with a Florida-bound pharmacist who is eager
to learn the game, which is still a staple of retirement
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Equal parts teddy bear, drill sergeant and Jewish mother,
Bayone, 50, badgers his students, yells at them and hugs them.
</P>
<P>
   The first paragraph of a book he has just written, ``It's
Bridge, Baby: How to Be a Player in 10 Easy Lessons'' (Riverhead,
1998), reads: ``Picture this. I am 6 feet 4 inches tall. One
hundred ninety pounds. I have a moustache. My name is Jeff. And I
am your mother.''
</P>
<P>
   The book offers a combination of tough love, motivational
language and straightforward instruction. His club has the same
no-fuss charm. The sunny, wood-paneled playing rooms, a kitchen and
an office occupy the top floor of the Olcott residential hotel on
West 72nd Street. Framed Collier's magazine covers line the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Before classes, Charles Nurse, the club's manager, sets out a
tray of midafternoon snacks (licorice sticks, vegetables and dip,
Oreo cookies, peanuts) on a Formica-top table. Nothing fancy.
That's how the students like it. When Bayone sauntered into the
room last Tuesday, the 12 intermediate students who sat patiently
practicing at the felt-top tables fell silent like an awe-struck
first-day kindergarten class.
</P>
<P>
   Bayone _ in gold-rimmed glasses, gold bracelet,
green-and-blue-plaid polo shirt and blue slacks _ sauntered over to
Muriel Sherwood's group to ponder the cards. He looked over one
woman's shoulder and then announced her hand to the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she has eight diamonds, she has 11 tricks,'' he said. He
set his steely gaze upon Ms. Sherwood. ``What do you have?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sherwood, a retired secretary who lives in Manhattan,
thought for a moment. He pointed at one card in her hand, wrinkled
his brow and glared playfully at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the master has spoken,'' she said, as Bayone glided
silently on to the next table.
</P>
<P>
   Bayone has been teaching at the club, one of about six bridge
clubs in Manhattan, since 1976, when he bought it. He estimates
that he has turned more than 3,000 novices into competitive
players. Does he think of himself as a bridge guru?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think of myself that way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But before you could say, ``Four no-trump,'' Ms. Sherwood
interjected, ``He has a very philosophical approach.'' With one
hand holding her cards and the other picking at a dish of peanuts,
she explained: ``He's not like a teacher. He wants you to
understand the concept. Bridge, you see, is about intellect and
memory. It's not in just how the cards lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kamlot, a manager of Broadway shows who plays at
Manhattan Bridge, said that Bayone's secret is that he doesn't
overcomplicate the game. ``He's very straightforward, and he's got
this method called `kiss,''' Kamlot said. Kiss? ``Yes. `Keep it
simple, stupid,''' Kamlot said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Older styles of bridge instruction encouraged memorization of
long lists of maneuvers. Bayone just wants his students to play.
``Young people are attracted to bridge because it's fast and it's
social,'' he said, his face shining. ``Chess is a two-hour
struggle. In bridge, each hand is about seven and a half minutes.
It's about as fast-paced as you could have. You can play 40 games
in a night, and every hand is a new adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Bayone was back at the club preparing for the week's
big social night, when more than 60 players of all levels come to
play, paying $10 admission. He offered the secret of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have learned to be mellow and adaptable,'' he said. ``I have
to be the policeman, the director of activities, the final judge,
the referee, and sometimes I have to walk over to a table that's
acting up and say: `What? Do I have to be the kindergarten teacher,
too?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
