<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-GAZA-2TAKES-$A     08-21 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GAZA-2TAKES-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL BAN IN GAZA REGION PUSHES PALESTINIANS' IRE TO `CRITICAL'
POINT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 23) 
(Eds.: Subheds included) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUSH KATIF, Gaza Strip _ A donkey cart carrying Palestinian
women draped in long black veils hurries across the highway, then
resumes its slow journey down a side road cut through sand dunes.
</P>
<P>
   After the women cross the main highway, an Israeli pickup with
yellow license plates speeds down the road. Yellow-plated cars on
their way to the Israeli settlement of Neve Dakalim follow.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Palestinians have been barred from traveling on this
stretch of highway in Gush Katif, the southern region of the Gaza
Strip that remains under Israeli control. Israel says the ban is
necessary to safeguard the area's 6,000 Israeli settlers, most of
whom live along the road.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiators agreed to give Israel control of this
part of Gaza _ and, by extension, the right to impose travel
restrictions _ when they signed interim peace accords in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, nearly 80 percent of Gaza _ which Israel
took from Egypt in the 1967 war _ was handed over to the
Palestinian Authority. Palestinians, who hope to create their own
state in Gaza and in the West Bank, had assumed that Israeli
settlements would eventually disappear. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Three years after the interim peace agreement was signed, the
scene along the highway in Gush Katif has come to symbolize what
ordinary Palestinians despise about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like the occupation is still here,'' says Marwan
Najjar, one of a few thousand Palestinian farmers who live in the
area. ``It interferes in our life, in our work, in our land. Even
roads are separate, and this is not right.''
</P>
<P>
   As peace talks falter and tensions rise, the travel restrictions
also highlight the &UR;  &LR; dangers posed by an arrangement _ meant to be
temporary _ that forces longtime enemies to live side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, as frustration over the travel restrictions mounted,
a Palestinian minister demanded access to the highway reserved for
Israeli settlers. Within minutes, Israeli soldiers and Palestinian
police were training their weapons on each other. The 12-hour
standoff ended peacefully, however.
</P>
<P>
   For 17 months now, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators have been
unable to drag peace talks out of a deep freeze, which began with a
dispute over a new Jewish neighborhood in Jerusalem, despite
several attempts to agree on the scope of a long-overdue Israeli
troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In a scenario that has changed little since the two sides
embarked on a new path toward peace, Israeli settlers and
Palestinians continue to squabble over land, plot by plot, parcel
by parcel.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's army is now preparing for the possibility of a war that
military analysts may come in 1999 if Palestinians make good on
their threat to declare an independent state in the West Bank and
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a critical moment,'' says Yaron Ezrahi, a political
scientist at Jerusalem's Hebrew University. ``If there is not going
to be withdrawal, there is going to be a wave of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`I MUST FOLLOW ORDERS' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a stretch of beach in Gush Katif, four Israeli soldiers and
four Palestinian policemen emerge from separate orange-flagged
jeeps to take a short break from the rounds of their joint patrol.
</P>
<P>
   When the joint patrols first started in 1994, something akin to
camaraderie developed. Palestinians and Israelis ate in the same
mess halls, and they got to know each other.
</P>
<P>
   Now during breaks, they stand in separate groups around jeeps
parked in the sand. Few words pass between them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, arguments break out. Last month, an Israeli soldier
was hospitalized with minor wounds after getting into a fight with
a Palestinian counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to like my work,'' says a 25-year-old Palestinian
policeman assigned to a joint patrol. ``Now I do it because I must
follow orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers and police charged with keeping the peace sometimes
take sides in squabbles between Israeli settlers and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, 15 Israeli soldiers and 60 Palestinians, many of
them policemen, were killed when high-pitched battles broke out
over a controversial archaeological tunnel in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the flare-ups have been less deadly but no less
tense. Nightly news programs often show soldiers and police
pushing, shouting and pointing weapons at each other following
incidents like one earlier this month in Gush Katif in which
Palestinians tore down a fence built by settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians question how long the joint patrols can go on in
the absence of progress in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do my job,'' says the policemen. ``The problem is that I
feel that I am enforcing a way of living that's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SETTLERS HUNKERING DOWN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just inside the steel gates of Neve Dakalim, the largest of 17
Israeli settlements in Gush Katif, children's music played in a
small zoo wafts through the air. On a manicured lawn next to a bank
and a supermarket, Naomi, a 28-year-old settler, talks about why
she moved here with her husband two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's important for the security of Israel for us to
live here,'' explains Naomi, who declines to give her last name.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we weren't here, the army wouldn't be here, and it would be
easier for the Palestinians to establish a state,'' she says. ``But
it's our country. They have enough Arab states. I don't think we
should give them another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Israeli settlers have hunkered down since most of Gaza came
under Palestinian rule. Like Naomi, many settlers came here out of
conviction that their presence would help stifle Palestinian
independence.
</P>
<P>
   On Gaza's highways, settlers take extraordinary precautions,
using only certain roads and sometimes traveling in convoys
escorted by the army.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the settlements, even petty crime is rare.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Neve Dakalim, the dust and grime of Gaza's crowded,
squalid chaos are forgotten. Besides the zoo, the Israeli
settlement boasts a high school, recreational facilities, a
synagogue, a seminary college and a botanical garden, all ensconced
behind a barbed wire fence guarded by soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   As most settlers see it, they have a right to live in Gaza and
the army has an obligation to protect them. If they evacuate Gaza,
they say, an Israeli retreat from the West Bank will inevitably
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Unless security deteriorates to unbearable levels, few settlers
seem willing to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we see that it will be insecure for our children, that will
be a reason to leave,'' Naomi says. ``But now I think it's a great
place to raise children, here in the country. We don't even really
need to go out anywhere. Everything we need is in here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`IT IS STILL PART OF GAZA' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not far from Neve Dakalim, past banana trees and tomato fields,
teen-age Palestinian girls play volleyball at a makeshift summer
camp set up in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Run by Zenab al-Wazir, the sister of slain Palestinian guerrilla
Abu Jihad, the camp, like most things in Gaza, is rife with
political symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Even the camp's name _ Statehood and Return _ is saturated with
meaning. Independence and the right of return for Palestinian
refugees displaced by wars with Israel have become almost sacred
demands.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the volleyball nets, two shrines to ``martyrs'' who died
in clashes with Israeli soldiers display the faces of young
Palestinian men. Large banners read, ``Jerusalem is the capital of
Palestine.''
</P>
<P>
   Camps like this have sprung up all over Gaza, even in Gush
Katif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still part of Gaza,'' says al-Wazir, the camp's
director.
</P>
<P>
   Her words speak volumes about the way Palestinians view the
Israeli settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Most consider the red-roofed houses as temporary intrusions on
Palestinian land. They view the settlers who live in them as
nuisances who use security as a pretext to bring Israeli soldiers
to Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   If Israel wants real peace, they say, the settlements will have
to go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE PRICE OF PEACE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Peleg understands the Palestinian viewpoint. She is one
of a handful of Gaza's Jewish citizens who came to Kfar Yam, a tiny
beach settlement near Neve Dakalim, for the quiet aesthetic life
that it offered. She espouses none of the religious or
nationalistic beliefs that brought most settlers to Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here, because I wanted a quiet place where I can
work,'' says Peleg, who paints and makes pottery. ``If I could pick
all of this up and put it somewhere else, I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Peleg says the government should offer aid to settlers who want
to leave Gaza but are trapped by mortgage payments and other debts.
</P>
<P>
   If help were available, she and her husband, Nir, could afford
to leave their greenhouse, where they grow carnations for export to
Europe, and begin again somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Peleg and others launched a campaign to try to
persuade the government to compensate settlers who wanted to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with peace negotiations stalled, the demands for
compensation are dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the most vocal settlers moved out of Gaza without
compensation. Others, like Peleg, are quietly waiting to see what
negotiations will bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a paradox,'' Peleg says. ``We want peace, but real peace
would mean the settlements would have to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will cost me my way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the
Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
