<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6228 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORGOTTENCOWBOYS-1000     08-21 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORGOTTENCOWBOYS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY BOOKS AND MOVIES OVERLOOKED FORGOTTEN COWBOYS OF SOUTH
TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REFUGIO, Texas _ The image of the Texas cowboy has been deeply
stamped in our minds: tall, weathered, rugged, Marlboroesque _ and
white.
</P>
<P>
   That image is dishonest.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Wayne wouldn't be nothing beside of us,'' Nathaniel
Youngblood, a black cowboy from the Texas coastal plains, was fond
of saying. ``They just didn't take our picture. John Wayne and Tim
Holt, Durango Kid, and that other one _ Gene Autry, oh, no. They
ain't nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the coastal bend of Texas, nearly a third of the cowboys
pushing cattle up the Texas trails in the 1840s were black. Roughly
another third were Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   They never enjoyed a place in the prevailing cowboy myth _ these
weren't flashy rodeo cowboys, or the silver-saddled cowboys of the
movies _ but they helped forge ranching empires along the coastal
plains.
</P>
<P>
   They were poor people from meager beginnings _ slavery primarily
_ but they learned to work cattle on the muggy landscape. They
lived on the ranches, raised their families there, worked tooth and
nail, and accrued an uncommon respect.
</P>
<P>
   Their descendants remain there today, a century and a half later
_ the last of their kind.
</P>
<P>
   Another generation works the ranches now, but they drive trucks
from brick homes in town to the pastures. They haul their horses in
trailers. And there aren't as many of them as there once were.
Technology has wiped out some of the jobs. Many, including the sons
and daughters of the old black cowboys, have found better pay and
benefits in town. The work is easier, too.
</P>
<P>
   Toney Lott is one of the original cowboys, one of only a dozen
or so left in this flat, brushy country just off the Gulf Coast. At
92, he is the oldest.
</P>
<P>
   When Lott talks about his early days around the ranches of South
Texas, he insists that his Bible be close by. It serves as proof
he's telling the truth, he says.
</P>
<P>
   It is by God's grace that he's still alive, Lott says. Wild
cattle, mean horses and bad weather have all chipped away at him.
He started out dirt poor in the backwoods of the San Antonio River
bottoms, but says the Lord's hand left him rich in pride and
memories.
</P>
<P>
   Lott is sitting at the O'Connor ranch with fellow cowboys E.J.
Garza, 80; K.J. Oliver, 84; and Willie Brown, 69. Both Garza and
Oliver were born on ranches and began their cowboy careers before
they reached 10. Garza left ranching at 15 to follow the rodeo
circuit but was back within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Garza and Oliver are retired now; Brown works for the sheriff's
department in Refugio.
</P>
<P>
   Lott glances around the air-conditioned room and gathers his
thoughts. Then, with a voice that comes from deep within and
explodes as a shout, he proclaims: ``The Lord was the one that got
us here. I remember a time when we couldn't be around no white
folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you all know we'd be sitting out there under a tree
somewhere,'' he says, shaking a finger at the rest of the group.
``The white people be in here, the Spanish-speaking people out
there with us under that tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``But see how the Lord fixed it? We're all together now. Look
where we come from.''
</P>
<P>
   CRYIN' FOR DAYLIGHT TO COME: Where they come from is the vast,
humid, brushy land in and around Refugio, Goliad, Victoria and San
Patricio counties. It is an old area where cattle and cattlemen
have worked for centuries. They were always different from their
northern counterparts _ never all white, always heavily Spanish and
African.
</P>
<P>
   At first, in the 1700s, the men who worked the cattle were
``vaqueros'' of Spanish and Indian descent, called ``mestizos.''
Later, there were ``mulattos,'' African and Indian.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico wanted the land populated, both to provide commerce and
to establish a barrier against unfriendly Indians who often raided
deep into its territory. By the 1820s, the Spanish were promising
huge land grants to those who would come.
</P>
<P>
   The whites who first settled here were Catholic colonists from
Ireland. Eventually, others came from the coastal regions of
Louisiana, Mississippi and Alabama in the 1820s and 1830s. They
brought with them their whips, dogs and slaves to work the cattle.
</P>
<P>
   South Texas, though, was far more vast than the small pastures
they were accustomed to. The raw-boned, half-wild cattle were
unlike the Eastern breeds they worked. The whips and dogs were
overwhelmed; slaves on foot were useless.
</P>
<P>
   The slaves, watching the ``vaqueros,'' learned to work
horseback. They continued, generation to generation. Families
intermarried; Spanish, black and Anglo heritages became
intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all mixed in,'' says Oliver, who went to work in 1929,
the same day his father drowned while swimming cattle across a
river. ``Some white, Mexicans, blacks ... we all eat at the same
table, and we all looked out for each other's interest. You never
know who's going to get in a jam, and you had to have somebody help
you out. You couldn't walk around with a chip on your shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   No one had much, he says, but what they had they shared. If one
man had a biscuit and the other had corn bread, they divided it
evenly. If one had a nickel, they all had a nickel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were raised together,'' Lott says. ``I didn't get no higher
than the third grade, and I didn't learn anything then. Listen. I
ain't lying, we were very poor people. Me and Papa had to go
hunting for coons, polecats and possums to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   The cowboys didn't get any richer by working cattle. When Lott
started, the pay was 50 cents a day. By the time Oliver and Garza
came along a few years later, the daily wage had inched up to
$1.25.
</P>
<P>
   They all worked the same ranches _ the O'Brien, the O'Connor,
the McFaddin. Those ranches are still there today, though they are
known as much for their oil production as for their cattle. The
O'Connor, established in 1836, still covers a half-million acres
and is still run by the O'Connor family.
</P>
<P>
   Louise O'Connor, a fifth-generation family member, published a
book on cowboys and ranchers in the area. She called it ``Cryin'
for Daylight,'' after what one cowhand told her: ``We just loved to
work cattle so much we'd just be sittin' around cryin' for daylight
to come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the hours you worked,'' says Brown. ``You just
worked until the job was done. Sometimes you would get your horses
ready before breakfast.'' It might be dark when you returned. That
was working ``from can't to can't'' _ you can't see when you get
up, and you can't see when you lay down.
</P>
<P>
   Like all cowboys, those on the coast got beans to eat, but most
of the time they were out in the pasture and had to make do with
strings of tasso. ``When you kill a beef, you string it; make
strings out of the meat,'' Brown explains. ``Then you would trim
most of the fat off, leave some on it. Every morning you would hang
it out on a line, just high enough so the dogs couldn't get to it.
...
</P>
<P>
   ``You could soak it in water all night, then the next morning
fry it and take it with you, or make a stew out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The longer the meat dried in the burning sun, the longer it
would last. The cowboys coated it with cornmeal and pepper _ not
for seasoning, but to keep the flies away.
</P>
<P>
   USING THE FRONT DOOR: Working cattle on the coastal plains was
like working cattle anywhere; the meanest of the steers would break
from the herds and try to hook the horses with their horns. The
bulls would stand on their back feet and fight a rope. Cows had to
be doctored daily against screwworms, and the whole herd had to be
dipped for ticks.
</P>
<P>
   In the pasture, all the cowboys were equal. Only the top hands
stood out, and they had loftier positions because of their ability
to rope, or ride or handle cattle. Color had nothing to do with a
man's stature.
</P>
<P>
   In town, it wasn't the same.
</P>
<P>
   Lott remembers the time a calf kicked him in the head and
knocked him out. James Welder, the boss at the Welder ranch, loaded
Lott in the truck and took him to Victoria to the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   When everything checked out all right, Welder and Lott went for
lunch at the Manhattan Cafe in town. Blacks were expected to go to
the back door for service, but Welder ushered Lott through the
front door with him.
</P>
<P>
   The waitress brought a single glass of water to the table;
Welder insisted on another.
</P>
<P>
   Lott couldn't read the menu, so he waited for Welder to order _
a T-bone and french fries. Lott ordered the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what I was getting,'' he says. ``I'm telling you
the truth. I got one of my french fries. Scared to death, I cut off
a piece of my steak, and that's all I had. I left all that good
food.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at the ranch, Welder joked with the other cowboys,
claiming, ``Old Toney ate a whole cow.'' The crew pressed in close
to Lott, asking him if it was true that he went in the front door
and ate at the tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Yeah, I went in there.' That was something. I was
about 18 or 19 years old, and you didn't see that at that time,''
Lott says.
</P>
<P>
   In town, Lott had to endure racial epithets, but on the ranch he
was treated the equal of any man. Even the bosses asked permission
to ride his horses. They did that with all the cowboys. It was
understood.
</P>
<P>
   BORN A COWBOY: Their memories sustain them now. They are men who
endured the hardships of the coastal plains and carved out
individual reputations _ Oliver with a rope, Garza riding tough
horses, Lott and Brown handling cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Life has never been as good for them as when they rode herd in
the hot sun. They never held their heads as high as when they were
working cowboys. They would continue to ride out at the break of
day if age hadn't stiffened their joints and shortened their
strides.
</P>
<P>
   They miss their friends: Nathaniel Youngblood died in November;
the Rev. Mack Williams, one of their most ardent spokesmen and a
spiritual leader, died in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in the middle of a pasture, so I was born a
cowboy,'' Williams once said. ``When I was just a kid I would hang
out with the cow crowd, eating and sleeping with them, and
eventually, I became a cowboy without even trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was raised on the O'Connor ranch. His grandfather,
Thornton, was a slave sold at auction in Louisiana to the O'Connor
family.
</P>
<P>
   Williams became a man of God in the 1940s when, while riding a
pasture, he heard a voice calling him to the Lord. He retired as a
cowboy and established his own church in Tivoli.
</P>
<P>
   Their memories are kept alive by their widows, who also worked
on area ranches. ``I was born and raised on the Pete Fagan Ranch in
Tivoli, and my family was nothin' but cowboys, so I married a
cowboy,'' Alice Mae Williams says.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Youngblood remembers her husband's love of ranching.
``They might be gone five or six or seven days at a time. Then on
Sunday night they would be ready to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Youngblood was proud of his heritage. He worked hard to gain it.
``These ranches were strength to us,'' he once said. ``It was our
backbone _ like leanin' on somethin' _ you don't worry about
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems impossible, the things we done. We'd do it and leave
the sun hangin'.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on things Texan for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail:
artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
