<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYERS FIND EX-PEERS TELL MORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Employers have warned their managers for years not to provide
much information about a former employee when a prospective
employer calls for a job reference.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about lawsuits from former employees who are unhappy
about what was said, company officials instruct their front-line
supervisors to provide only the former worker's title and dates of
employment.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by the dearth of information, some employers are
striking back. Instead of calling a former supervisor and hitting a
brick wall, they're calling the folks who have never been warned
not to provide details: the applicant's former peers, who are happy
to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Peers provide a lot of valuable information and often have a
good handle on what makes a candidate ``tick,'' said Bill Bufkins,
director of human resources for Johnson Engineering Corp. in
Webster, Texas. Co-workers know about an applicant's work habits
and whether he's a good performer, said Bufkins, who regularly
calls peers when his company is considering a candidate. And peers
often are not as guarded as supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Peer evaluations often provide better information than a
supervisor, said Mel Kleiman, president of Humetrics, a consulting
company in Houston that designs recruiting and retention systems
for companies. For example, a supervisor may hem and haw about why
an employee was terminated. A co-worker often will lay it on the
line _ he was so bad, everyone wondered how long the company was
going to keep him around.
</P>
<P>
   And with all the popularity of work teams, it's often the
co-workers who know more anyway, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kleiman suggests that employers ask a job candidate for names
and phone numbers of co-workers. And 90 to 95 percent of the time,
Kleiman estimates, they'll talk about their co-worker's job
performance.
</P>
<P>
   There's also another plus to this approach: It's a great
recruiting tool.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to all those co-workers is a great way to find other
good employees, said Bufkins. When he was considering an engineer
for a job, Bufkins called one of the candidate's co-workers who
mentioned he was looking for a job himself.
</P>
<P>
   The co-worker turned out to be a dream candidate with his great
breadth of experience and wide range of skills, said Bufkins, who
ended up hiring him, too.
</P>
<P>
   A senior human resource executive from an industrial service
company in Houston said he also tries to recruit the co-workers an
applicant supplies for a job reference.
</P>
<P>
   They are typically good employees because people associate with
people like themselves, he said, asking not to be identified
because he doesn't want his competitors to know how he is stealing
their employees.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch is easy once he has them on the phone, he said. A
rapport is developed, and he tells the co-worker that he sounds
good, too, and might he possibly consider a job change?
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of the time they end up switching jobs, said the
human resource executive. He also credits the fact that his company
keeps its human resource office open until 8 p.m. during the week
and open on the weekends to accommodate job candidates who can't
come in during the day because they're working or in school.
</P>
<P>
   While lawyers have done a great job warning supervisors and
managers on the dos and don'ts when asked to comment on a former
employee's job performance, many employers don't realize that the
comments from lower-level employees can get them into big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Say, for example, a prospective employer asks a co-worker about
his colleague's suitability for work and the co-worker mentions his
friend stole from the company. If it isn't true, the co-worker's
employer could wind up with a defamation lawsuit on his hands, said
Dorene B. Cohen, an employment lawyer with Vinson &AMP; Elkins in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, who represents employers, said she would argue that
commenting on an employee's job performance is not within the
duties of the co-worker and that he is not authorized to speak for
the company. But it's a sticky situation, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   She recommends that employers put in employee handbooks that all
requests for information on a worker's job performance should be
directed to human resources. The handbook should go on to say that
any infraction could result in disciplinary action, including
termination, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also not a bad idea to send out a memo once a year to
reiterate the rule, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
