<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Aug. 23, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOCUST-VALLEY (New York) _ Locust Valley is a slice of
Gatsbyesque, upper-class living, which seems preserved in aspic.
Just 30 miles from Manhattan, it is a land of French manor houses,
private dirt roads and small shops selling monogrammed
wastebaskets. The respect for life's little niceties would bring a
smile to Emily Post. By Monique Yazigi. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCANDAL-CLOTHES (Undated) _ Never before has clothing played
such an important role in a presidential scandal, from Monica's
beret to the Black Dog T-shirt to the Gap dress to The President's
ties. By James Barron. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRIDGE-TEACHER (New York) _ The Manhattan Bridge Club is being
bombarded these days with retirees seeking out Jeff Bayone, the
owner of the club. Bayone is a master teacher of bridge, who is
much in demand these days by those who wish to sharpen their game.
By Alex Kuczynski. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KALINSKY-FASHION (Atlanta) _ Jeffrey Kalinsky, a former shoe
buyer for Barneys New York, arrived in Atlanta in 1990, a pied
piper of high fashion convinced that a desire for sophisticated
apparel was not limited to Manhattan. His insight, coupled with
extraordinary personal attention to customers _ he sometimes flys
them to Europe to view runway shows with him _ have built a
mini-empire of cutting-edge clothing below the Mason-Dixon line. By
Elizabeth Hayt. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOT-ITEMS (Undated) _ Donut deliveries; Chinese Reeboks; Yankee
magnets; Martinit glass; hair knots.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ You wouldn't know it from the
azure-enshrouded mailboxes that line most rural routes, but there's
much more to morning glories than Heavenly Blue. Just ask Thelma
Crawford of Wellsville, Kansas, one of the dozens of morning glory
aficionados who send correspondence, advice and seed flying back
and forth across the country. By Tovah Martin.
</P>
