<HEADER>
A6253 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-BISHOP-2TAKES     08-21 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-BISHOP-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBARA HARRIS: THE ECLECTIC ECCLESIASTIC 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bishop Barbara Clementine Harris knelt at the altar, her
68-year-old knees padded only by her cassock's thin beige cloth.
Head lowered, she gently lifted a wet cloth from a plastic tub and
washed a man's bare feet.
</P>
<P>
   The foot washing is a yearly Episcopal ritual, symbolic of
Jesus' washing the Apostles' feet, a show of humility. For those
gathered, seeing Harris humbled was impressive. After all, she is
the suffragan (assisting) bishop for Massachusetts, which means she
is second in command of the nation's largest Episcopal diocese. She
has held the job since 1988, when she became the first woman
elected as a bishop in the world's 70-million member Anglican
Church.
</P>
<P>
   But what the 12 barefoot celebrants may not have known is that
they were seeing just one side of Harris, who, before becoming a
priest at age 50, spent nearly three decades as a corporate
executive _ occasionally barefoot herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara used to sit at her desk and take off her shoes while
she talked on the phone,'' said Bud Davis, who worked for Harris
when she was a Sun Oil Co. public relations manager. ``She'd turn
her head, and we'd go in and steal her shoe. Practical jokes were
not only tolerated, they were expected in Barbara's department.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was 30 years ago, when Harris was known for throwing
fabulous dinner parties in her native Philadelphia. And this is
now. Being a bishop for 10 years has to have changed Harris, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' said Dorothy Cousins, a retired Philadelphia
police detective who has been one of Harris's closest friends since
seventh grade. Harris still drives her BMW. She still vacations at
a condo in Cancun, Mexico. She still calls her three best friends _
friends she's had for 60 years _ once a week. She still has a
cleaning lady. She still spends her free time listening to
classical music. She still cooks like a chef. Harris has not
changed. It just so happens that she has always been a complex and
motivated human being.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't set out in life to be a bishop,'' Harris mused
during an interview in her office on the fourth floor of the
diocesan headquarters on Tremont Street, across from Boston Common.
``At least I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, dressed impeccably in slacks, a shirt tailored for her
petite frame, and purple pumps several shades removed from her nail
polish, did not choose to sit behind her large desk. Instead, she
offered her guest a seat on the crimson sofa and positioned herself
on a hard wooden chair nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Harris's religious mentor, Philadelphia's Reverend Paul
Washington, said that when he thinks of Harris, he gets an image of
a witty storyteller standing in front of a giggling group of
onlookers in her living room. He said he has often suggested,
almost seriously, that she be a stand-up comic.
</P>
<P>
   But in this formal office setting, that sense of humor was
clearly under wraps. Harris spoke in measured tones, outlining her
schedule as dryly as a press release. She works about 80 hours a
week, much of it spent behind the wheel of her car, en route to
churches, or to her home in Foxborough, Mass. The 45-minute
interview, rare and methodical, was all she could fit in.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of the office, however, hinted at the passions Harris
has experienced since she was a young girl. The framed watercolor
of a stained-glass window in a Roxbury, Mass. church spoke of her
upbringing in a black Episcopal parish; the honorary degrees showed
that little in life is impossible if you have faith (Harris never
completed college); the colorful African wall hangings were a
reminder that, despite the church's reputation in New England as a
white Anglo-Saxon institution, most Anglicans worldwide are not
white. (There are more in Uganda and Nigeria than in all of the
United States.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was a framed photograph of Harris herself, a
staff in one hand. A secret smile played at the corner of her
mouth. She looked as if she was meant to be here. As if someone had
called her. And, according to Harris, someone did.
</P>
<P>
   God.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Harris was 16 years old, and it was New Year's Eve. Her
friend Marilyn Allston was over at the Harris family home in
Germantown, Pa. The girls were doing their hair and laying out the
dresses they would wear for their double date. The plan was to go
to a church social. But the girls were sleepy and decided to take a
nap. When they woke up, it was past midnight. The boys had been
sent home, and they'd missed the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at each other, and I said, `What are we going to do
now?''' recalled Allston. ``The first thing Barbara said is `We are
going to pray.' That's the kind of person she's always been.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A segregated life
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harris grew up in a black neighborhood outside Philadelphia at a
time when life was segregated, including the YMCA, where her
picture now hangs in the Hall of Fame. Her father was a quiet,
gentle, and educated man who labored at a local steel mill.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days you had doctors working at the post office,''
said Allston. ``Among blacks, just because someone worked a
blue-collar job did not mean they were not well educated or well
mannered.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris's mother, Beatrice, was a classical pianist who worked as
the organist and choir director at the neighborhood church, Saint
Luke's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to call her Miss Bea,'' recalled Washington. ``I knew
Miss Bea rather well. She was a very outspoken person, unafraid to
address the issue or the question, no matter how sensitive. I
certainly feel that she gave Barbara a good dose of that dimension
in herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris's elder sister, Josephine, still lives in the family
home. Younger brother Walter lives in Florida. Harris said she is
close to both.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Harris kept busy with school, piano lessons, church
activities, and writing. At the Philadelphia High School for Girls,
she was recruited to write a weekly column on high school life in
the Pittsburgh Courier, a newspaper aimed at the African-American
community. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Making religion fun
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoons and evenings, friends recall, the Harris
home, with its enclosed porch and baby grand piano, was the place
to go. ``Barbara and her family had a way of making elegance, and
even religion, seem fun,'' said Dorothy Cousins. At 16, Cousins
converted to the Episcopal Church, just so ``I could go with
Barbara.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school, Harris attended
Philadelphia's Charles Morris Price School of Advertising and
Journalism. In 1949, at age 19, she was hired by Joseph V. Baker
Associates Inc., a local public relations firm. Without a college
degree, but armed with a quick mind, Harris moved up in the
company. By the time she left, in 1968, she was the president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1610EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6257 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-HARRIS-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     08-21 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-HARRIS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 UNDATED: ... was the president.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1968, Harris took a job at Sun Oil as a community relations
consultant. Once again, she was promoted, eventually chosen to head
the company's public relations department in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was briefly married and divorced. She has no children.
None of her friends was willing to talk about the former husband,
except to say that he remained close enough to the family to attend
Miss Bea's funeral. Harris declined to answer questions about her
personal romantic life.
</P>
<P>
   Key elements in Harris's life have been her friendships, her
civil rights activism, and her work in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Church was not something to be played with for Barbara,'' said
Washington. He met Harris in the mid-1950s, when both worked as
church youth counselors. ``She was never someone you could describe
as a pew warmer. She was going to get in the midst of things.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Civil rights crusader
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harris switched parishes as an adult to be closer to Washington,
a priest and author well known in Philadelphia for his political
activism. Fighting for the rights of blacks and women became a
central part of her life during the 1960s. She marched with Martin
Luther King Jr. and worked for the Urban League and other
organizations. She is still active in Episcopal groups for
African-Americans and is very outspoken against the church's
lingering disapproval of homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Harris, still a laywoman, was asked to be the cross
bearer at a historic ceremony in Philadelphia when the first 11
women were ordained as Episcopal priests.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``a beautiful foreshadowing of what was to come,''
according to Reverend Ann Robb Smith, now the priest at Harris's
hometown church, and one of many in attendance that day who
remember her leading the procession.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the ceremony, Harris said, she felt God tugging
at her to become more involved in the church. When asked to
describe that time in her life, Harris got a look in her eyes that
was so peaceful and intense it bordered on sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to explain,'' she said. ``I had a very
active lay ministry, which was very satisfying. But I discovered
that there was a different shape to my ministry, and that I was
being led to the ordained ministry for a different dimension of
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled against it for a long time. I didn't feel that I
was a worthy candidate. A friend of mine who was a priest and is
now a bishop said, `God does not call those who are worthy; he
makes worthy those who are called.' That helped.''
</P>
<P>
   After deciding to become a priest, Harris continued working at
Sun Oil. She took seminary classes nights and weekends and spent
her vacations studying, a nontraditional route. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Entering the order
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harris was ordained a deacon in 1979, and a priest in 1980, at
the age of 50. She left her position at Sun, but remained a
consultant for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Her first religious job was as part-time priest in charge of a
church in Norristown, Pa., called Saint Augustine of Hippo. Then,
in 1984, Harris was named executive director of the Episcopal
Church Publishing Co. and publisher of The Witness magazine, long
an open forum for dissent within the church. Harris had been on the
board of the company for years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, she took Washington's place as interim director of the
Church of the Advocate when he had stepped down. That same year,
she attended the Lambeth Convention, a gathering of Anglican
bishops from all over the world, in Canterbury, England, as a
reporter for The Witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was open talk at the time that a woman might be elected
in the United States,'' said Reverend Canon Edward W. Rodman, the
canon missioner for Massachusetts and Harris's friend for 30 years.
``Her name was lifted up at that time as one of the possible
candidates. She came back sort of on notice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really torn about whether it was something I really
wanted to do,'' said Harris. ``I thought about all of the potential
problems. I thought I wouldn't be nominated, as a woman. Then I
thought that I would not be elected, even if I was nominated ... I
was greatly surprised at each step in the process.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Caring and alert'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When she came in for the formal interview with the committee,
it was so very clear in that time that she would be one of the
nominees,'' said John J. Bishop, a retired priest living in
Yarmouthport, who chaired the committee that elected Harris as a
bishop. ``She was just caring, alert, bright, committed to the
issues that were confronting the church at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington remembers the day Harris was elected. ``She received
a call from David Johnson, the bishop of Massachusetts at the time,
saying she had been elected. I did the sermon at her ordination to
the priesthood, and she called and said `You better get another
speech prepared.' That was deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris's consecration as bishop was widely supported in this
liberal state. But some in the church, such as the Episcopal bishop
of South Carolina, who resigned one week after Harris was selected,
said her unorthodox religious education was unacceptable. Others
showed up at the consecration to protest, because of Harris's
gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the protests were very personal,'' Harris said. ``I
got death threats.'' She stopped to grin, and added, ``All in the
name of the Lord, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 years since Harris became a bishop, her performance
has opened doors for other women in the church. There are now eight
female bishops in the United States, seven in Canada, and one in
New Zealand. ``That's why the people who protested did so,'' Harris
said. ``They knew that if one woman was consecrated, that there
would be no stopping us after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris has also elevated the visibility of nonwhites in the
local Episcopal church, which has become increasingly diverse. She
works in tandem with the diocesan bishop, Thomas Shaw, in a
relationship that those who know them describe as harmonious and
productive. The arrangement, by which they share most duties, is a
new system, and one that Rodman says was created to increase
Harris's visibility.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her energy, and her clear love of the work, church rules
require that all bishops retire at 72, four years from now for
Harris. Though she is vague about her plans after retirement, those
who know her say to stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say that we haven't seen the best from Barbara Harris
yet,'' said Rodman. ``There's no telling what she'll do next, but
you can be sure it will be amazing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
