<HEADLINE>
LET'S CURB SPREADING REQUESTS FOR SOCIAL SECURITY NUMBERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'll admit to being way behind the curve on this tidbit of
information, but then, I haven't had to renew my driver's license
in person in more than six year.
</P>
<P>
   The white sign with its bold red letters, hanging above the
heads of the Texas Department of Public Safety employees, announced
in no uncertain terms that all applicants must present a Social
Security card to receive a new, renewed or replacement driver's
license.
</P>
<P>
   For something that was never supposed to be used as universal
identification, my nine-digit Social Security number sure gets a
workout.
</P>
<P>
   When the Social Security Administration was created in 1936, the
government assured the public that use of the number assigned to
each citizen would be limited to Social Security programs. Being
that no assurances ever made by the government is a promise, the
United States Code has been amended to allow states (or any
political subdivision of the federal government) the use of Social
Security account numbers in the administration of taxes or general
public assistance, or the issuance of driver's licenses or motor
vehicle registration.
</P>
<P>
   Since Feb. 3, 1997, Texans renewing their driver's licenses in
person or requesting a duplicate have been forced to provide what
should be a very private piece of information. The reason? The
state attorney general's office needs help in tracking down folks
delinquent in their child support. So we all get treated like
potential felons in the name of the Texas Family Code.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why you great outdoorsmen and women preparing for the
upcoming game seasons are going to be asked for your Social
Security number when you apply for a hunting permit. The AG is
using every type of state-issued license to track down deadbeat
parents.
</P>
<P>
   There was no use in refusing the pleasant but firm woman behind
the counter at the Department of Public Safety office _ no SSN, no
driver's license. I need a driver's license to do my job, among
other things crucial in my life, so I presented said card. But not
happily.
</P>
<P>
   If there's an upside to the Texas experience, at least the state
doesn't use Social Security numbers as the driver's license number.
Some do.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you living in a state where such information is not
yet required, get ready. In October 2000, a federal immigration law
will go into effect that mandates all states to record Social
Security numbers for all driver's licenses and state-issued ID
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations dealing with privacy issues warn citizens to guard
their Social Security account numbers as precious information.
According to the Privacy Rights Clearinghouse, banks and credit
card companies across the nation are reporting increases in
SSN-related fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Resist at every turn in providing a Social Security number to
retailers, telemarketers or nongovernmental agencies that request
it. Although the original law has been bastardized to allow use of
the number for government programs other than Social Security, that
doesn't mean you have to let go of the information without a fight.
If a retailer demands that you put the number on a check, take your
business elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Why should people care about who has access to their account
numbers? Because someone can literally steal your identity, running
up charges, ruining your credit and basically wrecking havoc on
your good name without your knowing about it until after
considerable damage is done.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com, and her phone number is (817)
390-7599. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
