  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR
AUGUST 21, 1998. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- WELFARE. Florida's welfare caseload has been cut in
half in the two years since President Clinton signed a historic
welfare reform bill. Williams
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA -- WELFARE. Georgia's welfare caseload has fallen by
more than 45 percent in the two years since President Clinton
signed a historic welfare reform bill. Williams
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS -- BRIEFS. Column for Sunday. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- RECESS. During congressional recesses, like the one
enveloping Washington right now, the usually bustling halls of the
Capitol give way to calm. Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA -- CRIME. Law enforcement efforts in Lafayette could
soon get a boost from the federal government. Egbert
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- QUALLS-FINANCE. Cincinnati Mayor Roxanne Qualls has one
of the largest war chests of any challenger in the country,
according to FEC documents. One political analyst said she and
Republican Steve Chabot will need that money for carefully targeted
advertising in the final weeks of the race. (Possible.) Gorman
</P>
<P>
   -- WELFARE-GRANTS. Ohio is one of 13 states to receive $50,000
grants from the U.S. Dept. of Health and Human Services to help
states further develop their welfare-to-work programs. (Possible.)
Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -- FOOD-BUCKEYE-EGG. Citing outdated food safety laws and a
fragmented federal structure, the National Research Council
released a report this week recommending a more consolidated,
science-based approach to federal food safety efforts. A new
program could prevent the kind of inspection loopholes that were
blamed for the oversight of sanitation problems at the Buckeye Egg
Farm earlier this year. (Possible.) Hurt
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- LANDMARK. A Civil War battlefield in South Texas was
designated as a national historic landmark, which could direct
grant money to the field, but the action itself does not change
anything. Lakin/Marlin
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- TOBACCO. The tobacco industry is targeting
middle-class voters in advertisements denouncing a congressional
plan to curb smoking by minors. Lawmakers have received many calls
urging them to vote against such measures. Marlin
</P>
