<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6282 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-FAILS-U.S.-GOA     08-21 1714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-FAILS-U.S.-GOALS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INTERVIEW WITH RANAN LURIE: THE STOMACH TO WIPE OUT TERRORISM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By CAROLEE B. MORRISON  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Ranan Lurie is an internationally known political cartoonist and
analyst, whose work is published in 103 countries in 1,105
newspapers with a total circulation of 104 million readers. A
former Israeli Army combat major, who served as a commando during
the Six Day War _ and survived 144 paratrooper jumps into enemy
territory _ Lurie is also a master military tactician.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks here about the U.S. retaliatory raid into Sudan and
Afghanistan and raises important questions about U.S. goals, combat
readiness and willingness to fight _ as well as our understanding
of terrorism and the degree of threat it poses for the future.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0-
</P>
<P>
   CAROLEE B. MORRISON: What do you think of the U.S. mission into
Sudan and Afghanistan in retaliation for the embassy bombings in
Africa?
</P>
<P>
   RANAN LURIE: The problem with this action is the historical
problem of human warfare, where generals always prepare for the
last war. Generals plan the next war according to the criteria of
the last war.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the French prepared the Maginot line in the late
'30s according to the trench warfare of World War I, and the
Germans just made a big circle with their very fast Panzer tanks
and encircled them. And France just fell. The French were not
planning for such a blitzkrieg.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Let's come back to what happened now.
</P>
<P>
   A: The cruise missiles were the most anticipated guests of those
super-Saudi Arabian/Afghanistani terrorists. The United States has
established itself as a fighting force that wants to rely as much
as possible on technology, and sacrificing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In terms of lives?
</P>
<P>
   A: Right. We don't want to report about casualties. So what
happened here ... that gentlemen, Osama bin Laden, just prepared
himself for it. The fact is that he is living deep in the
mountains. He is well-prepared for cruise missiles; he is not
impressed by them. And the cruise missiles really cannot serve any
function against terrorists unless they have a known, above-ground
headquarters or training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In terms of today, what should U.S. forces be doing instead?
</P>
<P>
   A: The only way to surprise them would be by helicopter attacks,
landing Delta force-type units, special-commando forces that also
enjoy superb intelligence. This is where the CIA has to come in
very strongly. The units would actually clear the area.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Meaning what?
</P>
<P>
   A: Clear the area, meaning demolish the ... for instance, I
could envision an attack from Pakistan, with the aid of Pakistan,
of our very superior helicopters, on that specific spot, protected
by air power, and a unit of about two companies coming down,
knocking on the door and demolishing the whole place. And hopefully
capturing its high command.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It sounds as if you're saying we have the capability of doing
this.
</P>
<P>
   A: I think we have.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do we not do this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Pardon me?
</P>
<P>
   A: We don't have the stomach for it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which means?
</P>
<P>
   A: We don't want to take a chance of losing lives. Of ... let us
take when President Carter was trying to save the hostages in Iran
in '79. He sent the helicopters and the helicopters got screwed up
... there was a sandstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was also taken as a certain sign of inadequacy of the
training of our troops.
</P>
<P>
   A: Correct. There has to be, and I hope we have these kinds of
units ... we are speaking really about nothing more than a few
hundred top warriors who go out to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A Delta Force, SEALS ...
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes exactly. You know, a platoon of Navy SEALS has so much
fire power, they could demolish the place.
</P>
<P>
   Q: That leads us back to stomach. Is this a problem,
particularly given what war scenarios are going to be in the
future?
</P>
<P>
   A: Look, I would say that the bin Laden individual is a person
who is so rich _ he's a billionaire, not merely a millionaire. And
there is already talk that he is planning a nuclear bomb,
purchasing a nuclear bomb. If this guy will deliver such a bomb to
Philadelphia or New York or Los Angeles without any moral
hesitation _ and establish himself as a hero for the next 1,000
years in the fanatic Islamic world _ well, we have to compare
stomachs to stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   We have to compare the stomach of facing a terrible loss of 20
or 30 very good young warriors to the stomach we'll need to face
the loss of millions in a metropolitan area of the United States.
This is not a game anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Based on your knowledge of American society, what will
meeting the challenge have to come to?
</P>
<P>
   A: It will have to come to American society understanding the
real threat _ the real nuclear threat _ to our cities, in order to
understand that we have to sacrifice everything in order to reach
him before he reaches us.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are we saying it would take some kind of tragic disaster in a
major city to give us the stomach to retaliate in the way that is
required?
</P>
<P>
   A: Either this or a very graphic description that conveys the
knowledge that this is quite imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Given the current skepticism about government, I wonder if
what you're suggesting is a realistic scenario.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm afraid that it's not a realistic scenario. I'm afraid
that the cruise missiles were the equivalent of a military lip
service. In brief, we say something and we don't really mean it.
Here, it was a military operation that really could not solve a
problem. On the contrary, that kind of military reaction is almost
a knee-jerk reaction, because the military is shouting from here to
Timbuktu, so that all the world can hear: ``We can't afford losing
people.''
</P>
<P>
   And the moment you say that you can't afford losing people, the
terrorists have a tremendous edge over us because they can relax.
They know that they are not going to suffer direct contact with
American forces. For they would lose in any kind of contact with
our elite troops. No one is trained as well as our elite troops.
I'm saying this ... my son is a West Point graduate and I know what
is happening there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There is no timidity among Mr. bin Laden and his forces about
losing lives, or is there?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is none whatsoever. On the contrary, the whole concept
is, like the classic Iranian concept, that the terrorists who blow
themselves up in buses, driving toward our embassies or
marketplaces in Israel, it is a tremendous honor. It is the
beginning of a new life. For them losing lives is a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So if among those who were killed in the camp in Afghanistan,
any of them were terrorists, they would be heroes, or have ...
</P>
<P>
   A: They are shahids. Shahid is the Arab word for martyr. And as
martyrs they are going to a fantastic world where they are given
dozens of virgins, gorgeous ones, and they have a life of terrific
_ a Donald Trump-style life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You mentioned ``no moral hesitation'' in connection with a
bin Laden person being willing to take out numerous cities and
millions of people. There are some who view this as a sign of
principles, in that it reflects a belief system that is adhered to,
unwavering, unflinching ...
</P>
<P>
   A: It's as if you would say that also Hitler was a principled
man. What does it mean? That his principles are that other races
are inferior. Therefore they are execution-prone, and they should
be burned in the gas chambers. This is more or less what Osama bin
Laden also thinks. That the Islamic way is the right way. That
America is Satan. And basically the only force that really stops
Islam from spreading is the American way of life and culture which
ruins the moral fabric of young people, including young Islamic
people. And therefore, we are condemned. And a nuclear bomb is a
very legal thing from his point of view, from his ``principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you believe the U.S. troops _ the special-ops you would
use in antiterrorist actions _ are ready to fight?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely. That's why they volunteer. Once you volunteer to
the Green Beret or the Delta Force or to the Navy SEALS, you make a
commitment. You make a declaration. No one forces them to do it.
And they join because of love of country, or maybe because of the
green beret, or they want to impress their girlfriends, or they
want to be higher paid, or they want action and adventure. In all
cases, they choose to do it. And they would like to do it because
that is what makes them a Delta Force.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So who is it that doesn't have the stomach? Their mothers?
fathers?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's, yes, but ... it's not even the high command. It's
basically the politicians who have to report and to say, ``I'm
sorry but we failed miserably.'' You know, this fiasco in Iran
caused Carter tremendous damage. He came out as a very incompetent
leader. Of course, while he approved the mission, he didn't know
the details, so technically he wasn't responsible, but he WAS
responsible, he was the commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And other commanders in chief would not want to accidentally
follow in those footsteps?
</P>
<P>
   A: Exactly. And when you have the cruise missile that does the
job, it sounds terrific. But they forget _ Clinton forgot _ that
the cruise missile by now is a very known quantity, a very known
weapon. It's not surprising any more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Carolee B. Morrison is international editor at The New York
Times Syndicate.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
