<HEADLINE>
CADILLAC INTRODUCES ITS REDESIGNED SEVILLE SEDAN
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best American luxury car just got a whole lot better.
</P>
<P>
   If Cadillac's redesigned Seville luxury sedan for 1998 doesn't
wow customers with its muscular exterior styling and luxury
interior (brazenly patterned after the previous generation Lexus LS
400), perhaps all of this car's high-tech features combined will do
the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Caddy is trying to do a better job of competing against import
luxury cars in the over-$45,000 price category. And the Seville _
which is all new except for the drivetrain _ is designed to appeal
to high-end buyers here and abroad. General Motors is even
producing right-hand-drive models for England and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The previous model, introduced for 1992, never quite reached the
sales goals GM set for it, even though it was by far the best
Cadillac built. The Seville just never caught on with baby-boomers,
who seem to view Cadillac as a stodgy old brand that their parents
might have bought.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac sought to break that image with the '92 Seville, and
this newer version is expected to continue to reshape the brand's
image with younger buyers. It comes in two models: the base Seville
Luxury Sedan, or SLS for short, and the top-of-the-line Seville
Touring Sedan, or STS, which we tested.
</P>
<P>
   The '98 STS, with a base price of $46,995, competes well against
similarly priced luxury cars that just aren't quite as peppy or as
well-equipped. Prices for 1999 haven't been announced, but there
are no significant changes in the vehicle. I would expect the price
to remain about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some consumers thought the previous Seville was just too
big. If that's the case, the new one might be more appealing. Even
though it still looks like its predecessor, it's three inches
shorter.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not even to mention all the high-tech stuff, which
surely should appeal to baby-boomers _ people who view technology
as a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Seville seats its front occupants in the lap of
luxury. The base bucket seats are comfortable enough, with their
lumbar support and eight-way power adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   But the optional ``adaptive'' front seats ($1,202), which came
on our test car, are enough to make weary folks want to sit in the
Seville for a long time. The seats are full of air cells that are
automatically filled or deflated to fit the backside, rump and
thighs of whoever is sitting there. The system even allows for a
wallet in a back pocket (which, of course, is a bit thinner after
paying the extra dough for these seats).
</P>
<P>
   The seat adjusts to the driver or front-seat passenger's profile
within 30 to 60 seconds, then checks again every four minutes to
make sure the settings are still correct.
</P>
<P>
   Another seat option, which didn't come on our test vehicle, will
also massage the back of the driver or front passenger at the touch
of a button.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots more high-tech features, many of them designed to
improve the car's performance, not just the driver and passenger's
posture.
</P>
<P>
   StabiliTrak, an exclusive on Cadillacs, works in conjunction
with the steering, traction control, suspension system and antilock
brakes to keep the car from skidding out of control. It used to be
that was the responsibility of the driver, but in the case of the
STS, I suppose even the lousiest drivers can look pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the system works: If the car begins fishtailing, this
computerized system gently applies the appropriate front brake to
bring the tail of the vehicle back into line. The whole effect is
to make the car go in the direction the driver wants it to go,
which is a concept that your passengers will heartily embrace _
especially in traffic on two-lane roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Performance Algorithm Shifting,'' another creative use of
technology, allows the STS's four-speed automatic transmission to
perform like a manual gearbox (without the clutch) if the operator
is driving aggressively. It holds in each gear long enough to get
the best acceleration, and is particularly useful on long grades _
eliminating unnecessary up- and down-shifting.
</P>
<P>
   The Seville's ``Continuously Variable Road-sensing Suspension''
is yet another high-tech toy. This system monitors road conditions
and sets the suspension system accordingly, to ensure that the ride
is always smooth and sure.
</P>
<P>
   A separate ``road-texture detection'' system measures the
roughness of the pavement and sets the antilock braking system for
optimal stopping performance. Cadillac says it allows the car to
stop in shorter distances than normal on rough roads, while also
reducing unnecessary use of the antilock brakes and improving
steering response.
</P>
<P>
   Had enough yet? Read on _ there's more.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
