<HEADLINE>
REBUILDING BERLIN AS A CITY OF INTELLECTUAL LIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `i' code) 
 (bl)  
 By KARL E. MEYER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ ``It is a new city,'' Mark Twain said of Berlin 107
years ago, ``the newest I have ever seen. Chicago would seem
venerable beside it.''
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, this seems true today of central Berlin. The city is
a forest of cranes, cavernous construction sites and a rising
palisade of new government ministries and imposing embassies
(including the United States', not far from the Brandenburg Gate).
</P>
<P>
   But the Berlin that Twain saw in 1891 had yet to make its mark
as an intellectual and artistic center. It was Europe's
third-largest metropolis, and its parks and boulevards were meant
to express imperial grandeur, but the total effect was pretentious,
as with the rows of marble statues of the royal Hohenzollern family
installed in heroic poses in the Tiergarten. Even Kaiser Wilhelm II
had doubts about his capital, remarking in an 1892 letter, ``Berlin
is a great city, a world city (perhaps?).''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, within a few decades, Berlin burst up near the top
as an acknowledged intellectual leader, especially in the sciences.
In 1901, Sweden bestowed the inaugural Nobel Prize for medicine on
a Berliner, Emil von Behring, for his serum against diphtheria. By
the 1930s, no fewer than 29 Nobel laureates had been associated
with Berlin University and its medical faculty, the biggest in
Europe, at Charite Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Einstein's general theory of relativity, Planck's quantum
mechanics and Heisenberg's uncertainty principle all came out of
Berlin. So did the spectroscope, the discovery of radio waves and
``the magic bullet,'' salvarsan, to treat syphilis.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin's preeminence was ominously underscored in 1938 with the
discovery of nuclear fission at the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute by
Otto Hahn and Fritz Strassmann, building on the intuitive insight
of Lise Meitner, who fled Berlin that same year.
</P>
<P>
   The prestige of professors, including nonscientists, was
immense; they were like film stars, everywhere recognized and
deferred to. When historian Theodor Mommsen rode a streetcar home,
conductors always slowed down rounding his corner so he could
appear to hop from the moving tram _ a blue-collar tribute to the
no-longer-nimble professor.
</P>
<P>
   This adulation had its downside. Professors became rabid
nationalists, or ``Teutomaniacs,'' in the words of Alexandra
Richie, author of ``Faust's Metropolis'' (Carroll &AMP; Graf, 1998), a
full-length portrait of Berlin. To the self-appointed guardians of
German culture, she writes, ``German virgins were more virginal,
German loyalty was more selfless, and German culture was deeper and
richer than that found in Paris or for that matter anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Germans are hardly alone in wondering (and worrying) whether
Berlin, once more the capital of a united country, will again
emerge as an imperious world city. Its intellectual future is
similarly pondered.
</P>
<P>
   Though the professor is still admired in Berlin, academic
chauvinism is not. Professorial dogmatism has generally yielded to
prudential caution, one reason being that not even the sagest
German scholar foresaw the imminent peaceful downfall of the Berlin
Wall in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Wolf Lepenies, the rector of the Institute for
Advanced Study at Berlin, said in a recent lecture: ``The collapse
of Communism is not so much a reason for triumph as a motive for
modesty. Nineteen eighty-nine has shown us the narrow limits of
expert culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor has unification been a boon to the three universities in
Berlin. Humboldt, Technical and the Free University are mired in
financial crisis as government spending on higher education is
being cut by a third. The ballooning costs of readying Berlin for
its formal debut next year as federal capital is one reason for the
squeeze, but the end of the Cold War is probably the bigger factor.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1989, Berlin's schools were extensions of political wars
(Free University, for example, was founded in 1948 by students and
teachers fleeing the communist takeover of Humboldt, formerly
Berlin University, in East Berlin). But the wall is now a memory,
faculties are being reduced in size and free tuition is ending,
propelling a wave of strikes among Berlin's 135,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   An effect of these cuts is to widen further the gap in resources
between Berlin's science faculties and those in the United States,
the country of choice for gifted students in most of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Berlin is trying to make an intellectual mark with
innovative postdoctoral institutes that are propagating eastward, a
benign form of Germanic outreach. In this, Berlin has exploited its
natural advantages: a tradition of research academies, strong links
with Western universities and a location at the heart of what
everybody now calls Middle Europe (from Berlin, it is one hour by
car to the Polish border).
</P>
<P>
   The heirloom among Berlin's 100-odd institutes is the Max Planck
Society, successor to the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute, founded in 1911
and once the world's leading laboratory for scientific research.
Since reopening its Berlin headquarters in 1993, the society serves
as the mother church for 75 research institutes, including a score
in eastern Germany reorganized on western lines (lubricated by $370
million in government money).
</P>
<P>
   Of newcomers, among the most enterprising is the Institute for
Advanced Study, established in 1981 and avowedly inspired by its
American namesake. This has historical justice because the
Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, N.J., was a haven in the
1930s for German scholars escaping Nazi rule, Einstein foremost
among them. In the verdant Grunewald quarter of Berlin, the
institute is funded partly by private foundations and partly by the
government, and it annually invites up to 40 fellows from around
the world, with a salting of writers (this author was one in 1994).
</P>
<P>
   Lepenies, the sociologist of knowledge and house table tennis
champion, saw an opportunity to bring together two political
cultures _ intellectuals in Eastern Europe with high moral stature
but a ``rather low level of expertise'' and those in the West
``with a high degree of expertise but without much concern for
moral issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1992, the institute secured support from six
European partners for the Collegium Budapest, the first such center
for advanced studies in the post-communist East. This was followed
(with help from the financier and philanthropist George Soros) by
the Graduate School for Social Science in Warsaw and an advanced
college in Bucharest, Romania _ the latter headed by a former
dissident, Andrei Plesu, who this year became Romania's Foreign
Minister. Soon to open is an academy in St. Petersburg, Russia, and
even a research center in Mali in West Africa, headed by a former
institute fellow.
</P>
<P>
   In the capital's postdoctoral circus, what promises to be the
third ring, vying with old and new institutes, is the American
Academy in Berlin, which will open in October as a center for
research and public debate. Generously endowed ($34 million), it
will be housed in a Wannsee villa with a typical Berlin biography
(owned first by a wealthy Jew, then by a Nazi official, later
plundered by the Red Army, used as a U.S. officers club and most
recently as a shelter for refugees from the East).
</P>
<P>
   Very much the brainchild of its chairman, Richard Holbrooke, a
former U.S. envoy to Bonn, the academy in his words is to be ``a
venue in Berlin where trans-Atlantic thinking will draw fresh
inspiration from the complex reality of the new German capital.''
</P>
<P>
   The academicians will be an eclectic mix of scholars, writers,
filmmakers and theologians; the inaugural Distinguished Senior
Fellow is the playwright Arthur Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The new Berlin very probably will not be as as arrogant,
riotous, inspired, sinister, catastrophic and heroic as the old.
But that may not be such a bad thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
