<HEADLINE>
YOUR GRANDFATHER'S MORNING GLORIES CLIMB AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Iowa)   (For release Sunday, Aug. 23)  
(lb) 
 By TOVAH MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You wouldn't know it from the azure-enshrouded mailboxes that
line many rural routes, but there's much more to morning glories
than Heavenly Blue.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Thelma Crawford of Wellsville, Kan., one of the dozens
of morning glory aficionados who send correspondence, advice and
seed flying back and forth across the United States. She's 84 and
says that ``time is so precious.'' She hasn't a minute for idle
chatter: There are seeds that need collecting, packaging and
labeling.
</P>
<P>
   Her mission is to cover the world with morning glories. And she
isn't particularly keen on the standard varieties like Scarlett
O'Hara or Pearly Gates that can be obtained through any seed
catalog. Instead, she's busy collecting Robe, with its white
picotee edge hemming velvety burgundy blossoms, or Carnaby Red,
smothered in cerise flowers accented by white throats.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Crawford and her correspondents are members of the Flower
and Herb Exchange, an offshoot of the Seed Savers Exchange, a
nonprofit international organization in Decorah, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Whealy, the head of the Flower and Herb Exchange, said
morning glories played a pivotal role in the founding of the Seed
Savers Exchange. In 1970, Mrs. Whealy's Grandpa Ott died, and she
found herself the custodian of the royal purple morning glory
strain that he brought to Iowa when he emigrated from Bavaria.
</P>
<P>
   To make certain they never slipped into oblivion, she started
sharing seeds with friends near and far. The exchange now claims
more than 1,000 active seed-swapping members.
</P>
<P>
   Grandpa Ott was not the only one with his own morning glory
strain, according to exchange lore. Mrs. Crawford said that a
Midwesterner named Harris Carnaby nurtured the morning glory that
exchange members know as Carnaby Red and that another gardener
found a multicolored type and named it Christensen Factory in honor
of the place where the seed was first collected.
</P>
<P>
   Undreamed-of shades came to light, like Brazilian Orange, with
clusters of small carrot-hued blossoms. Weird patterns also
surfaced, like the tie-dyed blossoms of Flying Saucers.
</P>
<P>
   Need a morning glory adapted to an arid region? There's
drought-tolerant Texas Pink, with soft pink blossoms accented by a
magenta eye. Have a bent toward the macabre? Kniola Bowles Black
has blossoms that are such a deep purple they appear midnight-hued.
Want something to stand out against your dark barn? Plant Wedding
Bells, with 3-inch pinkish-lilac blooms. And that's just a few.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the morning glories recently coming to light are
family heirlooms. Some were prominently featured in catalogs when
morning glories were enjoying their heyday in the 1940s and '50s.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, morning glories have waltzed in and out of
fashion. Although Ipomoea ancestors first came to Britain from
tropical America via Spain and Italy in 1621, they looked too
similar to a noxious pest, bindweed, the bully in the family with
perennial roots and an expansionist personality. Gardeners were
leery of letting any Ipomoea loose.
</P>
<P>
   And why bother? Ipomoea tricolor Blue Star, Heavenly Blue's
prototype, didn't bloom until season's end, and people didn't want
a vine covered only with foliage. It had another hitch: The flowers
bloomed at 4 a.m. and faded before anyone could get outside to see
them.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteenth-century Americans used the rampant heart-leaved vine
to camouflage the family privy. But that was the extent of its
employment until 1931, when a Colorado gardener by the name of
Clarke discovered an early-blooming, free-flowering,
large-trumpeted, sky-blue mutant. It became known as Clarke's Early
Heavenly Blue, and it gave rise to all the sky-colored morning
glories that have meandered around mailboxes ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements came regularly enough to hold the public
spellbound, like a pure white version known as Pearly Gates that
won the All-America Selection Award in 1942, followed by a rainbow
of colors.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1963, amid the craze for ingesting various
mind-altering substances, someone reported that chewing the seeds
could cause hallucinations. Sales skidded in the United States, and
Britain briefly banned their purchase. Many varieties that were
lost because of that character assassination are now resurfacing.
</P>
<P>
   The current resurgence of morning glories, which are annuals but
tend to self-seed, probably owes its momentum to the new
fascination with cottage gardens. Any flowering vine capable of
encasing an arbor lickety-split is receiving a hero's welcome.
Morning glories not only fit that bill, but also thrive on neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from one quirk _ they prefer warm temperatures, and you
can't push the seasons by planting them too early _ they're easy.
Plant seeds when the soil is warm, preferably in a place where they
won't receive light at night, which could prevent blooming.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the variety, they'll usually start to bloom in
July. They don't bloom as well in fertile soil; they require no
deadheading and prefer to forge upward without interference. Any
old sturdy support will do. In fact, Mrs. Whealy recalls that one
of her chores as a child was to collect pieces of old twine to tie
together as a trellis for her Grandpa Ott's morning glories.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain seeds from the Flower and Herb Exchange, you must be a
member, which costs $10 a year. The address is 3076 North Winn Rd.,
Decorah IA 52101; telephone (319) 382-5990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
