<HEADER>
A6303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICAL-TOP10-NYT &LR;      08-21 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-TOP10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICINE'S 10 GREATEST HITS: CURIOSITY'S REWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICIA COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget genius. Curiosity and methodical investigation are what
matter.
</P>
<P>
   At least those are the two characteristics that Dr. Gerald W.
Friedland and Dr. Meyer Friedman think are responsible for the 10
greatest discoveries in the history of Western medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We admire the natural, totally understandable mental capacity
of our 10 discoverers,'' the two research doctors write in
``Medicine's 10 Greatest Discoveries,'' which Yale University Press
is publishing in November. ``But we are not amazed at this mental
talent, primarily because we can follow the working of their fine
minds. Indeed, we almost believe that were we in their situation,
we might have arrived at their discoveries. None of us, though, has
any illusion that we could equal the genius of Mozart's music,
Shakespeare's dramas or Newton's laws of physics.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's also luck. Antony Leeuwenhoek by chance left
his rainwater standing for a few days, enough time for bacteria to
grow. Crawford Long accidentally got the idea for surgical
anesthesia after hurting himself but feeling no pain while under
the influence of ether at a party.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman and Friedland looked at the 5,000 or more discoveries
in Western medicine made over the last four centuries and consulted
other medical experts to select the winners, which fell into three
categories: the structure and functions of the human body and mind,
the diagnosis of medical disorders and their treatments.
</P>
<P>
   So which is No. 1? William Harvey's discovery in the early 17th
century that blood traveled in a closed circuit is labeled the
``greatest medical achievement of all time.'' Not only did it
initiate the field of physiology, but it also introduced the
principle of experimentation in medicine, the two doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Harvey's book, the doctors say, ``What the
authorized version of the Bible has been to the Church of England
and the Shakespeare Folio to English literature, `De Motu Cordis,'
has been to medicine everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   As for future discoveries, the authors are betting on cures for
two mental disorders: schizophrenia and manic-depressive syndrome.
With a little luck, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Here is their list in chronological order:
</P>
<P>
   1543 _ Andreas Vesalius presents ``De Humani Corporis Fabrica,''
or ``The Structure of the Human Body,'' which detailed the anatomy
of the human body. He was the first to point out that without
bones, human beings would be mushy blobs. ``It presented medicine
with the precious gift of the scientific method with which to
approach an infinite number of future medical problems.''
</P>
<P>
   1628 _ William Harvey published ``De Motu Cordis'' or ``On the
Motion of the Heart,'' in which he described the functions of the
heart and the circulation of blood. Introducing his discovery of
circulation, Harvey wrote that his findings were ``of so novel and
unheard-of character, that I not only fear injury to myself from
the envy of a few, but I tremble lest I have mankind at large for
my enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   1675 _ Anton Leeuwenhoek, a haberdasher and part-time janitor,
looking at a drop of rainwater under a microscope, discovered
``little animals'' _ or bacteria, a cause of myriad diseases.
</P>
<P>
   1796 _ By using cowpox, which causes a mild disease in human
beings, to protect a person from the deadlier smallpox, Edward
Jenner discovered vaccination. His method of injecting dead
bacteria or their toxins helped eradicate smallpox, and protects
against bubonic plague, chickenpox, cholera, diphtheria, influenza,
measles, mumps, rabies, typhoid fever, tetanus and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   1842 _ Crawford Long, using ether to prevent his patients from
feeling pain, developed surgical anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   1895 _ Wilhelm Roentgen discovered the X-ray beam, and developed
one of the most important diagnostic tools.
</P>
<P>
   1907 _ Ross Harrison figured out how to grow living cells
outside the body. ``It made possible the study of living organisms
at the cellular and even the molecular level and the development of
modern vaccines . . . and abetted the search for the causes of
cancer (and AIDS). Indeed, because of tissue culture, more has been
learned about the basic mechanisms of disease in the past 50 years
than in the previous 5,000.''
</P>
<P>
   1912 _ Nikolai Anichkov discovered that cholesterol was
responsible for coronary artery disease, currently the world's most
deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
   1928 _ Alexander Fleming discovered penicillin, which led the
way for the development of antibiotics to treat infections.
</P>
<P>
   1950-53 _ Maurice Wilkins did the pioneering work of isolating a
single fiber of DNA and examining it, which James Watson and
Francis Crick used to develop their own double helix model of DNA,
the heredity-bearing molecule. Wilkins shared the Nobel Prize with
them for the discovery, which opened the door to genetics research
in 1962.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
