<HEADLINE>
COMPANY COURTED BY MAYOR OWES MONEY TO IRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The security company Mayor Willie Brown has
courted to take over patrol and guard duties in the city's public
housing owes the U.S. government more than $300,000 in unpaid
taxes, federal records show.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service filed a lien June 22 for $314,226
in back taxes, interest and penalties against Ambassador Private
Security Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hongisto, a former police chief and sheriff who heads
the security company, failed to pay taxes his company withheld from
employee payroll checks during two quarters in 1997. He said the
money was not paid because of ``explosive growth'' and temporary
cash shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Hongisto said he was working out an arrangement to pay the tax
debt and would resolve the issue before bidding on a San Francisco
Housing Authority security contract.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said on Aug. 11 that he personally solicited Hongisto to
bid on Housing Authority security contracts that now cost nearly $3
million per year. The mayor said he courted Hongisto's company
because it is based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a city-first policy. Richard's firm is out on Third
Street. He's not ever bid, and he wouldn't have this time if I had
not solicited him,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Personal Protective Services of San Mateo, hired by the Housing
Authority a year ago, has been credited with helping reduce the
crime rate in the several projects it serves. It also has been the
subject of brutality complaints from tenants. The San Francisco
police are investigating the company after allegations of excessive
force and illegal searches. The U.S. attorney's office also is
investigating the company because of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Personal Protective Services' $2.9 million contract expires in
2000, but the mayor-appointed Housing Authority Commission that
governs public housing could end it sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The Housing Authority also has security contracts with the
police and two other private companies.
</P>
<P>
   Housing Authority spokesman Ron Sonenshine said Hongisto's tax
problems wouldn't prohibit his company from getting a Housing
Authority contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no request for proposals or contract to let, so it is
almost a moot point at this junction of the game,'' Sonenshine
said. ``There is no law that would preclude anyone with a tax lien
from applying for a federal job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
