<HEADLINE>
NEW SHOWS SAFELY AVOID THE EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THAT '70s SHOW 
Starring: Topher Grace, Ashton Kutcher, Danny Masterson, Laura
Prepon, Mila Kunis, Kurtwood Smith, Debra Jo Rupp  
On: Fox, Ch.25 
Time: Sunday night at 8:30 
Rated: TVPG 
 
HOLDING THE BABY 
Starring: Jon Patrick Walker, Ron Leibman, Jennifer Westfeldt,
Eddie McClintock 
On: Fox, Ch.25 
Time: Sunday night at 7:30 
Rated: TVPG 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the turbulent 1970s, TV delivered a nostalgic family
sitcom about the 1950s called ``Happy Days.'' It was an obvious
balm for a nation in which parents were breaking apart and kids
were feeding their heads with more than Ovaltine. Fonzie was meant
to serve as the anti-social figure in the cozy ``Happy Days''
society, but Fonzie was about as threatening as a water gun.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's the 1990s and we are steeped in 1970s nostalgia, for
reasons that seem far less clear. Is it those smiley buttons we
long for? Or is it simply the Captain &AMP; Tennille? Tomorrow night at
8:30 on Ch.25, ``That '70s Show'' provides us with the newest
chapter in American entertainment's love affair with the 1970s, as
it brings elements of both ``Wayne's World'' and ``Dazed and
Confused'' to the small screen. Lava lamps, Farrah posters, sand
candles, bad haircuts, and the ``My nose!'' episode of ``The Brady
Bunch'' _ they're all back with a vengeance, along with a guest
appearance by at least one of ``Charlie's Angels,'' Tanya Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, ``That '70s Show'' is ``Happy Days'' _ only dressed
in more colorful duds. It's Richie Cunningham in bell bottoms and
Potsie in paisley. The series' formula is pretty stock teen
material, with immature guys and unsuspecting parents and ditsy
girls, but it's got a few inventively surrealistic scenes and a
breezy tone that makes it worth watching. Set in Wisconsin in 1976,
the show's central character is Eric Foreman, a sensible
17-year-old whose basement serves as the hangout for a group of
friends. There's neighbor Donna, Eric's pal and maybe girlfriend;
Kelso, a thick but sweet-natured guy; Jackie, Kelso's annoying
on-again-off-again girlfriend; Hyde, a paranoid dude of all trades;
and Fez, a forever baffled exchange student. There's also Eric's
parents, who are living out their own tacky '70s disco fantasy. All
these characters are inoffensive and easy-to-read, as are the
plots. In tonight's episode, for example, Eric's parents give him a
car, and he and the gang sneak out to a Todd Rundgren concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``That '70s Show'' has been in the news thanks to a scene in
which pot smoking is implied, though never shown. The friends sit
in a circle, as the camera work turns a little trippy, Hyde gets
more paranoid than usual, and a backdrop rocks behind Eric's
parents. In the show's defense, it is an ambiguous scene, and
younger viewers might not even recognize the drug context. Also, a
series about the 1970s would be inauthentic if it never addressed
the fact that behind every paneled basement wall there stood a
carefully stashed bong.
</P>
<P>
   The drug controversy makes the series sound edgy and realistic,
but ``That '70s Show'' is all soft edges and eight-track jokes. The
ensemble is appealing _ none of the young actors really stands out,
although Laura Prepon does look remarkably like Claire Danes _ and
the sets and costumes are a gas. The production team includes Marcy
Casey and Tom Werner of ``Roseanne,'' and Bonnie and Terry Turner
of ``3rd Rock from the Sun.'' They've got a promising series on
their hands, except, of course, for the awful title.
</P>
<P>
   Another new Fox series, ``Holding the Baby,'' premieres Sunday
night at 7:30. It is, in short, ghastly. A workaholic father named
Gordon finds that his wife has run off to Tibet with her yoga
instructor, leaving him with their infant son. Who'll take care of
the baby when Dad has to work? A bleeding-heart liberal named Kelly
applies to be his receptionist, but after some bluster around the
office about some new clients, Gordon bribes her into becoming his
new nanny. The nuttiness continues, as Gordon's do-nothing hunk of
a brother hangs around the house, wondering if the new nanny might
be willing to give him a little bit of attention, too. (This aspect
of ``Holding the Baby'' mirrors a forthcoming series from ABC
called ``Brother's Keeper.'')
</P>
<P>
   As Gordon, Jon Patrick Walker is unbearably high-strung, yelling
his lines and running around crazily to emphasize the fact that
this is meant to be farce. The only watchable character is little
Daniel, the baby, who looks like a space egg with his round bald
head and his complete lack of expression. How do you teach such
perfect deadpan to an infant? Maybe the other actors could look
into that same course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
