<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6331 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-21 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ENEMIES OF LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- When Eric Partridge saluted the 100th
anniversary of the birth of a great guardian of civic discourse, he
wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people have nothing to say, and keep on saying
it. Henry Watson Fowler had much to say, but most of us wish he had
said more on almost every subject he touched. Nor did he confine
himself to the vast field of English language. He did not, like
Goldsmith, adorn every subject he treated: he did better than that:
he enriched and illuminated it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler and Partridge regarded cliches and euphemisms as enemies
of language. They did not live long enough to see cable television,
where discourse does not enrich or illuminate, but willfully
inflicts upon the English language what the Pentagon calls
collateral damage.
</P>
<P>
   Print, too, can offend. A New York Times writer whom I admire
wrote last week that ``the president talks a good game on many of
these issues, but he has yet to really put his shoulder to the
wheel behind most of them.'' I shuddered and recalled George
Orwell's essay, ``Politics and the English Language,'' which
contains six rules, one of them: ``Never use a metaphor, simile, or
other figure of speech which you are used to seeing in print.''
</P>
<P>
   I mentally argued with the newspaper, muttering, ``Come on, pal,
it ain't brain surgery or rocket science.'' Oops. In journalism, as
in life, the temptation is always strong to first cast a stone
(John 8:7).
</P>
<P>
   Fowler warned that a cliche is ``better than the phrase that
fails.'' By definition, a cliche is obsolete jargon, sometimes
overused for centuries. Several presidents, including Thomas
Jefferson, have complained of being criticized from pillar to post,
a phrase from ancient horse-training techniques in France. We must
banish every cliche lock, stock and barrel, a phrase describing the
contents of a blunderbuss, which Partridge, in ``The Dictionary of
Cliches,'' traces to 1820.
</P>
<P>
   When I was an editor, an editorial writer warned that ``the
president and Congress are at loggerheads.'' What, I inquired, does
a loggerhead look like? The flustered polemicist stammered, ``You
know what it is!'' (It's an old iron tool.) I've never seen one.
Neither have most readers. Try something else.
</P>
<P>
   Many cliches are named after real people. The phrase ``tawdry
behavior'' has its origin in the cheap lace sold on the Isle of Ely
on the feast day of St. Audrey. A lynch mob refers to a vigilante
band in Pittsylvania County in Virginia in 1780, led by Captain
William Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The second edition of Fowler's ``Modern English Usage,'' first
published in 1926, says that euphemisms, ``a substitute for blunt
precision or disagreeable truth,'' blossomed in ``the mid-Victorian
era, when the dead were the departed, or no longer living, pregnant
women were in an interesting condition ... ladies once termed
mistresses (itself a euphemism for the earlier concubines and
paramours) are unmarried wives.''
</P>
<P>
   Orwell wrote that ``the inflated style is itself a kind of
euphemism. A mass of Latin words falls upon the facts like soft
snow, blurring the outlines and covering up all the details. The
great enemy of clear language is insincerity.''
</P>
<P>
   The euphemism in politics is hardly a modern invention.
Partridge's ``Dictionary of Cliches'' traces terminological
inexactitude, for lying, to a Winston Churchill speech in 1906.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler, Partridge, and Orwell, all English essayists, had no
cure for cliches and euphemisms, but Jonathan Swift, the Irish
satirist, suggested one approach:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blot out, correct, insert, refine,
</P>
<P>
   Enlarge, diminish, interline;
</P>
<P>
   Be mindful, when invention fails,
</P>
<P>
   To scratch your head, and bite your nails.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Swift's high-concept notion might enrich and illuminate the
audio-visual food fight among talking heads on television. It could
even be a breath of fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
