<HEADER>
A6337 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WRONGFULLY-BOS &LR;      08-21 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WRONGFULLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WRONGFULLY ACCUSED' MISSES ITS MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WRONGFULLY ACCUSED
<TEXT>
<P>
   Directed and written by: Pat Proft
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Leslie Nielsen, Richard Crenna, Kelly Le Brock, Sandra
Bernhard, Michael York, Melinda McGraw
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Stars: (BS) 1/2
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even if Leslie Nielsen isn't your edge, you have to give the
star of ``Naked Gun'' and ``Airplane'' movies credit for the
physical pain he appears to endure for the sake of every joke. In
``Wrongfully Accused,'' he returns to the screen, this time as Tom
outsmarted by Jerry, or Wile E. Coyote burned by the Road Runner.
You're expecting a banana-shaped bruise to sprout from the top of
his scalp every time he hits his head against something hard.
</P>
<P>
   So the laughs are there from time to time. No doubt, they are
laughs mixed with grossed-out grimaces _ such as in the scene when
the seductive Lauren Goodhu, played by Kelly LeBrock, sticks her
toungue into one of Nielsen's ears, and out it comes through the
other. But considering there are 100 or so intended jokes,
``Wrongfully Accused'' hits the mark about as many times as
Shaquille O'Neal makes a free throw. In other words, a lousy
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Like the ``Naked Gun'' and ``Airplane'' film series that have
distinguished Nielsen as a gag comedian, this film is a spoof of
other movies and, more generally, pop culture. In particular, the
film parodies ``The Fugitive,'' the suspense-action movie in which
Harrison Ford, running from the law, tries to prove his innocence
in his wife's murder. Nielsen plays virtuoso violinist Ryan
Harrison, pursued by the wealthy socialite Lauren. Harrison finds
the body of Lauren's husband, a toilet tycoon, and brawls briefly
with a one-armed, one-legged, one-eyed killer who is scampering
around the murder scene. Harrison is wrongfully charged with the
killing but escapes from the bus of convicts after the wheels roll
over a banana peel. In his escape from the law and quest for
vindication, Harrison meets love interest Cass Lake (Melinda
McGraw). Richard Crenna, playing a role less memorable than Tommy
Lee Jones's marshal in ``The Fugitive,'' is US Marshal Fergus
Falls, the man who tries to track down the fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite possible to sit through ``Wrongfully Accused''
without a chuckle. It's sick humor, at times, relying on material
that should just remain hands-off. But Nielsen has mastered the
bulgy-eyed or cross-eyed faces that are quite convincingly funny.
Or at least, he's trying hard, and that counts for something,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Bernhard is on the credit line banner, but her role as
the prosthetics doctor for the one-armed, one-legged, one-eyed man
is minimal and forgettable. McGraw, who has played Scully's psychic
sister on ``The X-Files,'' shows promise with her deadpan face
amidst the contrived, off-the-wall antics around her. But the best
scenes are usually crafted by Nielsen, such as when he winks at the
camera while popping a Mentos before he jumps from a high-rise
window.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, anyone who has tuned into TV and movies over the past
five years will quickly get every allusion, but laughing about it
may be another matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
