<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Aug. 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Drenching thunderstorms and gusty winds will accompany the
remnants of Tropical Storm Charley in southern Texas on Saturday.
Torrential rainfall of up to eight inches will cause local flooding
of low-lying areas. Isolated tornadoes are possible in some of the
heavier rain bands. A weak tropical disturbance will also promote
thundershowers across Florida and along the Gulf Coast. Meanwhile,
strengthening Tropical Storm Bonnie will bring gusty winds and
squally rains to the southeastern Bahamas as it tracks northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Hot conditions will dominate from the interior Southeast to the
central Plains on Saturday as strong high pressure at 18,000 feet
promotes ample sunshine and suppresses cooling showers. A front
separating the hot air to the south from a cooler air mass to the
north will be the focus for isolated thundershowers from southern
New England to the northern Ohio Valley. North of the front, ample
sunshine and less humid air will grace northern New England and the
upper Great Lakes States. Farther west, a large area of
thunderstorms will develop in the eastern Dakotas and Minnesota as
a jet stream disturbance rapidly lifts tropical air near the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonably cool air will cover the the Pacific Northwest. Low
clouds will embrace the immediate coast while mixed clouds and
sunshine dominate east of the Cascades. A weak disturbance may
ignite a few afternoon showers over the high ground of eastern
Oregon. Afternoon showers will bubble up over the southern Rockies
while seasonal heat covers the interior Southwest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Balloons in Bonnie &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening, as the sun was setting north of the Leeward
Islands, a hurricane hunter plane released 59 special weather
balloons into the circulation of Tropical Storm Bonnie. These
devices transmitted fine details of the developing storm that were
immediately fed into sophisticated computer models. The oceans,
where hurricanes grow, are huge voids of weather data makes
forecasting the storms a challenge. This experiment should help
produce better short term computer predictions which may prove
invaluable as Bonnie threatens the Southeast coast early next week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
