<HEADLINE>
HOT ITEMS: YANKEE MAGNETISM; COSTLY COCKTAILS; HIGH-TECH TREADS;
BLOW-OUT AVOIDANCE; DONUT EXPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Japanese pitcher Hideki Irabu joined the New York
Yankees last season, he spoke little English but quickly became
known for his magnetism. That is, for taping tiny magnets on his
arms before games, a practice common in Japan, where ball teams
also enlist Shinto priests and burn incense in hopes of improving
their performance.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Darryl Strawberry, Paul O'Neill, Derek Jeter and
Scott Brosius are following Irabu's lead and wearing U-shaped
magnetic bracelets, which are touted by their Japanese
manufacturer, Tsujimoto, to increase circulation, ease pain, help
balance and promote energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've heard about it, it's going to make me healthy
and I'm going to live to be 150,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Carlos Vallbona, a medical authority on magnet therapy,
said that any benefit the Yankees receive from the bracelets is
mind over magnets. ``For the magnetic field to work, magnets have
to be applied directly to the area of distress,'' he said, adding,
however, that the jewelry did work nicely with the team's 1996
World Series rings.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Yankees are on pace to win 120 games this season,
magnetic bracelets, which can be bought for $50 to $150, may not
become as common among major leaguers as batting gloves and
creatine drinks. Another Yankee, Chuck Knoblauch, recently tried
the bracelet, but during a batting slump decided to stick with just
a sweatband. _ JOE BRESCIA
</P>
<P>
   Martini Liftoff
</P>
<P>
   Did Adam Tihany's martini arrive too late? When he designed a
space-age cocktail glass for a Bombay Gin advertisement in 1992,
the martini craze was just taking off. ``That glass was my homage
to James Bond,'' Tihany said. ``It was kind of like a little rocket
launcher.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ad appeared, people wanted to know where they could buy
the handmade Venetian glass, with a sphere for a stem, set down in
a silver stand. Nowhere, unfortunately. There were only two, props
commissioned by Bombay, which held the rights.
</P>
<P>
   The rights have since reverted to Tihany, who has made 200
limited-edition glasses with Christofle. But now that martinis have
reached a saturation point, will anyone spend $550 a pop for the
glasses? In two weeks at Pavillon Christofle (800-799-6886), 50
have been sold. The thirst for martinis hasn't gone completely dry.
</P>
<P>
   _ KIMBERLY STEVENS
</P>
<P>
   Sneakers as Art
</P>
<P>
   In the window of DDC Lab, a recently opened boutique at 180
Orchard St., sneakers hang like museum pieces. Understandable,
since the treads on display are limited editions that can cost as
much as a work of art.
</P>
<P>
   Safe behind locked glass are Reebok Insta-Pump collectibles: the
$180 Bjorks (named after the Icelandic techno star); the $300
Jackie Chans, which have the Kung Fu master's signature on the
tongue and heel, and last but not least, the Hong Kong Furies, for
$2,500. These inflatable sneakers command an exorbitant price
because only 1,997 pairs were made, commemorating Hong Kong's
reversion to China last year, said Steve Gardner, a spokesman for
Reebok, which has a factory in China.
</P>
<P>
   Made in yellow, black and red _ the colors of China's flag _ the
high-tech souvenirs come with Chinese characters that read ``Hong
Kong '97,'' a gold-plated serial number and a hand-held pump. Who's
buying? A stylist, Sharon Stone, for one. But she didn't buy hers
for their historical value. ``If they cost this much, you can be
sure that not everyone walking down Broadway will have on the same
pair,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ JULIA CHAPLIN
</P>
<P>
   Let's Twist Again
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started during the first heat wave,'' explained Gwen
LeMoine Sabahi, the owner of Parlor, a three-chair salon on Ninth
Street that has produced some of the summer's most twisted hairdos.
``We were looking for a way to avoid blow-outs.'' Their solution
was a modern, disheveled version of the African Zulu knot, hair
coiled into a jumble of tiny bumps and secured with bobby pins.
Clients started dialing Parlor (212-673-5520) in droves for the
process, which takes 20 minutes, costs $30 to $50 (free with a
haircut) and can be customized: weaving wet hair into a tapestry
effect, adding flowered bobby pins or fashioning straight, dry hair
into a spiky fan. Though Scary Spice was a pioneer of the look,
teen-agers are not the only ones copying it. A pediatrician's wife
recently came in to be knotted for a wedding. ``Messy is O.K. these
days,'' Ms. Sabahi said. ``For a special occasion, you don't need a
'50s French twist.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURA BEGLEY
</P>
<P>
   Fire Island Fat Fix
</P>
<P>
   George Dellinger wakes at 5 a.m. each Sunday and begins his
donut marathon. By Jeep, ferry and, finally, little red wagon, he
races to get his cargo of Krispy Kreme donuts from Eighth Street,
where they're baked, to Fire Island Pines by 9. That's still not
early enough for many of his customers, who often have just
finished the night's dancing, haven't slept and want their fat fix.
The Pines is better known for men with firm physiques than donut
figures. But Dellinger, a party promoter inspired by his own
post-dance cravings, got an exclusive contract for Fire Island
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Sales have risen from seven boxes the first weekend to nearly
200 last week for the annual Morning Party. Orders, $10 a dozen
(versus $6 in the store): (212) 358-5736. Next year, he will expand
to Ocean Bay Park and Cherry Grove. Now, if only he could get the
Kremes there still warm. Maybe a Domino's thermal bag?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.J. SIGESMUND
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
