<HEADER>
A6363 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPICE-COLUMN-$ADV23-H     08-21 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPICE-COLUMN-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPICE DAD MUST TACKLE `GIRL POWAH' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 23) 
(Filed in ``e'' and ``l'') 
 
By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ We knew our life together had entered a new phase the
day my wife and I came home to find that our 7-year-old daughter
had decorated her room with posters of the pop group Hanson.
Seemingly overnight, Chelsea had gone from singing ``the wheels on
the bus go round and round'' to referring to Zac Hanson as her
``boyfriend in Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the idea that our little girl wasn't so little anymore
sort of snuck up on us, at least we didn't have a problem with her
choice of music. Even snobby old Dad had to admit those Hanson boys
sound pretty good compared to a lot of stuff I cover on my job as
the pop-music critic for the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   When I gave Chelsea a Beatles greatest-hits tape to demonstrate
their influence on Hanson, she immediately claimed them as her
other favorite group. Before long, we were cruising around town
together belting out ``Eight Days a Week'' and ``Help!,'' and she
was asking me if I had any photos of Paul McCartney when he was
young and cute.
</P>
<P>
   But then came the unsettling day when most of the Hanson posters
were replaced by Spice Girls posters. Chelsea suddenly stopped
talking about Isaac, Taylor and Zac and started saying things like
``Girl Powah, blah, blah, blah'' in a dead-on working-class English
accent.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing was, she couldn't do the accent right without
also affecting a Spice-like pouty tone and impudent facial
expression, as if life among the young and beautiful was to suffer
through a series of petty annoyances, most of them caused by boys.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I examined the photos of Ginger, Baby, Scary, Sporty
and Posh in their heavy makeup, short skirts and low-cut tops. ``Is
this who we want our daughter looking up to as role models?'' my
wife asked. ``They look like bad girls,'' I said. (Actually, the
word I used is one we don't ordinarily print in the newspaper.)
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea and four of her girlfriends from school organized a
Spice Girls club. Each girl assumed the role of a different Spice,
dancing and lip-syncing to the tunes. We found some solace in the
fact that Chelsea's favorite is Sporty, who prefers athletic gear
and sneakers to little Gucci dresses and spiked heels.
</P>
<P>
   But then there was the matter of the nose ring and the tattoos,
with which she developed an obsession. She spent her allowance on
one of those costume-jewelry kits for kids and emerged with three
rings in each ear, one in her nose and one in her navel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, when I turn 18, can I get a nose ring for real?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't recommend it,'' I said. ``What if you were kissing
someone else who had a nose ring and got stuck?''
</P>
<P>
   She gave me one of those petulant Girl Power looks, as if to
say, ``You really think I'm still little and stupid enough to fall
for that?''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Spiceworld: The Movie'' came out, I took Chelsea to see
it despite my wife's mild protests. To my surprise, I enjoyed it
almost as much as she did. The madcap antics of a band on the run
reminded me of a classic rock flick from when I was a kid _ the
Beatles' ``A Hard Day's Night.''
</P>
<P>
   I was also relieved that the more risque humor seemed to go over
Chelsea's head, although she clearly got the movie's main themes _
girls just wanna have fun, and no uptight male should come between
a girl and a friend in need.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so maybe the Spice Girls weren't such a bad influence after
all. But there was still the matter of the music. While I found I
could listen to Hanson's bouncy bubble-gum pop hits ``Mmmmbop!''
and ``Where's the Love'' over and over without retching, I have
considerably less tolerance for the Spice Girls' breathy, barely
tuneful vocals and factory-built disco grooves.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when I suggested to Chelsea that the Spice Girls simply
aren't as musically talented as Hanson, much less the Beatles, she
reacted as though I'd just stabbed her in the back. ``Yes, they
are!'' she exclaimed. Then she ran to her room, slammed the door
and cranked up ``Spice Up Your Life'' to maximum volume on her
boombox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where have I gone wrong?'' I wondered. This is, after all, a
kid who was rocking in the cradle to John Coltrane's ``A Love
Supreme''; who when she was 4 told anyone who asked that her
favorite music was zydeco; and who now knows the words to the
Beatles' greatest hits.
</P>
<P>
   So how come all she wants to listen to is the Spice Girls?
</P>
<P>
   Then I remembered my own childhood: how from the time I was 5
years old my parents and I fought for control of the car radio; how
when I was 9 or 10 I sat outside a restaurant transfixed by the
elemental mystery of the Exciters' ``Tell Him,'' unable to get out
of the car until the song ended, even though the rest of my family
didn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   That was my music then, and it's still my music. My daughter may
eventually outgrow the Spice Girls, just as I outgrew Jan &AMP; Dean,
but she has a right to stake out her own turf. If her parents
actually liked it, then it wouldn't really belong to her.
</P>
<P>
   And it could be a lot worse; she could have a giant poster of
Marilyn Manson hanging over her bed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(COLUMN CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when I was a kid, I never got the chance to talk to
any of my musical heroes. Because of her dad's job, Chelsea found
herself on the phone with Sporty Spice a couple of months ago.
Although Sporty was very nice, neither one had a whole lot to say
to the other. But it was enough to make a big impression on the
Spice Girls club at Chelsea's eighth birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're looking forward to the concert Tuesday in The
Woodlands, an unincorporated community of 51,000 about 30 miles
north of downtown Houston. Chelsea's been going to concerts with me
all her life, but this will be the first time she's been to a
concert of ``her'' music.
</P>
<P>
   The other day I asked my daughter what it was she liked so much
about the Spice Girls' music. She said basically the same thing
kids used to say on Dick Clark's ``American Bandstand:'' ``It's got
a good beat, and you can dance to it.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked her if she thought the Spice Girls were smart. She gave
me another one of those looks. ``If they weren't smart, how could
they be where they are?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you think they can be sexy and smart at the same time?'' I
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they can,'' she said, as if only a boy would ask
such an obvious question.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
