A6409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-FLOODS-660&AMP;ADD-     08-21 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-FLOODS-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF EFFORTS UNDER WAY FOR CHINA'S FLOOD VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL  
 &HT;     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Even as battles against raging flood waters continue
in parts of China, relief workers have begun the herculean task of
providing food, water, health care and housing to the millions who
have been displaced by the floods.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, the government has had to evacuate 13.8
million people to keep them out of harm's way, sometimes with only
a few hours' notice; 5.8 million homes have been destroyed,
government officials said. And while the battle against new crests
and flood waters may be soon drawing to a close, the relief effort
_ which experts say will take months _ is only just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Chinese are now homeless, living on dikes or in
schools or factories that have been transformed into evacuation
centers. International aid workers say it will be months before
these people can return home or be moved into more suitable
housing. And in the meantime they are at high risk for infectious
diseases, from colds to cholera.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders seem to be expecting a long haul, and on Friday
night President Jiang Zemin announced that he would postpone
important state visits to Japan and Russia that had been scheduled
for September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese are excellent at what they do, but this is really
hard: There are so many in need and it's hard to get things out
into the field,'' said Sharilyn Amy, spokeswoman for the
International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies,
which has been in Beijing for the last month to help oversee the
distribution of international aid. ``There is always flooding, but
other years were really incomparable to this.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, millions of soldiers and civilian volunteers have
been fighting raging rivers near the Yangtze and in the industrial
Northeast, working day and night, reinforcing old dikes and, where
those have broken, hastily building new ones.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a daily struggle to keep the water out of major
cities and away from important industrial sites, like the huge
Daqing oil field near the northeastern city of Harbin. The Nen
River has already submerged several thousand of the field's 20,000
oil wells, and others are at risk, according to Chinese reporters
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Factories in Harbin have been working round the clock producing
sandbags to be stacked atop the levees to prevent water from
flowing over the top.
</P>
<P>
   The nightly news has featured endless images of this struggle
with soaked soldiers in chest-high water hauling sandbags to
reinforce the dikes. There has been far less coverage of the human
displacement, in part because the government has restricted access
to the more severely affected areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese Public Health Bureau and the vast Chinese Red Cross
have nearly doubled the number of public-health teams out in the
field, to 10,000, over the past four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many people are living on dikes in China,
perched precariously on narrow man-made structures with water
lapping on both sides. But Ms. Amy, from the Federation of Red
Cross and Red Crescent Societies, said that 300,000 people were
living on dikes in the Dongting Lake area when she visited two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   She said that some had been stranded because they had no time to
evacuate, but that many others angrily defied orders so that they
could guard their property. The government intentionally blasted
dikes and flooded some villages in order to reduce water levels in
urban centers downstream.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Amy said some families had brought furniture, chickens, pigs
and even tractors. She added that the crowded living conditions,
poor sanitation and cohabitation of humans and animals made the
refugees vulnerable to disease. Many people are drinking river
water that is contaminated by human waste.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross is distributing vast supplies of
water-purification tablets, medicines and chlorine spray for
disinfecting sanitation pits and previously submerged land once the
waters recede.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Outbreaks of skin infections and infectious diarrhea have
already occurred, although more serious diseases like cholera and
typhoid that sometimes follow flooding have not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not heard of these _ yet,'' said Ms. Amy. ``And I'm
saying `yet' because there are so many people out there and the
high-risk period hasn't arrived.'' She said that such diseases tend
to occur when the flooding stops and there is standing water that
allows for the breeding of germs.
</P>
<P>
   There have been emotional benefit shows on television in Beijing
the last two nights, featuring a mix of popular performers and
representatives of companies, schools and local Communist Party
cells announcing donations in cash or in kind. The Beijing Public
Security Bureau pledged $40,000. Mrs. Xue Wen and her 17 children,
grandchildren and great-grandchildren pledged $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   But there are rumblings that government policy, as well as the
rains, is to blame for the current catastrophe. An article this
week in a popular newspaper, Southern Weekend, blamed poor dike
upkeep and clear cutting of trees as factors.
</P>
</TEXT>
