r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMENTARY-BJT22-COX     08-21 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release the weekend of Saturday, August 22,
1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ If a shamed Bill Clinton stages a comeback, it
will be because a unashamed Marion Barry serves as his de facto
political role model. Such are the wretched depths to which we have
sunk in our public life. (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED 8/21.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ President Bill Clinton's misbehaviors and the
corrosion they have set on his administration are his own fault and
his own responsibility but they never should have become a state
issue. They have because of the wanton misuse of a
special-prosecutor law and because there really was a vast
right-wing conspiracy out to get the president. (Teepen, Cox News
Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ The editorial board of the Miami News
has not met for almost 10 years. That's because the newspaper has
been out of business that long. But, after hearing Bill Clinton's
brief, incomplete talk to the nation last Monday, I wished the
board was still around _ to keep me from going off the deep end.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ IVANGOROD, Russia _ You pass through here by
train from St. Petersburg on the way to Estonia. It's the border
stop. A hundred yards or so farther down the track and you're free
and clear. I didn't make it. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN _ I was disappointed at the opening
ceremonies of the ninth annual National Poetry Slam Wednesday
afternoon at the Electric Lounge. More than 200 poets are in town
for this four-day event. And not one of these clowns recited my
favorite poem. (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ I missed it. Once again, I'm a day late and a
dollar short. Did you know there is a National Splurge Day? Neither
did I, until it was past. It's a day promoting self-indulgence and
the abdicating of responsibilities. I always miss the good stuff.
(Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ I went looking for my missing box of Ding Dongs
when I came across my youngest son, holding a foil wrapper in his
hand and looking suspicious.''I absolutely, positively did not
steal that box of pastry -- Ding Dongs,'' he said, jabbing his
finger in the air. It was a pretty strong statement and despite the
physical evidence, I believed him. (Latham, Marshall News
Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ The reason we are in a foreign country is
because of a motorcycle convention in South Dakota and all the
trouble they're having in Wisconsin. Contrary to some reports, news
that Neal Boortz and his motor home were on our trail and gaining
had nothing to do with our decision to leave our native land.
(Minter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ When I was halfway through
writing a column condemning President Clinton's treatment of his
closest supporters, my editor called an editorial board meeting to
discuss the bombings. ``What bombings?'' I asked. ``Have they
bombed us again?'' ``No,'' he said. ``Clinton ordered air strikes
against terrorists bases in Afghanistan.'' ``Awwright!'' I said.
``I'll vote for that.'' (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
