<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6417 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN22-COX     08-21 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Escaping to Canada
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This comes to you from just the other side of Bashed in Head
Buffalo Jump, located in Alberta, Canada. Bashed in Head Buffalo
Jump is where the Moye and Minter Corps of Discovery is anchored
for the night after abandoning the Lewis and Clark trail for safer
territory.
</P>
<P>
   The reason we are in a foreign country is because of a
motorcycle convention in South Dakota and all the trouble they're
having in Wisconsin. Contrary to some reports, news that Neal
Boortz and his motor home were on our trail and gaining had nothing
to do with our decision to leave our native land.
</P>
<P>
   Reading about a possible dairy cow uprising in Wisconsin, we
decided to take our chances with buffalo and elk. As some of you
may have noticed while traveling on I-75, Wisconsin advertises
itself as ``America's Dairyland.'' Until lately Wisconsinites have
been as proud of the slogan on their automobile tags as we are of
the ``Fergit Hell'' tags we buy for our pickups as soon as we get
the gun rack paid for.
</P>
<P>
   That was before animal activists decided milking a cow is
offensive. Offensive to the cow, that is. Anyone who has performed
the chore of milking a cow on a cold winter morning knows it's
offensive to the milker, especially when the cow steps in the
bucket and swats you in the face with her tail.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe we've been so callous for hundreds, even
thousands, of years, milking all those cows and encouraging small
children to drink, without ever asking how the cows felt about it.
We still don't have it straight from the cow's mouth, but
fortunately the Wisconsin activists have learned how to ``speak for
those who cannot speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   They're demanding that the governor remove the offending slogan
from that state's automobile tags. Thank goodness we're more
forward thinking in Georgia. We got ``Peach State'' off our tags
several years ago after some insensitive chamber of commerce type
stuck it on without asking the opinion of a single peach.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not ready to say that milking a cow is a crime you'd want to
impeach a president for, but the next time you order a milkshake
you might think about it. Actually, the motorcycle convention in
South Dakota worried me more than threats of cow riots in
Wisconsin. Apparently Moye and Minter and Lewis and Clark are the
only folks who come to that part of the country not riding a
motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived in Sturgis, S.D., simultaneously with 250,000 _ maybe
up to a half-million, according to the papers _ Harley-Davidsons
and their riders. They had to skin half the cows in Texas to make
all the leather we saw in Sturgis and still didn't have enough to
adequately cover the female riders. I won't even go into the
tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard that motorcycle gangs include doctors, lawyers,
accountants and elderly TV weathermen, but I don't think they came
to Sturgis. We did meet one fellow who said he was from Oregon, on
his way to Florida to teach history and law. Probably somebody
Steve Spurrier hired to tutor his football team.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't get really nervous about the motorcycles until we went
to dinner at what we thought was one of the nicer restaurants in a
nearby village. Captain Moye, with all the elan we've come to
expect from residents of Northside Fayetteville, perused the wine
list, selecting a vintage white zinfandel. The steward poured the
ceremonial sip and let Captain Moye sniff the cork. We did have one
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you serving wine in plastic cups?'' inquired Mrs.
Moye. ``Back home many of the better restaurants use glasses,
especially in Peachtree City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally we do, too,'' explained the steward, ``but we never
put glasses on the table when bikers are in town.''
</P>
<P>
   I hope I'm not offending anyone when I say I've long been wary
of motorcycle riders. Even when they're old and fat and needing a
shave they seem to appeal to womenfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when I was posing as a newspaper editor, we decided
to hire a nonconventional columnist to attract nonreaders.
Newspaper executives, for some strange reason, often value
nonreaders above readers.
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing her resume I asked the young lady how a
preacher's wife in Texas got to be a nonconventional newspaper
columnist in Atlanta. She said one Sunday morning after services,
while her minister husband was shaking hands with his departing
flock, she wandered out to the street just as some fellows drove up
on their Harleys. One asked her if she'd like a ride. She said yes,
hopped on, and just kept riding. Left a pot roast in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of how much my own wife, a direct descendant of Marco
Polo, likes to travel, I was anxious to get out of Sturgis. That is
why, with apologies to Lewis and Clark, we are in Bashed in Head
Buffalo Jump, heading home to check the deer damage, and hopefully
before tomatoes quit bearing and the beans get too husky to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
