<P>
   GEORGIA-PACIFIC _ With the stock prices of forest products
companies in a slump and Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s at the bottom of
the group, Chairman Pete Correll has indicated he'd be willing to
sell the company. He also told an analyst recently he'd be willing
to buy, too, but acknowledged the company's price-to-earnings ratio
was currently too low relative to the rest of the industry. Also
will get a read on whether the company will resume the
share-repurchase program it had to halt June 30 and GP's take on
how it will fare given the industry's gloomy forecast for both its
building products and pulp and paper businesses. (Mitchell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH MUGSHOT and GRAPHIC comparing GP's stock
price versus rest of industry.
</P>
<P>
   ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RED _ Human Code co-founder Chipp Walters has reached an
agreement with the company to create a new company that will
develop new media products. Walter's new company, Red Echo, will
focus on an animated television series called ``Mission to
Avalon.'' (Hawkins, Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-DRIVE _ Yukon Denali sport-utility vehicle. (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   HONDA _ Honda Motor Co., Japan's third-largest automaker,
continued its record earnings pace by reporting that first-quarter
group profits rose 25.7 percent as strong U.S. sales made up for
sinking car sales in Japan. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN-REALESTATE _ AUSTIN _ In July 1993, the Prominent Pointe
office building in Northwest Austin sold for $10 million _ close to
$67 a square foot. While Prominent Pointe clearly carried a
prominent pricetag, it wasn't a record. But are the sky-high
skyscraper sales an indication that prices may be reaching their
peak? (Breyer, Austin American Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN-CONVENTION _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Now that the City of Austin
is planning to double the size of its convention center, officials
want to make sure there will be enough hotel rooms to accommodate
the added conventioneers. Beginning Friday, August 22, the city
will run ads in The Wall Street Journal, the Austin
American-Statesman and on the Urban Land Institute's Internet site
seeking developers to build and operate an 800-room convention
center hotel and 1,000-car parking garage near the convention
center, at Cesar Chavez and Red River streets. Developers have
until Oct. 6 to respond. (Breyer, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CRUISETERMINAL _ RIVIERA BEACH _ The architectural firm
Zeidler, Roberts &AMP; Associates recently unveiled its design for a
$12 million cruise terminal that is expected to become the
signature building for the Port of Palm Beach. The five-story
complex _ which, fittingly enough, resembles a ship _ is a key
element in the port's three-year, $65 million expansion. The
90,000-square-foot terminal also is widely expected to be the
cornerstone of a revitalization effort along the Riviera Beach
waterfront. (Utley, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ABLE-TELCOM _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Able Telcom Holding Corp.
has named its fourth chief executive in as many years in an effort
to stabilize the company and jump-start its flagging stock. Robert
Dupuis, a wireless telecommunications executive who lives in Boca
Raton, was picked as Able's top executive after a five-month search
by Korn/Ferry International, a Los Angeles-based executive
headhunting firm. He will start August 25 as Able Telcom's
president, director and CEO. (Murawski, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
