<HEADLINE>
STOCKS TUMBLE AS HONG KONG ENDS MARKET INTERVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ After a weeklong buying spree to prop up the
slumping stock market here, the Hong Kong government let the free
market take over Friday. And stocks promptly tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   To critics of the government, the abrupt reversal is proof that
its decision to intervene last Friday was wrongheaded _ a temporary
victory that will cost Hong Kong its reputation as a free-market
bastion in a region where governments do not hesitate to manipulate
markets.
</P>
<P>
   To supporters, the decline merely represents a tactical pause in
the government's campaign against currency speculators. They note
that since the Hong Kong Monetary Authority began buying stocks
last Friday, the Hang Seng index of 33 leading stocks jumped 16
percent, before Friday's decline.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that Hong Kong curbed its purchases of shares
and futures contracts, and may even have sold some shares. As a
result, the Hang Seng declined 214.9 points, or 2.8 percent, to
7,523.61 Friday. Hang Seng index futures plunged 2.8 percent in the
final five minutes of trading, as brokers who had been buying for
the government stopped, prompting a flood of last-minute sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clear message to investors is: Lock in your gains and get
out,'' said Adrian Faure, head of China and Hong Kong research at
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. in Hong Kong. ``This market is artificially
inflated.''
</P>
<P>
   Faure estimated that the government spent between $640 million
and $770 million of its foreign reserves to buy shares of blue-chip
firms. That is less than 1 percent of Hong Kong's almost $100
billion in reserves, but some analysts said the money could have
been better spent elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong may have more financial resources than other Asian
economies, but using its reserves for this is a waste,'' said Chia
Yew Boon, research director at Santander Investment Securities in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong officials spent the week defending the decision to
intervene in the market. They said it was a necessary response to
hedge funds that were improperly manipulating the territory's
financial markets. The speculative attacks, they said, were
destabilizing Hong Kong and fraying consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not out there to support the stock market at a certain
level, we are not out there to support the stock market at any
level,'' said Tung Chee-hwa, the chief executive of Hong Kong, in a
speech here on Thursday. ``It is a very defensive effort targeted
specifically at this particular action.''
</P>
<P>
   Tung insisted that Hong Kong ``was not departing from our
traditional free-market economy principles,'' though he added that
the government would consider intervening again if traders
continued speculating against the Hong Kong dollar with the goal of
depressing share prices.
</P>
<P>
   It is that sort of open-ended statement that worries analysts
like Faure. He said that as long as the government was willing to
prop up the stock market, investors could not be sure of its
commitment to linking the Hong Kong dollar to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hong Kong's monetary system, known as a currency board,
the Hong Kong dollar is pegged to the U.S. dollar at a ratio of 7.8
to 1. When traders sell the currency in large volumes, the board
can act to raise interbank interest rates, which draws dollars back
into the system.
</P>
<P>
   A side effect of the rise in interest rates is a decline in
stock prices, in part because the Hang Seng is heavily weighted
with shares of property and financial companies, which are
sensitive to rising rates. In effect, Hong Kong's stock market
absorbs the pain of maintaining the value of its currency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By arresting the slide of the stock market, some analysts said
Hong Kong was implicitly acknowledging that it was no longer
willing to tolerate the pain that goes with having a fixed exchange
rate.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling than the mechanics is the symbolism. Investors
are accustomed to government intervention in financial markets in
countries like Japan, Korea and Malaysia. But Hong Kong has always
operated without government interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a signal,'' Chia said. ``Investors say, `I thought
only the Japanese and Malaysians rigged the market. But now Hong
Kong does, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone thinks the intervention was ill advised. Miron
Mushkat, the director of strategy at Indocam Asia Asset Management,
said the government had legitimate concerns that the maneuvers of a
small circle of hedge funds were causing havoc for every
shareholder in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Mushkat said he was troubled last Friday, when Hong Kong's
financial secretary, Sir Donald Tsang, announced the intervention
as if it were a vendetta against currency traders. But Sir Donald
has since taken a lower profile, while Joseph Yam, the cool-headed
chairman of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority, has emerged as the
government's chief spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Given Yam's more reasoned tone, Mushkat said he was now
convinced that Hong Kong was fighting a tactical battle rather than
an all-out war. ``The policy- makers should act to protect the
interests of the whole community, not the interests of a few hedge
funds,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
