<HEADER>
A6439 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEST-LOOKOUTS-HNS &LR;      08-21 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEST-LOOKOUTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S BEST LOOKOUT POINTS GIVE MORE THAN DRAMATIC VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The power of a special place is difficult to
define, but for those who have felt it, easy to understand.
</P>
<P>
   California's 25 best lookouts are much that way. You get more
than a dramatic view _ you also get a sensation that goes with it,
and that is why the experience can stay with you _ sometimes for
years.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights of the best viewpoints in California include
long-distance panoramas from mountain tops, an aerial tramway,
famous and not-so-famous lookouts, from San Francisco to Mount
Shasta to distant canyon rims at sunrise. To be eligible for
consideration, all viewpoints had to be reachable in one day's
hiking from San Francisco, and while some require long, ambitious
climbs, others require just a ride in a car and short walks.
</P>
<P>
   All share one element: They are places so gifted with natural
beauty that you leave refreshed, infused with the beauty, a feeling
that can be recharged for months.
</P>
<P>
   Here are my rankings:
</P>
<P>
   1. Glacier Point, Yosemite National Park. There is no more
perfect view anywhere, and anyone can reach the point by car or
shuttle bus. Yet the experience can be enhanced by taking either of
two trails (Panorama or Pohono) that provide a far more private and
extended tour into California's most breathtaking landscape.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mount Tallac, Tahoe National Forest. Looking down from
Tallac's 9,735-foot summit, the cobalt-blue waters of Lake Tahoe
cradled in an alpine mountain bowl make this one of the most
breathtaking sights in the world. From Mount Tallac, directly below
you is Fallen Leaf Lake, Emerald Bay and then Tahoe, all of it
surrounded by forest and sky, and you may even feel blessed to take
in such a pristine view. The hike up requires a climb of 3,175 feet
over the course of 6 miles. It's a tough trip, and you may ask,
``Can it be worth it?'' Yes. Yes. Yes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mount Eddy, Shasta-Trinity National Forest. You can sit here
in awe for hours, as if you are absorbing power as well as beauty.
You see, Mount Shasta is by far California's most beautiful
mountain, and though it is visible from a 125-mile radius, there is
no more stunning viewpoint than from the top of Mount Eddy. That is
because Mount Eddy (9,025 feet) is set directly to the west of
Mount Shasta (14,162 feet), with Interstate 5 (at 3,200 feet)
running right down the middle between them, so you get a powerful
impression of how Shasta rises up 11,000 feet from the valley
floor.
</P>
<P>
   4. San Jacinto Peak (via aerial tramway), Mount San Jacinto
State Park. From start to finish, there is no experience like this
anywhere in California. From near the town of Banning, you start
the trip by taking the Palm Springs Aerial Tramway, which carries
you nearly 6,000 feet to the staging area at 8,516 feet. With
long-distance views en route, for many, this is the end of the
trip. But it gets even better: A 2,300-foot climb over the course
of 6 miles takes to San Jacinto Peak, 10,804 feet high, where it
can feel like you can see to infinity: virtually all of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   5. Mount Livermore (at night), Angel Island State Park. At
night, San Francisco is transformed into the Emerald City, and the
bay area becomes a land of charm when seen from the top of 781-foot
Mount Livermore. Long after the last ferry boat has left for the
day, the view is available only for those spending the night,
camping at one of the hike-in sites.
</P>
<P>
   6. Coast Trail, Point Reyes National Seashore. In one turn of
the body, you can take in a view like no other. My favorite lookout
here is 2 miles north of Wildcat Camp on the Coast Trail, where
there is a rock outcrop that towers over the coast. From north to
south, it feels as if you are absorbing the view, taking in Point
Reyes, Drake's Bay, Sculptured Beach, Arch Rock, then turning and
scanning miles of ocean, and onward south to Alamere Falls, Wildcat
Lake, Stormy Stack and miles of untouched coast. You may also spot
passing whales, ships and fishing boats, pelicans, cormorants and
murres.
</P>
<P>
   7. Mount Whitney, John Muir Wilderness. You have foothold in the
sky atop Mount Whitney, at 14,496 feet, the highest point in the
continental United States. Both near and far, and in all
directions, the view is staggering. To the north are rows of
mountain peaks (dozens over 12,000 feet) lined up for 125 miles; to
the east is an awesome drop of 11,000 feet into the Owens Valley;
to the west is the entire Great Western Divide.
</P>
<P>
   8. Klamath Overlook, Redwood National Park. Where else can you
sense the curvature of the earth? Nowhere better than on the Requa
Trail, and it can trigger all kinds of special feelings. The
Klamath Overlook is located just north of the Klamath River in
Redwood National Park, where you can drive to a pretty viewpoint of
the ocean. It turns out that this is just a start. From here, you
then hike off, climbing 2,000 feet over the course of 4 miles to
this drop-dead gorgeous view, where you really can see that the
horizon is curved, that the earth is round. It can set off emotions
you'll never forget.
</P>
<P>
   9. Sierra Buttes Lookout Station, Tahoe National Forest. It's a
euphoric sensation at the Sierra Buttes Lookout, where you stand on
a mesh-like metal deck, allowing you to look straight down, with
nothing but air beneath your boots for what seems a thousand feet.
The views of the Sierra Nevada stretch out for miles, to Mount
Lola, Castle Peak, Grouse Ridge and French Meadows Reservoir, but
what strikes the heart is the nearby panorama, of the nearby
Sardine Lakes, and the vertical drop on the Buttes' east face.
</P>
<P>
   10. Eagle View, Sequoia National Park. A hike of less than a
mile will take you to one of the best lookouts in the Sierra
Nevada. From the Crescent Meadow Parking Area in Sequoia National
Park, a half-mile walk will take you to a ridge on the High Sierra
Trail, and thus the views begin. It takes only about 15, 20 minutes
to Eagle View. At your feet is a plunging canyon, and as you scan
beyond, the landscape is highlighted by awesome Moro Rock (a
6,725-foot granite dome), Castle Rocks (granite spires) in the
relative foreground, with the horizon sprinkled with peaks all the
way to the Great Western Divide.
</P>
<P>
   Best of the rest:
</P>
<P>
   11. Kearsage Pass, Mount Whitney Ranger District, John Muir
Wilderness. 12. East Peak Lookout, Mount Tamalpais State Park. 13.
Yosemite Point, Yosemite National Park. 14. Shasta summit, Mount
Shasta Wilderness. 15. Cascade Falls (from the brink), Lake Tahoe
Basin.
</P>
<P>
   16. Thousand Island Lake, Ansel Adams Wilderness. 17. Fresno
Dome, Sierra National Forest. 18. Land's End (at sunrise), San
Francisco, Golden Gate National Recreation Area. 19. Mount Baldy,
Angeles National Forest. 20. San Pablo Ridge (at sunset) Wildcat
Regional Park.
</P>
<P>
   21. Lassen Summit, Lassen Volcanic National Park. 22. Hawk Hill,
Marin Headlands, Golden Gate National Recreation Area. 23. Half
Dome, Yosemite National Park. 24. Preston Peak, Siskiyou
Wilderness, Smith River National Recreation Area.; 25. Mt. Elwell,
Lakes Basin Recreation Area, Plumas National Forest.
</P>
</TEXT>
