<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCANDAL-CLOTHES-$ADV2     08-21 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCANDAL-CLOTHES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FUTURE WILL KNOW THEM FOR WHAT THEY WORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 23.)  
(js) 
 BY JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was, of course, the telltale navy dress, apparently a
simple little number, not a fancy designer creation but an
off-the-rack staple from a store as unremarkable as the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the beret. Maybe it was not the fashion statement
that Monica Lewinsky wanted to be remembered for. But an endlessly
repeated snippet of videotape has locked it in the national memory
as indelibly as her pre-makeover helmet hair.
</P>
<P>
   Louis XIV, who knew a few things about closed-door doings in the
chambers of power, said that fashion is a mirror of history. So it
is no surprise that clothing has figured prominently in the furor
over President Clinton's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky: the dress
and a T-shirt from the Black Dog restaurant on Martha's Vineyard,
which he apparently gave her _ and a tie that she is said to have
given him.
</P>
<P>
   There is a school of historians that argues that things _
``material culture,'' some call them _ can tell at least as much
about political events as closely reasoned analysis. They find
evidence in the display cases of museums, among the coats and wigs
of the past, for this is certainly not the first time that apparel
has been talked about at the highest levels of American government.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon mentioned his wife's ``good Republican cloth
coat'' in his Checkers speech in 1952. Nixon was denying spending
an $18,000 political fund on luxuries for himself and his family.
And Dwight Eisenhower's aide Sherman Adams had to resign after
accepting a vicuna coat from a lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Coats were also a problem for Chester Arthur, the 21st
president. He was criticized for owning too many _ 24 in all. ``He
was a dandy,'' the historian Henry Graff said, without suggesting
that anyone but Arthur had selected the coats that filled his
closet. ``It was just that this was a lavish guy in a time when the
class struggle grew keener.''
</P>
<P>
   A century later, Ronald Reagan defended his wife for wearing
dresses she borrowed from well-known designers. ``If she'd spent
the money, she'd have been criticized anyway, and here she was
criticized for getting them free,'' said Valerie Steele, the chief
curator of the museum of the Fashion Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Watergate burglars wore gloves, and other Nixon-era
operatives are remembered for their elaborate spy disguises. But
Warren Harding's letters were steamier than Nixon's tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you garbed,'' Harding declared to a woman not his wife,
``but naked more.'' Later he complained to another woman he was
involved with that she spent too much on clothes _ specifically, on
a fur coat she wore when she visited him at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The author Wesley Hagood writes that Harding made the first
remark to Carrie Phillips, with whom he had an on-and-off affair
over 15 years. The second was to Nan Britton, who was still in
school when they began seeing each other.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes Miss Britton intended to wear to their first
encounter are documented: a brand-new gray tailored suit and a dark
blue sailor hat with a gray veil. But there is a but: ``It is
unlikely she had time to change from her school outfit before
arriving at the Manhattan Hotel,'' Hagood speculates, describing
how Harding planted himself on the hotel steps, the better to see
her as she approached.
</P>
<P>
   Hagood suggests that all they did on that occasion was talk,
though they adjourned to his room, which happened to be the hotel's
bridal suite. After describing other meetings in hotel rooms,
Hagood writes, ``Nan believed she was safe and would not become
pregnant if she kept her clothes on.'' (She later had a child that
she said was Harding's.)
</P>
<P>
   But in the fashion-obsessed '90s, Walt Whitman's ``Leaves of
Grass,'' a copy of which Clinton is said to have given Ms.
Lewinsky, has not caught the public imagination the way Ms.
Lewinsky's beret has. ``The beret was a traditional kind of hat
wear for French men, and it was very much associated in World War
II with Frenchness,'' Ms. Steele said. ``But it became kind of
corrupted with French Fascists who were associating with the Nazis,
so there was a falling off of wearing berets after World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   And for women, berets were a minor trend in millinery, hard to
wear well and perhaps too flashy for the buttoned-down, sack-suited
look of official Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing about clothing is it is the object which is
closest to the naked human body,'' Ms. Steele said. ``It's also
closest to personal identity. We won't be too upset if someone
criticizes the furniture in the living room, but we'd be very hurt
if someone criticized or laughed at our clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   This raises a question unlikely to be asked by the prosecutors
in their workday uniforms: What, really, was the message Ms.
Lewinsky was sending when she gave the president a $100-plus
Ermenegildo Zegna tie? She is said to have told him, ``When I see
you wearing this tie, I'll know that I am close to your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Was she prompting Clinton to dress more fashionably?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele recalled Thoreau's warning: ``Beware of all
enterprises that require new clothes.'' She added: ``Only an
American could have come up with that. I think this is a very
American saga. In France they could have exchanged apartment
buildings and jewels, and it still wouldn't have been anybody's
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMBRUGLIA-SINGER-ART-     08-21 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMBRUGLIA-SINGER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SOAP STAR, VIA CAREER CRISIS, TO HIT SINGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LUISITA LOPEZ TORREGROSA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She recorded one of the top-selling albums of the
year so far, but when Natalie Imbruglia, a small, slender figure in
jeans and a T-shirt, with sunglasses propped on her head, moved
through Nobu restaurant in SoHo recently, she was barely noticed.
Her cover-girl face, featured in magazines and music videos and on
billboards, drew not a glance.
</P>
<P>
   This didn't seem to surprise her a bit. A former teen-age
soap-opera star in Australia, she came out of nowhere to crash the
pop-music scene. And she is well aware that many who have done the
same disappeared even more quickly than they emerged.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something about ``Torn,'' the heartbreak hit that
helped her album, ``Left of the Middle'' (RCA Records), go
platinum, that has led more than one critic to forecast a
continuing career for this 23-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   The song, written by three other musicians, had been recorded
several times by others but never with this success. A catchy
melody with a rhythmic rock groove, the song has ``Imbruglia's sad
vocals reaching a true lonely girl splendor,'' said Rob Sheffield's
review in Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   The song topped the charts in Britain and then in the United
States a few months after she made her first trip to a recording
studio. The album made its debut in the United States in March at
the No. 10 spot in Billboard's chart, rare for a disc by a
newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so prepared for the worst that it took me a while to
relax,'' Ms. Imbruglia said over lunch. ``Everyone was excited
around me, but I was almost too scared that it might go away.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't. With some potent support from RCA and the Creative
Artists Agency, Ms. Imbruglia plans to make her first concert tour
of the United States in the fall. ``I'm scared,'' she said, as she
pushed her flyaway hair from her eyes. ``I get scared about the
next album, the next song, the next everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Imbruglia (pronounced im-BRUE-lee-uh) was born in Campsie, a
suburb of Sydney, Australia, the second of four daughters of an
Italian father and an Australian mother. ``The Italian culture was
extreme and the Anglo-Saxon side was extreme,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As she grew up in the beach town of Berkeley Vale, her life was
centered on dancing and singing lessons and her parents' financial
sacrifices. Her mother was a teacher; her father switched from
business to business _ a screen-printing shop, a corner store, a
plant nursery. ``He would build them up and then he would be
overworked and he would move to something else. Money was always an
issue,'' Ms. Imbruglia said.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple put their daughters in Roman Catholic schools and
dancing classes, and at 13, Natalie began voice lessons. ``My
mother paid for all,'' she said. ``I felt it. I felt bad.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not her only worry. Boys made fun of her Italian name
and shouted slurs at her. She struggled with that until she was
around 12: ``I made myself fit in. I did what all kids do.''
</P>
<P>
   Later she quit high school and enrolled at a performing arts
college in Sydney. She dropped out again and tried acting. At 16,
she was doing commercials and had a role in ``Neighbors,'' a soap
opera popular in Australia and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go clubbing, drinking _ vodka and lemon soda back
then,'' she recalled. ``I was living the lifestyle because I was
famous. It affected me then in ways it doesn't now. I had money. If
I was depressed, I could go shopping. I was a little big for my
breeches.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, in 1994, she left the soap and moved to London,
and for a time enjoyed the lingering adulation. Then she crashed.
She couldn't get work as an actress. She was broke. Her visa was
expiring. Out of desperation, she said, she started writing. ``I'll
never forget sitting in my bedroom, getting a pen and paper, and
feeling stupid for ever thinking I could write songs.''
</P>
<P>
   An encounter at a bar changed that. She met Anne Barrett, now
her manager, who encouraged her to take her work to Phil
Thornalley, a producer, musician and co-writer of ``Torn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She brought me a schoolbook full of songs,'' Thornalley said.
``Her songs were a little bit different from most pop hits, more
left of center. We picked a few and started putting music to the
lyrics. The collaboration evolved. She does a lot of the melody,
she's very much in there, helping with the arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornalley played ``Torn'' for her, and it was her demo tape of
the song that locked the deal with RCA.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Levy, music editor of Rolling Stone, said that her album as
a whole did not match ``Torn.'' But he saw the potential for a long
career: ``People have one-hit singles, sell a lot of records and
disappear. She has yet to disappear. She's really just at the
starting point. It's incumbent on her record company to break
another song and see if they can broaden her field, take someone
who has become a sensation on the basis of one song and build a
career. If they don't, it won't be Natalie Imbruglia's fault. It
used to take people years to do what she's done in a matter of
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Other reviewers have been cooler, contending that she has
exploited the rage for angst-ridden female pop stars like Alanis
Morissette, whose ``Jagged Little Pill'' fired up the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an easy prey for critics,'' Ms. Imbruglia said. ``Pretty
face, pop artist, I used to be on a soap. It doesn't take much
criteria to be compared to Alanis Morissette. Be young, be female,
have a few angry songs and you are Alanis. It's something I was
aware was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   She has released another song from her album, ``Wishing I Was
There,'' which she co-wrote, along with black-and-white video that
is getting heavy airplay and moving up the charts. She will soon
release her third video, ``Smoke,'' and begin writing songs and
compiling her next album.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said: ``I don't check the music charts every week. I
actually keep myself far from it. If all this went tomorrow, my
world wouldn't fall apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
