<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6463 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLISTI-MUSIC-REVIEW-     08-21 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLISTI-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I SOLISTI VENETI: SAVORING AN APPETIZER OF ITALIAN SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For fans of Baroque music in the 1960s, I Solisti
Veneti often seemed like a vast offshore recording factory. The
chamber orchestra and its director, Claudio Scimone, plowed through
scores by the ream and churned out hundreds of disks for the French
Erato label, many of which were available inexpensively through the
Musical Heritage Society's mail-order record club. In more recent
times the group has been eclipsed by period instrument bands, but
Scimone and company have continued their explorations, both in the
Baroque and into the 19th century, and they have found ways to keep
their performing style fresh.
</P>
<P>
   For its contribution to the Mostly Mozart Festival at Avery
Fisher Hall on Thursday evening, the group presented an overview of
Italian compositional styles, from Vivaldi's to Rossini's. By far
the most compelling piece on the program was Boccherini's Symphony
in D minor (Op. 12, No. 4), a tone painting in three slow movements
(although the first and third have quick sections within them)
subtitled ``La Casa del Diavolo'' (``The Devil's House'').
</P>
<P>
   Boccherini's string writing is foreboding from the opening bars,
and touches like the brief horn bursts in the first movement and
the torrential string writing in the finale keep the work's
atmosphere changeable and its path unpredictable. Scimone and his
players supported Boccherini's coloristic touches with fluid
dynamics _ including some exquisite pianissimo playing _ and a
gorgeously balanced sound.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Vivaldi's less frequently heard violin concertos filled
out the first half of the program. Marco Fornaciari, the
orchestra's concertmaster, played the ``Grand Mogul'' Concerto in D
(RV. 208), an almost operatic work with an elegantly spun, songlike
slow movement surrounded by dramatic allegros. Myriam Dal Don, who
is listed on the roster as principal violinist, gave a graceful and
appealingly crisp account of the solo line in the Concerto in C
(RV. 581), a work in which the violin mediates between two distinct
orchestral groups. Both concertos demanded considerable virtuosity
of the soloists, whose able and sometimes brilliant readings were
tarnished slightly by passing touches of stridency.
</P>
<P>
   As unpredictable as the works on the first half of the program
were, the second half was largely a write-off. Tartini's Trumpet
Concerto afforded opportunities for the ensemble's trumpeter, Mauro
Maur, to show his bright tone and considerable agility, but the
work itself was bland and virtually featureless. Instrumental works
by Donizetti and Rossini are comparatively rare, but after a few
bars a listener is on entirely familiar ground: these pieces are
made of the same formulaic, mind-numbingly trivial chirping that
drives these composers' operas. Only the species of warbler has
changed: in Donizetti's Concertino in G, it is an English horn, and
Giuseppe Falco played it deftly; in Rossini's Variations on a Theme
from ``La Donna del Lago,'' Lorenzo Guzzoni played the solo
clarinet line with energy and spirit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
