<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CLINTON-WEEK-ADV0     08-21 2181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-WEEK-ADV08/23 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE BIZARRE, UNPREDICTABLE, HISTORIC WEEK THAT WAS
 &HT;    Advance for Sunday, August 23
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was muggy on Monday, a sticky, sweaty day in the
nation's capital, and room service at the Hay-Adams Hotel stayed
busy carrying bottled water and other refreshments to the TV crews
and correspondents working on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Located across Lafayette Park from the White House, the hotel
provides a picturesque perspective on history. And network anchors
Tom Brokaw of NBC and Peter Jennings of ABC and other newsmen wise
in the use of imagery chose this vantage point from which to report
the dramatic story unfolding at 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The whole world was watching.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that at the E. Everett Prettyman U.S. Courthouse,
several blocks away, federal marshals stuck pieces of dark paper
over the panes of glass above the guarded doors leading into U.S.
District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson's paneled courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Via closed-circuit television, Judge Johnson and 23 grand jurors
inside that darkened courtroom would be among the very few people
to witness the long, long day's first momentous event _ a five-hour
afternoon interrogation of President Clinton by independent counsel
Kenneth Starr and other prosecutors investigating whether the
president engaged in an illegal cover-up of a sexual affair with
young intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's second historic event in the White House Map Room would
attract a global audience, though, as Clinton went on national
television at 10 p.m. (Eastern time) to admit having an improper
relationship with Lewinsky and misleading the nation and his family
about it for seven months.
</P>
<P>
   The president's speech lasted just over four minutes, but
airwaves were filled for hours with opinions on what it all meant.
The final room service delivery to the roof of the Hay-Adams would
not come until 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the crowd that had stood on the sidewalk beside
Pennsylvania Avenue and peered at the White House through a
wrought-iron fence had dispersed. Police had taken away the young
man who screamed something about Iraq and stabbed himself in the
neck with a screwdriver. Gone was the group that sweltered in
overcoats and carried signs protesting Clinton's ``Snow Job'' and
``Blizzard of Lies.'' The TV correspondents had finally abandoned a
strip of crushed gravel _ dubbed ``Pebble Beach'' by photographers
_ that was laid to spare the presidential lawn when ``stand-ups''
are done with the North Portico as a backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   But in the basement of the Old Executive Office building, a
stone's throw from the Oval Office and from the TV stand-up sites,
military and intelligence planners from the CIA and Pentagon were
still working on a secret mission that would make the end of this
week as memorable as the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how Washington wished Tuesday that body language could truly
reveal the thoughts of the First Family.
</P>
<P>
   The heat and humidity of the previous day had mercifully
dissipated by mid-afternoon when the Clintons strode dutifully but
awkwardly across the South Lawn to the helicopter that would take
them on the first leg of their trip to Martha's Vineyard for a
planned two-week vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea Clinton, the 18-year-old daughter, walked between her
parents and clasped a hand of both _ trying to hold her hurting
family together in the opinions of countless armchair analysts who
watched on TV. First Lady Hillary Clinton walked stiffly, mostly
keeping her eyes straight ahead, looking as happy as a wife whose
husband had confessed marital infidelity on national TV the night
before. The president, improbably dressed in a dark suit and tie
for his trip to the beach, held his Labrador, Buddy, on a leash
with his right hand and smiled and chatted with Chelsea during the
walk.
</P>
<P>
   On the walk, Bill and Hillary Clinton did not speak to each
other, but only an hour earlier the First Lady's spokeswoman had
released a statement that ``she is committed to her marriage and
loves her husband and daughter very much.'' Later, aboard Air Force
One, the president sat at a table while his daughter and wife sat
together elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the president's speech was receiving withering
reviews _ too much anger and self pity, too little contrition and
apology _ on editorial pages across the country and from
politicians of both parties. The words and tone also upset a
besieged young woman whom the world has glimpsed almost daily but
never heard for the past seven months. Reports soon circulated that
Monica Lewinsky was angered and saddened by the president's
depiction of their relationship. Friends said she considered their
bonds emotional as well as sexual and that she had been led to
believe they had a future together.
</P>
<P>
   On this Earth, at least, there is no future for the father and
son whose remains were mournfully borne in flag-draped caskets to
Arlington National Cemetery on Tuesday. Among the Americans killed
at the August 7 bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, were
Julian Bartley, Sr., a 54-year-old career diplomat, and his
namesake and only son, Julian ``Jay'' Bartley, Jr., a 20-year-old
sophomore at the U.S. International University there.
</P>
<P>
   Their untimely deaths were the products of ``cowardly, inhumane,
ungodly actions of vicious, deranged minds,'' said retired
ambassador Terence Todman, a family friend who spoke at the
memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   Their deaths would soon be revenged.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent most of Wednesday in seclusion on Martha's
Vineyard, emerging briefly to walk Buddy on the beach
</P>
<P>
   while wearing a sweater tossed casually over his shoulders.
Meanwhile, most folks were talking about his neckties.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times broke a story that prosecutors suspected that
the president was signaling Lewinsky on the day she testified _
August 6 _ by wearing a tie she had given him. The tie, which
Clinton wore in televised appearances that day, was a patterned,
gold-and-blue, $100 imported silk Zegna. Lewinsky said that when
she gave Clinton the tie for his 50th birthday, she had told him:
``When I see you wearing this tie, I'll know I am close to your
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidently, Clinton celebrated his 52nd birthday on Wednesday
with a barbecued chicken dinner at friend and grand jury witness
Vernon Jordan's vacation home on the island. He received a blue
sweater made with wool from Martha's Vineyard sheep.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, Clinton spoke four times by phone with Samuel
``Sandy'' Berger, his national security advisor, and was reassured
that planning was on track for two missile attacks at terrorists in
retaliation for the bombings that killed the Bartley men and over
260 other people in Kenya and Tanzania. Berger, who had stayed in
Washington, also phoned House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and
other congressional leaders to alert them that military action is
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The corridors of Capitol Hill were occupied mostly by tourists.
Congress was in recess. Back in their home states, a few members
called for Clinton to resign but most were silent _ waiting to see
how the scandal plays out with the voters. At the federal
courthouse, a cool breeze blew across a largely deserted Monica
Beach _ the plaza and sidewalk where newspeople stake out Starr's
investigation _ as the grand jury took a day off. Inside, though,
secrecy still reigned _ albeit it in an unrelated case _ as a
federal appeals court ruled that the public and press cannot
witness the Justice Department's pretrial questioning of Microsoft
Chairman Bill Gates in an antitrust suit scheduled to begin in late
September.
</P>
<P>
   Around town, TV technicians and correspondents went to bed
early. The next morning, Lewinsky was due to testify for a second
time before Starr's grand jury and prime spots on Monica Beach
needed to be staked out by 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At about 3 a.m. on Thursday, Berger called Clinton for the final
okay on launching Tomahawk missiles against terrorist camps in
Afghanistan and a chemical weapons plant in Sudan. Clinton said
``go.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday morning, the Kennedy Center announced that among
the recipients of its 1998 honors for lifetime achievement in the
performing arts was Willie Nelson, the braided, outlaw Texas
troubadour who played a character pretty much like himself last
year in the movie ``Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   It would not be the last mention of that film on this momentous
day.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, by mid-morning, outside the federal courthouse, NBC
News make-up artist Linda Boyle was busy keeping correspondents and
commentators looking cool and competent for a sunny, eventful day.
``There are no real prima donnas,'' she explained. ``They treat me
well because they know I have to treat them well.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, prosecutors showed Lewinsky a videotape of Clinton's
testimony on Monday. Reports would soon be emanating from Monica
Beach that the star witness had contradicted the president on the
extent of their sexual relationship and how she came to turn over
gifts he had given her to presidential secretary Betty Currie. The
testimony could help Starr build a case of perjury and obstruction
of justice against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Just before 2 p.m., Lewinsky left the courthouse wearing a gray
suit, teal shirt and sunglasses. ``She answered all questions
truthfully and completely,'' said spokeswoman Judy Smith. ``It is
our expectation that today's appearance concludes her grand jury
testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she said, Lewinsky ``is looking forward to beginning the
process of rebuilding the rest of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time Lewinsky was leaving the courthouse,
Clinton made a surprise visit to the makeshift press center at
Edgartown School on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we have struck back,'' he informed shocked reporters,
many of whom who were dressed casually in shorts and T-shirts.
``The United States launched an attack this morning on one of the
most active terrorists bases in the world .''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was returning to Washington immediately,
scrambling the small traveling pool of reporters that would
accompany him.
</P>
<P>
   From the Pentagon briefing by Defense Secretary William Cohen to
movie buffs around the nation, the question was immediately raised:
Isn't this eerily like ``Wag the Dog.'' In that satirical film, a
president is caught in a sex scandal involving a young girl in the
Oval Office and his aides bring in a Hollywood producer to stage a
fake war and divert the nation's attention. Willie Nelson plays a
songwriter who writes the musical score to the war, incidentally.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration was offended by such cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only motivation driving this action today was our absolute
obligation to protect the American people from terrorist
activity,'' insists Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and many other Republicans declared their support for
the mission. But Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind., said ``given the
president's difficulties this week, it is legitimate to question
the timing of this action.''
</P>
<P>
   In late afternoon, Clinton addressed the nation from the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let our actions today send this message loud and clear,'' he
said. ``There are no expendable American targets. There will be no
sanctuary for terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Security was tightened Friday at the Washington Monument,
Smithsonian Institution and other landmarks in the nation's
capital. Outside the Pentagon, police in black SWAT uniforms
brandished automatic weapons on patrols. Osama bin Laden, the
Saudi-born Islamic militant whose terrorist camp was targeted by
the missile strikes in Afghanistan, reportedly issued new threats
against the United States, including a warning to Clinton that
``the battle has not started yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want to suggest to you or to the American people
that what happened yesterday means there will be no more
terrorism,'' Berger told reporters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright went to Capitol
Hill to brief members of Congress and staffers about the missile
attack. They answered some questions from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that we launched what we believe to be a successful
attack upon a training camp, a terrorist training camp, and we
believe it is successful in the sense that we destroyed a number of
facilities,'' said Cohen. ``The extent of that damage has yet to be
determined in terms of the clarity which we would want.''
</P>
<P>
   At about 4:50 p.m., Clinton left the White House and returned to
Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Reuters News Service reported that videotape rental
stores can't keep up with demand for ``Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This story contains information from The New York Times, The
Washington Post, The Los Angeles Times and the Associated Press).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
