<SLUG> BC-MA-UNEMPLOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB MARKET REMAINS STRONG IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite problems in Asia, the Massachusetts job market
is as strong as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The state's jobless rate dropped to 3.1 percent in July, the
second lowest level in the last 10 years, the Division of
Employment and Training reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts also added more than 89,000 jobs over the last
year, the largest annual increase since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The June jobless rate was 3.4 percent in Massachusetts, well
below the national rate of 4.5 percent. In April, the state's
jobless rate dipped to 2.9 percent, then the lowest in more than a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing expansion throughout the country, and in
Massachusetts as well,'' said Wayne Ayers, &UR;  &LR; chief economist at
BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Will the good times continue? ``That's open for question,'' said
Ayers. ``As the US economy begins to slow down in the wake of Asia
so, too, will the Massachusetts economy. Right now, though, we are
beyond full unemployment. It can't get much better than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is not the only state with positive news. Thirty
states and territories had July jobless rates below the national
average, Bloomberg News reported. By contrast, 18 states and the
District of Columbia had jobless rates above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Regionwide, the jobless rate in the Northeast was 4.6 percent,
according to the US Labor Department. The Midwest, by contrast,
reported a jobless level of 3.7 percent in July, the lowest of the
nation's four regions. The South's jobless rate was 4.3 percent
last month, while the West recorded a rate of 5.1 percent _ the
highest among the regions.
</P>
<P>
   Job gains in July were strong in nearly all sectors in
Massachusetts. The service sector, which added more than 44,000 new
jobs over the last year, led the way. Gains were reported in
business services, engineering, and management. Even the
manufacturing sector bucked a national downward trend and added
2,800 new jobs, bringing the total number of manufacturing jobs in
the state to 456,900.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are also seeing gains in hotel building, office, and home
construction,'' said Sara Johnson, an economist with Standard &AMP;
Poor's DRI in Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen such incredible growth that the only factors
holding back business growth right now are labor supply shortages
and the inability to find enough skilled workers,'' Johnson added.
</P>
<P>
   Noted Kim Milosh, an associate economist at Fleet Financial
Group in Boston: ``The low unemployment rate is good for people who
are looking for jobs. But for companies that are looking to hire
people to fill those jobs, it's a difficult situation. With an
unemployment rate this low, there just aren't enough qualified
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Between July 1997 and July 1998, the number of people without
jobs dropped 23 percent, from 131,400 to 100,800, said Angelo
Buonopane, director of the Massachusetts Department of Labor and
Workforce Development. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
