<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-AIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO SYSTEMS BUYING AMERICAN INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   California technology titan Cisco Systems Inc. is expanding its
presence in Massachusetts with a $56 million stock deal to buy
American Internet Corp., a networking software company in Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, privately held AIC's 50 employees will remain in
Bedford under the leadership of the company's current president,
Bob Brennan.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Darby, manager of business development at Cisco in San
Jose, said the deal grew out of a previous contract with AIC to
provide software for Cisco, which makes devices that manage traffic
on the Internet. ``We had an existing partnership with these
guys,'' said Darby. ``The chemistry's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco already operates a major facility in Chelmsford, Mass.
where engineers design hardware for use by Internet service
providers. The software produced by AIC is intended to strengthen
Cisco's line of products for this market.
</P>
<P>
   AIC makes software that makes it easier to attach computers to
networks that use the standard Internet Protocol, or IP. This
protocol was developed to direct Internet data to its final
destination, but IP has also been adopted as a standard for many
corporate computer networks as well.
</P>
<P>
   One AIC product, called Network Registrar, allows users of
portable computers to plug into network connections anywhere inside
an organization. Network Registrar automatically assigns a IP
address to the computer so that it can send and receive messages.
The software is used at Boston College, where students with laptops
can plug into the campus network in a library or dining hall, and
gain instant access.
</P>
<P>
   Another AIC product, Access Registrar, is used by Internet
service providers like MediaOne Express. This product automatically
assigns IP addresses to users of cable modems or telephone modems.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan said that the AIC software had been tailored to manage
IP addresses much faster than existing products, resulting in
faster service for users. In addition, the software can assign
different levels of service quality for different users. Someone
connecting to the network in order to send e-mail could get a
standard level of service, while a user sending a videoconference
would automatically get high-priority service, and be billed at a
higher rate.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco will take a one-time after-tax charge of between 3 and 6
cents per share to pay for ongoing research and development at AIC.
In the year ended in July, Cisco earned $1.05 billion, or $1.01, a
share, on sales of $6.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, its stock closed at 102 3/4, up 1/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
