<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23)  
 (af)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHINA &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Natural Disaster's Human and Economic Toll &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flood waters broke through a dike near Daqing, China, last week,
inundating more than 1,800 of the northeast region's oil wells.
Across China, the floods, the worst in 60 years, have killed more
than 2,000 people, left millions homeless and caused $24 billion in
economic losses. The damage is expected to cut at least 0.5
percentage point off economic growth this year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Floating Like a Butterfly Or Sinking Like a Stone? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government moved hastily last week to avert
financial collapse with a series of drastic measures, including
delaying payments for 90 days on foreign debt owed mostly by banks,
a restructuring of government bonds and the sacrifice of the ruble
to market forces.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the Russian currency is now free to float as low as
9.5 to the dollar, a risky step _ tantamount to devaluation _ that
many people fear could prompt a new round of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   It could also wipe out as much as a third of the ruble's
purchasing power in an economy heavily dependent on imports. The
decision came after a request for $22.6 billion from the West was
turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's cut Russia's long-term foreign-currency debt
rating by two notches. For this beggar at a McDonald's in Moscow,
the collapsing ruble was not of immediate concern. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE DOW &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Pain Worsens &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The global economic crisis and the aftermath of United States
strikes on Afghanistan and the Sudan ravaged Wall Street stocks on
Friday. After rising strongly early last week, the Dow fell
slightly on Wednesday, more than 80 points on Thursday, and more
than 200 points on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a mini-panic here,'' said Michael Metz, a
managing director at CIBC Oppenheimer &AMP; Co. Many traders could do
little more than hold their heads and hope for the best. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An iMac Moment &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Apple Computer &UR;  &LR; climbed to near a three-year high
after the company's debut of its iMac personal computer. Apple said
it had advance orders for 150,000 of the new computers, which, the
company says, will get users onto the Internet very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer &UR;  &LR; is also flying high, reporting a 62 percent gain
in earnings for its second fiscal quarter, exceeding Wall Street
analysts' estimates. Dell also cited market research showing that
it had moved into the No. 1 position in the United States in
desktop computer sales, and the No. 2 position over all, behind
Compaq Computer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Honda's Global Dividend &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After years of taking grief from its Japanese rivals for its
overseas emphasis, Honda Motor &UR;  &LR; is now benefiting more than ever
from that globalization. Even with the domestic market shrinking
rapidly, Honda, Japan's No. 3 auto maker behind Toyota and Nissan,
reported a 26 percent profit gain for the latest quarter, largely
because of sales in Europe and in Honda's largest market, the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Other Japanese car makers did not have such a good week. Moody's
Investors Service cut its rating of Toyota Motor's &UR;  &LR; long-term debt,
citing concern that falling sales in Asia would eat into profits.
</P>
<P>
   The downgrading followed an earlier announcement by Moody's that
it had lowered the credit ratings of Nissan Motor and Mitsubishi
Motors. Still, Toyota's credit rating remains well above those of
General Motors, Ford Motor and Volkswagen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;  MORE)
</P>
<P>
   THE ECONOMY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This New House &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Housing construction jumped last month for the second straight
month _ its fastest pace in more than a decade. New housing units
were going up at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1,718,000
units in July, the heaviest activity since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve did its part to help that boom by deciding
to leave short-term interest rates at 5.5 percent. Given that
United States consumer prices rose a seasonally adjusted 0.2
percent in July after a 0.1 percent increase in June, the Fed's
action was not unexpected. ... The trade deficit narrowed slightly,
to $14.2 billion in June, but was still not far from the record
high as deficits with troubled Asian nations continued to soar. The
June deficit was off 8.9 percent from the record $15.5 billion in
May, marking the first decline since January. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL WARMING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's Melting, It's Melting &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alaska is thawing, and much of northern Russia and Canada with
it. And many scientists say the warming of these cold regions is
one of the most telling signals that the planet's climate is
changing.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have long said that in an era of global warming, this
bellwether region should warm more and faster than the Earth as a
whole, and that is just how things are turning out, to the
consternation of walruses and people alike.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1997 study, longer summers have allowed Alaska's
tourism industry to grow and should expand shipping in the region,
too. But the warmer weather is taking a heavy toll on forests, and
by extension, eventually the forestry industry.
</P>
<P>
   The warming has promoted a buildup of tree-eating insects in
general and has prompted some species, like the spruce budworm, to
move farther north.
</P>
<P>
   Across southern Alaska, some of the forest is more than sick; it
is dead or dying, and spruce bark beetles are the killers.
Scientists estimate that a third to half of Alaska's white spruce
have died the last 15 years. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOBS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Downsizing With Less Gusto &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The country's most comprehensive survey of permanent layoffs
found that in the last three years, downsizing affected a smaller
percentage of the work force than in any other period this decade.
</P>
<P>
   But the layoff rate is still significantly higher than in the
1980s, and women now get pink slips almost as often as men. Eight
million people were pushed out of their jobs involuntarily in the
1995-97 period, the Labor Department said in its report, or one out
of every 15 adult job holders.
</P>
<P>
   That was down from 8.4 million in the previous three years, or
one in 12 workers, the decade's worst performance. But downsizing
is still occurring at a faster rate than in the late 1980s. Then
the displacement rate was one out of every 18 job holders. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEMICONDUCTORS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chips Are Down &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two computer chip makers said they expected sharply lower
quarterly results because of Asia's economic crisis, and a third
said its quarterly net earnings fell 81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings from LSI Logic and National Semiconductor, coupled
with the results from Analog Devices, suggested that any talk of a
recovery in the chip manufacturing industry might be premature.
</P>
<P>
   Chip companies are finding that they are much more vulnerable to
Asia's problems than they had thought. ``When something like Asia
happens, it doesn't really matter how good your products are or how
well managed your company is, you're going to feel it,'' said Drew
Peck, an analyst at SG Cowen &AMP; Co. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SWEDEN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Business(AT)ArcticCircle.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A mouse pad made of reindeer hide? Well, maybe that's a bad
example of a high-technology business with a big future. But Sweden
has a few other ideas up its reindeer coat-covered sleeve,
including extreme telecommuting.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to slow the flight of people from what is already
one of the world's most sparsely settled areas, the government is
encouraging businesses to set up computerized telephone-call
centers in remote Arctic Circle villages _ such as Arvidsjaur,
where Sara Andersson, is director of trade _ and to staff them with
young people who otherwise would be scouting for work in the
population centers to the south, or abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The companies benefit from special government subsidies, and
they find that outlying parts of Sweden have a supply of educated,
keyboard-literate young people with the Swedes' noted ability to
function comfortably in several languages.
</P>
<P>
   Swedes and telephones have a cozy relationship: The country has
the highest number of lines per person in the world _ 70 for every
100 inhabitants _ and 44 percent of Swedes have mobile phones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
