<P>
   N A T I O N A L / T E X A S &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORGOTTEN COWBOYS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REFUGIO, Texas _ The image of the Texas cowboy has been deeply
stamped in our minds: tall, weathered, rugged, Marlboroesque _ and
white. That image is dishonest. ``John Wayne wouldn't be nothing
beside of us,'' Nathaniel Youngblood, a black cowboy from the Texas
coastal plains, was fond of saying. ``They just didn't take our
picture. John Wayne and Tim Holt, Durango Kid, and that other one _
Gene Autry, oh, no. They ain't nothing.'' Along the coastal bend of
Texas, nearly a third of the cowboys pushing cattle up the Texas
trails in the 1840s were black. Roughly another third were
Hispanic. They never enjoyed a place in the prevailing cowboy myth
_ these weren't flashy rodeo cowboys, or the silver-saddled cowboys
of the movies _ but they helped forge ranching empires along the
coastal plains. By ART CHAPMAN. Story has moved in ``a'' general
news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
