<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6513 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCUST-VALLEY-$ADV23-     08-21 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCUST-VALLEY-$ADV23-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCUST VALLEY: WHERE THE SWELLS GO TO ESCAPE THE BARBARIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn.)   (For release Sunday, Aug. 23)  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Out along the North Shore of Long Island, in a land popularly
associated with lockjaw, ``Sabrina'' and Wall Street wealth
predating the crash _ the one in 1929 _ the wrong pair of shoes
gives you away.
</P>
<P>
   At the Piping Rock Club one night this summer, two men in khakis
and blue blazers crossed the wooden deck above the beach with their
30-something dates. Both women had on pretty cotton sundresses and
wore their blond hair in just-so bobs. Yet, the heels of their
patent-leather sandals were suspiciously thin.
</P>
<P>
   A 29-year-old club member, who was sipping a southside cocktail
with a friend, looked them over and whispered, ``They are not from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   This world of subtle uniforms and unspoken codes is called
Locust Valley, a slice of Gatsbyesque, upper-class living, which
seems preserved in aspic.
</P>
<P>
   Just 30 miles from Manhattan, it is a land of French manor
houses, private dirt roads and small shops selling monogrammed
wastebaskets. The respect for life's little niceties would bring a
smile to Emily Post. Strangers wave from cars, everyone says
``please'' and ``thank you,'' and friends exchange exaggeratedly
warm greetings at the country club, even though they had lunch
together just hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, darlins,'' said Jeff Lincoln, 38, a Manhattanite
walking from a game of golf, as he greeted two friends, Olexa
Farrell and Leah Ramirez. ``I'm looking at the prettiest women
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The young women blushed. They asked Lincoln, an interior
designer who was formerly a Wall Street Journal reporter, about the
rumor that his picture, clipped from W magazine, was going to be
posted on Elizabeth Shue's bulletin board in a new movie. It was
Lincoln's turn to blush. ``I am going to be Elizabeth's love
interest,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   The women giggled and moved on to lunch, joining two others
beneath a navy umbrella. They wore headbands and white cotton
dresses appropriate for the club's grass tennis courts, and ate
quartered egg-salad sandwiches. The conversation moved from cedar
shingling to Stubbs &AMP; Wooten slippers to what time everyone would
meet for dinner at the club that night.
</P>
<P>
   A scene from the 1920s, when Wall Street fortunes made by
families named Phipps and Morgan built Georgian piles, and Locust
Valley first rose to prominence? It could have been. But these days
the heart of the famous Gold Coast is not just a relic of a former
age.
</P>
<P>
   It has been rediscovered by a wave of young Manhattanites in
their 20s and 30s who are choosing Locust Valley as a weekend and
summer retreat over the Hamptons, where too many barbarians, as
they see it, have been let in the gates.
</P>
<P>
   What they've discovered is a Ralph Laurenlike world, little
touched by postwar suburbanization, which is both less expensive
and less socially formidable than the old-guard clubs and
neighborhoods of Southampton; Greenwich, Conn., and Bedford, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people our age that have begun to find
Locust Valley,'' said Ms. Farrell, 31, who is married to Bowen
Farrell, 38, the managing director of Triton Capital, a leveraged
buyout company.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of their friends, they live in Manhattan and drive to
Locust Valley for weekends packed with golf, horseback riding and
dinners at a half-dozen private clubs, including Piping Rock, the
Creek Club and Seawanhaka Yacht Club.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Anderson, a senior vice president of Sotheby's International
Reality, who has sold luxury properties in the New York area for
two decades, said, ``Right now, Locust Valley is at the top of the
list for young people looking for a country house.'' It outranks
Greenwich, Bedford, Southampton and Far Hills, N.J., he said.
``When people ask for Locust Valley, you know they know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They are not celebrities from the worlds of entertainment, the
news media and professional sports. Just as the North Shore was
built by discreet Wall Street bankers from the turn of the century
through the '20s, it is being revived by the latest wave of bull
market winners, self-effacing in the 1990s way.
</P>
<P>
   Flashiness of all sorts is frowned upon, and clubs like Piping
Rock, perhaps the most sought-after in the area, turn away people
with profiles that are a little too high. Deborah Norville, a
former NBC television anchor who is a member, goes by her married
name, Deborah Wellner.
</P>
<P>
   Strictly speaking, Locust Valley is the name only for an
unincorporated village, the site of a Long Island Rail Road
station, firehouse, library and a few shops. But Locust Valley is
also a state of mind, the name used by area residents to include
the villages of Lattingtown, Matinecock, Mill Neck, Upper
Brookville, Old Brookville and the estate section of Glen Cove.
</P>
<P>
   Boundaries matter in this enclave, where some refer to the
densely populated towns just beyond as ``Buttafuoco territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Although life in Locust Valley seems lavish, it can be quite
affordable. Many young couples and single people rent two or
three-bedroom cottages or gate houses for $1,500 to $2,000 a month,
compared with $5,000 and up per month for a summer rental of
similar size in the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   During the first half of this year, 450 houses sold in the
Locust Valley area at an average price of nearly $700,000 for a
four-bedroom house, on about two acres with a swimming pool, said
Bonnie Devendorf, a vice president and manager of Daniel Gale
Associates in Locust Valley. A comparable home in Greenwich on
one-third of an acre lists for about $950,000.
</P>
<P>
   One affordable way to summer in the area is open to junior
members of the Piping Rock Club, ages 21 to 35, who for about $50 a
night can stay in rooms at the club reminiscent of prep school
dormitories. There are rooms for couples, and others for those the
club refers to as ``bachelors'' and ``bachelorettes,'' furnished
with chintz-covered armchairs and white bedspreads on twin beds.
</P>
<P>
   Piping Rock, a club begun by wealthy sportsmen in the early
1900s, was once famous for polo and equestrian sports, but those
programs ended in the '60s. As the membership aged _ today
60-something men in straw hats wrapped with plaid bandanas drive
golf carts past 60-something women in hot-pink skirts _ the club
sought out new blood through its junior program. With just a single
sponsor's letter from a member (full admission requires multiple
letters), and for a fee of about $1,000, young people can try out
the club while simultaneously being sized up themselves. The junior
program has never been so popular, members say, with about 90
participants in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   These younger members say that the emphasis on juniors makes
Piping Rock more accessible than similar country clubs in the
Hamptons and elsewhere. At Greenwich's Round Hill Country Club, for
example, new members must wait five years for full golf privileges.
``God, I would be 50 before I ever tee off out there,'' said a
Piping Rock member in his 30s, citing a prime reason he rents a
room at the club rather than moving to Greenwich, where he has
family and social connections.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who described country clubs in Locust Valley,
which form the core of social life, spoke on condition of
anonymity, because of the old guard's longstanding, unwritten
prohibitions on discussing personal issues in the press. ``They
still believe the only time to be mentioned in the paper is when
you get married and when you die,'' said a 36-year-old newcomer to
Locust Valley, who used parental connections to get into Piping
Rock. ``We don't want to hurt them in any way. And we don't want to
jeopardize our position.''
</P>
<P>
   The socialite C.Z. Guest, who has lived in Old Westbury most of
her life, put it this way: ``It's a different class of people out
here than in the Hamptons. Out there they need publicity to exist.
Here you know who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Another resident noted the emphasis on politesse and good
manners, what etiquette writers used to call ``breeding.'' ``You're
going to get further being thoughtful to people than being tough
with them,'' she said. ``It's the opposite of the whole New York
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Pauline Boardman, a decorator in Manhattan whose family has had
a Locust Valley home for generations, said, ``In a funny way, it's
been preserved out here.'' She said she was surprised at the number
of young people, many of them single, discovering the area. In some
cases, grandparents once lived in Locust Valley, parents moved away
and now grandchildren are coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am utterly amazed by the enormous groups of people in their
mid-20s and mid-30s coming out here,'' Ms. Boardman said. That
includes her two daughters, Serena, 28, who works at Sotheby's, and
Samantha, 26, a medical-school student. Both stay at their mother's
house.
</P>
<P>
   Many attribute the rediscovery of Locust Valley to a
disillusionment with the excesses of the Hamptons. ``This is our
antidote to the Hamptons,'' Lincoln, the interior designer, said.
Many young Locust Valley residents like to drop in on the Hamptons
for a society party like a recent benefit for Southampton Hospital.
But invariably, they drive the 100 miles back home for the night.
``You don't get stuck out there, God forbid,'' a Locust Valley
woman in her 20s said.
</P>
<P>
   The flirtation with the Hamptons might seem paradoxical _ except
when one considers that it is the old-line, exclusionary Hamptons
embodied by the Meadow Club or the Bathing Corporation, both in
Southampton, that many Locust Valley young people see as a social
pinnacle, although one that is all but insurmountable by newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   For those who are not to the manner born, which includes many of
Locust Valley's new wave, the old money look can be acquired by
hiring the right decorator or visiting the right haberdasher. Thus
is the community socially accessible to members of ethnic groups
that were never welcome in the area's earlier heyday as a WASP
enclave. Piping Rock has a number of Jewish and Asian members, more
than tokens, several members said.
</P>
<P>
   Locust Valley's most popular decorator is Tom Samet, who gives
newcomers' homes an instant old money look with chintz, toile de
jouy, early American and English furniture and knickknacks from
consignment shops that look like they've been in the family for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sells out there is anything that looks old,'' said Marcos
Delgado, who ran a design store in Locust Valley until last year.
His most popular items included tin sconces, Windsor chairs,
painted American furniture and old lanterns for walkways.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-three years ago, F. Scott Fitzgerald described a piece
of the North Shore that was the setting for ``The Great Gatsby'' as
``the most domesticated body of salt water in the Western
Hemisphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Charles Scribner III, a great-grandson of
Fitzgerald's publisher, acquired a summer house in Locust Valley,
which in popular imagination has become identified with Gatsby's
East Egg.
</P>
<P>
   Scribner, 47, plainly admits that the draw of the place is the
fantasy of moving into the pages of the classic novel about the
self-invented millionaire Jay Gatsby, who in his quest to recapture
his lost love, Daisy Buchanan, throws extravagant parties populated
by social swells. The drive to the Scribner house, a modified Cape
of white shingles and white-washed brick, passes a line of Oriental
cherry trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Nick Carraway's cottage,'' Scribner said wryly,
ushering in a guest. The reference, of course, was to the narrator
of ``The Great Gatsby,'' who observed the action from a modest home
adjacent to Gatsby's.
</P>
<P>
   The Scribner ``cottage'' is unassuming but exquisitely tasteful,
with mahogany furniture, English chintz and paintings by Scribner's
wife, Ritchie. It seems out of an earlier, less-frantic era, with
its black-and-white televisions and rotary-dial telephones.
</P>
<P>
   The Scribners invited their guest to sit by a marble-dusted pool
and sip iced tea with orange juice and fresh mint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out here we're left our privacy and quiet,'' Scribner said.
``Locust Valley is so blissfully quiet that the only noisy thing
you hear is the rushing of air when you open a new can of tennis
balls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
