<SLUG> BC-INVEST-UTILITY-VALUE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY STOCKS REMAIN A SAFETY NET IN TURBULENT TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.Y.)   (For release Sunday, Aug. 23)  
(js) 
 BY VIRGINIA MUNGER KAHN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Utility stocks, a traditional shelter for investors in times of
market upheaval, have run true to form this summer, despite utility
deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   While the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index is down 8.9 percent
from its high on July 17, the S&AMP;P utility index has fallen only 1.8
percent. One big reason is that utilities offer a relative safety
net in dividends. Payouts average 4.8 percent for these stocks,
more than three times the typical 1.5 percent dividend of the S&AMP;P
500.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is that utility stocks are relatively cheap now,
having been hammered over the last five years for lackluster
earnings growth and concern over deregulation. Their average
price-to-earnings ratio is 30 percent below that of the S&AMP;P 500, so
investors reason that they have less downside potential than the
high-fliers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to good defensive characteristics, other factors
strengthen the case for utilities, several money managers said.
Mario Gabelli, chairman and chief investment officer of Gabelli
Funds, who has been buying electric and gas utility stocks lately,
said the drive by state regulators to unbundle the generation side
of the business from the transmission and distribution side, which
would stay regulated, was creating ``very powerful dynamics.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his favorite stocks is Eastern Enterprises, which he
expects to ``either consolidate or be consolidated.'' He has also
been nibbling at electric utilities north of New York City, looking
to potential takeover targets like Central Hudson Gas and Electric,
based in Poughkeepsie, and New York State Electric and Gas, of
Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   Another money manager who has played the consolidation theme _
including a position in Central Hudson _ is Sheldon Simon,
co-manager of the Putnam Fund for Growth and Income. Until June he
was senior portfolio manager at Putnam Utilities Growth and Income.
His other picks include Connecticut Energy and Yankee Energy, which
both provide gas in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   A more conservative way to play the industry's consolidation is
to invest in companies that have already announced mergers. Phillip
Davidson, portfolio manager of the American Century Value and
American Century Equity Income funds, bought both Sierra Pacific
Resources and Nevada Power this spring after the companies
announced that they were merging.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two good companies getting better, selling at a
discount to the industry,'' he said, adding that the merger should
eliminate the discount.
</P>
<P>
   Another attraction is when regulatory issues have been resolved
more favorably than analysts expected, specifically for what is
known as ``stranded costs'' _ how much companies can collect from
rate payers for plants that generate power at above-market costs.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Simon bought Peco Energy and PP&AMP;L Resources, which
are resolving these issues. Simon expects Peco, which adopted a
plan in May, to trade up to $38 a share within the next 18 months;
PP&AMP;L should trade ``north of $30 a share'' in that period, he said.
They now trade at $31.875 and $24.4375, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk Power in New York should also benefit from
resolving the stranded-costs issue. In June it adopted a
restructuring agreement that allows it to terminate or amend 27
high-cost power contracts. ``This company has gone through a
gut-wrenching reorganization,'' said Richard Howard, manager of T.
Rowe Price Capital Appreciation. He sees ``lots of upside'' in the
stock, which is selling at $15.1875, just above book value, and
figures it should be worth $22.50 within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Another popular stock pick is Duke Energy, which is committed to
increasing its earnings at an annual rate of 8 percent to 10
percent over the next three to five years. ``It is my favorite
among the big, liquid names,'' Simon said. ``They probably have the
best management in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors seeking defensive issues should stick to big, liquid
stocks _ that's what institutional investors do when they're
looking for a ``parking place'' for money, said Steven Fleishman,
electric utility analyst at Merrill Lynch. His picks include Duke
Energy, Texas Utilities and Consolidated Edison.
</P>
<P>
   The hazards for utility stocks include interest-rate risk,
normal market risk and, this year, a slowing of merger activity,
which Fleishman expects to pick up.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the risk involved in trading electricity or having
to buy high-priced power on the new open market. That was
highlighted in June when utility prices spiked during a heat wave
in the Midwest. Pacificorp, First Energy and other companies took
hits to their second-quarter earnings as a result. But there were
also winners _ companies that sold power into the market _
including Peco and Duke. ``It supports the view that to be a
long-term winner, you have to be big,'' Fleishman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
