s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-COTNER-ART-2T     08-21 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-COTNER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIMMING STOCK POSITIONS: INVESTING WITH C. BETH COTNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 23)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM R. LONG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When to sell is an anxiously asked question in a jittery stock
market. C. Beth Cotner offers some answers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cotner, lead manager of the Putnam Investors fund, imposes a
``trim discipline'' for fast-growing stocks: If a holding goes up
10 percent or at more than twice the market rate within 10 days,
she trims her position by 10 percent, thus locking in some profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times when stocks go up quickly it's because there's
very positive news or positive developments that investors get
euphoric about,'' she said, ``and then later on, the euphoria wears
off or something happens so the stock comes back down again.''
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, she buys back trimmed shares after the price has
declined.
</P>
<P>
   Such practices have helped make Putnam Investors a strong
performer during her tenure. The fund _ categorized as a
large-capitalization growth fund _ returned 18.59 percent for the
12 months ended Thursday, surpassing the 16.79 percent average of
its peer group, according to Morningstar Inc., the financial
publisher in Chicago. And the fund has narrowly outperformed the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index over the last three years and
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Started in December 1925, Putnam Investors is one of the three
oldest open-end funds in the country. It has assets of $4.5
billion. Ms. Cotner, 45, has been lead manager since the end of
September 1995; she previously managed mutual funds at Kemper
Financial Services.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's management team uses quantitative screening with a
point system to find attractive stocks.
</P>
<P>
   A computer model developed by Putnam Investments, based in
Boston, scores companies on a 1-to-5 scale in each of five
categories: potential earnings surprises, earnings revisions,
cash-flow reinvestment, dividend yield and sales-to-price
valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Combining the category scores gives a company a composite score
of 1 to 5, and a stock with a 1 or a 2 merits further study.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we've back-tested our model, 1's and 2's have
consistently outperformed the market,'' while 5's have
underperformed, Ms. Cotner said.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes fundamental research _ visiting the companies, their
suppliers and their competitors, then putting together extensive
five-year earnings and cash-flow models.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cotner said she discussed all buying decisions with the
fund's co-managers, Richard England and Manuel Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a controversial issue, we try to assign someone to
be the devil's advocate,'' Ms. Cotner said. No miracles are
required for a stock to make the portfolio, she added, but ``we try
to reach the right decision, not just one that seems to be easy to
reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a stock is in the portfolio, the three managers continually
review its financial and management fundamentals. If there is a
basic problem, or a company is likely to miss earnings targets, Ms.
Cotner said, ``we'll eliminate the whole position.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, when a company is doing well and its share price is growing,
``we'll trim the stock, if it just gets to be too large as a
percentage of the overall portfolio,'' she said. The co-managers
rebalance the portfolio each quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``we would trim back something like Microsoft to 3
percent,'' Ms. Cotner said. ``If we just let it ride all the time
and it never hit the trim discipline, it might just gradually over
time grow to be 10 percent of the portfolio, and that's too big.''
</P>
<P>
   Using their quantitative scoring program, the co-managers
rescreen the portfolio's stocks daily, immediately looking into any
that have fallen to a 4 or 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it remains a 4 more than a week or two, it triggers a sell
decision on our part, and by the time it gets to a 5, it's gone
from the portfolio,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Growth stocks tend to do better than value stocks under current
economic conditions, with a slowing economy and stable interest
rates, Ms. Cotner said, but she acknowledged that because of its
growth bias, Putnam Investors tends to be slightly more volatile
than the benchmark S&AMP;P 500 and could underperform in a down
market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finding stocks that would weather a bear market is not easy, she
said. The best bets might include drug chains and grocery chains,
``areas that are relatively immune'' from economic or political
events, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among these groups, Putnam Investors has stakes in Safeway Inc.,
Walgreen Co. and CVS Corp.
</P>
<P>
   CVS, the nation's No. 2 pharmacy chain, after Walgreen, has been
expanding rapidly through acquisitions and now has more than 4,000
stores.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 it merged with Revco, which had more than 2,500 stores,
and this year it bought Arbor, a Michigan chain with more than 200
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get a lot of their sales through filling prescription
drugs,'' Ms. Cotner said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the aging population and recent approvals of new drugs
like Viagra, ``prescription drugs are growing very rapidly,'' she
said, adding that ``drugs are taken no matter whether the economy
is strong or weak.''
</P>
<P>
   CVS is also good at merchandising in the other parts of its
stores, she said, adding, ``They have been able to go into the
newly acquired stores and ramp up their product offerings in what's
called the front end of the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cotner predicted that CVS earnings would grow 18 percent
this year and again next year. Putnam Investors bought the stock,
which is now trading at $44.25, at $22 more than two years ago. She
expects the stock to reach $57 in 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Another retailer that Ms. Cotner likes is Wal-Mart Stores. It
has been improving its systems by allowing stores to cut prices to
meet local competition and to manage in-store inventories more
efficiently. Putnam Investors started buying Wal-Mart stock in
spring 1997 at about $28 a share, and it continued to buy over the
last year, for an average cost of about $40, Ms. Cotner said. The
stock ended last week at $65.
</P>
<P>
   A year from now, the price could be $75, she estimated.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 holding in Ms. Cotner's fund is Tyco International, a
holding company with a market capitalization of about $35 billion
and subsidiaries that offer disposable medical and specialty
products, fire and security services, flow-control supplies and
equipment, electrical and electronic components and underwater
telecommunications systems.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco announced in May that it was buying U.S. Surgical Corp., a
medical products company, in a $3.3 billion stock trade. That and
other acquisitions, Ms. Cotner said, are expected to raise
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, their strategy is to buy the company,'' she said.
``They cut costs quickly in the first year, and then they build the
businesses in the second, third and fourth years so that not only
do they get cost-cuttings, but they get growth out of these
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyco is expected to produce earn $2 a share for the fiscal year
ending in September, up about 40 percent, and for the next year of
$2.65, up about 33 percent, Ms. Cotner said.
</P>
<P>
   Her fund bought Tyco early last year ``at around 30,'' she said.
In Putnam's last SEC filing in January, Tyco accounted for 2.1
percent of assets. A spokesman said the fund had since built up the
position, but declined to say how much. Tyco is now trading at $59,
and Ms. Cotner predicted that it would reach about $80 in 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Such predictions, of course, are based on the assumption that a
particular stock's gains will not be wiped out by the treacherous
currents of a volatile stock market. But the thought does cross Ms.
Cotner's mind.
</P>
<P>
   She spent her childhood in Crescent City, a usually tranquil
spot on the coast of Northern California, where a tidal wave struck
in 1961. ``A lot of houses there got wiped out _ a lot of
casualties,'' she said. ``Maybe you can tie that in to the tidal
wave of today's market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
