<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6527 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-BONDS-ART-$ADV     08-21 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BONDS-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RARE STAR TURN FOR THE BOND MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on total returns for bonds vs. other indexes is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With bonds selling at historic highs, many investors are
wondering whether there are more good plays to make or whether a
peak has been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, bond investors have had good returns of late. Over
the past 12 months, the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond has
generated a total return _ capital appreciation plus interest _ of
15.4 percent, far better than the performance of any of the major
stock indexes. The Dow Jones industrial average, for example, is up
9.98 percent for that period _ and is now down 8.6 percent from its
historic high on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   As inflation has stayed low, prices of long-term bonds have
risen and the bonds' yields, which move in the opposite direction,
have fallen to 30-year lows; interest rates on the 30-year Treasury
bond have slipped to 5.43 percent from a 12-month high of 6.66
percent last August.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four years, the booming stock market has received
an ever-expanding slice of the average investor's portfolio while
the slivers for bonds and cash have shrunk. According to data
compiled by the Federal Reserve, the share of household financial
assets composed of equities rose 12.6 percent between 1994 and
1997, to a total of 47.3 percent. Fixed-income assets like bonds
declined 7 percent, to 20.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, because of recent turmoil in stock prices, some investors
want to decrease their allocation to equities.
</P>
<P>
   If they do, one analyst says, they will still find a good
alternative in the bond market. ``Bonds continue to have very
favorable fundamentals,'' said Joseph Battipaglia, chief investment
strategist for Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``In fact, when you account for
inflation and taxes, bond yields are more attractive now than in
1981.''
</P>
<P>
   During that year, inflation was 10.3 percent, the yield on the
long-term government bond was 13.5 percent and the top tax bracket
was 70 percent. This combination of inflation and taxes meant that
the real after-tax yield was a negative 6.25 percent, Battipaglia
said. In contrast, the real yield after taxes is now 1.63 percent,
based on a 1.7 percent inflation rate and a much lower top tax
bracket of 39.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Battipaglia predicted that the favorable climate for bonds would
continue, thanks to ``the absence of inflation in the economy and a
gradual decline in the supply of bonds,'' as the government's
budget moves from deficit to surplus. Although the last 20 years
have been marked by rate volatility, ``from a historical
perspective, this new low-rate scenario actually typifies the
normal level of interest rates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Battipaglia suggests Treasuries and investment-grade corporate
issues for tax-deferred retirement accounts, and municipal bonds
for most taxable accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In the municipal arena, Battipaglia favors some bonds currently
trading above their face values. ``While the premium is sacrificed
over the life of the bond, the higher coupon payments provide an
enhanced cash flow to investors,'' he said. He likes the 5.75
percent New York City general obligation bonds that are due to
mature Aug. 1, 2013. They are trading at 106\ _ $106.25 for every
$100 of face value _ having moved up in price as yields have
fallen. There is one caveat: the city could elect to call them
before maturity, once in 2007, when it would pay holders $101 per
$100 of face value, or it could call them in 2009 and pay par. The
yield to maturity is 5.15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Battipaglia also sees favorable investment opportunities in
corporate bonds. He favors Lehman Brothers' 7| percent bonds due
June 1, 2006, priced at 107] to yield 6.40 percent. The bonds, with
no call provision, are investment grade.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes the zero-coupon bond of Revlon Worldwide that is
due March 15, 2001. Typically, zero-coupon bonds pay no monthly
interest and are sold at a discount to face value. The Revlon issue
has a current price of 77} to yield about 10.09 percent at
maturity. It is callable as of March 15, 2000, at a price of 92.479
and rises to 101.81 on the due date of Feb. 15, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Battipaglia likes convertible securities when a stock price has
collapsed. Known in Wall Street parlance as ``broken converts,''
these securities trade below par value. He cited Sunglass Hut
International, which is in a turnaround situation and has had a
sharp increase in revenues. However, the stock price, which was at
$13 on June 10, has lagged, closing Friday at $7.625.
</P>
<P>
   Because he expects the stock to catch up, Battipaglia likes
Sunglass Hut's 5.25 percent convertible bonds due June 15, 2003,
which are priced at $80.25 to yield 10.59 percent at maturity and
are likely to gain with the stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
