A6534 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-MEDIA-TEX     08-21 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-MEDIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO CELEBRITY ENDORSEMENTS, BUYER BEWARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who hasn't heard the stories?
</P>
<P>
   Punch-drunk prize fighters, their championship belts
long-pawned, shuffling and greeting the swells at Vegas casinos,
trading faded fame for a pocketful of recognition and a handful of
cash.
</P>
<P>
   One-time millionaire ballplayers, their riches spent on
God-knows-what excesses, trolling the bushes for minimum-wage
coaching gigs.
</P>
<P>
   Big-name jocks, forced into court to find out what happened to
all that money they made _ and what happened to the financial
manager who ``invested'' it all for them.
</P>
<P>
   The personal finances of famous athletes do not always make for
pleasant memories.
</P>
<P>
   So I wonder: Would you entrust your life savings or your home to
a ballplayer?
</P>
<P>
   Thought not.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes all the more interesting this trend of using
athletes, mainly retired stars, as celebrity pitchmen on TV
commercials for consumer loan companies.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Among others, there's Terry Bradshaw for The
Associates (''We make loans that make life better.'') Dan Marino
for FirstPlus Financial. Phil Rizzuto for The Money Store and
George Foreman for Beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon it'll be Mike Tyson for Loan-and-Groan.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, this is not a challenge to the investment acumen of
Messrs. Bradshaw and Marino, et al. For all I know, their financial
smarts outstrip Michael Milken's. But that's between them and the
IRS.
</P>
<P>
   What I wanted to know is why a person would listen to an old
jock when it comes to money matters, especially when those matters
might involve hocking your house and taking on double-digit
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   So I asked someone who should know. Doug Shabelman is vice
president of Burns Sports Celebrity Service, a Chicago firm that
links athletes with advertisers for endorsement deals.
</P>
<P>
   Burns put Foreman and Beneficial together.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies are looking for someone who's trustworthy, and
these people are,'' Shabelman explained. ``Plus, these guys,
especially the quarterbacks, are seen as field generals _ it's a
leadership issue.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people aren't a big risk,'' Shabelman said. ``They've
been around a long time, and they have a following.''
</P>
<P>
   Their followings, he added, continue to expand thanks to their
sports media careers. Bradshaw, for example, gets heavy weekly
exposure as a football commentator on network TV. Former New York
Yankee Rizzuto has broadcast major-league baseball. Foreman and
Marino are still competing. Plus, they've received additional
celebrity through other commercials and even through movies.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release, Associates said Bradshaw ``epitomizes hard
work, honesty and integrity, which are the very attributes we hope
our customers see in us.''
</P>
<P>
   So Bradshaw is good for Associates' image. But are all consumer
loan companies good for the athlete's image?
</P>
<P>
   In its July issue, in an article headlined, ``Poverty Inc.,''
``Consumer Reports'' magazine tackles lending companies, saying
some poor or unsuspecting borrowers can wind up losing a home
because they can't afford to pay back ill-advised loans.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine talked with a publicist for Bradshaw and a
spokesman for Marino. Bradshaw's publicist said the Fox broadcaster
only recently learned of questions over industry lending practices.
Marino's spokesman defended FirstPlus, although not the entire
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Chance-taking is part of any celebrity product endorsement, and
both sides share some risk. Kmart suffers when Fuzzy Zoeller
speculates on Tiger Woods' dining habits. Michael Jordan suffers
when Nike is criticized for treatment of its overseas factory
workers.
</P>
<P>
   What seems like a good partnership in a strict
business-marketing sense, doesn't always hold up under the scrutiny
of social activism.
</P>
<P>
   Like they say: Buyer beware.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
