<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-DAMAGE (Washington) _ The Clinton administration said
Friday that Thursday's simultaneous cruise-missile strikes
obliterated a pharmaceutical factory in the Sudanese capital of
Khartoum and caused ``moderate to severe damage'' to the
mountainous redoubt in Afghanistan linked to terrorists supported
by Osama bin Laden. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT (Jerusalem) _ In mosques, on street
corners, and from some government ministries, many Muslims voiced
fury Friday over the American missile strikes in Afghanistan and
Sudan and predicted that the assault would beget more violence. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-RECAP (Washington) _ A recap of the process leading up to
the decision to attack: Clinton had cut short a political trip to
California to attend a military strategy meeting. For the next
eight days, he and the White House were consumed with planning on
two tracks for two events: his grand jury testimony and the
attacks. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ The man who climbed atop a tank and
led Russia out of communism in 1991 has scarcely been seen in
public since his country's financial markets and its currency fell
off a cliff last week. The big question _ for him and for the
reforms he champions _ is whether Russians any longer care.
President Boris Yeltsin, already deeply unpopular, now seems to
have sunk even lower in political and public esteem than his
country's ruble. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLL (Undated) _ President Clinton continues to draw
high ratings from the American public for his job performance, but
his admission of a relationship with a White House intern has
produced signs of a darkening public view of both the president's
moral character and his overall personal image, the latest New York
Times/CBS News poll shows. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MISS-KLAN-TRIAL (Hattiesburg, Miss.) _ Former Ku Klux Klan
leader Sam Bowers was found guilty Friday of murder and arson, and
sentenced to life in jail here in connection with the 1966 slaying
of civil rights activist Vernon Dahmer. (Summary from wires.) By
Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   CT-NUKE-PILLS (Datelie to kum) _ Connecticut is considering
giving potassium iodide pills to people living near the Millstone
nuclear power plant, which was recently restarted after being idle
for two years because of major problem. The pills would be taken in
case of an accident, and have been shown to reduce the risk of
thyroid cancer after radiation exposure.
</P>
</TEXT>
