<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USSTRIKES-QUESTIONS-0     08-21 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USSTRIKES-QUESTIONS-0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KEY QUESTIONS ON THE U.S. STRIKES
 &HT;    With USSTRIKES-POLICY-0822.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here are some of the key questions raised by the
American missile strikes against sites in Afghanistan and Sudan:
</P>
<P>
   Question: Were the attacks on Thursday timed to draw attention
away from President Clinton's confession on Monday that he had
``misled people'' about his adulterous affair with Monica Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon brass would spurn any such Hollywood-style caper.
As National Security Adviser Sandy Berger noted in a Friday
briefing, the attack plan was developed by Clinton's advisers,
including its proposed timing. Only then, Berger said, was it given
to Clinton for his approval. The key decisions were made last
Friday, before the president testified to a federal grand jury
about the sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, in light of his testimony, administration officials
felt obliged to provide Clinton with ``air cover'' -- saturating
the electronic media with a virtually non-stop interviews. These
intensive public briefings seem to have the dual goal of slackening
coverage of dissenting voices, mostly from abroad, and of shoring
up Clinton's eroded credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Q: By and large, are Americans less safe from a terrorist
onslaught because the administration took, as Berger put it,
``offensive action''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most probably so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is, unfortunately, the war of the future,'' Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright said on Friday. Since the raids, Albright
herself has been moving around Washington with a heavily armed
SWAT-type escort in tow. Ordinary tourists encounter beefed-up
security measures at most public places. These measures reflect
officials' well-founded fears that the Islamic radicals are getting
ready to retaliate against the strikes. They know that's how things
work in that part of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If that's so, where will the terrorists strike next?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, responding to intelligence reports, ordered U.S.
embassies in Albania, Egypt and Pakistan reduced to skeleton staffs
until the crisis eases. American military bases around the world,
including the Pentagon, are also being much more closely guarded.
</P>
<P>
   But a bomb can be planted in any place where its sends a lethal
message to the enemy, especially if attackers are ready to die in
the bargain. Since not every site can be safeguarded, heightened
security may merely serve to point terrorists toward more
accessible targets.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what can be done, once and for all, to end the terrorist
threat against Americans at home and abroad?
</P>
<P>
   A: At this point, not much.
</P>
<P>
   Well-heeled terrorist networks, such as the one funded by exiled
Saudi millionaire Osama bin Laden, would agree to back off only if
the United States agreed to shut down its bases in the Middle East,
lifted the oil embargo against Iraq and halted its political and
financial support for Israel. None of these steps are viable policy
options for the Clinton team.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has the administration offered any direct convincing or
compelling evidence that Bin Laden's network was behind the Aug. 7
U.S. embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, beyond repeated assertions that he did it.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Albright and Defense Secretary William Cohen led an
official mission to Capitol Hill to brief members and key
congressional intelligence staffers, who had been kept in the dark.
Cohen said they shared ``what the information was we had to operate
on, what kind of intelligence we had, (and) the basis for the
action.'' None of that data has yet to be made public, however.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were U.S. officials hoping to kill Bin Laden when the
missiles struck an Afghan terrorist training camp -- originally
built for his followers with CIA funds to fight the Soviets?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably so, although they can't admit it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually Bin Laden was a collateral target, much as Libyan
leader Muammar Gaddafi was viewed in 1986 when President Reagan
ordered a retaliatory U.S. air raid against Gaddafi's home as he
slept. Nor is it at all clear that a long-standing presidential
executive order which bars assassination attempts against foreign
officials would apply as well to terrorist chieftains
</P>
<P>
   Q: Should Sudanese assertions that Washington itself committed a
terrorist act by destroying a totally harmless pharmaceutical plant
in a northern suburb of Khartoum be believed?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. planners say they have hard proof that the plant was doing
more than producing medically useful drugs. At some point, either
at the United Nations, where Sudan has launched a complaint, or in
another venue, the administration must offer its evidence or risk a
loss of face in the Arab world. Berger dismissed Sudanese claims of
innocence on Friday, telling reporters: ``This was a plant that was
producing chemical warfare-related weapons and we have physical
evidence of that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
