<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESIGNERS-HOWPROSLIVE     08-21 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGNERS-HOWPROSLIVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Like his gardens, designer Brooks Garcia draws inspiration from
the past
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through the trees, the sunlight dances on a warm and peaceful
afternoon. Deep in the woods, the birds are singing as all the
world sits back in joy, yearning for nothing beyond this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous
</P>
<P>
   The words may seem sappy for his office answering machine
recording, but for those who know Atlanta garden designer Brooks
Garcia, they speak volumes about a plantsman whose passion is as
much spiritual as scientific.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this has been a gift to me, to be able to create
beautiful settings for people,'' Garcia says. ``Plus, I'm just a
big old romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is that more evident than the East Atlanta cottage he's
been refurbishing the past four years. Surrounding the 1930s house
on Metropolitan Avenue is an overstuffed, overgrown English cottage
garden _ a look that's become Garcia's signature style.
</P>
<P>
   Even the rear deck holds romantic touches, such as the quaint
collection of watering cans sitting next to a nostalgic milk box
from Garcia's childhood. Lush grapevines billow from the rail,
while below, giant sunflowers bob over a stone path wandering
through a forest of everything from heirloom tomatoes to
old-fashioned roses. It's an intown jungle with just enough order
to make it charming and inviting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put 15 plants where most people put one,'' Garcia says of
his addiction to green.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old has been hooked since childhood. The native
Atlantan rattles off memories of his earliest gardening experiences
as if they occurred yesterday. ``I planted my first garden when I
was 12 or 13 to attract hummingbirds,'' he recalls. ``The first
plant I ever dug up was bloodroot. It put it in my pocket and
planted it in the yard. When most kids were building huts out of
old Christmas trees, I was planting them.''
</P>
<P>
   An early bloomer. The inspiration to garden came early for
Garcia, as did his talent for arranging plants.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Kenneth Garcia, founded an interior design business,
and his mother, Betty, had studied fashion illustration. ``I can
remember the vegetable garden my father had outside his shop,'' he
says. ``And my grandmother was a big gardener _ mainly daffodils _
so I couldn't escape gardening if I tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Only once, when he was 12, was horticulture ``forced'' on him.
After a Chastain Park neighbor caught him riding his bike over her
flower bed, the victim, Goody Davis, sentenced him to some dirty
work _ hauling horse manure into her garden. An avid gardener, she
began to nurture Garcia's interests. As a teen, he won the
horticultural sweepstakes at Rich's Harvest Show _ on his second
try.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Buckhead ladies started hiring me to work in their
yards,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   While earning his degree in landscape architecture at the
University of Georgia, Garcia worked in a flower shop, a job that
would help prepare him for a later stint with Atlanta garden
designer Ryan Gainey.
</P>
<P>
   After two years, Garcia formed his own design business, Fine
Gardens. Though well-versed in gardening styles, he soon developed
a niche for cottage gardens. ``I always end up with this overgrown
look,'' he says. ``I hope one day to be able to do something more
restrained.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the romantic look, reminiscent of those rose-filled
enclaves in the English countryside, strikes a chord with
homeowners weary of the suburban cookie-cutter blend of manicured
landscapes. During consultations, Garcia says, clients unsure of
what they want often become nostalgic. ``I tell them to tell me
about your grandmother's garden,'' he says. ``I ask, `What do you
remember from your childhood? Is it a fragrance? Is it the
pathways?'''
</P>
<P>
   He believes the most successful projects result when the client
gets just as involved as he does. ``For me, gardening is such a
spiritual thing,'' Garcia says. ``It just transcends everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Anna Davis feels the same way _ which made the two quite a team
when Garcia designed her last two gardens, the first teeming with
more than 300 roses. ``Brooks is wonderful with color, especially
with mixing roses with perennials,'' Davis says. ``He has gotten a
very good overall education _ both in life as well as gardening.''
</P>
<P>
   A new classroom. One of Garcia's best classrooms was the cottage
garden he created outside his last home _ an apartment building on
East Paces Ferry Road. There, he experimented with an assortment of
perennials, roses, annuals and herbs, grabbing the eye of many
passing admirers.
</P>
<P>
   But four years ago, Garcia left Buckhead for East Atlanta. ``I'd
always wanted to live in a 1920s or '30s house that was well-built
_ one with big attic fans, a screened porch, all reminders of my
childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   He found it in a red brick cottage that had been well-maintained
but needed some personality. Garcia painted the living room and
dining room walls with a mottled yellow wash and the ceilings light
blue. In the bathroom, he replaced bright red wall and floor tiles
with slate. A spare bedroom made a convenient office for his
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside was nothing but grass and one tree, and an enormous
carport took up half the back yard,'' Garcia says of the lot, a
former peach orchard.
</P>
<P>
   A large deodar cedar shrouds the front yard enough to create the
perfect spot for a shade garden, while on the side, a blue gate
ushers visitors into a rear cottage-style oasis laid out in rooms.
Boxwoods help define the spaces, brimming with roses, phlox and
sunflowers, while tepees holding tomatoes and green beans provide
added structure. There also are plenty of old-fashioned plants such
as snow-on-the-mountain, a variegated shrub whose green leaves are
edged in white.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot to look at in this yard,'' Garcia says.
</P>
<P>
   Hops and ornamental grapevines draw the eye up to the deck,
where they form a canopy over his ``experiment station'' _ a
potting bench lined with cuttings from his travels. In a corner, a
row of antique cloches gives the garden even more of an English
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Like his old watering cans, the bell-shaped glass lids, used for
protecting seedlings, aren't just nostalgic garden ornaments. ``I
actually use them,'' Garcia says.
</P>
<P>
   Who says romance is dead?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
