<HEADER>
A6573 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-LMAY22-COX     08-21 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Summer holds joyful surprises along with heat
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like imaginative people of talent and consequence, gardens can
surprise. In every season something happens that did not happen the
year before, that might never happen again: an unexpected bloom, a
death, a new arrival that came on its own.
</P>
<P>
   This summer of exceptional heat has been no exception. As the
season steams on, it leaves its legacy in my garden, including the
bad, the good, the beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in the nine years I've gardened on Peeples
Street, I did what I had chided friends for doing: I gave too much
license to the heat, allowing it to have its way with my garden.
Yes, I watered and pruned and deadheaded, but not as diligently as
I had in past years, when it was not unusual for me to water daily
_ sometimes twice in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, I've increasingly slacked off on the watering,
getting to the point by August where I've focused almost solely on
container plants, leaving plants in the ground to fend for
themselves as I dashed out at first light and gave the plants a
lick and a promise, fending off mosquitoes, and trying not to
breathe the soggy air.
</P>
<P>
   The result, at times, was bad ugly. Lush became a foreign word
in parts of my garden, as vines, such as the purple clematis and a
creeping raspberry, burned as crisply as saucer magnolia blossoms
in winter's last blast. I lost more plants this summer than in any
previous season, among them a rose I had nurtured in a tub for
almost two years.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising, most of the garden lived.
</P>
<P>
   Such willpower.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, however, I didn't see much of that willpower in
action. Watering time used to be looking time, when I'd get down to
the ground and see what each plant was doing, how it was doing,
what subtle changes it was going through.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I did take that time, I found some unexpected delights,
including two purple surprises.
</P>
<P>
   In late July I noticed that a heather I thought had died in the
winter began putting out tiny new leaves. By the first of August,
it was blooming purple. It was also in July that the wisteria that
refused to bloom in the spring _ again _ produced one strikingly
beautiful purple cluster that was barely visible in the thick
foliage winding up the porch railing.
</P>
<P>
   From where the fragrant phlox volunteered (I noticed it a few
weeks ago), I didn't ask; I simply appreciated an addition amid too
many departures.
</P>
<P>
   A potted Confederate jasmine that I took inside for the winter
languished on the back porch all through spring, its leaves never
getting past a pale yellow. But in July it began blooming, yellow
leaves and all, and hasn't stopped. Nearby, a Florida jasmine
bonsai flowered for the first time in the three years I've had it.
Together, they really light up the back porch, making comings and
goings sweet, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   And just when I thought the dry weeks had done in the autumn
clematis living with the Carolina jessamine on the arbor, there it
came, a sprig at the top curling down with sweet white blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Such surprises make me glad I didn't give in completely to the
hellish heat. And now that I can believe it will end someday soon,
I can even find a silver lining in the losses my garden has
suffered: Every plant that died leaves a space for something new.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
