<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-CURSING-COX     08-21 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-CURSING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Swearing has become an everyday way of life for many people and
there seems to be little shame
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News ServiceR
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1939, Rhett Butler scandalized American film audiences when
he told Scarlett O'Hara at the end of ``Gone With the Wind'' that
he didn't ``give a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do we anymore when it comes to cursing.
</P>
<P>
   Like a verbal fungus, profanity has seeped into the everyday
fabric of American life. Damn and hell are now common on network
television. And there seems to be no limit to the use of such
language on cable TV, radio and in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Many CDs today are triple X-rated, filled with vile ideas and
sordid language. Sports stars scratch, swear and give the finger
for all to hear and see. And many youngsters use profanity like
grizzled war veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all sailors now,'' said Jonesboro Police Chief Michael
Montgomery, who has helped implement a city ordinance that makes it
unlawful for a person in his community to curse in front of a child
under 14 years old _ in public or even in the child's home.
</P>
<P>
   But such efforts might be too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   The surface civility of the '40s and '50s _ a time when ``gosh
darn'' still meant you were angry and seemed to fit perfectly with
the white gloves worn by many women _ is a fading memory.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Jay, professor of psychology at Massachusetts College of
Liberal Arts and author of ``Cursing in America'' (John Benjamins
Publishing Co., $14.95), isn't shocked by profanity, but is struck
by how pervasive such talk has become in American society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get off at Penn Station in New York and the stuff I hear on
the street is incredible,'' he says. ``There are no consequences
for swearing in public anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that way.
</P>
<P>
   Court records in Cherokee County show that in 1940, a judge
sentenced a woman to a year in a public work camp ``for using
vulgar, profane and unbecoming language in public.''
</P>
<P>
   If such laws remained in force today, our jails would be filled
with movie stars, professional athletes, politicians and CEOs, the
occasional teacher and minister, and legions of ubiquitous
trash-talking teens.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers say students as young as 12 years old routinely curse
in front of them. In a poll published by USA Today last year, 89
percent of high school principals said they face profanity from
students.
</P>
<P>
   Thalia Watson, 41, a teacher at Sequoyah Middle School in
Chamblee, has firsthand knowledge of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't give a damn what you're going to do to me,'' one
13-year-old student told Watson after the teacher tried to
discipline her.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my day I couldn't even say `What?' to an adult,'' said
Watson, who grew up in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   That phrase, ``in my day,'' comes up a lot when talking with
baby boomers and those who are older. There's a general belief that
people didn't curse as much in the ``good old days.''
</P>
<P>
   Not true, says Jay, who calls that notion ``linguistic
snobbery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think a saloon sounded like in the 1800s?'' he
adds.
</P>
<P>
   He's got a point. Profanity has been around forever.
</P>
<P>
   Take the all-purpose f-word. One professor traced it back to a
1504 English manuscript, ``Flies, Fleas and Friars.'' The f-word
was originally employed as a substitute for ``swiving,'' an old
English term that functioned as a obscene euphemism for sex.
</P>
<P>
   What is different today is that many people no longer feel any
shame about using profanity in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still sensitive to shame, but we've moved it around a
bit,'' said James Twitchell, author of ``Carnival Culture: The
Trashing of Taste in America'' (Columbia University Press, $16.00).
``The word `bitch' has lost its power, but you still don't use the
word `chick' or the n-word,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Colbert, a MARTA bus driver, has been able to monitor the
growing acceptance of public profanity from his driver's seat over
the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   When he joined MARTA in the mid-'80s, he says, it was mostly
teens in the back of the bus who used profanity.
</P>
<P>
   Now women are the major offenders. ``And they're sitting in the
center of the bus,'' said Colbert, 50.
</P>
<P>
   For Colbert, the focus may be women. But no group is untouched
by the use of profanity.
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers curse aloud in the mall. Drivers display profane
bumper stickers. Radio talk-show host Howard Stern spews profanity
at his guests and audience, and grows rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   Public profanity has even reached our highest office. A cursing
landmark was reached in 1984 when George Bush, at the time a vice
presidential candidate, bragged after a debate with Geraldine
Ferraro that he had ``tried to kick a little ass.'' Bush jovially
denied at a news conference later that he had used the words ``a
little.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay says cursing is a central aspect of human communication and
it's simplistic to say it is wrong. Such words, he says, intensify
emotional communication in ways that other words cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stubbed your toe, saying `Oh pooh-pooh' doesn't do it
like saying, `Oh s---,''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Like much in life, Twitchell thinks the rise of profanity can be
linked to money. Corporations began to realize the impact of the
youth market, teens and young adults from 15 to 25.
</P>
<P>
   And youngsters, he says, were interested in what kids have
always been interested in _ any behavior, cursing included, that
would shock their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``All swearing is a breaking of a taboo,'' Twitchell says.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, in search of blockbuster hits, movie and music
producers, publishers and entertainment CEOs have stretched the
envelope, resulting in ever-increasing amounts of vulgarity in
books, movies and on television.
</P>
<P>
   The family hour on network television has become filled with
sitcoms that exploit sex and violence and create the environment
that allows such shows as ``South Park,'' featuring three profane
third-graders and an animated piece of excrement, to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Critics can lambast this change in public tastes, but they don't
have the consumer clout of America's youth culture, Twitchell
thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This audience is the great piston of American culture,'' he
said. ``They don't just have money, but they also have the most
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people shrug their shoulders at such low-brow humor,
thinking it's just a passing phase and will have little real impact
on society. Stephen Carter isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Author of ``Civility'' (Basic Books, $25), Carter fears we'll
all become losers if we allow one another to use profanity casually
in public. He believes that the ability to hold dialogue is
essential to democracy and that vulgar language doesn't encourage
reasoned responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sparks anger or shame but not dialogue,'' Carter said. ``So
it makes it harder for us to talk to each other, and thus hurts
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay said cursing often makes it easier to talk to one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``This language has been around a long time,'' Jay said. ``You
can't do away with these words. There are emotions already built
into them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ban dirty words, Jay said, and people will adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd make new ones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
