<HEADER>
A6579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-PAKISTAN-475&AMP;A     08-21 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-PAKISTAN-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN CONDEMNS U.S. ATTACK ON AFGHANISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-DAMAGE,
ATTACK-RECAP, ATTACK-ISLAM, ATTACK-RUSSIA-REACT,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT, ATTACK-KENYA.) 
(lb) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ The Pakistan government on Friday
condemned the U.S. attack on neighboring Afghanistan, calling it a
violation of the norms of international behavior and saying that it
sets a ``dangerous precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   It also summoned a senior U.S. diplomat to the Foreign Ministry
to hear an official protest by the government, which maintains that
the missiles the United States fired at targets in Afghanistan
crossed Pakistan's air space without permission.
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported that the United States received permission,
but the Pakistani Foreign Ministry on Friday denied that it had
given permission or even been asked for it.
</P>
<P>
   In another protest, which was later withdrawn, the government
maintained that one cruise missile had gone astray, landing in
Pakistan and killing six people. There is no evidence that anyone
in Pakistan was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani government was striving for a balance Friday
between not being too harsh on the United States, an important
ally, but not appearing too soft, lest it fuel the passions of
militant Islamic groups.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of the capital, and in other cities around the
country, condemnation of the U.S. attack was widespread, cutting
across class and political lines. There were small demonstrations
here and in the country's other major cities, but no reported
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Two senior diplomats from countries closely allied with the
United States, sided with the Pakistani version. One said that U.S.
officials had told foreign diplomats in a briefing that the United
States had not sought permission to overfly Pakistan, and that
Pakistan had not been notified of the attack until the missiles
were in the air.
</P>
<P>
   These diplomats also said that Pakistan's protests against the
U.S. attack were not as strong as they appeared to be _ or might
have been. For example, one noted, Pakistan could register a
complaint with the U.N. Security Council over the violation of the
air space. Pakistan has given no indication that it intends to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were the Americans, I wouldn't be feeling too sore,'' he
said. ``I'd be thinking they could have hammered us a lot harder
than this.''
</P>
<P>
   The other diplomat said of the Pakistani response, ``I think it
is for domestic consumption.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released to the public, Pakistan's foreign
minister, Sartaj Aziz, said, ``Irrespective of the motives of these
strikes, the act of violation of the sovereignty and territorial
integrity of these Islamic countries cannot but be a matter of
grave concern to the people of Pakistan, who justifiably feel
outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, Tariq
Altaf, said Friday that Pakistan would continue to cooperate with
the United States in the investigation of the bombings of the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania two weeks ago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the missile attack on Thursday was aimed at
a training complex run by Osama bin Laden, the man that U.S.
officials have charged was behind the embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   To many in Pakistan, bin Laden is not a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   It is not because people here are anti-American or approve of
his terrorist connections. It is rather that they know him as a
hero of the Afghan resistance against the Russians in the 1980s.
And they are not convinced he is a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he really involved? I think not,'' said Tanweer Hussain, a
52-year-old medical doctor. ``How could one man do all that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistanis have a good feeling about America, for its
technology, its education,'' Hussain said, standing on a wide
boulevard lined with leafy trees, after coming from Friday prayers;
sweat stained his loose-fitting, long shirt and thin pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it should not be the policeman of the world,'' he added.
And he criticized the attack on Afghanistan because ``there are
certain norms, certain procedures to be followed.'' The United
States should have been ``more patient,'' he said, and worked
through the United Nations or with other countries.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to find anyone who defended the U.S. action. ``It
was unjust,'' said a woman buying a few items in a shop in
Rawalpindi, a nearby city, as brightly colored minibuses added to
the cacophony on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Although the country's fundamentalist Islamic parties are a
minority and do not do particularly well in elections, they are
well organized and can put tens of thousand of protesters on the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   The first signs were apparent Friday, with small demonstrations
around the country, most of them after Friday prayers.
</P>
<P>
   During prayers at the Lal Mosque, Maulana Mohammed Abdullah told
those gathered, ``You can kill all the Americans around the world,
and those who have helped them.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the men went into the streets. They mounted a small boy on
a car roof, where he posed with a cap gun and a Pakistani flag.
They burned American flags and an effigy of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During one demonstration Iran was a target of the invective,
along with the United States. Iranians are predominately Shiite
Muslims; Pakistanis are primarily Sunni Muslims. And Iran has been
opposed to the Taliban, which has taken control of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   In Peshawar, near the Afghan border, where the fundamentalists
are strongest, there were at least three demonstrations. One group
of several hundred marched on the U.S. consulate there. They were
dispersed by tear gas. The army was deployed to control a
demonstration in Peshawar's university district.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to fight with us, bring your forces. But this is a
cowardly way to attack us,'' said Zaz Mohammed, 50, an algebra
teacher with a gray beard. ``What kind of way is this to fight one
man _ Osama bin Laden?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-STOCKS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-STOCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK STOCKS REFLECT GLOBAL TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The week started out with a bang and ended in a
whimper for bank stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks, which have been battered for a month, posted a nice
rebound earlier this week before economic turmoil in Russia and
concerns about financial instability in Latin America sent the
group reeling.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, the stocks of big money center banks were down
4.52 percent as a group, while large regional banks plunged 3.14
percent as a group.
</P>
<P>
   While Russia alone hardly poses an earnings threat to banks, and
a rumored currency devaluation in Venezuela is not disastrous in
itself, investors are backing away from banks because several
hazards are starting to add up.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Southeast Asia's once robust economies are already
severely wounded. Link those woes to the possibility that the
travails in Venezuela and Russia could spill over into the rest of
Latin America and Eastern Europe, and the scale of global economic
problems looms much larger _ and may portend economic troubles in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market capitalization of the banking industry has declined
by $200 billion in the last month,'' said Michael Mayo, an analyst
with Credit Suisse First Boston. ``The risks in emerging markets,
year 2000 problems and other factors are getting better reflected
in stock prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Large U.S. banks that do business overseas _ the money center
banks _ have only $3.5 billion of lending and investment exposure
to Venezuela, spare change by big bank standards. But they have
$25.7 billion in exposure to Brazil, $17.3 billion to Mexico and
$16.2 billion to Argentina, according to Brown Bros. Harriman &AMP; Co.
The exposure is $98.9 billion to Latin America and the Caribbean as
a whole.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of banks that do a lot of business in Latin America
were punished Friday. Citicorp fell $4.75, or 3.4 percent, to
$134.3125; Chase Manhattan fell $1.625, or 2.5 percent, to $63.50;
J.P. Morgan dropped $3.4375, or 2.8 percent, to $119.375; Bankers
Trust fell $4.9375, or 4.9 percent, to $96.3125, a new 52-week low,
and BankBoston sank $2.4375, or 5.5 percent, to $41.9375.
</P>
<P>
   ``This group has led the market in both directions, and that
behavior is likely to continue,'' said Raphael Soifer, an analyst
at Brown Bros. Harriman. ``But we do feel that the banks are
oversold based on the fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   For big U.S. regional banks, subject to a potential drop-off in
loan growth and heightened credit concerns, also ended on a sour
note Friday. Nationsbank slipped $1.0625, or 1.5 percent, to
$70.3125, and Norwest dropped $1.0625, or 3.2 percent, to $32.0625.
First Union, on the other hand, rose 56.25 cents, or 1.1 percent,
to $51.625.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 50 percent of the sell-off is emotional and 50 percent
is fundamental,'' said Edward Furash, a banking consultant with
Furash &AMP; Co. in Washington. ``But it's clear that the banks that
don't have the capacity to cover earnings shortfalls with other
sources of income are going to get hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
