<HEADER>
A6585 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROYALS-PRENTICE-2TAKE     08-21 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYALS-PRENTICE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYALS DIRECTORS BACK PRENTICE BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES R.T. CRUMPLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City Royals directors on Thursday all but anointed Miles
Prentice as the next owner of the baseball team _ then announced he
needs more local money to complete the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he still has competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference at Kauffman Stadium, directors revealed
that Prentice's $75 million bid to buy the Royals must be composed
of at least 50 percent local money.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they declared his the superior bid and once even called it a
successful one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board is now challenging the citizens of Kansas City to
step up to the plate and support the Prentice bid,'' said Michael
Herman, the Royals president. The ``citizens'' would have to be
wealthy because Prentice wants investments that are measured in the
millions.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Royals did not eliminate other bidders for
the team. That means Prentice's biggest rival, the duo of Chiefs
owner Lamar Hunt and the Topeka utility firm of Western Resources
Inc., could still weigh in with a bid. The Hunt-Western group had
submitted a low bid that was rejected, but the group has been
working behind the scenes to try to boost it.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Hunt-Western team said they had agreed among
themselves not to comment on Thursday's developments. A Western
Resources spokeswoman said, ``Our position is, we continue to work
at the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Prentice said that he was pleased, on the whole, with the Royals
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they endorsed our group not only as the best bid but
as the group they really think could make this operation a
success,'' said Prentice, a New Yorker and minor league team owner.
``They're encouraging Kansas Citians to join. I think it was a
pretty strong endorsement.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't particularly worried about the Royals failure
to eliminate his competitors. ``You can't look over your
shoulder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an afternoon meeting with the editorial board of /{The Kansas
City Star/}, Prentice outlined a survival plan for the area's
baseball franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Royals are on pace to lose $10 million this year,
Prentice believes the team can break even. His plan calls for
higher ticket prices, a lower player payroll, and at least 1.5
million fans a year. The team drew 1.5 million last year and is on
pace to draw 1.6 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   He also would favor about $75 million worth of stadium
improvements that would generate money for the owners. That
presumably would be paid by taxpayers. The Royals have already
outlined a $75 million plan for glassing in the concourse level,
building a pavilion for fans beyond center field, and putting in
bigger concession stands and shops.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice also said he was surprised by the Royals requirement
that he round up 50 percent local money. He said the Royals didn't
tell him that until three weeks ago. Until then, he had been
working toward getting Kansas City investments that equaled
one-third of the total.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Prentice said he hadn't heard until Thursday that
the 50 percent level was a requirement included in the Royals'
articles of incorporation. Herman, the Royals president, revealed
that at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice said he had seen those documents but didn't remember
seeing that provision. He said he didn't have a copy.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Prentice said that if the Royals want 50 percent,
he'll work to accumulate 50 percent. He understood that the Royals
want to be comfortable with his bid because he's from out of town
and must overcome the fear that he secretly desires to move the
baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was so charitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they've done is changed the rules on him,'' said Jerry
Green, the Kansas City banker who last year tried unsuccessfully to
buy the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Green was in much the same position as Prentice, in that Green's
bid was composed mostly of out-of-town money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere did they say I had to have 50 percent. Never was that
mentioned,'' said Green. ``They knew my investor had most of the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Merritt, a spokesman for the Royals directors, said that
Green didn't know about the 50 percent requirement because his bid
never got far.
</P>
<P>
   He further said that it always had been implied that the board
wanted local ownership in the team. The exact 50 percent amount was
disclosed to bidders in documents they saw in May.
</P>
<P>
   The matter apparently didn't come up again until about three
weeks ago when Prentice and the Royals had entered an intense phase
of negotiations called full disclosure. It apparently was a
misunderstanding; the Royals assumed Prentice knew about the 50
percent requirement.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the 50 percent requirement was an important fact
that should have been explicitly disclosed to all bidders at the
very beginning of the process, Merritt said it should have been
explicit to those bidders who saw the documents in May.  &LR; brk:Time
is a factor  &LR; tx:One reason the Royals made their announcement
Thursday is that time is pressing them.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals want to straighten out the Prentice bid within a
couple of weeks. That way, they could present the bid to members of
the major league baseball ownership committee in advance of their
meeting Sept. 16. The officials could approve of the ownership
change at that time. That way, the baseball team could be
transferred during the off season. Otherwise, Prentice couldn't get
approval until the next meeting, which isn't until January.
</P>
<P>
   If the Royals miss the September meeting, it's not likely they
could call a special meeting, said Bud Selig, the commissioner of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have quarterly meetings, and unless it's an emergency we do
not meet until then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice said that a January approval wouldn't kill his bid
because he and the Royals could work cooperatively for a few
months. But it would complicate matters and decision-making could
bog down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1902EDT &QL; 
