<HEADLINE>
ROYALS DIRECTORS BACK PRENTICE BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES R.T. CRUMPLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   making could bog down.
</P>
<P>
   Although Prentice did not reveal many specifics of his bid, he
did drop tidbits about it during a press conference Thursday
afternoon and the meeting at /{The Star/}.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said he had more than 10 local investors.
</P>
<P>
   Among Prentice's out-of-town investors, two are from Detroit.
One out-of-town investor owns a minor league baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   His $75 million bid includes some ``sweat equity'' in which he
gets some ownership stake for no money. But he added that he was
making a significant personal investment.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he's trying to raise more than $75 million _ he'd
like to raise $15 million more _ as a cushion to absorb future
operating losses of the baseball team.  &LR; brk:Prentice says he's
close  &LR; tx:At the news conference on Thursday, Herman said the
Royals were working all but exclusively on the Prentice bid. The
bid has cleared contract negotiations and more or less awaits
signatures. The contracts would be signed as soon as Prentice gets
hits the 50 percent level.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice would not say how close he is to that level, other than
to say he's close.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks he has signed up banker R. Crosby Kemper Jr.;
mortgage banker Jim Nutter Jr.; Julia Irene Kauffman, who is the
daughter of Royals founder Ewing Kauffman and Muriel Kauffman; and
Nancy Kauffman, who is the Kauffmans' daughter-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Herman challenged Kansas Citians to get behind Prentice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people of Kansas City don't want to step up to the
plate, then we'll have to make other decisions. That's what we're
saying,'' Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what other decisions, he said, ``other decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said: ``I'm very disappointed after all this effort
that people of Kansas City have not come forward.''
</P>
<P>
   He nodded toward David Glass, the Royals chairman who last year
decided against buying the Royals after fans reacted negatively to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very nice person here who was willing to do
something,'' Herman said. ``For some reason, people didn't like him
to be an owner. A lot of things have gone on here that chase people
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Royals Director Joe McGuff, who as a longtime sports columnist
for /{The Star/} covered the old Kansas City Athletics and later
the Royals, said that with the exception of Royals founder Ewing
Kauffman, no Kansas Citian has been an owner of a Kansas City major
league baseball team. ``That's disappointing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether more Kansas Citians will quickly join Prentice is
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Mayor Emanuel Cleaver said, ``I know the business
leadership of the city is extremely concerned about major-league
permanence and they would in all likelihood want to try to step up
to the plate. However, we ought to look at all kinds of
opportunities for (others) to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Prentice reflected on his situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has done a lot to vet me, trying to get comfortable
with me,'' he said. ``I'm still an outsider. I'm still a little bit
of an unknown quantity. They're doing everything they can to make
sure that if they pick me and my group, they're picking the right
people. I understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I wish they'd do it a little faster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
