<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-REACTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBINGS ELICIT MIXED REACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Appalling. Murderous.
</P>
<P>
   Warranted. Critical.
</P>
<P>
   The response to U.S. attacks on alleged terrorist camps in
Afghanistan and a chemical plant in Sudan on Thursday could be
described in three ways: swift, emphatic and, above all, mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the United States government for retaliating and
doing anything against terrorism,'' said Surur Puma, a native of
Juba, Sudan, who lives in Kansas City after moving to this country
three years ago to escape persecution. ``We had cried for the
United States to do something, because they killed hundreds of
innocent people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm appalled,'' said Mary K. Meyer of the Shalom Catholic
Worker House in Kansas City, Kan. ``This is about the suffering of
the people. I'm so sad. Here we go again.''
</P>
<P>
   Retaliating 13 days after the deadly U.S. embassy bombings in
East Africa, U.S. forces committed the attacks, President Clinton
said, to ``counter an immediate threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the decision to attack was based on intelligence
information that pinpointed ``one of the most active terrorist
bases in the world'' and an industrial plant that made agents for
chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Some counterterrorism experts said the president had no choice
but to order the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain acts that warrant a military response, and
terrorist attacks are among them,'' said Brent Smith, an expert on
terrorism at the University of Alabama-Birmingham. ``We either had
to attack their training and weapons sites, or sit back and accept
whatever wrongs they've dealt out, or will deal out in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who supported the strikes was Kansas City Mayor
Emanuel Cleaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a person who believes in peace and pacifism, I've got to
say that I was extremely pleased _ as I believe most Americans will
be _ that we are not going to just take terrorism sitting on our
hands,'' Cleaver said Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver said he hoped Americans would not be cynical enough to
view the bombings as an administration attempt to distract
attention from Clinton's personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say, `We'll get the terrorist camps after November,
after Ken Starr finishes his report,' '' Cleaver said. ``You find
who did it, and you hit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said the attacks were a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sudan is not a terrorist state,'' said Kisangani Emizet, a
political science professor at Kansas State University and an
expert on Sudan. ``It is a nation at civil war, not a nation that
seeks to destroy elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it had accurate intelligence, he said, the United States
was wrong in its actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot respond to a terrorist bomb with a bomb,'' he said.
``It is never the terrorist leaders who suffer and die in these
explosions. Just as happened in Nairobi, it is the innocent people
who happen to be nearby who suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   A major concern of those interviewed Thursday was that someone
may attempt to retaliate for the U.S. strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot depends on how good our intelligence is and whether we
can intercept these things ahead of time,'' said Mayer Nudell, a
counterterrorism consultant formerly with the State Department.
``But there will be people who will undoubtedly attempt, whether
successfully or otherwise, to do things against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Barbara McCracken, who works in Peace and Justice of the
Department of Parish Ministries for the Archdiocese of Kansas City
in Kansas, said Thursday's actions will only serve to escalate the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never for responding with violence,'' she said. ``This is
such an extreme misuse of our bloated military capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   A better way, McCracken said, is to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrorists only act because they see no other way,'' she said.
``We won't negotiate with terrorists; we just retaliate. I find
this an immature response. It's not using our full mental
capability.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some might generalize about the American military
``bombing Afghanistan and Sudan,'' University of Kansas political
science professor Philip Schrodt says that is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the attacks are occurring on Afghan and Sudanese
soil, the attacks are against terrorist groups and not these
countries,'' said Schrodt, who studies international conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's bombing was just the latest violence to hit Giselle
Rafiq's home country of Afghanistan. First, the invasion by the
Soviet Union. Then internal civil strife. Now trouble started by
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Rafiq, who has lived here for about two years, said she is glad
the United States took action.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these were terrorists who were bombarded, I hope every one
of them died,'' said Rafiq. ``But I really hope that there were no
innocent people who were hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   About 150 families from Afghanistan live in the Kansas City
area, Rafiq said. Many fled the country after the Soviet invasion
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   But many refugees left relatives behind.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad Sultani's siblings, cousins and uncles still live there.
It is nearly impossible to communicate with them by phone or mail,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sultani said he understands the importance of taking action
against terrorists. Still, that doesn't make him worry less about
relatives back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sad situation. It used to be such a beautiful
country,'' said Sultani, who lives in Lenexa. ``Of course, everyone
has concerns if they have family or friends there. They are every
minute in my mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
