r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBING-WAGDOG-2NDTAK     08-21 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-WAGDOG-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMING OF EVENTS BECOME ISSUE FOR CLINTON CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON AND RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   to draw public attention from his domestic troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Even close to home, the issue became a hot topic on talk radio,
with even the suggestion that Clinton was ``staging the whole
thing.'' joked about the White House ``staging the whole thing.''
Clinton, he suggested, was ``caught with his pants down and now
he's looking for someone to bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one caller protested that idea: ``You're suggesting he
killed people to cover up his sex scandal. You're sick.'' But
others wondered aloud why Clinton, for example, ``announces the air
strike while Monica is testifying.'' ]
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution in
Washington, said that ``if that's a man-on-the-street sentiment,
it's too bad.'' He called the military strikes ``a very serious
response to a dastardly act of terrorism ...and Americans should
approve.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess conceded, however, that some Americans might have trouble
embracing Clinton's case for national security, coming as it does
from the same man who Monday told a national audience he ``misled''
the public about his personal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has lied to them in the recent past, so he'll need to
work hard on this one,'' Hess said. ``It's a problem that will be
out there on everything the president does from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential scholar Douglas Brinkley of the University of New
Orleans dismissed the timing of Clinton's military moves as
``surreal coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing coming out of a lot of people's mouths was,
`My God, it's `Wag the Dog'!'' Brinkley said. (In fact, all 12
copies of the movie were checked out of a Prairie Village video
store by 7 p.m., rare for a Thursday night, a clerk said.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a sex scandal; this is not a joke. We're talking
about war,'' said Brinkley. ``I think you'll find near-unanimous
support (for the decision to strike). Ma and Pa America will be 90
percent behind it. When America goes to war, Main Street rallies
around.''
</P>
<P>
   To Brinkley, the notion of using America's war machine for
political convenience ``would be naive, very cynical and very ugly.
It would defy the reality of these kinds of situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, such thoughts are not new to American history.
Secretary of State William Seward once suggested to a newly elected
Abraham Lincoln that he pick a fight with the French or the
Mexicans to distract his Southern critics.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln thought better, and the Civil War came to pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
