<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6601 &Cx1f; kan-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBING-WAGDOG-2TAKES     08-21 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-WAGDOG-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMING OF EVENTS BECOME ISSUE FOR CLINTON CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON AND RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington's politicians responded Thursday as they usually do
when a president orders military action. They reminded all the
world that they stand with their commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Yet consider how U.S. Sen. John Ashcroft couched his support,
reminding the nation that while smoke hung over Khartoum Thursday,
there remained ``a cloud over this presidency....''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tragic that momentous decisions must be made under these
circumstances,'' the Missouri Republican said in a press release
alluding to President Clinton's sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, the president is entitled to the presumption that his
action is based solely on his judgment of the national interest.''
</P>
<P>
   So although neither politicians nor foreign policy experts on
Thursday accused Clinton of launching strikes to distract a country
from talk of Monica Lewinsky, there was wide agreement on his
vulnerability to the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood suggested recently in the movie ``Wag the Dog'' that a
president would try to blast scandal from the public consciousness
with images of bombs and bullets. But that was a farce, experts
point out, and not reason to believe Clinton is now giving in to
political temptation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The starting point for this military action started with the
bombing of our embassies in Tanzania and Kenya,'' said Robert
Litwak of the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The juxtaposition of these events, in our post-O.J.
sensational pop culture, will inevitably create accusations that he
is trying to create a distraction from his domestic troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-day evaluations typically noted that the attacks in
Afghanistan and Sudan came with the support of Defense Secretary
William Cohen, a former Senate Republican, and Joint Chiefs of
Staff chairman Gen. Henry Shelton, widely referred to as ``a
soldier's soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These professionals clearly believed it was the best course of
action,'' said Abraham Sofaer, a senior fellow at the conservative
Hoover Institution who served as a legal adviser to the U.S. State
Department during the Reagan and Bush administrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never know what's on the president's mind, but I don't
think those people would go through with this just as some sort of
favor to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidents engaged in foreign affairs crises while weathering
tough politics at home have long had their motives questioned.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan's decision to invade Grenada in 1983 was
interpreted in some quarters as an effort to divert the nation's
focus from the bombing of a Marine Corps military barracks in
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   President Carter was accused of trying to shift attention from
double-digit inflation and runaway interest rates when he called
the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in late 1979 the most serious
international event since World War II. He then embargoed grain
sales and led an Olympic boycott.
</P>
<P>
   President Nixon, under attack for firing special prosecutor
Archibald Cox, stood accused of diversionary tactics when he scaled
up the military's nuclear alert status in response to the Soviet
Union's threat to step into the Yom Kippur War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time this argument that presidents stir up foreign
clashes to cover for their other problems is really unfounded,''
said Gaddis Smith, a professor of American diplomatic history at
Yale University. ``The Clinton presidency is an empty shell now, so
you'll hear it a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The effects of Clinton's domestic problems showed through in
varying degrees in responses from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there is clearly much more we need to learn about this
attack and why it was ordered today, given the president's personal
difficulties this week, it is legitimate to question the timing of
this action,'' said Sen. Dan Coats, an Indiana Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, a Kansas Republican who is chairman of the
Near Eastern and South Asian Affairs Subcommittee of the Foreign
Relations Committee, said he is satisfied that the timing of the
bombing was valid.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback based his view on a conversation he had after the
bombing Thursday afternoon with a high-ranking State Department
official. Evidence had become clear that those who were targets
were responsible for the American embassy attacks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the intelligence system gives this kind of information,
you have to quickly respond,'' Brownback said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback said he can understand speculation that Clinton was
trying to divert attention from Lewinsky, especially on the day she
returned to the grand jury for testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing leads people to ask those questions, particularly
now that the president made his statements earlier this week,''
Brownback said. ``I'd hope they didn't take into account a desire
to spin this politically.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nonsense,'' said Rep. Ike Skelton of Missouri, the
ranking Democrat on the House National Security Committee. ``We
found out who the culprits were (in recent bombing attacks) and we
went after them.''
</P>
<P>
   One person not hesitant to challenge the timing of the bombing
was Oliver North, who was on Reagan's National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the administration officials heard from thus far are
accurate, we have apparently long known of Osama bin Laden's role
in several previous terrorist attacks,'' North said in a press
release. ``If that is the case, why didn't the United States strike
/{before/} embassies in Africa were blown up?''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, who is laying the groundwork for a presidential bid,
also noted earlier attacks on Americans and said, ``I look forward
to knowing at the proper time why this action wasn't taken
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sudanese television, that nation's information minister,
Ghazi Salah-Eddin, accused Clinton of trying to draw public
attention from his
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
