<HEADLINE>
WORLD EVENTS CATCH UP WITH MARKETS; DOW DROPS .9% IN VALUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors responding to a chain reaction of plunging world
markets forced the Dow Jones industrial average down more than 280
points Friday before it rebounded and ended with a modest loss.
</P>
<P>
   Recovering most of what was lost during hectic trading, the Dow
Jones industrial average, a basket of 30 of the country's premier
stocks, closed at 8533.65, down 77.76 points, or 0.9 percent.
Broader indexes, including the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 and the Nasdaq
Composite, took similiar roller coaster rides.
</P>
<P>
   US investors were reacting to a day of chaos in stock and
currency markets in emerging markets around the world, analysts
said, amid nervousness that a long-running bull market in this
country may be near its end.
</P>
<P>
   Russian stocks slid for a fifth day, with the main RTS-1 index
tumbling 6.9 percent. European markets responded with sharp
declines _ Germany's DAX stock index was down 5.4 percent, while
Britain's FTSE 100 lost 3.4 percent. The emerging markets panic
spread to Latin America where concerns about Venezuela's currency
caused markets there to plunge.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic comeback in the US market Friday afternoon was read
as an indication of investors' faith in this country's stability as
the full force of a widening global economic and banking crises hit
elsewhere. The Dow index has fallen 8.6 percent from its July peak
_ shy of a ``correction,'' or 10 percent decline _ but remains up
7.91 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great deal of political instability in the world,''
said Jack Smiley, vice president of Easton Vance Management in
Boston. ``The US market still offers a great deal of good valuation
but we haven't had a correction like this in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The US bond market benefited most as investors fled unstable
currencies and scurried to put their money in US dollars: The yield
on 30-year Treasury bonds hit a series of record lows before
settling at 5.38 percent, the lowest rate since the government
began regularly selling the securities in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are ``flying to our bond market which is safety with a
capital `S,''' said Nancy Kimelman, chief economist for Thomson
Global Markets, a Boston consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide panic was triggered by the panic inside Russia,
where the government Friday called for speedy passage of measures
needed to avert a collapse of the entire financial system. That
came a day after the government agreed to guarantee private bank
accounts. Day after day of bad news caused a 14 percent slide this
week in the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's deep problems have been heaped on top of financial
system collapses and economic contractions across Asia over the
past year and concern about the stability of China's currency.
</P>
<P>
   Stock markets in western Europe, which are closely tied to
Russia, also fell sharply and gave up a portion of the large gains
they have earned since January.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's market was hard hit because its banks are major
lenders to Russian enterprises. Investors jittery about extensive
ties to Latin America, an emerging market that is showing signs of
weakness, drove Spain's market down by 5.8 percent. Austria's
market fell by 4.93 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mistake to focus just on Russia or Asia or Japan,''
said Peter Sullivan, European equity strategist for Goldman Sachs
International in London. ``The markets that are down the most in
Europe are those that are most exposed to emerging market shocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging markets in South America also weakened Friday amid
speculation that Venezuela's currency is under severe pressure and
may be the next currency to be devalued. Venezuela said Friday it
would allow the bolivar currency to fluctuate more freely and
introduced a bill to speed reforms aimed at boosting confidence in
the battered economy.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela's stock market was the world's worst performer Friday,
losing 8.4 percent. Argentina's stock market lost 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a global currency crisis afoot,'' said Mark Madden,
emerging markets manager for Pioneer. ``Venezuela may be on the
verge of devaluing its currency.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Bolsa index fell by 2.4 percent and Brazil's stock
market was down 2.8 percent, after collapsing by 10 percent earlier
in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't anything particularly positive at the moment that
can offset a series of negatives,'' said Tim Thomas, head of global
equity team for Guinness Flight Investment Mangement Ltd. in
London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cumulatively there are a lot of things investors don't like,''
Thomas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
