<SLUG> BC-BANKBOS-ATM-FEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSTON TO IMPOSE $1 ATM FEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ BankBoston Corp. said Friday it would soon charge a $1
``convenience fee'' for people who use its automated teller
machines but are not customers of the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes just one week after rival Fleet Financial Group
Inc. said it would charge noncustomers 75 cents each time they used
a Fleet ATM. BankBoston's fee is set to go into effect at its ATMs
in Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Rhode Island over the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts attorney general's office, which criticized
Fleet's decision, also decried BankBoston's plan as
``anti-consumer'' and ``anti-competitive.'' It had supported a bill
to ban so-called ATM surcharges that died in the Legislature last
month.
</P>
<P>
   According to BankBoston, customers of the region's
second-largest bank presently subsidize the use of ATMs by
noncustomers. About 25 percent of the 140 million transactions at
BankBoston's ATM network last year were from noncustomers, and
those transactions cost 50 cents to a dollar each for BankBoston to
process, said bank spokesman Bruce Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   An ATM ``convenience'' fee would force noncustomers to pay their
fair share, and most of the revenues generated would be used to
reduce banking fees paid by BankBoston's customers in
Massachusetts, Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Anthony, chief of the public protection bureau at
the AG's office, took a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ATM surcharge,'' she said of the fee. ``Calling it
by a different name is just a gloss. It doesn't change the fact
that this is a double charge to the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the surcharge, many noncustomers using Fleet or
BankBoston ATMs will continue to pay a transaction fee to their own
banks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; With BankBoston and Fleet, &UR;  &LR; the region's largest bank,
operating about 60 percent of the ATM machines in the commonwealth,
the imposition of an ATM surcharge is likely to induce customers at
small banks to move their accounts to large banks, said Dale
Zelony, director of legislative services at the Community Bank
League of New England, a group that represents small banks.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the surcharge becomes ``a predatory pricing
practice'' against small banks by encouraging customers to switch
their accounts to large banks to avoid the surcharge, said Zelony,
who contends that processing a noncustomer ATM transaction costs a
bank about 27 cents, not the 50 cents to a dollar that BankBoston
claims.
</P>
<P>
   According to Spitzer, large banks in some other states have been
imposing ATM charges on noncustomers for about a decade and there
has been no evidence of ``huge migrations of customers'' from small
banks to large banks.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Zelony's group has tried unsuccessfully to persuade
the Massachusetts Legislature to ban ATM surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony said the attorney general's office may ask the
Legislature to revisit the issue of a ban on ATM surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the attorney general's office will monitor the
marketplace to see what effect the ATM surcharges have on consumers
and smaller banks, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
