<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANK-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTRUCTURING OF JAPANESE BANK SIGNALS LIKELY MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Long Term Credit Bank of Japan, which has come to
symbolize the problems of Japan's banking system and the
government's slowness in addressing them, Friday night announced a
restructuring that paves the way for an injection of public funds
and increases the likelihood of an eventual merger with Sumitomo
Trust &AMP; Banking Co.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring was a clear sign that the government was
hoping to steer the battered Japanese financial system to a
``soft'' landing, rather than the swift overhaul many foreign
investors long for.
</P>
<P>
   Its gradualist approach to one of the worst banking crises the
world has seen, however, may be challenged by those investors, who
have already harshly punished Japan's banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is to have any credibility, the Japanese government must
demonstrate that it is going to allow the market to determine final
outcomes, and if those outcomes suggest losses, it can manage
then,'' said Alicia Ogawa, head of research at Salomon Smith Barney
in Tokyo. ``But what they seem to be demonstrating is that they are
trying to build a wall around the market, and that is just not
going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the government did little to conceal its role in the
rescue effort. On Thursday night, Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi met
with Atsushi Takahashi, president of Sumitomo Trust, in his
official residence, where the banker was wooed not only by the
nation's leader but also by Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine Bill Clinton and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
summoning a bank executive to the Oval Office for a late-night
`chat' about his intentions and their opinion of them,'' snapped
one bank analyst, who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, however, Takahashi appeared to be keeping his
options open, issuing a brief statement that said little other than
that Sumitomo Trust would study the restructuring plan and continue
pursuing ``highly transparent due diligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Obuchi, Miyazawa and numerous other
government officials promised an announcement from Long Term Credit
and revealed the government's intention to shore it up with an
infusion of public funds.
</P>
<P>
   The government started laying the groundwork for a taxpayer
rescue of Long Term Credit earlier this week, when Miyazawa and
other officials testified in Parliament that to allow any of
Japan's 19 largest banks to go under would be courting worldwide
financial chaos.
</P>
<P>
   They made the statements even though the government had
previously pledged to protect international creditors who in good
faith signed swap agreements and other contracts that keep the
global financial system liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Critics described the rescue operation as too little, too late.
``If they have no plan to strengthen profitability, then anything
else is just a stop-gap measure,'' Ms. Ogawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Stop-gap or not, Friday's announcement called into question the
government's ballyhooed ``bridge bank'' plan _ currently under
discussion in Parliament _ for resolving the problems of failed
banks while keeping credit lines open to worthy lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Under the restructuring proposal, Long Term Credit intends to
write off 750 billion yen ($5.2 billion) in bad debts in exchange
for government assistance. These will include some 520 billion yen
in loans to three of its most beleaguered nonbank affiliates, Japan
Leasing Corp., Japan Landic Corp. and Nippon Enterprise Development
Corp. Japan Leasing, which has some 1.9 trillion yen in bad debt,
according to the Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's business daily, will
be ordered to stop financing businesses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dozens of other affiliates to which the bank has transferred
portions of its nonperforming loans in an effort to clean up its
own balance sheet will be liquidated, and its president, Katsunobu
Onogi, and two other senior executives will resign to take
responsibility for the bank's straits. A planned reduction of 700
jobs will be accelerated, and managers and others will see their
pay cut.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Ministry of Finance was coy Friday night about the
extent of the government's assistance to Long Term Credit, earlier
in the day officials said the restructuring will pave the way for
the government's Deposit Insurance Corp. to provide assistance to
the tune of as much as 800 billion yen. Analysts, noting that the
government often provides tax breaks and other sleights of hand
designed to avoid provoking a public outcry, said the actual cost
of the financial cleanup could go much higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan is also expected to keep the struggling bank
afloat with uncollateralized loans to support its day-to-day
funding operations in the event that other Japanese and foreign
banks move to limit their exposure. Long Term Credit has been
relying on the interbank lending market less and less, and analysts
believe it has had little or no access to credit lately, although
the bank claims its borrowing patterns have been normal.
</P>
<P>
   Long Term Credit will withdraw from overseas operations, which
will be assumed by Sumitomo Trust, and try to sell its office
building in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   All of that, analysts say, may only begin to repair the hole in
the bank's balance sheet caused by bad loans. The bank has
officially put the amount of bad loans against which it does not
have reserves at 690 billion yen, but most analysts agree the true
figure is at least 985 billion yen _ not counting bad loans held by
its nonbank affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring will extinguish 520 billion yen worth of loan
credits to the three nonbank affiliates, which owe the bank a total
of 2.84 trillion yen. In other words, Long Term Credit will be
writing off just 20 percent of its own bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   That means Sumitomo Trust may be forced to swallow at least 755
billion yen in bad or potentially bad loans, which it has said it
will not do.
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo Trust has gone so far as to hire Arthur Andersen to
audit Long Term Credit, an obvious sign it does not trust the audit
being conducted by the new Financial Supervisory Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Takahashi has said repeatedly that his bank will not assume any
bad loans in the merger, and, indeed, it can ill afford to. It has
its own debt problems, and its two biggest businesses, pensions and
lending to large corporations, are going elsewhere. And that bodes
ill for the proposed merger, some analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sumitomo Trust and LTCB together is a disaster waiting to
happen,'' said James McGinnis, senior banking analyst at Dresdner
Kleinwort Benson in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   While McGinnis and some other bank analysts have no objections
to merging the good operations of bad banks into stronger banks, he
contends that the government lacks the credibility to force such
combinations without insuring acquiring banks against nasty
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect, the Japanese government needs to issue a return
policy to acquiring institutions if this kind of thing is to work
at all,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
