u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     08-21 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE ARE THE DOUBTERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Red Sox' season ends five weeks from Sunday. Thirty-seven
games remain. The Sox are 23 games over .500, own the second-best
record in the American League, and have a whopping seven-game lead
over the Orioles for the AL's fourth and final (wild-card) playoff
slot.
</P>
<P>
   So where's the panic? Why aren't we hearing the usual ``sky is
falling'' stuff from citizens of Red Sox Nation and those who cover
the Towne Team? Where are those Calvinist clouds of doubt that are
supposed to swirl around the Fenway light towers this time of year?
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows I've tried to inspire some fear in the fandom. I even
spent this week talking to some ghosts of the past to see if they
can throw a scare into the Red Sox machine.
</P>
<P>
   Former Oriole manager Earl Weaver, recently hospitalized with a
mild heart attack, was back at his Florida home this week and said,
``Are the Red Sox gonna blow it again? I see where the Orioles have
been gaining on 'em. A game a week for six weeks wouldn't be too
much. That's how we always did it.''
</P>
<P>
   I explained to Earl that it's not like that here anymore. It's
not like the 1970s and '80s, when Weaver would come to town, his
Orioles trailing by seven games, and announce, ``We've crawled out
of more coffins than Bela Lugosi. If we win the rest of our games,
the Red Sox have to play .600 ball to stay ahead of us. Know how
hard that is?''
</P>
<P>
   It was irrational _ how were the Orioles supposed to win all
their games? _ but Boston fell for it. In those days, Sox fans were
too often burned by Boston teams that folded in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Mr. Russell Earl ``Bucky'' Dent. Twenty years
after he drove a pipe through the heart of the Red Sox, Dent is a
bench coach for the Texas Rangers. He was in town this week and
said, ``I start getting asked about the home run just about this
time of year whenever the Red Sox are trying to make a run at
winning the division or getting in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now if Boston wins the wild card, we might play them in the
playoffs. And there I am again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't that be a sight? If the Sox play Texas, Dent would be
in the visitors' dugout on Friday, Oct. 2, for Game 3 at Fenway
Park _ the 20th anniversary of his shot-heard-round-New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the people from my time will get over it,'' he
said. ``Some of the younger kids that don't know what that game
was, eventually, they'll forget about it. But the people that saw
the game or were here or part of it, I don't think they'll get over
it until they actually win a World Series, and then they can get
rid of the old memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I travel around in the Boston area, there isn't a day
that goes by when I don't have somebody come up to me and tell me I
broke their heart 20 years ago. Everybody kind of remembers that
game and that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Dent knows the New England mind. In the offseason, he does
public relations work for an Auburn, Mass. company. It brings him
to Greater Boston several times a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a couple of years ago, I came up here to play some
golf with some customers at Cape Cod,'' he said. ``There was a bar
out there, and the bartender was a diehard Red Sox fan, and after
the golf game, they told me, `You've got to come over and see this
guy. We're going to bring you in there, sit you down, and see if
this guy recognizes you.' It was the year of the strike, and he was
such a big fan, he had all the baseball hats in his bar covered up
because of the strike. So I walked in and sat down, and he looked
at me and his face kind of dropped. I said, `Hi, I'm Bucky Dent,'
and he said, `I know who you are.'''
</P>
<P>
   We all know who he is. Like Mookie Wilson, Dent is a reminder of
something that went horribly wrong here. Standing in a noisy bar
across the street from Fenway after the Sox' doubleheader sweep of
the Rangers Tuesday, I saw Fox television footage of Dent's homer,
then Wilson's grounder. Back-to-back nightmares. It was too loud to
hear the audio. None was needed.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaker Ken Burns recounted his Mookie story:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a function with Bob Costas, and Mookie Wilson was
there and I didn't know what to say to him. Finally, I walked up
and blurted out, `My therapist said it's important that I speak to
you.' Mookie looks at me and says, `Red Sox fan, huh?'''
</P>
<P>
   It is the legacy of Sox fans. Weaver, Dent, and Wilson still
haunt the Boston ballyard. But this year feels different. The Red
Sox are not winning games by pounding people with three-run homers.
The Sox are winning with pitching, defense, smart baseball, and
teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   If/when the Sox get to the playoffs, we will have to remind you
that Boston has lost 13 consecutive postseason games _ a major
league record. The Sox have not won since Bill Buckner booted
Mookie's grounder.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1998 Red Sox don't remind us of those teams that choked.
They've withstood every challenge. And they look like a dangerous
team in any short series. Maybe this explains the curious absence
of panic around here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
