A6638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITADEL-COX     08-21 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITADEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Citadel president cracked down on hazing, stresses leadership
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ After enduring the grueling freshman year as
a ``knob'' on a campus still grappling with the arrival of women,
Mandy Garcia returns to The Citadel with hard-earned advice for the
new crop of females arriving today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure you try to be 50 percent better than everyone else
just so you can fit in the middle,'' Garcia said. ``You always want
to make sure you look 10 times better so you can look average.''
</P>
<P>
   Such advice applies as well to male cadets who learned early
that upperclassmen looking to discipline or even harass knobs prey
on those who stick out in the grayish ranks. But for the rising,
though still small number of women at the formerly all-male,
state-supported military college, Garcia's formula has special
implications for coping at The Citadel.
</P>
<P>
   More than 580 freshmen are scheduled to arrive for a weekend of
academic orientation, followed by a week of rigorous drill before
upperclassmen return.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of ways, we still stand out,'' said Garcia, one of
the 50 or so women expected to join the approximately 1,700 men on
campus. ``They call it the long gray line, and we want to fit right
in the gray, in the middle, as much as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy differs markedly from August 1995 when trailblazer
Shannon Faulkner stormed The Citadel in the national spotlight. She
arrived on the fortress-like campus after school officials dropped
their contentious, highly publicized court fight to preserve the
corps of cadets' 150-year-old tradition of males only.
</P>
<P>
   An exhausted, poorly conditioned Faulkner faltered just hours
into the first day of ``Hell Week.'' The contrasting images of
Faulkner standing alone against a barrack's wall and upperclassmen
rowdily celebrating her departure portrayed an institution clinging
to the past, despite its decision to admit females.
</P>
<P>
   Attitudes have changed among many cadets, alumni and
administrators, spurred by the hiring of former U.S. Marine Corps
Gen. John Grinalds as The Citadel's president. Now in his second
school year, he has cracked down on hazing, eliminated ``Hell
Week'' for knobs, and stressed leadership development among
upperclassmen, who in years past had ruled partly by hazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the philsophy and the procedures in place,'' Grinalds
said. ``The challenge this year is to live through the
experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Still hanging over The Citadel is a lawsuit by Jeanie Mentavlos,
one of two women who quit in December 1996 claiming she was hazed
and harassed. The other, Kim Messer, settled her suit in state
court for $33,750, while Mentavlos' suit, which seeks $4 million in
damages, is proceeding in federal court. A trial is possible as
early as January.
</P>
<P>
   Mentavlos and Messer enrolled in August 1996 with two other
women, Nancy Mace and Petra Lovetinska. They did not complain of
abuse and have both excelled, with Mace, who arrived with college
credits, expecting to graduate in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Mace will be the first woman to earn The Citadel's ring,
presented to seniors in a history-laced ceremony scheduled for Oct.
8.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, a 19-year-old cross-country runner from Fayetteville,
N.C., also earned a spot in history as The Citadel's first female
scholarship athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was one of 20 female freshmen who enrolled a year ago.
Three resigned during the year, including one who was involved in
an incident that administrators described as sexual misconduct with
a male upperclassman, who also quit.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said another four of her female classmates do not plan to
return this year. One of them was Garcia's roommate, who told
Garcia last spring, ``I don't want to do it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight fell on Garcia last year as The Citadel's
one-woman cross-country team. Despite favorable national publicity,
she said she felt ``lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was devastating to me,'' said Garcia, who said her male
teammates tried their best to include her in activities when they
took road trips.
</P>
<P>
   On race days, the men competed first, then the women. The
Citadel's runners would fan out along the race course, cheering
Garcia on, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But before and after the meets, Garcia said she missed the
camaraderie that her teammates enjoyed in their locker room.
</P>
<P>
   At the Citadel, Garcia had 36 lockers all to herself. To fill up
the loneliness, she got in the habit of putting her shoes, clothes,
towels and other belongings in several of them.
</P>
<P>
   This year, she'll have a half-dozen female teammates. The school
is also sponsoring a new women's volleyball team.
</P>
<P>
   As happy as Garcia is to have the camaraderie, she said she's
already treating her freshmen teammates tougher than she treats the
male freshmen who arrived early on athletic scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself doing that,'' she said, ``because I want them to
be good so people won't be able to say, `See, you shouldn't be
here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
