A6640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-$ADV23-A     08-21 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-$ADV23-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BULL MARKET IS ALIVE (IN BONDS) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
(af) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For all the Sturm und Drang endured by stock market
investors in recent months, equities have remained the favored
vehicle. In the race for returns, however, bonds are the hands-down
winners.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 12 months, a 30-year Treasury bond has produced a
total return of 15.4 percent; the Dow industrials are up 9.98
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of United States Treasuries rocketed last week as
investors fled troubled overseas markets for them _ the most stable
securities in the world. On Friday heavy buying pushed the yield on
the 30-year bond down 1.4 percent, to 5.43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Given the recent move up in bond prices, many investors wonder
whether it's time to sell and lock in their gains. After all, no
less an investment guru than Warren E. Buffett recently dumped his
holdings in zero-coupon bonds, a position he had amassed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Although bonds may retrace some of their steps when world
markets settle down, their long-term prospects remain excellent,
said Charles I. Clough Jr., chief investment strategist at Merrill
Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Clough has been a bond bull since 1996 _ one year too early, he
acknowledges. But now, the scenario that he mapped out two years
ago, when he suggested that investors put more of their money in
bonds than stocks, seems to be unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonds will outperform stocks this year and also in 1999,''
Clough said. ``That may be because stocks provide very little
return. Our anticipation is that they trade sideways.''
</P>
<P>
   Why will stocks be lackluster as bonds shine? In Clough's view,
it all derives from an expected slowdown in the American economy,
caused by a falloff in capital expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has made the economy so strong has been a boom in
corporate investments,'' he said. ``But that has put a lot of
capacity out there, which is reducing prices.'' As a result, cash
flow after capital expenditures is starting to decline at many
corporations, a sign that we may be near the top of the investment
cycle.
</P>
<P>
   How low could bond yields go? Try 5 percent on the 30-year bond
by year-end, which would give a total return of around 14 percent
for the year, based on recent prices.
</P>
<P>
   Yields could drop even further with a recession _ a distinct
possibility in 1999, in Clough's view. The long bond yield could
fall to 4 percent, bringing returns of nearly 30 percent to someone
buying bonds today.
</P>
<P>
   Gemma Wright, strategist at Fimat USA Inc., a broker-dealer in
New York that specializes in futures and derivatives, concurs that
bonds are a buy, but cites another reason.
</P>
<P>
   She sees more investor dollars chasing fewer Treasury issues. At
the end of August, for example, a five-year Treasury note with
$12.4 billion in face value is maturing, with no five-year issue to
replace it.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the reissuance of a maturing two-year note will raise
$4.5 billion less than the issue it is replacing. That's almost $17
billion looking for a home in just those two issues in just two
weeks' time.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for Treasuries, meanwhile, will come from portfolio
managers investing in mortgage-backed securities. These folks are
lagging behind their benchmarks and will buy Treasuries to make
their bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supply side is smaller yet demand will be big,'' Ms.
Wright said. ``For people concerned about global fragility, there's
only one place to be: U.S. Treasuries.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
