<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6645 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERNSTEIN-CENTURY-AZR     08-21 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERNSTEIN-CENTURY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEONARD BERNSTEIN CHANGED THE WORLD IN HIS OWN WAY  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH LAFAVE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Classical music is dead, say pundits and books. And
indeed, it's hard to make a case that it's anything better than
deeply dormant.
</P>
<P>
   I think it went to sleep when Leonard Bernstein died in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein had something that made Classical music live for
Americans. Bernstein, who would have been 80 on Saturday (Aug. 22)
and whose birthday has been celebrated this summer in performances
and tributes that included a full-length ballet on his life, had
all the obvious requirements for a musician of stature: talent,
knowledge, ambition, training. Yet his sum was greater than the
total of those parts.
</P>
<P>
   What did Bernstein have that no one else had?
</P>
<P>
   Naivete. An endless supply of it.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Bernstein was so naive he thought music could change the
world. He was so naive he thought all he had to do was explain
Beethoven to people and they'd prefer it to the Everly Brothers. He
was naive enough to write musicals and think they'd last; to
conduct the sprawling symphonies of Mahler, believing they'd enjoy
a long-delayed success in America; to champion American music in
the hope that native symphonists would find a place alongside
Brahms.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he was right. When he explained, like nobody else
could, what made Beethoven or Stravinsky or Puccini great, people
listened who otherwise couldn't have cared less. His first
recording of Mahler's complete symphonies in the early '60s made
Mahler a household name in American homes. His musicals have not
only lasted; they've cried out for successors. ``West Side Story''
is ubiquitous, ``Candide`` is frequently revived and ``On the
Town,'' age 54, is still like a refreshing slap. The American
symphonies Bernstein fought to get into the repertoire _ scores by
Ives and Copland and Harris and many others _ are now there
ensconced.
</P>
<P>
   Did he change the world through music? Not as much, nor for as
long as he wished, but for a while and for the better.
</P>
<P>
   Without his sense that everything was possible, without the
innocence that came with his self-absorption, none of it would have
happened. People who knew him only for the Young People's Concerts
or recordings might have thought Bernstein the ultimate
sophisticate. Those afflicted with the notion that Classical music
must be ``elitist'' perhaps assumed he was a snob.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the real Bernstein, here's a scene-from-the-life,
one I witnessed personally. It's backstage at Avery Fisher Hall in
New York, 1986, and Bernstein is about to go onstage to conduct his
old orchestra, the New York Philharmonic. Is he immersed in the
music? Does he pace the floor or stare at the walls? No. The
conductor laureate of the New York Philharmonic is instead
effusively making the case for the songs of Irving Berlin to a
janitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there were all those great waltz tunes, he could spin
them out one after the next,'' Bernstein tells the amazed janitor.
And Lenny, as he has asked the janitor to call him, starts to sing:
``Remember the night, the night we met, well I forgot to
re-mem-ber!''
</P>
<P>
   Then the puzzled janitor's new buddy walks onstage and conducts
three American ``thirds'' _ the Symphonies No. 3 of Aaron Copland,
Roy Harris and William Schuman _ like nobody else.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the birthday celebrations this year have been
centered on the East Coast, the rest of us at least have ``The
Bernstein Century,'' a re-issue on Sony compact disc of Bernstein's
early recordings for what was then Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The series of several dozen CDs contains many old friends as
well as fresh surprises. Here is the first release on compact disc
of Bernstein's first recording of Copland's Symphony No. 3, of the
celebrated Mahler Fifth Symphony ``Adagietto'' recorded live at the
funeral of Robert F. Kennedy, of the first (and best) version of
Bernstein's own Symphony No. 3, ``Kaddish.``
</P>
<P>
   Like all performing artists, Bernstein was better at some things
than at others, but to all things he brought an insouciance that
made every score at worst a misadventure, at best an unforgettable
journey of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   From this attractively packaged, expertly remastered and
moderately priced series, Bernstein fans will surely want to choose
the Mahler Symphony No. 2, the ``Resurrection'' (SM2K 63159, with
the aforementioned live performance of the ``Adagietto``) because
it was Bernstein's signature symphony. But don't ignore the
overwhelming sense of visceral power Bernstein brought to Mahler's
Symphony No. 6 (SMK60208), which relates in purely instrumental
terms the inevitability of beauty and tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   All truly naive artists are dramatists at heart. For Bernstein
as conductor, this meant he could turn himself into the imagined
protagonist of every score he led; he lived the music as he
conducted it. This thespian knack worked at a high level for
Mahler, which might be described as operatic music without scenery,
plot or characters. It also meant that Bernstein's Beethoven did
not always please purists who wanted a more restrained sound than
Bernstein could manage.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein did not lead the works of his contemporaries out of
duty but out of love. Ives and Copland and Schuman and the rest
were his models, mentors and friends. They made up a musical
community and Bernstein was their greatest advocate. In the CD
``American Masters'' (SMK60594), Bernstein shows what it takes to
make the one-movement essay Roy Harris called his Third Symphony
sing and dance. This performance has a fire that has never been
equaled.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein the composer was frequently at odds with Bernstein the
conductor. They vied for time and recognition, and conducting
usually won. But when composing got the lion's share of his
attention, Bernstein mustered a unique voice that uttered things
from deep in some place where all of us live. In scores like the
three symphonies and the ``Mass,'' he was bold enough to speak like
a child, and childlike enough to talk to God.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein's ``Mass'' probably received more media attention than
any other Bernstein score, except the musicals. The reason: It was
composed for the 1972 opening of Kennedy Center in Washington D.C.,
an event weighted with political and sentimental baggage. Listening
to it more than a quarter-century later, it is more cohesive _ or
at least less incoherent _ than it seemed at the time. The opening
half-hour of variations-on-a-theme makes for an arresting suite.
But ``Mass'' was intended to be more than that. It was to be a
statement about the relationship of God to man and man to man, with
a little (or a lot of) contemporary liberal '60s stuff thrown in.
The result overflows in several directions. Ultimately, it's still
a letdown.
</P>
<P>
   The real stunner is an earlier Bernstein score that has yet to
be given its due as a major work of the mid-20th century: Symphony
No. 3, ``Kaddish,'' re-released here in its original, 1964 version,
with the narration supplied by his actress-wife, Felicia
Montealegre. On SMK 60595, it's paired with the ``Chichester
Psalms,'' a brief set of choral-orchestral settings of David's
psalms Bernstein composed in 1966 as a sort of postlude to
``Kaddish. ``Chichester'' is the more popular of the two pieces.
Its gentle, sweet ministrations have become fairly standard fare,
while the poetic, dramatic, world-wrenching and (some would say)
religio-bombastic God-questing of ``Kaddish'' (the name comes from
a Jewish prayer) has not caught on.
</P>
<P>
   It would if people listened to this remarkable recording, filled
with the early, undiluted intensity of Bernstein's intentions,
which was nothing less than the proclamation of a religious vision
in musico-dramatic terms. Here, Bernstein's naivete mated with his
ambition and his talent to produce a moment of genius.
</P>
<P>
   Others might blush to write an epic poem addressing God in which
the usual roles of Creator and Created are blurred, so as to make
each entity both Created and Creator. Not Bernstein. Still others
might not see fit to set the completed poem to massive, surging,
embracingly tender, stormily angry music and place the whole
strange package before a public uninterested in new music and bored
by questions of theology. Not Bernstein. Not someone so innocently
in love with his own mind and soul.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Kaddish'' and ``Chichester,'' Bernstein's composing
talent waned. Maybe the naivete wasn't endless, after all. Seeing
that he couldn't change the world for keeps, did Bernstein stop
trying to change it in the fleeting, temporal world of music?
</P>
<P>
   No matter. These recordings can change the universe for us
anytime we choose. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kenneth LaFave writes on classical music for The Arizona Republic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
