<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6647 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USSTRIKES-DETER-0822-     08-21 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USSTRIKES-DETER-0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. AIR STRIKES MOVES WAR ON TERROR INTO 'ANOTHER ERA'
 &HT;    With USSTRIKES-POLICY-0822.
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Americans braced for possible repercussions for
missile strikes aimed at a suspected terrorist regime in
Afghanistan and Sudan, a question tugged at defense experts: Will
such shows of military might prevent future attacks?
</P>
<P>
   As former Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn sees it, the $100-million attack
on key operations of Osama Bin Laden, the wealthy Saudi who has
declared war on Americans, was well worth the price. Nunn, who
served on the Senate Armed Services Committee for most of his 24
years in Congress, is no stranger to the fall-out that will likely
come from the U.S. strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly and unmistakably, we are telling them that they aren't
going to be permitted to do this and get away with it,'' Nunn said
in an interview with the Cox News Service. ``It won't keep it from
happening again, but . . . it sends a signal that it (the regime of
bin Laden) won't be a safe haven.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States claimed that its cruise missile strikes
flattened a chemical weapons plant in Sudan, but Pentagon officials
remained uncertain about how much damage was inflicted in
Afghanistan where the target was a suspected meeting of terrorist
leaders organized by Bin Laden. President Clinton ordered
Thursday's missile strikes as an act of retribution for attacks on
U.S. Embassies in East Africa earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a meeting Friday with congressional leaders on
Capitol Hill, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told reporters
that more is yet to come. ``This is unfortunately the war of the
future and we have to understand the importance of sustained
operations here,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   So if, as Nunn and other defense experts said Friday, America is
engaging in ``a long-term struggle'' against terrorist attacks, how
best can it protect itself?
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the nation should be firmly on how to bolster the
nation's intelligence-gathering operations, according to Nunn and
other experts. Without solid intelligence networks, President
Clinton would not have had knowledge that Bin Laden was convening a
group of terrorist leaders at his camps in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   And that means accepting that the CIA is going to have to have
to hire individuals of a nefarious ilk to penetrate the
organizations of terrorists such as Bin Laden, someone who has
called himself the president of a ``terrorist university.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation wants us to stop this, but . . . when the CIA gets
involved . . . and the operation goes wrong, they are criticized,''
Nunn said. ``We have this notion that we can get good intelligence
by penetrating the good guy organizations, the Boy Scouts. But we
have to penetrate the bad guy organizations and we have to be
willing to make some mistakes to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way to prevent terrorist attacks from Bin Laden in the
future is ``a bullet in the head,'' said Dr. Neil C. Livingstone,
who has urged Congress to combat terrorists with military might.
</P>
<P>
   As Livingstone sees it, this is a case where ``might does make
right'' because it is the only language that terrorists seem to
understand.
</P>
<P>
   How effective the American strikes were in stopping Bin Laden
depends on how aggressive the Clinton Administration is in
continuing to attack him and his organization, Livingstone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to cripple them. You have to kill them. If you
declare war, you have to win unconditionally,'' Livingstone said.
``It's like running up to a bear with a sharp stick and jabbing it
a few times. If this is part of a series of attacks, it will be
effective. But if we give him time to lick his wounds, these will
be seen as ill-conceived.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't that merely creating an ``eye for an eye'' situation,
a situation that gives cause for more violence to break out in a
volatile region of the world?
</P>
<P>
   ``In that region of the world it goes far beyond an eye for an
eye,'' Nunn said. ``It goes to two eyes for an eye or an eye for a
finger. ``
</P>
<P>
   Nunn predicted that future attacks are going to be even more
sporadic and unpredictable than the bombings of the U.S. embassies
in the relatively peaceful countries of Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should believe that this is a conclusive act and that
there will be a quick resolution to this,'' Nunn said. ``We are in
another era now.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
