<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-FRAUD-ART-2TAK     08-21 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-FRAUD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC BALKS AT THE GOSPEL ACCORDING TO PASTOR CHUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif., Mich., N.M., Neb.)  (ART ADV: Photo of Charles Groeschel is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sums were not huge. No famous people or exotic locales were
involved. But investigators call this a swindle with an unusual
angle: It had God on its side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a dream that a CNN reporter finally managed to get an
interview with God,'' Charles Groeschel, the head of the
Association of Individual Ministries, used to tell visitors to his
religious group's Internet Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't miss a thing that goes on down on earth,'' God tells
the reporter, and then launches into a rousing endorsement of the
fund-raising efforts of Groeschel's group. ``Understand this,'' God
said, ``these people can't be stopped! I have empowered them with
my Holy Spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever God's opinion of the group, though, federal
law-enforcement officials have a dimmer view, describing it as one
of the more exploitive frauds in recent memory, one that snared
about 2,000 victims nationwide between 1996 and earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In what appears to be an unusual mix of an investing pitch and
religious hucksterism a la Jim Bakker, Groeschel used the
Association of Individual Ministries as the centerpiece of a
pyramid scheme that promised copious _ and ultimately nonexistent _
financial returns, according to the U.S. attorney's office in New
York, which has filed criminal charges against Groeschel.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission made similar charges in a
civil case filed against Groeschel and the group.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC, responsible for policing securities fraud, was involved
because the group's pitch, in spite of its religious trappings, was
basically a promise of a return _ a hefty one _ for investing
money.
</P>
<P>
   Groeschel, who was arrested last month in North Carolina and
released on bail, has returned to his home in Palm Desert, Calif.,
and is awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Nehra, an attorney in Muskegon, Mich., who is
representing Groeschel before the SEC, said he would have no
comment until the criminal charges were resolved. Noell Tin, a
Charlotte, N.C., lawyer, said Groeschel intended to hire him to
contest the criminal charges but had yet to do so and therefore he
declined to comment. Tin said Groeschel declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   In recent testimony before the SEC, Groeschel, known to his
followers as ``Pastor Chuck,'' said his organization was a ``group
of people who are working together, seeking to build the church, a
congregation, a ministry,'' and he expressed a desire to expand the
boundaries of his enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a prejudice against the church in America,'' he told
the SEC ``And we want to establish ourselves internationally
because we have a worldwide mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Groeschel's ``church,'' though, appears to exist only in a small
office in Palm Desert. If it has a worldwide mission _ or, in fact,
any physical trappings beyond that office _ there is no evidence of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Groeschel did attend a seminary, according to the SEC, and for a
time in the '70s _ it could not be determined for how long _ he
served as a Baptist minister in Thermal, Calif. But the group's
ties to organized religion seem to end there.
</P>
<P>
   While the sum that Groeschel and the group are suspected of
stealing _ $1.5 million to $2.5 million _ is paltry compared with
many other noteworthy frauds, the nature of the alleged swindle is
hardly run-of-the-mill.
</P>
<P>
   The group is charged with masquerading as a nonprofit church
that persuaded people to become ``associate ministers'' by making
weekly ``donations'' to the organization. The ministers,
investigators say, were instructed in company handbooks to emulate
Jesus Christ and recruit at least 12 ``disciples'' who would also
invest and recruit 12 others, and so on and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Ministers at the top of the chain were to receive a portion of
the money paid by disciples on the rungs below them. Disciples were
told that once they had achieved financial independence from what
the religious group derided as the ``world system,'' they would be
free to help spread the association's message of spiritual and
material salvation.
</P>
<P>
   But only a tiny portion of the money put into the organization
by members was returned to them. The bulk of the money was siphoned
away by Groeschel, with some of it landing in off-shore bank
accounts, according to federal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic pitch was give and ye shall receive, but I hardly
think that when Jesus told his disciples to follow him and put away
all earthly things, they expected to become millionaires,'' said
Dorothy Heyl, an SEC lawyer in New York. ``Unfortunately, that's
what the AIM investors we spoke to expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Groeschel, 66, is described by former associates and some
purported victims as the very model of a conservative religious
leader: well-groomed and handsome, with neatly trimmed, snow-white
hair and a mellifluous voice.
</P>
<P>
   He was also well armed. When federal agents searched his home in
early July, they confiscated four handguns, hundreds of rounds of
ammunition, and ``approximately six long-barreled guns, including
shotguns, rifles, and one that appeared to be an assault-type
weapon,'' according to a search warrant in California.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior members of the Association of Individual Ministries,
a group of 13 people known as ``elders,'' sounded sympathetic
toward Groeschel but said they did not want to say anything on the
record, adding that their lawyers told them not to talk about the
group or Groeschel. Yet some former group members now have a
distinctly unvarnished opinion of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a thief, a crook, a scum and a scam artist,'' said
Richard Clark, a former elder, who said he left the group after he
became disillusioned with it and Groeschel's methods. ``He has
taken the Bible and the word of God and used them deceitfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who lives in New York, said he and about 60 other members
he recruited invested about $18,000 in the group. Clark said that
about $15,000 of that was his own money and that he ended up
getting only about $600 back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what he did to unsuspecting poor folk and Christian
people,'' Clark continued. ``I was sick and tired of this man using
people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Financial shenanigans are not uncharted territory for Groeschel.
In 1993 he was convicted in New Mexico on criminal charges of
running an illegal pyramid scheme at Santa Rosa Sales and
Marketing, which he founded in 1981 in Palm Desert.
</P>
<P>
   It evolved in the late 1980s into a phony marketer of silver
coins and operated in several states, according to court records.
Santa Rosa salespeople were told they could earn large commissions
buying and selling the coins and then reap further rewards by
bringing in new recruits.
</P>
<P>
   The coins sold by Groeschel to his sales staff were priced well
above their value to collectors, and thousands of people lost
millions of dollars. Santa Rosa was eventually shut down by state
law-enforcement agencies. In New Mexico, Groeschel was sentenced to
18 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was a nice guy,'' said James Burroughs, a lawyer
in Albuquerque, N.M., who represented Groeschel in the Santa Rosa
affair. ``He sets out to do something and he gets it done. I didn't
find him to be anything of those things he's always accused of
being.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gordon Kosmicki, a resident of Grand Island, Neb., who
worked with Groeschel at Santa Rosa in the early 1990s until he
quit after Nebraska officials ordered the company to stop doing
business in that state, had this to say: ``He's as crooked as a
dog's hind leg. He's a real good con artist. You better be
handcuffed to him, because that's the only way you can keep track
of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Groeschel, investigators say, picked up where he had left off
soon after he was released from prison in 1994. He had originally
incorporated the Association of Independent Ministries in 1992,
even as he was fighting legal challenges to Santa Rosa, but the
religious group did not begin rounding up disciples until 1996. By
1997 the group was in full flower.
</P>
<P>
   The group told prospective members that 66 percent of the money
it collected would be returned to them, investigators say, and told
some of them that if they recruited five new members, and each
recruit recruited five new members, and so forth until 780 other
members had joined, a weekly ``donation'' of $50 by the original
member would, through a complex formula, produce returns to him or
her of $5,875 a week.
</P>
<P>
   According to the federal suits filed against Groeschel, his
group actually redistributed only a small amount of the money and
diverted a large chunk of it into Sage Computer Services. Sage,
which is controlled by Groeschel and his wife, Robyn, purportedly
provided clerical and accounting services for the Association of
Individual Ministries, but also provided a healthy stream of income
to Groeschel.
</P>
<P>
   To buttress the aura of religious zeal surrounding it, and to
appeal to the spiritual sensibilities of those being recruited, the
group regularly cited scripture in its marketing materials. In one
``lesson for sharing'' written by Groeschel, he offered the
following observation:
</P>
<P>
   ``When a person joins AIM, they are simply donating or giving to
the financial support of their brothers and sisters in Christ. They
are also receiving from their brothers and sisters in Christ. We do
this in a manner where we see our giving multiplied. Thus, we
receive more than we give, just as Jesus stated in Luke 6:38.''
</P>
<P>
   Groeschel also made abundant use of the Internet, on a site that
recently ceased to exist, toured the country in recruiting
``jubilees,'' and held conference calls on the telephone that he
christened ``faith healings.'' In a tape-recorded message played
for recruits and cited in the U.S. attorney's case, Groeschel said,
``It tells us in 2nd Corinthians that it is God's will that we
become rich, in order that we might be generous, that God might
receive the praise.''
</P>
<P>
   To expand his membership, Groeschel early last year stopped
promising ``ministers'' that the only path to riches lay in
recruiting new disciples. Instead, Groeschel told the membership, a
new ``growth strategy'' he had put in place would produce returns
of 15 percent a week as long as they ``redonated'' checks they had
already received from the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, AIM had no means to pay such a preposterous return,''
the SEC said in its lawsuit against Groeschel and the group. ``AIM
was not itself engaging in any activity that would generate
returns, as Groeschel has admitted.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, membership has dropped from roughly 2,000 to about
500, and those allegedly duped by Groeschel are licking their
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed in Pastor Chuck because he was quoting the
scripture and we were all spiritual people,'' said Franki Brownlee,
a 66-year-old New Yorker who said she lost more than $1,100. ``I
thought I could help others and help myself to be free of the world
system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
