<HEADLINE>
HEARST-ARGYLE TO ACQUIRE CALIFORNIA STATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Deletes extraneous word in lede; changes headline)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hearst-Argyle Television Inc. announced Friday that
it agreed to acquire KCRA-TV in California's Central Valley from
Kelly Broadcasting Co., and a management .MDSU/.MDNM/interest in
KQCA-TV in a deal valued at $520 million.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction, subject to regulatory approval, is expected to
close early next year.
</P>
<P>
   KCRA, an NBC affiliate, and KQCA, an affiliate of the WB
network, serve the Sacramento, Stockton and Modesto market. Under a
time-brokerage agreement with KQCA, the station would remain under
separate ownership but Hearst-Argyle would provide programming and
management operations for the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are especially pleased to announce this particular
transaction,'' said Bob Marbut, chairman and co-chief executive of
Hearst-Argyle. ``Kelly's Sacramento TV operations constitute a
unique opportunity for Hearst-Argyle Television, similar in quality
and strategic benefit to the Pulitzer TV stations that we recently
announced plans to acquire.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst-Argyle owns or manages 15 network-affiliated stations and
manages two radio station. If approved, the acquisition of the
Kelly and the Pulitzer properties would bring to 26 television and
seven radio stations owned by New York-based Hearst-Argyle.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate transaction, Hearst-Argyle announced an agreement
in principle to acquire Kelly News &AMP; Entertainment, a production
and syndication company, for $10 million. Kelly News &AMP;
Entertainment is the syndicator of ``Rebecca's Garden'' and
``Living Better with Carrie Wiatt,'' two lifestyle programs
produced by Hearst-Argyle Television Productions.
</P>
<P>
   The combined operations would give Hearst-Argyle four stations
in the top 20 television markets and seven in the top 30, said John
G. Conomikes, president and co-chief executive of the company. The
company's television stations will cover 20 states, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The transactions will bring Hearst-Argyle's reach to at least
17.6 percent of U.S. television households and will make the
company one of the two largest independent television station
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, KCRA and the KQCA time-brokerage agreement produced
net revenue of more than $65 million. Hearst-Argyle anticipates
1998 net revenue for the stations to increase by about 9 percent
over last year.
</P>
<P>
   The television market served by the two stations in California's
Central Valley is the 20th largest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The total consideration for the two stations, which at closing
will include $11 million in working capital, is $520 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
