<HEADLINE>
THE SUMMER OF '98 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 23, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Televisions flickering fitfully at odd hours; each day's
newspapers gathered in sheaves and quickly scanned; arguments among
old friends ending in bitter words: just three times in the last 50
years have there occurred summers like this one, during which much
of the nation has been gripped by a galvanizing political drama
played out in courthouses and hearing rooms: 1954, 1973, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The turning point that was the Army-McCarthy hearings on the
summer of '54 had one set of economic consequences. Watergate in
the summer of '73 another.
</P>
<P>
   What might be the long-term consequences of the summer of '98?
</P>
<P>
   When Senator Joseph McCarthy rose to power in the early 1950s,
the Cold War was at its height. Under the banner of anticommunism,
using a potent combination of official hearings, press releases,
and leaks, the Republican junior senator from Wisconsin attacked
several of the reigning institutions of US society: the State
Department, the universities, the Protestant clergy, the Army.
</P>
<P>
   As McCarthy browbeat witnesses before his Senate Investigations
Sub-Committee on lengthy televised hearings during the summer of
1954, Boston lawyer Joseph Welch turned on him at a crucial moment
(``Have you no sense of decency, sir, at long last? Have you left
no sense of decency?''), President Eisenhower denounced him, the
Senate formally rebuked him in December, and McCarthy died a broken
man in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   The ritual of censure had the effect of establishing a broad
consensus about the limits of acceptable political behavior _ a far
more binding constraint than the growth of the money supply. A long
smooth run in the markets was the result.
</P>
<P>
   When the Watergate scandal slowly unfolded after the election of
1972, the effect was the reverse. Aside from the narrow agreement
on the necessity of President Richard Nixon's resignation, the
affair put a a high chop on the political waters. But in the summer
of 1973, the Senate Select Committee's televised hearings _
presided over by Sam Ervin and Howard Baker _ riveted the nation's
attention and, thanks to the disclosure of the existence of the
secret White House tapes, prepared the way to closure.
</P>
<P>
   Watergate indubitably contributed to the Turn to the Right, a
considerable irony, since Nixon was in many ways the last of the
line of ``big government'' presidents who began with Franklin D.
Roosevelt and the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Yet the new consensus took nearly a decade to form, requiring
strong action by a Democrat (Federal Reserve chairman Paul Volcker)
and the election as president of another Republican (Ronald Reagan)
to take hold. Betweentimes, the Dow Jones industrial average
floundered.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these previous summertime crises were profoundly
inclusive: They invited in all parties and, for the most part,
bound them together. So far, this one appears to be the opposite.
At least among its commentators, it has been deeply divisive, as if
two sets of persons were reading from two completely different
pages.
</P>
<P>
   (But for the emphasis on legal procedure, you could argue that
the nerve-racking summer of '98 bears more of a resemblance the
street warefare of 1968 than to the stately dramas of those other
years.)
</P>
<P>
   One side sees ``the character issue,'' in the form of
Whitewater, Travelgate, Filegate, hush money to Webster Hubbell,
the campaign contribution scandals of the reelection year. So
tainted is the president, goes the argument, that he must now
resign or be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   The other side sees a special prosecutor who, having failed to
document wrongdoing in five or six or seven matters _ having tried
to resign his commission without issuing a report _ finally has
gone to town when the Monica Lewinsky matter was brought to his
attention. According to this view, Clinton's antagonists are
attempting to win through the special prosecutor what they could
not achieve through the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the press is a big player. The Wall Street Journal has
been in full throat since Clinton was first elected in 1992. The
big surprise is The New York Times. As Jack Shafer wrote earlier
this summer in the e-zine Slate (where he is deputy editor), The
New York Times and The Washington Post have mysteriously swapped
identities in the course of the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In place of the Old Gray Lady Persona of the Times, wrote
Shafer, is the deviltry that was the Post's franchise in the
Watergate years, complete with ``barrelhouse editorials demanding
action _ such as the resignation of Janet Reno _ that stir
substance and fanfaronade.'' &UR;  &LR; Now it is the Post that exemplifies
even-handed decorum.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the public is not with the press. Clinton's
favorable ratings rise in defiance of the editorialists' screeds.
Newspersons emerged from Watergate as heroes; in the current
controversy they must share the blame with Clinton, Starr, and all
the others who have contributed to the current mess.
</P>
<P>
   As Russell Baker of the Times wrote the other day, ``Taste-free
journalism makes you wince with shame for what used to be an
honorable calling.... Sensitive people will be content to loathe
them all for what they have done to the country, for how they have
debased our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   What next? These conflicts are usually resolved by a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a tide running that would give the Democrats the 11
seats they would require to control the House after the November
elections? The conventional wisdom is no.
</P>
<P>
   But let Kenneth Starr file his report, let Clinton go on ``60
Minutes'' to demonstrate the contrition that he failed to exhibit
last Monday _ and unpack the anger _ and the situation could
change.
</P>
<P>
   My own hunch is that the campaign waged against Clinton all
these years will lead relatively quickly to the resurrection of the
Democratic Party, just as the campaign against Nixon enabled the
Republicans to reclaim power in just six years.
</P>
<P>
   And a good thing too, for long-term economic growth depends on
broad consensus. Such agreement was formed by the New Deal,
reaffirmed during Dwight Eisenhower's first term in office,
reconfigured along slightly different lines by the election of
Ronald Reagan, and embraced in 1992, albeit reluctantly, by William
Jefferson Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The instability of markets in the summer of '98 is just the
beginning. Only when Kenneth Starr has joined Joe McCarthy among
the shades of memory, and Clinton taken his place in history along
side Nixon, Harry Truman, and Warren Harding, will America again
see the kind of friendly, practical bipartisanship that is the
necessary framework for solid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
