<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6666 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-REBELLION-600&AMP;A     08-21 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELLION-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA TO MEET WITH LEADERS IN CONGO CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ As the countries entangled in the civil war
here threatened to turn the nation into a battlefield for divergent
ethnic, political and diplomatic rivalries, President Nelson
Mandela of South Africa on Friday announced plans for weekend talks
with the leaders involved.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to President Laurent Kabila here said they might
participate in the negotiations, and the South African government
announced that heads of the main countries involved in the conflict
had also agreed to meet in Pretoria, South Africa, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after Zimbabwe began openly supplying
Kabila's hard-pressed forces with arms and troops in the region
southwest of here, an effort that may have tipped the scales when
the fall of Kinshasa seemed all but inevitable. Meanwhile, Rwanda
and Uganda, which have steadfastly denied buttressing the rebellion
against Kabila, used unusually harsh words to denounce Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   The South African government, which has been pressing for a
peaceful resolution to the conflict and has opposed military
intervention, said that Mandela would meet on Saturday with Kabila
and the presidents of Zimbabwe, Uganda and Rwanda. The next day,
representatives of the 14 nations of the Southern African
Development Community are scheduled to meet to try to agree on a
policy toward the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the organization's biggest members, South Africa and
Zimbabwe, have locked horns on the issue of military involvement.
Uganda and Rwanda do not belong to the organization, which is
chaired by Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a turning point,'' said a European ambassador in
this city. ``I think on Saturday, they might try to get the major
players together to iron out their differences before the Sunday
meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   But the conflict has already damaged long-term relations among
countries in this region, he said, adding: ``Relations between
South Africa and Zimbabwe are deteriorating as this goes on.
Clearly, Rwanda and Uganda are unhappy. I think it will be
difficult to see how this will all end.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks will allow Kabila's government to reinforce the point
among the Congolese that outsiders started this civil war. On
Thursday, a leader of the rebellion offered to negotiate a
cease-fire with Kabila's government, which immediately rejected any
talks with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to negotiate with our real enemies, that is to say,
Rwanda and Uganda,'' Dominique Sakombi Inongo, a senior adviser to
Kabila, said Friday in an interview in his office. ``What we have
realized is that the rebels are just servants. Why would we want to
negotiate with servants? We'll negotiate with their masters.''
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, ethnic Tutsi from eastern Congo began an
uprising near the Rwandan border and in the region southwest of
Kinshasa. The Tutsi-led Rwandan government, with its Ugandan ally,
is believed to have encouraged and helped the rebels to try to
overthrow Kabila _ the same man both countries plucked from
obscurity less than two years ago to lead a successful coup against
Congo's longtime dictator, Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
   At first, many top aides in Kabila's government were Rwandan
Tutsi, but he dismissed them as his popularity plummeted. Residents
in Kinshasa and elsewhere in the country openly express their
hatred of the Tutsi and Rwandans.
</P>
<P>
   Sakombi said that the government is succeeding in
counter-attacks on the rebel forces in the region near the Atlantic
Ocean by using Angolan jets to bomb rebel troops. Reports that
Angola had also sent troops Friday into that area to help Kabila's
forces could not be confirmed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Thursday night, however, state television in Kinshasa showed
for the first time troops from Zimbabwe arriving at the airport in
Kinshasa. A European diplomat said Friday that soldiers from
Zimbabwe had been coming to Kinshasa for several days now, but that
so far they numbered only in the hundreds. The soldiers are
expected to reinforce government troops being posted west of
Kinshasa as well as to help repel a possible rebel attempt to take
over the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda have strongly denied any involvement in the
rebellion, but Friday they issued statements that appeared to belie
their claims. The Rwandan government condemned Zimbabwe and said it
now reserved the right to enter the Congolese conflict ``in
whatever manner it deems appropriate.'' Uganda issued an equally
strong, though more colorful, warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebels will stretch them out in the forests of Congo,''
said Capt. Shaban Bantariza, spokesman for the Ugandan army,
according to Reuters. He added that the fighters from Zimbabwe
``will go home without shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Uganda and Rwanda have emerged as strong allies of Washington.
And in post-Cold-War Africa, American foreign policy-makers have
held up their leaders, especially Uganda's president, Yoweri
Museveni, as new models for Africa, an attitude resented by many
other African nations.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Washington also backed Kabila. But Kabila's membership
in the new leaders' club was withdrawn quickly after he committed a
series of diplomatic mistakes and openly sneered at reports of
human rights abuses in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   In a December news conference that marked the beginning of the
end of Washington's support of Kabila, he vowed to arrest his
critics as Secretary of State Madeleine Albright stood by his side.
``Long live democracy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
