<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (th) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, Aug. 22. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story (under a four-column, one-line headline):
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-DAMAGE (Washington) _ Lede-all of days developments: The
Clinton Administration made measured claims of success for
Thursday's cruise-missile attacks in the Sudan and Afghanistan,
saying the raid on a mountain redoubt in Afghanistan would disrupt
training and, possibly, future attacks by terrorists sponsored by
Osama bin Laden. By Steven Lee Myers. (With 3-column agency photo.)
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Stories above the fold, under the photo:
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT (Jerusalem) _ In mosques, on street
corners, and from some government ministries, many Muslims voiced
fury Friday over the American missile strikes in Afghanistan and
Sudan and predicted that the assault would beget more violence. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 8:30 ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-RECAP (Washington) _ A recap of the process leading up to
the decision to attack: Clinton had cut short a political trip to
California to attend a military strategy meeting. For the next
eight days, he and the White House were consumed with planning on
two tracks for two events: his grand jury testimony and the
attacks. By James Bennet. (With a timeline graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
