<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACK BASHING PECULIARLY NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There will be a few intriguing sideshows in
the Patriots' fourth exhibition game Saturday night, but the No. 1
show is always Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the Land of Naysayers known as New England would anyone
pay much attention to a proven three-time All-Pro veteran
quarterback in preseason. In Dallas, Troy Aikman couldn't care less
about exhibition games. In Green Bay, Brett Favre laughs through
the game. In Miami, Dan Marino isn't yelling at his receivers and
nobody is saying he lacks fire. In Denver, fans don't want John
Elway to exert himself for fear the Broncos may not have him when
it counts.
</P>
<P>
   But in New England, fans fret, ``Geez, Bledsoe just doesn't look
that great.'' Or ``He'll never get to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no plan when I came in,'' said Bledsoe. ``I just try
and improve every year. I am making progress each year, and as long
as I continue to do that, I am accomplishing something. I would
have liked to have won a championship by this time in my career,
but I plan on doing that before I'm done.''
</P>
<P>
   For his sake, it would be better to do it sooner rather than
later. Like right now.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to hear about a new system. The Naysayers wanted
Bledsoe to immerse himself in Ernie Zampese's offense and know it
cold immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked how it's going, Bledsoe said, ``I don't know.
Some days it's 90 percent and some days 40 percent. Sometimes you
hit and sometimes you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't appease the Naysayers.
</P>
<P>
   What may be more alarming is that in Week 4 of the preseason,
Bledsoe still doesn't have his entire offense intact. No. 1 draft
pick Robert Edwards will likely be held out again against the
Redskins, even though he has practiced on a limited basis this
week, because the trainers don't believe his groin pull has healed
100 percent. Sedrick Shaw, who played well in Mexico City Monday
against the Cowboys, will start again and get the bulk of the
carries. Harold Shaw and Derrick Cullors are also expected to see
much more action.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is that Bledsoe has yet to connect with Terry
Glenn in three games. Last week Bledsoe had Glenn wide open for a
touchdown but overthrew the speedy receiver. This may be the game
in which the two need to connect right away and begin to form a
bond like the one Aikman and Michael irvin have had for many years
in the old Zampese offense in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't developed that to that extent with any of the guys
in our offense, but hopefully, we can be successful while we try to
get to that point,'' Bledsoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe and the first offense are expected to play about three
quarters, their most action to this point. He was in for 21 plays
in the first game and 29 in each of the last two. The Patriots
would like for the first unit to get about 35 plays Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   That should be plenty of time to determine how the Patriots'
offensive line is holding up against the Redskins' punishing
interior defense led by Dan Wilkinson (6 feet 5 inches, 313 pounds)
and Dana Stubblefield (6-2, 315). Stubblefield, who played for Pete
Carroll at San Francisco when Carroll was defensive coordinator,
was the NFL Defensive Player of the Year last season. He and
Wilkinson should provide center Dave Wohlabaugh and guards Max Lane
and Todd Rucci with quite a workout. If the Patriots are able to
run the ball up the middle, then you know those three are doing a
great job.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Rucci and right tackle Zefross Moss blocked well for
the run, allowing Sedrick Shaw to spring loose for a couple of long
gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're progressing with our running game,'' said
Carroll. ``The offensive line has had a better rhythm. They were in
a good mind-set last week, and I think they're understanding the
importance of what we're telling them. I've challenged them from
the start of the minicamps to do the job. In the last five years,
this has never been a team known for its running game, even when
Curtis Martin was here. And we're probably not going to be known
for it now, either, as long as we have Drew Bledsoe's arm. But we
need to have an effective running game where we can go to it when
we need it.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, one of the biggest sideshows will involve the
cornerback spot.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Canty is the probable starter on one side at the moment,
and it doesn't appear that first-round draft pick Tebucky Jones
(hamstring) will play for the second straight week. Jones is
definitely losing ground. The battle for the other corner spot is
being waged by Steve Lofton, Mark Tate, and Kato Serwanga. Lofton,
a veteran, may have the edge because of his experience. With a
young starter like Canty on the other side, experience is
important. But Carroll is taking a long, hard look at Serwanga, who
seemed to leapfrog ahead of Tate, and perhaps Lofton, last week.
</P>
<P>
   The coach also wants to see how the tight end situation pans
out. He's not opposed to keeping all four currently on his roster.
There's no doubt second-round pick Rod Rutledge will make it, and
Lovett Purnell is quite a threat as a receiver. But Carroll still
wants to see a more all-around game from Purnell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is giving us something in the passing game,'' said Carroll,
``and he continues to work on blocking, as all of them do. But he's
not a big power blocker that maybe Rod can become. But it's a nice
mix.''
</P>
<P>
   This game will mark the last chance for borderline players to
show something before Monday's cut, when the team will reduce its
squad to 61 (including Devin Wyman, its NFL Europe exemption) from
78. It'll be huge for punt returner Tony Gaiter, defensive lineman
Mike Jones, receivers Anthony Ladd and Dietrich Jells, rookie
center Jason Andersen, fullback/special-teams player Marrio Grier,
and linebackers Vernon Crawford and Bernard Russ.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
