A6674 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-MUNIS-$ADV23-     08-21 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MUNIS-$ADV23-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YIELDS ON MUNICIPAL BONDS MAKE A HAVEN LOOK BETTER THAN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of Muni vs. Treasury is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
(af) 
 By TIMOTHY MIDDLETON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Municipal bonds, often a haven from a turbulent stock market,
are more attractive than they have been for years because of a
narrower gap between their yields and those of Treasury securities.
</P>
<P>
   High-quality, long-term municipal bonds, which usually yield
nearly 20 percent less than Treasury bonds, are now yielding only
10 percent less. That may not sound very appealing, but after
taxes, that narrowing can become a big positive.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: While interest from Treasuries is subject to federal
income taxes, most muni interest is generally tax-exempt.
</P>
<P>
   That means that investors in the top federal tax bracket of 39.6
percent would need a return of more than 8 percent on a taxable
investment to have the same after-tax return that they could get on
a municipal bond yielding 5 percent, and the 30-year Treasury bond
is now yielding only 5.43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Municipal bonds are not a very exciting investment,'' said Joe
Mysak, editor of Grant's Municipal Bond Observer, a newsletter
published in New York. But considering the uncertainties of the
stock market, he added, ``maybe you want something where you know
you're going to get your money back.''
</P>
<P>
   The spread between yields on Treasury bonds and municipal bonds
is as narrow as it has been since Steve Forbes undercut the market
with a call for a flat income tax during his presidential campaign
in 1996. A flat tax would have negated the chief appeal of
municipal bonds, their tax-free coupons.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, the tightest spreads were seen a decade earlier,
when investors anticipated the tax cut that ultimately came when
the Tax Reform Act of 1986 was passed.
</P>
<P>
   The prices of municipal bonds, which move in the opposite
direction from their yields, have become so attractive to some
professional investors lately that even hedge funds have been
buying munis, although such funds do not pay taxes and, therefore,
enjoy no benefit from the bonds' tax status.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the municipal market gets to levels we're seeing at this
stage of the game, you start to get crossover buyers, and we've
seen that over the last 30 days,'' said Peter Allegrini, who runs
the municipal bond group at Prudential Investments in Newark. Such
buyers, including insurance companies and arbitragers, are seeking
capital gains when the bonds return to their normal relationship to
Treasuries. ``The relationship will get back in sync again,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spreads are tight because demand for municipal bonds is very
light while the supply is surging. Ever since interest rates spiked
in 1994, domestic investors have taken a dim view of bonds, sending
fixed-income securities into their steepest price decline in at
least 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors, a mainstay of the market for Treasury bonds,
shun municipal bonds because the tax exemption is worthless to
them.
</P>
<P>
   But the supply of munis is growing, because governments and
agencies are investing heavily again in infrastructure projects _
and issuing bonds to pay for them _ even as they refinance other
bonds that yield 6 percent and more with new debt priced closer to
5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think municipals are an extreme opportunity here,'' said
Reid Smith, manager of the Vanguard Municipal High Yield Portfolio
and Vanguard Municipal Insured Long Term Portfolio, pointing to
yields as high as 5.05 percent for a high-quality, 30-year issue.
For someone in the top federal tax bracket, the taxable equivalent
would be 8.36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is very handsome,'' Smith said, bigger than the yields on
many junk bonds but with much less risk.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that bond refinancings in the first half of this year
totaled $42 billion, or more than twice as much as in the first
half of 1997. Issuance of all municipal bonds was up 50 percent, to
$146 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that more munis are often issued in the second half
of a year, the total for 1998 could exceed the $293 billion in the
record year of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on a pace to exceed $300 billion in new issues,'' said
Tom Metzold, manager of several tax-free Eaton Vance funds.
</P>
<P>
   And investors have started to warm to munis, Metzold said.
Nearly $1 million a day is coming into his national and high-yield
municipal bond funds; this time last year, that much was flowing
out. ``It appears the more proactive investor is beginning to
realize there is tremendous value in the municipal bond market,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, bonds with the longest maturities and lowest credit
quality pay significantly higher yields than shorter, high-quality
debt. But the spreads are much narrower than usual in today's
tax-free market.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the riskiest investment-grade municipal bonds _
hospital bonds rated BBB _ yielded 90 to 95 basis points more than
high-quality bonds two years ago, but now pay just 40 to 45 basis
points more. (A basis point is a hundredth of a percentage point.)
</P>
<P>
   Bonds rated BB, the highest junk rating, have seen their usual
175-point premium reduced to 90 points. Meanwhile, 20-year and
30-year municipal bonds are yielding only about 50 basis points
more than those with a duration, or effective maturity, of 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're absolutely not being paid for low quality'' or
long-duration bonds, Smith said. He said the best buys were
high-quality, intermediate-term tax-free bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Unless an investor is wealthy, buying mutual fund shares may be
the best way to hold municipal bonds, Mysak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price of admission to the tax-free market is inordinately
high, compared to the stock market,'' he said. The usual minimum is
$5,000 to $10,000 a bond, and to diversify you need at least a
half-dozen of them. ``This is why so few people enjoy tax-free
income,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an important caveat for anyone investing in credit
markets through funds instead of direct ownership: bond owners who
keep their securities until maturity do not lose principal; fund
shareholders do not have this protection.
</P>
<P>
   If a fund sells securities at a gain, it will have to pass on a
capital gain to shareholders, and if it sells at a loss, it passes
on the loss. This surprises some shareholders who think of their
fund as tax exempt, but the exemption applies only to the yields.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the advantages of diversification and security
selection in a fund may well outweigh this disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the overall risks of investing in bonds are not trivial,
even if they are less than those of the equity market. Bond values
will sag if interest rates rise, and, in less turbulent times than
investors are facing today, returns can be expected to lag behind
those of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Breitner, president of Excomp Asset Management in
Manhattan, noted: ``Historically, over the long haul, equities do
much better than tax-free bonds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
