<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRIKE-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      08-21 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIKE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CLINTON, QUESTIONS NO MATTER WHAT THE MOTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was a week like no other in the Clinton presidency, perhaps
in any presidency. But President Clinton's unprecedented grand jury
testimony, his extraordinary national acknowledgement of a sexual
affair, and then his decision to strike against terrorist centers
halfway around the world all conspired to underscore the
president's weaknesses at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   At home, his credibility is under assault in the wake of
admissions that he misled the nation about his relationship with
the former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky, for seven
months.
</P>
<P>
   Abroad, the air strikes reinforce the difficulty facing the
world's only superpower, with its nuclear weapons and vast
conventional forces, as it struggles to deal with terrorist cells
and lone extremists determined to find America's vulnerable spots.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, this awkward, painful, unsettling and wrenching week
underlined a new handicap that besets Clinton: His motives will be
questioned, at least initially, no matter what he does, no matter
how he does it, no matter when he does it, in spheres domestic or
foreign.
</P>
<P>
   Most responsible American politicians and commentators agreed
that the president's antiterrorist offensive was justifiable and
prudent. Even some of his most habitual and vocal Republican
critics, such as the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott of
Mississippi, and the Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman,
Jesse Helms of North Carolina, swiftly lined up behind Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But constrained by an independent counsel investigation and
hobbled in the traditional lame-duck period of any two-term
presidency, Clinton no longer has the automatic benefit of the
doubt that Americans customarily grant their president.
</P>
<P>
   When Senator Dan Coats, an Indiana Republican who sits on the
Senate Armed Services Committee, said this week that there was ``a
dark cloud of doubt hanging over every further action,'' he was
referring specifically to the president's decision to launch air
strikes against the terrorist targets. Coats, who is no hothead,
might as easily _ and more accurately _ have been speaking about
any action the president takes at any time in the next few weeks
and months in any area of politics and diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to send cruise missiles flying encapsulated
Clinton's principal challenge in the wake of his grand jury
testimony and his admission. He acted to show credibility,
redeeming his vow that ``no matter how long it takes or where it
takes us, we will pursue terorists until the cases are solved and
justice is done.'' But in seeking to display his credibility, he
only underlined his credibility problem.
</P>
<P>
   Although he made good on his threat, an undercurrent of
suspicion ran cold and deep through the nation, at least in the
first hours after the attacks. The missile strikes came at the end
of the worst week Clinton has had as president, amid doubts about
his veracity, calls for his resignation, assessments of his power.
</P>
<P>
   There was, to be sure, an explanation for all of it _ for the
timing of the raids, for the targets, for the reassertion of
presidential and national force.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents often have to explain their actions in foreign and
military affairs, but seldom are called on to explain their
motives. In this case, the administration had to argue that
political life, in the form of a terrorist threat, had not come to
imitate theatrical art, in the form of the movie ``Wag the Dog''
or, in an Elizabethan context, the Shakespearean gambit of a leader
giddying the public's minds with foreign wars.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a time, as Shakespeare wrote, when ``oaths are
straws, men's faiths are wafer-cakes,'' in part because of the
president's own deceptions. For that reason, Clinton who misled the
nation, his staff, his political allies, his friends, and his
family about events in his own home, is reaping what he sowed.
</P>
<P>
   So now a president reared in a time of the ``credibility gap''
of Lyndon B. Johnson _ indeed, drawn into politics in that era _
faces a veracity gulch of his own. The suspicions that swirl around
Clinton now are palpable _ and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton now faces the sort of multi-front combat that ordinarily
challenges only wartime presidents. He must deal with the
likelihood of a damaging report from independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr; the possibility of impeachment hearings in the House;
uncertainties in foreign affairs, where terrorist threats have
created an eerie instability; and in the economy, where there are
mounting signs that the boom may be winding down.
</P>
<P>
   These challenges are particularly difficult in the struggle
against terrorism, which, unlike conventional national-security
threats, do not involve massing armies or traditional
nation-states. Terrorism is conducted by small groups, operating in
stealth, often without the overt assistance of nations. Massive
conventional acts of retaliation can be ineffective and only stoke
the passions of the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his wife have long argued that they are adept
in placing their concerns in ``little boxes,'' a notion the
president's mother taught them. This allows them to keep their
thoughts and their feelings about subjects as disparate as their
marriage, their emotions, their political ambitions and issues such
as US trade policy and welfare completely separate.
</P>
<P>
   But now the president is in a box simply because the items in
all the little boxes seem to demand urgent attention all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Starr and the grand jury are examining ambiguities or even
outright omissions and obfuscations in the president's testimony,
terrorists are testing his resolve, Clinton's political opponents
are testing his strength, and his actions and deceptions are
testing his marriage and his sense of trust with the people he
serves.
</P>
<P>
   In all these boxes the critical element is the same _ not
resiliency, of which the president the master; not toughness, of
which the president has a surfeit; and not intelligence, with which
the president is gifted; but credibility, which is the ultimate
power of the presidency and which is this president's greatest and
gravest challenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
