<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VINEYARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RESUMES ISLAND VACATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN AND ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ Just one day after President Clinton
announced retaliatory strikes against terrorists and departed
suddenly from Martha's Vineyard, the president returned Friday to
the island to resume his family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The president's plane touched down at Martha's Vinyard Regional
Airport just before 6:15 p.m. &UR;  &LR; The presidential motorcade, which
passed by a group of about 20 people waving handmade signs and
trying for a souvenir snapshot, went directly to the Oyster Pond
estate where the first family is staying.
</P>
<P>
   The president's quick return comes as the United States
continues to assess the damage done by its missile attacks on
suspected terrorist sites in Afghanistan and Sudan. Asked in
Washington whether the president would be accompanied by his
foreign policy team, National Security Adviser Samuel Berger
replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``The phones work very well Martha's Vineyard, including the
secure phones....If there's a need for someone else to go up there,
they will.'' He added, ``If, obviously, there were a need for the
president to come back down here, he would.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons are scheduled to stay on the island until August
30. Each summer, the Clinton's have made fewer and fewer forays to
island special events, though last year First Lady Hilary Rodham
Clinton attended a birthday party for Dorothy West, The last
surviving member of the 1920 Harlem Renaissance. Today, many
islanders will mark a memorial service for West, who lived in Oak
Bluffs and died this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton's last year also attended the annual agricultural
fair, which this year lasts through Sunday. But otherwise their
summer vacations have consisted mainly of private parties at the
homes of friends and liesurely days at private beaches or the golf
course.
</P>
<P>
   Because this is such an unusual time for the Clinton family,
White House aides do not want to speculate on how much socializing
the Clintons will do.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they were hard-pressed to tell the press what the first
lady gave her husband for a birthday gift. Last year, the press was
told that Mrs. Clinton had given her husband a piece of American
Indian artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night the Boston Pops will perform at the Tabernacle in
Oak Bluffs, and it seems islanders were more interested in seeing
Conductor Keith Lockhart than Bill Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
