   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-ATTACK (Washington) _ The first damage reports on the
American missile strikes at suspected terrorist sites in
Afghanistan and Sudan indicate moderate to heavy damage to the
targets. Senior U.S. officials indicate that more attacks aimed at
crippling terrorists are possible. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   MARIJUANA-TEENS (Washington) _ Marijuana use among adolescents
aged 12 to 17 is continuing to skyrocket because fewer youngsters
see the drug as dangerous, the Clinton administration warns in a
report. By NICOLE TSONG. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BAILOUT (Mexico City) _ A government attempt to use
public funds to pay for a $65 billion bank bailout has met with a
storm of controversy in the opposition-controlled Mexican Congress.
The political fight over the attempted bailout looms as perhaps the
defining crisis of President Ernesto Zedillo's administration. By
DUDLEY ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOLIC-SUCCESS (Paris) _ already filed _ Ingvar Kamprad, the
founder and owner of the innovative Ikea assemble-it-yourself
furniture chain in 30 countries, has just added a chapter to the
literature of rags-to-riches by admitting in a new biography that
during the years he built his commercial empire, he was usually in
an alcoholic daze. Maybe more execs should follow his example. By
BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Also filed in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEARST-ARGYLE (New York) _ Hearst-Argyle Television Inc.
announces it has agreed to acquire KCRA-TV in California's Central
Valley from Kelly Broadcasting Co., and a management
.MDSU/.MDNM/interest in KQCA-TV in a deal valued at $520 million.
By The Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' Sports)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-CUBS (Milwaukee) _ In what looms as one of the pivotal
series in the NL Central race this season, the Houston Astros will
head to Chicago this weekend for three games against the Chicago
Cubs. Houston will have new-found ace Randy Johnson on the mound
Saturday afternoon for the opener. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Milwaukee) _ The Houston Astros try to bounce back
from a frustrating loss Thursday as they wrap up a two-game series
against the Milwaukee Brewers. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
