   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DAMAGE (Washington) _ President Clinton has been a major
cash cow for the Democratic Party and its candidates. But with his
admission of a relationship with a former White House intern, will
Democratic candidates run away from him, as was the case in the
off-year election in '94? By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOTOLOGY-COLLECT (Houston) _ Every time the state of Texas
inaugurates a new scratch-off lottery game, Dr. Alfred Ricks goes
out and buys 200 or 300 tickets. But he's never scratched the paint
off one of them to see if he's won a prize. Ricks is a
``lotologist,'' one of a growing number of people who collect,
study and admire lottery tickets _ not for the prizes they promise,
but for their art and value as collectors' items. By RICHARD
STEWART. (Already filed; photo available on New York Times photo
service.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-DRUGS (Puerto Asis, Colombia) _ Despite millions of
dollars in U.S. aid for eradication of drug crops, Colombia is
harvesting record amounts of coca. The fumigation efforts are
forcing coca-growing peasants to move deeper into the jungle, often
to areas controlled by guerrillas. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GAZA (Gush Katif, Gaza Strip) _ A donkey cart driven by
Palestinian peasant women darts across a two-lane highway, then
resumes its slow journey along a dusty road cut through sand dunes.
Palestinians are barred from traveling this stretch of highway
under an agreement that gives Israel full control in Gush Katif.
The ban has come to symbolize what Palestinians despise about the
deal. ``The occupation interferes in our life,'' complains a
Palestinian farmer. By DEBORAH HORAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ No matter what happens to Bill
Clinton, the presidency will remain a powerful force. For more than
200 years, it has survived crisis after crisis. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday)
</P>
