<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-FUNDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTUAL FUND HOLDERS UNFAZED BY MARKET SWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Worries about a spate of global economic, political, and
currency crises that pushed world markets down Friday did not
appear to jolt mutual fund investors, who in a summer of swings
again resisted panic selling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; On a volatile day in which the Dow Jones industrial average
dipped 283 points, or nearly 3.3 percent, before trimming the loss
to close down 0.90 percent at 8533.65, individual fund shareholders
seemed unruffled. Major fund firms reported only slight increases
in the number of phone calls from concerned shareholders and said
stockbrokers were unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   Some fund firms said shareholders were shifting assets out of
equity funds into ultra-safe money market funds. Others said
investors simply put new cash into money market funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear to me individual fund shareholders aren't
driving this market,'' said John A. Rekenthaler, research director
at Morningstar Inc., the Chicago fund tracker, ``It's almost
certainly big institutional pulls and hedge funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Selling came as investors fretted about the United States' raids
Thursday on Sudan and Afghanistan and Moscow's escalating debt and
ruble crises. Wall Street shook on renewed fears about Asia's
effect on US corporate earnings, while across Europe, markets
slipped from 3 to nearly 6 percent on Russia fears. In Latin
America, markets shuddered at pressured emerging debt prices and
the prospects for Venezuela's battered currency.
</P>
<P>
   Because US mutual funds of all types hold 19 percent of all US
stocks, or $5.1 trillion in assets, industry watchers like to know
what happens at fund firms when markets wobble. Individual
investors _ as opposed to institutional investors, such as
corporations, insurers, and pension funds _ are a favored
barometer, since they account for two thirds of all fund holdings,
according to the Investment Company Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments of Boston, the nation's largest fund firm,
reported only a slight increase in phone calls from investors. Some
money had been transferred out of stock funds and into conservative
funds, but overall there were net positive flows into funds across
the complex. ``Investors generally favored more conservative
investments, like money market and bonds funds,'' said spokeswoman
Jessica S. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   At Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. Inc., the nation's largest discount
broker, phone traffic was below average, perhaps because investors
were on vacation. ``Maybe people are just getting used to these
swings,'' spokeswoman Tracy Gordon said. Phone calls from
individual investors were up 5-10 percent on usual levels at Putnam
Investments. Most investors asked about account balances, spokesman
Matthew Keenan said, and did not sell. T. Rowe Price said clients
pulled some money out of international funds but that net flows
into all other funds were positive.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dow down 8.6 percent since its July 17 high and again
near the 10 percent drop deemed a correction, analysts wonder if
fund investors think the party is over. Investors have poured cash
into mutual funds this decade, pushing the stock market up.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of some optimism, investors put $2.67 billion into
domestic stock funds in the week ended Aug. 19, AMG Data Services
of Arcata, Calif said. That is the most since the Dow's high a
month ago, but far below year-ago inflows, which topped $6.47
billion. Investors also continued to hedge bets by putting cash
into money market funds _ $7.78 billion last week, after $19.49
billion in the previous week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 1952EDT &QL; 
