<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLL-ART-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC'S PERCEPTION OF CLINTON, AS PRESIDENT, REMAINS POSITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic depicting results from recent polls is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also CLINTON-STARR) 
(js) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY with MICHAEL R. KAGAY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton continues to draw high ratings from the U.S.
public for his job performance, but his acknowledgment of a
relationship with a former White House intern has produced signs of
a darkening public view of both the president's moral character and
his overall personal image, the latest New York Times/CBS News poll
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton is now viewed more approvingly by the
U.S. public than her husband, according to the survey, which was
conducted on Wednesday and Thursday. Overwhelmingly, respondents
said they admired how Mrs. Clinton had stood by her husband since
he admitted his relationship with Monica Lewinsky _ even as most
people said they did not believe the first lady's claim that she
first learned of her husband's infidelity last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was conducted in the midst of what has surely been the
most tumultuous week of Clinton's political career, and suggested
once again America's profound ambivalence about this president.
</P>
<P>
   By varying measures, respondents said they were bothered that
Clinton had an an affair and lied about it, and were narrowly
inclined to believe he had encouraged Ms. Lewinsky to lie about it
at a grand jury. They also were inclined to believe he had sexually
harassed Paula Jones, his denials notwithstanding. And the number
of Americans who say that Clinton does not share their moral values
is as high now as it has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   Yet rising concerns about Clinton's conduct and character do not
seem to have tarnished the public view of his performance as
president. The percentage of Americans who applaud Clinton's
handling of foreign policy, 68 percent, and of the economy, 70
percent, is statistically as high as it has been at any point in
his presidency. His overall approval rating is at 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton does not appear to have been particularly
hurt among the group of Americans who have been among his strongest
supporters: women. The polls found that men and women generally
view Clinton and the scandal similarly, and what differences there
were tended to be small, with women slightly more supportive of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The Times/CBS News survey spanned Clinton's announcement that he
had ordered the bombing attacks in Afghanistan and Sudan, allowing
at least a preliminary measure of how events overseas might affect
Clinton's political standing during a difficult time. Americans
overwhelmingly approved of the attack, although they were less
certain on the question of whether it would discourage terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The military action did not appear to produce any immediate
changes in the nation's measure of Clinton, with perhaps one
exception: The number of respondents who said that Clinton could be
``trusted to keep his word as president'' increased, from 49
percent to 57 percent, from before to after the bombing. Overall,
the respondents said by a two-to-one margin that they believed
Clinton had acted out of genuine military concerns, rather than
executing a so-called ``Wag the Dog'' strategy to shift public
attention away from his troubles.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 944 adults nationwide has a margin of
sampling error of plus or minus three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Although the poll included a number of findings that should
cheer Clinton and his supporters as they assess his prospects of
emerging from his immediate difficulties, it nonetheless was
sprinkled with evidence of the enormity of the political task
Clinton faces in trying to salvage the final 28 months of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two out of three respondents said they agreed that the
scandal ``will have a serious impact on President Clinton's
administration'' for the next two years. One in two said that
Clinton, rather than his enemies, were to blame for the president's
predicament, a definite shift in the public's view of who was at
fault here. Nearly 60 percent say that Clinton does not share the
moral values of most Americans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
