<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KROFFT-PUPPETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIFTY YEARS OF SID AND MARTY GO ON THE BLOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; In the past half century, Sid and Marty Krofft
have created Elvis puppets and Saddam Hussein puppets, bug-eyed
Carol Channing puppets and hirsute Whoopi Goldberg puppets.
</P>
<P>
   But the brothers claim they owe their success mainly to a cadre
of adults-only puppets made for the Seattle World's Fair in the
1960s. ``Les Poupees de Paris,'' an elaborate fantasy of a risque
Paris nightclub that included a 36-piece puppet orchestra, became
an overnight sensation _ thanks to the fair's ribbon-cutting guest
of honor, the Rev. Billy Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Graham refused to go backstage because the `women'
didn't have bras on,'' Sid, 69, recalled recently. ``So, that night
he had an enormous rally, and he announced to 100,000 people,
`Don't go see this!' &UR;  &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   ``We credit him (Graham) with our careers,'' said Marty,
chuckling at the memory of the subsequent media fallout and the
overflow audiences it generated.
</P>
<P>
   The anecdote is vintage Sid and Marty Krofft _ wry, old-school
entertainers whose most enduring accomplishments probably are the
handful of quirky, sophisticated, semi-Freudian Saturday morning
children's TV shows they created in the 1970s: ``The Bugaloos,''
``Sigmund and the Sea Monsters,'' ``Land of the Lost'' and, of
course, ``H.R. Pufnstuf.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, several original costumes from those shows, along
with drawings, posters, memorabilia and about 20 of the Kroffts'
startlingly realistic life-size celebrity puppets will go on the
auction block at the Beverly Hilton Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most recognizable items will be the bright yellow
Pufnstuf costume, complete with the white cowboy boots and
orange-crested head that made the happy-go-lucky character look
like a country-western Komodo dragon.
</P>
<P>
   While the brothers say one of their primary purposes was ``to
share this stuff with our friends,'' they also view the auction as
marking the end of a phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't empty out our warehouse, but it is time to get on
with our lives,'' said Marty, 60.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Kroffts have been standing still. Since their
whimsical cartoon heyday ended, they've produced hit prime-time
variety shows such as ``Donny and Marie'' (1976-79), ``Barbara
Mandrell and the Mandrell Sisters'' (1980-82) and ``D.C. Follies''
(1987-89).
</P>
<P>
   They're also scoping out feature film versions of ``Pufnstuf,''
``Land of the Lost'' and the popular '60s sitcom ``Family Affair''
that ran on CBS from 1966 to 1971, to which the Kroffts own the
rights.
</P>
<P>
   They also served for many years as creative consultants to the
Six Flags theme parks. Recently, they set up shop again in the San
Fernando Valley, in Sherman Oaks _ a homecoming of sorts, given
that they started out in Sun Valley in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their careers, the brothers often have found ways to
bend TV's creative conventions. That wasn't easy in the 1960s, when
TV was far more conservative than today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that to network executives, our shows were so bizarre
that they left us alone,'' Marty said. ``It was only when we
started doing `The Donny and Marie Show' that they started getting
into our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sid, ``When we created our shows, we wanted Mom and Dad to
sit in front of the television set and have as good a time as their
kids. We did not put the child down. When parents see those shows
now, they get even more out of them than they did then.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Montreal-born brothers have come a long way since
they started out working in vaudeville and circuses, their old
show-biz instincts still serve them well. Often, they sound like a
comedy team, with Sid playing straight-man and Marty getting the
best of the one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Marty,'' Sid asks, ``didn't our dad always say, `If you
drop your pants on stage to get a laugh, that's not a laugh. That's
an easy laugh. That's not a proper laugh. So we never dropped our
pants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At least not on stage,'' Marty shoots back with perfect
timing.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of their patter holds true when it comes to naming
their all-time favorite character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pufnstuf,'' Sid said unhesitatingly. ``They always say the
first child is the most popular, and Pufnstuf is our first child.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite character,'' his brother retorted, ``is Sid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
