<HEADER>
A6689 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLL-ART-2NDT     08-21 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLL-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: most Americans.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And 40 percent of those questioned said they had an unfavorable
opinion of Clinton, which is close to the president's worst score
on that question. By contrast, 48 percent of those questioned said
they had a favorable rating. ( A 20-point drop in Clinton's
favorability rating reported by the Gallup Poll on Tuesday was
later discovered to have been largely caused by a change in the
wording of the question.)
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of a brief period earlier this year, Clinton
has never in the course of his public life broken the 50 percent
favorability rating in the Times/CBS News poll, even when Americans
were giving him strong ratings on his performance in office. The
only time Clinton's favorable rating rose above 50 percent was in
February _ at the height of the disclosures about Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I approve of what he has done up to this point, but I don't
find him trustworthy,'' said one respondent, Lisa Wolynski, 35, a
day-care business owner from Highland Ranch, Co., who was
re-interviewed after the poll, in a remark that neatly captured the
conflict many Americans are feeling about this president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like the guy I don't want my daughter to go out with,''
she said. ``At first I felt that who he sleeps with is his
business. But then as I began explaining this to my kids, it's
begun to bother me.'' She said the president was like ``a little
boy who got his hand caught in the cookie jar and I don't think he
was all that sorry for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most intriguing findings in the poll regarded Mrs.
Clinton. Nearly three-quarters of respondents said they thought
well of Mrs. Clinton for voicing support for her husband during
this crisis. Of those, 63 percent said they admired her for
standing by her husband, for being a good wife, and for keeping her
marriage together.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is now viewed favorably by 50 percent of
respondents, compared to 25 percent who view her unfavorably, which
matches her previous record-high standing of last February, when
she was at the forefront of defending Clinton on these charges.
``It's her stamina really,'' said Edward Sullivan, 52, an engineer
from Norwood, Mass. ``She's quite smart and durable. I suppose I
admire her for putting up with all this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wolynski said Mrs. Clinton was ``in a very difficult
situation and she's handling it very well. If I was her, I would
have given him the boot many years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the depth of support for Mrs. Clinton these days
suggests that the first lady might be helping her husband yet again
_ that her own popularity might be providing Clinton with something
of a lift.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the public rallied behind Mrs. Clinton, it seemed not
entirely believing of what she said: Two in three people said they
believed that she had in fact known of her husband's relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky before last weekend, a public statement by her
office not withstanding.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Clinton seemed to fare as well among women as
he did among men. For example, 73 percent of women, compared to 64
percent of men, said they wanted Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, to drop the investigation. There was, though, one subject
on which women took a sterner view of Clinton: Thirty percent said
they were bothered a lot by the very fact of Clinton's relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky, compared to 22 percent of men.
</P>
<P>
   There was some good news _ if only relatively _for Clinton in
the poll, as it relates specifically to the scandal. About half the
respondents said they were satisfied with the speech Clinton gave
to the nation on Monday night, though the approval of Clinton's
performance has been slipping throughout the week, amid a wave of
negative commentary.
</P>
<P>
   About half of those questioned said it was understandable that
Clinton had lied to the public about the nature of his relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky when asked about the allegations last January.
And about two out of three respondents think that the investigation
should be dropped. Nearly 40 percent of the respondents said the
issue is of ``very little importance'' to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Starr continues to suffer from his public exposure: only 19
percent view him favorably, compared to 43 percent who do not.
Starr might find some solace in Ms. Lewinsky's position: only five
percent of Americans view her favorably this week, compared to to
54 percent who view her unfavorably. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
