 (EDS: Restoring ATTACK-SUDAN as a separate story)    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; U.S. ATTACK ON TERRORIST SITES &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a three-page package of stories
covering the aftermath of attacks Thursday against suspected
terrorist sites in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The ledeall will move by  &UR; 9 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-DAMAGE (Washington) _ Ledeall: The Clinton administration
said Friday that Thursday's simultaneous cruise-missile strikes
obliterated a pharmaceutical factory in the Sudanese capital of
Khartoum and caused ``moderate to severe damage'' to the
mountainous redoubt in Afghanistan linked to terrorists supported
by Osama bin Laden. Other developments. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   These stories will move by  &UR; 8:00 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-PAKISTAN (Islamabad) _ The Pakistan government condemned
the American attack on alleged terrorist bases in neighboring
Afghanistan, calling it a violation of the norms of international
behavior and saying that it sets a ``dangerous precedent.'' The
government first lodged a protest that one of the missiles had gone
astray, landing in Pakistan and killing six people, but late Friday
withdrew the charge. By Raymond Bonner. (Story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-KENYA (Nairobi) _ FBI Director Freeh says his agents
still have a long way to go before putting together a conspiracy
case against Osama bin Laden that will hold up in an American
court. ``We are still in a fairly preliminary stage,'' Freeh told
reporters in Kenya before returning to Washington. By James C.
McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ Albanian agents continued to comb
Albania on Friday for Islamic terrorists after having apparently
thwarted a bomb plot against the U.S. Embassy here and breaking up
a cell of Moslem fundamentalists wanted in Egypt. By John Kifner.
(Story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ISLAM (Undated) _ President's Clinton's speech was an
unprecedented recognition of the Islamic faith, but also a
carefully nuanced attempt not to whip up hostilities between the
United States and believers. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   This stories will move by  &UR; 8:30 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-RECAP (Washington) _ A recap of the process leading up to
the decision to attack: Clinton had cut short a political trip to
California to attend a military strategy meeting. For the next
eight days, he and the White House were consumed with planning on
two tracks for two events: his grand jury testimony and the
attacks. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   These three reaction pieces will be packaged together in The New
York Times:
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT (Jerusalem) _ In mosques, on streetcorners,
and from some government ministries, many Muslims voiced fury
Friday over the American missile strikes in Afghanistan and Sudan
and predicted that the assault would beget more violence. The
condemnation came from around the Islamic world, and were issued by
clerics, officials, and ordinary citizens. For their part, most
Arab and Muslim governments remained silent or equivocal about
their views on the missile strikes. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT (Berlin) _ Reaction from Europe. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-RUSSIA-REACT (Moscow) _ Reaction from Russia. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   This story will move by  &UR; 9:00 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SUDAN (Khartoum, Sudan) _ The first group of reporters
has reached the target area where American missiles fell. A
description of what they find there. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-EVIDENCE (Washington) _ The administration has long
considered Osama bin Laden to be a top terrorist. A look at what
evidence they had in the past, and what they learned in recent
weeks that allowed the administration to finally agree to an
attack. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   With map graphics.
</P>
