u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRIKE-RESPONSE-BOS &LR;      08-21 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIKE-RESPONSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKS PUT US IN ISRAELI LEAGUE ON TERRORISM, SOME SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN AND ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American missile attacks in Afghanistan and Sudan follow the
Israeli model of a quick, tough response to terrorism _ a shift in
US strategy that experts praised Friday for finally putting
militants on notice that they'll pay a high price if they continue
their aggression.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they agreed that if Washington's new behavior
becomes ongoing policy, it carries a potentially huge cost of its
own: thrusting this country into a cycle of violence of a kind that
Israel has experienced for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something in these operations which very much
resembles what has been Israeli policy,'' said Shai Feldman, head
of the Jaffe Center for Strategic Studies at Tel Aviv University.
``And I think it is the result of a realization that you can't let
people around the world just keep blowing up American embassies and
killing Americans ... and the United States will not react and the
perpetrators will go unpunished.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman added a caution, however. ``The United States will have
to start living with the fact,'' he said, ``that such operations
will cause some unpleasant reactions.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it appeared Friday that a strike-counterstrike
escalation may already be in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of each other, Secretary of Defense William Cohen
said in Washington that more US assaults are being planned and may
be executed, and the editor of a London-based Arab newspaper
transmitted a threat from Osama bin Laden _ whose alleged terrorist
activities instigated Thursday's US bombings _ to retaliate with
additional attacks against American targets.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts with strong ties to the National Security Council said
they understood that the Defense Department has already plotted the
next American strikes. They said that the intent was not only to
damage terrorists' infrastructures before they could strike again,
but also to reverse an international perception of the United
States as a tough talker in areas from Bosnia to North Korea to
Iraq, but that's one unwilling to back its words with action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only the beginning. There are going to be more strikes,
because it's a message, not just about counterterrorism but about
American authority,'' said Bill Taylor, director of the
political-military program at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Washington. ``This week's hits were not a
whim. They were a signal: Look out, here we come.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli counter-terrorism specialists saw another similarity
between the American attacks and their own country's approach to
terrorism; that is, the underlying notion of both is to hit before
getting hit. US officials said the bombings in Afghanistan
essentially were conducted for self-defense reasons, to destroy the
terrorists' potential to carry out additional actions that they'd
already planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get information about active bases where plans are
being designed, you bomb, you don't wait for them to do it first,''
said Yigal Carmon, who was the adviser on terrorism to Prime
Ministers Yitzhak Shamir and Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli attacks on terrorists, some of which have never been
publicly acknowledged, have proved costly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, for example, an Israeli helicopter rocketed a car
carrying a leader of the radical group Hezbollah, Abbas Musawi,
killing him, his wife, and their infant child. A month later, a
bomb believed to have been planted by Hezbollah ripped through the
Israeli Embassy in Buenos Aires, killing 30 people.
</P>
<P>
   And in February 1996, Hamas bomb-maker Yehiya Ayyash was killed
by a booby-trapped cellular phone in the Gaza Strip. Militants
blamed Israel for his death, which was followed by four suicide
bombings that killed 58 people in the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course in some cases there is retaliation, but what is the
answer, to keep quiet and act like a lamb and don't fight the
terrorists and let them strengthen themselves and develop?'' asked
Carmon.
</P>
<P>
   The counterterrorism experts said the United States must take
into account in pursuing its current tactics that any attack is
likely to boost the targeted group's motivation to retaliate. But
they added that the attack also could cut the group's operational
abilities, something US officials say was done to bin Laden's
organizations this week.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some assaults can succeed in the long term. For
instance, after the leader of the militant Palestinian organization
Islamic Jihad was assassinated in Malta in 1995, presumably by
Israeli agents, the group never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Politically and militarily, the calculation for the United
States clearly is different than it is for Israel, which stands at
the center of a region rife with hostility and whose people solidly
support military responses to perceived or real threats.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding the skepticism of many Americans that President
Clinton acted this week to distract attention from his domestic
woes, the climate in this country may be shifting as a result of
the bombings in Oklahoma City and at the World Trade Center in New
York. There was little criticism, experts pointed out, of the
American attacks for having risked innocent lives or even for
not-so-covertly targeting bin Laden, even though US law forbids
deliberate assassinations.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some political analysts said that if this week's
attacks turn out to be a one-shot deal rather than a sustained
policy, Clinton risks looking like he really was recreating the
script of the movie ``Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would bet the store ... that this is the start of a new
phase in our foreign policy,'' said Richard Shultz, head of the
International Security Studies program at the Fletcher School of
Diplomacy. ``And it does have a positive lesson from Israeli, that
by being offensive ... you put the terrorists on the defensive, and
give those who direct terrorism against us currently don't have to
worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   But he and others added that there are downsides, in addition to
the possibility of creating a cycle of violence. Those include
questions about whether democracies like the United States should
engage in essentially undeclared wars, and whether such actions
will end terrorism or just fuel it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the embassy bombings in East Africa represent how the game
is going to be played, we're really up against it,'' said Shultz.
``There's nothing you can do defensively about things like that.
You just can't build enough walls. It's a scary thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
