<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-ISLAM-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DRAWS A DISTINCTION BETWEEN TERRORISTS AND MUSLIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-DAMAGE,
ATTACK-RECAP, ATTACK-RUSSIA-REACT, ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT,
ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT, ATTACK-KENYA, ATTACK-PAKISTAN, ATTACK-SUDAN.) 
(lh) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In explaining the decision to strike targets in Afghanistan and
Sudan on Thursday, the Clinton administration has been careful to
say that the United States was aiming at terrorist organizations
and their bases, not at a religion with adherents worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the world to understand that our actions today were not
aimed against Islam,'' President Clinton said Thursday, in remarks
that were unusual in a speech on national security for their
recognition of the broad importance of a religious faith, and for
declaring that faith to lie beyond any goals of U.S. foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton carefully distinguished between Muslims _
followers of what he called ``a great religion'' _ and radical
groups that hold to ``a horrible distortion of their religion to
justify the murder of innocents.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as if, after a Cold War that obscured forces like
religion, ethnicity and national culture within a global struggle
between democracy and communism, Clinton was saying that his
administration did not want to see the struggle revived as a
confrontation between the West and Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is remarkable to me,'' said John L. Esposito, director of
the Center for Muslim-Christian Understanding at the Georgetown
University School of Foreign Service, ``is that both the president
and the secretary of state went out of their way to say this is not
about religion.''
</P>
<P>
   That Clinton ``and his team were prepared to draw those
distinctions'' _ proclaiming disinterest toward Islam and a
determination to respond with force to violent groups that claim to
act in its name _ is ``important in terms of U.S. relations with so
many Muslim countries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Esposito added that the United States still risks
accusations of a double standard with regard to the Muslim world.
``Will a comparable action be taken against the Serbs in Kosovo?''
he asked, citing a region of Serbia where a largely Muslim
population has come under siege from a Serbian army battling
guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
   David Little, a senior fellow at the U.S. Institute of Peace in
Washington, said he also thought that the administration's remarks
on Islam were necessary. ``I think the president needed to go out
of his way to emphasize this isn't an anti-Islamic campaign, but
was against terrorism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Little added, ``I think there is now, among policy people, a
deep awareness that Islam-bashing is imprudent and incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, a senior official said the administration
has been trying to show that it does not confuse Islam with the
actions of radical groups like that of Osama bin Laden, the exiled
Saudi businessman whom the administration has accused of
masterminding the recent bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a growing disdain for the rhetoric these
terrorists use in trying to wrap their actions in some religious
cause,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``We wanted to make a point we draw a distinction and it's
important.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said Clinton's speech was written before two American Muslim
organizations phoned the White House to ask that any remarks by the
president distinguish between individual terrorists and the vast
majority of Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim Hooper, a spokesman for one of those organizations, the
Council on American-Islamic Relations in Washington, said, ``We're
pleased that he added the portions that this wasn't a war against
Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Religious faith should be left out of it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Atif Harden, executive director of the American Muslim Council,
in Washington, said that among U.S. Muslims, a group estimated at
anywhere between 2 million and 6 million people, many were relieved
by Clinton's warnings, after the bombing of the federal building in
Oklahoma City in 1995, that Americans should not ``rush to
judgment'' in deciding who was responsible. Until the police
announced that they had arrested a former soldier, Timothy McVeigh,
in the case, some media reports, particularly on television, gave
free reign to the suspicion that Middle Eastern radicals might be
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   But not all American Islamic groups viewed Clinton's speech
favorably. Aslam Abdullah, editor of The Minaret, a Los
Angeles-based magazine, said he considered the speech cynical and
wondered if the president was not in fact trying to call a negative
attention to Islam, despite his choice of words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
