<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCEAN-PEPSI-BOS &LR;      08-21 0216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-PEPSI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DENIES OCEAN SPRAY REQUEST FOR INJUNCTION AGAINST PEPSI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A federal court has denied a request by Ocean Spray
Cranberries Inc. for a preliminary injunction that would prevent
PepsiCo Inc. from distributing some Tropicana juice products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court has decided that it's more appropriate to deal with
this (issue) in a trial,'' an Ocean Spray spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray has a distribution agreement with Pepsi. But Pepsi
recently announced plans to acquire Ocean Spray rival Tropicana.
Presumably, once the acquisition was completed, Pepsi would
distribute single-serve Tropicana juices through the same channels
that it distributes single-serve Ocean Spray juices.
</P>
<P>
   Alleging that such a development would be a breach of its
contract, Ocean Spray, of Lakevill, Mass., filed suit against
Pepsi, of Purchase. N.Y., in US District Court in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi claims Ocean Spray's suit is without merit, and Friday a
spokesman for the world's No. 2 soft-drink company said, ``We are
obviously pleased with the judge's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray said it has appealed that decision and that it
expects a ruling on the appeal some time next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
