<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S GIFTS TO LEWINSKY EXCEED EARLIER DISCLOSURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-POLL) 
(js) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During their final White House meeting on Dec. 28,
President Clinton gave Monica Lewinsky more than a half-dozen
``going-away'' presents, including an Alaskan stone carving and a
decorative pin, said several lawyers familiar with Clinton's
grand-jury testimony on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The president met in the Oval Office for 20 minutes early that
December morning with Ms. Lewinsky, who was under subpoena to
testify in the Paula Corbin Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit against
Clinton, the lawyers said Friday. At the time, the former White
House intern was preparing to leave Washington for a job in New
York that Clinton's close friend, Vernon Jordan Jr., was helping
her try to secure.
</P>
<P>
   The gifts that Ms. Lewinsky received from Clinton _ the list was
even more extensive than previously disclosed _ had also been
subpoenaed by the Jones lawyers. They included such items as a
signed copy of a State of the Union address and a souvenir from
Radio City Music Hall, where Clinton celebrated his 50th birthday
at a fund-raising party in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the original interest in the gifts was aimed at
determining the degree of intimacy of their relationship. But on
Monday, both in his grand jury testimony and in his speech to the
nation, Clinton acknowledged an intimate relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, how Clinton dealt with the gifts remains part of
his most serious problem as Starr investigates whether he committed
perjury and obstructed justice in the Jones case. In questions
posed this week to both Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky before a grand
jury, prosecutors have tried to determine whether the president
sought to conceal the relationship from the Jones lawyers by
instructing Ms. Lewinsky to turn the gifts over to his secretary,
Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   Some presidential aides argued that Clinton's willingness to
give Ms. Lewinsky new gifts in December after the subpoena had been
issued demonstrates he was not trying to obstruct justice. He had
earlier given Ms. Lewinsky a book of poetry and a dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was so worried about the gifts and told her to get them,
why would he turn around and get her more gifts?'' said one adviser
to the president, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Another adviser said the president did not view the gifts to Ms.
Lewinsky as signifying anything serious because he routinely gives
keepsake items as mementos to many people. That adviser, who also
spoke on the condition of anonymity, said that none of the gifts
were especially valuable or personal.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors pursued a vigorous line of questioning on this
issue in sessions this week with both Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky,
said two lawyers with knowledge of the testimony. Prosecutors were
asking whether the president's gifts were part of an attempt to
keep Ms. Lewinsky quiet about the relationship. In December and
January, Jordan helped Ms. Lewinsky find a job in New York.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with Ms. Lewinsky's testimony said that she
told Clinton that the Jones subpoena had demanded the gifts he had
given her. They talked about it, and Clinton told her that she
could not turn over the gifts if they were not in her possession,
Ms. Lewinsky was said to have testified.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, Ms. Lewinsky received a phone call from Ms.
Currie, who said, ``I hear you have something for me,'' Ms.
Lewinsky told the grand jury, the lawyers said. And later that day,
they said Ms. Lewinsky testified, Ms. Currie went to her apartment
to retrieve the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   But the president in his testimony on Monday adamantly denied
telling Ms. Currie or anyone else to retrieve the gifts, said a
lawyer familiar with the testimony. In fact, the president said he
did not know that Ms. Lewinsky had given the gifts to Ms. Currie
until after Starr's inquiry became public on Jan. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their 18-month relationship, Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky
exchanged numerous gifts. He gave her a T-shirt, a book of poetry,
a brooch, a hat pin and a stuffed animal. She gave him six ties and
several books, including the novel Vox, by Nicholson Baker.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting in the Oval Office, Ms. Lewinsky also discussed
her plans to find a job in New York. They ended the meeting with a
kiss, Ms. Lewinsky has told friends.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prosecutors were preparing Friday to present further
testimony to the grand jury next week. They may call back Ms.
Currie and Linda Tripp, the Pentagon employee who surreptitiously
tape-recorded Ms. Lewinsky for 20 hours as she discussed her
relationship with the president. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
