<SLUG> BC-BRYCECANYON-HIKE-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTAH'S NATIONAL PARKS ARE NO LESS MARVELOUS THAN YELLOWSTONE, GRAND
CANYON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAYLN WILKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYCE CANYON, Utah _ Your hiking boots are barely out of the
box. Grizzled sideburns leak out from under a new cap. You are
obviously high on expectations and low on fitness. So what else
would you deserve and expect from a Utah park ranger?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir,'' she says with an impatient sigh, ``all our trails are
strenuous.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she agrees that on a sunny fall morning we should see
Bryce Canyon _ and see it afoot, not from a car safely parked on an
asphalt road. That means breaking in the new hiking boots on a
trail with switchbacks, trudging over landscape described by a
surveyor 125 years ago as ``a masterful work of giant hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Each member of our foursome is approaching or past the
nothing-more-strenuous-than-a-waltz age of 60. Yet we feel
reluctant to abandon high adventure, no matter the physical cost.
Not all that long ago, we navigated the deep blue of the eastern
Caribbean on a 45-foot sailboat without spilling a drop of rum or
inciting a mutiny. Another time, we went skiing and suffered but a
single knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Now we feel eager to challenge the natural masterworks of Utah _
Bryce Canyon, Zion National Park, Cedar Breaks and (listen to this,
Ms. Park Ranger) some 10,000-foot-high mountain bike trails.
</P>
<P>
   Bryce Canyon is where we choose to begin. We park our rented car
at its rim, arm-wrestle the straps of day packs into place, and,
taking deep breaths, start down. Geologists would say we are really
starting back, for in these lands marked by fire, wind and water,
it is possible to see rocks formed in the Jurassic period. We
aren't the only fossils in Bryce Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Moving as briskly as new boots and old legs allow, we realize we
might survive this hike when, 45 minutes into our trek, we pass a
family of three hikers. Their youngest member is sleeping soundly
in a baby carriage. Later, we pass a group of French tourists. The
eldest looks to be from the Jurassic period and is managing quite
well walking in what appear to be house slippers.
</P>
<P>
   Survival anxiety somewhat alleviated, our concern turns to
another topic. It could be possible, we wonder, that if you've seen
one canyon, you've seen them all. Since we are veteran visitors to
the Grand Canyon, what if Bryce Canyon seems like a minor-league
ditch in comparison?
</P>
<P>
   Again, we have no cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   Bryce Canyon isn't a ditch. It's a staggering 56-square-mile
configuration of rock steeples, walls, caves and, from the rims,
colorful views to what seems like forever and beyond. A century
ago, it was Ebenezer Bryce's ranch. To look into its wondrous maze
is to understand what old Ebenzer meant when he remarked, ``It's a
hell of a place to lose a cow.''
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly a place to grow cattle or wheat or Wal-Marts. No
wonder it became a national park.
</P>
<P>
   ZIONWARD: The next day we find an even easier trail in Zion
National Park, which is less than two hours' drive southeast of
Bryce Canyon. This trail, I'm almost embarrassed to admit, is paved
and as smooth as a drag strip. It is as scenic as the baby-stroller
pathway at Bryce; this trail leads past a lagoon and under a
waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   Zion is another example of what erosion can accomplish, given
enough time. To the Mormon pioneers, the park's towers and cliffs,
stained with the hues of the ages, resembled temples. Hence the
park's name. Once there, you feel like humming ``Rock of Ages.''
</P>
<P>
   The trail we take leads to the Narrows, where the Virgin River
enters a gorge that eventually shrinks to the size of an NFL
lineman. Here, the hiker's freeway ends and, to continue, you must
carry two things _ a permit from the park rangers and an acute
awareness of canyon meteorology.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
