<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE CALLS MISSILE ATTACKS SUCCESSFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration made measured claims of
success Friday for the cruise-missile attacks in the Sudan and
Afghanistan on Thursday, saying the attack on a mountain redoubt in
Afghanistan would disrupt training and, possibly, future attacks by
terrorists sponsored by Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Cloudy weather and haze obscured satellite photographs of what
the administration has described as a sprawling terrorist training
camp near Afghanistan's border with Pakistan, hampering efforts to
learn the extent of the damage done when cruise missiles fired from
four Navy warships and one submarine pummeled the area.
</P>
<P>
   But senior administration officials said preliminary
assessments, based in part on sources other than spy satellites,
indicated the missiles destroyed or damaged many of the buildings
spread throughout the remote complex about 90 miles south of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of bin Laden sought to play down the extent of the
damage and said the Saudi-born millionaire was still alive and
ready to retaliate. The widely varying claims of damage and
casualties from both sides were impossible to verify independently.
</P>
<P>
   But Secretary of Defense William Cohen said the strike was
``successful in the sense that we destroyed a number of
facilities'' at the camp, known as Zhawar Kili Al-Badr. At the
White House, the president's national security adviser, Samuel
Berger, said, ``The attacks have significantly disrupted the
capability to use these camps as terrorist training facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials, while circumspect in their choice of
words, left open the possibility that the United States was
prepared to strike at bin Laden's network again if necessary. ``We
have contingency plans that we are developing, and there may be
more in the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the administration opened a new front in its
fight against bin Laden, the Saudi exile whom the United States has
accused of sponsoring terrorist attacks, including the bombings of
the American Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania two weeks ago Friday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton signed an executive order that, effective
Friday, placed bin Laden on the Treasury Department's list of
terrorists and their sponsors, clearing the way for officials to
identify and seize any of bin Laden's financial assets in the
United States, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, in this context, money matters,'' Berger said
Friday, suggesting that the action could undercut bin Laden's
sponsorship of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was not immediately clear whether bin Laden, whose
fortune is estimated between $200 million and $300 million dollars,
has any assets here. It was also unclear why bin Laden had not been
placed on the department's list earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO diplomat said Friday that the administration had begun
asking allies in Europe to help in the effort to freeze bin Laden's
assets and those of terrorist groups associated with him.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Thursday's strikes nor this latest step appeared to have
tempered bin Laden, who has vowed to wage war against the United
States. A man claiming to be a spokesman for bin Laden told the
editor of an Arabic newspaper in London, al-Quds al-Arabi, that bin
Laden had survived the missile attack and was vowing to avenge it
with attacks on American targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle has not yet started,'' the editor, Abdel-Bari
Atwan, quoted the spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
