<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-KENYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENYANS HOLD SECOND SUSPECT IN EMBASSY BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Kenyan authorities are holding a second man in
connection with the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, the FBI
confirmed Friday. The FBI declined to comment on a local newspaper
report that witnesses had picked the suspect out in a line-up as
the man who threw a grenade at security guards outside the embassy
seconds before the bomb exploded.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, FBI agents on Thursday afternoon raided
the premises in Nairobi of Mercy Relief International, an Islamic
charity active in Kenya and Somalia. It was not clear whether the
charity has any link to Osama bin Laden, the Saudi-born millionaire
identified by the Clinton administration as the main suspect in the
Aug. 7 bombings that killed more than 250 people in Nairobi and in
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden controls dozens of Islamic businesses and charities
throughout North Africa and the Arab world, according to U.S.
intelligence officials.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents confiscated a fax machine, several business ledgers,
assorted documents, about $4,000 in cash and a handful of
videotapes, said an official of the charity, Abdullah Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed also said the director of the organization, Mohammed
Abdulla, who is Sudanese, had been missing for at least three
weeks. Another employee of the charity, Saban Hassan, was taken
into custody by the agents, employees said.
</P>
<P>
   The second suspect detained in the bombing was identified by The
Nation newspaper as Khalid Mohammed. No other details were given.
Quoting unnamed officials, the Nation said a security guard and a
civilian employee of the embassy had positively identified him as
the attacker who had thrown the grenade.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Horan, the special agent in charge of the FBI
investigation, acknowledged that the authorities had a second
suspect in custody, but declined to give details about the line-up
or the person's identity.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the main suspect, Mohammed Siddique Odeh, still
had not admitted to U.S. authorities that he took part in the Aug.
7 bombings. Neither has he implicated other people, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, agents also raided a house in Malindi, a coastal
town about 75 miles north of the port of Mombassa, and detained the
owner, identified as Hassan Omar Hassan.
</P>
<P>
   That has become commonplace here in recent days. More than 40
people, most of them of Middle Eastern ancestry, have been rounded
up and detained indefinitely by Kenyan police. The detainees
include some witnesses who appear to have little to do with the
bombing plot.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, police arrested Jamil Hassan Abdi, a Kenyan man of
Yemeni parentage, in the town of Mandera on Thursday. The only
reason given to reporters was that Abdi had stayed at the Hilltop
Hotel in Nairobi between Aug. 4 and Aug. 7, when investigators
believe the bombing conspirators were staying at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Director Louis Freeh said before leaving Nairobi for
Washington on Friday that the FBI had not detained anyone in
connection with the bombing. His statement rested on a narrow
technicality, however, since the Kenyans have arrested dozens of
suspects for the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators' move on Mercy Relief International raises
interesting questions about the direction of the inquiry. The
charity assists mostly Somali nationals and has offices in
Mogadishu and other Somali towns.
</P>
<P>
   In Somalia, bin Laden has channeled financial support to certain
militia leaders, including Hussein Aidid, the head of Hebr Gedr
militia that controls part of the Somali capital.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden has also funneled money to Al-Itihad, a radical
Islamic organization in Somalia that has been fighting the
Ethiopian government in the Ogaden region of that country.
</P>
<P>
   The main suspect, Odeh, who also goes by the last name Howaida,
is known to have lived for some time on Kenya's coast and,
according to local newspapers, married a Kenyan woman.
</P>
<P>
   On the coast, he would have been well-positioned to take
advantage of the shadowy world of gun-runners, drug dealers,
smugglers, bandits and mercenaries who cross and recross the
relatively lawless border between Somalia and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   In part because Somalia has lacked a central government since
1991, the border is porous and customs controls are almost
non-existence. Gun traders have an easy time moving weapons, Kenyan
police say. Explosives would have been easy to smuggle across the
border as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6707 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRYCECANYON-HIKE-2ndT     08-21 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRYCECANYON-HIKE-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
BRYCE CANYON, Utah: canyon meteorology. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We wade into the river, ankle-deep, and look up. The rock walls
leap 2,500 feet into the blue sky. Obviously, they have not and
will never yield to a flash flood. This is impressive, because a
note in the park hiking guide warns that when nature's dams burst,
water in the gorge can rise 100 feet in 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In her book ``Canyons of Color,'' Caroline Wilson recounts a
childhood memory of a flash flood that nearly swept away her
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were heading up North Walsh and all of a sudden my mother
leaned out the (car) window and said, `What's that noise? Sounds
like thunder.' My dad stuck his head out the window and muttered,
`Oh, my God.' He whipped the car over a shrub and onto the nearest
bank above the wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tumbled out of the Chevrolet and stared. Twenty yards
upstream, there came a froth of foam and flotsam the color of a
chocolate milkshake. A ton of muddy water was right behind that
foam. We were stuck there for the night. The flood picked up trees
and rocks and swept them downstream with great force. The roar was
like a busy freeway, and the ground shook beneath us all night.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder native guides refused to take early explorers and
surveyors into the Narrows. Today, the trail there is 16 miles long
and, properly equipped, hikers can obtain a permit to walk it all.
But we stopped where the native guides stopped, happy with just
enough rushing water to cool our toes.
</P>
<P>
   ROAMING ROOM: Zion can seem remote, since it is 2 1/2 hours
north of Las Vegas and 3 1/2 hours south of Salt Lake City. Yet it
has the same tourist pressures and problems as Yosemite or the
Grand Canyon. Plans are being made to banish automobiles at Zion in
two years and ferry visitors in and out of the park by shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   However you finally get there, once inside the Utah parks there
is room to roam _ 61 trail miles in Bryce and 55 in Zion. Despite
our experiences, rangers warn that most of these miles are beyond
the range of strollers and elderly French tourists.
</P>
<P>
   If the American masses _ as well as the French and even a
busload of visitors from China with whom we shared a trail in Bryce
_ still want to get out and walk, there is another option. Cedar
Breaks National Monument is a virtual secret, though it is just 35
miles east of Utah's Interstate 15.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Breaks, too, has fascinating trails. We try one that
meanders through a forest and around a lake. Another one _ and on
the same day, too! _ follows along a ridge that offers views over a
2,500-foot-deep canyon and across the Utah plains beyond. We walked
these paths in near-seclusion, except for the company of mountain
larks and occasional meetings with beavers.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles north of Cedar Breaks, I wander timidly into a
mountain bike rental shop at Brian Head. I figure the kid behind
the counter will card me _ ``Sorry, Mister, nobody over 21
admitted.'' Instead, he sends me and my fellow travelers along new
trails on 21-speed steeds, adding helpfully that the Log Cabin
Trail might be the easiest.
</P>
<P>
   This trail does take us through meadows, across creeks, past a
pioneer cabin and, two hours later, back to civilization. It was
all pretty country, but at an elevation of 10,000 feet it is lung-
and thigh-busting to bike around it. Fortunately, Brian Head is
sophisticated enough for hot tub plumbing (and two video rental
shops, but no gas stations), so we have recovered enough by
midafternoon to try a wheeled descent from the 11,000-foot-high
perch of the town itself.
</P>
<P>
   Flying down the switchbacks in high gear, I find myself agreeing
with the kid in the bike shop. A healthy tourist can handle these
trails at almost any age. But no, when we return the bikes he
doesn't offer a senior citizen discount.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of a week, we have also hiked the Mountain of
Mystery, Weeping Rock, the Queen's Throne and Angel Landing. We
have seen mule deer, antelope and elk. It's all nice country, and
we are able to think of it this way: In all of it, only the rocks
of ages are really old.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
