<HEADER>
A6709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-NOBEL-CHECK-6     08-21 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-NOBEL-CHECK-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROME, MY DEAR WATSON, WAS NOT BUILT IN A DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PAUL LEWIS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The mystery of the disappearing Nobel Peace
Prize is about to be solved, my dear Watson, almost 10 years after
that check for $339,000 first appeared to be missing.
</P>
<P>
   The check was last seen briefly at a ceremony in the hall of
Oslo University, in Norway, on the wet and chilly morning of Dec.
10, 1988, when Javier Perez de Cuellar, then the U.N.
secretary-general, stuffed it into his breast pocket after formally
accepting that year's Nobel Peace Prize on behalf of the 10,500
blue-helmeted peacekeeping soldiers his organization had sent to
keep order in trouble spots around the world.
</P>
<P>
   It was cashed and deposited. But then the money itself simply
seemed to vanish from view. For almost a decade, the United Nations
uttered not a word about what it had done, or planned to do, with
the money. That was decidedly odd for an organization perennially
strapped for cash.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally some suspected a fiendish purloining of funds. But the
truth is far more prosaic. Put 5,000 international civil servants
from 185 countries into a 38-story skyscraper and what do you get?
A recipe for indecision. The United Nations simply could not make
up its mind.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Marrack Goulding, the warden of St. Anthony's College at
Oxford University, who was in charge of U.N. peacekeeping when the
Nobel Prize was awarded, said the secretary-general wanted to use
the money for a high-profile essay competition that would encourage
young people to take an interest in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an idea I was sympathetic towards myself,'' Sir Marrack
said. But it fell victim to the curse of Babel, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   If the essays were to be written in English, Anglophones would
enjoy an unfair advantage. But if all languages were allowed, the
cost of translation would be prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   Commanders of peacekeeping forces naturally wanted the money
spent on a shiny new medal for their soldiers to wear. But once
again the United Nations' passion for evenhandedness thwarted
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly it would be unfair to give such a medal only to present
and future peacekeeping soldiers. But the United Nations doubted
that it could track down all those who had served under its flag in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the money was still unresolved when Boutros
Boutros-Ghali took over as secretary-general in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He favored using the check to build a wall-like monument to
those killed on peacekeeping duty, similar to the Vietnam War
Memorial in Washington. But who exactly would be commemorated?
Would peacekeepers killed in drunken-driving accidents be eligible,
or those who died of natural causes? And what about civilian staff
members, like secretaries, cooks and interpreters? Once again
indecision carried the day.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later when Kofi Annan became secretary-general, he
embarked on another quest for a good cause to spend the money on.
And now his officials believe they finally have one.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, the Security Council entered the picture by
adopting Resolution 1121, which created a Dag Hammarskjold Medal,
named after the organization's most famous secretary-general, to be
awarded to the families of the more than 1,500 people, civilian and
military, who have died on peacekeeping missions, no matter what
the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   So on Oct. 6, when the United Nations celebrates the 50th
anniversary of its first peacekeeping operation _ organized in 1948
to oversee the truce ending the first Arab-Israeli war _ the
secretary-general plans to announce a double initiative.
</P>
<P>
   First the United Nations will issue Dag Hammarskjold Medals to
the relatives of all slain peacekeepers, paid for out of its own
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Nobel Peace Prize check will be spent on a memorial at
the U.N. headquarters in New York commemorating those fallen
peacekeepers, as well as any who may die in the years ahead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since the Dag Hammarskjold Medal will go to civilians as well as
soldiers, the secretary-general has chosen an egg-shaped crystal
object designed by the New York firm of Louis Nelson Associates
that could be displayed, say, in a living room. It will carry the
dead peacekeeper's name, the U.N. logo and the words, in English
and French, ``In the Service of Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are interpreting the word `medal' loosely,'' said Shashi
Tharoor, the secretary-general's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, the first recipient will be the family of
Hammarskjold, who died in a mysterious plane crash in 1967 while
trying to restore peace in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   But the United Nations has not chosen a design for the
peacekeeping memorial, so it remains uncertain when, and indeed
whether, that Nobel Prize check is finally going to be spent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the good news is that the $339,000 that Perez de
Cuellar pocketed almost a decade ago has grown to about $700,000
today, thanks to the miracle of compound interest. Indecision, my
dear Watson, has its own rewards. Now where did I put my violin?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
