<HEADER>
A6713 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COD-FISHERY-BOS &LR;      08-21 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COD-FISHERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY BOATS DEPLETING MAINE COD FISHERY, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years after overfishing caused the collapse of the
once-vast cod population on Georges Bank, scientists say cod
fishermen have moved north and are on the verge of depleting
another important fishing ground, this time in the Gulf of Maine
that extends as far south as Cape Ann in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the National Marine Fisheries Service say their
finding that the cod population in the Gulf of Maine is near
collapse, the 13th New England fish population that is officially
``overfished,'' illustrates a central fact in the continuing
crisis: There are too many fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
   The federal officials say that Gulf of Maine cod, economically
vital to hundreds of small boat fishermen from Gloucester to
Eastport, Maine, have faced intense fishing pressure since 1994 as
former Georges Bank fishermen moved in and local fishermen
increased their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have too many boats,'' said National Marine Fisheries
Service Deputy Director Andrew Rosenberg, who estimates that
eventually the New England codfishing fleet will have to be cut
roughly in half. ``You can't continue to exert the kind of pressure
that we did in the past, even if the fisheries recover.''
</P>
<P>
   The disappearing Gulf of Maine cod are part of a growing string
of troubled fisheries in New England from lobster to monkfish to
scallops. Only eight of the region's 33 commercial fish stocks are
harvested within safe limits, according to a National Marine
Fisheries Service report.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, overfishing continues as fishermen try to offset declining
catches by working harder to satisfy a consumer demand for seafood
that has not declined with the fishing grounds. For instance,
steady demand for dwindling cod has pushed up prices, giving
fishermen incentive to catch more despite warnings that the
population is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite waves of fishing restrictions from the New England
Fishery Management Council, relatively few fishermen are getting
out of the business. Only 39 fishermen gave up permits to catch cod
and other groundfish last year out of 1,810 permit holders, despite
a federal effort to buy fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
   But fishermen say they already sacrifice heavily in the name of
conservation. The fishermen's assistance center in Gloucester alone
has retrained and found jobs for 250 fishing industry employees and
their families since 1995, and those who remain face a bewildering
array of limits on their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, fishermen are fighting the National Marine
Fisheries Service call for a clampdown on cod fishing in the Gulf
of Maine, calling it unfair and unnecessary. They say a recently
adopted 400-pound limit on daily cod catch should be enough, while
allowing some fishermen to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are saying allow some of us to survive, at least the roots,
so that later the tree can grow. They are ... totally getting rid
of the roots,'' said Angela Sanfilippo of the Gloucester
Fishermen's Wives. She said closure of the cod fishery would force
at least some of the 214 small boat fishermen on Cape Ann to find
other work.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of the fishing crisis in New England, a microcosm of
a global dilemma, is an industry that has become too good at what
it does. Sophisticated electronic equipment allows fishermen to
precisely track their quarry, while 200-foot-wide drag nets
virtually vacuum the fish out of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the US government encouraged the industry to
grow after the 1976 Magnuson Act gave the United States exclusive
control over fishing within 200 miles of the coast, subsidizing an
explosion of the fleet that finally exhausted the famed Georges
Bank fishing ground in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   National Marine Fisheries Service biologists say the rapid
decline of cod in the Gulf of Maine mirrors the Georges Bank
collapse. Fishermen catch nearly half of all the cod in the gulf
each year, far outstripping nature's ability to replace them, just
as they did on Georges Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Federal biologists' advice for the Gulf of Maine is just as
stark as it was for Georges Bank, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fishing rate ought to be cut to as close to zero as
possible,'' said National Marine Fisheries Service biologist Steve
Murawski, whose recommendation will be taken up at an August 27
emergency meeting of the fishery management council.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Georges Bank, however, much of the cod catch in the Gulf
of Maine is made by small boats that can't make the 50 miles-plus
trip out to Georges Bank, and many of those small boat owners blame
regulators for the gulf's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They closed down Georges Bank and there's a huge amount of
horsepower which was diverted into the Gulf of Maine,'' said Dean
Tsonas, a fisherman in Hampton, N.H. ``It is totally unconscionable
that they allowed this to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Doug Hopkins, an attorney with the Environmental Defense
Fund and a member of the New England Fishery Management Council,
says the near-shore can't blame the problem only on interlopers
from Georges Bank. He said it is ``crystal clear'' that the small
boats were landing too many fish also.
</P>
<P>
   ``As painful as it is, and as much as there will be an impact
(on fishermen), there aren't many other options'' to closing the
Gulf of Maine to codfishing, said Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   To date, restrictions on fishing have had some positive effects,
especially in closed areas of Georges Bank where cod populations
have begun to rebound. But fishermen have also undercut the
restrictions by fishing harder and using new technologies that
increase their catch.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the oversized fishing fleet keeps constant pressure on
regulators to relax rules or re-open fishing grounds at the first
sign of improvement. On Georges Bank, for example, the National
Marine Fisheries Service is studying whether to reopen parts of
Georges Bank to scallopers amid signs that some scallopers were
dredging there illegally anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Murawski of the National Marine Fisheries Service says his
agency won't allow scalloping unless it's proven the scallopers
won't also catch cod or other groundfish. But some observers view
the scallop study as a cave-in to industry pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a vocal constituency contacting Congress saying
regulations are hurting us and you need to get the council to go
slower,'' said Hopkins of the council, noting that even Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci had recently written to council members
urging them to ``take it easy on the scallopers.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate solution for the scallopers as well as other
fisheries is less fishing, said Rosenberg of the National Marine
Fisheries Service. He supports a scallop fleet of 100 to 120 boats
instead of the current 211, and he believes the number of permits
for groundfishing should be halved as well. But he says such goals
are difficult to reach quickly and fairly.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government tried to cut the number of boats in 1995
and 1996, buying 69 highly productive boats under a $25 million
buy-out program. WHile the buy-out eliminated about 8 percent of
the groundfishing fleet, it did not address the hundreds of
fishermen who aren't fishing for cod now, but easily could return
if fishing improves.
</P>
<P>
   Until this ``latent'' fishing power is eliminated, Rosenberg
said, it will be difficult to permanently protect the cod.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Anderson, a New Hampshire fisherman on the New England
Fishery Management Council, believes the fisheries service is too
gloomy, and that his industry will recover. But, if government is
determined to reduce the fleet, he has some advice: Do it openly,
and pay fishermen for their loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's an unstated mandate that you're going to reduce this
down to a few people who can be managed quite easily, then please
come out and say it ... then people can plan appropriately,'' said
Anderson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
