<HEADER>
A6714 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-T     08-21 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFF GORDON A CHEATIN' DAWG? NAW, HE'S JUST GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He cheats.
</P>
<P>
   That's the latest rumor making the rounds among the huge segment
of NASCAR's fandom that loves to loath the sport's poster boy, Jeff
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, that's it. That's why Wonder Boy has won a record-tying
four consecutive races, and why he'll probably break the record
with a victory tonight in Bristol, Tenn. And that's why he's on
track to become just the fifth driver to win three championships.
</P>
<P>
   He's a no-good, cheatin' dawg.
</P>
<P>
   And get this. Those NASCAR people not only know about it,
they're in on it. You ever notice how he gets a yellow flag just
when he needs one?
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, ridiculous. Almost as ridiculous as that
earlier rumor that NASCAR officials let Dale Earnhardt cheat to win
the Daytona 500 this year.
</P>
<P>
   That one, at least, sort of made sense. Why not reward ol' Dale
for everything he has done for stock-car racing? Kind of like a
lifetime achievement award.
</P>
<P>
   But Gordon? Preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   Why would NASCAR, with it's well-documented penchant for
legislating parity, want to help a driver? Especially a young
whipper-snapper like Gordon, who really isn't ``one of us'' anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rumor that the legions of Gordon haters _ the bitter
souls who boo his every move and cheer when he wrecks _ desperately
want to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry guys and gals, it just ain't so.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, it's hard to understand the depth of feeling that
Gordon evokes.
</P>
<P>
   He's young, handsome, well-spoken. He's talented. He's humble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how I got here,'' he said last week after
winning in Michigan, his fourth consecutive victory. ``I have to
pinch myself. I don't believe it. Mark Martin deserved this win. He
should be the guy who's here.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a man of faith, and while there might be rumors about
cheating, there's not a hint out there of drinking, drugs or
carousing.
</P>
<P>
   He's everything, in short, America should be looking for in a
hero.
</P>
<P>
   He should be cheered. Instead, he's jeered.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to think it's because he's the antithesis of
the stereotypical good old boy stock-car racer and fan. He was born
on the West Coast and raised in the Midwest, far from the sport's
deep-fried Southern roots.
</P>
<P>
   It's somehow unsettling to think it's because he's too good,
he's too talented, his smile too bright, his wife too pretty, his
checks too big. If that's the case, it doesn't speak very highly of
our society.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because people are simply tired of seeing Gordon win
all the time. If so, that would make him a lot like Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Gordon is a lot like Jordan in another way.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, second in the points race to Gordon last year and
third this year, recently invoked Jordan's name in discussing his
rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't stop Michael Jordan from scoring points or setting
records, can you?'' Jarrett said. ``Well, going up against Jeff is
sort of like the same thing. You know it's going to happen. You
just hope you can stop him from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
   The comparison is a good one.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Gordon so good? Why is Gordon, at the still tender age of
27, going after a record tonight? Not because he cheats, but
because he's like Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jordon, he has been blessed with an immense amount of
talent. Even someone like Rusty Wallace, who isn't exactly Gordon's
biggest fan, admits the boy racer already is one of NASCAR's
all-time top 10.
</P>
<P>
   But like Jordan, that isn't enough. Jordan wins championships
because of an outstanding supporting cast. Gordon wins races and
championships because his crew chief, Ray Evernham, is the best in
the business, because he has an outstanding pit crew and because he
is bankrolled by the deep pockets of Hendrick Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon goes for a modern-era record tonight when he lines up for
the Goody's Headache Powder 500 at Bristol Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Being humble, he doesn't expect to get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't thinking a lot about four in a row, so it's hard
for us to think about five in a row,'' he said. ``We've got to look
at the big picture and the championship, so we'd be happy with a
top-five finish.''
</P>
<P>
   There's so many variables at Bristol it'll be hard to do. Even a
driver having a great ride easily can get caught up in a wreck on
the .533-mile, high-banked oval and have his race ruined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can have a bad race at Bristol,'' said Mark Martin,
second in the points. ``It takes more than just a good car to win
there. You have to have luck on your side.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wouldn't be wise to bet against Gordon. Not because he
cheats, and not because of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Because he's that good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
