<SLUG> BC-MOB-FLEMMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOBSTER FELT BETRAYED BY FBI AFTER HIS ARREST IN 1995 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sitting in his jail cell, week after week, Stephen
Flemmi felt abandoned, double-crossed by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   For decades the bargain had held. He and his criminal partner
James ``Whitey'' Bulger fed the bureau information on their rivals
in the Mafia. In turn, the FBI tipped them off to investigations,
warned them away from fellow criminals whose phones were tapped,
bought them Christmas presents.
</P>
<P>
   They were protected and prized. Until they were prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest in January 1995 on extortion and racketeering
charges, Flemmi waited for the FBI to say the words that would free
him, to reveal the Faustian bargain it had made in its zeal to
dismantle the Mob.
</P>
<P>
   But the words never came, only silent betrayal from the agents
he'd funneled information to for 30 years, particularly John
Connolly, the one who'd courted him and Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be up here testifying on our behalf,'' Flemmi
testified Friday, trying to convince a federal judge to drop the
charges because the FBI had promised not to prosecute him or
Bulger. ``I feel we've been adandoned.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was first arrested at gunpoint outside a downtown
restaurant, Flemmi expected that Bulger would straighten things
out. ``I believed that Jim Bulger would contact the people who
would be able to help us...I expected someone to offer assistance,
namely John Connolly.''
</P>
<P>
   The help never came. After being denied bail twice, Flemmi said
he asked Bulger associate Kevin Weeks to get in touch with
Connolly. ``I waited in jail for 27 months for John Connolly to
intervene,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly has refused to testify about his dealings with Bulger
and Flemmi without a grant of immunity. But he has publicly
criticized the FBI for going back on its word, saying Bulger and
Flemmi had been given permission to continue their gambling and
loansharking operations while acting as informants.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi insisted that his silence on the deal he claimed to have
with the FBI was caused by the bureau's refusal to do the right
thing. He said he was also concerned that exposing his and Bulger's
longtime roles as informants would endanger Bulger, who fled before
the 1995 indictments and remains a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   But the government sees its differently. Under cross-examination
Friday in US District Court, Assistant US Attorney Fred M. Wyshak
Jr. suggested that Flemmi concocted the story about having been
granted immunity from the FBI as a last-minute defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inexplicable why he sat in jail for 2 1/2 years without
saying anything,'' Wyshak said, addressing US District Court Judge
Mark L. Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Wyshak also cast doubt on Flemmi's claim that he and Bulger were
tipped off to the indictments by former FBI supervisor John Morris
a week before they were handed down. Given that Bulger believed
Morris had confirmed Bulger's role as an FBI informant to the
Boston Globe Spotlight team in the fall of 1988 -- angering Bulger
and perhaps endangering his life -- Wyshak suggested it was
implausible that Morris would tip off Bulger more than six years
later, when he no longer even worked for the Boston FBI office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can prove that that's absolutely not true,'' Wyshak
said.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who testified earlier this spring under a grant of
immunity, denied alerting Bulger and Flemmi to the 1995 indictment
and recounted a threatening phone call he got from Bulger after
he'd been on the run for nine months. During the call, a ``menacing
and vengeful'' Bulger accused Morris of making him a ``marked man''
for outing him as an informant but said nothing about the FBI
reneging on its immunity deal, Morris testified.
</P>
<P>
   Wyshak tried to show that Flemmi was closely tracking the grand
jury that would indict him and that he fled to Montreal in the fall
of 1994 in anticipation of charges being brought.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is holding pretrial hearings to decide whether Flemmi's
immunity claim is valid and if so whether charges against him
should be dropped. Since the 1995 indictments allege a decades-long
criminal conspiracy between Bulger and Flemmi's Winter Hill Gang
and the Mafia, dismissing the charges against Flemmi would imperil
the case against his co-defendants as well, including New England
Mafia boss Francis P. ``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme, mob soldier
Robert DeLuca and Winter Hill gangster John Martorano.
</P>
<P>
   During Wyshak's questioning, Flemmi invoked his Fifth Amendment
right against self-incrimination more than two dozen times,
refusing to answer questions about discussions he and Bulger may
have had about fleeing in the months before they were indicted.
Flemmi was also vague about the time he spent in Montreal and the
landlord who rented him an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   He also refused to answer questions about Bulger leaving for the
West Coast with his girlfriend in September 1994 and refused to say
if he'd seen Bulger since then or spoken to him.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi has testified that he remained in contact with Connolly
even after Connolly retired from the bureau in December 1990,
mainly providing information on the activities of Salemme. Flemmi
said he and Connolly often discussed the ongoing grand jury
investigation targeting him and Bulger, but he said he never
considered asking Connolly to intercede with the US Attorney's
office to block his prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a position to keep us from being prosecuted, that's
why I wasn't too concerned,'' Flemmi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
