<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS BACK U.S. ACTION AGAINST TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-DAMAGE,
ATTACK-RECAP, ATTACK-ISLAM, ATTACK-RUSSIA-REACT,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-KENYA, ATTACK-PAKISTAN,
ATTACK-SUDAN.) 
(lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS  
 &HT;     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ European leaders on Friday generally supported
President Clinton's bombing raids in Sudan and Afghanistan, and
even those who appeared uneasy defended the right of a country to
counterattack terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany, a friend of Clinton and one
of the United States' most consistent allies, was among the
president's effusive supporters on Friday. The German government
``supports all measures to combat terrorism,'' he said, adding that
governments must be united on such issues.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from most other Western European nations, among them
Britain, Spain and Austria, characterized the U.S. attacks as a
fully justifiable defense and appeared ready to believe the Clinton
administration's assertions that the strikes were a response to
overwhelming evidence it had amassed of planned terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Even the French government, which has quarreled repeatedly with
the United States over the threat of military action against Iraq,
seemed ready to support the White House. Though the French Foreign
Ministry issued a somewhat chilly statement Friday morning that it
had ``taken note'' of the missile attack, Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin was more explicitly supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever terrorism is launched from, we must respond with a
decisive and firm answer,'' Jospin said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Blair, the British prime minister, praised the United
States. ``I hope that everyone will understand that the U.S.A. must
have the right to defend itself against terrorism,'' he said while
on vacation Friday in the south of France.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Schuessel, foreign minister of Austria and a leading
foreign-policy adviser to the European Union, said, ``I presume
that the United States can justify its attacks against the targets
in Afghanistan and Sudan with incontrovertible evidence.'' He
called for international collaboration against terrorism in order
to prevent a ``spiral of violence and counterviolence.''
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear Friday night whether the United States had
given its European allies any notice of its plans. Kohl said he had
been informed about the action in a timely fashion, and few
political leaders complained about being left out.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's opponents in the Social Democratic Party were also
supportive of the United States. Rudolf Scharping, the head of the
party in Parliament, said the attack was justified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
