<HEADER>
A6718 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRIKE-RETALIATE-BOS &LR;      08-21 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIKE-RETALIATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY BEEFED UP AT US-LINKED INSTALLATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fears that terrorists could retaliate against the
United States by striking on American soil or targeting Americans
abroad have prompted heightened security across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   While airport workers searched through suspicious bags, and US
corporations with foreign operations took added measures to protect
employees, the federal government adopted security precautions
taken during the Persian Gulf War. The moves follows Thursday's
missile strikes of terrorist operations in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Tightened security was visible in the nation's capital: Metal
barriers were up at entrances to the Justice Department, police
cars ringed entrances to the State Department, and National Park
Police fanned out across Washington to beef up protection at
tourist attractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the new face of terrorism,'' said Harvey Kushner, a
specialist on domestic terrorism. ``This ratchets up the risk to
both Americans in the US and abroad, whether they are tourists,
businessmen or diplomats. This is a big-time threat, and it isn't
going to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration banned travel by US citizens
or individuals holding US-issued tickets to _ or over _ Afghanistan
and Sudan, but did not recommend additional measures to aviation
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has closed several embassies around the
world, evacuated nonemergency personnel in others, and strengthened
its most recent travel advisory by issuing a ``worldwide caution''
to US nationals working or vacationing overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The warning tells travelers to exercise ``much greater caution''
than normal and to keep in touch with the nearest embassy or
consulate for up-to-date information on security. It does not
advise people to cancel or cut short their trips.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the FBI issued a general security warning to all law
enforcement agencies, and the Justice Department warned its 117,000
employees to take precautions against possible terrorist
retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a position to tell other agencies what to do to
enhance their security, but we told them they should have a
heightened awareness,'' said Paul Bresson, an FBI spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also moved from ``Threatcom Normal'' to ``Threatcon
Alpha,'' explained as ``a general threat of possible terrorist
activity against installations, building locations and/or
personnel, the nature of which are unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   A CNN poll showed only 10 percent of Americans fear a terrorist
attack. Specialists, however, warned against complacency, pointing
out retaliatory action against US installations or individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of Pan Am 103 was payback for US attacks on Libya,
according to Kushner. And the more recent killing of two Americans
working in Pakistan was in response to the conviction of a Muslim
fundamentalist for his role in killing CIA workers outside the
agency's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terrorist network built in Afghanistan exists here in the
US,'' Kushner said. ``Most of the people involved in the World
Trade Center bombing had links to the terror network we're trying
to take out, but they are here. We're fighting a loosely knit
network of fanatical radical terrorists who are nameless and
faceless.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents contacted Friday did not see a significant drop or
change in travel plans, and airlines did not comment on whether
ticketing has been affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to take this in stride,'' said Evvy Harris, a
travel agent at Austin Travel in New York specializing in
international travel. ``Frankly, people here are more afraid of
going in the subway tunnels.''
</P>
<P>
   There is usually a lag time of a few weeks after an incident
before bookings trail off, said Richard D'Ambrosio, public affairs
director for American Express travel services.
</P>
<P>
   But corporations are concerned about the safety of their
personnel. William J. Daly, a former FBI counterintelligence agent
and managing director at Kroll Associates, an international
security firm based in New York, said he had been receiving calls
from corporations with multinational operations all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``At any one time, there are several million Americans outside
the US on business, and they have a security exposure. Businesses
literally fly American flags and represent our way of life,'' Daly
said. ``But people are still naive about protecting themselves
against terrorist attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Businesses need a highly detailed plan to evacuate employees and
respond to bomb threats, as well as heightened awareness of their
physical safety in their work area, said Leonard C. Cross, a former
FBI counterterrorism specialist who investigated the World Trade
bombing as well as other Middle East bombings. Garages and any
entrance point should be monitored, and individuals should keep a
low profile and be aware of being watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``US businesses with large buildings in manufacturing areas or
with prominent signs advertising their company are very soft
targets, and many don't have adequate security,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rest assured, we take adequate measures to protect our
personnel abroad,'' said Dave Shea, spokesman for Raytheon Co., a
defense contractor. Shea refused to explain measures taken for
security reasons. So did Matt Miller of Gillette Co., although he
said ``security was always a concern'' and that the company was
``monitoring the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Airports in Boston, Los Angeles and San Fransisco increased
security by searching any suspicious bag and towing unidentified
cars, while cities such as New York had police encircling some
government buildings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
