<HEADLINE>
MORE U.S. STRIKES POSSIBLE, COHEN SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen raised the
possibility of more U.S. attacks on suspected terrorist facilities
Friday as the administration began assessing the damage done a day
earlier in strikes against targets in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a briefing with lawmakers on Capitol Hill, Cohen
told reporters that ``contingency plans'' for more military
assaults on Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden's network and other
terrorist cells are being developed and ``there may be more in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The warning came as an associate of bin Laden _ whose terrorist
training camps in Afghanistan were struck by dozens of U.S.
Tomahawk cruise missiles _ contacted a London-based Arab-language
newspaper to threaten revenge attacks on American interests and
citizens. In a statement to the paper, the bin Laden representative
said: ``The battle has not yet started. The response will be with
action and not words.''
</P>
<P>
   In his comments Thursday on the missile strikes, Clinton blamed
the Aug. 7 embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania on bin Laden's
network and described him as the ``pre-eminent'' merchant of
terrorism in the world today.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he ordered the missile attacks because of
intelligence information indicating that more terrorist acts on
U.S. embassies and other interests were imminent. He also suggested
that the strikes were aimed at killing terrorist leaders who were
supposed to be meeting at the bin Laden camps Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen and National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said they
could not confirm whether the meeting had actually taken place, or
how many people may have been killed. Taliban sources in
Afghanistan said 21 people died as a result of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met Friday morning with Berger and the rest of his
national security team to get a damage assessment on the strikes
that hit the complex in Afghanistan and a pharmaceutical plant in
Khartoum, Sudan, suspected of producing agents used in the
production of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden was believed to have strong ties to the plant, and
Berger insisted there was no doubt that the facility was producing
agents for chemical weapons, despite claims by the Sudanese
government that it was ``a medicine factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger told reporters that the Khartoum plant had been
``functionally destroyed'' with limited casualties while ``moderate
to severe damage'' had been inflicted on bin Laden's bases in
eastern Afghanistan near the Pakistani border.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said, however, that the full extent of the damage to the
three sites hit in Afghanistan won't be known until cloud cover
over the area clears, allowing U.S. satellites a better view.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they were still uncertain of bin
Laden's whereabouts, and denied again that the missile attacks were
intended to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   However, Berger warned bin Laden not to rebuild his damaged
facilities in Afghanistan or anywhere else, noting ``that would not
be a terribly wise decision for them to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who resumed his vacation Friday afternoon on Martha's
Vineyard, continued making phone calls to world leaders in an
effort to explain the U.S. action. Most voiced their support, with
the exception of Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who condemned the
unilateral action and complained that he was not informed
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton dispatched Cohen, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Gen. Hugh
Shelton and CIA Director George Tenet to brief lawmakers on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   After the briefing, Albright underscored Cohen's comments that
further military action may be necessary to damage terrorist cells
that threaten U.S. lives and interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are involved here in a long-term struggle,'' Albright said.
``This is, unfortunately, the war of the future, and we have to
understand the importance of sustained operations.''
</P>
<P>
   She also stressed that despite the absence of better damage
assessments on the strikes, they were still ``very successful in
having made clear that the United States will not be intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the missile attacks, federal authorities took
steps to tighten security at U.S. facilities abroad and at home,
particularly in Washington around federal buildings. At the same
time, the FBI issued a nationwide alert to all U.S. law enforcement
officials requesting that they be on guard against any suspicious
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines and airports were also asked to implement heightened
security measures. At major international facilities like Los
Angeles International and O'Hare in Chicago, extra baggage searches
were the rule, and some passengers were asked to turn on and
operate any electronic devices.
</P>
<P>
   The state department also issued an advisory warning Americans
traveling or living abroad to be watchful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be targeted,'' Berger told reporters, in response to
questions about whether the missile strikes could prompt other
terrorist activity. ``But we're also going to be on offense as well
as defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to take military action in the wake of the
embassy bombings in Africa drew support from two-thirds of the
American people, according to several public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   But the surveys also indicated that up to a third of the country
remains suspicious about the timing, coming as it did just three
days after Clinton acknowledged an inappropriate relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind., reiterated an earlier call
for Clinton to resign, charging that he had ordered the attacks to
divert attention away from his personal problems. But Cohen told
reporters that Coats had backed away from that position after being
presented with the intelligence information on which Clinton had
based his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Following the briefings on Capitol Hill, lawmakers generally
praised Clinton's action. But some said it was too early to claim
it a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out on whether the strikes had a major
impact on the terrorist training camps,'' said Rep. Peter Goss,
R-Fla. ``Tents and obstacle courses can be rebuilt or relocated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
