<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS CRITICIZE U.S. ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-DAMAGE,
ATTACK-RECAP, ATTACK-ISLAM, ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT,
ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT, ATTACK-KENYA, ATTACK-PAKISTAN, ATTACK-SUDAN) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL WINES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Almost nostalgically, it seemed, Russia reopened its
Cold War phrase book Friday to denounce the United States for its
cruise-missile attacks on Afghanistan and the Sudan. But in almost
the same breath, it declared that the differences would have no
effect on President Clinton's trip to Moscow in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   On Russia's far-north Kola Peninsula, where he was witnessing
naval exercises, President Boris Yeltsin said he was ``outraged''
by news of the U.S. attacks and in particular by Clinton's failure
to warn of them in advance. Afghanistan is on the southern border
of the fraternity of former Soviet republics now called the
Commonwealth of Independent States.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude is indeed negative, as it would be to any act of
terrorism, military interference, failure to solve a problem
through talks,'' Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Yeltsin spokesman seemed to play down those
remarks later by stressing Russia's agreement with the United
States that terrorism is an international threat.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko called the attacks unacceptable,
but added that ``international acts of terrorism cannot go
unpunished.''
</P>
<P>
   The Communist-led lower house of Parliament called the U.S.
strikes acts of aggression, said they were contrary to
international law and predicted that they would provoke terrorists
to still more radical measures.
</P>
<P>
   And former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev told the Interfax
news service in Moscow that the U.S. actions were not ``legitimate
or balanced.'' He said, ``The international community, the United
Nations Security Council and the United Nations secretary general
should have been notified.''
</P>
<P>
   He said terrorism is an international threat and that world
governments should combine forces against it, rather than working
alone and in secret. ``The entire international community was just
placed before an already accomplished act,'' Gorbachev said. ``The
United Nations Secretary General was told about the missile strikes
40 minutes after they had been carried out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev added, however, that Russia's criticism should not
prevent Clinton and Yeltsin from meeting as planned Sept. 1.
Interfax later quoted high-level Russian sources as saying the
summit meeting would be unaffected by what they called Yeltsin's
``irritation'' over Clinton's decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
