<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-RECAP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAYS AND DEVELOPMENTS LEADING UP TO THE ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic on the missile attacks is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-DAMAGE,
ATTACK-RECAP, ATTACK-ISLAM, ATTACK-RUSSIA-REACT,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT, ATTACK-KENYA,
ATTACK-PAKISTAN, ATTACK-SUDAN.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES BENNET    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In retrospect, the only public hint of the assault
to come _ the only moment when President Clinton's intense,
parallel preparations for his political survival and for a strike
against terrorists might have crossed _ came on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   After he grimly admitted his intimate relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, the president tried to turn the nation's attention to
more noble subjects, to ``important work to do'' including ``real
security matters to face.''
</P>
<P>
   That was it. The president did not mention his meeting that
afternoon in the White House solarium to discuss Thursday's
counter-terrorist missile strikes, even as prosecutors were
arriving downstairs to grill him under oath about Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention that, before he went to face the prosecutors,
he ordered Samuel Berger, his national security adviser, to convene
the government's top security officials Tuesday for one more
run-through of the mission. That meeting came just before the
president left on what the world and even most of his aides
expected to be a 12-day vacation, spent mostly in seclusion with
his wife, daughter and dog.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, from his borrowed Martha's Vineyard estate, Clinton
interspersed telephone conversations to outside political advisers
to discuss the dismal reaction to his speech with calls to his
security aides about the mission. On Wednesday night, the president
and his family went out to celebrate his 52nd birthday. He returned
at 11:30 p.m. to more telephone calls, including to Vice President
Al Gore to chew over a last, troubling question about the targets.
</P>
<P>
   He made up his mind about the targeting, then gave his final
go-ahead in a talk with Berger at 3 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Never has Clinton's fabled ability to compartmentalize his life
been more starkly demonstrated than in the last two weeks. As the
one man in the world who held all the information, he walled off
meetings with his lawyers to prepare for his testimony from
meetings with his national security advisers to plan one of the
largest military operations of his presidency, simultaneous strikes
seas apart by about 75 cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the last two weeks _ from the embassy bombings in East
Africa until the president's Oval Office address on Thursday
evening _ look in retrospect like a trick mirror version,
compressed and exaggerated, of the split presidency Bill Clinton
has had for more than five years now: Fierce damage control and
political strategizing on the one hand, studied policy debate on
the other. And connected to each hand, standing in the middle and
alone, was the president.
</P>
<P>
   The president's national security advisers have repeatedly
scorned the slightest suggestion that politics played a role in the
assault. Several said that the recommendation for the attack was
based on very strong intelligence and was unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating accusations of political manipulation, the national
security team took pains to avoid any appearance of political
meddling. Berger, who chaired the meetings to plan the mission, was
said by one senior official to be very concerned about any
appearance ``that there were any factors other than the merits.''
He kept the operation a secret until the middle of this week from
all but two of the president's top political advisers, Erskine
Bowles, the chief of staff, and his deputy, John Podesta.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Clinton's lawyers were said by White House aides to
have complained last week that they were not getting enough time
with him to prepare. They learned the reason why only when the rest
of the world did, as the president appeared at 1:55 p.m. before
reporters gathered in an elementary school gymnasium on Martha's
Vineyard and announced: ``Today we have struck back.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of a possible mission began on Friday, Aug. 7, after
powerful bombs exploded outside American Embassies in Nairobi,
Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania. Twelve Americans and nearly 300
Africans were killed. The senior officials who would ultimately
plan the strike held their first meeting. Sketchy intelligence
reports already pointed at a culprit, Osama bin Laden, an exiled
Saudi millionaire living in Afghanistan who had declared a
terrorist war on the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also began what would be a series of briefings
for Speaker Newt Gingrich on the intelligence findings about the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, in a rare piece of good news for Clinton, a
federal judge found that Kenneth Starr, the independent prosecutor,
may have violated legal rules prohibiting leaks of grand jury
material. Leaving it to his advisers to praise the decision,
Clinton devoted his own public statements to deploring the bombings
and promising retribution.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, Clinton departed on a political fund-raising
trip to California, with White House officials insisting he was
going about business as usual despite his approaching date with
prosecutors. Aides who accompanied the president described his as
cheerful as ever, playing hearts and swapping political strategy
with Democratic candidates he met.
</P>
<P>
   But the president cut short his trip to fly back to the White
House on Tuesday night, arriving after dawn. Some political
commentators surmised that Clinton was returning to prepare his
defense. In fact, his stated reason was the real reason: He wanted
to meet with his national security team.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting lasted for an hour in the Situation Room in the
White House basement, beginning after 10:30, for a briefing on the
investigation into the bombings and diplomacy with Africa. Then top
White House, Pentagon, State Department and CIA officials _ what
came to be called the ``small group'' _ moved up to the Oval Office
with the president for a 45-minute talk about retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Further intelligence had confirmed links between bin Laden and
the bombings, officials said, and suggested that a group of
high-level terrorists would be gathering on August 20 at a large
compound in Afghanistan that was associated with him.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Hugh Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
had already prepared a proposed missile assault on directions from
Berger. The general had worked up a set of the Pentagon's flip
charts, showing the concept for the operation, the potential
targets, the possible risks.
</P>
<P>
   The president starting firing off questions. His security
advisers described his as clear-headed and focused at every
meeting. He never referred to his political or legal troubles, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, according to one senior official who was
present, the president pressed hard about the mission's risks. ``He
said, when we get back together on Friday, I want you to tell me
all of the down sides,'' the official said. He wanted to know more
about collateral damage, possible terrorist retaliation, the
expected response of other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton focused on one of the targets, a factory in Khartoum
that intelligence showed was used to manufacture the building
blocks of deadly VX gas. The building blocks were inert. But what,
the president asked Shelton, if the factory also stored a great
deal of the completed gas itself? What would an explosion do to the
surrounding population?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave permission to begin moving ships into position in
the Red and Arabian Seas for an attack to begin in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Thursday, the president wept silently at Andrews
Air Force Base as ten flag-draped coffins arrived from Nairobi;
meanwhile, some of his closest advisers told reporters from The New
York Times that, contrary to his previous denials, Clinton was
preparing to tell the grand jury that he had an intimate
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, at a meeting in the Oval Office, Clinton got the
answers he had requested two days before. Shelton described a
so-called ``plume analysis,'' which showed that because of the
location of the factory, the casualties would not be high. Tenet
presented intelligence that he said clearly tied bin Laden's
network to the attacks in East Africa. Clinton gave the green light
for the mission on Thursday, and Shelton informed him that he had
until 6 a.m. that day to call it off.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, David Kendall, the president's private lawyer,
practically moved into the White House. He met for hours with
Clinton in the residence, on the second floor. Saturday morning,
the president delivered his radio address about receiving the
bodies at Andrews. ``Our administration will remain committed to
the fight against terror,'' he said, with no elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard weekend for the president. His advisers said that
he spent much of it trying to prepare his wife, his daughter and
himself for the admission Monday of a liaison with Ms. Lewinsky.
Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, had a long talk by telephone with Clinton
on Sunday afternoon, and found him deeply concerned about his
family. ``I think he recognized that this was going to be publicly
humiliating, but because of his actions he had to do it,'' Harkin
said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
