<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR US TO ACT ON OTHER TROUBLE SPOTS, SOME SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By moving forcefully against suspected terrorists,
President Clinton won praise even from critics of his foreign
policy. Now, some foreign policy specialists say, the president
should act with equal resolve to manage another set of overseas
problems that could be even more important to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has suspended its cooperation with United Nations weapons
inspectors. North Korea shows new signs of building nuclear arms.
Mideast peace talks have stalled. And Serbian leader Slobodan
Milosevic is forcibly pushing ethnic Albanians out of the province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In some of these cases, the United States warned there would be
stern consequences for bucking US policy. But the president has
followed those warnings with little action, his critics say _ at
least not much that can be seen publicly.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's strike against terrorists this week was welcome,
``regrettably, that credibility and resolve have been lacking from
other critical foreign policy challenges,'' Senator John McCain,
Republican of Arizona, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Several foreign policy analysts called the anti-terrorist
strikes on Thursday proper but limited. They said Clinton put few
US lives and little political capital at risk in ordering the
missile attacks _ launched from faraway ships _ on people who are
universally unpopular in the United States for their alleged ties
to the US embassy bombings two weeks ago in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very strong statement about our willingness to use
force, and I don't think it would change the resolve of Saddam
Hussein (of Iraq) or Milosevic in Kosovo,'' said Michael O'Hanlon,
a Brookings Institution fellow, about the missile strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The missile attacks, in fact, have diverted public attention
from more important foreign problems, said Edward Luttwak, a senior
fellow at the Center for Strategic and International Studies, a
Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Events like the Aug. 7 embassy bombings ``are unimportant,
almost trivial,'' Luttwak said. ``It's sad that people got killed
there, but that has the importance of a car crash ... Compare that
to the Russian economic crisis, with its potential for bursting
Russia and having maybe 25,000 nuclear weapons spill out.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``But President Clinton has not been available to deal
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of the administration are also waiting for a public
response to news that US spy satellites recently detected a large
facility in North Korea that could be part of a new nuclear weapons
program. If so, North Korea may be in violation of a four-year-old
agreement to freeze its nuclear weapons program in return for
foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's foreign policy team also stands accused of failing to
solve problems at home. The administration has said repeatedly that
the International Monetary Fund needs a cash infusion so it can
make new loans to ease the economic crisis in Asia and Russia. But
the president so far has been unable to force Congress to set aside
new money for the international lending agency. Moreover, Clinton's
push for special ``fast track'' powers to negotiate trade treaties
has stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics blame the Monica S. Lewinsky sex scandal and other
domestic problems for the inaction on foreign matters.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Luttwak said, warnings by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright that Israel must speed up the peace process have
proven to be empty. Clinton has been unwilling to rebuke Israel, he
said, for fear of angering pro-Israeli lawmakers who he may need
later as the Lewinsky scandal comes before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, at this point Madeleine Albright is incapacitated,''
Luttwak said.
</P>
<P>
   At the United States Institute of Peace, a nonpartisan research
group created by Congress, research director Patrick Cronin said US
leaders ``haven't followed through as they should'' on some of the
most pressing foreign policy problems. But he said those problems
are more complex than some critics acknowledge, and the United
States is trying to find new ways to manage some of them.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, threats of force against Iraq now produce
``diminishing returns,'' and the United States needs a new
strategy. And US officials are properly alarmed by the possible
resumption of a nuclear arms program in North Korea, even if that
is not publicly apparent, Cronin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's focus on foreign policy ``clearly
could be better, but it's not as bleak as the critics portray it,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
