s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTHERS-LIVES-BOOKS-$     08-21 0323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHERS-LIVES-BOOKS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS THE GROUP GRADED `INCOMPLETE'  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JANE GROSS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tide of books about women, work and motherhood has reached the
shelves of the nation's bookstores in the last year. At the request
of Money and Business, the women in a Brooklyn book group, all of
them mothers, read a broad sampling and discussed their reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, these readers tried: ``Not Guilty: The Good News
About Working Mothers'' by Betty Holcombe (Scribner), ``When
Mothers Work'' by Joan Peters (Addison Wesley), ``A Mother's
Place'' by Susan Chira (HarperCollins) and ``When Work Doesn't Work
Anymore'' by Elizabeth Perle McKenna (Delacorte).
</P>
<P>
   The women were unanimous in saying that they found the books
dull, tendentious and largely irrelevant to lives in which the
decisions they make are more often idiosyncratic than ideological.
</P>
<P>
   The reading was a departure from their usual diet of fiction and
memoir; indeed, some of them said that other books they had read,
like ``Rosie'' by Anne Lamott or ``Angela's Ashes'' by Frank
McCourt, offered richer insight into motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the women complained that the books read like
extended magazine articles but were vastly more expensive and
time-consuming _ an important issue when they had neither money nor
hours to spare.
</P>
<P>
   (Money and Business provided the copies that the book group's
members read.)
</P>
<P>
   Observations like these, publishing experts said, could account
for the slow sales of these books and others on the topic of
mothers and work, despite favorable reviews and abundant interest
in the issues they address.
</P>
<P>
   To date, none of these titles are showing up in the weekly sales
reports that booksellers make to The New York Times for purposes of
compiling the newspaper's best-seller list, Deborah Hofmann, the
editor of the list, said Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
