<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-LEAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-COLUMNIST GRANTED LEAVES FROM TV COMMITMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fallout from Mike Barnicle's resignation Wednesday from
The Globe continued Friday when the former columnist was granted
90-day unpaid leaves of absence by two of his television employers.
</P>
<P>
   WCVB-Channel 5, where Barnicle has worked for 15 years, said it
was giving him an opportunity to ``address the issues raised about
his work at The Boston Globe'' and that his role as a ```Chronicle'
contributor'' would be assessed after the absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are constantly reassessing ourselves,'' said WCVB director
of programming and communications Liz Cheng. ``To say Michael has
been the subject of meetings is not incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   Another media outlet that employs Barnicle, cable news network
MSNBC, also said Friday it was granting him a 90-day unpaid leave
at his request. ``We will wait ... to see how the facts lay out,''
said MSNBC spokeswoman Kyle Kaino.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Lott, communications director for PBS's ``NewsHour with
Jim Lehrer,'' where Barnicle was on a panel of regional
commentators, said Friday that Barnicle has withdrawn from that
panel and will no longer participate on the program. &UR;  &LR; Lott
explained that all the regional commentators work for daily
newspapers, and Barnicle no longer qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   And the board of the Maine Press Association is reconsidering
its invitation for Barnicle to speak at its fall conference Sept.
11. ``I feel it is inappropriate for him to speak at an event when
we are trying to recognize the highest standards of journalism,''
association director Doug Kneeland told the Associated Press
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe could not reach Barnicle for comment Friday, but the
AP reported this statement from him: ``This morning I called both
MSNBC and Ch. 5 to request a 90-day leave of absence. I explained
to them that I need this time in order to clear my name and remove
the cloud that has been placed over my career.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as Wednesday, WCVB's intention was to retain
Barnicle. ``Our point of view is that in the 15 years that Mike has
been on our air, we have found one 3-second transgression,'' Cheng
said then, referring to his endorsement of comedian George Carlin's
book ``BrainDroppings'' without having read it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have so far is the 3 seconds,'' said Cheng Friday,
explaining that the station will not be reviewing Barnicle's past
on-air work. ``We wouldn't know where to begin.''
</P>
<P>
   At WCVB, the Barnicle matter is clearly a hot topic. David
Ropeik, WCVB reporter and author of a weekly science
question-and-answer column in the Globe, said, ``Opinions were
mixed as to his apparent ethical lapses. There was a lot of deep
concern over whether his continued appearance on our air might
taint the credibility of Channel 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of the details ... the appearance becomes the
reality, and people make associations. The idea is to sort it
through, and protect the credibility of the station in the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, who had been serving a two-month suspension without
pay at the Globe, resigned from the paper Wednesday after being
unable to verify the details contained in an Oct. 8, 1995, column
about two children being treated for cancer at Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In resigning from the Globe, Barnicle attributed his decision to
a ``feeding frenzy'' over his work that ``has disrupted this
paper.'' He also said he believed the information in his October
1995 column to be true and was attempting to verify it.
</P>
</TEXT>
