</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-EVIDENCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIDENCE OF BIN LADEN'S TERRORIST ACTIVITIES IS `IRREFUTABLE,'
SENATORS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-DAMAGE, ATTACK-RECAP,
ATTACK-ISLAM, ATTACK-RUSSIA-REACT, ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT,
ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT, ATTACK-KENYA, ATTACK-PAKISTAN, ATTACK-SUDAN.) 
(ART ADV: A map-graphic on bin Laden and his operations is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's top national security advisers
began on Friday to show a small group of lawmakers the evidence
they had to justify the missile attacks on terrorist targets.
Although they would not reveal details, the lawmakers said they
agreed that the case against Osama bin Laden is as compelling as
the administration contends.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon Smith, an Oregon Republican on the Foreign Relations
Committee, and Sen. Chuck Robb, a Virginia Democrat on the Select
Committee on Intelligence, said the administration officials laid
out ``irrefutable'' evidence from a variety of sources.
</P>
<P>
   The sources include satellite photographs, eavesdropping
intercepts and statements from Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, who was
arrested in Pakistan and sent to Kenya for interrogation by
Americans about the twin bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania two weeks ago. Odeh has told Pakistani investigators that
the bombings were the work of bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the information from Odeh was crucial: ``This person
corroborated a lot of other pieces. It tied the bow. This was a
person who brought the ends of string into a good knot.''
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen Republican and Democratic lawmakers and aides
attended the classified briefing that lasted more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they shared with us made it crystal clear that terrorism
had escalated against us,'' Smith said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enemies who don't want to kill a few of us. They want
to kill a lot of us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robb said: ``It was the most compelling briefing I've had in 10
years in the Senate. They had such a solid, unequivocal story to
tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither senator would describe in detail the briefing from
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright; Secretary of Defense William
Cohen; Gen. Henry Shelton, the chairman of the joint chiefs of
staff; and George Tenet, the director of Central Intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Smith characterized the briefing as a ``chronology of crimes
past and crimes in the planning.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence, the senators said, conclusively tied bin Laden to
the embassy bombings of Aug. 7 as well as to strikes planned
against other U.S. embassies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence linked bin Laden both to the bombings in Africa,
as well as to the prospect of additional violence,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The senators declined to identify the specific embassies. But
the government in recent days has removed nonessential personnel
from vulnerable embassies in Albania, Pakistan and Eritrea. The
embassies in Malaysia, Uganda, Egypt and Yemen have also been
affected.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the cruise missile attacks was driven largely by
the extraordinary meeting of the terrorist leaders at the training
camps in Afghanistan _ ``a gathering of the hornets'' as Robb put
it.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. intelligence had known of the terrorist camps, the
bombings of the U.S. embassies in Africa ``substantially upped the
ante,'' said Smith. ``This is not just an action-reaction,'' Smith
said. ``Clearly, what I heard today indicated a great escalation on
the war against terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nairobi, the head of the FBI said that his agents still have
a long way to go before putting together a conspiracy case that
will hold up in a U.S. court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still in a fairly preliminary stage,'' the director,
Louis Freeh, said at a news conference just before boarding a plane
to Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
