<HEADER>
A6735 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-SCHOUSE     08-21 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-SCHOUSE </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   South Carolina reopens Capitol today
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: FREELANCE MATERIAL _ not for NYT wires.)
</P>
<P>
   By Lyn Riddle
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL TO THE ATLANTA JOURNAL-CONSTITUTION
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ South Carolina's State House has weathered
General Sherman's torches and cannons, a major earthquake, some
tornadoes and a brief skirmish with Hurricane Hugo.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the classical-style center of government has come
through yet another milestone: a three-year, $48 million renovation
that required digging underneath 10-foot-thick granite walls to
install earthquake protection, knocking down walls and rewiring,
reroofing and general repairing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This building is clearly the most symbolic in South
Carolina,'' said University of South Carolina art history professor
John Bryan, whose book on the history of the State House is due out
this fall. ``It is utterly unique, irreplaceable and it's been in
hazardous condition for a quarter of a century. I am exceedingly
pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   The State House will reopen to public tours today after a
ribbon-cutting at 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Located on 23 acres in the heart of this city at the center of
the state, the State House is actually South Carolina's third
Capitol. The first was in Charleston and the second was burned when
Sherman's troops marched through Columbia in 1865. The existing
building was under construction at that time. Except for a few
still-visible cannonball scars, it was undamaged by the flames that
devastated Columbia. In researching his book, Bryan uncovered
evidence that the building was meant to be a monument to states'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous symbols remain in the building to show state leaders'
intense drive to keep the federal government out of the state's
business, especially with regard to slaveholding. Underneath the
cornerstone was placed a copy of former Vice President John C.
Calhoun's speech in which he declared ``let us secede peacefully or
we will respond with force.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the state constitution or the U.S. Constitution, it
was Calhoun's last speech that was laid underneath,'' said Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   (Coincidentally, as workmen moved Calhoun's statue back into the
State House on Wednesday, a crane dropped its 5,500-pound granite
base, causing it to careen down the outside steps, almost knocking
over a statue of George Washington.)
</P>
<P>
   Bryan said planners in the 1860s also had intended to decorate
the massive columns outside the State House with statues
representing slaves working the fields. The statues had been
completed and stored on the State House grounds when Sherman burned
the city, destroying them and the marble intended for the inside of
the building.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan said he was ``tremendously heartened to see how far we
have come since then, how much broader and genuinely democratic our
vision is.''
</P>
<P>
   The building was begun in 1851, and construction continued over
50 years. With the new work, Bryan said, it looks much as it did
when it was completed in 1902.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators and the governor moved out of the building in 1995
so the work could begin. Three sessions of the General Assembly
have taken place in a renovated hotel across the street from the
State House.
</P>
<P>
   By the book, the renovation looks as daunting: 4 million pounds
of granite and four tons of debris removed, 2,300 gallons of paint
used and 80 miles of electrical conduits installed. The slate roof
was replaced with slate from the same company that supplied it in
the 1800s. Plus, the imposing dome now glistens copper in the
sunlight, not green as the old top did. It will take about 15
years, planners said, for the copper to weather.
</P>
<P>
   But even as legislators relish their new desks and high-tech
computers and audiovisual equipment, some state leaders are having
to adjust. The building actually has 40 percent less office space
than before, sending numerous folks used to working in the historic
digs to office complexes scattered around the Capitol complex.
</P>
<P>
   One controversial legacy remains. When Gov. David Beasley cuts
the ribbon to reopen the building, flying high above the sparkling
copper dome will be the Confederate battle flag, long a source of
contention between some blacks and some whites over whether a
symbol of the Civil War should remain atop a government building.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6736 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUTU-COX     08-21 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUTU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Archbishop Tutu in Atlanta for a year as professor
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While condemning attacks on U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania, Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu Friday stopped short
of embracing American military retaliation aimed at terrorist camps
in Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not myself too comfortable with, `We hit them.''' Tutu
said Friday after arriving at Emory University, where he will spend
a year as a visiting professor of theology. ``Are we sure that the
targets are accurate?''
</P>
<P>
   Awarded the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize for his anti-apartheid
campaign in South Africa, Tutu said no one should ``ever have truck
with terror wherever it may happen.'' The difficulty, he said, is
how to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, it will be OK to try and find the people who are
the ringleaders who are responsible for giving the orders,'' said
Tutu, 66. ``We've got to be very careful that we don't, in trying
to counteract, find that we are ourselves eroding the very
structures of the law. I mean, there is international law, and
one's obviously concerned that it seems that in retaliating in the
fashion that appeared to have happened, international law, morality
_ that all of those are put in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearied by his daylong trip from Cape Town, Tutu made the first
appearance connected with his arrival at Emory to teach two courses
in the spring. He wore khaki pants, a blue blazer and a
wine-colored shirt as he spoke for 20 minutes before campus staff
drove him away in a Saturn station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu said he looked forward to unwinding after two years of
chairing South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission, which
is investigating crimes committed during the country's period of
white rule.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu, who will attend a faculty retreat this weekend, arrived on
campus the day a judge fined and sentenced former apartheid
president P.W. Botha for ignoring a summons from Tutu's commission.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he supported a jail sentence for Botha, Tutu said, ``Of
course not. We are not blood thirsty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The TRC does not seek to gloat, does not want to find the
truth in order to humiliate or belittle people or embarrass
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now in failing health, Botha led the country during some of the
bloodiest days of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in his worst nightmare did he ever think that he would sit
in a court presided over by a black magistrate,'' Tutu said. ``I
think there is an appropriateness in demonstrating that this is a
moral universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a moral symmetry, a moral appreciation in what has
taken place. He has been found guilty in an open court where he had
the opportunity of being defended by lawyers of his own choice _
something he did not allow opponents at the time he was state
president.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate matter, Tutu revealed the TRC uncovered letters
that may document South Africa and other countries plotted to kill
U.N. Secretary-General Dag Hammarskjold in 1961. Hammarskjold and
15 others died in a plane crash while working on a peace agreement
between Congo and a breakaway province.
</P>
<P>
   The documents referred to aircraft sabotage and include
correspondence among the South African military, the CIA and Great
Britain, the British Broadcasting Corp. reported. At Emory, Tutu
conceded the letters may be disinformation planted during an era
when the Soviet Union favored such ruses.
</P>
<P>
   But, Tutu added, ``It isn't something that is so bizarre. Things
of that sort have happened in the past. That is why you can't
dismiss it as totally, totally incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
