<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY TO TEST REVOLUTION RESOLVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Robin Fraser is dispelling doubts about the
Los Angeles Galaxy's motivation in Saturday's Major League Soccer
game against the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot to play for,'' said Fraser, the Galaxy's
defensive leader and a US national team member. ``We still need 9
points to clinch first place in our group.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy own the best record in MLS (55 points in 25 games),
have scored the most goals (71), and have the top goal differential
(plus-35). They have clinched a Western Conference playoff berth
with more than a month remaining in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are in a much different situation. They have
earned 20 points, fewest in the league, and only 10 points since
May 10. They are 6 points behind the Miami Fusion in the race for
the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no shame in losing to a team that potentially is
better than us,'' Revolution coach Thomas Rongen said Friday. ``But
we are in a precarious situation. And I firmly believe that
regardless of who we are playing, we have a chance to win. Will it
be a tough task? Absolutely. We are playing against a very good
team. We almost have to win, and I feel we can.''
</P>
<P>
   A New England victory or a Miami defeat in Kansas City Sunday
would set up a Fusion-Revolution showdown in Miami next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution appeared to be out of contention after enduring
an MLS-record eight-game home losing streak, then falling, 6-1, at
Columbus two weeks ago. But they were rejuvenated by the recovery
of midfielder Jair, the move of David Nakhid to an attacking
midfield position, and the goalkeeping of Ian Feuer against Tampa
Bay last week. The game finished tied, 1-1, in regulation time, but
the Revolutuion, who won the post-match shootout, displayed enough
of an attacking threat to salvage some hope for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Galaxy should be a difficult test, with striker Carlos
Hermosillo, former Revolution forward Welton and Cobi Jones on the
wings, and Salvadoran midfielder Mauricio Cienfuegos.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a well-balanced team,'' Rongen said. ``With D.C.
United, they are the upper echelon of the league. They have so many
good pros and they have acquired a winner's mentality. They have
put the pressure on themselves that they expect to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
