<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Los Angeles Dodgers
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Today at 4:05 p.m., Sunday at 8:05 p.m, Monday at 1:10
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV, radio: FOX will telecast today, ESPN will telecast Sunday
and TBS will telecast Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Today, LHP Denny Neagle (11-11,
3.57; 7-5, 2.11 lifetime vs. Dodgers) vs. RHP Darren Dreifort
(6-11, 3.72; 0-3, 6.23 lifetime vs. Braves). Sunday, RHP Greg
Maddux (16-6, 1.65; 8-3, 2.24 lifetime vs. Dodgers) vs. LHP Carlos
Perez (7-12, 3.82; 2-4, 3.47 lifetime vs. Braves). Monday, LHP Tom
Glavine (16-5, 2.53; 13-14, 3.90 lifetime vs. Dodgers) vs. LHP
Brian Bohanon (6-8, 2.85; 0-1, 5.73 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: Atlanta trails the all-time series 232-301 but
is 29-12 at home against the Dodgers since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Braves were 5-0 this season and had taken
eight in a row from L.A. until the Dodgers' 1-0 victory Sunday.
Atlanta swept a three-game series at home May 4-6 and then took two
of three at Dodger Stadium last weekend. The Dodgers are batting
.212 against the Braves this year, but second baseman Eric Young
has hit two of his four homers this season against Atlanta pitching
within his last seven at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers leaders: Avg. _ Trenidad Hubbard (.327); HRs _ Raul
Mondesi (27); RBIs _ Gary Sheffield (77); SBs_ Eric Young (36).
Wins _ Chan Ho Park (10); ERA _ Jeff Shaw (1.31). Saves _ Shaw
(37). Strikeouts _ Darren Dreifort (152).
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: The Dodgers went into Friday night's game in Florida
with a 6-12 record this month, blowing their playoff chances before
any possible stretch run. Before beating Florida on Thursday, L.A.
had dropped five road games in a row. . . . The arrival of Charles
Johnson has done little for the offense. He is hitting .183 in road
games. But behind the plate, he has helped to lower the club ERA
from 4.11 when Mike Piazza was traded to its current 3.76. . . .
Offense, not pitching, is the pressing concern. The Dodgers' team
average of .252 is 14th in the league, and their on-base percentage
(.309) is the lowest in either league. The team has been held to
two or fewer runs eight times in its last 14 games. . . . The
Braves see a rarity this weekend: back-to-back starts by Dodgers
left-handers. L.A. had not had two lefties in the regular rotation
since 1987, Rick Honeycutt and Fernando Valenzuela. . . . Today's
game is a pitching rematch of Sunday, when Dreifort threw seven
shutout innings, Neagle allowed a Eric Young homer in the eighth
and L.A. won 1-0. The game marked the third time this year Dreifort
had a scoreless performance, but never against the Braves. In his
previous 10 1/3 career innings against Atlanta, he had given up 12
runs. . . . 3B Bobby Bonilla has been in and out of the lineup
because of a tender left wrist that had required surgery. He had a
five-game hit streak entering Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   On the DL: OF Todd Hollandsworth (left shoulder surgery), INF
Adam Riggs (torn right labrum), RHP Ramon Martinez (right rotator
cuff surgery), INF Jose Vizcaino (sprained left ankle), RHP Ismael
Valdes (sprained left ankle), INF Tripp Cromer (right quadricep
pull), RHP Darren Hall (torn right rotator cuff).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: 2B Eric Young took an 11-game hitting streak into
Friday night. RHP Jeff Shaw has not allowed a run in 51 of his 58
appearances this season. SS Mark Grudzielanek is hitting .326 since
the Dodgers acquired him from Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: OF Raul Mondesi had two hits in his first 13 at-bats
of the road trip. Gary Sheffield's home run Thursday night snapped
a 4-for-28 slide. OF Matt Luke is batting .139 since the 4th of
July.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
