A6739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MINORS-GREENVILLE     08-21 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MINORS-GREENVILLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On the verge of stardom
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ It became a clubhouse joke. But as the July
31 non-waiver trade deadline neared, the laughter became more
hollow.
</P>
<P>
   Trade anxiety usually is confined to a big-league clubhouse. But
not this year. Not on the Greenville Braves, a minor-league team
with three of baseball's best major-league prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Atlanta general manager John Schuerholz tried to make a
deal for bullpen help, three names almost always came up _ Bruce
Chen, Odaliz Perez and George Lombard. Other general managers
thought the Braves might be just desperate enough to sacrifice part
of their future for a closer that could help them win a World
Series this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time the phone rang in the clubhouse, someone would joke
that one of us had been traded,'' Lombard recalled. ``That's all a
lot of people were talking about. We'd kid each other about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all out to get to the big leagues as quick as we can,
but none of us wanted to be traded. We all wanted to make it in
Atlanta with the Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially Lombard, an Atlanta native who turned down a chance
for college football stardom at the University of Georgia to sign a
baseball-only deal with the Braves in 1994 after graduating from
the Lovett School. The $425,000 deal was a record for a
second-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Until this season, it seemed that the Braves and Lombard might
have made a mistake. A .238 lifetime hitter entering the season,
the 22-year-old outfielder is having a breakout year in the Class
AA Southern League.
</P>
<P>
   After a torrid first two months, Lombard's hot hitting has
cooled after missing two weeks with a strained left shoulder. But
the left-hander still is batting .301 with 20 homers, 60 RBIs and
31 stolen bases in 35 attempts. He is the first G-Brave to have at
least 20 homers and 30 steals in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is a lot of fun when you are doing well,'' Lombard
said. ``When you're not, it isn't. I thought I was making progress,
but I hadn't really put up the numbers. Now I'm starting to, and it
feels good. I've come a long way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part of baseball is all the ups and downs. It's
not like football. Baseball is like a roller-coaster and you have
to not worry about a bad day or a bad at-bat. You've got to have a
little bit of cockiness when you're on the field. I've struggled to
have that in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed about missing college life and frustrated by his
lack of baseball success, Lombard thought about quitting several
times his first few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time,'' he said, ``I went through about a three-week phase
of, if I struck out, then I would say to myself, `I'm through with
this. I'm going to go back and play football.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That would have made Georgia football fans happy, but Lombard
didn't want to be labeled a quitter. Right decision or wrong, he
was determined to make himself into a baseball player, no matter
how many barking Bulldogs fans he heard in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken a while, but I think people are finally seeing me
as a baseball player first, not a football player learning to play
baseball,'' Lombard said. ``I'm not thinking and worrying about
everything now.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer does the 6-foot, 200-pounder look out of place at bat
or in the outfield. He still strikes out too much and his arm is
not the best, but Lombard has the combination of speed and power
that makes baseball officials drool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball just explodes off his bat when he hits it,''
Greenville manager Randy Ingle said. ``You put that with his speed
and you know he's got a chance to be a heck of a major-league
player. It takes time, but George is willing to put in the work to
get there.''
</P>
<P>
   After a good winter in the Australian League, Lombard went to
major-league spring training with the Braves for the first time
this year and hopes to make his major league debut after rosters
are expanded Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Chen and Perez were moved up to AAA Richmond earlier this month
and also could be in Atlanta soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team I talked to asked about three players from our
system,'' Schuerholz said. ``I never say that anyone is
untouchable, but our action (in not making a trade) shows how
highly they are held (by the Braves).''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks of July, it wasn't uncommon for scouts
from 12 to 15 teams to attend a Greenville game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around the minors a while, and I'd never seen that
many before,'' Ingle said.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the deadline passed, most of the scouts were gone.
Now with Chen and Perez promoted, Lombard has the attention all to
himself in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Most minor leaguers get little or no mail from fans; Lombard is
an exception. He is flooded with autograph requests, especially on
baseball cards. Collectors know a future star when they see one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's kind of nice,'' Lombard said. ``It shows someone
thinks you are going to make it to the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Lombard, who will play in the Arizona Fall League, hopes to be
at Turner Field by September. ``It will be a great story when he
makes it,'' Schuerholz said. ``He took a risk to give up football.
He has worked very hard to make it pay off. He is on the verge.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer are afternoons at Sanford Stadium on Lombard's mind,
although he attends at least one game each season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more years that pass,'' he said, ``the less I think about
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
