<SLUG> BC-BBO-MINORS-GVILLE-CHAPEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Religion finally has a place in clubhouse
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Religion and baseball didn't mix when former
Atlanta Braves pitchers Jose Alvarez and Marty Clary were in the
minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams didn't want Bibles in the clubhouse,'' Alvarez said.
``Managers thought religion made you soft.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was considered a sign of weakness,'' Clary said. ``If you
weren't cussing or throwing things when you lost, people thought
you didn't care. Christians got a bad name.''
</P>
<P>
   But the atmosphere in baseball has changed. Baseball Chapel,
begun more than 30 years ago, is now active on all major-league
teams and all but a few minor-league clubs.
</P>
<P>
   With Alvarez, 42, or Clary, 38, leading the chapel services, the
Greenville Braves' weekly sessions often attract more than half the
team. The players usually meet in the bullpen for about 20 minutes
on Saturdays after batting practice. Chapel services also are
conducted for the visiting teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get more players than on any other team I've played with,''
outfielder George Lombard said. ``It means a lot to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The players know we experienced some of the same things they
are going through,'' Clary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in the minors is a time of great uncertainty and
longing,'' Alvarez said. ``Young players need to know that God's
love is unconditional and that we are all saved by God's grace. To
be a complete person, you need to be strong physically, mentally
and spiritually.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez and Clary were active in Baseball Chapel services while
they were Atlanta Braves in the late 1980s. Neither is a minister,
but Alvarez is active as a Christian speaker. Both are members of
Greenville-area Baptist churches _ Alvarez at Southside and Clary
at Siloam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a Christian doesn't mean being passive,'' Alvarez said.
``Jesus Christ certainly wasn't. ... But just because you are a
Christian doesn't mean you are going to win the game or hit a home
run. You can't use your faith as a crutch.''
</P>
<P>
   Clary said, ``Christianity isn't a good-luck charm.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
