<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-DRIVE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yukon Denali reaches its peaks
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the original Denali is the 6 million-acre national
park in Alaska, what does that make the GMC Yukon Denali? It's a
thinly, but sumptuously, disguised Chevrolet Tahoe, soon to be
similarly reworked and rebadged to appear as the Cadillac Escalade.
</P>
<P>
   The Denali park is home to one of the world's highest peaks,
Mount McKinley, while the GMC Denali is for those willing to pay
the lofty base price of $42,855 (the option-free test vehicle
totaled $43,495 after delivery charge was added). Pricey? Yes, but
as Consumer Guide _ like other publications _ notes, the Denali
``matches luxury features with any rival and beats most in power
and refinement.''
</P>
<P>
   Such praise is almost as good as hearing ``ka-ching'' for GMC
execs, who were outflanked by the Lincoln Navigator, a similarly
reworked version of the Ford Expedition. Ford/Lincoln beat the GM
crowd to the super-luxury sport-utility market, but the playing
field is being leveled.
</P>
<P>
   The Denali may lack the traditional cachet of a Lincoln, but
it's equally imposing, from its color-keyed luggage rack to its
color-keyed running boards. With its large rectangular grille
flanked by headlamp clusters seemingly large enough to light up
football fields, the Denali is 201.2 inches long, 79 inches tall,
78.8 inches wide and has a curb weight of nearly 6,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   GMC has further enhanced the brawny appearance of the Denali
with squared-off body cladding above the 16-inch wheels, which are
gleaming six-spokers. The Denali is a mass of sheet metal and glass
that justifies dropping a 5.7-liter V-8 into an engine bay only
slightly smaller than an efficiency apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The surprisingly quiet V-8 pounds out 255 horsepower at 4,600
rpm and begins generating its peak 330 feet-pounds of torque at a
utilitarian 2,800 rpm. Channel that power through an idiot-proof
two-/four-wheel drive system smooth enough to make barely
noticeable upshifts and the driving, hauling and towing is a
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   The test Denali's out-of-balance wheels created some annoying
vibration in the floor at expressway speeds (the Cadillac version
will have more insulation), but the ride remained soft. Body
movement is well-controlled, but mild off-road venturing proved
that while capable of sport-utility trekking, the Denali is not for
the timid. A three-ton vehicle isn't for throwing about by anyone
lacking self-confidence as a driver.
</P>
<P>
   Far better to keep the Denali on paved surfaces and wallow in
its luxury. The power front seats seem built to NFL standards, and
the interior boasts leather, Zebrano wood and such a multiplicity
of features that there's a six-disc CD changer in the chest-size
center console and a one-disc player in the dash.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its interior space (ample seating for five), the
Denali's controls are well within a driver's reach, and good
outside mirrors help with staying in touch with the outside world.
Parking the Denali in lined spaces or even at curbs is a bit of a
guessing game, but overall visibility is quite good.
</P>
<P>
   The price for the occupant security and roominess stemming from
the Denali's bulk does, of course, continue after the purchase. The
EPA figures of 12 mpg in the city and 16 on the highway are
marginal, at best, but at least regular unleaded gas can be used.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be enough gas to get through the sprawling Denali
National Park and Preserve, but the Yukon Denali is large enough to
feel at home there and its appointments will make roughing it a
foreign phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
