<HEADER>
A6744 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-GORDON-TEX     08-21 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GORDON RULES: HOW FAR CAN HE GO?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A victory tonight in the Goody's 500 at Bristol (Tenn.) Motor
Speedway would give Jeff Gordon five consecutive victories in
NASCAR Winston Cup races, a record for the modern era, which began
in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon leads the points race and has eight victories and six
poles this year. He has won four times at Bristol, including this
year's spring race.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of The Streak, staff writer Len Hayward answers 10
questions about Gordon, why he is hot now and how far he can go: &QL; 
1. WHY IS GORDON WINNING NOW? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has won in any kind of car he has driven _
quarter-midgets, sprint cars, championship dirt cars, the Busch
Grand National Series and Winston Cup stock cars. He started
driving a car with a big engine when he was 13. He has the talent
and now has a team behind him that his worthy of his talent.
</P>
<P>
   Also, people forget that Gordon and crew chief Ray Evernham have
been together throughout Gordon's Cup career, which began in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested that the team cheats. But when a driver wins
often, wild rumors surface about whether the team is on the
up-and-up.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Yates, who owns the car Dale Jarrett drives, believes
that a key to Gordon's midseason charge has been his team figuring
out the new Chevy engine better than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good and smart,'' Yates said. &QL; 
2. HOW FAR CAN GORDON GO? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has the potential to win as many Winston Cup
championships as he wants, but whether he breaks Richard Petty's
and Dale Earnhardt's record of seven titles is another question. A
recurring rumor has Gordon leaving NASCAR to drive Formula One
cars. Or Gordon could be the next Fred Lorenzen, who won 26 races
before he turned 33. Lorenzen left the sport in 1967 for various
reasons. He returned in 1970 at age 36, but never was as
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   If Gordon stays in Winston Cup, he will win a lot, but he has
little chance to catch Petty's 200 career victories. Gordon would
have to win at least 10 races for the next 17 years to have a
chance. &QL; 
3. WHERE DOES CREW CHIEF RAY EVERNHAM FACTOR INTO THE QUESTION? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among NASCAR crew chiefs, Evernham is one of the best _ if not
the best. He continually makes the right adjustments to the car
during a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray and the crew just never give up,'' Gordon said after
coming from well behind to win at Michigan on Sunday. ``We don't
ever give up until the checkered flag drops.''
</P>
<P>
   Evernham's attention to detail might be as important to the
team's success as Gordon's driving. After each race, Evernham
compiles his notes and notes from the chief mechanic, the engine
tuner, the tire specialist and the team engineer into a document of
three or four pages describing the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On race day, before the car is rolled to the starting line, it
has been through a checklist with a name signed to every item. &QL; 
4. IS GORDON THE BEST DRIVER EVER? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That remains to be seen. Gordon is talented, but Richard Petty
won on dirt tracks, short tracks and big tracks at a time when the
cars were not as safe, weighed more and did not have power
steering. But it is like comparing apples to oranges because Petty
was at his prime in a different era. &QL; 
5. WHY AREN'T MORE CHEVROLET TEAMS WINNING? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because there always seems to be a lead-dog team outperforming
every other team. Five years ago, that Chevy team was Dale
Earnhardt's. Gordon's team seems to have everything figured out
about the new SB2 engine. &QL; 
6. WHY DO MANY STOCK-CAR FANS DESPISE GORDON? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The group of fans that most despise him are 18- to 35-year-old
Southern males, typically Earnhardt fans. Gordon is young,
good-looking and does not come from the South. He is cheered more
in the Midwest and West than he is in the South or on the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at Bristol last August, the public-address
announcer could not even finish Gordon's name during a driver
introduction before a majority of the crowd began to boo.
</P>
<P>
   But at Indianapolis and Sears Point, he was cheered for
victories in both of those races this season. &QL; 
7. CAN HE BEAT RICHARD PETTY'S RECORD OF WINNING 10 CONSECUTIVE
RACES? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is set up in a way that he can. Whether he will is
another story. He has been winning so much that if someone, such as
Rusty Wallace or Dale Earnhardt, is close to him at the end of the
race, Gordon is likely to end up in the wall. Remember the bumping
between Gordon and Jeff Burton last season in the Southern 500,
with Burton admitting that he tried to put Gordon in the wall?
</P>
<P>
   If he can win tonight, Gordon would have victory No. 38, moving
him past the late Bobby Isaac into sole possession of 15th place in
career victories. The next two races are in Loudon, N.H., and
Darlington, S.C., and Gordon has impressive credentials at both
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   At Darlington, considered the toughest track on the circuit,
Gordon has won the granddaddy of stock-car races _ the Southern 500
_ three years in a row. On Labor Day weekend, he will try to make
it four.
</P>
<P>
   That would make seven consecutive victories and move him closer
to Petty's record of 10 in a row _ set in the pioneer era when
NASCAR staged about 50 races per season. &QL; 
8. DOES NASCAR NEED JEFF GORDON? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Gordon represents a new generation of drivers, whom race
fans essentially watched grow up on television. He is young,
good-looking and has a beautiful wife. Why would NASCAR, a sport
that is attempting to sell itself to Wall Street and not only to
its typical Southern constituency, not want him?
</P>
<P>
   And consider this: Chicago-based Burns Sports Celebrity Service
conducted a survey to determine which athletes were most desirable
to advertising decision-makers. Time magazine reported the results
reveal Gordon trailed only ``basketball deity Michael Jordan and
golfers Tiger Woods and Arnold Palmer.'' &QL; 
9. WHAT MAKES GORDON SUCH A GREAT DRIVER? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greer Smith of the ``Southern Motoracing'' newspaper in
Winston-Salem, N.C., who has been covering the sport since the
1970s, said there are three drivers he has seen do things no other
driver would even try _ the late Tim Richmond, Dale Earnhardt and
Jeff Gordon. &QL; 
10. COULD ANYONE WIN IN THE NO. 24 CAR? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but not as often as Gordon. No. 24 is owned by Rick
Hendrick, who is one of the most powerful and richest men in
motorsports. He will give his teams the best that can be bought, so
if Jeff Burton were in that car he would win, but not as often as
Gordon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
