<HEADER>
A6748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FSU-PREVIEW-COX     08-21 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FSU-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bowden as excited as ever to embark on new season
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ You'd figure after 368 games as a head
football coach _ 281 of them wins _ one loss wouldn't keep a guy up
late at night. But it does if you're Florida State's Bobby Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, who has won more games than any active Division I coach
but Penn State's Joe Paterno, is still having nightmares over last
season's 32-29 loss to Florida in the regular-season finale. For it
proved to be as costly as any regular-season defeat that Bowden has
had in 22 years at FSU.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State, ranked No. 1 in the coaches' poll coming into the
game, led the Gators 29-25 after kicking a field goal with 2:38
remaining. But on Florida's very next play, FSU's vaunted defense
broke down and gave up a 63-yard pass from Doug Johnson to Jacquez
Green. That set up the Gators' winning touchdown with 1:50 left.
</P>
<P>
   The loss not only knocked the Seminoles out of the No. 1
ranking, but it denied them a matchup with undefeated Nebraska in
the Orange Bowl. As talented as Nebraska was, Bowden was convinced
his team had enough speed to beat the Cornhuskers.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, always upbeat in public, was privately devastated.
Another shot at a national championship _ and a good one at that _
had gone by the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy didn't sleep much at all for a long time after that (the
Florida game),'' said Bowden's son Terry, head coach at Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, who is about to enter his 30th season as a head coach,
agrees that the Florida loss of 1997 rates as one of the toughest
of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I held on to that one longer than any one I can remember,''
said Bowden, who turns 69 in November. ``The year before when they
beat us in (52-20 in the Sugar Bowl for the national championship)
that didn't bother me. We just weren't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when it's (three) points. And to lose like that ... man,
that hurt. And it hurt a long time. Especially when it's against
your 'favorite' team.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a strange way _ maybe in a way that only another football
coach could understand _ Bobby Bowden has taken some comfort in the
pain. Because to feel pain after so many years means you still
care. And if you still care you can summon the energy necessary to
go through the physical grind of another season. At an age where
most men are cooling their heels in retirement, this grandfather of
23 will jump back into what should be another white-hot race for
the national championship in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm getting older but the drive to win has always been
there,'' said Bowden, whose teams have won a gaudy 118 games over
11 seasons. ``I'm just as excited about this season as I've ever
been about any one I've coached.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Bowden's success over those 11 seasons, and the goals that
still lay ahead, the desire to go to work every day shouldn't wane
anytime soon. The numbers are by now familiar but bear repeating:
</P>
<P>
   _ Since 1987, Bowden's teams have won 10 or more games every
year, an NCAA record.
</P>
<P>
   _ For 11 straight years, FSU has finished in the final top four
of the Associated Press poll. Florida is second on that list with
three.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bowden is 12-1 in his last 13 bowl games, including a streak
of 11 straight snapped by the Sugar Bowl loss to Florida in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ His teams are 47-1 in ACC play since joining the conference in
1992. This fall the Seminoles will be going for their seventh
straight ACC title.
</P>
<P>
   The only negative to be found in all those numbers is the number
one. That's how many national championships Bowden's troops have
been able to win during this remarkable string. Bowden's critics _
and they are out there _ insist that Florida State should have more
titles given the incredible talent that has passed through
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden does not disagree but neither does he dwell on what might
have or should have been. To survive in this business, the focus
must always be on the next team and on the next game. It is the
only way to stay sane in what is a crazy profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to look ahead at what this team could do and I'll tell
you, if we could put it together, we could be in the hunt,'' said
Bowden. ``The good thing for us is we've go the pieces out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve starters return and Florida State has all its ``tough''
games _ Southern Cal, North Carolina, Virginia, and Florida _ at
home. The Seminoles have a 26-year-old quarterback in Chris Weinke
and two of the most talented offensive players around in tailback
Travis Minor and wide receiver Pete Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, the Seminoles are even faster than a year ago when
they finished third in the nation (241.4 ypg). At 281 victories,
Bowden could reach the magical 300 mark some time in 1999. He needs
42 wins to catch Alabama's Bear Bryant on the all-time list for
Division I coaches. To Bowden, who grew up in Birmingham and was a
long-time Alabama fan, that would be something special.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden says he has no idea when he might retire. But he has set
up a few personal ground rules that will tell him when it's time to
go:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``If I wake up one morning and I don't want to go to work,
that's it. I'm history.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said he admired the decision of Dean Smith, North
Carolina's legendary basketball coach, who suddenly retired last
October. ``Maybe that's the way to go. Just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ When his health can no longer hold up. _ When he can no longer
look a recruit in the eye and promise him that he'll be at FSU the
whole time the recruit is there.
</P>
<P>
   _ If he starts losing. ``I'm not going through that again. That
ain't no fun.''
</P>
<P>
   If the past 11 years are any indication, Florida State and Bobby
Bowden still have a lot of fun days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
