<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History in his sights
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ Jeff Gordon will make his run at NASCAR history
tonight in the Goody's 500 at Bristol Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   If Gordon wins, he will become the first driver in modern-era
history to win five-consecutive Winston Cup races. NASCAR's modern
era began in 1972, when the race schedule was trimmed to 30 events.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said the key will be to negotiate Bristol's .533-mile
high-banked oval, where the field runs nose to bumper under the
lights for 500 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, if I could pick and choose where we were going to try to
do this thing, I'd probably say Sears Point or some place like
that,'' Gordon said, tongue in cheek. ``Maybe Pocono. Yeah, Pocono
would be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is trying to play down the moment as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just saying we're going to Bristol to race, and we know
what a dogfight that could be and how difficult this place is,''
Gordon said. ``This is a Russian-roulette track. The bomb can go
off, and it's an explosion. This place is simple: You have to be in
the right place at the right time. You've got to have the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has had a steady hand on the wheel, meshing with crew
chief Ray Evernham for comeback victories at Rockingham, Charlotte
and Michigan. He hasn't finished out of the top five since Rusty
Wallace put him into the wall at Richmond nine races ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's 15 or 20 laps to go, and you can put the leaders
in his sight, he's got a sight like a jet fighter,'' Evernham said.
``He can pick it up a little. Put that with a pretty awesome pit
crew and you've got something.''
</P>
<P>
   And his peers have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the best ever in the sport,'' said former racer
Harry Gant, who won four-straight in 1991. ``He's done more in less
time than any driver in history. If you look at where he is now,
he's further along than Richard Petty or Dale Earnhardt or any
other great driver at this point in his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he's doing has his closest pursuers shaking their heads
in wonder. Dale Jarrett is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got everybody going his way right now, and it just
doesn't seem anything Mark or I can do is going to make a
difference,'' Jarrett said. ``We're doing everything we can, and
nothing's working. It's a little frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen that before with different people,'' Gordon
teammate Terry Labonte said. ``They've just got things figured out.
They've got a good combination, and they are communicating well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got the right setups in the car, and they unload with
the right stuff. They're never chasing it. They're right when they
get to the track until the time to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why they're winning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
