<SLUG> BC-FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FASSEL MADE RIGHT CALL ON SEHORN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the ligaments in the right knee of New York Giants
cornerback Jason Sehorn were torn apart while he returned a kickoff
against the Jets on Thursday night, it did not take long for the
second-guessing of coach Jim Fassel to begin. As word of Sehorn's
injury spread among the players during the game, some mumbled to
each other on the sideline about why one of the best athletes in
football was being ``wasted'' on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room afterward, players said, defensive teammates
huddled in various corners of the room, some crying, praying for
Sehorn while wondering why he was returning kickoffs to begin with,
especially in the preseason. The next morning, reeling from the
knowledge that Sehorn was lost for the year because of torn
anterior cruciate and medial collateral ligaments, some in the
Giants organization wondered whether it had been necessary to
expose Sehorn to the madness that is special teams.
</P>
<P>
   It is at times like this when a head coach is truly alone.
Fassel made the decision, so he will take the heat, which is now a
raging fire. But where were all of the second-guessers before
Sehorn was injured? Making a decision after the fact is always
easy. If Sehorn had broken his return for a touchdown, fans and
news media types would be calling Fassel a genius.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, if emotion and hindsight are put aside, it is not
difficult to see that Fassel's decision to use Sehorn was the right
one. In fact, it was a smart one.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Giants' kick-return team was among the worst in
the league, failing to score a touchdown. Consistently starting
deep in its own territory can cripple an offense and cost a team
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel's decision: use one of the fastest, most fluid athletes
in all of pro sports as a return man so he can break a game wide
open with a jaw-dropping runback. At first, the decision seemed
foolhardy. Why risk your future Pro Bowler for a few extra return
yards, or, at most, two touchdowns a season?
</P>
<P>
   The reason is simple: very few kick returners get hurt. The top
11 return men in the game last season missed a total of four games
to injuries related to returning kicks. In all, they had some 571
returns, and the only players hurt were Aaron Bailey from
Indianapolis (he missed three games) and Desmond Howard from
Oakland (he missed one). That is a stunningly low ratio of
performance to injury. The only safer job in the National Football
League is kicking field goals.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened to Sehorn was a freakish accident.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if fans truly want to find a culprit, they need look no
further than the salary cap. Because of it, teams can no longer
keep players who only return kicks. Too expensive. These days, it
is almost impossible to find an NFL team that does not have a
starting wide receiver, a key defensive back or a top running back
pulling overtime as a kick or punt returner.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the salary cap, many top coaches would use some of
their best players on special teams. Dallas special-teams coach Joe
Avezzano, one of the best in the business, always has key starters
on his unit. Deion Sanders has returned punts and kicks for years.
Pro Bowl fullback Daryl Johnston has been on field goal and punt
protection units. Darren Woodson is used on kickoff coverage, the
football equivalent of bumper cars, and he is perhaps the best
safety in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Carter, Kansas City's four-time Pro Bowl cornerback, who is
better than Sehorn, is one of the top punt returners in Chiefs
history. Jets coach Bill Parcells puts some of his top players on
special teams as well, including cornerback Aaron Glenn, who
doubles as a kick returner.
</P>
<P>
   Former Washington Redskins coach Joe Gibbs, who is in the Hall
of Fame, often used his best athlete, cornerback Darrell Green, to
return punts. That is much more dangerous than returning kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   What most people who are criticizing Fassel feel is a sense of
frustration at losing Sehorn in such a meaningless game, and, of
course, Fassel feels that as well. But Fassel should not change his
way of thinking. He is an aggressive, talented, forward-thinking
coach, and those qualities are what make him a winner. If he
becomes shy because of what happened to Sehorn, it would be a major
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll quit coaching,'' he said, ``the day I stop trying to put
our players in the best position to help win football games.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
