<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-CHAMPIONSHIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maloney leaps past Moceanu
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Kristen Maloney doesn't mind if people spell her
first name ``Kristen,'' as it is listed at the U.S. Gymnastics
Championships, or ``Kristin,'' as it's spelled in the media guide.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no two ways about who was the most consistent
gymnast Thursday night in the women's all-around preliminaries and
individual event finals before 4,801 at Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to win anything. I'm just trying to go out
there and do the best that I can do,'' said Maloney, 17, of Pen
Argyl, Pa., who scored 38.162 points to stay ahead of 1996 gold
medalist Dominique Moceanu (37.437), who won two events to
Maloney's none.
</P>
<P>
   The scores carry over to Saturday night's finals. Maloney, who
was second on balance beam and fourth in the other three events,
was fourth last year and has excelled this year despite a stress
fracture in her right tibia.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, competing with a heavily taped left knee and against
doctor's advice, won balance beam and vault. Her first
individual-event gold medals were more remarkable considering she
hadn't trained for two weeks because of the injury. However, she
wouldn't receive funding from the national federation if she had
failed to show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to be back out there and fighting to the end,''
said Moceanu, of Houston, who won the Goodwill Games last month.
She is the only member of Atlanta's Magnificent Seven competing
here, but Kerri Strug is working in the NBC truck and Shannon
Miller, Amanda Borden and Jaycie Phelps were in the stands.
Dominique Dawes qualified for the event, but chose not to attend
and Amy Chow is in school at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Defending national champion Vanessa Atler, 16, of Canyon
Country, Calif., fell twice on the uneven bars _ an event she
dislikes _ and scored a dismal 8.225 to land in sixth place.
However, she won the floor exercise with a 9.85, the highest score
of the night in any event.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Zmeskal, the 1991 world champ on the comeback trail at age
22, is in ninth place but was angry at herself for mistakes on the
uneven bars, the last of her four events.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she proved she could hold her own with the teenagers even
if the start values of her routines were low.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all new to me again,'' said Zmeskal, who was tied for
third after three rotations and said she felt calm and in control.
``I have it in my body to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   In a bow to the past, Zmeskal did essentially the same balance
beam routine as Barcelona, where a fall 10 seconds into her
Olympics doomed her.
</P>
<P>
   Elise Ray of Columbia, Md., who was a junior last year, won the
uneven bars and is in fourth place behind Jennie Thompson of
Cincinnati, a former national junior champion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
