<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nascar notes: Goody's 500
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ Rusty Wallace was up to his old habits Friday,
winning poles at Bristol Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace put his Ford Taurus up front again Thursday for
tonight's Goody's 500 with a speed of 123.530 miles per hour. It
was his fifth career pole at Bristol, and back-to-back this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skinner was second fastest, 123.523. He now has started in
the top 10 in seven of his last nine races here.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points leader Jeff Gordon ran 123.039 mph and starts
from the fourth row, the deepest he's started since Texas 15 races
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''My main concern this week is to get in here and just win this
race,'' Wallace said. ''I'll do what I have to do and Jeff can do
what he has to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hamilton take
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hamilton's take on Bristol. ''You get behind a guy . . .
and pop him a little on the rear end. He gets mad and won't let you
by or lets you by and then takes a wack at you. Then you get mad,
and next thing you know, everybody's mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Musgrave for Spencer
</P>
<P>
   With Jimmy Spencer sidelined with injuries suffered at the
Brickyard, Ted Musgrave will fill in for him in tonight's Goody's
500. ''I could have driven the car, but the doctors tell me it
wouldn't be wise,'' said Spencer, who added his status will be
evaluated week-to-week.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine on the mound
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Bodine takes a taste of the fastest growing sport to the
national pastime Monday when he throws out the first pitch at
Yankee Stadium prior to the Yankees-California game. Fans will be
given a baseball card featuring a picture of Bodine and his racing
statistics. During the seventh inning stretch, Bodine's sponsor,
Phillips, will give away seven baseballs autographed by the last
two pitchers to toss perfect games, David Wells and Don Larson.
</P>
<P>
   They said it
</P>
<P>
   ''Trust me when I tell you I know exactly how Jeff Gordon feels
when he is booed. Heck, at driver introductions in the '80s, there
was a time when I would step up to the mike and say, ''Boo, if you
love DW.'' Now that's the way to quite 'em up.'' - Darrell Waltrip
on vocal race fans
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
