<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-LEATHER-$ADV23-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RISING TIDE OF HIDES LIFTS LEATHER IN THE CAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., N.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
(af) 
 By DAN NEIL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   American drivers have had their flings with vinyl, their
dalliances with synthetics and crushed velour. Now, they seem to
have developed a fetish for leather.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers tripled their use of leather from 1982 to 1992,
according to a trade group, Leather Industries of America. Demand
doubled again in the next five years, and the trend is
accelerating.
</P>
<P>
   American tanneries serving the auto industry buy 20 percent of
the 36 million hides produced domestically. At roughly 45 square
feet per cow, that's 58 square miles _ enough to upholster
Manhattan two and a half times, with enough skin left over for
headrests.
</P>
<P>
   Once the schmaltzy offering of a few luxury import brands like
Rolls-Royce and Jaguar, leather is now tres ordinaire on midpriced
sedans like the Toyota Camry and even economy cars like the
Chevrolet Cavalier, and practically de rigueur on high-end sport
utilities and top-line pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the 60s might have been in love with synthetics,''
says Philip D. Kaltenbacher, 60, chairman and chief executive of
the Seaton Co., a big supplier of leather seats to car makers.
``The buyers' generation of today have this profound love of
natural materials, like cotton, wood, stone and particularly
leather.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, less than 2 percent of Honda Accords were sold
with leather trim; currently, about 35 percent have leather.
Roughly half of the Ford Explorers and Jeep Grand Cherokees sold
last year had leather interiors, along with nearly all the Lincoln
Navigators and Mountaineers, the Lexus LX 470s and RX 300s, the
Mitsubishi Monteros and GMC Denalis.
</P>
<P>
   In sheer acreage, sport utilities account for most of the
increased demand. ``SUVs use two to three times more leather than
the average car,'' said Drew Winter, an analyst with Ward's
Automotive Reports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even proletarian pickup trucks are filled with the heady scent
of leather. About 10 percent of pickups have leather interiors,
which may not sound like much until you consider that full-size
pickups ``are the highest-volume vehicles in the market,'' Winter
said, with annual sales of almost two million. ``That's a lot of
leather.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is also a lot of money. Big trucks and sport utilities _ the
industry's cash cows, if you will _ have taken a drubbing over
environmental issues, and leather executives are eager to seem
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we want is people thinking we're burning down
rain forests for cattle just to put leather in big sport-utes,''
said Jeffery Bonello, a spokesman for the Eagle Ottawa Leather Co.
of Grand Haven, Mich., the largest supplier of leather to
automakers. In fact, most of the world's $2 billion supply of auto
leather comes from North America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tanneries have their own bad press to live down. Anders
Segerdahl, president and chief executive of Eagle Ottawa, remembers
when the chromium-laced effluent from one of his plants turned the
hulls of white fishing boats shades of red. But his company, with
annual sales of about $500 million, is now recognized a pioneer in
environmentally friendly tanning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has done as much to clean up the leather-making
process,'' said Charlie Myers, president of the leather industries
group. In 1991, Eagle Ottawa's Grand Haven tannery was the first to
convert from solvent-based to water-based finishing processes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the company completed its on-site waste-water treatment
plant. For his efforts, Segerdahl received the Theodore Roosevelt
Conservation Award in 1992 from President George Bush. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These days, Eagle Ottawa is promoting its recyclable Phoenix
leather, the first American automotive leather to be made without
chromium. It is tanned with a vegetable extract made of Peruvian
berries (the exact kind is a closely held trade secret). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix leather made its debut on the 1998 Volkswagen Passat,
and though it is more expensive and trickier to process _
vegetable-tanned leathers tend to crack and discolor when subjected
intense sun, heat and cold _ it already exceeds vehicle recycling
regulations anticipated in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Segerdahl, 74, learned his trade in the Old World, sorting hides
in a 300-year-old tannery in Sweden, where his family products
included leather for buggy whips and Ford Model T's. He is also a
footnote in the realm of kitsch culture, having coined ``rich
Corinthian leather,'' the catch phrase Ricardo Montalban trilled in
the 1970s in commercials for the Chrysler Cordoba. ``It was just a
name we picked,'' Segerdahl said with a chuckle. ``We thought it
was funny when Montalban made it so famous.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Montalban's seductive salesmanship lent an exotic touch to what
was, in fact, a rather mundane type of embossed leather. Indeed,
the Cordoba's interior wouldn't make the grade in today's
marketplace of high-grade skins.
</P>
<P>
   And while consumer expectations have soared, prices have
remained relatively stable because of slackening demand in the
domestic leather goods industry. In 20 years, for example, shoe
production has fallen from 400 million pairs a year to 139 million.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of hides are available. While consumption of red meat _
the prime factor in the hide supply _ has declined in the United
States and Europe, it has increased in Asia and the Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a slew of moderately priced cars can be had with
newly affordable leather options. A leather package adds $895 to
the sticker of a 1999 Mercury Cougar V6, or $795 to the Mercury
Tracer LS Sport. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers can offer leather at the low end by making their
cowhides go farther. ``If you look at the fine print on the
sticker,'' said Myers of the leather industry group, ``it may be a
leather seating surface, but the entire interior of the car is not
leather. Often the seat surrounds and backs are vinyl.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The leasing boom has also raised demand. Winter said, ``When the
salesman says, you know, for 10 bucks more a month you can have
leather, people go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the lease is up, leather often holds more of its
original value than other add-ons. ``When you consider usage and
convenience it virtually pays for itself,'' said Tim Hippo, sales
manager of Sir Walter Chevrolet in Raleigh, N.C. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such a statement might astound anyone who has tried to salvage
the leather-lined insides of an old British sports car. Older
leathers did not have much protective coating, and while they were
softer, more aromatic and developed a lustrous patina through long
use, they didn't look new for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, people want leather to wear like vinyl,'' said Don
Brown, national product planning manager for Toyota. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers have mostly overcome the durability issue, but one
problem remains. ``Leather can be kind of boring, I guess,'' Brown
said. ``Designers are always looking for ways to add interest.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The current generation of high-tech leather attempts to
re-capture the feel of natural leather. These products can be
coated, textured, perforated or embossed with a natural grain, or
infused with a fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   Segerdahl, dean of the industry, seems eager to face the next
technical challenge and scorns retirement. ``You know,'' he says,
setting up the inevitable pun, ``the business just gets under your
skin.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
