<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US ASSESSES MISSILE DAMAGE, PLOTS NEXT MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ US forces inflicted ``moderate to severe'' damage
to a sprawling terrorist camp in Afghanistan during Thursday's
missile strikes, administration officials said Friday, as President
Clinton and his advisers tried to gauge the next move in what
increasingly appears to be an uneasy war against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   US intelligence officials, hampered by heavy clouds over
Afghanistan, were uncertain of the number of suspected terrorists
killed in the attack, but Taliban Radio reported 27 killed and 50
injured.
</P>
<P>
   The strike was timed to occur as a large group of terrorists
from across the Middle East gathered at a training camp that serves
as the operations base for Osama bin Laden, the multimillionaire
exile who is the main suspect in the deadly African embassy
bombings on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   US officials, believing bin Laden survived, offered him a
warning Friday. ``Bin Laden, like any other terrorist, should not
rest easy,'' said Samuel R. Berger, national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   As assessments seeped in through the CIA and the military,
President Clinton made a round of telephone calls to world leaders,
and his senior national security officials descended on Capitol
Hill to brief senators and House members and rally their support.
Meanwhile, across the nation, law enforcement agencies went on a
heightened state of alert, on guard for a possible retaliatory
terrorist strike on US soil.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's senior aides explicitly warned that Thursday's attack
_ as many as 75 Tomahawk missiles launched from ships on the
Arabian Sea and the Red Sea _ marked just another round in what
will become an increasingly pitched battle with terrorist forces
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's strike itself brought the United States into largely
unchartered territory. While one of the most significant attacks
launched by Clinton in his 5 1/2 years in office, it was also
targeted at an elusive underworld figure rather than a specific
government or state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are involved here in a long-term struggle,'' said Secretary
of State Madeleine K. Albright, after briefing congressional
leaders on Capitol Hill. ``This is unfortunately the war of the
future, and we have to understand the importance of sustained
operations here.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials stressed that the attack was both retaliatory and
defensive, in one fell swoop. Even as the United States sought
retribution for the US embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania,
intelligence officials also believe bin Laden was plotting similar
attacks, possibly against US diplomats in Pakistan and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't guarantee that something like this will prevent
further attacks on the United States, but I am absolutely certain
that had we not done this, we would have been the victim of other
terrorist attacks in the not too distant future,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Berger added: ``We're also going to be on offense as well as on
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, after talking with advisers and world leaders
from the Oval Office for much of the day, boarded Air Force One at
Andrews Air Force Base just after 5 p.m. and flew back to Martha's
Vineyard, Mass. to resume his vacation. White House officials said
he would receive regular briefings on the impact of the military
action and its aftermath on a secure telephone line in his borrowed
vacation compound.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Clinton's actions garnered an increasing level
of support, and lawmakers who only the day before questioned the
timing of the strikes, coming as they did just a few days after
Clinton's unprecedented federal grand jury testimony, were now
offering their strong backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just simply saying, whatever the president's other
shortcomings may be, in this instance I believe he acted
appropriately, and as a Republican, I take my hat off to him,''
said Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Said Senator Rod Grams, a Minnesota Republican: ``It was a very
measured response,''
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent our military intelligence people can make these
judgments at this point, their conclusion is that the camps which
comprise the Khost complex have sustained moderate to severe
damage,'' said Berger. ``The attacks have significantly disrupted
the capability to use these camps as terrorist training
facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, public opinion polls indicated widespread
support for the strikes, along with lingering questions over
Clinton's motives. In a CNN poll, 66 percent of the respondents
approved the strikes, compared to 19 percent who registered
disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in that same poll whether Clinton was trying to divert
attention away from his extramarital affair with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky and the allegations that he obstructed
justice, 58 percent of the respondents said no, while 36 percent
answered yes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sudanese capital of Khartoum, the damage inflicted by
half a dozen US missiles was obvious. A pharmaceutical company
which US officials believed was a front for a bin Laden-financed
chemical company was flattened, as well as some of the surrounding
buildings in the industrial district in which it stood. The
casualty toll in the missile strike remained unclear. The governor
of Khartoum said several people were killed and injured in the
strike. Khartoum Hospital officials said 10 people were being
treated, for injuries, including four in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the so-called pharmaceutical company in Sudan was
functionally destroyed,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   In the hills of Afghanistan, at the sprawling training camp and
terrorist operations base, damage was more difficult to measure,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The missiles carried small bombs and lethal projectiles meant to
kill the terrorists who were supposedly gathered at the facility
for a round of meetings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
