<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-FINANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich goes to middle-America to hear farmers' concerns
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ He delivered his complaint softly and
politely, this Iowa farmer, dressed in the unofficial uniform of
his trade, jeans and a ball cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have these prices for long, there will be a lot of
farmers going out of business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a still day at the Iowa State Fair Friday, the humidity
worthy of Atlanta, this farmer, who blended into the crowd without
identifying himself, put his finger on the one issue that seems
capable of exciting the Midwest electorate in an otherwise sleepy
election year.
</P>
<P>
   Low prices for corn, soybeans and other products, a result of
Asian and Russian economic troubles, are making this year a tough
one for many farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich came to the fair Friday for a town hall
meeting at the start of a seven-state trip that will focus raising
campaign money in the some of the most hotly contested districts in
the West.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich promised two actions when Congress returns from its
summer vacation next month that would help farmers. He said he
expects Congress to approve additional funds for the International
Monetary Fund, which would pump some of that money into the
troubled economies.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he also will bring to a vote ``fast track'' trade
authority for the president, which would maximize the president's
flexibility in negotiating trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Both, however, are extremely contentious. Members of his own
party strenuously object to sending more money to the IMF, which
some Republicans believe is at best inefficient and at worst
corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats failed to rally behind the fast track issue when it
was last raised in the fall because the proposal did not require
new trade treaties to have child labor and worker safety
provisions. They think Gingrich is bringing the issue back now,
just before the elections, to drive a wedge between Midwestern
Democratic candidates and voters.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting at the State Fairgrounds was a ragged rendition of
the crisp productions that are the hallmark of Gingrich's traveling
road show. Empty seats and faulty microphones combined with the
oppressive humidity.
</P>
<P>
   But then Gingrich learned that not even the ``third ranking
constitutional officer of the United States,'' as he and his staff
sometimes call Gingrich, can compete with public milking
demonstrations, the appearance of the Hereford queen and the Butter
Cow.
</P>
<P>
   While repeated public announcements could not fill the seats for
the speaker, a steady stream of visitors passed by the display
featuring a life-size cow, replete with udders, made of butter. Of
course, it was also cooler in there.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich crisscrossed the state Friday, campaigning for
gubernatorial candidate Jim Ross Lightfoot, a former congressman,
in Sioux City, Rep. Tim Nussle and congressional candidate Larry
McKibben.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa visit, at least his third this year, drew the
inevitable suggestions that Gingrich has a presidential campaign in
mind. But Gingrich did not address the topic or, for that matter,
President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the event at the fair urged questioners to confine
their comments to agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   In Ames, Iowa, Gingrich spoke at a fund-raising breakfast for
McKibben, whom Republicans consider one of their top chances to add
to their majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   McKibben, a lawyer and state senator, faces freshman Democrat
Leonard Boswell, who won with just 49 percent of the vote in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich accused Boswell, who said he would vote for fast-track
authority if it had a child-labor clause, of siding with ``the
unions in the East'' over Iowa farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Iowa Farm Bureau has designated Boswell ``a friend of
agriculture.'' Boswell is also a farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
