u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-NUKE-PILLS-400&AMP;ADD     08-21 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-NUKE-PILLS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRC PLANS TO DISTRIBUTE POTASSIUM IODIDE TO STATES WITH NUCLEAR
PLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Maine, Ala., Tenn., Ohio)  (lh) 
 By JONATHAN RABINOVITZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ After years of resistance, the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission is preparing to distribute to states with
nuclear power plants a drug that would block a type of radiation
that causes thyroid cancer. Already, people in Connecticut and
other states are clamoring for the medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The move was spurred, in part, by new evidence about thyroid
cancer in the wake of the 1986 nuclear accident at Chernobyl, and
the lower incidence of the disease in areas where the drug,
potassium iodide, was widely used.
</P>
<P>
   The policy change also comes at a time when the NRC is
revisiting many regulations and addressing what many critics of the
nuclear power industry say were the agency's weakest policies.
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal government had previously argued that the
drug might cause dangerous side effects and give people a false
sense of security during a nuclear accident, some critics had
accused the agency of declining to offer potassium iodide out of a
concern that it would promote fears of a nuclear accident.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Alabama and Tennessee have started stockpiling the
pills at evacuation centers, while Maine and Ohio are moving toward
requesting a supply from the federal government. New York is
reconsidering its refusal to provide the medicine to the public,
and Kristine Smith, a state Health Department spokeswoman, said
that only last month, a departmental advisory committee of
physicians concluded that access to potassium iodide in a nuclear
accident would benefit public health.
</P>
<P>
   In Waterford, Conn., on Thursday night, only a few miles from
the Millstone nuclear power station, residents told a state nuclear
policy panel that they wanted the pills. ``I want it in my purse,''
said Billie Staub of Niantic. ``I want my children and
grandchildren to have it at the ready.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the evening, the Nuclear Energy Advisory
Commission had voted 9-2, with one abstention, to recommend that
the state distribute the pills to residents living within five
miles of the Millstone plant, which until last month had been shut
down for more than two years because of safety concerns. The
Connecticut Health Department, in conjunction with other state
agencies, is considering the recommendation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The use of potassium iodide to block radiation is not new. It
has been used in other countries, like Poland, for a number of
years, and Peter G. Crane, an NRC staff lawyer who has lobbied as a
private citizen to change the agency's policy, said it was first
approved by the Food and Drug Administration for medical use in
this country in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Today it is available over the counter at many pharmacies, with
a prescription, at a cost of about 7 cents a pill, Crane said.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear power regulators, physicians and government health
officials emphasized Friday that potassium iodide should not be
viewed as a cure-all for radioactivity from a nuclear power
accident. It blocks only one of many isotopes _ radioactive iodine
_ that may be emitted from a leak or meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if no action is taken, radioactive iodine is absorbed
into the thyroid, where it can lead to thyroid cancer and other
thyroid disorders. A 130-milligram pill of potassium iodide can
prevent the radioactive iodine from entering the thyroid for
several days, if it is taken within a few hours of exposure to the
iodine, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about its effectiveness,'' said Jacob
Robbins, former president of the American Thyroid Association and a
scientist emeritus at the National Institute of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some emergency preparedness and public health officials
harbor doubts about whether it is a good idea. They said that
people may misunderstand what the pill does and fail to evacuate
when officials order them to do so. And it is not clear how state
officials will make sure that everyone who needs the pills will get
them.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Maurer, a spokesman for the New York Emergency Management
Office, said that the justification for the state's present
position not to distribute the pills to the public is
straightforward. ``The bottom line is that we intend to have people
out of harm's way before they would need potassium iodide,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a question of liability, if people who take the
pills suffer side effects. Connecticut and other states are
considering requiring people to sign release forms before they are
given the pills.
</P>
<P>
   And Mary Lou Fleissner, the Connecticut health department's
director of environmental epidemiology said that potassium iodide
had side effects, such as risk of cardiac arrest for people who
already have high levels of potassium.
</P>
<P>
   But Crane, who has thryroid cancer and has lobbied for 10 years
to make the pill more available, disputed such an assessment and
noted that its use after the Chernobyl accident provided strong
evidence of its effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins said that while there was a high incidence of thyroid
cancer _ as many as 1,200 cases _ in Ukraine and other former
Soviet republics that did not use potassium iodide, the number was
much smaller in Poland, where the drug was distributed to about 10
million people immiediately after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were very few cases of any kind of trouble, because of
potassium iodide,'' Robbins noted, referring to side effects. Older
people do tend to have more problems with the drug than younger
people, but they also are less suceptible to thryorid cancer, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The pill has a half-life of eight days, meaning that half of it
would disappear from the body during that span, Dr. Fleissner said.
The pill has a shelf-life of five years, before it must be
replaced, she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
