<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMP-ALLIED-530&AMP;ADD-NY     08-21 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMP-ALLIED-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMP REJECTS $10 BILLION OFFER FROM ALLIED SIGNAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J.)  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The board of AMP Inc., a leading making of electronics
equipment, rejected a $10 billion bid from Allied Signal Inc. on
Friday, igniting a rare hostile takeover battle in a market that
has grown accustomed to friendly mergers.
</P>
<P>
   AMP, which dismissed Allied Signal's all-cash tender offer as
too low, overhauled its top management Friday and appointed Robert
Ripp, formerly executive vice president, as chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Harrisburg, Pa., has enacted ``poison
pill'' defenses against hostile bids and vowed to shed divisions,
close plants and lay off more workers to make itself more
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no synergies between our companies, and we are not
interested in a combination,'' Ripp said in an interview on his
first day as AMP chief. ``We absolutely believe that we have far
greater value than the offer they put on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal, based in Morristown, N.J., makes aerospace and
automotive products. It said it would seek to wrest control of AMP
by appealing to shareholders and fighting the company's board in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Bossidy, Allied's chief executive, heatedly denounced
the rejection of his company's offer. He described Ripp, a former
IBM executive and chief financial officer of AMP, as having
``neither the experience or track record'' to improve AMP's
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is puzzling that a company in dire operating straits would
appoint as CEO someone who had no operating experience prior to
this year,'' Bossidy said in a statement that observed few of the
usual corporate courtesies. ``AMP's manufacturing and
administrative structures are antiquated, its margins are lower
than its competitors' and its market share is eroding, resulting in
plummeting profits and a bleak future.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the 1980s, when companies routinely tried to
resist corporate takeovers, most mergers and acquisitions are now
amiable, because stock prices have been inflated by a long bull
market. Allied Signal is a good example: The company has made a
string of acquisitions of smaller companies in recent years, deals
designed to keep its earnings growth strong. All its purchases have
been friendly, a company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Allied Signal decided to make a hostile bid for ailing AMP,
which declined to negotiate a sale despite overtures from Allied
Signal that began a year ago. AMP officials argue that Allied
Signal has sought to buy its shares at a steep discount from their
proven value.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just trying to buy us on the cheap,'' Ripp said.
</P>
<P>
   AMP's results have suffered this year as sales growth has
dwindled and profit margins have contracted. Ripp blamed Asia's
economic crisis _ the company sells 20 percent of its
interconnection devices there _ for most of its sales slump.
</P>
<P>
   The company's share price has plunged by half in 10 months. It
hit a low of $28 on Aug. 3 of this year, the day before Allied
Signal made its tender offer at $44.50 a share. Allied Signal
argues that the offer is a 55 percent premium on its share price on
the date the offer was made. AMP says the offer is a 20 percent
discount on its peak price and called the bid ``opportunistic.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   AMP's board chose Ripp, 57, to replace James Marley as chairman
and William Hudson as chief executive. Marley will retire and
Hudson will become vice chairman. Ripp told analysts Friday that he
would speed up a restructuring plan first announced in July. That
includes shutting several production plants and firing 3,500
workers, about 7.5 percent of the company's total.
</P>
<P>
   Bossidy dismissed that revamp as too little, too late. ``AMP has
had ample opportunity to restructure and fix the company,'' he
said. ``But its ability to change on its own is at best
improbable.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal has sued to test the legality of AMP's measures to
thwart a hostile takeover. Pennsylvania law has strong
anti-takeover provisions that tend to favor the board of a target
company. The laws recently helped Mellon Bank of Philadelphia to
defend itself against an unsolicited bid from Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal has also appealed to AMP shareholders to tender
their shares despite the board's rejection.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders will have an opportunity to overrule the board and
accept Allied Signal's offer beginning Oct. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
