<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS DROP IN HONG KONG AS FREE MARKET TAKES OVER
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong government ended a weeklong buying spree to prop
up the slumping stock market and let the free market take over,
causing stocks to plunge. The Hang Seng index of 33 leading stocks
declined 214.9 points, or 2.8 percent, to 7,523.61. Hang Seng index
futures plunged 2.8 percent in the final five minutes of trading,
as brokers who had been buying for the Government stopped,
prompting a flood of last-minute sales.
</P>
<P>
   BANK STOCKS HURT BY GLOBAL TURMOIL
</P>
<P>
   Bank stocks rebounded early in the week before economic turmoil
in Russia and concerns about financial instability in Latin America
sent the group reeling. For the week, the stocks of big money
center banks, as measured by the Standard &AMP; Poor's Money Center
Bank Index, were down 4.52 percent. The index has declined 12.84
percent since Aug. 3, as shown above.
</P>
<P>
   TELLABS POSTPONES TAKEOVER VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Tellabs postponed a shareholder's vote on the company's pending
purchase of Ciena after Ciena said it might not win an important
contract from AT&AMP;T. Shares of Ciena, a maker of products that
increase capacity on phone networks, plunged 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA'S REFORMERS WANE
</P>
<P>
   Efforts toward westernizing the Russian economy are in danger
now that the financial crisis has greatly dimmed the political
prospects of President Boris Yeltsin and other champions of market
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA TRIES TO RESTORE ORDER
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian government closed three banks and seized
ownership of four others in its most comprehensive effort yet to
restore order to the devastated financial system. Among the banks
were institutions owned by some of the most powerful business
families in the country. Bambang Subianto, the finance minister,
said that the government would try to recover money lent to the
banks from their shareholders, but that there would still be
substantial costs to the state.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN PESO PLUNGES TO A NEW LOW
</P>
<P>
   Despite central bank intervention, the Mexican peso fell to a
record low of 9.74 pesos to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   NESTLE GAINS ALL OF PHILIPPINE UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Nestle has agreed to acquire the 45 percent stake in Nestle
Philippines held by San Miguel Corp. for $640 million.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS BANK WILL NOT CONTRIBUTE
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss central bank refused to contribute to a $1.25 billion
settlement the country's two biggest commercial banks have agreed
to pay Holocaust victims and their heirs. The bank welcomed the
private settlement, but said its participation would ``lend this an
official character, which is not in the interests of the country as
a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT ON TRACK FOR A SURPLUS
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration reported a $24.1 billion deficit for
July _ 6 percent less than a year ago _ leaving the government on
track for the first annual budget surplus in 29 years. The July
deficit put the surplus for the first 10 months of the fiscal year
at $43 billion.
</P>
<P>
   UNEMPLOYMENT CLAIMS FALL
</P>
<P>
   The number of newly out-of-work Americans seeking unemployment
benefits slipped by 2,000 in the latest week. Initial jobless
claims fell to 301,000 in the week that ended last Saturday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
