<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLEGHENY-COLLAPSE-AR     08-21 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLEGHENY-COLLAPSE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA SHAKEN BY COLLAPSE OF HEALTH-CARE GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif., Tenn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ This venerable city with some of the United
States' oldest hospitals and medical schools is reeling from the
collapse of an institution that swooped into town a decade ago and
shook up every aspect of health care here.
</P>
<P>
   That institution, the Allegheny Health, Education and Research
Foundation, is the largest health-care provider in Pennsylvania and
one of the largest nonprofit providers in the country, owning 13
hospitals _ four in Pittsburgh and nine in and around Philadelphia
_ and nearly 600 physicians' practices in the two cities. Its goal
was to build an integrated health-care network that would treat
patients from diagnosis to discharge, and from cradle to grave.
</P>
<P>
   But a month ago, with debts of $1.3 billion and losses recently
of $1 million a day, Allegheny filed for protection from creditors
under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law. Moody's Investors
Service says the nation's last big hospital-system failure, in
California six years ago, was a third the size of Allegheny's.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has since dismissed its chief executive, whose
bold ideas about managing health care drove its wave of
acquisitions and consolidations. Allegheny's strategy of rapid
expansion is now widely seen as having been risky from the start,
the foundation moving too far and too fast,
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very high-flying warning flag to others who are trying
to do these things,'' said Richard Wade, spokesman for the American
Hospital Association. ``It was created too quickly to manage.
Allegheny is a model you don't want to replicate.''
</P>
<P>
   The damage from Allegheny's failure is leaching through the
local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of creditors, from big health-maintenance
organizations and drug companies to plumbers and office suppliers,
stand to lose most of the $497 million that they are owed.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy could also bring the closing of more Allegheny
hospitals here _ the foundation shut one last year _ since by all
accounts Philadelphia has far more hospital capacity than it needs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if all the hospitals survive, jobs are in doubt. Allegheny
laid off 1,200 workers last fall _ aides, technicians, billing
clerks _ but many of the 16,000 who remain in its Philadelphia
operation have reason to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Few tears are shed here over the 25 percent pay cuts that
Allegheny imposed in May on a handful of superstar
physician-professors who had been lured aboard with $1 million
salaries to bring in patients. But the contracts and
Allegheny-owned practices of $150,000-a-year neighborhood doctors
are in limbo too.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are those the only issues.
</P>
<P>
   No one, for instance, appears to know what has become of much of
the more than $100 million in endowments and restricted gifts that
benefactors left to Philadelphia hospitals or affiliated medical
schools acquired by Allegheny.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has not challenged reports in The Philadelphia
Inquirer that some of that money was used to keep the hospitals
afloat instead of going to the purpose for which a given endowment
was created, like research or teaching. State Attorney General
Michael Fisher has stepped in to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts say the Allegheny failure is an example, however
extreme, of the kind of turmoil that could afflict the hospital
industry far more broadly as it struggles to cope with changes in
public policy and the continued expansion of managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Allegheny blames government policy changes in part for
its problems. For one thing, the Balanced Budget Act adopted last
year has reduced Medicare payments to hospitals. At the same time,
the federal government is encouraging elderly Medicare recipients
to join managed-care plans, which seek to save money in large part
by reducing hospital stays, while states including Pennsylvania are
ordering indigent Medicaid recipients into such plans.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the spread of managed care is leaving the typical
hospital with just 60 percent to 65 percent of its beds filled on
any given day.
</P>
<P>
   ``For managed care to work, you have to underutilize hospitals,
so it's a Catch-22,'' Dr. Clarence Martin said of the prospects
that had faced both the foundation and the physicians it employed.
(Until several months ago, he was one of them.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet Allegheny clearly contributed to its own demise, rapidly
assuming the enormous debt of troubled hospitals that it acquired
and then failing to generate enough revenue to bring that debt
under control.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was brought down by ``a combination of factors,''
including, ``quite candidly, what pundits have labeled a very
aggressive expansion strategy'' in the Philadelphia area, said its
spokesman, Thomas Chakurda.
</P>
<P>
   Allegheny's leading strategist was its chief executive, Sharif
Abdelhak, who, until the board deposed him in June, earned $1.2
million a year. Little has been seen of Abdelhak since his
departure, and repeated efforts to reach him for comment were
unavailing.
</P>
<P>
   Abdelhak, now 52, left his native Egypt at the age of 25, earned
a business degree at the University of Pittsburgh and worked his
way up from food-service management to chief executive at Allegheny
General Hospital in Pittsburgh, which became the flagship for his
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 he came up with an idea that was novel at the time but
has since been widely adopted: capturing patients by building a
tightly integrated network of hospitals, medical schools and
physicians' practices.
</P>
<P>
   He acquired the century-and-a-half-old Medical College of
Pennsylvania here in Philadelphia, later added the equally
venerable Hahnemann University and merged the two to create the
nation's largest private medical school, Allegheny University of
the Health Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Abdelhak's goal of providing managed care was achieved primarily
by contracting with HMOs. He expected to manage their members' care
for less than the HMOs could, and to pocket the difference. But the
costs were more than he had anticipated. Instead of getting
payments from this region's two big HMOs _ Independence Blue Cross
and Aetna U.S. Healthcare _ Allegheny now owes them tens of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of buying family-physician practices also failed.
Most of them wound up losing money, Allegheny says. One reason was
that doctors employed by the foundation often routed those in their
care to hospitals other than Allegheny's when they felt it best
suited the patients.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Being prodded not to send his patients to non-network hospitals
was hardly Clarence Martin's only problem with Allegheny.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 47, had a successful solo practice in the Chestnut
Hill-Mount Airy section of town, with 2,500 middle-class patients.
In early 1996, he says, Allegheny offered him a deal: Sell us your
practice and become an employee. We'll pay you $150,000 a year,
about what you have been earning, and provide for a bonus equal to
40 percent of office revenue that exceeds expenses. Martin will not
say what he sold for, but typically doctors received around
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then odd things happened. Allegheny dismissed his office
manager, who was vital to the rhythms of his practice, and assigned
her work to a regional, circuit-riding manager. The message on his
answering machine purged his name. ``Stenton Avenue Medical
Practice,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, after the end of the fiscal year, ``I looked at my
books and thought I should get a nice little bonus.'' His revenue
exceeded expenses by $24,000, so he calculated that he would get
$9,600.
</P>
<P>
   When the bonus did not arrive, he began calling. ``I got an
answer in early October,'' he said. ``They told me, `We looked at
everything, and you're not getting a bonus.'''
</P>
<P>
   He went back to his books and realized that Allegheny had been
charging him for visits of various consultants _ one to survey the
flow of patient traffic, others to survey his office exit signs and
his handicapped-parking spaces. He swears he was charged $180 by
one to change a light bulb.
</P>
<P>
   Martin negotiated a termination of his contract and by January
was on his own again.
</P>
<P>
   Under its bankruptcy plan, Allegheny would keep the hospitals in
Pittsburgh and put the entire Philadelphia operation up for sale.
Since the filing, two for-profit hospital-management companies _
Tenet Healthcare Corp. of Santa Barbara, Calif., and Vanguard
Health Systems of Nashville, Tenn. _ have begun bidding on the
spoils. But both are offering less than $500 million, well below
Allegheny's debt.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a year ago, with Allegheny's losses mounting,
Abdelhak visited Mayor Edward Rendell and stunned him with a
proposal to buy the city-owned six-square-block site of an
abandoned naval hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to build a brand-new medical campus for multiple
hundreds of millions of dollars,'' Rendell said. ``They had picked
out a developer. They were going to tear it down and build on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the deal never went through, ``it's an example,'' the
mayor said, ``of how Alice in Wonderland this all was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
