<SLUG> BC-EXP-ATTACK-SUDAN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DESTROYED FACTORY BECOMES STAGE FOR DEMONSTRATIONS  (EDS: This
article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed version of a
story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
(jw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHARTOUM, Sudan _ Not quite 24 hours after American cruise
missiles hit a factory in a decrepit industrial area of this
capital, clouds of white smoke and acrid smells still hovered over
the site Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen Sudanese soldiers lounged on the ground at the
entrance of the destroyed factory, which the Sudanese say made
pharmaceuticals, but which the Americans contend was a cover for
the making of chemical weapons. Deep puddles on the muddy ground
attested to the fire-fighting efforts after the strike.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic government, accused by the Clinton administration of
assisting in the terrorist activities of Osama bin Laden, used
these fiery remnants as a backdrop for a well organized
anti-American demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday prayers in the city's mosques, worshipers were
urged to attend rallies, including a particularly vocal one at the
plant, where leading figures accused the United States of being a
``terrorist'' state.
</P>
<P>
   At one rally, pictures of President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky
were on prominent display, a juxtaposition of a man and his
mistress that is interpreted in this very conservative society as
the ultimate mockery.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan al Turabi, speaker of Parliament and the ideological
power behind the ruling National Islamic Front, remained silent
Friday. American intelligence officials have called Turabi a close
comrade of bin Laden, whom the administration has accused of being
the mastermind bombings of two American embassies leaving hundreds
dead.
</P>
<P>
   But Gen. Omar Hassan al-Bashir, the Sudanese president, said he
would prove that the destroyed factory was not used for making
terrorist supplies. ``We have undeniable proof,'' he said.
International companies that had provided equipment for the plant
that opened two years ago would back him up, he added. The general
did not name them.
</P>
<P>
   But Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, said bin
Laden had given key financial help for the plant that was part of
the ``Sudanese military industrial complex.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
