<HEADER>
A6803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK22     08-21 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook: Assistant GM talks to L.A.
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dean Taylor, the first man John Schuerholz hired as
his chief assistant after coming to Atlanta in 1990, has
interviewed with the Los Angeles Dodgers for the general manager's
job.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 46, met with Dodgers president Dan Graziano, team
chairman of the board Pete O'Malley and their staff Thursday in Los
Angeles. Though the Dodgers are in the early stages of finding a
permanent replacement for interim GM Tommy Lasorda, Taylor is on a
short list of six executives that interest the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor to be considered for one of the best jobs in
baseball,'' Taylor said. ``I'm just going to leave it at that. The
interest came from them. They went through all the proper
channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Also under consideration are Florida GM Dave Dombrowski, ex-New
York Yankees GM Bob Watson, Cincinnati GM Jim Bowden, Baltimore
assistant GM (and former Montreal GM) Kevin Malone and New York
Mets assistant GM Omar Minaya. Dombrowski and Bowden are considered
front-runners. The Dodgers are hopeful of filling the job before
the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who worked under Schuerholz for 10 years in Kansas City
before working a season in the commissioner's office, has overseen
the administrative and operations side of the Braves front office
and has handled contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hard working and deserving and he's competent and
capable. He'll be a good general manager,'' Schuerholz said. ``Now,
it goes without saying he's been my right arm and leg and right
brain for 18 years. So I would miss him terribly, but I think he's
a very deserving guy and I hope he gets the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer returns
</P>
<P>
   The Braves activated right-handed reliever Russ Springer before
Friday's game and returned left-handed rookie Adam Butler to Class
AAA Richmond. Springer received a cortisone treatment Aug. 6 for a
bone spur in his right elbow, a problem the club was aware of when
it acquired him from Arizona for Alan Embree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it's brand new,'' Springer said, ``but it's
been as good as it's felt since I've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Springer will not throw his split-fingered pitch again
this season, due to the stress it causes. Instead, he will use his
change-up.
</P>
<P>
   Butler had thrown two scoreless innings (no hits, one walk,
three strikeouts) in Springer's place, a turnaround from his first
tour with the club when he allowed four runs in 1 1/3 innings in
early April.
</P>
<P>
   Re-deal
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies have returned right-handed pitcher David
Cortes, claiming the reliever had an injured shoulder when Atlanta
shipped him in the Greg Colbrunn trade. The Braves took him back in
exchange for a player to be named later. Though Cortes had spent
some time on the Richmond DL due to a sore shoulder in late spring,
the Rockies became concerned after seeing Cortes pitch six times.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Braves were at no obligation to take him back Cortes
is still held in high regard by Atlanta's scouting office, sore arm
or not. He had accumulated 44 saves in 92 minor league appearances
since signing him out of a try-out camp in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the Rockies) are wrong,'' said Schuerholz said. ``The
doctor looked at him and he was cleared to pitch. He threw the ball
95 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
