   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- NY-LIBRARY, 8-21 --
Accompanied by Elton John on a raspy radio, workers this week were
patching the creamy old marble floors and treating the bronze
frames of the new audiovisual carrels in the Main Reading Room of
the New York Public Library. The enormous chamber is to reopen Nov.
16 after a $15 million, 16-month renovation. (Jack Manning/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ROCHESTER HILLS, Mich. -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., AUG. 23 -- ABOUT-CARS-LEATHER-2, 8-21 -- At Eagle Ottawa in
Rochester Hills, ``Simulated buttocks'' test a hide's durability by
repeatedly pressing into a seat. Auto makers tripled their use of
leather from 1982 to 1992, according to a trade group, Leather
Industries of America. Demand doubled again in the next five years,
and the trend is accelerating. (Peter Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ROCHESTER HILLS, Mich. -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., AUG. 23 -- ABOUT-CARS-LEATHER-1, 8-21 -- Skins destined to be
seat coverings are stacked after embossing by Eagle Ottawa in
Rochester Hills. Americans had flings with vinyl, synthetics and
crushed velour. Now, snuggling into their cars and trucks, they
seem to have developed a leather fetish. (Peter Yates/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 23 -- CAR-SMART-EXOTIC-HIDES, 8-21 -- Mike Hemus, a prominent
restorer in Palo Alto, installing alligator seats in a 1938
Bugatti. While hide is now seen as a luxury, in the grand
automotive era of the late '20s and '30s, custom coach builders
availed themselves of a menagerie of hides, from anteater to zebra,
to distinguish their artworks from the hoi polloi. (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- IMBRUGLIA-SINGER, 8-21 --
Australian singer Natalie Imbruglia. There is something about
``Torn,'' the heartbreak hit that helped her album, ``Left of the
Middle,'' go platinum, that has led more than one critic to
forecast a continuing career for this 23-year-old. ``Imbruglia's
sad vocals reaching a true lonely girl splendor,'' reads Rob
Sheffield's review in Rolling Stone. (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LOCUST VALLEY, N.Y. -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 23 -- LOCUST-VALLEY-3, 8-21 -- Chloe Coleman, 11 months, poses
with her family in Locust Valley. The respect for life's little
niceties here would bring a smile to Emily Post. Strangers wave
from cars, everyone says ``please'' and ``thank you'' and friends
exchange exaggeratedly warm greetings at the country club, even
though they had lunch together just hours earlier. (Linda
Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LOCUST VALLEY, N.Y. -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 23 -- LOCUST-VALLEY-2, 8-21 -- Bowen Farrell takes a timeout
from a polo match. A young wave of bull market winners have
discovered Locust Valley, where what matters is chintz, polo and
anything that looks old. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LOCUST VALLEY, N.Y. -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 23 -- LOCUST-VALLEY-1, 8-21 -- Christina Coleman, left, and
Leah Ramirez in tennis uniform. This world of subtle uniforms and
unspoken codes is called Locust Valley, a slice of Gatsbyesque,
upper-class living, which seems preserved in aspic. Just 30 miles
from Manhattan, it is a land of French manor houses, private dirt
roads and small shops selling monogrammed wastebaskets. (Linda
Rosier/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ATLANTA -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
KALINSKY-FASHION, 8-21 -- Jeffrey Kalinsky, who built a fashion
mini-empire in an Atlanta mall, among the Pradas, Blahniks,
Clergeries and Maud Frizons. ``It is the opinion of most people in
the fashion industry that if it's not in New York or L.A., then it
doesn't exist,'' he says. ``We have a ton of people in Atlanta and
everywhere who have good taste and want nice things.'' (Alan S
Weiner/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
BRIDGE-TEACHER, 8-21 -- The Manhattan Bridge Club is being
bombarded these days with retirees seeking out Jeff Bayone, the
owner of the club and a master teacher of bridge who is much in
demand. ``Young people are attracted to bridge because it's fast
and it's social,'' he says. ``Chess is a two-hour struggle. In
bridge, each hand is about seven and a half minutes. You can play
40 games in a night, and every hand is a new adventure.'' (Barbara
Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 23 -- MARKET-BLACKS-2, 8-21 -- J. Fred Acree, 38, a mortgage
loan originator with a minority-owned firm, at a property under
construction. After attending college, Acree spent years putting
all his spare cash into a savings account, waiting until just a few
years ago to funnel some of the money into stocks. (Richard
Puchyr/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHICAGO -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
MARKET-BLACKS-1, 8-21 -- ``Our mission is to make the stock market
a subject of dinner conversation in every black home in America,''
says Mellody Hobson, a senior vice president at Ariel Capital
Management of Chicago, where John Rogers Jr., is president. Today,
57 percent of black households with annual incomes of more than
$50,000 have money in the stock market, according to a survey
conducted by Yankelovich Partners Inc. for Ariel. (Angel Franco/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
MUTFUND-COTNER, 8-21 -- C. Beth Cotner, lead manager of Putnam
Investors, a large-capitalization growth fund, invests by the
numbers. To determine whether to buy a stock, she and her
co-managers use a quantitative screening system that takes into
account factors like potential earnings surprises, dividend yields
and sales-to-price valuations. (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
MOTHERS-LIVES, 8-21 -- For a recent meeting, the books sampled by
this Brooklyn women's book group explores the balancing of
motherhood and work. At the request of Money and Business, each of
the eight women had read one of four recent books about the
quandary of working mothers as a jumping-off point for discussion
of their own lives. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN BARTOLO COYOTEPEC, Mexico -- Aug. 21, 1998 --
MEXICO-POTTERY-2-COX, 8-21 -- Black pottery, some of which have
been scored with intricate patterns, for sale at the Oaxaca city
market. The classic pieces of black pottery are orbs with fluted
edges, and they range from a few inches to nearly two feet tall.
San Bartolo Coyotepec which is the home of black pottery, is seven
miles south of the colonial city of Oaxaca. (Sergio Dorantes/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SAN BARTOLO COYOTEPEC, Mexico -- Aug. 21, 1998 --
MEXICO-POTTERY-1COX, 8-2 -- Nieto Real works on a black pottery
vessel in his studio. Using ancient methods and the same clay as
his ancestors, he and other potters in this community spin vessels.
The dull gray clay is harvested from the hills and turns black when
fired. ``This is our culture,'' Nieto Real says. (Sergio
Dorantes/Cox News Service)
</P>
