<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6806 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-COOPER-TEX     08-21 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-COOPER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WORLD OF WOMEN'S HOOPS, WNBA'S COOPER UNEQUALED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask Cynthia Cooper about talk of her being the best player in
women's basketball, and she might shy away from such discussions
for fear of it becoming a bad omen.
</P>
<P>
   But others who have seen the Houston Comets' guard light up the
basket are not so indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that right now Cooper's the best player in
the country,'' longtime University of Texas coach Jody Conradt
said. ``I haven't seen all of the other players in the world, but
I'd put her up against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Yolanda Griffith and Long Beach's Natalie Williams are
the top players in the American Basketball League. Tennessee's
Chamique Holdsclaw and Tamika Catchings are college basketball's
most prolific players. And Russia's Elana Baranova _ she also plays
for the Women's NBA's Utah Starzz _ was chosen the most valuable
player of last spring's World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   The world's other top players are Lisa Leslie of the WNBA's Los
Angeles Sparks, Teresa Edwards and Dawn Staley of the ABL's
Philadelphia Rage, Houston's Sheryl Swoopes, and Jennifer Gillom of
the WNBA's Phoenix Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cooper is the person many followers of women's
basketball say is the game's most distinguished player. She hopes
to drive home that point this afternoon against the Charlotte Sting
as the Comets open defense of their WNBA title when they play Game
1 of their best-of-three series at 3 p.m. in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the Comets' success will hinge on how Cooper performs
on the playoff stage. And if Cooper's past performances are any
indication, the Comets will be crowned WNBA champions again
sometimes late next week.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who averages 22.7 points, 4.4 assists and 3.7 rebounds,
has a knack for taking over games the way Chicago Bulls superstar
Michael Jordan does. She plays with a flair for the dramatics, and
has the ability to take it to the basket, or pull up and drop in a
feathery jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at Michael Jordan and I see all of the things that he
brings to the Chicago Bulls,'' Comets point guard Kim Perrot said.
``He's an all-around player, and he enjoys the game. Cynthia is
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she has taken the WNBA to another level, especially
without them recognizing her as a marquee player.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Cooper won the WNBA's MVP award, and she's the leading
candidate to win it again this year after winning the scoring title
for the second consecutive season and guiding the Comets to a
Bulls-like 27-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA's second-best player is Gillom, who finished second in
scoring behind Cooper with 20.8 points per game. Comets coach Van
Chancellor coached Gillom at the University of Mississippi, and
added that ``it's just a landslide'' as to who is the WNBA's best
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jennifer Gillom is a great player, and there are a lot
of great players out there,'' Chancellor said. ``But not everybody
can do what (Cooper) does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cynthia can score, but she's as good as I've ever seen at
getting other players a shot and getting them easy baskets. What
separates Cynthia Cooper from a lot of players is the fact that she
can create so many opportunities for other players.''
</P>
<P>
   Even David Letterman confirmed Cooper's stature in the game when
she made an appearance on ``The Late Show With David Letterman''
last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're great for the world of basketball,'' Letterman told
Cooper. ``You're great for the world in general.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Gillom, other players have also been superb in
handling their basketball craft. Tracey Williams, the ABL vice
president for player personnel and basketball operations, told
Chicago Condors coach Jim Cleamons that the 6-4 Griffith is
``Scottie Pippen with a dress'' because of her versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told coach Cleamons that, he looked at me really
funny,'' Williams continued. ``But Griffith's definitely got big
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Griffith finished first in the ABL in steals (3.1),
second in rebounds (11.2), second in blocks (1.3) and fourth in
scoring (18.8). She wound up second in the league's MVP race behind
Natalie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future of women's pro basketball, Conradt believes
that marquee college players such as Holdsclaw and Catchings will
hold the sport together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Holdsclaw has the potential to be another Cynthia
Cooper type of player,'' Conradt said. ``You're impressed with her,
because she blends in with her team. But when it gets down to the
critical parts of the game, she always steps it up.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, no one steps it up better than Cooper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
