<P>
   (NYT11) LOCUST VALLEY, N.Y. -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 23 -- LOCUST-VALLEY-3, 8-21 -- Chloe Coleman, 11 months, poses
with her family in Locust Valley. The respect for life's little
niceties here would bring a smile to Emily Post. Strangers wave
from cars, everyone says ``please'' and ``thank you'' and friends
exchange exaggeratedly warm greetings at the country club, even
though they had lunch together just hours earlier. (Linda
Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LOCUST VALLEY, N.Y. -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 23 -- LOCUST-VALLEY-2, 8-21 -- Bowen Farrell takes a timeout
from a polo match. A young wave of bull market winners have
discovered Locust Valley, where what matters is chintz, polo and
anything that looks old. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LOCUST VALLEY, N.Y. -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 23 -- LOCUST-VALLEY-1, 8-21 -- Christina Coleman, left, and
Leah Ramirez in tennis uniform. This world of subtle uniforms and
unspoken codes is called Locust Valley, a slice of Gatsbyesque,
upper-class living, which seems preserved in aspic. Just 30 miles
from Manhattan, it is a land of French manor houses, private dirt
roads and small shops selling monogrammed wastebaskets. (Linda
Rosier/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ATLANTA -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
KALINSKY-FASHION, 8-21 -- Jeffrey Kalinsky, who built a fashion
mini-empire in an Atlanta mall, among the Pradas, Blahniks,
Clergeries and Maud Frizons. ``It is the opinion of most people in
the fashion industry that if it's not in New York or L.A., then it
doesn't exist,'' he says. ``We have a ton of people in Atlanta and
everywhere who have good taste and want nice things.'' (Alan S
Weiner/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Aug. 21, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
BRIDGE-TEACHER, 8-21 -- The Manhattan Bridge Club is being
bombarded these days with retirees seeking out Jeff Bayone, the
owner of the club and a master teacher of bridge who is much in
demand. ``Young people are attracted to bridge because it's fast
and it's social,'' he says. ``Chess is a two-hour struggle. In
bridge, each hand is about seven and a half minutes. You can play
40 games in a night, and every hand is a new adventure.'' (Barbara
Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
