<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-DAMAGE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE SAYS MISSILE ATTACK WAS SUCCESSFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: SUBS for smoothing, new material throughout.)   (See also: ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-RECAP,
ATTACK-ISLAM, ATTACK-RUSSIA-REACT, ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT,
ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT, ATTACK-KENYA, ATTACK-PAKISTAN, ATTACK-SUDAN.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration made measured claims of
success for the cruise-missile attacks in the Sudan and Afghanistan
on Thursday, saying the attack on a mountain redoubt in Afghanistan
would disrupt training and, possibly, future attacks by terrorists
sponsored by Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Cloudy weather and haze obscured satellite photographs of what
the administration has described as a sprawling terrorist training
camp near Afghanistan's border with Pakistan, hampering efforts to
learn the extent of the damage done when missiles fired from four
Navy warships and one submarine pummeled the area.
</P>
<P>
   But senior administration officials said preliminary
assessments, based in part on sources other than spy satellites,
indicated that the missiles destroyed or damaged many of the
buildings spread throughout the remote complex about 90 miles south
of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of bin Laden sought to play down the extent of the
damage but spoke of 20 or more deaths. They said the Saudi-born
millionaire was still alive and ready to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   But Secretary of Defense William Cohen said the strike was
``successful in the sense that we destroyed a number of
facilities'' at the camp, known as Zhawar Kili Al-Badr. At the
White House, the president's national security adviser, Sandy
Berger, said, ``The attacks have significantly disrupted the
capability to use these camps as terrorist training facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials, while circumspect in their choice of
words, left open the possibility that the United States would
strike bin Laden's network again if necessary. ``We have
contingency plans that we are developing, and there may be more in
the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the administration opened a new front in its
fight against bin Laden, the Saudi exile whom the United States has
accused of sponsoring terrorist attacks, including the bombings of
the American Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania two weeks ago Friday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton signed an executive order that, effective
Friday, placed bin Laden on the Treasury Department's list of
terrorists and their sponsors, clearing the way for officials to
identify and seize any of bin Laden's financial assets in the
United States, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, in this context, money matters,'' Berger said,
suggesting that the action could undercut bin Laden's sponsorship
of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was not immediately clear whether bin Laden, whose
fortune is estimated between $200 million and $300 million, has any
assets in the United States. It was also unclear why bin Laden had
not been placed on the department's list earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO diplomat said Friday that the administration had begun
asking allies in Europe to help in the effort to freeze bin Laden's
assets and those of terrorist groups associated with him.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the strikes on Thursday nor this latest step appeared to
have tempered bin Laden, who has vowed to wage war against the
United States. A man claiming to be a spokesman for bin Laden told
the editor of an Arabic newspaper in London, al-Quds al-Arabi, that
bin Laden had survived the missile attack and was vowing to avenge
them with attacks on American targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle has not yet started,'' the editor, Abdel-Bari
Atwan, quoted the spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Washington to return to his vacation in Martha's
Vineyard on Friday night, Clinton met with his national security
advisers for about an hour and telephoned Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu of Israel and Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan.
Pakistan has vigorously protested the attack, which sent dozens of
cruise missiles soaring over its territory.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's senior aides also sought to rally support for the
attacks on Capitol Hill, where some critics on Thursday had
questioned the strikes, or at least their timing, given the furor
over Clinton's admission on Monday night that he had had an
intimate relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, joined by Gen.
Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, met in a
classified briefing with a dozen Republican and Democratic
lawmakers Friday afternoon. The lawmakers emerged sounding
persuaded by the administration's justification for the strikes,
citing what some called ``irrefutable evidence'' from satellite
photographs, intercepts of telephone conversations and statements
by a suspect in the embassy bombings who is now being held in
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they shared with us made it crystal clear that terrorism
had escalated against us,'' Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers said they found persuasive the information
gleaned from the suspect who has begun to cooperate with the
authorities, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh. When he was arrested by the
Pakistani authorities on Aug. 7, the day of the embassy bombings,
he said that he was a follower of bin Laden's. Odeh also told them
he helped to build the Nairobi bomb, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton administration officials declined to make public
specific evidence that led to such swift and surprising attacks on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the strikes, which involved roughly 75 cruise
missiles fired from undisclosed positions in the Arabian and Red
seas, the administration warned that retaliatory attacks against
American targets were a grave possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI reiterated a security alert first issued in the hours
after Thursday's strikes, and public buildings, airports and
military bases in the United States and abroad beefed up security.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the risks, the administration defended the strikes,
citing the nation's right, as defined in the U.N. charter, to
defend itself. Berger said the administration considered the camp
outside the remote Afghan town of Khost ``to be a military
target.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, Thomas Pickering, the undersecretary of
state for political affairs, declared that the United States could
not sit idly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not simply batten down the hatches and wait for the
next attack to hit us,'' he said. ``We had to act decisively. We do
not expect that these strikes will in themselves end the threat,
but they are important because they clearly show that we are in
this for the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Abroad, the strikes generated official denunciations and street
protests in the Sudan and Afghanistan. There were also angry
demonstrations in Pakistan. In the Afghan capital, Kabul, protests
converged on the U.S. Embassy. In Kabul, two U.N. workers were shot
in separate attacks that appeared to be related to anger over the
American strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's reticence to confirm publicly even the most
fundamental details of the strikes _ including the names of the
Navy ships involved or even the exact number of missiles fired _
compounded the uncertainty that prevailed Friday, as did Cohen's
vague assertions that additional American attacks could be in the
offing.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's strike in the Sudan seemed to have accomplished its
mission. Stark television images confirmed that the strike heavily
damaged a factory that officials described as a manufacturer of
building blocks for chemical weapons. Berger declared it
``functionally destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudan's state-run television said 10 people had been injured,
but none, evidently, were killed. Sudan's president, Omar Hassan
al-Bashir, was quoted by Reuters as saying the factory, Al Shifa
Pharmaceutical Industries Co., was a benign commercial venture that
produced half the nation's medicines.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the strike in Afghanistan was less clear. In
Kabul, the Taliban faction that rules the country announced that 21
people had died in the attack on the base, while 30 others were
injured, but the spokesman for bin Laden put the dead at 28 in his
remarks to the editor of Al-Quds Al-Arabi. He said the dead
included six Arab militants, 15 Pakistanis and seven Afghans.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Washington, officials said they had no way of knowing
who died, and the Pentagon received conflicting, unverifiable
intelligence reports. Some said bin Laden was dead; others said he
was alive, a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States timed the attack to what they believed to be a
gathering of terrorists at the camp, but Cohen saif Friday that it
was not clear that the assembly had in fact taken place.
Regardless, Cohen said the attack was aimed less at individuals
than at the barracks and ammunition stockpiles spread over the
complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Striking the facilities in themselves is a worthy goal,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With only one chance a day for spy satellites to photograph the
area, a full assessment will take at least another day, perhaps
longer, depending on the weather. There were early indications that
while some missiles hit their targets, others missed entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the facilities have been destroyed completely,'' a
senior Pentagon official said. ``Some have been damaged heavily.
Some have been damaged lightly. And some have been missed
entirely.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
