<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6823 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-BAILOUT-HNS &LR;      08-21 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BAILOUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAILOUT FIGHT MAY BE DEFINING CRISIS OF ZEDILLO ADMINISTRATION 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The video is both damning and enlightening, an
indictment of politics as usual in Mexico and an advertisement for
the benefits of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   As the tape begins, a cartoon figure of an impoverished Mexican
Everyman shuffles along until he is assaulted by an elegantly
attired thief in top hat and tails. The rich again, Mexico's bane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know that very soon they will want to pay for their
mistakes with your money?'' a disparaging voice asks while the
video parades images of fugitive bankers, discredited politicians
and long-suffering poor.
</P>
<P>
   Those mistakes, the video's voice says, include more than $65
billion in bad loans made by Mexican banks, which have been assumed
over the past three years by a government agency called Fobaproa.
The amount already equals about a sixth of Mexico's annual economic
output.
</P>
<P>
   The leftist Democratic Revolution Party has been distributing
the video as part of an all-out drive to frustrate President
Ernesto Zedillo's attempt to pass the check for the bank bailout
along to Mexican taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the Fobaproa affair might have proved scarcely an
embarrassment for a political and financial system riddled with
cronyism and corruption. But now that the political opposition
controls Mexico's Congress, the fight over the bailout looms as
perhaps the defining crisis of Zedillo's 44-month-old
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The affair was spawned by the 1994 peso devaluation and
subsequent economic crisis. As some banks folded and others were
bought by new investors, including U.S. and foreign financial
firms, the Fobaproa agency paid for the institutions' bad loans
with 10-year bonds. Last April, Zedillo asked Congress to approve
legislation that would have paid the bad bank debt with the
people's purse, forcing Mexico's poor majority to cover the losses
of some of its wealthiest moguls.
</P>
<P>
   The debate heated up amid a worsening financial squeeze caused
by a sharp drop in oil prices. The Zedillo government made deep
cuts in social spending for housing, hospitals, schools and other
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The money at stake is enough to build 4.5 million houses for the
poor, the opposition party video claims. It's enough to fund the
budgets of Oaxaca or Sonora states for a century. It's enough, the
video says, to be enraged about.
</P>
<P>
   Financial scandals are nothing new in Mexico. And when both the
Congress and the Mexican press were tools of the president and the
ruling party, such a cozy bailout would have been easy to pull off
in the shadows. But this time the Congress _ controlled by
opposition parties since July 1997's historic midterm elections _
refused to play along with the government's bailout plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Revolution Party, which has spent a decade
fighting what it calls the government's bias toward the rich,
immediately balked. The pro-business National Action Party waffled
and then also refused to cooperate with the president. Even members
of Zedillo's own Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, have
threatened to abandon the president on Fobaproa.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the media is testing its growing independence
from government control by pouring on information about, and sharp
criticism of, Zedillo's plans for Fobaproa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of information that is coming out is remarkable,''
says Sergio Aguayo, a political scientist and leading democracy
advocate. ``The constant flow (of information) coming out of the
printed media is defining the debate. At least now we have
information. That was not the case in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, the administration and other Fobaproa backers have
launched an advertising blitz on radio and television, arguing that
a bailout actually would protect the savings of ordinary Mexicans.
A government book explaining the program has hit the streets, but
it is priced above the daily wage of most Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   For all the noise, the fight over Fobaproa testifies to the
promise that democracy offers Mexico, Aguayo and other analysts
say.
</P>
<P>
   Stymied in its effort to get its Fobaproa plan through Congress,
the Zedillo administration is now working on a compromise proposal.
National Action's leaders issued a six-point plan that would cut
half the public's debt over the next 10 years, and the Democratic
Revolution Party has called a nationwide referendum on the matter
for Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The bailout controversy is but one of a handful of scandals
buffeting Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   The fugitive former head of Aeromexico, an airline once
controlled by the government, has alleged in testimony published
this week that top members of Zedillo's Cabinet schemed to funnel
some $8 million in company money to the president's 1994 election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, IBM agreed to a multimillion-dollar settlement with
Mexico City's new opposition-controlled government. The deal
settles a fraud complaint surrounding the purchase of what the city
administration argued was a shoddy computer system put in by a
former ruling-party administration.
</P>
<P>
   Smelling blood, the Democratic Revolution Party has gone for the
jugulars of both Zedillo and the PRI, which has controlled Mexico's
national politics for nearly seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition party's president, Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador,
is travelling the country with the anti-Fobaproa video to drum up
support against any bailout.
</P>
<P>
   The National Action Party has been less vocal but equally
uncooperative. National Action has gone along with Zedillo on
economic and financial policies in the past. Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't turn away from this Fobaproa matter,'' National
Action President Felipe Calderon told reporters earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be resolved. It's necessary to avoid tolerating
impunity,'' he said, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``No act against the national interest should go unpunished.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
