<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6835 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS     08-21 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cracks are showing &QL; 
in Comets' veneer
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN the NBA added a women's auxiliary last year, everybody was
supposed to have been created equal. But effort, intelligence and
luck never will be dispensed equally in any competitive human
endeavor, so the WNBA's haves and have-nots wasted no time in
identifying themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets organization worked harder, hired better, drafted
smarter and got more breaks than any of the franchises that chose
to participate in this baby first step toward gender equality on
the play-for-pay stage. As a result, when Leslie Alexander
purchased the Comets, he wound up with an entire solar system.
</P>
<P>
   They had the requisite star at their center in Cynthia Cooper
plus a full complement of planets to orbit her. The smallest and
least-known among them, Kim Perrot, frequently would reflect the
most light. With Perrot dishing and Cooper swishing, the first
champions of the ``We got next'' league called Houston home.
</P>
<P>
   On a hot August afternoon in a sold-out Summit, Clutch City
became Coop City.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for an encore, the Comets raised the bar in 1998, winning
a remarkable 27 of 30 games and setting a standard of excellence
against which all future women's pro basketball teams will have to
measure themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But if it looked easy
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't,'' coach Van Chancellor said. ``And now comes the
hard part.''
</P>
<P>
   Bull's eye on champs
</P>
<P>
   Irrefutable evidence that coaches, whatever the sex of their
hired jocks, are chronic doomsayers? Perhaps. Alas, the truth is
the Comets wander into Charlotte's web today in a spot of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor frets over the ``law of averages'' _ the Comets are
9-1 against the Sting _ but that's probably the lesser of their
worries, considering their opponent's lackluster performance in
recent weeks and the fact they're playing a best-of-three series,
not a sudden-death knockout round. They can survive a wake-up
mess-up, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern are disturbing signs that, quite the opposite
of Stella, the Comets have lost their groove. And because of it,
they also might have lost their floor leader/defensive conscience
Perrot, who suffered a severe ankle sprain late in the final game
when she should have long since been on the bench cooling down,
saving her energy for this second season's second season.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor, understandably, didn't want to enter the playoffs
having been beaten by a 12-18 Los Angeles team at Compaq Center,
but a lethargic effort had the Comets in a bind. So Perrot, whom he
used to call ``Mosquito,'' was doing her usual buzzing about when
an awkward collision with Octavia Blue with less than seven minutes
to go left her exactly that _ blue.
</P>
<P>
   By appearances, the injury appeared career-threatening. Someone
compared it to watching Joe Theismann's leg break in midshin on
Monday Night Football. Fortunately, it wasn't remotely that
serious, but Perrot is in a lot of pain, and she admits she doesn't
``do pain very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Although, knowing Perrot, the most self-made Comet, she'll
attempt to play today. But she needs every step of quickness she
has to be the player that binds the others together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we try to do defensively starts with Kim,''
Chancellor says. ``She's got to be able to run and jump normally,
or it will be tough on us. She's about the best defensive player in
women's basketball. You'd hate to lose all that pressure that she
puts on the other guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Team chemistry test
</P>
<P>
   And if any frustration sets in, you wonder if the Comets will
come apart. As you know, they haven't been the happiest of
families, and the bad chemistry that blew up in their faces several
weeks ago _ much to Chancellor's amazement _ no doubt lingers
beneath the surface. Such issues rarely can be talked through,
despite public lip service to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, championships tend to be more easily won than
defended, and the Comets are about to put said maxim to the test.
Everything about last year was fairy-tale stuff, all warm and fuzzy
and brand spanking new. Things went smoother than the Tupelo honey
in Chancellor's Ole Miss accent.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by their record, which is about as good as any pro team
ever produced, the Comets appear to be a team of sisters living the
Brothers Grimm existence. With a healthy Perrot, they would be
prohibitive favorites to defend their title, some internal
bickering notwithstanding. Hey, the Bulls didn't all love each
other, either.
</P>
<P>
   But without Perrot? The court is a lot more level. It's amazing
how valuable the 5-5 dervish has become when you consider that
before the Comets' tryout camp last year, Chancellor had her rated
66th among his prospects _ who were only 65 in number.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he calls Perrot's injury ``a severe blow,'' and it is. The
Comets remain good, but suddenly they aren't lucky. Guess something
had to give.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
