<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0486 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6836 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-SUDAN-1STLD-WR     08-21 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-SUDAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESTROYED FACTORY BECOMES STAGE FOR DEMONSTRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Includes detail about factory, moves up casualties and adds
tour by foreign diplomats.)  (See also: ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-DAMAGE,
ATTACK-ISLAM, ATTACK-RECAP, ATTACK-RUSSIA-REACT,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT, ATTACK-KENYA,
ATTACK-PAKISTAN.) 
(jw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHARTOUM, the Sudan _ Not quite 24 hours after American cruise
missiles hit a factory in a decrepit industrial area of this
capital, clouds of white smoke and acrid smells still hovered over
the site Friday night. Deep puddles of water on muddy ground
attested to the firefighting efforts after the strike.
</P>
<P>
   The factory, which is about a half-mile square, was destroyed in
the attack, though surrounding areas went unscathed. There were no
known deaths at the plant, which was hit at night, when it was
closed, but local reports said 10 people were hospitalized, four of
them in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's Islamic government invited foreign diplomats to
tour the ruins Friday. Afterward, many remained puzzled, saying it
was not clear whether the plant, as Washington asserts, made
precursors for nerve gas or whether it was purely a medical
manufacturing site, as the Sudan contends.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday prayers in the city's mosques, worshipers were
urged to attend frenzied rallies, where leading figures of the
government accused the United States of being a terrorist state,
and where the American flag was torn, burned and trampled into the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   At one rally, pictures of President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky
were on prominent display, a juxtaposition of a man and his
mistress that is interpreted in this very conservative society as
the ultimate mockery.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Mustafa Osman Ismail said Sudan would remain a
``tomb for its enemies, whatever this costs us in human lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most important Sudanese leader, Hassan al-Turabi, who is
the speaker of Parliament and the ideological power behind the
governing National Islamic Front, remained silent.
</P>
<P>
   American intelligence officials have called Turabi a close
comrade of Osama bin Laden, whom the administration has accused of
being the mastermind of the bombings of two American embassies in
East Africa that left hundreds dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration accuses the Sudanese government of
assisting bin Laden in terrorist activities. The Sudan rejects the
charge and has asked for an urgent meeting of the United Nations
Security Council to discuss the missile strike.
</P>
<P>
   Turabi has always been considered a Rasputin by Westerners, a
mysterious figure of the fundamentalist government that took power
in a military coup in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Hassan al-Bashir, the army general who is the Sudanese
president, made up for Turabi's silence by furiously waving a long
stick as he addressed a raucous crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Bashir said he would prove that the factory hit by the American
missiles was not a cover for making the precursors of nerve gas as
Washington charged. ``We have undeniable proof'' that the plant was
only used for pharmaceutical products like children's and
antimalarial medicines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said international companies that had provided equipment for
the plant, which opened two years ago, would back him up. He did
not name them.
</P>
<P>
   In describing the reasons for destroying the plant, Sandy
Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, said that bin Laden
had given key financial help for the plant, which was part of the
``Sudanese military-industrial complex.'' Bin Laden lived in the
Sudan from 1994 to 1996, a period when Washington says he invited
international terrorists to train at camps here.
</P>
<P>
   He was forced to leave in 1996, when the government decided that
he was too much of an embarrassment and his presence too costly.
After telling bin Laden to leave, the government hoped to win some
concessions from the Clinton administration, including economic
aid, but failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their case that the plant was a benign operation,
government officials said that it was owned by a Sudanese
businessman, Salah Idrisse, who is also a citizen of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the factory, where most of the smoke was still
billowing, was off-limits to reporters Friday, and it was
impossible to tell what was made there. In the rubble at the front
of the compound, there were wrappers from a veterinary solution
made at the plant and leaflets on how to take Profenil, a trade
name for ibuprofen, a widely used pain reliever. Trays of small
empty brown bottles, apparently used for medicine, were scattered
about on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Hussein, 23, a builder who lives about a mile from the
plant, said he had seen bright lights and then heard the swoosh of
missiles during the attack. At first, he said, he thought the
nearby power station had been struck. Then he thought a plane had
crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he said, it occurred to him that John Garang, the leader
of a southern rebel group that has been waging a civil war for more
than a decade, had finally struck the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The plant's managing director, Sayed Hamed, said the factory
employed 360 workers. He said the enterprise made 30 kinds of drugs
for humans and 23 kinds of veterinary medicines.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital spokesman said that 10 people wounded from the strike
were admitted to the wards. Four of them were in critical
condition, he said. The plant does not operate at night, and there
were apparently few workers around during the attack.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Sudanese opposition political parties based in
Cairo, Faruq Ahmed Adam, said he agreed with Washington that the
plant was a cover for the manufacture of chemical weapons. He said
another factory, in the suburb of Kafouri, also made chemical
weapons. He added that Sudanese security forces were investors in
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Washington and the Sudanese government have
gone from bad to worse in the nine years of fundamentalist rule.
But even so, ordinary people seemed to be bewildered why American
should aim cruise missiles here.
</P>
<P>
   Some said they were skeptical that the pharmaceutical plant was
a cover for preparing chemical warfare agents. ``Most people here,
even those who are anti-government, do not believe this particular
factory was making chemical weapons,'' one man said.
</P>
<P>
   But another longtime opposition supporter, a lawyer, said he
believed that the Americans knew what they were doing. ``Bin Laden
has never built a factory for medicines in his life,'' said the
lawyer. ``He's only interested in killing and terrorism.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
