r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     08-21 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FALL A FEW ACES SHY OF YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memo: Tom Hicks
</P>
<P>
   Owner, Texas Rangers
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 22, 1998
</P>
<P>
   Tom:
</P>
<P>
   Saw your team of the future last night at The Ballpark in
Arlington. Funny thing: The guys were wearing navy blue and gray
with a white NY on the cap.
</P>
<P>
   Just kidding. Those were the Yankees, of course _ the team the
Rangers hope to be when they grow up.
</P>
<P>
   The thought occurred during batting practice _ while attendants
were stocking the owners' bunker beneath the stands next to the
Rangers' dugout with pheasant under glass and an assortment of fine
imported wines for your pregame nibbling pleasure _ that there
really isn't all that much difference between George's team and
yours.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting those 25 games in the win column, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   But there is this one thing.
</P>
<P>
   Come closer, I don't want to spread this around.
</P>
<P>
   Keep this under your hat, but a little investigative journalism
has uncovered some highly interesting numbers and one indisputable
fact: You don't have a single starter on your team who could crack
the Yankees' rotation. Not one who could bump David Wells, Hideki
Irabu, Andy Pettite, Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez or David Cone
from a single start.
</P>
<P>
   Check that. You might not have a starter on your team who could
crack the Yankees' ``top six,'' considering talented Ramiro Mendoza
is New York's sixth starter.
</P>
<P>
   This is not said to denigrate the fine seasons Rick Helling and
Aaron Sele have put together or how well Esteban Loaiza has pitched
since he was obtained from the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   But facts are facts.
</P>
<P>
   My mission last night was to discover what it is that spurred
this Yankees team to be this good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best team I ever saw?'' Yankees coach Don Zimmer said, sitting
in the visitors' dugout before last night's game. He shakes his
head. ``Best record I ever saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep asking me if this team is as good as the '55
Dodgers, or the '55 Yankees or The Big Red Machine. My answer
hasn't changed. I don't compare teams. But a lot of goofy things
have happened this year. We've won games every way you can think
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cerone, the former Yankees catcher who works for Fox out of
Baltimore, said this group of players came together as a team after
the big bench-clearing brawl with the Orioles in May.
</P>
<P>
   Others talk about team chemistry, how part-time players like
Darryl Strawberry, Tim Raines and Chad Curtis have accepted their
roles, how everybody in the lineup contributes, how everyone wants
to win.
</P>
<P>
   All well and good, but like Mr. Robinson said to Benjamin in
``The Graduate,'' I've got one word for you, Tom, and it ain't
plastics:
</P>
<P>
   Pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single night,'' said your very own manager, Johnny
Oates, ``they have outstanding starting pitching. There are no 7.00
earned-run averages coming out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they're barely half that. At game time last night,
Andy Pettite had the worst ERA among the Yanks' six starters at
3.73. The Rangers' best was Loaiza's at 3.79 and that covers just
six starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks' team ERA was 3.60, the Rangers' 5.07.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had given up 478 runs, the Rangers 688, a 210-run
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Get the picture?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret,'' Oates said, ``It's right there in the
numbers. Talent-wise, they outclass everybody else totally.''
</P>
<P>
   Way I see it, you've got two problems to solve.
</P>
<P>
   How do you beat the Yankees in a short series (like in the
playoffs)?
</P>
<P>
   How do you get to be more like them?
</P>
<P>
   There's no easy answer to either question.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to beat them over a 162-game schedule, thank
goodness,'' Oates said. ``You just can't do that. But you can beat
them in a short series if you pitch well and play well. You don't
have to play a perfect game, but you can't give them extra outs
because they're sure not going to give you any with their pitching
and defense.''
</P>
<P>
   I know, it can be discouraging competing against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Example: Your general manager, Doug Melvin, was talking about
off-season possibilities the other day and someone suggested the
Yankees might sign Mike Piazza. And let Bernie Williams go, Melvin
wondered?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the writer suggested, maybe they'll just sign them all.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin frowned. ``If they sign everybody,'' he said, ``I think
I'll just quit.''
</P>
<P>
   He was just kidding. I think.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, Tommy boy, if you really wanted to, if you really set
your mind to it, you could out-George ol' Steinbrenner any day of
the week and twice on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to prove it any time you're ready.
</P>
<P>
   And keep the P-word word close to your heart:
</P>
<P>
   Pitching.
</P>
<P>
   It's the difference between the Yankees and everybody else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
