<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-APPEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYER APPEALS RULING ON PRIVILEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID STOUT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Warning of a constitutional crisis, a lawyer for
President Clinton asked the Supreme Court on Friday to overturn a
lower court ruling that some of the president's legal advisers must
testify in the investigation of Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   If such compelled testimony continues, Clinton's lawyer said,
the consequences could be terrible ``both for the institution of
the presidency and for the nation it serves.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Neil Eggleston, asked the High Court to reverse the
July 27 ruling by the District of Columbia U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals that a blanket attorney-client privilege could not prevent
some government lawyers from being called to give evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist refused on Aug. 4 to block that
ruling from taking effect, forcing Eggleston to go to the full
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand now upon the brink of the most serious confrontation
between branches of government contemplated in our constitutional
order,'' Eggleston said in his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Some White House lawyers have been subpoenaed by the Whitewater
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, who is investigating whether
the president tried illegally to cover up his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Since Starr began looking into Clinton's relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky, various White House lawyers and other aides have sought
to avoid giving testimony, either on the grounds of executive
privilege or attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Although the president's conversations with the lawyers retained
to defend him remain protected, as they would be for any defendant,
the appeals court held, in effect, that a lawyer who happens to be
a government employee and White House adviser is not automatically
shielded from having to give testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Since Rehnquist's refusal to intervene, at least two more White
House lawyers, Cheryl Mills and Lanny Breuer, have gone before the
grand jury. But Eggleston still has good reason to seek a reversal
of the appellate decision.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Bruce Lindsey, who is acknowledged as one of
Clinton's closest confidants and has been at the center of the
president's battle over attorney-client privilege, is due to be
questioned again. Although Lindsey has testified several times
before the grand jury, he has declined to answer certain questions
because the administration says those areas should be protected.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Clinton admitted that he had an improper
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, his troubles are not over. Starr is
still pursuing his investigation into possible presidential
criminality. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
