</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-KONG-MEDIA-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG TALK RADIO HOST RECOVERING FROM BRUTAL ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ On any given morning here, you could turn on the
radio and hear Albert Cheng lay into Beijing, the Hong Kong
government, the Hang Seng stock index, politicians, property
tycoons, lawyers, newspaper editors _ in short, anything that
matters in this former British colony.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, two unidentified men attacked Cheng with
carving knives as he arrived at work, inflicting deep slashing
wounds on his arms, back and right leg that required six hours of
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng will survive. But in a city where talk radio has become a
vital form of public expression, the brutal assault on its most
famous practitioner has left people reeling. Doctors said Cheng may
no longer be able to wield chopsticks. Listeners fear he may no
longer wield his sharp tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as a threat to people who want to be outspoken,''
said Emily Lau, a member of the Legislative Council and herself a
vocal critic of both Beijing and the Hong Kong government. ``People
may say, `Why should I bother?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cheng's radio program, ``Teacup in a Storm,'' is far and away
the top-rated morning show in Hong Kong. It has become a potent
outlet for the territory's 6.5 million people to sound off about
issues ranging from the Asian financial crisis to Hong Kong's
handover to Chinese rule last year. And it turned the 52-year-old
Cheng into one of the most influential, and controversial, figures
in town.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Friday they did not have a motive for the assault,
which occurred at 6:40 a.m. Wednesday, as Cheng was striding into
the studios of his station, Commercial Radio, in Kowloon. Police
inspectors said they were studying tapes of Cheng's last 40 radio
broadcasts to see if he had made remarks about people or groups
that might have been deemed offensive.
</P>
<P>
   If being offended by Cheng was a sufficient motive to attack
him, most of official Hong Kong would fall under suspicion. In a
raspy voice and style that he himself describes as ``sarcastic,''
Cheng regularly hurls insults at Hong Kong's chief executive, Tung
Chee-hwa, and many of his top advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Of Tung, who was appointed by Beijing, he once said: ``We don't
even know where this guy came from. He is so conservative. He's
from outer space and out of time. Where'd they find him? People
look to him to speak up for Hong Kong. Now people know he's only a
mouthpiece for China.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheng also has a television program, ``Hong Kong Affairs.'' And
when the Hong Kong secretary for education and manpower, Joseph
Wong, declined to appear on it, Cheng flayed him so mercilessly on
the program that the ATV broadcasting company apologized. Cheng
then publicly repudiated the apology, saying he had meant to insult
Wong.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheng has taken his strongest stands against China. Before
the handover, he warned that Hong Kong could become a larger
version of Singapore, a prosperous but politically repressive city.
After the handover, Cheng seized on any hint that Beijing was
eroding civil liberties in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, he waded into a dispute about whether Tung had
attempted to muzzle the government-owned broadcaster, Radio
Television Hong Kong, at the behest of China. ``Beijing has a
problem with talk show hosts,'' he said at the time. ``They think
we're out of control, out of line.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Cheng feared he would be yanked off the air after the
handover, he has continued to broadcast without interference. Even
now, some local journalists are playing down the assumption that
Cheng was attacked because of his strong views. They note Cheng
also had a colorful business career in which he published the first
Chinese-language edition of Playboy magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the motives behind this crime,'' said Kin-ming
Liu, the chairman of the Hong Kong Journalists Association. ``We
may never know.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, the two most notorious attacks on Hong Kong journalists
in recent years remain unsolved. Leung Tin-wai, a magazine
publisher, had his left forearm chopped off with a meat cleaver by
two men outside his office in May 1996. Jimmy Lai, a Hong Kong
media magnate known for his criticism of China, was robbed in his
home by knife-wielding intruders in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Given the striking similarity between this week's attack and
that on Leung two years ago, Cheng's co-host, Peter Lam, believes
this is hardly a case of a business deal gone sour. ``Albert thinks
there is a high degree of probability that it was related to
remarks he made on the air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng would not be the first radio personality victimized for
his on-air vitriol. In 1984, an outspoken Denver radio talk show
host, Alan Berg, was gunned down outside his house with a machine
pistol. Berg, who was Jewish, spoke bluntly about what he saw as
pervasive anti-Semitism. Two members of a neo-Nazi gang were later
convicted of murder in the case.
</P>
<P>
   As for Lam, he seems to be carrying on Cheng's take-no-prisoners
style. On the radio Friday morning, he excoriated a hospital for
inadvertently pumping contaminated fluid into the bloodstream of
six patients, killing three of them. Lam said he had no plans to
soften his tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had any doubts about how I was doing this job, I would
leave it,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
