<SLUG> BC-IMAGE-DVD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGE ENTERTAINMENT EXPANDS DVD HOLDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Image Entertainment, seeking a major Internet
presence, agreed to buy the DVD and laserdisc division of retailer
Ken Crane Home Entertainment for $6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Image, which remains the nation's largest laserdisc distributor
as it scrambles to boost its DVD operations, said Friday it chose
to buy Crane's business after exploring a variety of options for
moving onto the Web. Crane said its site, www.kencranes.com, is the
Internet's largest retailer of DVDs and laserdiscs with $15 million
in sales over the past 12 months and 3 million to 4 million hits
per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Image recognized the enormous growth opportunity represented
by electronic commerce,'' said Martin Greenwald, president and
chief executive officer, in a statement. ``This acquisition
solidifies Image as the leading independent DVD and laserdisc
distributor.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement noted that Adams Media Research has forecast
Internet sales of home video items, including DVD and laserdisc, to
reach $2.5 billion by 2003. The International Recording Media
Association recently said there will be 8.6 million DVD players in
U.S. homes in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Image, which has annual sales of more than $50 million, will pay
a combination of cash, stock and debt assumption for the business.
The deal, expected to close within a month, will add 55 Ken Crane
employees to the staff of the suburban Chatsworth-based company.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this will do essentially is cut out the middleman on
orders from the Ken Crane site,'' Image spokesman Mark Bates said.
</P>
<P>
   Image has seen the value of its stock nearly triple this year as
it switches its focus to DVD, which accounted for 38 percent of its
second-quarter sales. The issue traded in a wide range Friday, from
$7.50 to $9.125, and closed down $1.1875 at $7.75 a share.
</P>
<P>
   DVDs, or digital versatile discs, are the same size as compact
discs with seven times the capacity. They play full-length movies
with digital clarity and six-channel sound and offer massive
amounts of background information.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ken Crane, the deal will enable the suburban
Hawthorne-based retailer to focus on its specialty of selling home
theater systems and large-screen TVs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cash infusion will help fund our continued expansion and
store remodeling to prepare for the arrival of high-definition
TV,'' said Ken Crane Sr., president of the chain.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
