<HEADER>
A6855 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      08-21 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Aug. 23, will move Saturday in the `a' category.
</P>
<P>
   TERRORISM-REVIEW _ The images and the rhetoric last week were
those of a fast-spreading war. In the Red Sea and the Arabian Sea,
Tomahawk cruise missiles roared from the decks of American
warships, bound for targets in Afghanistan and Sudan, where they
smashed into what U.S. officials describe as a terrorist training
center and a chemical-weapons plant. In Washington, some of
President Clinton's harshest congressional critics put aside
partisanship and saluted the nation's scandal-burdened leader for
responding to terrorism with military strikes. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-POLITICS-REVIEW _ Things are so unsettled that politicians
in both parties last week found themselves, simultaneously,
condemning Bill Clinton, offering solace _ and keeping their mouths
shut. While the uproar over sex at the White House has eclipsed the
elections that are only 72 days away, the Lewinsky saga could have
a tremendous influence on how they play out, not only in November
but in 2000 and beyond. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   SOVEREIGNTY-REVIEW _ If diplomats are sent abroad to lie for
their countries, sometimes their greatest contribution to peace can
be to sell creative, convenient and competing fictions to both
sides in a civil war. As Chechnya went, so, perhaps, can go Kosovo.
In both places the ideals of absolute sovereignty and
self-determination are being bent days to make way for the notion
that peace is more complicated than either of those ideals permits.
By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-RELIGION-REVIEW _ In southern Nigeria, which is mainly
Christian, religious bumper stickers abound. ``Be a sweatless
winner,'' says one. ``Work with us at the Living Faith Church.''
Another advises that ``Jesus Christ gives, heals and delivers.'' Or
there is this simple admonition: ``Be careful, God is watching.''
The exhortations can be hard to read through the black exhaust
fumes that belch from Nigeria's crumbling fleet of vehicles, but
there is no mistaking the religious fervor that has gripped the
southern half of Africa's giant as misery has grown. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   POLS-APOLOGY-REVIEW _ Never admit fault or apologize after a car
accident, especially if you caused it. That is the standard warning
of a personal injury lawyer, but unnecessary advice for
politicians. Most would rather be flayed than express actual
contrition for a mistake, especially if they have to use those two
unthinkable words, I'm sorry. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   MANHUNT-REVIEW _ For much of the summer, hundreds of searchers
dressed in camouflage and armed with tracking devices that detect
the slightest motion of warm-blooded bipeds have been scouring the
woods of North Carolina and the slick-rock canyons of Utah looking
for three of the nation's most-wanted fugitives. They have used
helicopters, night-vision scopes, heat sensors, motion detectors,
smoke bombs, armored personnel carriers, small planes and radios
with encrypted transmissions _ all for naught. The technology may
be James Bondian. But what the searchers really need, says one
frustrated sheriff, is a snitch and a good bloodhound. By Timothy
Egan.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RUBLE-REVIEW _ As Russia's woes of the past week have
illustrated, the new buzzwords of international diplomacy are
devaluation, currency speculation and debt moratorium _ terminology
just as opaque and loaded with free-floating dread as anything in
the cold war lexicon. By week's end, not only were Russian
lawmakers calling for the resignation of President Boris Yeltsin,
but the world's financial markets were being pummeled, largely
because of fears set in motion by the decision of Yeltsin's
government to devalue the ruble. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   HYPOCRISY-REVIEW _ President Clinton has always been a
politician who plays by his own rules: Never give people more
information than they know, never use active words when passive
words will do, accept responsibility but place blame elsewhere,
excuse yourself within any admission. So people who abide by the
more conventional rules of required hypocrisy when they deal with
him almost always get burned. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   ANIMALS-USE-REVIEW _ Is there really any hard logic to which
animals Americans exempt from consumption, and which ones they
exploit? Is the triage of concern for different breeds _ whether
they are eaten, used in experiments or simply eliminated as pests _
a matter of sense or sentimentality? By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW YORK TIMES NEWS SERVICE
</P>
</TEXT>
