<HEADER>
A6857 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISS-KLAN-TRIAL-1STLD     08-21 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-KLAN-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-410-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DELAYED BUT NOT DENIED: EX-KKK CHIEF CONVICTED IN '66
MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 2nd graf to clarify day)  (bl) 
 By RICK BRAGG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ Vernon Dahmer Jr. covered his face and wept
into his hands. His brother, Dennis, gently pounded a railing in
the old courthouse balcony. And their mother, the elderly Ellie
Dahmer, shut her eyes and steepled her fingers, thanking God for
the jury's verdict that, almost 33 years after the crime, found an
old, stooped klansman guilty of ordering her husband killed.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a jury of six blacks, five whites and one Asian
convicted Samuel Bowers, a former Imperial Wizard of the
Mississippi White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan, of murder in the
Jan. 10, 1966, firebombing that killed Vernon Dahmer Sr., who had
been marked for death because he helped register blacks to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Richard McKenzie immediately sentenced Bowers, 73, to life
in prison, and slammed down his gavel to close the courtroom as an
old black woman in the back row of the courtroom clapped her hands,
twice, in a celebration that has been on hold for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than justice for the Dahmer family, who have been
frustrated after after four previous trials _ including two state
murder trials in the 1960s _ let Bowers stroll free after all-white
juries deadlocked. The verdict proved, said Vernon Dahmer Jr., that
the society his father died to help create is alive here in
south-central Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what my dad's life was about,'' he said, motioning to
the jury box that had seated a racially diverse cross-section of
the community, not an all-white, all-male jury from which blacks
were traditionally denied justice.
</P>
<P>
   Dahmer Sr., a respected storekeeper, farmer and local official
with the NAACP, was singled out by the Klan because he allowed his
store to be used as a place for blacks to pay the $2 poll tax that
was required for voter registration.
</P>
<P>
   Juries were selected from voting lists, and the Klan did
everything in its power, from cross burnings to whippings, from
church burnings to murder, to thwart the power that a vote can
bring.
</P>
<P>
   Klan members knew, Dahmer Jr. said, that their world could only
exist if blacks could be held back from using their numbers to
elect change, could fill jury boxes and public offices with people
of varying color.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was working to make sure this day would come,'' said Dahmer
Jr. of his father. ``This,'' he said of the diverse jury,
``represents America. This represents our community. The system has
now worked for us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As one of the younger members of the Dahmer family, a man in his
late teens or early twenties, moved through the crowded courtroom,
an older white man gripped his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw history here, son,'' the older man said.
</P>
<P>
   The case was history-making, for several reasons. While it was
only the second high-profile case in the past few years in which a
white supremacist was convicted of killing a civil rights leader _
Byron De La Beckwith was convicted in 1994 in Jackson, Miss., of
the 1963 murder of Medgar Evers _ this case was different.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith, a onetime salesman who had been a virtual nobody in
the ranks of white supremacists, murdered a nationally recognized
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Dahmer had not been nationally known, just a merchant and farmer
in Forrest County, outside Hattiesburg. But Bowers, a businessman
in Laurel, Miss., was a powerful Klan figure _ the only klansman
who had the authority to order a man's death, former Klan members
testified in the trial this week.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people who have been convicted in civil
rights-related killings have been foot soldiers, the ones who
actually threw the bombs, not the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers, whose organization was tied to church burnings, murders
and other terrorism throughout the 1960s, has served only six years
_ for his role in the infamous Neshoba County murders of Andrew
Goodman, Michael Schwerner and James Chaney. That was a federal
conviction. No Mississippi jury, Bowers once bragged to another
klansman, would convict a white man of killing a black man in the
state of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers, who had shown little emotion during the trial and showed
none at the verdict, answered no when the judge asked him if he had
anything to say before sentencing. But when his defense lawyer,
Travis Buckley, asked the judge to poll the jury, Bowers turned to
stare at them, one by one.
</P>
<P>
   Once, that look might have struck fear in people who lived at
the mercy of Klan nightriders, but now it was just an old man
watching time catch up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the jury came out, he started emptying his pockets,
took off his watch in anticipation of what was going to happen,''
said Forrest County District Attorney Lindsay Carter. Prisoners are
not allowed to take such things insider Parchman Prison, where he
will be held.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he knew what was coming,'' said Carter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the winter of 1965-66, Jones County, north of Hattiesburg,
was regarded as one of the meanest in Mississippi for Klan
activity. It was where Bowers made his base.
</P>
<P>
   In a farmhouse just to the south, outside Hattiesburg in Forest
County, Bowers summoned Klan members there in the months before
Dahmer's murder and asked them why ``something hadn't been done''
about Dahmer, former klansmen testified. Bowers planned Dahmer's
death, and on a cold January night, sent two carloads of Klansmen
south with 12 gallons of gasoline and shotguns. One way or the
other, Vernon Dahmer Sr. would be a dead man.
</P>
<P>
   The men hurled the gallons of gasoline into the house, where
Dahmer Sr., his wife and three of his children slept.
</P>
<P>
   He was burned so badly that the skin came loose from his arms,
but while his body was in flames, he fired his shotgun over and
over at the shapes darting through his yard, giving his wife and
children time to escape through the back of the house.
</P>
<P>
   A former klansman turned government informant who took part in
that raid, Billy Roy Pitts, testified in this trial that he heard a
man ``cry out in distress'' from inside the burning house.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing argument, Robert Helfrich, the prosecutor who
handled the case, evoked that image for the jury. ``A man's voice
in distress,'' said Helfrich. ``And yes, he was a man. A man's
voice is still in distress, because Sam Bowers is still walking the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice delayed,'' he added, ``is not justice denied.''
</P>
<P>
   Dahmer was still standing that night as the Klansmen, so
surprised at the fury of his reaction to their attack that they
shot out the headlights of one of their own cars in confusion,
rumbled away. But his lungs were so badly seared by the flames that
he died in a hospital bed 12 hours later, in his wife's arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tears that I am shedding, I am shedding for Vernon,''
said Mrs. Dahmer, standing later in the hot sun outside the
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   A daughter, Bettie, 10 years old at the time of her father's
murder, was handed out a window of the house from her father to her
mother, and was already burned on her arms and forehead. After the
verdict she said she was not able to talk, and stood with tears in
her eyes as her brothers thanked prosecutors for bring Bowers back
to court.
</P>
<P>
   Citing new evidence, and under renewed pressure by the Dahmer
family and others to reopen the case, prosecutors here _ backed by
state Attorney General Mike Moore _ dusted off an old indictment of
Bowers and two other klansmen, Deavours Nix and Charles Noble.
</P>
<P>
   Nix testified from a wheelchair for a variety of health
problems, although a Jackson newspaper photographer had snapped his
picture playing golf a few months ago. Nix testified as a defense
witness Thursday that he had never heard Bowers use a racial slur,
let alone order a killing, and that the Klan was not a violent
organization. He said he joined because he had heard the Klan was a
benevolent organization that passed out fruit baskets to the poor
at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Nix is charged with arson and Noble with murder and arson in the
Dahmer case. They are expected to go to trial later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dahmer family said they did not want to worry about that
now. They would celebrate this victory, quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts had testified earlier that Bowers' lawyer, Travis Buckley,
once attended Klan meetings himself. Friday, Buckley's efforts to
portray a government conspiracy against Bowers fell flat.
</P>
<P>
   He said his client was sacrificed to the Moore's political
ambitions and compared his client's prosecution to Hitler's
persecution of the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But Buckley's witnesses did little to refute a parade of other
witnesses who painted a more ominous picture of Bowers.
</P>
<P>
   Two witnesses Thursday had testified that they saw a jubilant
Bowers boast about the killing days after it. ``Look at what my
boys did to that Dahmer'' Bowers had said, testified former
klansman Robert Earl Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers, he said, was holding up a newspaper at the time, with
the story of Dahmer's death on the page. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
