</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LINCOLN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: YOUNG MR. LINCOLN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Aug. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, in courtrooms coast to coast, the
benchmark of human identity has gradually shifted to the DNA
standard, the molecular dog tag inherent in even our most
fragmentary bodily bits. Where genetic material _ that laconic term
_ survives, other proofs of identity are essentially immaterial.
</P>
<P>
   But what about a case like the daguerreotype, soon to be
auctioned by Christie's, which may or may not depict Abraham
Lincoln, circa 1843, as a young Illinois state legislator? If it is
Lincoln, the portrait could be worth a great deal of money, because
it would be the earliest portrait of him known to exist. If it is
some less illustrious young man, the portrait would have, as they
say, only antiquarian interest.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists cannot pluck a hair from this portrait-sitter's head
or take a swab from the inside of his cheek. All they can do is
analyze, in various clever ways, the resemblance between confirmed
portraits of Abraham Lincoln and this man with the pale forehead
and the tanned lower face, attributes every frontiersman would have
shared.
</P>
<P>
   The sitter's features have been measured and morphed and
mathematicized, and the pattern of the veins in his hand has been
plotted against the veins that show in genuine Lincoln portraits.
</P>
<P>
   But what it all comes down to is doing by other means one of the
things that humans, for evolutionary reasons, happen to do
exceptionally well even without scientific tools: recognizing
faces. Suffice it to say that this portrait would never have been
so rigorously tested if the judgment of the common-sensical eye
were unequivocal, if this distant visage announced unmistakably
that it was Lincoln's own.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the portrait-sitter's mouth argues on behalf of Lincoln,
and perhaps the nose argues against, unless you take into account
the fact that deeply tanned noses set against pale foreheads often
look more pronounced. The eyes themselves seem watery, unfocused,
as if the sitter could not keep them still in the studio. But
humans do not, as a rule, decipher faces feature by feature, except
when looking at infants. Recognition is deeply intuitive, a kind of
eclat that almost defies analysis.
</P>
<P>
   This is indeed a face only a mother could love. But when it
comes to being Lincoln, it may also be a face that only a computer
could recognize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
