<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEDICARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PROCESS FOR MEDICARE PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Aug. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Managed care will inevitably become the subject of more and more
litigation as millions of Americans come to live under its rules. A
recent ruling by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals found that
Medicare beneficiaries enrolled in health maintenance organizations
have a constitutional right to due process when they are denied
services by the plans.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling affirmed an earlier decision by a U.S. District Court
in Arizona. That court declared that patients must be given prompt
notification when a benefit has been denied, a full explanation for
why the benefit was denied, a clear avenue of appeal and other
procedures designed to protect their right to due process. The
lawsuit was filed on behalf of the nearly 6 million Medicare
beneficiaries enrolled in managed care plans. Those numbers are
growing rapidly, and could reach 12 million, or roughly 30 percent
of all Medicare recipients, by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court essentially found that Medicare benefit
decisions made by HMOs, which are paid by the government to provide
the coverage, amount to government action. In the field of health
care, at least, the courts are finding that managed care
organizations through which public benefits are distributed must
now meet constitutional requirements that few considered before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
