<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WARREN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT WARREN, 72, WISCONSIN FEDERAL JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., N.M.)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Willis Warren, a senior federal judge in Wisconsin who
caused a national uproar in 1979 when he reluctantly became the
first federal judge ever to sign a prior-restraint order against a
magazine, died on Thursday at Columbia Hospital in Milwaukee. He
was 72 and lived in Mequon, a Milwaukee suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said the U.S. District Court for the
Eastern District of Wisconsin, to which President Richard Nixon had
nominated Warren in 1974 in what turned out to be one of his final
official acts before leaving the White House after his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The target of the judge's order was The Progressive, a left-wing
magazine in Madison, Wis., which had scheduled an article by a
freelance writer, Howard Morland, titled ``The H-Bomb Secret: How
We Got It, Why We're Telling It.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government contended that the article told ``how a
hydrogen bomb works,'' and Defense Secretary James Schlesinger
asserted that publication ``would irreparably impair the national
security.''
</P>
<P>
   The Progressive then accused the Department of Justice of making
a ``sweeping attack on the First Amendment rights of the American
people.'' It also rejected an out-of-court compromise suggested by
Warren.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle, the judge ruled that the rights guaranteed
by the First Amendment were ``not absolute and unlimited'' and
forbade publication until the courts could sort things out.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a task he relished. ``Such notoriety is not to be
sought,'' Warren said in court. Predicably, his action prompted a
furor that allied civil libertarians, publishers and editorial
writers.
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court set aside Warren's injunction several months
later, and The Progressive published the article. The appeals panel
then halted all further litigation in the case but kept some
documents under seal, an action the American Civil Liberties Union
vainly protested.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Raton, N.M., Robert Warren graduated from Macalaster
College in St. Paul, Minn., and earned a master's degree at the
University of Minnesota. He graduated from the University of
Wisconsin Law School in 1956 and went into private practice in
Elkhorn and Green Bay. He became an assistant district attorney in
1958.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican, he served as a state senator and assistant
majority leader in the 1960s and as Wisconsin's attorney general
from 1969 until he joined the court.
</P>
<P>
   He took senior status and a reduced work load in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Warren is survived by his wife of 50 years, Laverne Voagen
Warren; three daughters, Cheryl Sensenbrenner, Treva Livesey and
Tara Warren; three sons, Iver, Gregg and Lyle; a brother, David;
seven sisters, Dorothy Olson, Bonnie Conditt, Betty Moede, Marylin
Blackmon, Jean Miller, Robin Cooprider and Lynda Warren, and 12
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0503 </DOCNO>
