<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0504 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6872 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS-HNS &LR;      08-21 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Comets try to beat 
odds against Sting
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perrot hopes to start in playoff opener
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By W.H. STICKNEY JR. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ A recurring theme for the Comets has become
annoying for coach Van Chancellor. But with the defending WNBA
champions about to open a best-of-three semifinal series against
Charlotte at 3 p.m. today, Chancellor might be asked about the
Comets' dominance of the Sting a few times over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The Sting and Comets have met 10 times, including exhibitions
and playoffs. The Sting has won only once.
</P>
<P>
   But each of the past three wins, all this season, has been by a
diminishing margin, concluding with a 70-67 victory at Compaq
Center on Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord,'' Chancellor said Friday, ``I believe in omens. Is there
any way in the world we could quit mentioning that we've won nine
out of 10? Because they're going to read the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't look forward to playing them, because they have
so many weapons. They run everybody in the world out there.
Sometimes, I just worry that the law of averages is going to catch
up with us. But if we can get (point guard Kim) Perrot well, we'll
take our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Even bigger than the question of how long the Comets (27-3) can
beat the odds against the Sting (18-12) is whether they can survive
in the playoffs with Perrot operating on a sprained right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a struggle,'' Chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Cynthia Cooper: ``I think we can win without her. It would
be so much tougher without her. I can't even imagine playing
without Kim. She's just been an integral part of our team all
season long, even last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been the rock on our team, unwavering. She's always been
there for us defensively, offensively. So right now, I'm imagining
Kim out there on the floor at point guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, who sprained her ankle in the second half of the Comets'
80-71 win over Los Angeles in the season finale Wednesday night,
might see only limited duty today.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, the quarterback of the offense and the spark plug on
defense, has made progress in her rehabilitation. She was walking
normally when the Comets worked out Friday at the Sting's practice
facility. But her availability remains a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The straightaway is going to be OK,'' Perrot said. ``But to
get down and play defense, the thing that scares me the most is
that I'm not going to be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot said she will start, but a determination as to how much
she can play will be made after the first five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a healthy Perrot, it has become more difficult for the
Comets to maintain their dominance over the Sting.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets and Sting first met last season at Rice's Autry Court
in an exhibition that helped christen the WNBA. They faced off a
second time in the preseason, then as members of the Eastern
Conference squared off four times during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets won five of those games by an average margin of 12.
The Comets' only loss came Aug. 16, 1997, at the Charlotte Coliseum
when Andrea Stinson scored 19 first-half points to spirit the Sting
to an 80-71 victory.
</P>
<P>
   After disposing of the Sting 77-69 on Aug. 19 at Compaq Center,
the Comets lost their final two games of the regular season, then
faced the Sting again in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Although starting center Wanda Guyton suffered a concussion in
the second half and was knocked out of the championship round, the
Comets beat the Sting 70-54 and went on to defeat New York 65-51 to
claim the inaugural WNBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Comets and Charlotte are geared for meeting No. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, the four top players for the Sting _ Stinson, power
forward Vicky Bullett, rookie small forward Tracy Reid and center
Rhonda Mapp _ have been compared to the Comets' Big Three _ Cooper,
Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Cooper relishes facing Charlotte. She expects a
war throughout the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a tough team,'' Cooper said, while downplaying the
significance of the 10 games. ``I don't think there's a danger in
(having met 10 times previously). We understand this is the
playoffs. We understand the importance of winning the first game
and how tough Charlotte really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not taking them lightly. Every single time we've played
them, they've been a tough team. They have certain strengths that
happen to be our weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper cited the Sting's rebounding superiority and the need for
the Comets to play 40 minutes of intense defense if they are to
win.
</P>
<P>
   If the Comets must defend without Perrot, Cooper said it will be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is definitely a concern of mine, of the team's and, I'm
sure, of the coaching staff,'' she said. ``But she'll be over on
the bench, and from there she can motivate us in a lot of different
ways. She'll be with us in spirit, and hopefully physically,
also.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
