u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPS-BASEBALLS-NY     08-21 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPS-BASEBALLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.)  
 SELLER OF BASEBALLS FROM PERFECT GAME SAYS LETTER IS FAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a bizarre twist to the sale of baseballs
supposedly used in David Wells' perfect game, the man who sold the
balls to a Long Island memorabilia dealer said Friday that he, and
not the American League umpire Al Clark, wrote and signed the
letter authenticating the Yankee pitcher's signature on the balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told people at major-league baseball when this first started
that Al had nothing to do with this, but nobody wanted to believe
that,'' said Rich Gressle, who said he owns a delivery service in
Essex County, N.J. ``Al Clark did not write the letter. I wrote
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gressle said he got six balls directly from Wells about a week
after the pitcher threw the perfect game against the Minnesota
Twins, but he said he could not be certain the balls were used in
the May 17 game at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials are investigating the sale of the balls to
Mark Lewis, a dealer in Centereach, N.Y. Lewis has said he bought
six balls for $300 each and sold four of them for $1,000 each
before requesting their return after baseball initiated its
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The letter that was signed by Clark and authenticated Wells'
signature said that Clark, who did not work the Wells game,
obtained the balls from John Hirschbeck, who was the game's
first-base umpire. Hirschbeck denied on Thursday that he had any
involvement with the balls, and on Friday a baseball official said
that investigators had found nothing to implicate him.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the official said, Hirschbeck has been irate that
Clark used his name. But Gressle said it was he, and not Clark, who
used Hirschbeck's name. Gressle, attributing his actions to
stupidity and greed, said in a telephone interview Friday: ``I made
up the letter and traced over Al's signature from something I had
here and gave it to Mark. This is all my fault. It's nobody else's
fault. I did it. Al Clark had nothing to do with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Clark, who is on vacation, through the league
office have been unsuccessful. Richie Phillips, the lawyer for the
umpires' union, said he did not know where Clark was but added that
he had spoken to him earlier. ``Clark denies dealing through any
middleman,'' Phillips said by telephone from Stone Harbor, N.J.
``He denies trafficking in those baseballs in any respect and
denies guaranteeing their authenticity. He denies any
involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Gressle said he has known Clark for about 10 years, having met
him through a mutual friend.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the Long Island dealer, said he had bought memorabilia on
several occasions from Gressle, including items from the 1995 game
in which Cal Ripken Jr. broke Lou Gehrig's record for consecutive
games played. Clark was the third-base umpire in that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood the balls came from Clark and other umpires,''
Lewis said in a telephone interview, speaking generally of the
memorabilia, ``but the majority from Clark.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had no knowledge that the Wells balls came from Clark
but believed Clark's signature looked the same as the Clark
signature he had on letters on American League stationery. Gressle
said he got the balls from Wells at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met with David Wells the week after his perfect game,''
Gressle said. ``He wanted some photographs from me. He signed those
six baseballs that were already rubbed up and used in games. I
don't know what games. They came out of a big bag that balls go in.
He also signed some ticket stubs and a couple of photos, and that
was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gressle said Wells signed each ball and added the date and the
initials ``PG'' _ for perfect game. Wells has declined to discuss
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Gressle said he could understand why people might be skeptical
about his explanation of what happened with the balls and the
letter. But he added: ``Am I taking the fall for somebody? No, I'm
not taking the fall for anybody. I did what I did. I admitted I did
it. I told people at major-league baseball I did it, and they don't
want to believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials declined to comment on Gressle's story or any
aspect of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought he could face criminal charges based on what
he says is a fake letter, Gressle, 38, said: ``I would imagine
something could come of this. I'm trying to do the right thing. I'm
trying to make the situation right. This was just something stupid
I did. It was probably a greedy thing more than anything else. It
was a chance to make what I thought was quick, easy money, and all
that it's done is given me and my family a problem. All I can say
is I'm sorry. I've told Al that a thousand times.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, without passing judgment on Clark or any other umpire,
said he felt the ``sale of memorabilia, especially for profit, is
absolutely disgusting.'' He said that was his view and also the
view of the umpires' association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
