<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-McGWIRE-HORMONE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McGWIRE USES SUBSTANCE BANNED IN SOME SPORTS  
(lb) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his pursuit of Roger Maris' home-run record, Mark McGwire has
become a folk hero, with testaments to his popularity unfolding
daily. Beginning Saturday in Pittsburgh, the Pirates will play host
to the St. Louis slugger in the first back-to-back regular-season
sellouts in Three Rivers Stadium's 27-year history.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no wonder that the man of the moment has been drawn
into a debate of the time. McGwire acknowledges he uses a
nutritional supplement that is legal in baseball but has been
banned by the National Football League and the International
Olympic Committee because it is thought to provide an unfair
advantage. It is a supplement that many doctors say they believe is
potentially dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The testosterone-producing pill is called androstenedione and is
intended to raise levels of the male hormone, which builds lean
muscle mass and promotes recovery from injury. It is sold over the
counter, and McGwire says he has used it for more than a year. No
one is suggesting outright that it has made a difference in his
pursuit of Maris' record of 61 homers in a season.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie, McGwire hit 49 home runs in 1987, long before he
says he used the substance. And in the seasons that followed, he
solidified his reputation as one of the game's premier power
hitters. In 1996, he hit 52 home runs, the first time he crossed
the 50-homer mark. He followed that with 58 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've done is natural,'' McGwire told The Associated
Press. ``Everybody that I know in the game of baseball uses the
same stuff I use.'' He also acknowledged that he uses the
muscle-builder creatine, which is an amino acid powder.
</P>
<P>
   Many baseball players are proponents of creatine _ Sammy Sosa,
who is just behind McGwire in the home-run race, and the Yankees'
Chad Curtis among them. But no other baseball player has come
forward with support for androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   Because baseball's drug policy bans only illegal drugs, the
popularity of the supplements in clubhouses hardly draws the
league's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't comment,'' major-league baseball Commissioner Bud
Selig said of McGwire's use of the supplement. ``I have no
knowledge of it. The Cardinals are a disciplined organization, and
I don't think anything goes on there that shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   But many in the medical community question the safety of both
creatine and androstenedione, and the concern is beginning to take
hold in other sports. A sign in the Miami Dolphins' locker room
this summer advised players not to use creatine during two-a-day
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee added androstenedione to its
banned list last December because it believed the supplement gave
its users an unfair advantage. This summer, Randy Barnes, the 1996
Olympic shot-put gold medalist, was banned from the sport for life
because of his use of androstenedione. It was his second drug
offense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
