<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-NY-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. MUSLIMS CALL U.S. BOMBINGS CRUEL AND WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-DAMAGE,
ATTACK-RECAP, ATTACK-ISLAM, ATTACK-RUSSIA-REACT,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-EUROPE-REACT, ATTACK-KENYA,
ATTACK-PAKISTAN, ATTACK-SUDAN.) 
 (bl)  
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The U.S. bombings in Afghanistan and the Sudan did
not come up at all during juma _ traditional Friday prayers _ at
Masjid Alfalah, a mosque in Corona, Queens, that is attended by
Muslims from many nations. But afterward, it was clear they were on
everyone's minds.
</P>
<P>
   And the feeling among the immigrant worshipers was almost
universal: the attacks launched by their adopted country were cruel
and very plainly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Some called the U.S. government a bully in the schoolyard of
international relations, eager to show off its power and anxious to
beat up helpless developing nations. Others pointedly criticized
President Clinton for singling out the Islamic world while turning
a blind eye to injustices against Muslims in Palestine and Bosnia.
Still others said they suspected that the president authorized the
bombings to divert attention from the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do what Clinton did, he had to have no feelings,'' said
Isslam Hadidy, 21, an immigrant from Egypt. ``Innocent lives were
lost, and the only reason all this happened is because they
couldn't control those two countries.'' Hadidy, a U.S. citizen, was
steadfast in his assessment that his adopted country had sinned
against the Muslim world and somehow, someday, would pay for its
arrogance. ``We believe, as Muslims, that injustice will never
prevail,'' he said. ``And what happened here, this was not
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashad Mohammed, 25, a business student at St. John's University
from Sri Lanka, agreed. ``They're taking a big risk,'' he said of
U.S. officials. ``Because they haven't targeted terrorists, but
innocent people, and this isn't going to finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed said he had nothing against America, particularly since
he had been granted a visa allowing him to study business
administration here and learn skills that will help him when he
returns to his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give people from other countries opportunities like that,
but they should treat the international situation in the same way,
and policies should be equal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed said that at the core of the anger that many Muslims
feel for the United States was its continuing support for Israel.
``They target the Islamic world, but why haven't they taken any
steps against the Israelis for all the hardships they have forced
on Arabs?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mahamed Ismail, 65, an immigrant from India who has lived in the
New York region for almost 50 years, said the Alfalah mosque was a
decidedly apolitical place. ``They don't discuss politics there,''
he said. ``You just pray to Allah, and Allah will take care of the
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite his protestations that he didn't know anything about
``this bomb business,'' Ismail let slip a hint of anger at
Clinton's actions. ``What he did might be wrong or it might be
right,'' he said. ``But if they're looking out for American
interests, they should think before they kill innocent people who
know nothing about politics.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the hundreds of worshipers who gathered outside
the mosque to retrieve the shoes they had shed before kneeling for
prayers wholeheartedly supported the bombings. ``To strike back and
control them is the right step,'' said Aziz Bhatti, a Pakistani
immigrant who runs a film developing shop in Jackson Heights.
``They have their own selfish motives, and they don't represent
everybody in the Muslim world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
