<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER HALL'S DEBACLE, JETS BRING IN A NEW KICKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when the New York Jets think they have figured out John
Hall, he mis-hits a 37-yard field-goal attempt, blows an
extra-point attempt and squibs three consecutive kickoffs _ all in
the same game.
</P>
<P>
   So coach Bill Parcells made a trade Friday following Hall's
Thursday night debacle against the New York Giants. He called his
good friend, Green Bay Packers general manager Ron Wolf, and
acquired Brett Conway.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who named Conway the kicker in the preseason finale
next Friday against the Chicago Bears, then cautioned that the deal
did not mean the end of Hall's career as a Jet.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said Hall ``was the highest-rated kicker on our board
last year,'' although he went undrafted and was signed by the Jets
as a free agent. Conway was drafted last year in the third round
out of Penn State. He had a training-camp battle with Ryan Longwell
but sat out the season because of a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   Hall set a National Football League record as a rookie last year
with 29 touchbacks on kickoffs, but Parcells said: ``It doesn't
make any difference if you can identify the problem if you can't
correct it. I have to satisfy my own curiosity about Conway. You
can't fix something after three, four games.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall kicked on grass this preseason at Giants Stadium and
practiced on both grass and artificial turf at the Jets' training
facility at Hofstra University. He also had a new holder, the new
punter Nick Gallery. Last year, Hall converted only 1-of-5
field-goal attempts after his regular holder, punter Brian Hansen,
was injured. When Hansen held, Hall made 75 percent of his
attempts. But Hansen was traded to the Packers last Monday as
Gallery exhibited an extremely strong leg.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, like all kickers, prefers to kick on the consistency of
artificial turf. But after Thursday's 27-23 victory, he said:
``It's over. I'm not going to get into that. It doesn't matter what
kind of footing it is. I've got to make the kicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Hall's performance, Parcells said: ``I can't take that. It's
not just a couple of things gone wrong. It's everything. When you
see those kind of signs, it worries you.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hall is the man who helped Parcells' Jets dominate on
special teams last season. Because of his touchbacks and uniformly
deep kicking, the opposition was forced to begin an average drive,
following kickoffs, 76.1 yards from the goal line _ farther than
any other team in the American Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Hall still might get back to those booming numbers. The grass
experiment at Giants Stadium will end once the regular season
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Hall had not missed a field goal or extra point in the preseason
before Thursday, and he had been booting field goals in practice at
a rate close to what Parcells demands: 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hall's erratic charts looked like the recent stock
market. He started by making the second-longest field goal by a
rookie, a 55-yarder on his first attempt. He knocked kickoffs
through the end zone. But he also missed 2-of-6 kicks in the
40-yard range. Overall, his field-goal average was 68.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The special teams coach, Mike Sweatman, offered a rhetorical
question: ``Do you know who his holder was?'' He stopped short of
then saying that that was the reason.
</P>
<P>
   But Hall was a 20 percent field-goal kicker with quarterback
Glenn Foley as his holder.
</P>
<P>
   Gallery, meanwhile, was apparently learning the hold technique
very well, even though he had never held in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hall worked out in the bubble in the off-season, which was
very helpful,'' Sweatman said. ``We've tried to get a more
consistent swing.''
</P>
<P>
   The hierarchy seemed pleased with Hall until his errant kicking
against the Giants. That led to the trade for Conway, for whom the
Jets promised unspecified considerations if he makes the team. The
6-foot-2-inch Conway has converted 3-of-5 field-goal attempts in
the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells dismissed the idea of keeping two kickers _ one for
kicking off, the other for field goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hall was more consistent last year,'' Parcells said. ``I don't
want anyone to get the wrong idea. Nothing is resolved. I want to
create an option for myself. If we had a problem in our first game
and I hadn't tried to fix it, I couldn't forgive myself.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells said the Jets had agreed to a four-year contract
extension with safety Victor Green and were close to a similar deal
with wide receiver Wayne Chrebet. ... ``We're a long way from being
where I want to be,'' Parcells said of the club. ``No. 1 is the
kicking. No. 2 is the offensive line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980821.0509 </DOCNO>
