<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS WAKE UP TO LIFE WITHOUT SEHORN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than a minute had gone by in the Jets-Giants game Thursday
night when Tiki Barber turned to look at Jason Sehorn, the Giants'
most gifted player, whose bounty of athletic gifts engendered an
aura of invincibility that fed an entire team.
</P>
<P>
   Barber saw Sehorn's face buried in a white towel on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he going to be all right?'' Barber said on the sideline to
Danny Kanell, Sehorn's best friend on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell had just left Sehorn's side with an affectionate jostling
of Sehorn's hair. Kanell's face was ashen, his eyes teary, when he
turned to face Barber.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Kanell said.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, the question is: Will the Giants be all right?
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fassel, the coach, vowed to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've still got a knot in my stomach,'' Fassel said Friday.
``The whole game I had an empty feeling. We're going to miss him.
But we've always dealt with it. We've picked up and went on to win.
Others guys are going to have to do the same now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sehorn's right knee injury _ a torn anterior cruciate
ligament and a torn medial collateral ligament that will require
season-ending reconstructive surgery _ has had a profound effect on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a team with few question marks, especially
defensively, has a hole where it was heretofore considered
strongest. It is impossible to hide a weak or even mediocre
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Giants' pass rush and middle-of-the-field pass
coverage was bolstered by Sehorn's presence.
</P>
<P>
   As Kanell said late Thursday: ``Any time you can isolate a
cornerback on a wide receiver and just forget about the receiver,
it lets the rest of the defense attack. It was a given that Jason
would shut the other receiver down.''
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Hamilton, a 23-year-old third-year player who has started
one NFL game, will take Sehorn's place. The rookie Shaun Williams,
a safety in college, will get the accelerated textbook instruction
at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, with Sehorn sitting on a long table in the
trainer's room, players streamed in to comfort and commiserate with
their fallen teammate. The locker room was chaotic, with a parade
of players going back to the smaller trainer's room to see Sehorn.
</P>
<P>
   They found Sehorn upbeat and serene, encouraging his mates,
indeed even consoling others.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes earlier, in an unusual break from football locker room
protocol, Sehorn's wife of six months, Whitney, had been brought
into the trainer's room to see her husband.
</P>
<P>
   She felt like crying. He would not let her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about me,'' Sehorn said.
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn's cheerfulness and spirit eased the mood of many Giants,
several of whom later acknowledged they had trouble concentrating
on the game. When intermission ended, players returned to the
field, but many on the defensive side had been so wrapped up in
meeting with Sehorn, some had not even discussed _ or paid
attention to _ what the plan for the second half was to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was surreal, like it didn't really happen,'' Barber said
Friday. ``You're thinking: `Stuff like this doesn't happen.' Ten
seconds into a preseason game and the best athlete on the team is
gone _ just like that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jessie Armstead, the team's spiritual leader and an All-Pro
linebacker, said he ran onto the field for the first series of the
game with one eye on the Giants bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't help looking over there to see if Jason would come
running out,'' Armstead said.
</P>
<P>
   No Giant, most notably Fassel and Sehorn, had considered such a
devastating injury likely when the decision was made to use Sehorn
as one of the team's prime kickoff return men this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In lengthy private conversations with both Fassel and Sehorn at
training camp last month, both argued that it would not put Sehorn
in additional jeopardy. The Giants were trying to improve what was
the National Football League's worst kickoff return average a year
ago, and Sehorn had all but begged Fassel to let him do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a play where the ball carrier gets hurt very often,''
Fassel said last month. ``I wouldn't consider it if Jason didn't
want to do it so badly. Plus, he has the fluid stride, quickness,
breakaway speed and aggressiveness that should make him a great
returner. This is a guy who plays with abandon in the secondary. I
don't think the risk is any greater on kickoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn, who returned punts as a cornerback and safety at
Southern California, found the discussion about possible injury
annoyingly negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I hold myself back because of the risk of injury?''
he said. ``Besides, I heard people in the stands at practice
cheering when I was returning kicks today. It's considered fun now,
there's no outcry against it, right? If I get hurt, people can't
say `no' to this then. They've got to remember that they were
cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a few seconds of cheering Thursday night when Sehorn
burst up the middle of the field with the opening kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things looked pretty good,'' Sehorn said later after he had
limped into a press conference with reporters. ``Then I saw
somebody come at me. And here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The fragile psyche of what is already a diverse group of
defensive backs will have to mold anew. This is the group, after
all, that erupted in argument during the second half of the Giants
playoff loss to Minnesota. That on-the-field quarrel started when
cornerback Phillippi Sparks scolded Hamilton about a coverage and
Armstead came to Hamilton's aid.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on the secondary will increase now. Their poise
will be tested and any lack of united will be exploited.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the defense, Armstead and defensive end Michael
Strahan, the team's only All-Pros, have a job to do and it includes
protecting Hamilton and insuring that the Giants pass rush and
punishing run defense is at its best. Because the Giants no longer
have Sehorn, one of the NFL's top five cornerbacks, following an
opponent's top receiver, thwarting his best efforts from sideline
to sideline.
</P>
<P>
   That extravagance disappeared with an awkward twisting and a
tackle at the end of the opening kickoff Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said he had not slept much in the aftermath of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up a number of times,'' he said. ``I think everybody
felt it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   As Fassel said, crisply and loudly when he was asked about
Sehorn's injury minutes after the game had ended, ``It was my worst
nightmare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
