u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-5     08-21 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT, AND CONCERN, OVER MARCH IN HARLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER and MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For weeks, the debate over next month's planned
Million Youth March has largely been confined to mayoral news
conferences, televised sound bites, newspaper articles and, most
recently, a federal courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the streets and stoops of Harlem are slowly
beginning to buzz with interest and speculation about the march,
which organizers say will fill Malcolm X Boulevard on Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents are voicing support for the idea of bringing
hundreds of thousands of young black men and women to Harlem and
encouraging them to seize control of their lives and make peace
with one another. But mixed with that enthusiasm are concerns about
the potential for violence; talk of shuttered businesses on one of
the busiest shopping days of the year; and ambivalence, at best,
about one of the march's primary organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Hadassah Laurie, a legal secretary, said she was looking forward
to the event and saw little reason to fear disturbances or
violence, even if gang members attend the march, as organizers have
proposed.
</P>
<P>
   As for the event's leader, Khalid Abdul Muhammad _ a former top
official in the Nation of Islam, who has called Jews
``bloodsuckers'' _ Ms. Laurie, 22, arched her eyebrows and sighed.
``I'm not condoning what he says,'' she said. ``But you're not
going to find anyone who's perfect. All the Martin Luther Kings of
our day are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in Harlem is so forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Johnson, 37, a life insurance salesman, said he was
adamantly opposed to the event and had his doubts about Muhammad's
intentions. ``I have yet to hear what the purpose of the march
is,'' he said, soliciting customers from behind a table on 125th
Street. ``I commend the mayor for not issuing the permit. And many
of my brothers feel the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials have denied the organizers a permit for the Sept.
5 march because, they say, the area cannot safely accommodate 1
million people, the number that the organizers originally set as
their goal. The Giuliani administration has offered Randalls Island
or Van Cortlandt Park in the Bronx as alternative locations, and
Sept. 19 as a more suitable date, to avoid conflicts with other
events already scheduled for the Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the organizers sued the city in U.S. District Court
in Manhattan, saying the refusal of a permit was unconstitutional
and reflected Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's discriminatory treatment of
black New Yorkers. A hearing is scheduled for Wednesday, although
organizers of the march have vowed that it will take place with or
without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how many people will show up for the march is impossible
to know, and it is not clear how extensive an organization is in
place to promote the event nationwide. A Web site provides contact
telephone numbers in several cities, but calls to those numbers
Friday were answered by machines. Calls to an information number in
New York were not answered at all.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a separate event billed as the Million Youth Movement
is scheduled for the same weekend in Atlanta, and has the backing
of the Nation of Islam, the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People and the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Advertising for the march has also been scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Harlem residents, like other New Yorkers, have been
learning plenty about it from newspapers and television. The news
reports have mostly revolved around Giuliani's objections to the
event, and his attacks on Muhammad as an anti-Semitic hatemonger.
For many Harlem residents, however, the mayor's opposition is just
another reason to support the march.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Laurie, for one, said she could not accept the mayor's
objections to the event at face value. ``He's not really for black
people or minorities,'' she said. ``He's all for himself and
whoever voted for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said the mayor's stated concerns about safety seemed
patronizing.
</P>
<P>
   Lina Cannon, 26, the owner of a beauty salon on Malcolm X
Boulevard, said Giuliani seemed to have conjured up a nightmare in
which mobs of rampaging gang members, whipped into a frenzy, would
overwhelm the decent people of Harlem. ``If anything, I feel the
mayor will be trying to start a war,'' she said. ``His objections
to everything are causing the chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Woodard, a Mount Vernon, N.Y, resident arriving for an
appointment, agreed, saying that city officials' proposals of
alternative locations belied their motives. ``This is the
crossroads of our lives,'' she said, pointing to the corner of
125th Street and Malcolm X Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   But others shared Giuliani's concerns about safety. Pierre
Davis, 16, said that a march attended by teen-agers and gang
members would inevitably lead to violence, in contrast to the
Million Man March in Washington in 1995 and the Million Woman March
in Philadelphia last October.
</P>
<P>
   Those were adults, he said. ``They know how to come together for
a cause,'' he said, in between smoking a cigarette and calling
after nearly every young woman who walked by. ``Youth don't know
how to act.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. David Paterson said several business owners were
planning to close their doors the day of the event, sacrificing
back-to-school sales on what is traditionally the second-busiest
shopping weekend of the year in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   But to Damien Lemons, the 17-year-old retail manager at a Krispy
Kreme doughnut shop on Frederick Douglass Boulevard and 125th
Street, the talk of mayhem seemed ridiculous. He said he had spoken
to several acquaintances who belonged to gangs and who were unsure
of whether to attend the march. He said that far from worrying
about whether they would come, city officials and Harlem residents
should encourage them to.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be afraid of them,'' he said. ``You can't tell them
to stay away. If they were all to come, we'd know that they are
listening, that they want to help, to make a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in Harlem seemed to agree, though, when it came to
Muhammad, the organizer of the youth march. While some said they
admired him for speaking his mind, many people who were interviewed
said they were offended by his statements over the years denouncing
whites, Jews, Roman Catholics and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad was dismissed by the Nation of Islam as its spokesman
in 1994 after a 1993 speech in which he referred to Jews as
``bloodsuckers.'' As recently as last month, he called New York a
``Jewish-controlled city'' and implied that Jews and other whites
working for the mayor were responsible for official opposition to
the Million Youth March.
</P>
<P>
   But while disapproving of Muhammad's rhetoric, many Harlem
residents appeared willing to look past it for the sake of an event
that otherwise seemed worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Others said they believed that Muhammad would be unlikely to
resort to racist diatribes at a large gathering for fear of
alienating his audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-98 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
