<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TURNING CRISES INTO COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jonathan Rosario answered his door dressed as if he
were ready to go on stage and do his comedy routine: black vest
over a loose white shirt, burgundy jeans and impeccably shined
shoes. He excused himself and lingered in the foyer, where he keeps
a pantheon of saints and celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't mind, let me light my candles,'' he said.
``People come by and leave their names so I can pray for them. I
don't think I'm anything special, but people think my prayers do
something for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He touched a match to candles near a statue of an Indian, one of
the Virgin Mary and a black cloth doll that clutched a pile of
business cards. He glanced at autographed photos of Whoopi Goldberg
and Melba Moore. They were divine in another way, having survived
tough times in their pursuit of the big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melba Moore,'' he said reverently. ``One day I'm going to open
for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Along Bainbridge Avenue in the Bronx, Rosario is hailed as a
stand-up guy, and not just for his shtick. Although cutbacks cost
him his day job as a crisis counselor at a housing center, he still
tackles cases for no pay. Old ladies and single mothers short on
money or luck stop him on the street and ask for advice.
</P>
<P>
   Few of them know that the counselor-comic faces his own quiet
crisis. He expects an eviction notice to be slapped on his door
because he owes $4,100 in rent on his tiny apartment. Reluctant to
burden anyone with problems that also include a close friend's
death and a recent break-in, he mines his life for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so broke that when I go to the ATM, I get food stamps,''
he said. ``Then there's my paranoia. Every time I open my door and
see a restaurant menu, I think it's an eviction notice.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly knows the difference. He has been working _ either
for pay or for nothing _ as a housing advocate since he was a
teen-ager. He got into it seriously soon after he had testified in
a court case involving someone who he knew was not guilty of a drug
hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone can walk in here with a really nice suit and say
something against somebody who doesn't look so hot, that means that
the one with the suit will win,'' said Rosario, 25. ``That means
that sometimes innocent people have to pay for something they
didn't bring upon themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains enough of a hook for him that he continues his
freelance counseling even though his unemployment benefits have run
out, his phone is about to be cut off and his part-time job at a
video store isn't cutting it. When he hits the streets of Norwood,
he becomes the answer man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I am able to forget about my problems is to help
people with worse problems,'' he said. ``I'm a lonely guy. I really
have nothing to do with my time except see who else is lonely and
who needs help.''
</P>
<P>
   He exaggerates, since he also sends out dozens of letters to
clubs, producers and anyone else who might discover him. He also
writes new jokes, sometimes drawing on the absurdity of the social
services maze.
</P>
<P>
   He dreams of being on ``The Rosie O'Donnell Show,'' since he
shares her love of wonderfully cheesy sitcoms. Like her, he said,
those old shows helped ease a rough childhood. ``She's like one of
my biggest inspirations,'' he said. ``I loved her even before she
had her own show. I remember her from `Gimme a Break.' I can even
sing the theme song.''
</P>
<P>
   Until he gets his own break, Rosario has enough fans in Norwood
looking out for him. When they learned that he was not being paid
for all the problems he was solving, they took care of him. His
hair stylist never charges him. The thrift shop gives him a
discount on clothing. And every day, Efrain Cruz feeds him pasteles
and flan at his restaurant, A Touch of Latin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He puts everybody else prior to him,'' Cruz said. ``I tell him
to pay when he can. With certain people I do that. Not everybody.
You got to take care of those who have heart. If somebody has
heart, you got to have heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosario does not forget the favors. ``If I ever make it, I'm
going to make him the next Jimmy's Bronx Cafe,'' he vowed. After a
while, and a brief hello to Esther, his ``hair savior'' down the
street, Rosario returned to his apartment. Some of his friends
think he's wasting his time writing jokes. He slogs on, even though
on some days it's enough of a chore to get out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time is not wasted,'' he insisted. ``One day, all the
things I'm writing about I'll be able to express little by
little.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
