<SLUG> BC-NY-EMAIL-FRAUD-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE TARGETING ONLINE CRIMES
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Christian Curry had what appeared to be a foolproof
method for winning a lucrative judgment in a federal discrimination
lawsuit he had filed against his former Wall Street employer,
investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a man who he thought was a computer hacker,
officials said, Curry, who is black, asked him to break into the
company's e-mail system and distribute a phony message filled with
anti-black vitriol, and references to himself.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail, when produced in court, would bolster Curry's claim
that the company, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, fired him in April
because he is black.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was that the man Curry was trying to hire was
an undercover New York City police detective, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested on Thursday, Curry, 24, was arraigned Friday in
Manhattan Criminal Court on charges of forgery, tampering with
physical evidence and coercion.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, who is from Chappaqua, N.Y., was later released from jail
and faces up to seven years in jail if convicted, prosecutors said.
His lawyer, Earl Rawlins, did not return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   His case is the second in the last month to involve computer
hackers' manipulation of e-mail accounts for purposes ranging from
the mischievous, to the comical, to the criminal.
</P>
<P>
   As concerns about e-mail security have intensified, companies
that provide Internet access and law-enforcement agencies have
stepped up their efforts to catch people in a crime that leaves few
traces. The officer who arrested Curry was a member of the New York
Police Department's Computer Investigations and Technology Unit.
The unit is three years old and consists of a lieutenant, sergeant
and six detectives recruited from within the department.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. James Doyle, a member of the unit, said its caseload has
doubled each year since it began. After 22 arrests in all of 1997,
the unit has 29 arrests so far this year. The charges range from
pedophilia-related offenses, to credit card fraud, to computer
hackers harassing people by taking over their e-mail accounts and
sending out false messages under their name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole new area for us, and it's an area that grows
exponentially,'' Doyle said. ``There's something new every six
months and we have to try to keep up with that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a case filed in late July, investigators say another former
employee of an investment bank used the e-mail accounts of his
former bosses to send out bizarre messages that resulted in dozens
of letters being mailed to them.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, investigated by the Manhattan district attorney's
office, Michael Lissack, a former investment banker and
whistle-blower, was charged with aggravated harassment last month
in an episode in which false e-mail messages were sent in the name
of former colleagues at Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, one message sent out on a Smith
Barney vice chairman's e-mail account stated that the 6-year-old
son of one of the vice chairman's friends had been diagnosed with
liver cancer. The message listed the vice chairman's home address
and said ``Little Jim would love whatever cards you could send in
the few months he has left.''
</P>
<P>
   In a second message, the papers say, Lissack pretended to be a
second Smith Barney vice chairman and asked people to send the
executive ``photos of babies for a book I'm writing'' and then
listed that vice chairman's home address.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Lissack faces up to a year in prison if
convicted. Reached by telephone Friday night, Lissack said he had
no comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Curry's case came to light, Doyle said, through the unit's use
of classic police work, not high-tech tracing. He said the unit
maintains contacts in the computer industry who tipped them that a
man was looking for a hacker who could penetrate Morgan Stanley's
e-mail system. The unit then made contact with Curry and set up the
meetings with the undercover officer.
</P>
<P>
   Other cases the unit has been involved in include tracing the
origin of e-mail threats to blow up Canarsie High School last
spring, exposing computer fencing operations, and breaking Internet
schemes involving the sale of sports memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, Doyle said, is applying old police tactics to a new
field. He said that when an officer goes online posing as a child
in an effort to ferret out potential pedophiles, for example, they
use the same tactics as an undercover detective trying to arrest a
prostitute or drug dealer. ``Just as you're taught as an undercover
how to avoid entrapment,'' he said, ``you have to avoid doing that
on computer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
