<HEADLINE>
WOODS RETURNS, BUT AS RECEIVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE _ Quincy Woods, who was AWOL from USC football camp for
three days, resurfaced Friday and began preparing to catch the ball
insteadof throw it.
</P>
<P>
   Woods left the camp at UC Irvine on Monday after coach Paul
Hackett told him he wouldn't be able to compete for one of the top
two quarterback spots. Hackett asked the 6-foot-1, 185-pound junior
to consider a move to receiver. At the time, Woods took most of his
clothes and his electric fan, but he said Friday he never intended
to leave for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went home to think things out,'' Woods said. ``My heart was
at quarterback. You know how bad I wanted to be a quarterback here.
I just needed time to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods spent the past three days thinking and talking on the
phone to his mother in Illinois, his brothers and friends. He
returned to UC Irvine on Friday morning and rejoined the team for
the afternoon practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see being away a couple of (days) how much I love
being on this team,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he never considered transferring and, while he
prefers to play quarterback, he accepts the position change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about that,'' Woods said when asked if he
received a fair shot at the job. ``I just need to move on with my
life. I respect (Hackett) as a coach and need to live with the
decision he made.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who completed 5 of 12 passes for 46 yards in his two
seasons at quarterback, played wide receiver briefly in 1997 but
didn't catch a pass. He'll try to add depth to a position which is
strong at the top but has only seven healthy scholarship players.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The players will get a day off today for the first time
since the camp opened on Aug. 10. Today was supposed to be the
final two-a-day session, but Hackett decided to let the players
rest. Preparation for the Aug. 30 opener against Purdue will take
full attention when practice resumes on Sunday....
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans survived a scary moment in Friday's early practice
when the starting quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst injured his right
ankle during a non-contact passing drill. Van Raaphorst slipped
while stepping away from a charging defensive lineman. He iced the
ankle and was back to full strength by the afternoon....
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he was awaiting the result of MRIs performed on
backup offensive tackle Ken Bowen (hyperextended elbow) and
defensive lineman Darren Collins (foot). Aside from freshman tight
end Scott Huber (hip), it's a pretty healthy group. Receiver Larry
Parker, who has been troubled by a hamstring, made a spectacular
catch on a fly pattern in the afternoon and then rested the
remainder of practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
